1. e4 {Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'RR RR: 'Marjanovic,Slavoljub Marjanovic,Slavoljub Marjanovic,Slavoljub''} g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 c6 4. Be3 Qb6 {Neil McDonald: 'Question: S'RR: 'Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: 'Neil McDonald: 'Question: So what are the pros and cons for Black in taking the pawn on e4? Answer: The positive point of the capture is that, although White will get a pawn on e5, he won't be able to construct a 'perfect' centre with pawns on d4 and e4 any longer. Having reduced the white centre in size and flexibility, Black is in less danger of falling into a long term positional bind. His pieces have more centre squares available to them. On the minus side, capturing on e4 and getting the knight away takes three moves, so the white pieces are getting out more quickly than the black pieces. Black will have to make some concession to survive the increased energy he is giving the white pieces by opening lines in the centre. In the Berlin Endgame, for example, Black 'buys off' White's immediate pressure by forfeiting the right to castle. ''''' o what are the pros and cons for Black in taking the pawn on e4? Answer: The positive point of the capture is that, although White will get a pawn on e5, he won't be able to construct a 'perfect' centre with pawns on d4 and e4 any longer. Having reduced the white centre in size and flexibility, Black is in less danger of falling into a long term positional bind. His pieces have more centre squares available to them. On the minus side, capturing on e4 and getting the knight away takes three moves, so the white pieces are getting out more quickly than the black pieces. Black will have to make some concession to survive the increased energy he is giving the white pieces by opening lines in the centre. In the Berlin Endgame, for example, Black 'buys off' White's immediate pressure by forfeiting the right to castle. '} (4... d6) (4... d5) 5. Rb1 {Neil McDonald: '!''RR: 'Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: 'Neil McDonald: '!'''''} (5. a3) 5... d6 {This alternative to the mo'RR: 'Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: 'This alternative to the more popular 5...Nd6 is a pet line of the Russian GM Malakhov and was advocated by many great players in the past including Steinitz, Anderssen, Zukertort, Lasker and others.'' Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: 'This alternative to the more popular 5...Nd6 is a pet line of the Russian GM Malakhov and was advocated by many great players in the past including Steinitz, Anderssen, Zukertort, Lasker and others.' Mikhalevski, V: 'This alternative to the more popular 5...Nd6 is a pet line of the Russian GM Malakhov and was advocated by many great players in the past including Steinitz, Anderssen, Zukertort, Lasker and others. Neil McDonald: 'The Rio de Janeiro Variation. Howell returns the pawn at once to speed up his development.''''' re popular 5...Nd6 is a pet line of the Russian GM Malakhov and was advocated by many great players in the past including Steinitz, Anderssen, Zukertort, Lasker and others. Neil McDonald: 'The Rio de Janeiro Variation. Howell returns the pawn at once to speed up his development.'} (5... Nf6) 6. Nf3 Nf6 {Neil McDonald: 'Black saves'RR: 'Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: 'Neil McDonald: 'Black saves his knight with gain of time by hitting the white bishop.''''' his knight with gain of time by hitting the white bishop.'} 7. Be2 Qc7 8. O-O Nbd7 {Here White has a wide choi'RR: 'Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: 'Here White has a wide choice of options.'' Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: 'Here White has a wide choice of options.' Mikhalevski, V: 'Here White has a wide choice of options. Neil McDonald: 'Strategically speaking, a very double-edged situation has arisen. Black's development has suffered – the bishop on c8 is still shut in – and his knight is on a strange square, though given time it could go from c5 to e6, where it would sit nicely in the centre. Meanwhile White has a serious space advantage, but Black hopes to neutralize it with ...f7-f6, when his bishop pair might become the defining feature of the position.''''' ce of options. Neil McDonald: 'Strategically speaking, a very double-edged situation has arisen. Black's development has suffered – the bishop on c8 is still shut in – and his knight is on a strange square, though given time it could go from c5 to e6, where it would sit nicely in the centre. Meanwhile White has a serious space advantage, but Black hopes to neutralize it with ...f7-f6, when his bishop pair might become the defining feature of the position.'} ({or} 8... Bg4) 9. a4 {This rare continuation (les'RR: 'Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: 'This rare continuation (less than 10 games in the last 10 years) was introduced by Zukertort in 1868! The idea behind the move is to take better control over the centre before playing Nc3.'' Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: 'This rare continuation (less than 10 games in the last 10 years) was introduced by Zukertort in 1868! The idea behind the move is to take better control over the centre before playing Nc3.' Mikhalevski, V: 'This rare continuation (less than 10 games in the last 10 years) was introduced by Zukertort in 1868! The idea behind the move is to take better control over the centre before playing Nc3. Neil McDonald: 'Adams increases his pawn presence in the centre before developing his knight to c3. ''''' s than 10 games in the last 10 years) was introduced by Zukertort in 1868! The idea behind the move is to take better control over the centre before playing Nc3. Neil McDonald: 'Adams increases his pawn presence in the centre before developing his knight to c3. '} (9. Nd2 b5 10. f4 b4 11. Na4 O-O {and the mate threat on g7 soon decides – it's mate in three at the latest. That might seem a long variation, but the writing was on the wall after 20 Ne4 as Black's defence was hopelessly outnumbered.}) 9... O-O 10. Nd2 e5 {The main line. The exchange'RR: 'Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: 'The main line. The exchange of the e5-pawn is important for Black, though as the game shows, it has drawbacks, in particular it weakens the position of Black's king.'' Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: 'The main line. The exchange of the e5-pawn is important for Black, though as the game shows, it has drawbacks, in particular it weakens the position of Black's king.' Mikhalevski, V: 'The main line. The exchange of the e5-pawn is important for Black, though as the game shows, it has drawbacks, in particular it weakens the position of Black's king. Neil McDonald: 'The thematic challenge to the white centre. Even so, Black has to be careful not to try for too much activity when his queenside is still undeveloped.''''' of the e5-pawn is important for Black, though as the game shows, it has drawbacks, in particular it weakens the position of Black's king. Neil McDonald: 'The thematic challenge to the white centre. Even so, Black has to be careful not to try for too much activity when his queenside is still undeveloped.'} (10... a6 {Marjanovic,Slavoljub: '+-' RR: '+-'} 11. f4 {Marjanovic,Slavoljub: '(RR) Marjanovic,Slavoljub'} b5) 11. dxe5 {This line is considered to 'RR: 'Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: 'This line is considered to be equal and was out of fashion for quite a while until Svidler beat the main expert of the line, Malakhov, in 2010.'''' be equal and was out of fashion for quite a while until Svidler beat the main expert of the line, Malakhov, in 2010.} (11. d5 $18 {and Black will have to sac on e7 to stay in the game. However, White is already clearly winning. RR: 'Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: '+-' Mikhalevski, V: 'and Black will have to sac on e7 to stay in the game. However, White is already clearly winning.''' RR: 'schnell.'} cxd5 {(clearing f8 for the queen) RR: 'Marjanovic,Slavoljub'} 12. exd5 Ne8) 11... dxe5 (11... Nxe5 12. h3 d5 $18 13. f4 (13. exd5 {The subsequent line confirms my words. Neil McDonald: 'Exercise: Tr