ut the text is also enough for a win. By the way, this position also arises after 18...Qd6. See above.'' Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: '+-!' '+-!' Mikhalevski, V: 'White wins a tempo attacking Black's queen, but the text is also enough for a win. By the way, this position also arises after 18...Qd6. See above.''''} fxe6 21. Rbc1 Bh6 22. Rfd1 $1 {Marjanovic,Slavoljub: '+-''RR: '+-' 'Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: '!'' Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: '!' '!''''} Rad8 {Marjanovic,Slavoljub: '(RR) Marjanovic,Slavoljub'} 23. b3 $1) 19. Rbd1 $1 {Neil McDonald: 'Exercise: H'RR: 'Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: '!'' Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: '!' '!' Mikhalevski, V: 'Neil McDonald: 'Exercise: How should White continue after 19...Nxc4? Generally speaking, in order to carry out a successful attack on the enemy king, a large superiority in firepower is required. This is because the king himself and his defensive wall of pawns can be surprisingly resilient. Here, however, White's advantage is overwhelming. He has all his pieces – the queen, two rooks and a knight – engaged in the attack, whereas only the black queen and rook on f8 are available to the defence. ''''' ow should White continue after 19...Nxc4? Generally speaking, in order to carry out a successful attack on the enemy king, a large superiority in firepower is required. This is because the king himself and his defensive wall of pawns can be surprisingly resilient. Here, however, White's advantage is overwhelming. He has all his pieces – the queen, two rooks and a knight – engaged in the attack, whereas only the black queen and rook on f8 are available to the defence. '} (19. f4 exf4 {with the knight to follow as well after} 20. Bxf4 Ne5 $1 {RR: 'Marjanovic,Slavoljub'} 21. Bxe5 Bxe5 $1 $18 {is also winning. See 18...Qd6.} {or Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'RR: 'Oder''} 22. Rxf7 Be6 {Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'RR: 'Marjanovic,Slavoljub''}) 19... Bf8 {Protecting the last rank.'RR: 'Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: 'Protecting the last rank.''''} 20. Nb1 $1 {Neil McDonald: 'Question: I'RR: 'Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: 'Neil McDonald: 'Question: I guess you need strong powers of calculation to carry out a kingside attack? Answer: Not particularly, the important thing is to be familiar with standard attacking patterns. For example you might have seen the 'Greek Gift' sacrifice. If you look at Adams' move 20 Nxh7!, you can see it borrows the theme of the Greek Gift – a piece is sacrificed on h7 to expose the black king and so win time for a decisive combination by the white queen and knight. It isn't quite as forcing as there is no check, but Black can't ignore the destruction of his kingside. So Howell decides to take the knight and in sporting style lets his opponent carry out a neat mate in the centre of the board. ''''' guess you need strong powers of calculation to carry out a kingside attack? Answer: Not particularly, the important thing is to be familiar with standard attacking patterns. For example you might have seen the 'Greek Gift' sacrifice. If you look at Adams' move 20 Nxh7!, you can see it borrows the theme of the Greek Gift – a piece is sacrificed on h7 to expose the black king and so win time for a decisive combination by the white queen and knight. It isn't quite as forcing as there is no check, but Black can't ignore the destruction of his kingside. So Howell decides to take the knight and in sporting style lets his opponent carry out a neat mate in the centre of the board. '} Rxd1 21. Rxd1 $1 {Neil McDonald: 'The white q'RR: 'Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: '!'' Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: '!' '!' Mikhalevski, V: 'Neil McDonald: 'The white queen has to stay on g3 to support his next move. ''''' ueen has to stay on g3 to support his next move. '} Kg7 {Otherwise 22.Qg6 with the s'RR: 'Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: 'Otherwise 22.Qg6 with the subsequent 23.Nef6.'''' ubsequent 23.Nef6.} (21... Nc5 $1 {with catastrophe on h7 for the black king.} 22. Rd8 {Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Marjanovic,Slavoljub'} Nxb3 {picks up the queen,} {as does} 23. Bh6 {Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Marjanovic,Slavoljub'}) (21... Bc5 22. Rxd7) 22. Na3 Bxa3 (22... Nc5 $1 $18 {also leads to a disaster. Neil McDonald: '!' Nei'also leads to a disaster. Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'also leads to a disaster. Mikhalevski, V: 'also leads to a disaster. Neil McDonald: '!' Neil McDonald: 'wins: upon'''' l McDonald: 'wins: upon'} 23. Bxc5 {Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Marjanovic,Slavoljub'} {the quickest of many wins is} Bxc5 24. Rd8) 23. bxa3 Kf8 {This last attempt to protec'RR: 'Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: 'This last attempt to protect the king fails.'''' t the king fails.} 24. a5 Ke7 (24... b6 25. Rd6) 25. f4 $1 {A decisive move. Black is doomed. N'RR: '!' RR: 'Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: '!' Mikhalevski, V: 'A decisive move. Black is doomed.'' Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: '!' '!' Mikhalevski, V: 'A decisive move. Black is doomed.' Mikhalevski, V: 'A decisive move. Black is doomed. Neil McDonald: 'Threatening 26 Rf5+. ''''' eil McDonald: 'Threatening 26 Rf5+. '} Nf6 (25... b6 {Oder} 26. fxe5 {RR} Nxe5 27. axb6 axb6 28. Bxb6 Nd7 {mit baldigem Matt.} {After} 29. Bc7 $1) (25... exf4 26. Bxf4 $1 $18 {White wins a tempo attacking Black's queen, but the text is also enough for a win. By the way, this position also arises after 18...Qd6. See above.} {Neil McDonald: 'Answer'Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: 'Neil McDonald: 'Answer: After'''' : After'} f6 {Neil McDonald: ',''(RR) Marjanovic,Slavoljub Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: 'Neil McDonald: ',''''}) 26. fxe5 Nxe4 27. Rd4 Bf5 (27... Nc5 28. Bg5+ $18 {is similar to the game.} Kf8 29. Rd8+ Kg7 30. Be7 $1 $18) ({or} 27... f5 {Marjanovic,Slavoljub: '(RR) Marjanovic,Slavoljub'} 28. exf6+ Nxf6 29. Bg5 $18 Bf5 {RR: 'Marjanovic,Slavoljub'} 30. g4) 28. g4 {An elegant checkmate in the m'# RR: 'Marjanovic,Slavoljub: '#' Marjanovi