1. Nf3 {Roiz,M} Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nb4 6. Bc4 (6. Bb5+ $11) 6... Nd3+ 7. Ke2 Nf4+ 8. Kf1 {This advance is frequently seen in various lines of the Italian nowadays.} Ne6 {GM Howell chooses a considerably rare way of handling the position.} 9. d3 {The most challenging - the pressure on the e5 is one of Black's main worries.} (9. b4 cxb4 10. Ne2 Nc5 (10... Nc7) 11. Qc2 e6 12. d4) (9. Ne5 g6 $6 10. Qa4+ Bd7 11. Nxd7 Qxd7 12. Bxe6 fxe6 13. Qxd7+ Kxd7) (9. d4 $16 {1/2 (44) Kramnik,V (2808)-Karjakin,S (2781) Stavanger NOR 2017} cxd4 $142 $1 10. Bxe6 Bxe6 11. Nxd4 Bc4+ 12. Kg1) 9... g6 {This is a positional pawn sac - the exchange of the powerful b5 is Black's undisputable achievement.} (9... Nc6 10. h4 h5 ({The flexible response} 10... Ned4 $5 {looks perfectly playable and leads to a complicated struggle:} 11. Bf4 e6) 11. Ng5 g6 12. Nxe6 Bxe6 13. Bxe6 fxe6 $14 {Giri,A (2782)-Aronian,L (2792) Leuven BEL 2016}) 10. h4 h6 11. Na4 Bg7 12. Be3 $1 $146 {This innovation is a definite improvement} (12. Bxe6 Bxe6 13. Nxc5 Bg4) 12... Nc7 $6 {David manages to regain the pawn, but the lack of coordination enables White to seize the initiative.} 13. Nc3 (13. Nxc5 b6 14. Qa4+ {wouldn't yield White real winning chances.} {After} Kf8 15. h5 bxc5 (15... g5 16. Nb3 Bd7 17. Qa3 b5 18. Bd5 $14 {Shankland,S (2656)-Nakamura,H (2814) Baku AZE 2015} {Quite popular is also} Nxd5 {, but exposing the b5-spot might cause Black some problems. For instance,} 19. exd5 a5 20. Nbd4 Na6) 16. hxg6 fxg6 17. Nh4 $44 {Alekseev,E (2636)-Eliseev,U (2606) St Petersburg RUS 2016, Black had decent compensation for a pawn à la Marshall.} {The modest} Qe8 18. Qxe8+ Kxe8 19. Nxg6 $11 {offers Black comfortable play.} Rh7 {doesn't offer Black full equality:} 20. Bxc5 (20. Bg8 Bxb2 21. Rb1 Rg7)) (13. Bxc5 b5) 13... Ne6 14. Rh3 Nc6 15. Kg1 $1 Ned4 16. Rg3 $14 {White's pieces are suddenly getting very active. Roiz,M: 'is just a transposition.'} e6 17. Bb5 Nxb5 18. Nxb5 a6 19. Nc3 {Obtaining the bishop pair secures White a small, but long-lasting advantage.} b6 20. Qd2 e5 {The most natural.} (20... Ra7 $16 {Mamedov,R (2666)-Balogh,C (2614) Baku AZE 2016} {The correct} 21. a3 $1 Rd7 22. Rd1 a5) 21. a3 $6 {An unsuccessful decision - the queen is clearly misplaced there.} a5 22. Qd1 $6 {Another inaccuracy, which drastically changes the course of the game.} Nd4 $1 23. b4 Nxf3+ $1 24. Rxf3 (24. gxf3 cxb4 25. Nd5 Rb8 26. h5 g5 (26... Be6 $2 27. hxg6 f5) 27. axb4 O-O 28. bxa5 bxa5) 24... Bg4 {Unfortunately, there is no good square for White's bishop at the moment.} 25. bxc5 $6 Bxf3 $1 {This strong move is connected with a pawn sacrifice.} 26. Qxf3 {Accepting the challenge.} bxc5 27. h5 (27. Nd5 O-O $44 {Sedina,E (2275)-Loiacono,A (2085) Trieste ITA 2016; Black was fine.} {Another way of grabbing the pawn is} 28. Bxc5 Re8 29. h5) 27... Qxd3 28. Nd5 O-O $1 {The activity of Black's pieces is threatening.} 29. Rd1 $2 {Alas, Anton Guijarro doesn't withstand the pressure.} (29. Rc1 c4 30. Rc3 Qb1+ 31. Rc1 $17 {the penetration of Black's rook puts White in big danger.} {A better move was} Qb7 32. Rxc4 Rfc8) (29. Qg4 $15 {Black's position would be better also in the event of} Kh7 (29... g5 {though in the resulting position Black still has to claim sufficient compensation for a pawn.} {over} 30. Bxc5 Rfd8) 30. Rd1 Qxa3 31. Nf6+ Bxf6 32. hxg6+ Kh8 $15 {but the simplifications might make White's defensive task easier.} (32... Kg7 33. gxf7+ Kxf7 $36 34. Rd7+ Be7 35. Rb7 c4 {is just a transposition.} {A better choice would be} 36. Qf5+ Ke8 37. Qg6+ Rf7 38. Qc6+ Kf8 39. Bxh6+ Rg7 40. g3) {It was necessary to connect the rooks:} 33. Bxh6 fxg6 34. Qxg6 {even though in the subsequent position Black is able to set up a blockade and solve the problems:} (34. Bxf8 Rxf8 $14 {Of course, David isn't happy with exposing his king with} 35. Qxg6 {It was also possible to keep the tension by means of} Bg7 $5 36. Kh2) 34... Qa4 35. Rd6 Qe8 36. Qf5 Be7 $11 {The correct way was} 37. Bxf8 Bxf8 38. Re6 $1) 29... Qa6 (29... Qxa3 30. Nf6+ (30. Rc1 $17 {the result still would be unpredictable.} {In the event of} c4) 30... Kh8 31. Nd7 c4 32. Nxf8 $19 {White's position was desperate, but had he played} Qxf8 33. Rd7 g5 34. Rxf7 Qd6) 30. Bxc5 Rfe8 (30... Rfd8 31. Ne7+ Kh7 32. Rxd8 $19 {The alternative -} Rxd8 33. Qxf7 gxh5 {was equally bad:} 34. Nf5 Qf6 35. Qa7 $1) 31. hxg6 fxg6 $1 {The major loss of material is unavoidable now.} (31... Qb7 32. gxf7+ Qxf7 33. Qg4 Kh7 $19) 32. Nc7 Qc6 33. Qb3+ Kh7 34. Nxe8 Rxe8 $1 35. Qf7 Rc8 $1 {GM Howell is playing precisely - now the vulnerablity of White's king starts to tell.} 36. Rd7 Qxd7 (36... Rg8 37. Qd5 Qxd5 38. exd5 g5 39. d6 {Black should be able to convert the material advantage into a full point, but the task is not trivial.} {An even stronger move was} Kg6 $1 40. Ra7 Bf6 41. g4) 37. Qxd7 Rxc5 38. Qa7 Rc4 39. Qxa5 Rxe4 40. a4 Rc4 41. Qb5 Rc1+ {The resulting endgame is hopeless.} 42. Kh2 e4 (42... Bf8 $19 43. Qb7+ $1 Kh8 44. a5 Bc5 45. Qb8+ {wins on the spot.} {After} Kh7 46. Qc7+ Kg8 47. a6) 43. a5 Rc7 44. Qa4 Ra7 {Now White is almost paralysed.} 45. a6 h5 46. g3 Kh6 47. Kg2 Bf6 48. Qc6 Bd8 49. Kf1 Ba5 50. Ke2 Kh7 51. Ke3 Kg7 52. Kxe4 Rf7 53. Qc5 Be1 {Or} 54. a7 Bxf2 55. Qe5+ 0-1


