1. c4 e5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. Nc3 Nb6 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. O-O Be7 8. a3 Be6 (8... O-O 9. b4 Be6 (9... Re8) (9... a6)) 9. b4 Nd4 (9... O-O) 10. Rb1 Nxf3+ 11. Bxf3 c6 {Diagram [#] Flear,Glenn: '!?' Flear,Glenn: 'A provocative move that has hardly occurred, but was once tried by Negi.'} 12. d3 $146 (12. b5) 12... O-O 13. Qc2 Rc8 14. Be3 {Flear,Glenn: 'Both sides jostle for position, but there is no residual advantage for White.'} (14. Bb2 f5 (14... c5 15. bxc5 (15. Bxb7 Rc7 16. Ba6 (16. bxc5 Rxb7 17. cxb6 Rxb6 18. Ba1 Qa8) 16... cxb4 17. axb4 Bxb4 18. Rfc1 Qd6) 15... Rxc5 16. Bxb7 Qd7 17. Bg2 Rfc8 18. Rfc1 e4 (18... Bg5 19. e3 Bf5 (19... Be7 20. Bf1) 20. Be4 Bxe4 21. dxe4 Nc4 22. Qe2) 19. Qd1 (19. Bxe4 Bf6 20. d4 Qxd4 21. Qd1 Rxc3 22. Rxc3 Rxc3 23. Qxd4 Bxd4 24. e3 Bf6 25. Bxc3 Bxc3) 19... exd3 20. Qxd3 Qc7) 15. Na4 Nd7 (15... Nxa4 16. Qxa4 Bd6 17. Qxa7 Rf7 18. Qe3) 16. Nc5 Nxc5 17. bxc5 Qc7 18. Ba1 Bf6) (14. Ne4 Nd7 (14... Bd5 15. Bg2 f5 (15... Nd7 16. Bh3 f5 17. Nc3 Be6 18. e4 Qe8 19. exf5 Bxf5 20. Qb3+ Kh8 (20... Qf7 21. Bxf5 Qxb3 22. Bxh7+ Kxh7 23. Rxb3) 21. Bxf5 Rxf5 22. Be3) 16. Nc5 Bxg2 17. Kxg2 Qd5+ 18. e4 fxe4 19. dxe4 Qc4 20. Rb2 Bxc5 21. bxc5 Qxc2 22. Rxc2 Nd7 23. Bb2) 15. Bd2 b6) 14... Nd5 15. Bc5 {Flear,Glenn: 'The plan is to improve the dark-squared bishop's prospects.'} b6 $1 (15... Bxc5 16. bxc5 Nxc3 17. Qxc3 Qc7 18. Rb4) 16. Bxe7 $6 {Diagram [#] Flear,Glenn: '?' Flear,Glenn: 'An oversight.'} Qxe7 $1 {Flear,Glenn: 'A tactic that rattles White's hold on the centre.'} 17. Rfc1 Nf6 (17... f5 18. Nxd5 cxd5 19. Qb2 Qd6) 18. Ne4 $6 (18. Qa4 Bd5 (18... Qd7 19. Ne4 Nd5 20. Ng5 Bg4 21. Rc2 Bxf3 22. Nxf3 f6 23. Rbc1 Ne7) 19. Nxd5 cxd5 20. Bg2 e4 (20... Rfd8 21. Bh3 Rxc1+ 22. Rxc1 g6 23. Qc6 Ne8 24. Bg2 d4 25. Qa4 Kg7) 21. Bh3 (21. dxe4 dxe4 22. e3 Rfd8 23. Bh3 Rc7) 21... Rxc1+ 22. Rxc1 exd3 23. exd3 Re8) 18... Nxe4 19. Bxe4 c5 20. Qb2 cxb4 21. axb4 Rxc1+ 22. Rxc1 Rc8 {Flear,Glenn: 'The smoke has cleared and it seems inevitable that White will drop his a-pawn, with nothing to show in return.'} (22... g6) 23. Rxc8+ Bxc8 24. Qc3 Bh3 {Flear,Glenn: 'There's no rush, the opponent isn't going anywhere!'} 25. f3 g6 26. Bd5 {Diagram [#] Flear,Glenn: '?!' Flear,Glenn: 'Already this smacks of desperation.'} h5 (26... a5 27. bxa5 Qd6 28. Bb3 bxa5 29. Kf2 (29. Qxa5 Qd4+ 30. Kh1 Qf2 31. Bxf7+ Kxf7 32. Qc7+ Ke8 (32... Kg8 33. Qd8+ Kf7 34. Qc7+) (32... Kf6 33. Qd8+) 33. Qxe5+ Kd7 34. Qb5+) 29... Qd4+ 30. Qxd4 exd4 31. g4 Kg7 32. Kg3 Bf1 33. Kf2 Bh3 34. Kg3) 27. Kf2 Kg7 28. b5 Qc5+ $19 {Flear,Glenn: 'Obeying the rule that 'when in doubt, keep improving one's pieces'!'} (28... Qd6 29. Qc4 f6) 29. Qxc5 bxc5 30. Ke3 Bd7 (30... f5 31. f4 Kf6 32. Kd2 exf4 33. gxf4 g5) 31. Bc4 {Flear,Glenn: 'David was already anticipating this counter with his 29th move.'} f5 32. f4 Kf6 33. h4 Be8 (33... Be6 34. fxe5+ $15 (34. Kd2 Bxc4 35. dxc4 exf4 36. gxf4 Ke6 37. Kc3 Kd6) 34... Kxe5 35. Bxe6 Kxe6 36. Kd2 Kf7 $13 (36... Kd6 37. e3 (37. Kc3 g5 38. hxg5 f4 39. Kd2 fxg3 {(so with the long diagonal still open, the natural riposte is...)} 40. Ke3 $1 {(...which obliges White to take risks if he wants to seek any advantage)} Ke6 41. Kf3 {Valderrama Quiceno, E - Soto, M Medellin 2020. A draw was agreed, but the position was just livening up. After} h4 42. e4) 37... Kd7 (37... Kc7 38. Kc3 Kd7 39. Kc4 Kd6 40. d4 cxd4 $44 {when the two pawns plus the initiative compensate for the missing piece} 41. exd4 {- 101/(366)}) ({Banusz has faced} 37... Kd5 {but in this case it's not clear if one should avoid f2-f3 or not:} 38. Kc3 $5) 38. Kc3 Ke7 39. Kc4 {(pushing all four central pawns in a row gains space but tends to leave some holes)} Kd6 40. d4 cxd4 41. exd4 Ke7 42. d5 Kd7 $5 $13 {Hakobyan, A - Salem, A St.Petersburg blitz 2018} 43. Kc5 $5 {is plausible, when the engine suggests}) (36... f4 37. gxf4 Kf5 38. Ke3 Kg4 {Black would have to give up a piece, but this is far from clear as} 39. Ke4 Kxh4 40. Kf3 $13 {leaves White with a draughty king.} {the Hungarian GM settled on} g5 {but wasn't able to claim an opening pull:} 41. e4 (41. f5 g4+ 42. Kg2 Kg5 43. e4 {(the threat of N-c5 is a nuisance, but perhaps only a temporary one)} h4)) (36... Ke7 37. e3 g5 38. hxg5 {Banusz, T - Van Wely, L Spanish league 2017, and Black unravels with equality close to hand} {Khismatullin, D - Efimenko, Z Moscow 2008, continued with the more popular} Kf7 {see the archives.} 39. Kc3 Kg6 40. Kc4 Kxg5 41. Kxc5 Kg4 42. d4 Kxg3 43. d5 h4 44. d6 h3 45. d7 h2 46. d8=Q h1=Q 47. Qc7+ Kf2 48. Qxa7 Qe4 49. Qa2+ Kxe3 50. Qb3+ Kf2 (50... Qd3 51. Qxd3+ Kxd3 52. b6) 51. b6) (36... Kf6 37. Kc3 g5 38. e3 gxh4 39. gxh4 Ke6 40. Kc4 Kd6 41. d4 cxd4 42. Kxd4 Ke6 43. Kc5 Ke5 44. Kc6 Ke4 45. Kb7 Kxe3 46. Kxa7 f4 47. b6 f3) 37. e3 g5 {Flear,Glenn: '(delaying the inevitable for one more turn)'} 38. hxg5 Kg6 39. d4 cxd4 $13 {Flear,Glenn: '=!' Flear,Glenn: 'is a typical ploy, as White will have to take some positional risks if he wants to avoid the exchange of light-squared bishops'} 40. exd4 $6 Kxg5 41. Ke3 Kg4 (41... Kf6 42. Kf3 Ke7 $16 {Cheparinov, I - Firat, B Batumi 2018.} {a natural enough move when one considers that} 43. Kf4 $1 Ke6 {would (at first) seem to be promising for White. However, after} 44. Kg5 Kd5 45. Kxh5 Kxd4 {the complications are apparently playable e.g.} 46. Kg5 Ke4 47. Kf6 $1 f4 48. gxf4 Kxf4 49. Ke6 $44 {as Black's pieces are going to be the more active.} Ke4) 42. d5 Kxg3 (42... Kg5 $1 {(this recurrent theme is important to remember)} 43. Kf3 Kg6 44. Kf4 Kf6 $6 45. d6 Ke6 46. d7 Kxd7 47. Kxf5 Kd6 48. Kg5 Kc5 49. Kxh5 Kxb5 50. g4 a5) 43. d6 f4+ 44. Ke2 $14 {Ibrayev, N - Negi, P New Delhi 2009, with a tense position where the bishop pair should keep White ahead.} {There are other ways to meet the threat to the bishop:} Kg2 45. d7 f3+ $6 46. Ke3 $1 f2 {0.5-0.5 Nogueiras Santiago, J - Garcia Martinez, S Las Tunas 2001, and Black can seize the initiative following} 47. d8=Q $1 f1=Q $5 $13 {removes the rook from a vulnerable square} 48. Qg5+ Kh2 49. Qxh5+ Kg1 50. Qg4+ Qg2) 34. Kd2 Bd7 {Flear,Glenn: 'Suddenly White's king finds himself surrounded by trouble.'} (34... e4 35. Kc3 exd3 36. exd3 Ke7 37. d4 (37. Kb3 Kd6 $44 38. Ka4 {seems to be fine, as the 'obvious'} a6 {is well met by} 39. Ka3 axb5 40. Bb3) 37... Kd6 $15 (37... cxd4+ 38. Kxd4 Kd6) 38. Kd3 cxd4 (38... Bd7 39. dxc5+ Kxc5 40. b6 $13 {Flear,Glenn: 'etc.'} axb6 $2 (40... Kxb6 41. Bf7 Bb5+ 42. Kd2 Kc5 43. Bxg6 Kd6 44. Bxh5 $1 Ke6) 41. Bf7 Bb5+ 42. Ke3 $16 Ba4 43. Bxg6 Bd1 44. Bxf5 b5 45. Bb1 b4 $1 ({Flear,Glenn: 'Simply'} 45... Kd5) 46. f5 Kd5 47. Kf4 b3 48. Be4+ Kd6 $11 49. Ke3 Bc2 50. Bxc2 bxc2 51. Kd2 Ke5 52. Kxc2 Kxf5 $36) 39. Kxd4 Kd7 $1 40. Kc5 Ke7 $17 {Flear,Glenn: 'Black is also comfortable following the superior'} 41. Bd3 {Flear,Glenn: 'e.g.'} Bd7) 35. Kc3 Be8 (35... e4 36. d4 ({Flear,Glenn: 'Or'} 36. Kb3 Ke7 37. Ka4 a6 38. Ka5 axb5 39. Bxb5 exd3 $17 40. exd3 Bxb5 41. Kxb5 $1 {and Black has the initiative.} Kd6 42. Kc4 Kc6) 36... cxd4+ $19 37. Kxd4 Be6 38. Bd5 $17 Bd7 $5 39. Kc5 Ke7 40. e3 Be8 $17) 36. Kb3 e4 (36... exf4 37. gxf4 Ke7 38. Ka4 a6 $19 39. Ka5 {Flear,Glenn: '!' Flear,Glenn: 'is immediately decisive.'} axb5 40. Bxb5 $1 Bf7 41. Bc4 $19 Be8 $19 42. Kb6 Kd6 43. Bb3 $19 g5 $1 (43... Bc6 44. Bf7 Bd5 45. Bxg6 $17 c4 46. dxc4 Bxc4 47. Bxh5) 44. fxg5 Bg6 45. Bg8 f4 $19 46. Kb5 f3 47. exf3 Bxd3+ 48. Bc4 Bf5 $17 49. f4) 37. Ka4 {Flear,Glenn: '?'} a6 38. Ka5 {would resist a little longer, when Black would have to find a way to increase the pressure. The following being a convincing way:} axb5 39. Bxb5 Bf7 40. Bc4 exd3 {(White has run out of constructive moves)} 41. exd3 Be8 42. Kb6 0-1


