1. e4 {Berg,Emanuel Berg,Emanuel Berg,Emanuel Berg,Emanuel: 'Berg,E'} e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 {Having played the Spanish in almost all my games of late, it was time for a change not the least to surprise my opponent.} Bb4 4. e5 c5 5. a3 $5 {The Italian Wing Attack. Not really something particulary dangerous for Black but leading to interesting play and hopefully something my opponent hadn't checked.} Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Qa5 7. Bd2 {White hopes to get a space advantage on the queenside with some long term pressure.} Qa4 $1 8. Qg4 (8. Qb1 c4) 8... g6 (8... Kf8) 9. Qd1 {The bishop gives space for the knight on b1. It's better to wait with castling for White to avoid} Nc6 (9... b6 10. h4 h5 (10... Ba6 11. Bxa6 Nxa6 12. Ne2 (12. h5 cxd4 13. hxg6 fxg6 14. Rh4 Ne7 15. cxd4 Rc8 16. c3 Nc5) 12... h5 13. Bg5 Rc8 14. O-O Ne7 15. Bf6 Rf8 16. Qd2 Nb8) 11. Nf3 Ba6 12. Bxa6 (12. Bd3 Nd7 13. O-O Bxd3 14. cxd3 Qxd1 15. Rfxd1 Ne7 16. Bg5 Nc6) 12... Qxa6 13. Bg5 Nd7 14. Qd3 Qxd3 15. cxd3 Rc8 16. Kd2 Ne7 17. a4 Nc6 18. dxc5 bxc5 19. Rhb1 Rc7) (9... cxd4 10. Rb1) 10. Rb1 (10. Nf3 b6) 10... a6 {Black opens a route for his bishop to c7.} (10... c4 11. h4 Qxa3 (11... h6 12. Qc1) 12. h5) 11. Nf3 b5 {Now Black's plan is to proceed with ...d5.} 12. h4 (12. Bd3 c4 13. Be2 Qxa3) 12... h6 (12... cxd4 13. cxd4 Nxd4 14. Bd3 Nxf3+ 15. Qxf3) 13. dxc5 (13. Bd3 c4 14. Be2 Qxa3 15. h5 g5 16. Ra1 Qb2 17. O-O) 13... Nge7 {White can no longer stop Black from ...d5 so it's time to retreat with the knight from c4.} (13... Qe4+ 14. Be3 Nxe5 15. Nxe5 Qxe5 16. Qd4) 14. Bd3 {A good square for the knight preventing ...g4.} (14. c4 dxc4 15. Qc1) 14... Nf5 {Black has achieved his main aim and has a nice pawn centre. However this is where the real battle starts.} (14... Qxa3 15. O-O (15. Rb4) 15... Qxc5 16. Qc1) (14... Qg4) 15. Rb4 Qxa3 (15... Nxb4 16. axb4) 16. O-O $1 {A good move restricting Black's knight on g6 while also securing White's king against attacks along the b8-h2 diagonal. True it also has a drawback of weakening the light squares but that's nothing Black can take advantage of at first sight. I had been analysing this exact position at my hotel room before the game and come to the conclusion that White had interesting chances to fight for an edge although theoreticaly Black should be just fine.} Bd7 {A logical move preparing the a8-h1 diagonal for the light squared bishop.} 17. Qe2 {White's main idea in the position. Now after ...e4 he can play his knight back to d2 preparing the c4-break.} d4 {Black keeps the centre dynamic hoping for an opening of the long diagonal.} 18. Rxd4 {So far I had evrything under control having played my moves quickly while my opponent had used a considerable amount of time.} (18. Rb3 Qxc5 19. Ra1 Ra7 (19... O-O 20. g4) 20. g4 Nfe7 21. Qe4) (18. h5 dxc3 (18... g5 19. Nxd4 Nfxd4 20. Rxd4 Qxc5 (20... Nxd4 21. cxd4) 21. Re4) 19. Rb3 Qxc5 20. Rxc3) 18... Ncxd4 {A human move which I had not investigated during my preparation.} 19. cxd4 {Played after a long period of thought. The fact that Black's pawns were not static on d5 and e4 troubled me and I was slightly concerned about ...h3 ideas.} Bc6 {This plays into White's hands, especially as now I knew exactly which plan to follow.} 20. Be4 Rc8 $6 {This plan might look logical but in fact it only wastes time and in the end even helps White.} 21. Bxc6+ {A practical move but there might well have been better options.} Rxc6 22. Qe4 (22. c4 b4 (22... bxc4 23. Rb1 O-O 24. Qxc4) 23. Qe4 Rc8 24. Qb7 O-O 25. Qxb4 Qxb4 26. Bxb4) 22... Ne7 {This exchange gives White a very harmonious position. Perhaps Black should rather have allowed the advance c5 although that's not an easy decision to make.} 23. Nh2 h5 24. Bg5 $1 {Nicely preparing for e5 which is now a major concern for Black.} Nd5 25. Bf6 Rf8 $6 {Black was in a difficult situation but this does not solve the issue.} (25... O-O 26. Rd1 b4 27. Nf1 Rcc8 28. Rd3 Qa1 29. Rg3 Kh7 30. Rg5) 26. Nf3 $6 {Not at all bad but there was better to be found.} Qc3 27. Ng5 Qc4 (27... a5 28. Nxe6 fxe6 29. Qxg6+ Rf7 30. Qg8+) 28. Rd1 (28. Qf3 Qxd4) 28... Kd7 29. Qf3 Qxc2 (29... Nxf6 30. Qxf6 Qxc2 31. Qf3 Qf5 32. d5 exd5 33. Qxd5+ Kc7 34. Ne4 Qe6 35. Qd2 Kb8) 30. Bg7 Re8 {A tricky move in time trouble. Black bravely enters the complications with the risk of losing a piece.} 31. Ne4 $6 (31. Nxf7 Qf5) 31... Kc7 $6 32. Kh2 Re7 33. Rd2 $1 {Liquidating into a very comfortable endgame for White.} Qc1 34. Bh6 (34. Bf8 Rd7 35. Bd6+ Kb7) 34... Rd7 35. Nd6 Qb1 (35... Rcxd6 36. exd6+ Kb7 37. Ra2 Qxh6 38. Qa3) 36. Rd1 (36. Qa3) 36... Qc2 37. Rd2 {White has a nice grip holding Black passive defending his e5-pawn.} Qc3 38. Rd3 $1 {Launching the g-pawn is a good way to play for White. It gives more space and at some point the g-pawn might continue to g5 or even g6.} Qb2 39. Rd2 (39. Nxf7) 39... Qb4 40. Nxf7 {A safety move to complete the time control.} Ne7 41. Nd6 Nf5 42. Bg5 $1 {It's time to regroup the pieces. Now h1 and c4+ can cause Black serious trouble.} a5 (42... Rh7 43. Bd8+ Kxd8 (43... Kd7 44. d5) 44. Qxc6 Nxd6 45. Qb6+ Ke8 46. Rd3 Nf5 47. Qxe6+ Ne7 48. Qxa6 Qc4 49. Rf3 Qd5 50. Qxb5+) 43. Rd3 (43. d5 exd5 44. Qxd5 Nxd6 45. cxd6+ Kb6 46. Qe6 Qg4 47. Qe8 a4 48. Qa8) 43... Nxd6 (43... a4 44. Bd2) 44. exd6+ {Importantly defending against the exchange of queens on f4.} Kb7 $2 45. Qh3 $1 {Allowing this move should normally mean the end for Black. Now g6 is a crucial threat.} Rdxd6 (45... Qc4 {½-½ (42) Jobava,B (2712)-Hammer,J (2601) Rogaska Slatina 2011; when Black has a nice initiative on the kingside.} 46. d5 {is the main alternative and the most popular move over the years. However I find it rather comfortable for White following} Rcxd6 {intending ideas like b3 and c4.} 47. cxd6 Rxd6 48. Qf3 Rxd5 49. Rc3 Qd4 50. Bd8 a4 51. Rc7+ Kb8 (51... Ka6 52. Rc6+ Kb7 53. Rxe6) 52. g3 b4 53. Rh7 Rd7 54. Bf6 Qd5 55. Be5+ Ka8 56. Qf8+ Ka7 57. Qb8+ Ka6 58. Qc8+) 46. Bd2 $4 {I saw that this would give Black good drawing chances but} Qc4 47. cxd6 b4 (47... Rxd6 48. Bxa5) 48. Qf3 (48. Bf4 $1 Rc8 $1 $13 {An important defensive resource which is the only way of surviving for White. Although the computer engine keeps rather calm all the way down these lines even the smallest error could end up in disaster for White.} 49. Be5 $5 {also deserves serious attention intending} a4 50. Qf3+ {with great complications.} Qd5 51. Qf7+ Kb6 {Instead the computer gave} 52. d7 Rd8 {which I was quite satisfied with. Having the pawn on e4 it's hard for Black to create anything really dangerous on the kingside. But White for his part can always open up with c4 at some point.} 53. Qe7 Rxd7 54. Qxb4+ Qb5 55. Qc3) 48... Qd5 49. Qxd5 (49. Qf7+ Ka6) 49... exd5 50. Bf4 Rc8 (50... Kc8 51. Re3 Kd8 {when White has driven away Black's queen and has things pretty much under control.} {My first thought was to play} 52. Re7 {which is also the computer's top suggestion. However I was not quite comfortable and thought that perhaps Black could get a quick attack on the kingside following} b3 $5 {Even with the computer by my side I'm far from convinced that the fearless} 53. Ra7 $1 {would lead to something good for White. To open the long diagonal towards White's king looks like a nightmare. When going down the lines a bit we end up in a critical position after} {The main continuation follows} b2 54. Bg5+) 51. Rd1 Rd8 (51... Kb6 52. Bg5 Kc6 $16 {During the game I started to think about} 53. Rc1+ {intending ...g5-f3. This would at least be slightly annoying for White but the central counterplay should prove stronger after} Kd7 54. Rxc8 Kxc8 55. Bd2 Kd7 $14 {since Black lacks the power to continue his attack.} {The immediate} 56. f4 $5 {is one interesting alternative.} Kxd6 {looks better to keep control in the centre and be ready for the c4-break.} {Instead} 57. g4 {was what I expected when White has to be careful.} {I had planned to continue} hxg4 58. Kg3 b3 59. Bc1) 52. Rc1 Kb6 (52... Ka6 {when White's attack will become decisive.} 53. Rc6+ $1 {was more precise when White keeps only a symbolic advantage.} Kb5 $1 {would have forced Black into giving up his knight after the forced line} 54. Rc5+ Ka4 55. Rxd5 b3 56. Bc1 Kb4 57. d7 a4 58. Bg5) (52... b3 53. Ra1 Kb6 $16 {with excellent winning chances for White.} 54. Ra3 $1 a4 {would simply leave Black in very bad shape having a king without a real shelter, e.g.} 55. Rxa4 Kb5 56. Ra1 $18 Kc4 $5 {was another good way to a clear advantage following} 57. Be5 b2 $16 {with two potentially strong concted passed pawns as well as the pir of bishops.} {The straightforward} 58. Rb1 {looks best when after} Kc3 59. Kg3 Kc2 60. Rxb2+ {followed by ...e6 Black is at least able to limit White's attacking chances. Still White has a solid plus following} Kxb2 61. Kf4) 53. Rc5 b3 54. Bd2 (54. Bc1 Rxd6 $18 55. Ba3 {would have been better.} Rc6 $4 {cannot be played due to}) 54... b2 55. Bxa5+ Ka6 (55... Kb7 56. Bxd8 b1=Q 57. Rc7+ $18 {White's two passed pawns will decide.} Kb8 58. d7 Qf5 59. Bg5 $11 {is just a draw.}) 56. Bxd8 b1=Q 57. Rc6+ Ka7 58. d7 {White could win a pawn by playing} Qf5 {but after} 59. Bb6+ (59. Rc7+ $18 Kb6 {is the most stubborn but after} 60. Bg5) 59... Kb7 60. d8=Q {Black will soon be able to force an exchange of his a-pawn against White's b-pawn which leads to a completely drawn endgame.} (60. d8=N+ Ka6 (60... Ka8 61. Bc7 Ka7 62. Rc5 Qf6 63. Ra5+) (60... Kb8 61. Rc7 Qf4+ 62. Kg1 Qxc7 63. Bxc7+) 61. Bc7+ Kb5 $1 62. Bg3) {in the eternal time trouble I did not realise that} 60... Qf4+ $1 {was just winning.} {There might follow} 61. Kg1 Kxc6 62. g3 (62. Qc7+) 1/2-1/2


