{[%evp 0,86,17,23,19,19,20,15,15,-37,-11,-11,1,1,1,3,0,0,12,23,26,40,55,54,12,30,39,35,35,5,-5,16,32,32,35,26,59,5,50,-38,-45,-185,-135,-347,-307,-524,-558,-579,-372,-353,-392,-539,-177,-222,-174,-311,-6,-8,-8,-3,100,113,119,-21,109,94,83,96,104,153,152,-20,-27,-66,-48,-78,-105,-105,-65,-169,-160,-237,-47,-386,-503,-539,-724,-1289,-1080]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Bg7 $1 5. c4 Nc6 6. Nc2 e6 (6... Nf6) (6... d6) (6... a6) 7. Nc3 Nge7 8. Be2 $5 {This is an interesting sideline, as White develops the queen winning a tempo by both pinning and attacking c6.} (8. Bf4 $5 {looks like a desperate attempt already:}) (8. h4) 8... O-O $1 {A nice and active answer. Black should not hesitate in such positions, but instead go for active play.} (8... f5 $19 {[%cal Gb7a6]} 9. h4 {was also good.}) 9. O-O $6 {White will soon realise that being materialistic here is not a good choice .} f5 10. exf5 Nxf5 $1 {[%csl Yc6,Yg5][%cal Gb8b6,Gc8b7] My suggestion is that Black should think not about one or two pawns in such positions, but in terms of development and (mainly) piece mobility (like AlphaZero!). White has won a second pawn, but in doing so he gave up the bishop pair and helped Black to solve a potential problem (the a5). On the other hand, by covering the check with the knight Black hits the g5, and the queen can be harassed with moves like ,,,b6 and ...b7. Black is two moves away from completing development, when he will be ready to look for active ideas like advancing the f-pawn. Although White is two pawns up, it looks like he acquired too many practical problems in return, and surviving the middlegame already seems a very difficult task.} 11. Ne4 (11. Bf4 $19 b6 $2 {would lead to a quick loss:} 12. Qd2 Bb7 13. Rad1 Ncd4 14. Nxd4 Nxd4) 11... b6 (11... d5 12. cxd5 (12. Ng5 {White has some chances of resistance here but he needs to accept a bad position, since} h6 $2 {loses to} 13. Nf3 $1 Kh7) 12... exd5 13. Ng5 Nfd4 14. Nxd4 Nxd4) 12. Rb1 Bb7 {A natural move and also one that you always want to play in such positions.} 13. b3 Ne5 (13... Nb4 $2 14. Nxb4 $1 Bxe4 15. Bd3 $19 Bb7 $19 {was probably simpler.}) 14. Ng3 Qh4 $1 {This rook is very annoying.} (14... Nh4 {[%cal Yg7g5] and White is defenceless.} 15. f3) (14... d5 15. cxd5 Qxd5 16. Qxd5 Bxd5 $19) 15. Nxf5 $2 {The problem is that after this move White can hardly find a good place for his king.} (15. Ne3 Nd4) 15... gxf5 $1 {[%cal Ga8h1,Yg6g1] The pressure on White's camp is very unpleasant now.} (15... Rxf5 $142 {was safer.} 16. f4 $142 Raf8 $142 17. fxe5 Rxf1+ 18. Bxf1 {was a clear-cut continuation.} Qf2+ 19. Kh1 {It is even harder to suggest a move for White here.} Qxf1+) 16. f4 Ng4 17. Bxg4 $6 {It is not easy to suggest how White should play, but this move normally creates new targets for Black.} (17. h3 Qg3 {would still offer more resistance.}) 17... fxg4 $1 {[%csl Yd3] Howell immediately spots the new weakness.} (17... Qxg4 $19 18. Qxg4 fxg4 19. Bb2 Be4 20. Bxg7 Kxg7 21. Rbc1) 18. Qxd7 Bxg2 $1 (18... Rf7 19. Qxe6 $2 (19. Qd3 Rd8 20. Qe2 $2) 19... Rd8 20. Qe2 Re7 21. Be3 Be4 $17) 19. Kxg2 $2 (19. Qxe6+ Kh8 20. Kxg2 Rae8) 19... Qh3+ 20. Kg1 g3 21. Qd2 (21. hxg3 {Things have even changed now and the advantage is with White.} Qxg3+ 22. Kh1 Rf6 $6) 21... Rad8 {Black is already completely winning, and the only explanation for the game lasting so long from this point is the short time control which probably made Howell's task harder.} (21... gxh2+ 22. Qxh2) 22. Qg2 gxh2+ 23. Kh1 Qd3 24. Bb2 Rf7 25. Rf3 Qf5 26. Rg3 Rdd7 27. Rf1 h6 $2 {Unnecessary.} 28. Nd4 Qf6 29. Rg6 0-1


