1. e4 Nc6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 $5 {Played quickly, and the idea was probably to transpose to a Panov after 4.d4 cxd4 5.exd4 c6 6.c3.} 4. c3 {Played after a great many minutes thought. I remember it amused me during the game that at many points I was actually behind David on the clock, and I then wondered how common this could possibly be. The following round, Luke McShane went even further behind David on the clock, proving my suspicions unfounded.} e6 5. Be2 f6 6. f4 {The 'backup' idea that I had in mind when playing my 4th move.} g5 7. Bh5+ Kd7 8. fxg5 fxe5 9. Nf3 h6 10. c4 (10. g4) 10... Nge7 $2 {A fairly significant error after half an hour of thought. Possibly, my opponent was convinced that on psychological grounds I would have to trade the queens, and simply wanted to do so in the best way he could.} (10... e4 11. cxd5 exd5 12. Nh4) (10... hxg5 11. cxd5 Nxd4 (11... exd5 {could still be a bit interesting.} 12. O-O) 12. dxe6+ Kc8 13. Nxd4 exd4 (13... Qxd4 14. Qxd4 exd4 $19 15. O-O) 14. O-O Nh6 15. Nd2) (10... Kc8 11. cxd5 Qxd5 12. Nc3 Qc4 $15 {was something I assessed as lost, but in reality it may not be.} 13. Nxe5 Nxe5 14. dxe5 $17 Bb4 15. Bd2 Ne7 16. gxh6) (10... dxc4 $15 {is a little unpleasant, but White is not a million miles away from setting up some kind of d3, e3 fortress.} 11. Nxe5+ $11 {was almost certainly best, trying to play either e2 or f4.} Nxe5 12. dxe5+ Bd3 13. Nc3 Kc8 14. Be2 $1 $132 (14. Bg4 Kb8 15. Bxe6 Qd4 $11) 14... a5 $11 {was my first thought, but I somehow couldn't countenance leaving development for even one more move, the bishop pair notwithstanding.} (14... Qd4 15. Qa4 c6 $1 $14 {has the potential to go even worse for Black} 16. Bxd3 $1 {The best way to pose questions about the legitimacy of White's quality-over-quantity approach to development.} Qxd3 17. Rf1) (14... hxg5 15. Bxd3 cxd3 $1 16. Qg4 $3 {Black has a more pleasant position, even if it is still basically equal.}) 15. Rf1 $1 {It is not clear to me why I didn't choose this move, which is easily the most natural, and which might even give White an edge.} hxg5 16. Bxd3 {Now White gets all kinds of useful developing moves for free, like g3, e3 and e5.} (16. Bxg5 $14 Be7 17. Bf4 Bb4) 16... cxd3 17. Qg4 $1 Ra6) 11. g4 Bxb1 (11... Be4 12. Nc3 Bxf3 13. Qxf3 Nxd4 14. Qg2 Kc8 {I assessed this position type as lost, though maybe it still forces Black to find an idea or two. The general idea is that Black plays ...g5-g4, then ...f3-h1 to tie the White king to e3, then ...h5, and finally ...g3. Matters become a little bit complicated if White takes on e5, but not too much. For instance:} 15. O-O) 12. Rxb1 $2 {Returning the favour after half a minute of thought...} e4 13. Ne5+ Nxe5 14. dxe5 Bg7 (14... Kc8 15. O-O a5) 15. O-O {Not bad as such, but in practical terms this severely limits my winning potential. Now Black can relax and play for a win in his own time, which he proceeds to do.} c6 (15... Bxe5 16. cxd5 Nxd5 (16... exd5 17. gxh6) 17. Qa4+) 16. Be3 hxg5 {There was also ...b6.} 17. Bd4 (17. cxd5 exd5 18. Bd4) 17... Rf8 $1 {Correctly noticing that he has to defend d8 with the rook and not just the bishop.} (17... Qb8 18. cxd5 {Simply taking on g4 also wins.} cxd5 19. Rf7 Bxe5 20. Bxe5 Qxe5 21. Qa4+ Kd8 22. Qa3 Qc7) 18. Rxf8 Qxf8 (18... Bxf8 19. Qb3 b6 20. Rf1 dxc4 $2 21. Qxc4 Nd5 22. Bg6) 19. Qb3 b6 20. Rf1 Qh8 21. cxd5 exd5 (21... Bxe5 22. dxc6+ Kc7 23. Qxe6 Bxd4+ 24. Kg2 $1 Qd8 25. Rf8) 22. Qc3 Rg8 23. Rf7 Ke6 24. Rxe7+ Kxe7 {There follow some repetitions.} 25. Qa3+ Kd8 26. Qd6+ Kc8 27. Qxc6+ Kb8 28. Qd6+ Kb7 29. Qxd5+ Kb8 30. Qd6+ Kb7 31. Bf7 Rc8 32. Bd5+ Ka6 33. Qa3+ Kb5 34. b3 $2 {Very close to losing by force.} a5 35. Qa4+ (35. Bb7 {Now Howell doesn't miss his chance. There isn't any way to keep the pawn.}) 35... Ka6 $1 {Now White goes on tilt, despite his position not yet being indefensible.} 36. Bc4+ Kb7 37. Qb5 $2 {In perfect chess, maybe the losing mistake.} Qh6 38. Qa6+ Kb8 39. Bxb6 Rxc4 40. bxc4 Qc6 41. Ba7+ Kc7 $6 42. Qxc6+ $2 Kxc6 43. Bd4 0-1


