{[%evp 0,113,80,27,39,18,17,12,12,12,19,15,17,23,29,-6,5,-4,13,-20,-12,-14,6,-16,-7,3,1,1,11,4,3,9,18,10,21,3,19,-41,-26,-34,-3,-36,-8,-8,34,22,48,0,24,13,27,30,13,13,26,48,111,132,132,115,132,122,132,69,74,68,63,90,90,92,102,100,98,98,95,101,94,85,99,88,91,103,106,107,112,110,112,112,112,109,151,163,164,161,190,185,190,194,227,250,246,250,245,253,253,253,254,269,289,298,301,307,307,320,315,321]} 1. e4 {Tadic,Branko Giri, Anish Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish Giri,Anish: 'Giri, Anish''} e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 {Italian is a frequent guest in the practice of modern top players and Firouzja's is no exception there. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'Italian is a frequent guest in the practice of modern top players and Firouzja's is no exception there.''} Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 5. d3 d6 {Many players these days prevent Bg5 at the first possible opportunity. This also has downsides, but perhaps this is not a moment for one of my favourite lectures- the lecture on the Italian move order subtleties. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'Many players these days prevent Bg5 at the first possible opportunity. This also has downsides, but perhaps this is not a moment for one of my favourite lectures- the lecture on the Italian move order subtleties.''} 6. O-O h6 7. Re1 O-O 8. Nbd2 {This is not neccessary here and there is also quite some point in the 8.bd2 move order, intending to save on the move h3, after, for example, 8.bd2 a5 9.f1. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'This is not neccessary here and there is also quite some point in the 8.bd2 move order, intending to save on the move h3, after, for example, 8.bd2 a5 9.f1.''} Bb6 {I believe it was Eljanov, who was one of the first players to introduce this system to high level practice. As space started to get more appreciated by the modern engines and therefore also modern players, the system with a5, limiting the queenside expansion with b4, has gained in popularity.  Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'I believe it was Eljanov, who was one of the first players to introduce this system to high level practice. As space started to get more appreciated by the modern engines and therefore also modern players, the system with a5, limiting the queenside expansion with b4, has gained in popularity. ''} (8... a5) 9. a4 {One disadvantage of 8...a5 over 8...a6, is that White doesn't have to address the positional threat of a5 and can focus on development without wasting a tempo on a4 or b3. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'One disadvantage of 8...a5 over 8...a6, is that White doesn't have to address the positional threat of a5 and can focus on development without wasting a tempo on a4 or b3.''} a5 10. Bb5 {Another disadvantage of 8...a5 system, is that it weakens the b5 square, where the bishop can relocate itself. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'Another disadvantage of 8...a5 system, is that it weakens the b5 square, where the bishop can relocate itself.''} (10. Nf1) 10... Ng4 {A decent side-system, which is a sound alternative to the complex main-line 10...b8!?, where the queen gets into the game via the a7-square. That system has a good reputation, but is very complex and double edged. What David does instead, is simpler, intending to tranfser the c6 knight to g6 via e7 and expand on the queenside with c6-b5-a5.  Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'A decent side-system, which is a sound alternative to the complex main-line 10...b8!?, where the queen gets into the game via the a7-square. That system has a good reputation, but is very complex and double edged. What David does instead, is simpler, intending to tranfser the c6 knight to g6 via e7 and expand on the queenside with c6-b5-a5. ''} 11. Re2 (11. d4 exd4 12. Nc4 Ba7 (12... dxc3 13. Nxb6 cxb2 (13... cxb6 14. bxc3) 14. Bxb2 cxb6 15. Ra3) 13. h3 (13. cxd4 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 Qh4 15. Be3 Qxh2+ 16. Kf1 Qh1+ 17. Ke2 Qxg2) 13... Nge5 14. Nxd4 Nxd4 15. cxd4 Qh4) (11. Rf1 f5) 11... Ne7 (11... f5 12. h3 Nf6 13. Nc4 fxe4 14. dxe4 Ba7) 12. d4 {It made sense to start with 12.d4 as well, but then White had to deal with 12...exd4 13.cxd4 d5 14.e5 e4 15.g3 c5 sequence, typical for this line, that happened in Tabatabaei-Sevian 2020. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'It made sense to start with 12.d4 as well, but then White had to deal with 12...exd4 13.cxd4 d5 14.e5 e4 15.g3 c5 sequence, typical for this line, that happened in Tabatabaei-Sevian 2020.''} Ng6 13. Nf1 d5 14. exd5 (14. h3 dxe4 15. Rxe4 Nf6 16. Re1 exd4 17. Nxd4) 14... exd4 {Grabbing space on the queenside. The point of this setup for Black, is that while he does give White the opportunity to stabilise a strong centre after 15.d4, the queenside expansion with b5-a4 had made sure that Black has some queenside space and if White is to challenge it with b3 and c4, a lot of trades will happen, leading to simplifications, that are favorable for Black, the side that has less space in the centre.  Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'Grabbing space on the queenside. The point of this setup for Black, is that while he does give White the opportunity to stabilise a strong centre after 15.d4, the queenside expansion with b5-a4 had made sure that Black has some queenside space and if White is to challenge it with b3 and c4, a lot of trades will happen, leading to simplifications, that are favorable for Black, the side that has less space in the centre. ''} 15. h3 Nf6 {Tadic,Branko: 'Diagram [#]'} 16. Nxd4 {Tadic,Branko: 'N'} Nxd5 17. Re1 Ndf4 {The bishop is generally better placed on b6, anticipating the typical b3 push and the opening of the a-file with axb3 axb3. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'The bishop is generally better placed on b6, anticipating the typical b3 push and the opening of the a-file with axb3 axb3.''} 18. Be3 $5 {Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: '!?'' An interesting concept that I hadn't come across before. Usually White would fight for the queenside space and squares with b4/b3, leading to a lot of trades. Alireza solves the issue of the hanging a2 pawn differently, weakens the light squares further, but does keep literally all the pieces on the board and thus more pressure on the opponent. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'An interesting concept that I hadn't come across before. Usually White would fight for the queenside space and squares with b4/b3, leading to a lot of trades. Alireza solves the issue of the hanging a2 pawn differently, weakens the light squares further, but does keep literally all the pieces on the board and thus more pressure on the opponent.''} (18. Ng3 c6 19. Bf1 Bxd4 20. cxd4 Be6) 18... c6 {Alternative and possibly a clearer plan would have been 17...c7, preparing d5, with mass simplifications in the centre to follow.  Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'Alternative and possibly a clearer plan would have been 17...c7, preparing d5, with mass simplifications in the centre to follow. ''} (18... Nxg2 19. Kxg2 Nh4+ (19... Qh4 20. Qf3 c6 21. Be2 f5 22. Bd2) 20. Kh1 Qd5+ 21. f3 Bxh3 (21... c5 22. Nc2 Qf5 23. Nh2 Bc7) 22. Nh2 Bg2+ 23. Kg1 Bh3) 19. Bc4 {Introducing the c3-c4 break idea. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'Introducing the c3-c4 break idea.''} (19. Be2 Qf6) 19... Bc7 {Black starts being clever here. Very possible was not to be too deep about things and just bring the a8 rook towards the center- Rad8, hinting at the d5 break. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'Black starts being clever here. Very possible was not to be too deep about things and just bring the a8 rook towards the center- Rad8, hinting at the d5 break.''} (19... Nxg2 20. Kxg2 Qh4 21. Nf3 (21. Kg1 c5) 21... Qxh3+ 22. Kg1 Rd8 23. Qb3 (23. Qe2 Bc7 24. N3h2 (24. Ng3 Bg4) 24... Nh4 25. f3 Rd6 26. Kh1 Rg6) 23... Bc7 24. Bxf7+ (24. N1d2 Nh4 25. Nxh4 Bh2+ 26. Kh1 Bg3+ 27. Kg1 Qh2+ 28. Kf1 Bxh4) 24... Kh8 25. Bxg6 Qg4+ 26. Ng3 Bxg3 27. fxg3 Qxg3+ 28. Kh1 Qxf3+ 29. Kh2 Qh3+ 30. Kg1 Qg3+) 20. Ng3 Nd5 {Moving out of the c-file and intending to meet 21.c4 with 21...bxc4 22.Bxc4 and 22...d5. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'Moving out of the c-file and intending to meet 21.c4 with 21...bxc4 22.Bxc4 and 22...d5.''} (20... Nxg2 21. Kxg2 Qh4 22. Bf1 Bxh3+ 23. Kg1 Bxg3 24. Nf3 Qg4 25. Bxh3 (25. fxg3 Qxg3+ 26. Kh1 Bg4 27. Bg2 Nh4) 25... Qxh3 26. fxg3 Qxg3+ 27. Kh1 Rfe8) 21. Bd2 {It was hard to improve the position further and White decides that it is a good time to start some action. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'It was hard to improve the position further and White decides that it is a good time to start some action.''} Qd6 22. Bb3 Bd7 $1 {Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: '!'' Creating tension in the center. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'Creating tension in the center.''} 23. Nf3 {Neither 23.exd5 cxd5 nor 23.dxe5 Nxe4 promise anything clear for White, so instead he maintains the tension. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'Neither 23.exd5 cxd5 nor 23.dxe5 Nxe4 promise anything clear for White, so instead he maintains the tension.''} Rfe8 $6 {Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: '?!'' So far Black has done quite okay, but the next phase of the game goes badly wrong for him. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'So far Black has done quite okay, but the next phase of the game goes badly wrong for him.''} 24. Qc2 {White's pieces are ready to activate themselves and Black had to realize that this is a point of no return. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'White's pieces are ready to activate themselves and Black had to realize that this is a point of no return.''} (24. Ne4 Qe7 25. Ng3 Qd6) (24. c4 Nf6 25. Bc3 Rxe1+ 26. Qxe1 Re8 27. Qd1 Ne5) 24... Ngf4 $2 {Tadic,Branko: '?!' Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: '?'' Too submissive. Now White gets the time he needs to regroup and go on the offensive. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'Too submissive. Now White gets the time he needs to regroup and go on the offensive.''} 25. Rad1 $1 {Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: '!'' Now the direct threat is d6 and at the same time, White is ready to up the heat with d4 coming up next. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'Now the direct threat is d6 and at the same time, White is ready to up the heat with d4 coming up next.''} Rxe1+ 26. Rxe1 Qf6 $2 {Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: '?'' Black doesn't have a good response to 27.d4, so he had to take with the knight instead. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'Black doesn't have a good response to 27.d4, so he had to take with the knight instead.''} 27. Nd4 $1 {Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: '!''} Rd8 {Tadic,Branko: 'Diagram [#]' This natural attempt to neutralize the d4 bishop has two tactical flaws. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'This natural attempt to neutralize the d4 bishop has two tactical flaws.''} 28. Re4 {Tadic,Branko: '!' This shot works quite well, but the computer points out that the simple 28.xe5! was even more efficient. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'This shot works quite well, but the computer points out that the simple 28.xe5! was even more efficient.''} Qg6 (28... c5) 29. Bxd5 {The tactics work for White, as he basically ends up up a pawn. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'The tactics work for White, as he basically ends up up a pawn.''} (29. Bxf4 Nxf4 30. Re7 Qxc2 31. Nxc2 Nd5 32. Bxd5 cxd5) 29... Nxd5 30. Ngf5 Qf6 31. Rg4 $2 {Tadic,Branko: 'Diagram [#] Giri,Anish: '?'' Trying to be clever almost backfired, as Firouzja overlooks a cute tactic, that doesn't win for Black only thanks to a very fortunate save. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'Trying to be clever almost backfired, as Firouzja overlooks a cute tactic, that doesn't win for Black only thanks to a very fortunate save.''} (31. Re1 c5 32. c4 cxd4 33. cxd5 Bb6 34. g4 Bxf5 35. Qxf5 Qxf5 36. gxf5 Rxd5) 31... g6 $1 {Tadic,Branko: '!!' Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: '!'' A beautiful resource, based on the back rank theme (Rxc6 Re1+). Now if White moves the rook, Black would remain up a piece, but fortunately for White he still has a way to keep the largest portion of his advantage.  Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'A beautiful resource, based on the back rank theme (Rxc6 Re1+). Now if White moves the rook, Black would remain up a piece, but fortunately for White he still has a way to keep the largest portion of his advantage. ''} (31... Kh8 32. Rxg7 $13 (32. Rh4 Bxf5 33. Nxf5 Ne7) (32. Qe4 Re8 33. Qf3 Re5) 32... c5 {Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish' Probably best, going for complications that will likely lead to lots of simplifications.} 33. Rh7+ (33. Bxh6 {(Tadic,Branko) - 127/116} cxd4 {(Tadic,Branko) - 142/115} 34. Nd6 Qxh6 35. Nxf7+ Kxg7 36. Nxh6 Kxh6) 33... Kxh7 34. Ne7+ Kh8 35. Nxd5 Bxa4 {White regains the piece, but is not fighting for any advantage here, as for example 27...b3!? leads to a comfortable endgame for Black, by force.} 36. Qxa4 {Tadic,Branko} Rxd5 {Tadic,Branko}) 32. Nxh6+ $1 {Tadic,Branko: '' Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: '!''} Kf8 $2 {Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: '?'' The alternatives were offering better chances to save the game. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'The alternatives were offering better chances to save the game.''} 33. Re4 {White ends up up a pawn in an endgame. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'White ends up up a pawn in an endgame.''} (33. Bg5 $1 {Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: '!'' Black had to create counterchances here and play more concrete. This move not only hits the g3 knight, but also guards the d6 square and now Ndf5 is no longer the same. Black is doing fine here, though the position is yet to clarify. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'Black had to create counterchances here and play more concrete. This move not only hits the g3 knight, but also guards the d6 square and now Ndf5 is no longer the same. Black is doing fine here, though the position is yet to clarify.''} Qd6 $1 {This was a strong shot here, when the position would be very double edged and White would have to show quite some accuracy here too, in order not to get into some trouble. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'This was a strong shot here, when the position would be very double edged and White would have to show quite some accuracy here too, in order not to get into some trouble.''} 34. Bxd8 Qh2+ $1 {Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: '!'' A positional pawn sacrifice- the point behind the 23...c5! break. The c5 pawn is in fact doomed and will eventually get surrounded and picked up. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'A positional pawn sacrifice- the point behind the 23...c5! break. The c5 pawn is in fact doomed and will eventually get surrounded and picked up.''} 35. Kf1 {Tadic,Branko} Bxg4 36. Nxg4 Qh1+ 37. Ke2 Nf4+ 38. Kd2 Bxd8) 33... Nf4 (33... g5 $16 34. Ng4 {Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish' This might have been Black's idea, but now the shot on g7 or h6 is even more powerful.} (34. Ndf5 Be6 {now 29.xg7 c5! as well as 29.xg7 xf5 30.xf5 d8! 31.Rc3 c5! gives Black a lot of counterplay, hitting the g2 pawn, but the simple and strong 29.f1! maintains some advantage, thought after 29...e5 30. xe5 xe5 Black is still in the game.}) 34... Qg6 35. Ne5 Bxe5 {And Black's position crumbles.} 36. Rxe5 {Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish' Here Black at least gets to activate his f6 knight, which gives chances for counterplay.} Qxc2 37. Nxc2 {The knight on f4 is also doing stuff and it turns out that capturing the g7 pawn leads to a mess that is quite favourable for Black.}) 34. Ng4 Bxg4 35. hxg4 {White is just up a pawn and has almost stabilsed. There was still a way for Black to fight on here. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'White is just up a pawn and has almost stabilsed. There was still a way for Black to fight on here.''} Kg7 $2 {Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: '?'' The final mistake, closing the a1-h8 diagonal, making the b2 pawn breath a sigh of relief, as Be5 is no longer an idea. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'The final mistake, closing the a1-h8 diagonal, making the b2 pawn breath a sigh of relief, as Be5 is no longer an idea.''} 36. Bxf4 $1 {Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: '!'' Now Black is done, as the h6 pawn needs protection and 37.d3 is queued up. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'Now Black is done, as the h6 pawn needs protection and 37.d3 is queued up.''} (36. Nf3 {Tadic,Branko}) 36... Bxf4 37. Nf5+ {Black had to be in time with Bd6-Rb8, but now the c8 rook is practically trapped for a trade and the bishop endgame is dead lost, slowly but surely. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'Black had to be in time with Bd6-Rb8, but now the c8 rook is practically trapped for a trade and the bishop endgame is dead lost, slowly but surely.''} gxf5 38. Rxf4 {Tadic,Branko: '+-' Black is down a pawn and is completely helpess here. Firouzja converts smoothly. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'Black is down a pawn and is completely helpess here. Firouzja converts smoothly.''} Qg5 39. Rxf5 Qxg4 40. Rf3 Qh5 41. c4 {The king is slowly making its entree. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'The king is slowly making its entree.''} Rd4 42. Qc3 Qe5 43. Rd3 c5 (43... Re4 44. Qxe5+ (44. Rg3+ Kf8 {White regains the exchange and ends up strategically winning, thanks to the powerful bishops. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'White regains the exchange and ends up strategically winning, thanks to the powerful bishops.''} 45. Kf1 Qxc3 46. Rxc3 {Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish'} b5 {White is quite simply winning, as the d4 bishop is unopposed and the attack is absolutely free, besides the large positional advantage.}) 44... Rxe5 {Tadic,Branko} 45. Re3 Rc5 46. b3 b5 $16 47. Re4 $1 {This is actually even cleaner. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'This is actually even cleaner.''}) 44. Rg3+ (44. Rxd4 cxd4 45. Qd2 {Black has quite some material for the queen. Now White has a strong sequence.} d3 $1 46. Qxd3 Qxb2 $1 {a simple double attack on the f7 and h6 pawns.}) (44. g3 Kg6 {and White is the one playing for a win here, but with some accurate play, Black is likely able to setup a succesful defense here.} 45. Re3 {Tadic,Branko} Rd1+ 46. Kg2 Qxc3 47. Rxc3 Rd4 {Was obviously the way to go, with a winning advantage, though work still had to be done after Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'Was obviously the way to go, with a winning advantage, though work still had to be done after''}) 44... Kf8 45. Qxa5 Rd1+ 46. Kh2 {All black pawns are weak and it is the d4 pawn that is falling first. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'All black pawns are weak and it is the d4 pawn that is falling first.''} Qh5+ 47. Rh3 Qe5+ 48. g3 Qf5 49. Qa8+ Ke7 50. Qxb7+ Rd7 51. Qh1 (51. Qg2 {Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish'} Rd2 {This endgame is terribly unpleasant for Black, but there are some drawish tendencies, thanks to the opposite coloured bishops and the fact that White hasn't yet mobilised his king.} 52. Kg1 {Is also a decent attempt at fighting on. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'Is also a decent attempt at fighting on.''} Rd1+ {Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish'} 53. Kh2 Rd2) 51... Qxf2+ 52. Qg2 Rd2 53. Qxf2 Rxf2+ 54. Kg1 Rxb2 55. Rh5 Ra2 56. Rxc5 Rxa4 57. Kg2 {The h5 pawn drops as well. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'The h5 pawn drops as well.''} Kd6 $1 {Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: '!'' Would actually still keep the game going. There is a threat of d4 followed by Rb8, while if White goes 36.Bd3 now, there is a strong reply 36...Be5!. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'Would actually still keep the game going. There is a threat of d4 followed by Rb8, while if White goes 36.Bd3 now, there is a strong reply 36...Be5!.''} 58. Rd5+ Ke6 $1 {Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish' And as Black will trade the dark squared bishops, White will still have quite some trouble converting this  (perhaps it is even holdable, objectively), as the b2 pawn will need protection.} 59. Rd4 {Now the variation is forced- Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'Now the variation is forced-''} Ke5 60. Rf4 f5 61. Kh3 Ra3 {Tadic,Branko: ''} 1-0


