1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Nf3 Nbd7 6. Bd3 dxc4 7. Bxc4 b5 8. Bd3 Bb7 9. O-O a6 {The set-up David Howell has chosen here is a solid way of meeting the 4 e3 Queen's Indian. There are clear similarities here with the Tal Variation of the Nimzo-Indian.} 10. e4 c5 11. d5 Qc7 12. dxe6 {The first new move.} fxe6 {Now this is pretty much forced, as otherwise Black has to worry about cxd5 and Bxa6.} 13. Bc2 c4 14. Qe2 Bd6 $1 15. Nd4 $6 {The c4-c5 advance is what White has been angling for, but it doesn't turn out well. The question is, though, what else does White do? Maybe Black is already at least equal after 14...f5.} Nc5 16. f4 e5 17. Ncxb5 axb5 18. Nxb5 $2 Qb6 19. Nxd6+ Qxd6 20. fxe5 Qxe5 21. Rf5 Qe7 22. Qxc4 $2 {Losing a pawn.} Ncd7 $1 (22... Rc8 23. Qb5+ Ncd7) 23. Bd2 Rc8 24. Qb3 Ba6 ({Earlier this year Glenn enjoyed a very quick win in this line:} 24... Rxc2 25. Qxc2 Bxe4 $2 26. Qc8+ $1 {(a nice shot)} Kf7 27. Qc4+ Qe6 28. Qxe6+ Kxe6 29. Rg5 $1 {(White has a winning attack)} g6 30. Bc3) (24... g6 25. Bb4 $1 (25. Qxb7 Rb8) 25... Qf7 (25... Nc5 {is the Tal Variation of the Nimzo-Indian (see below).} 26. Rxc5 Rxc5 27. Qe3 Nd7 28. Rd1) 26. Qxf7+ Kxf7 27. Rf2 Rhe8 (27... Kg7 28. Bc3) 28. Rd1 {1-0 Flear, G-Brunner, N/Montpellier 2015.} Kg7 29. Bc3 $1 {Black has to play} Ne5 {The most popular choice for Black has been} 30. Rd6 Nxe4 {and only now} (30... Bxe4 31. Rfxf6 Bxc2 32. Rfe6) 31. Bxe4 {The alternative is to release the tension in the centre with} Bxe4 32. Re2 {- see the notes to Mamedjarova, Z-Chiburdanidze, M/Calvia 2004.} Rc4 33. Rd4 Rxc3 34. bxc3 Bf5) 25. Bb4 Qf7 {Black is a clear pawn ahead with a good position, and David Howell goes on to convert his advantage without any real problems.} (25... Bc4 26. Bxe7 Bxb3 27. Bxb3 {with a slight edge for White} Kxe7 28. e5 Ne4 {is met by} 29. Rf7+ $1 Ke8 $2 30. e6 Ndc5 31. Bd5 Nf6 32. Bc4 Rb8 33. a4 {wins}) 26. Qa4 (26. e5 Qxb3 27. Bxb3 Ne4 28. Re1 g6 $1 29. Rf4 Nec5 (29... Bb7 $4 30. Rf7 {or} Ndc5 31. e6 Bc6 32. Bc2) 30. e6 Nxb3 $1 (30... Nb6 $2 31. e7) 31. exd7+ Kxd7 32. Rf7+ Kc6 33. axb3 {White has won the exchange, but Black has a pawn and the two bishops as some compensation.}) 26... Qe6 (26... Qc4 27. Re5+ Kd8 28. Ba5+ Rc7 29. Rd1 Kc8 30. Bxc7 Kxc7 31. Qxc4+ Bxc4 32. Re7 Kd8 {1/2-1/2 was Petrosian, A-Schlosser, P/Budapest 1991.} 33. Rxg7 $1 {seems to be critical. Indeed c4-c5 is the consistent follow-up to 11 Rc1 and probably explains why Black normally chooses to play ...dxc4 followed by ...c5 to avoid this.}) 27. Rd1 Rc4 (27... Rc6 28. Bb3 $1 {is stronger.} Qxe4 $1 $17 (28... Bc4 29. Qa8+ Kf7 30. Qxh8) 29. Re1 $1 {keeps White's pieces more active and restricts Black's advantage.} Rc1 $5 30. Rff1 {is also possible.}) 28. Kh1 (28. Rd6 Qxd6 29. Bxd6 Rxa4 30. Bxa4 Bd3 31. Ra5 Bxe4 (31... Kf7 32. e5) 32. Re5+ Kd8 33. Be7+ Kc7 34. Bxd7 Kxd7 35. Bxf6 gxf6 36. Rxe4) 28... Bb7 29. Qb3 (29. Rg5 Ng4) 29... Rc6 30. e5 (30. Qxe6+ Rxe6 31. e5 Nd5 32. Bb3 Rb6 33. Bd2 Rf8) 30... Ng4 (30... Nd5) 31. Re1 (31. Qxe6+ Rxe6 32. Rxd7 Bxg2+ (32... Kxd7 33. Rf7+) 33. Kxg2 Kxd7 34. Rf7+ Ke8 35. Rf3 Rxe5 (35... Nxe5 36. Re3 Kd8 37. Bf5) 36. Ba4+ Kd8 37. Rd3+) 31... Qh6 (31... Rc4 32. h3 Bd5) 32. Qf7+ Kd8 33. Rh5 Qe6 (33... Rxc2 34. Rxh6 Nxh6 35. Qb3) 34. Qxe6 Rxe6 35. Bf5 0-1


