1. c4 {Damljanovic,Branko} Nf6 2. Nc3 e5 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. g3 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Bg2 Nb6 7. O-O Be7 8. a3 O-O 9. b4 Be6 10. d3 f6 11. Ne4 {This is the opening from the 11th game of the World Championship match between Anand and Topalov this May.} a5 $2 $146 {#My opponent tried to improve on Topalov's play with this move, however I think it is premature as it weakens his pawns.} 12. Nc5 Bxc5 13. bxc5 {Now the b7 pawn becomes vulnerable. With the pawn still on a7, he would have the option of playing b6.} Nd7 {Damljanovic,Branko: 'N?!' #Black's plan is to play Bd5 and take control of the diagonal so I played} (13... Nd5 {(Damljanovic,Branko) Ü 109/(13)}) 14. d4 $1 (14. Be3 $5 {Damljanovic,Branko}) 14... e4 ({Black could take with} 14... exd4 15. Nxd4 Nxc5 {but this would be very dangerous because after} 16. Nxe6 (16. Nxc6 {Damljanovic,Branko} bxc6 17. Be3 Nb3 18. Rb1 Qxd1 19. Rfxd1 Ra6 20. Rd3 a4 21. Rc3 $14) 16... Nxe6 17. Qb3 {I have fantastic compensation for the pawn with the two bishops and the open position. I would play Be3 followed by Rfd1 and Rac1. A kind of Catalan, but a very good kind.} (17. Rb1 {Damljanovic,Branko} Qxd1 18. Rxd1 Rad8 19. Rd2 $14)) 15. Nh4 {He now played} Bd5 {but after} ({He doesn't have the time to play} 15... f5 $2 {because of} 16. d5) (15... g5 $6 {Damljanovic,Branko} 16. d5 $16 Nxc5 $145 17. dxe6 Qxd1 18. Rxd1 gxh4 19. Be3 Nxe6 20. Bxe4 hxg3 21. hxg3 { ab1}) 16. Nf5 {Damljanovic,Branko: '' I take control because the bishop cannot hold its position as the knight will kick it off.} Qe8 (16... a4 {Damljanovic,Branko} 17. Rb1 Ra7 18. Ne3 Bb3 19. Rxb3 axb3 20. Bxe4 $16) 17. Bf4 {is a good intermediary move since he must protect it with} Rc8 18. Rb1 {It is now difficult for him to protect the position from all sides.} g5 {I was happy to have provoked this because it weakens the king which will be telling in the long run.} ({If he had played} 18... b6 {instead, I would have} 19. cxb6 Nxb6 20. Bxc7 {winning a pawn.}) ({or} 18... Ne7 19. Ne3 g5 20. Bd6 $1 cxd6 21. cxd6 {Black's position collapses.}) 19. Bd2 b6 20. Qa4 (20. Ne3 {Damljanovic,Branko} Ba2 21. Rb2 Qe6 22. Rxa2 Qxa2 23. Bxe4 Ne7 24. Qc1 Kh8 25. c6) 20... Qe6 21. Bh3 ({Another move was} 21. Ne3 Ne7 {to prevent Bh3 as in the game.} (21... bxc5 $2 {isn't possible because of} 22. dxc5 Nxc5 23. Qb5) 22. Rfc1 {and it is very difficult for Black to withstand all this pressure.}) 21... Kh8 {#} 22. Ne3 $1 {The point behind 21.Bh3.} Qxh3 (22... f5 $145 {Damljanovic,Branko} 23. cxb6 Nxb6 (23... cxb6 24. Rb5 $16) 24. Qc2 g4 25. Bg2 $16 Nxd4 $2 26. Bc3 c5 27. Rxb6 $18) 23. Nxd5 {This exchanges off his strong bishop but more importantly it frees up the option of advancing d5.} Qe6 24. Ne3 Ne7 25. Rfd1 Rfd8 26. Rbc1 (26. Be1 {(Damljanovic,Branko)  b5, d5+-}) 26... Nf8 (26... Nd5 {is unplayable due to} 27. Qb3 Nf8 28. cxb6 {and White wins a pawn.}) 27. cxb6 cxb6 28. Rxc8 {The problem is that whichever piece he takes with on c8 is one that helped control the d5 square.} Rxc8 29. Qb5 {A key move preparing d5.} Rd8 {#} (29... Qc6 $142 {Damljanovic,Branko} 30. Qb1) 30. d5 $1 {Damljanovic,Branko: '+-' The loss of a pawn with} Nxd5 {is protected by the tactic} 31. Bxa5 bxa5 ({If} 31... Nc7 {then} 32. Qxb6) 32. Rxd5 Rxd5 33. Nxd5 {Black's position has so many weaknesses, I believe that a pawn loss is probably forced.} a4 34. Ne3 {A nice move. It will join the attack now.} Qd7 35. Qb4 Qe8 36. Nf5 Kg8 37. Qb7 Qd7 38. Qxe4 Ne6 39. Qc4 Kf8 40. Ne3 Qe7 {This blunders a pawn, but even without this the position was absolutely won.} 41. Qxa4 1-0


