{The following game between the young Indian prodigy and strong English Grandmaster was really entertaining. Gukesh is a rising star, while Howell is an experienced player who played quite well throughout the event and shared the 3rd place in the end making the best of Aronian's reckless play in the last round.} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 d5 3. Bg2 e6 4. O-O Be7 5. d4 b5 {A very popular move nowadays.} 6. a4 b4 7. c4 (7. Nbd2 {Ribli,Zoltan 2605 - Luther,Thomas 2510, Tilburg 1994 - 61/365}) 7... bxc3 8. Nxc3 O-O ({Also, it is possible to continue with} 8... Nbd7 9. Bf4 c6 10. Rc1 Ba6 11. b4 Bxb4 (11... Nh5 12. Bd2 O-O 13. b5 cxb5 14. axb5 Bb7 {(Harikrishna,Penteala 2551 - Sasikiran,Krishnan 2670, Hastings 2002/03)} 15. Ne5 $14) 12. Na2 Ba5 13. Rxc6 Bc4 14. Qc2 Rc8 15. Rxc8 Qxc8 16. Nd2 Nb6 $13) 9. Bf4 ({A rather interesting is} 9. Ne5 Nfd7 10. Nd3 Nc6 11. e4 Nf6 12. exd5 exd5 13. Ne5 $14 {Leiva,Giuseppe 2427 - Santiago, Yago de Moura 2453, Florianopolis (zt) 2017}) 9... a5 $146 ({Known moves are:} 9... Nbd7 10. Nb5 Ne8 11. Rc1 c5 12. e4 $36 {Dilanyan,Grigor 2281 - Kalashian, David 2409, Armenia 2013}) (9... c5 10. Rc1 (10. Nb5 Na6 11. dxc5 Bxc5 12. Rc1 $11 {Manog,Mondo - Rupp,Markus 2243, Internet (blitz) 2004}) 10... Qb6 {(Simonsen,Hans Kristian 2240 - Thinius,Marco 2389, Gausdal 2003)} 11. e4 $5 $36) (9... c6 10. Ne5 Nfd7 11. Nd3 a5 12. e4 Na6 13. exd5 exd5 14. Re1 Bf6 15. Ne2 Re8 $13 {Bluebaum,Matthias 2620 - Prusikin,Michael 2510, Deutschland 2018}) 10. Rc1 c6 11. Ne5 ({White should play} 11. Re1 {and after} Ba6 12. e4 $14) 11... Ba6 12. Qd2 Nfd7 13. Nxd7 ({White is well advised to try} 13. Nf3 $14) 13... Nxd7 $11 14. Rfd1 Qb6 15. e4 Rfc8 16. exd5 {Too early opening of the position.} ({Interesting here is} 16. h4 $11) 16... cxd5 $15 17. Bf1 Bxf1 18. Kxf1 ({White should try to keep his king safe:} 18. Rxf1 Rc4 19. Ne2 $15) 18... Rc4 19. Ne2 Nf6 20. Rxc4 dxc4 21. Be3 ({A bit better was} 21. Nc3 $15) 21... Qc6 $17 22. Qc2 (22. Rc1 $17 {was necessary at this point.}) 22... Qh1+ 23. Ng1 Rc8 (23... Qxh2 $142 24. Nf3 Qh5 $17) 24. f3 (24. Bg5 $17 {offers a better defence.}) 24... Nd5 25. Bc1 h5 26. Qf2 c3 27. bxc3 Rxc3 {Diagram [#]} 28. Bd2 $2 (28. Bf4) 28... Rc2 $19 29. Rc1 Ra2 30. Qe2 Kh7 ({A bit simpler for Black is} 30... Bb4 31. Qd3 Ne3+ $1 32. Qxe3 Rxd2 33. Qxd2 Bxd2 $19) 31. Rc8 (31. Rc2 Rxc2 32. Qe4+ Kg8 33. Qxc2 Qxh2) 31... g6 (31... Bb4 32. Rc2 Bxd2 33. Qd3+ g6 34. Rxa2 Ne3+ 35. Qxe3 Bxe3) 32. Qe5 Bf6 33. Qd6 Rxd2 0-1


