1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. g4 Be4 {A nice move to throw in before allowing e6.} ({For} 4... Bd7 {see Ponkratov-Fedoseev, European Hybrid 2021 in the archives.}) 5. f3 Bg6 6. e6 Qd6 (6... c5 $5 {is noteworthy, trying to establish a 2v0 or even 3v0 central majority. After something like} 7. h4 $5 fxe6 8. h5 Bf7 9. f4 cxd4 $13 {the position is not simple, but White has reasonable chances of control with a normal Nd2-f3, Ne2 plan.}) ({In the above-mentioned game I noted} 6... fxe6 {as the best move, and would have to stick with that recommendation for now.}) 7. exf7+ Bxf7 8. Nc3 {White temporarily avoids f4, which can have (limited) specific uses for a tempo or two.} ({Another recent test saw} 8. f4 {which was a move I noted in July as well:} Nf6 9. Nc3 Nbd7 10. Be2 (10. Bh3 $1 {looks temporarily more awkward but is actually better as it allows White to develop normally with Nf3 next. For instance} g6 11. Nf3 Bg7 12. Ne5 Be6 13. Qe2 $14 {and Black will still need to answer a couple of questions, as well as timing ...c5 exactly right. My feeling is that if those things can be done there is no reason they are not equal.}) 10... h6 $1 11. h3 {White needs to play Nf3, but this move creates more holes.} g5 $1 12. fxg5 $6 {and here in Tsydypov,Z-Bryakin,M Sochi 2021 Black could have opted for} Ne4 $1 {, with a very significant lead in development that is rapidly translating into an attack.}) 8... Nd7 {Prompting White more strongly to push f4.} (8... e5 {In this case, it may be Black that holds off opening the centre due to worse development.} 9. dxe5 Qxe5+ 10. Nge2 Nd7 11. Bf4 $14) 9. f4 e6 $5 {This pawn will wind up backward for the rest of the game, but there is nothing in this move to arouse suspicion about Black's position yet.} ({Of course,} 9... Ngf6 {transposes to the 8.f4 note.}) 10. Be3 h5 ({The computer recommends the incisive} 10... Qc7 {followed by either ... Bb4 or ...Bd6, and keeping an open mind about where the g8-knight is going.}) 11. g5 Ne7 12. Qd2 {White develops the pieces in a slightly strange order, though there is nothing seriously wrong with it.} (12. Nf3 {was the most natural, with one marginal benefit being that after} Bg6 {White can react} 13. Bd3 $5 {and the queen will be able to recapture in one move.}) 12... Qc7 13. O-O-O Bg6 {An interesting moment. It is of course important that this bishop avoids getting buried, but for now the f5-square was actually better off used by the knight.} (13... Nf5 $1 14. Bd3 (14. Nf3 Bd6 {is close to forcing} 15. Ne5 {, after which Black's structural problem is gone.} Nxe5 16. fxe5 Bb4 $36) 14... Bb4 15. Re1 (15. Nf3 Bxc3 $1 16. bxc3 Bg6 $15) (15. Bxf5 exf5 $11 {Black's f7-bishop will always have ways out, and being able to capture like this just remedies the structure nicely.}) 15... Bg6 {Black is about to castle short to attack the f4-pawn, and the time has come for White to make a decision regarding the g1-knight.} 16. Nf3 (16. Nge2 $6 Nb6 $17 {Now there is no problem deserting the e5-square, and so Black can threaten ...Nc4.}) 16... O-O 17. a3 Bd6 18. Ne5 {To relieve the pressure White ultimately has to do this anyway.} Bxe5 19. fxe5 Nb6 $11 {After a likely future exchange of light-squared bishops, I would marginally prefer playing Black's position.}) 14. Nf3 Nf5 15. Bd3 Bb4 (15... Bd6 {now doesn't force anything in particular since White can just play} 16. Kb1 $14 {and the e6-pawn will hang in any line where Black takes on e3.}) 16. a3 Bxc3 (16... Ba5 $5) 17. Qxc3 O-O 18. Bd2 {White has sealed both the bishop-pair and a permanent weakness on e6, two things that are not easily taken away.} b6 ({There is no time for, for example,} 18... Ne7 $2 19. Rde1 Bxd3 20. Qxd3 $16 {and the e6-pawn is likely to simply go missing.}) 19. Rde1 $14 Rfe8 20. Re2 Qd6 21. Rhe1 a5 22. Ne5 ({The forcing} 22. Bxf5 {is also a bit interesting, if inhuman.} Bxf5 (22... exf5 23. Rxe8+ Rxe8 24. Rxe8+ Bxe8 25. b4 $1 axb4 26. Qe3 $36) 23. Nh4 Be4 24. f5 $1 {Intending f6 to break open the kingside, and leveraging that possibility to effectuate a useful trade of minor pieces.} exf5 25. Nxf5 Qg6 26. Ng3 $14) 22... Nxe5 23. Rxe5 Kf7 $1 {Black has played the last couple of moves quite well and it's not clear if White will be able to find something constructive to do, or if Black will start to roll forwards from this point. There are ideas like ...Nh4 in the pipeline.} 24. Qb3 {White extracts the queen from the temporary awkwardness of being stuck defending the d4-pawn, which is certainly constructive but also gives Black the possibility of breaking with ...c5.} Rab8 25. c3 (25. c4 $5 {is possible to try and open things for the bishop-pair, using the detail that} Nxd4 $2 {fails to} 26. Bxg6+ Kxg6 27. Qe3 $1 dxc4 28. Bc3 $16 {winning back the critical e6-pawn together with at least one of its friends on c6 or c4.}) 25... c5 $1 26. Qa4 Re7 (26... c4 $5 {made sense as well, followed by seeing after} 27. Bb1 $13 {whether it's possible to arrange a light-squared bishop trade or a ...b5 push. One idea might be to walk Black's king all the way to a6.}) 27. dxc5 {Presumably relieved that Black didn't close up the position entirely on the previous move, White takes his chances on opening it.} bxc5 28. Qxa5 c4 29. Bxf5 {Now this is more practical than keeping the bishop. White constantly thinks about sacrificing the exchange on f5 from here on, counting on the power of a centralised bishop on d4 and e5 plus the pawn that has already been snaffled.} Bxf5 30. Be3 Reb7 31. Re2 Kg6 32. Bd4 Rc8 (32... Rb3 $11) 33. Qa4 h4 $2 {David is understandably keen to play for a win and not just await White's choice of either consolidation (h4 etc.) or an exchange sacrifice (Rxf5.) In an ideal world, this pawn advances onward to h3 and creates a pathway for a black rook to enter White's position: h8-h4-g4.} ({While White does have everything defended, there is still some traction in playing} 33... Rcb8 {followed by ...Rb3 and possibly trying to triple, to isolate White's queen and tie down the rest of White's pieces to b2.}) 34. Qd1 Ra8 (34... h3 35. Qe1 Rc6 (35... Re7 36. Rxf5 Kxf5 37. Re5+ Kg6 38. f5+ $18) 36. Rxf5 exf5 37. Re5 Qd7 38. Qe3 $16) 35. Qe1 Ra6 (35... Kh5 {deserves consideration, protecting the h4-pawn and escaping from the Rxe6 ideas. However, White breaks through in a new way:} 36. g6 $1 {Threatening Rg2-g5.} Rxa3 $5 37. Rxf5+ exf5 38. bxa3 Qxa3+ 39. Kd2 $18) 36. Qxh4 Qf8 37. Qe1 $2 {Creating an unfortunate alignment of queen and king along the back rank, which Black could have exploited.} ({A solid move like} 37. Qg3 {would have kept a huge advantage.}) 37... Kh7 ({I am sure that after} 37... Rxa3 {White was relying on} 38. Rxe6+ {, but Black has an answer.} Kh5 $3 {The king actually can't be checked here! But the move looks so unlikely as to evade consideration completely, especially in time-trouble.} (38... Kf7 $4 39. g6+ (39. Re7+ $2 Kg6 {and the game continues}) 39... Bxg6 (39... Kg8 40. bxa3 Rb1+ 41. Kd2 Rxe1 42. Kxe1 Bxe6 43. Rxe6 $18) 40. Re7+ Rxe7 41. Rxe7+ Qxe7 42. Qxe7+ Kxe7 43. bxa3 $18) (38... Kh7 39. Qh4+ Kg8 40. bxa3 $18)) 38. g6+ $1 {Back on track. Black won't get any more chances to create devious king pathways through the light squares.} Bxg6 39. Qh4+ Kg8 40. Rg5 Rxa3 41. Rxg6 Ra1+ 42. Kd2 Qf5 43. Qd8+ Kh7 44. Rh6+ $3 {A Carlsenesque move. The game is over.} gxh6 45. Qh8+ Kg6 46. Rg2+ Kh5 47. Rg5+ Qxg5 48. fxg5 Rxb2+ 49. Ke3 Kg4 50. h3+ Kxh3 51. Qxh6+ Kg2 52. Qh4 Rf1 53. Qg4+ Kh1 54. Qh3+ Kg1 55. Qxe6 Rff2 56. Qg4+ Kf1 57. Qd1+ Kg2 58. g6 Rb8 59. Qg4+ Kf1 60. Qh3+ Ke1 61. Qh1+ Rf1 62. Qh2 Re8+ 63. Be5 d4+ 64. cxd4 1-0


