{It seems that this time Mark Hebden was ready to sacrifice a queen but his opponent chose a different line. Nevertheless, it was White who came up with a novelty. It was not too dangerous for Black, but to play such messy positions over the board and analyse them with a powerful computer are two big differences... Black was unable to find the right path and soon found himself terribly lost. However, then it was White's turn to blunder, after which Black got winning chances, which he converted into a full point only after some more mistakes from his opponent.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6 4. Bg5 dxc4 5. Nc3 c6 6. e4 b5 7. e5 h6 8. Bh4 g5 9. Nxg5 hxg5 10. Bxg5 Nbd7 11. exf6 Bb7 12. g3 c5 13. d5 Qb6 14. Bg2 O-O-O 15. O-O b4 16. Na4 Qa6 17. a3 Bxd5 18. Bxd5 Ne5 19. axb4 Rxd5 20. Qe2 cxb4 21. Nc3 Ra5 22. Rxa5 Qxa5 23. Ne4 Nd3 24. Be3 Qh5 25. f3 Qe5 26. Qc2 Qb5 27. Nd2 {This logical manoeuvre is a novelty. However, Black has got an adequate response.} ({White has recently tried} 27. b3 $5 {- see the game Krush - Becerra Rivero/USA-ch Saint Louis 2009, for details.}) 27... Nxb2 $1 28. Qxb2 (28. Rb1 {did not promise anything:} Bc5 ({or} 28... c3 $5 29. Rxb2 Qe2 $1 30. Nf1 (30. Qe4 cxb2 31. Qa8+ Kd7 32. Qb7+ Kd8 33. Qb8+ Kd7 $11) 30... Qxc2 31. Rxc2 Kb7 32. Kf2 a5 {with more than sufficient compensation for the piece thanks to the strong Q-side passers, for example:} 33. Ke2 Kc6 34. Kd3 Kb5 35. Bd4 a4 {and so on}) 29. Bxc5 Qxc5+ 30. Kg2 Nd3 31. Nxc4 Rd8 32. Rd1 b3 $1 33. Qxb3 (33. Nd6+ $4 Rxd6 34. Qxc5+ Nxc5 35. Rxd6 b2 36. Rd1 Nd3 37. Rb1 a5 $19) 33... Qf2+ 34. Kh1 Qxf3+ {and Black at least gives perpetual check but probably not more than that.}) 28... c3 29. Qa2 ({A tempting} 29. Rc1 {could be well met by} Qe2 $1 {forcing White to sacrifice his rook by} 30. Rxc3+ bxc3 31. Qxc3+ {with numerous repetitions of moves. For example,} Kb7 32. Qd4 ({or} 32. Qb3+ Ka8 33. Qc3 Qxh2+ 34. Kf1 Qh1+ 35. Ke2 Bh6 36. Qc6+ Kb8 37. Qd6+ $11) 32... Qxh2+ 33. Kf1 Qh1+ 34. Ke2 Qc1 $1 35. Qxa7+ Kc8 36. Qxf7 (36. Qa6+ Kd7 37. Qd3+ Kc8 38. Qa6+ $11 {was always there}) 36... Rh2+ 37. Kd3 Qa3+ 38. Ke4 Qb4+ 39. Kd3 $11 {with a draw.}) 29... cxd2 $4 {Such opening lines have to be thoroughly studied at home - otherwise the first independent move might become the last one! This natural capture gives White a decisive attack.} (29... Bc5 $1 {should have been played:} 30. Bxc5 ({White could have secured his extra piece by} 30. Qc4 $2 {but it was bad for him!} Rh5 $1 31. Kg2 ({or} 31. Bxc5 Qxc4 32. Nxc4 Rxc5 33. Nd6+ Kc7 34. Ne4 (34. Nxf7 c2 $19) 34... Rc6 $19 {and Black's pawns are unstoppable}) (31. Bf2 Qxc4 32. Nxc4 b3 $19) 31... Qxc4 32. Nxc4 Bxe3 33. Nxe3 b3 {and Black's Q-side pawns decide the game. For example,} 34. g4 Rb5 35. Nd1 c2 36. Nb2 a5 37. Kf2 (37. Rc1 Rb4 38. g5 Kd7 $19) (37. Kg3 Rd5 38. h4 a4 $19) 37... a4 $1 38. Nxa4 Ra5 39. Ke3 (39. Nb2 Ra2 $19) 39... Rxa4 40. Kd2 Kd7 $19) 30... Qxc5+ 31. Kg2 cxd2 32. Qxd2 Rd8 33. Qf4 {with a very complicated position. A possible line would be} Kb7 34. Rc1 Qd6 35. Qc4 Kb6 36. h4 a5 37. h5 {- here any result seems to be possible, but everything might still be ended with some repetition of moves.}) 30. Qxd2 Qd5 31. Rc1+ Kb7 32. Qc2 Qd7 (32... Bd6 33. Qa4 {was equally bad for Black.}) 33. Qa2 $1 a6 34. Qa5 Qd6 {The only defence.} 35. Bc5 $6 {This move does not spoil the decisive advantage but White had a more convincing one.} (35. Qa4 $6 {could be met by} Bh6 $1 36. f4 Rd8) ({but after a preliminary, though rather difficult to find} 35. f4 $1 {Black had no defence against Qa5-a4 and Rc1-d1:} Rg8 ({or} 35... Bh6 36. Rc5 Qd1+ 37. Kf2 $18) 36. Qa4 Bh6 37. Rd1 $18 {with a mating attack.}) 35... Qc6 36. Qxb4+ Ka8 37. Kg2 Rh5 {This move loses on the spot but at least it gives a concrete problem to White.} ({A routine} 37... Qb5 38. Qe4+ Qb7 39. Qe2 Qb5 40. Qe5 $18 {left White almost no chances to go wrong.}) 38. Rb1 $4 {And it works! Most probably, White thought the game is over...} (38. Rd1 $1 $18 {was correct:} Rxc5 (38... Rd5 39. Rxd5 exd5 40. Bxf8) 39. Rd8+ Qc8 40. Rxc8+ Rxc8 41. Qb6 $18) 38... Bd6 $3 $15 {In fact it only begins!} ({Perhaps White only calculated a simple line} 38... Qc8 39. Qe4+ $1 Rd5 40. Bxf8 Qxf8 41. Qc4 $18) 39. Bxd6 $6 {Being shocked, White fails to offer tougher resistance.} ({After} 39. Qg4 $1 Rxc5 40. Qg8+ Qc8 41. Qxf7 {Black still had to do good work.}) 39... Qc2+ 40. Kg1 Rb5 ({Surely not} 40... Qxh2+ $4 41. Kf1 Qh1+ 42. Ke2 Rh2+ 43. Ke3 $18) 41. Qe4+ Qxe4 42. fxe4 Rxb1+ 43. Kg2 {Black has got an extra exchange in the ending and his a-pawn will certainly cost White his bishop. However, the position might still be drawish as White's K-side pawns might begin rolling.} Rb2+ 44. Kh3 Kb7 45. g4 Kc6 $2 {This natural move probably spoils the win but it wasn't trivial.} (45... Rb3+ $1 {seemed to be the right way:} 46. Kg2 (46. Kh4 $6 {was less stubborn:} e5 $3 47. Bxe5 Kc6 48. g5 Kd7 49. Kg4 a5 50. h4 Ke6 51. Ba1 a4 52. h5 Rb1 53. Bc3 a3 $19) 46... e5 $3 {Only this pawn advance, which makes White's bishop unstable, keeps Black's winning chances alive.} 47. Bxe5 Kc6 48. g5 Kd7 {and Black should be winning but still a lot of work has to be done:} 49. Bf4 (49. h4 Re3) 49... a5 50. h4 a4 51. h5 a3 52. g6 a2 53. Be5 Rb5 54. gxf7 Rxe5 55. f8=Q a1=Q 56. Qf7+ Kd6 57. Qf8+ Kc7 58. Qf7+ Kb6 59. Qb3+ Kc5 {and so on.}) 46. e5 Kd7 47. Kg3 (47. g5 {was simpler:} Ke8 48. Kg3 a5 49. h4 {and White was completely okay:} Rb3+ 50. Kg4 Rb1 51. h5 Rg1+ 52. Kf4 a4 53. h6 {and Black had no chance to go through the a3-square without being destroyed.}) 47... a5 48. h4 $2 {For some reason White refrained from the g-pawn advance, which could have saved him.} (48. g5 $1 Rb1 49. Kg2 $1 Ke8 (49... a4 $4 50. g6 $1) 50. h4 {was a dead draw.}) 48... a4 49. Kf4 (49. g5 {was already late due to} a3 $1) 49... Rb3 50. g5 a3 51. g6 a2 $1 52. gxf7 a1=Q 53. f8=N+ $5 {This is just to delay the inevitable.} (53. f8=Q {led to a quick mate after} Qd4+ 54. Kg5 Rg3+) 53... Ke8 54. Nxe6 Qa4+ {White resigned.} 0-1


