{Rogozenco,D: 'Rogozenco,Dorian: 'Vigorito, D: 'When I saw the pairing for the London Chess Classic, I expected this battle: one of the world's foremost 2.c3 Sicilian practitioners against the world 1 rated player! In the game we see an interesting semi-novelty at a very early stage.'''} 1. e4 {Rogozenco,D Rogozenco,D Rogozenco,D Rogozenco Rogozenco,D: 'Rogozenco,Dorian'} c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 e6 6. Be3 {Rogozenco,D: 'Rogozenco,Dorian: 'Vigorito, D: 'This is the most popular move nowadays. Alternatives are aplenty:''' This move is supposed to force Black to exchange pawns on d4.'This move is supposed to force Black to exchange pawns on d4. Vigorito, D: 'Rogozenco,D: 'This move is supposed to force Black to exchange pawns on d4.'''} (6. Na3 {(Rogozenco,D) Rogozenco,Dorian}) (6. Be2 {(Rogozenco,D) Rogozenco,Dorian}) (6. Bd3 {(Rogozenco,D) Rogozenco,Dorian}) (6. a3 $5 {(Rogozenco,D) Rogozenco,Dorian}) 6... Be7 $5 {Rogozenco,D: 'Rogozenco,Dorian: 'Vigorito, D: 'This move is not even mentioned in Rozentalis's authoritative 2002 (has it been that long?!) book. Carlsen is not afraid to give up a pawn.''' In most of the games Black automatically takes on d4, but Carlsen shows that the rare 6...e7 is a reasonable option as well. Especially since he declared later on "I was well prepared in this variation". 'In most of the games Black automatically takes on d4, but Carlsen shows that the rare 6...e7 is a reasonable option as well. Especially since he declared later on "I was well prepared in this variation".  Vigorito, D: 'Rogozenco,D: 'In most of the games Black automatically takes on d4, but Carlsen shows that the rare 6...e7 is a reasonable option as well. Especially since he declared later on "I was well prepared in this variation". '''} (6... cxd4 {(Rogozenco,D) (Rogozenco,Dorian) is the main move.}) 7. dxc5 {Rogozenco,D: 'Rogozenco,Dorian: 'Vigorito, D: 'Of course. The whole point of 6.Be3 is to 'force' Black to exchange on d4!'''} Qxd1+ 8. Kxd1 O-O {Rogozenco,D: 'Rogozenco,Dorian: 'Vigorito, D: 'Black is ahead in development and has ideas like ...Ng4 and ...Nd5 available. White must try to hold onto the pawn. I imagine we will see more of this position in the future.'''} 9. Nbd2 Ng4 {This position has occurred only three times in praxis. 'This position has occurred only three times in praxis.  Vigorito, D: 'Rogozenco,D: 'This position has occurred only three times in praxis. '''} 10. Nb3 $146 {'Vigorito, D: 'Rogozenco,D: 'N''' Faced with a rare variation and a well prepared opponent, Howell understandably tries to play as safe as possible. However, thanks to the bishop pair (there will be an exchange on e3 sooner or later) now Black can fight for advantage in a quiet and pleasant position.'Faced with a rare variation and a well prepared opponent, Howell understandably tries to play as safe as possible. However, thanks to the bishop pair (there will be an exchange on e3 sooner or later) now Black can fight for advantage in a quiet and pleasant position. Vigorito, D: 'Rogozenco,D: 'Faced with a rare variation and a well prepared opponent, Howell understandably tries to play as safe as possible. However, thanks to the bishop pair (there will be an exchange on e3 sooner or later) now Black can fight for advantage in a quiet and pleasant position.'''} ({Rogozenco,D: 'Rogozenco,Dorian: 'Vigorito, D: 'A prudent choice.''' The most principled continuation is'The most principled continuation is Vigorito, D: 'Rogozenco,D: 'The most principled continuation is'''} 10. b4 {which was played in previous games and which is probably the only way to test the viability of 6...e7. Then after'which was played in previous games and which is probably the only way to test the viability of 6...e7. Then after Vigorito, D: 'Rogozenco,D: 'which was played in previous games and which is probably the only way to test the viability of 6...e7. Then after'''} a5 ({The exchange on e3 is premature:} 10... Nxe3+ 11. fxe3 a5 12. Nd4 Rd8 13. Kc2 axb4 14. cxb4 Bf6 (14... e5 15. N4b3 Bf5+ 16. e4) 15. Bb5 Bxd4 16. exd4 Rxd4 17. Nc4 e5 18. Kc3 $16 {1-0 Murariu,A (2430)-Doncea,V (2380)/Baile Tusnad 2005 (33)}) {White can continue} 11. Kc2 {In order to evaluate precisely this complicated position practical examples are needed. In most cases Black wins back the pawn, but in return White gains more space on the queenside. The following variations show that in spite of his exposed king, there are hopes for White to achieve some advantage:} (11. Nd4 Rd8 $5 (11... axb4 12. cxb4 Rd8 13. Kc2 Bf6 (13... e5 $44) 14. N2b3 e5 15. Nb5 Nc6 16. a3 Bf5+ 17. Kc3 e4+ 18. N3d4 Nxd4 (18... b6 $142 $44) 19. Nxd4 Rac8 20. Bb5 b6 21. c6 Bxd4+ 22. Bxd4 Bd7 23. Bxb6 Bxc6 24. Bc4 $16 {0-1 Seret,J (2455)-Adorjan,A (2565)/Luzern 1985 (77)}) 12. Kc2 $140 e5 $36 13. N4b3 Bf5+ {Now the advantage of postponing exchanges both on b4 and on e3 become clear. White doesn't have e3-e4 (as in case of an earlier exchange on e3), nor can he play} 14. Kb2 {in view of} a4 15. Na5 Nxe3 {winning a piece.}) (11. Bc4 {Rogozenco,D: 'Rogozenco,Dorian: 'Vigorito, D: '?!''' Rogozenco,D: 'Rogozenco,Dorian: 'Vigorito, D: '?!' '?!'''} axb4 12. cxb4 Nc6 $44 13. b5 Nb4 14. Ne4 Nxe3+ 15. fxe3 Ra3 16. Re1 Rd8+ 17. Kc1 f5 18. Ned2 Rc3+ {Rogozenco,D: 'Rogozenco,Dorian: 'Vigorito, D: '!''' Rogozenco,D: 'Rogozenco,Dorian: 'Vigorito, D: '!' '!'''} (18... Bxc5 $17 {(Rogozenco,D) Rogozenco,Dorian}) 19. Kb2 Bf6 20. Nd4 Rxe3 {Rogozenco,D: 'Rogozenco,Dorian: 'Vigorito, D: '!' Vigorito, D: 'gave Black a winning position in Van de Oudeweetering, A (2369) -Pavlovic, M (2545)/Amsterdam 2004 although Black somehow went on to lose....''' Rogozenco,D: 'Rogozenco,Dorian: 'Vigorito, D: '!' '!' Vigorito, D: 'gave Black a winning position in Van de Oudeweetering, A (2369) -Pavlovic, M (2545)/Amsterdam 2004 although Black somehow went on to lose....'''} 21. Rxe3 Rxd4 22. Kb3 Rxd2 23. Rc1 Rb2+ 24. Ka4 Nxa2 $19 (24... Nc2 25. Bxe6+ Kf8 $2 26. Re2 Rxa2+ $4 27. Bxa2 {1-0 Van de Oudeweetering,A (2369)-Pavlovic,M (2545)/Amsterdam 2004 (36)})) (11. a3 $5 {'Vigorito, D: 'Rogozenco,D: '!?'''}) 11... axb4 12. cxb4 Bf6 (12... Nc6 13. Kb3 Nxe3 14. fxe3 b6 15. Bb5 Na7 16. Be2 bxc5 17. b5 Bb7 18. a4 $14) (12... Bd7 13. Bc4 Ba4+ 14. Bb3 Nc6 15. a3 Bf6 $13) 13. Rb1 ({also deserves attention} 13. Bd4 Bxd4 14. Nxd4 Nxf2 15. Rg1 e5 16. Nb5 Nc6 17. Kb3 $13) 13... Rxa2+ (13... e5 14. Ne4 Rxa2+ 15. Kb3 Be6+ 16. Bc4 Bxc4+ 17. Kxc4 Nxe3+ 18. fxe3 Rxg2 19. Rhg1 $44) 14. Kb3 Ra8 15. Ne4 Be7 16. Bb5 $13 {/}) 10... Nxe3+ 11. fxe3 Nd7 12. c6 {Rogozenco,D: 'Rogozenco,Dorian: 'Vigorito, D: 'White cannot hold onto the pawn any longer, so he breaks up Black's pawn structure, which will also grant some squares to his knights.''' This way White at least breaks up his opponent's pawn structure.'This way White at least breaks up his opponent's pawn structure. Vigorito, D: 'Rogozenco,D: 'This way White at least breaks up his opponent's pawn structure.'''} bxc6 13. Na5 Bc5 $5 {Rogozenco,D: 'Rogozenco,Dorian: 'Vigorito, D: 'The next several moves see Carlsen using tactics to maintain material equality.''''Rogozenco,Dorian: 'Vigorito, D: 'The next several moves see Carlsen using tactics to maintain material equality.'' Vigorito, D: 'The next several moves see Carlsen using tactics to maintain material equality. Rogozenco,D: '!?''' An interesting approach from Carlsen: he doesn't even try to defend his c-pawn. Instead he activates the pieces.'An interesting approach from Carlsen: he doesn't even try to defend his c-pawn. Instead he activates the pieces. Vigorito, D: 'Rogozenco,D: 'An interesting approach from Carlsen: he doesn't even try to defend his c-pawn. Instead he activates the pieces.'''} (13... c5 {with an equal position is of course possible as well.}) 14. Nd4 {Rogozenco,D: 'Rogozenco,Dorian: 'Vigorito, D: 'Now the undefended c6-pawn is attacked twice.'''} Nf6 {Rogozenco,D: 'Rogozenco,Dorian: 'Vigorito, D: '!''' Rogozenco,D: 'Rogozenco,Dorian: 'Vigorito, D: '!' '!''' It turns out that taking the pawn on c6 leads only to a temporary material advantage for White: thanks to the activity of his pieces Black will regain the pawn in all variations. 'It turns out that taking the pawn on c6 leads only to a temporary material advantage for White: thanks to the activity of his pieces Black will regain the pawn in all variations.  Vigorito, D: 'Rogozenco,D: 'It turns out that taking the pawn on c6 leads only to a temporary material advantage for White: thanks to the activity of his pieces Black will regain the pawn in all variations. '''} 15. Bc4 (15. Naxc6 Ng4 16. Ke2 (16. Kd2 e5 17. Nc2 Bb7 18. Na5 Rad8+ $17) 16... Bd7 $44 {/} (16... Bb7 {(Rogozenco,D) (Rogozenco,Dorian) leaves White in a tangle. If} 17. h3 Nxe3 $1 18. Kxe3 Bxc6 $17)) 15... Ng4 16. Ke2 e5 {Rogozenco,D: 'Rogozenco,Dorian: 'Vigorito, D: '!''' Rogozenco,D: 'Rogozenco,Dorian: 'Vigorito, D: '!' '!'''} 17. Nc2 (17. Ndxc6 Nxe3 $17 {'Vigorito, D: 'Rogozenco,D: ''''} 18. Nxe5 {(Rogozenco,D) Rogozenco,Dorian} Bf5 $1 {leaves White's king and minor pieces in a mess.}) 17... Bf5 {Rogozenco,D: 'Rogozenco,Dorian: 'Vigorito, D: 'Hitting the c2-knight and creating the possibility of ...Be4.'''} 18. h3 Nf6 19. Nb4 Be4 20. Nbxc6 {Rogozenco,D: 'Rogozenco,Dorian: 'Vigorito, D: 'White finally eats the pawn!'''} Rfe8 {Black's advantage is minimal, since regaining the pawn will lead to further simplifications. 'Black's advantage is minimal, since regaining the pawn will lead to further simplifications.  Vigorito, D: 'Rogozenco,D: 'Black's advantage is minimal, since regaining the pawn will lead to further simplifications. '''} ({Carlsen calmly defends the e5-pawn.} 20... Rac8 {(Rogozenco,D) Rogozenco,Dorian} 21. Nxe5 Bb6 22. Nb3 Rce8) ({and} 20... Bxg2 {(Rogozenco,D) (Rogozenco,Dorian) were good alternatives.}) 21. Rhg1 Bb6 22. b4 Rac8 23. b5 (23. Bb5 Nd5 $17 {[%csl Rc3,Re3]}) 23... Bxa5 ({Carlsen decides to force matters. Instead} 23... Rc7 {(Rogozenco,D) (Rogozenco,Dorian) intending to double rooks on the c-file also looks good.}) 24. Nxa5 Rc5 {White has succeeded in exchanging a knight for his opponent's bishop, but he is still on the defensive due to the lack of coordination between his pieces and multiple pawn weaknesses. 'White has succeeded in exchanging a knight for his opponent's bishop, but he is still on the defensive due to the lack of coordination between his pieces and multiple pawn weaknesses.  Vigorito, D: 'Rogozenco,D: 'White has succeeded in exchanging a knight for his opponent's bishop, but he is still on the defensive due to the lack of coordination between his pieces and multiple pawn weaknesses. '''} 25. a4 $1 {'Vigorito, D: 'Rogozenco,D: '!'''} Rec8 26. Bd3 ({There is no time to bring the rook to the d-file:} 26. Rgd1 Bxg2) ({or} 26. Rad1 Bc2) 26... Bxd3+ (26... Rxc3 27. Bxe4 Nxe4 28. Nc6 $132) 27. Kxd3 Rxc3+ 28. Ke2 {Rogozenco,D: 'Rogozenco,Dorian: 'Vigorito, D: 'Material is even and Black certainly has some initiative, but White's position should be defensible.'''} Rc2+ (28... e4 29. Rgd1 Rc2+ 30. Rd2 {favours White again.}) 29. Kf3 e4+ 30. Kf4 R8c5 {Rogozenco,D: 'Rogozenco,Dorian: 'Vigorito, D: 'This looks scary for White, but Howell finds the best move.'''} 31. Nc6 {Rogozenco,D: 'Rogozenco,Dorian: 'Vigorito, D: '!' Vigorito, D: 'By attacking a7 White at least gives Carlsen something to think about. If Black's attack does not bring dividends White will push his queenside pawns home.''' Rogozenco,D: 'Rogozenco,Dorian: 'Vigorito, D: '!' '!' Vigorito, D: 'By attacking a7 White at least gives Carlsen something to think about. If Black's attack does not bring dividends White will push his queenside pawns home.''' Finally bringing the knight back into the game. Black can't create decisive threats against the white king, which means that the position should be close to equal.'Finally bringing the knight back into the game. Black can't create decisive threats against the white king, which means that the position should be close to equal. Vigorito, D: 'Rogozenco,D: 'Finally bringing the knight back into the game. Black can't create decisive threats against the white king, which means that the position should be close to equal.'''} g5+ 32. Kg3 R5c3 33. Ne7+ ({Rogozenco,D: 'Rogozenco,Dorian: 'Vigorito, D: 'In time pressure, White keeps his knight in play. It was possible to take on a7 though:'''} 33. Nxa7 Rxe3+ 34. Kh2 g4 {threatening xh3 mate looks scary for White, but the computer shows that it is a draw after'threatening xh3 mate looks scary for White, but the computer shows that it is a draw after Vigorito, D: 'Rogozenco,D: 'threatening xh3 mate looks scary for White, but the computer shows that it is a draw after'''} 35. Kh1 {Rogozenco,D: 'Rogozenco,Dorian: 'Vigorito, D: '!''' Rogozenco,D: 'Rogozenco,Dorian: 'Vigorito, D: '!' '!'''} gxh3 36. b6 (36. gxh3+ {(Rogozenco,D) Rogozenco,Dorian} Kf8 {Black is in check, so he cannot mate White with ...Rxh3 just yet, and} 37. Rg2 {seems to defend.}) 36... Ng4 37. b7 Nf2+ 38. Kh2 Ng4+ 39. Kh1 $11) 33... Kf8 $1 {'Vigorito, D: 'Rogozenco,D: '!'''} (33... Kg7 34. Nf5+ Kg6 35. Ne7+ Kh5 {exposes unnecessarily the king. For instance:} 36. Rae1 ({not} 36. Raf1 Rxe3+ 37. Kh2 Rf3 $1) 36... Ra3 $140 37. Kh2 {[%cal Ge1f1]} Rxa4 38. Ref1 $132) 34. Nf5 Nd5 35. Rge1 $2 {A blunder in time trouble.'A blunder in time trouble. Vigorito, D: 'Rogozenco,D: 'A blunder in time trouble.'''} ({Rogozenco,D: 'Rogozenco,Dorian: 'Vigorito, D: 'This is just a blunder (at this level at least)'''} 35. Rad1 {would have allowed White to escape:'would have allowed White to escape: Vigorito, D: 'Rogozenco,D: 'would have allowed White to escape:'''} Rd3 (35... Nxe3 $4 {(Rogozenco,D) Rogozenco,Dorian} 36. Rd8#) 36. Rc1 Nxe3 37. Nxe3 Rxe3+ 38. Kg4 Rf2 (38... Rxc1 39. Rxc1 $11) 39. Kxg5 ({but not'but not Vigorito, D: 'Rogozenco,D: 'but not'''} 39. Rc7 h6 $1 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gf4h4] 'Vigorito, D: 'Rogozenco,D: '!'''} 40. Kh5 (40. g3 {(Rogozenco,D) Rogozenco,Dorian} Rb3 {and Black's e-pawn is stronger than anything White has going on the queenside.}) 40... Kg7 41. h4 ({or} 41. g3 Rh2 42. Rxa7 Rf3 43. b6 Rxh3+ 44. Kg4 Rh2 $19) 41... Rg3 {and Black wins, since} 42. Rxa7 {runs into mate after} g4 {[%cal Gf2f5]}) 39... Ra3 (39... Rg3+ 40. Kh4 Rgxg2 41. Rxg2 Rxg2 42. Re1 f5 43. Rf1 $11) 40. Rc4 e3 (40... f5 $2 41. Kf6) 41. Rf4 {and White will achieve a draw, although accurate defence is still required.}) 35... Nf4 $19 {Rogozenco,D: 'Rogozenco,Dorian: 'Vigorito, D: '!''''Rogozenco,Dorian: 'Vigorito, D: '!' '!'' Vigorito, D: 'Rogozenco,D: '-+'''} 36. Rg1 Ne2+ 37. Kg4 Nxg1 38. Rxg1 f6 {Rogozenco,D: 'Rogozenco,Dorian: 'Vigorito, D: 'Up a whole exchange, Black is winning now. It is still not so simple because White's king and knight are active and it's not easy for Black to create a passed pawn. Still, one would think that a 2800 player would win this position with Black! Not today...''' Of course this should be winning for Black, but things are not trivial due to White's excellent knight on f5 and his active king. 'Of course this should be winning for Black, but things are not trivial due to White's excellent knight on f5 and his active king.  Vigorito, D: 'Rogozenco,D: 'Of course this should be winning for Black, but things are not trivial due to White's excellent knight on f5 and his active king. '''} 39. h4 gxh4 40. Kxh4 Ra3 41. g4 Rxa4 42. Rd1 Raa2 43. Rd7 Rh2+ 44. Kg3 Rhg2+ 45. Kh3 Rgf2 46. Nd4 Kg8 $6 {Starting with this moment Carlsen loses the thread, missing even a forced win later on.'Starting with this moment Carlsen loses the thread, missing even a forced win later on. Vigorito, D: 'Rogozenco,D: 'Starting with this moment Carlsen loses the thread, missing even a forced win later on.'''} ({After'After Vigorito, D: 'Rogozenco,D: 'After'''} 46... Ra3 47. Kg3 (47. Nf5 Rf3+ 48. Kh4 Ra2 $19) 47... Rf1 48. Kg2 (48. Nf5 Rf3+ 49. Kh2 Ra2+ 50. Kg1 h5 $19) 48... Re1 49. Kf2 Rh1 50. Kg2 (50. Nf5 h5 51. Kg2 (51. gxh5 Rxh5 52. Nd6 Rh2+ 53. Kg3 Rd2 $19) 51... Rc1 52. gxh5 Rc5 53. Nd6 Rg5+ 54. Kh2 Rxe3 $19) 50... Raa1 {Black would have kept excellent winning chances, since} 51. Rxa7 Rxa7 52. Kxh1 Ra3 {is lost for White.}) 47. Re7 Kf8 48. Rc7 ({White correctly prefers to keep his opponent's king cut off rather than release it after'White correctly prefers to keep his opponent's king cut off rather than release it after Vigorito, D: 'Rogozenco,D: 'White correctly prefers to keep his opponent's king cut off rather than release it after'''} 48. Rxe4 {Rogozenco,D: 'Rogozenco,Dorian: 'Vigorito, D: 'is possible as well, but Howell understandably prefers to keep the Black king pinned to the first rank.'''} Kf7 {when it is much easier for Black to play than in the game.}) 48... Ke8 49. Kg3 Rf1 50. Rxh7 Ra3 51. Kg2 $2 {Both players became visibly tired. Bringing back the king is a bad mistake, which, however, remained unpunished.'Both players became visibly tired. Bringing back the king is a bad mistake, which, however, remained unpunished. Vigorito, D: 'Rogozenco,D: 'Both players became visibly tired. Bringing back the king is a bad mistake, which, however, remained unpunished.'''} ({The active king after} 51. Nf5 Rf3+ 52. Kh4 {would have been enough for successful defence:} ({Again going back is hopeless:} 52. Kg2 $2 Ra2+ 53. Kg1 Rff2 54. Rxa7 Rg2+ 55. Kf1 Raf2+ 56. Ke1 Rb2 57. Kf1 Rgd2 $19) 52... Ra2 53. Nd6+ Kd8 (53... Kf8 54. Rf7+ Kg8 55. Kh5 Rd2 56. Rd7) 54. Nb7+ Kc8 55. Nd6+ Kb8 56. Rb7+ Ka8 57. Kh5 Rxe3 58. Re7 $11) 51... Rd1 52. Nf5 (52. Nc6 Rxe3 53. Kf2 Rf3+ 54. Ke2 Rd7 $19) (52. Rh3 Rd2+ $19) 52... Rd7 $2 {'Vigorito, D: 'Rogozenco,D: '?'''} ({Rogozenco,D: 'Rogozenco,Dorian: 'Vigorito, D: 'I believe Black played this quickly. Even the best make bad practical decisions. It does not take much calculation to see that'''} 52... Ra2+ {wins by force, since after'wins by force, since after Vigorito, D: 'Rogozenco,D: 'wins by force, since after'''} 53. Kg3 Rg1+ 54. Kf4 Rf2+ 55. Kxe4 Rxg4+ {Rogozenco,D: 'Rogozenco,Dorian: 'Vigorito, D: 'wins the f5-knight!'''} 56. Kd5 Rxf5+ 57. Ke6 {Black simply gives a check on e5} Re5+ $19) 53. Rh8+ Kf7 54. Kg3 Rb3 55. Kf4 {The king is back into play and Black is not able to win anymore.'The king is back into play and Black is not able to win anymore. Vigorito, D: 'Rogozenco,D: 'The king is back into play and Black is not able to win anymore.'''} Rb1 (55... Rb4 56. Rh7+ Ke6 57. Rh6 $132 {[%cal Gg4g5]}) 56. Kxe4 {Rogozenco,D: 'Rogozenco,Dorian: 'Vigorito, D: 'Now White is safe.'''} Rf1 57. Rh7+ Ke6 58. Rh8 Rc7 59. Nd4+ Kd6 $11 {'Vigorito, D: 'Rogozenco,D: '='''} 60. Rd8+ Rd7 61. Rc8 Rg7 62. Rd8+ Rd7 63. Rc8 Re7+ 64. Kd3 Rc7 65. Rd8+ Rd7 66. Rg8 Rg1 67. Ke2 Kc5 68. Kf2 Rb1 69. Rf8 Rd6 70. Rf7 Rb2+ 71. Kf3 Ra2 72. Ke4 Kb6 73. Rf8 Rg2 74. Kf3 Rh2 75. Rb8+ Kc7 76. Ra8 Kb7 77. Rf8 Rh7 78. Kf4 Rh1 79. Kf3 1/2-1/2


