1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Nxf6+ exf6 6. c3 Bd6 7. Bd3 O-O 8. Ne2 Re8 9. Qc2 h5 {The modern main line of the 4...Nf6 variation. We have considered it a couple of times, although the reader might notice that most of the archived games resulted in a White win. This score line is obviously not reflective of the soundness of the defence instead, it seems to reflect the fact that it is extremely impressive whenever White manages to breach Black's setup.} 10. O-O h4 11. h3 Nd7 (11... Na6 $6 {Sometimes the knight reroutes to e6 via c7. This is usually seen when White's bishop is committed to f4. In this case, the knight does not belong to the e6-square at least, not in the short run.} 12. Be3 Nc7 13. c4 $1 Ne6 (13... Be6 14. Nc3 $16) (13... Bd7 14. Rad1 $16) 14. Rad1 $14 {It is difficult for Black to find play, while White has a few plans. Namely, the central pawn break d4-d5, the queenside expansion with c4-c5 and b4-b5, and the kingside attack with f4-f5.}) 12. Be3 Nf8 13. Rad1 {At this juncture, most of Black's legal bishop moves are plausible.} ({White may also want to start with} 13. c4 Bc7 (13... Bd7 {is a decent move against 13.Rad1, but it might be less effective here as after} 14. Nc3 Rc8 {White has the option of} 15. Rae1 {Protecting the bishop on e3 immediately so that f4 can be played next.} Bb8 16. f4 $36 {Nevertheless, it is difficult to determine the significance of this nuance, and Black may still have reasonable counterplay with} b5) ({As against 13.Rad1, the most typical development is} 13... Be6) 14. Rfe1 {is probably slightly inaccurate on account of} g5 $1 {Preventing a piece from coming to f4, and thus, preparing ...Qd6.}) 13... Bc7 ({Even} 13... Bb8 $5 {deserves attention.}) (13... Bd7 $5 14. c4 Rc8 15. Nc3 Bb8 $13 {is offered by Rambaldi in his book 'The Caro-Kann Revisited' and gives good counterplay. There are a few advantages to having the bishop on d7: the knight can jump to e6, the e-rook is not obstructed and ...b7-b5 is supported. All the same, I think White can avoid this line altogether by starting with 13. c4, so I would recommend the reader to consider 13...Be6 as well.}) (13... Be6 {is the most logical continuation.} 14. c4 (14. Nf4 Qc7 15. Nxe6 Nxe6 16. Bc4 Bf4 17. Rfe1 Ng5 $132) 14... Rc8 (14... Qc7 $6 {is definitely not the right setup as the dark-squared bishop needs to have a retreat square along the h2-b8 diagonal. After} 15. c5 $1 {the only way in which the dark-squared bishop can remain on the diagonal is} Bh2+ 16. Kh1 {but now the standard trap f2-f4 will become a serious problem for Black. For instance} Rad8 17. Bd2 $5 (17. f4 {is less precise because after} Bg3 18. Nxg3 hxg3 {White cannot drop the bishop back to d2 immediately because the d4-pawn is hanging. Thus} 19. Rde1 Bd5 {and Black has a better version. Note that} 20. f5 b6 21. Bf4 Qxf4 $1 22. Rxf4 Rxe1+ 23. Rf1 Rde8 {gives Black full compensation.}) 17... Bd5 (17... b6 18. f4 $1 Bg3 19. Nxg3 hxg3 20. f5 Bd5 21. Bf4 $16) 18. f4 Bg3 19. Nxg3 hxg3 20. f5 $36) (14... Bc7 {is still possible, although it is a bit strange to combine this plan with ...Be6.}) 15. Nc3 (15. b3 Bb8 $1 16. Rfe1 b5 $1 17. Bf4 (17. Nf4 bxc4 18. bxc4 Qc7 19. Kf1 Bd7 20. Rb1 Ne6 21. Nxe6 Bxe6 22. f4 Rcd8 $13) 17... bxc4 18. bxc4 Bxf4 19. Nxf4 Qa5 $13 20. d5 Bd7) 15... Bb8 16. Rfe1 Qd6 $1 17. f4 Ng6 $1 {An important pawn sacrifice to remember.} 18. c5 (18. Rf1 {gives Black the option of schematic play with} b5 ({or the more intense variation} 18... Bxh3 $5 19. Ne4 Qe6 20. gxh3 f5 21. d5 cxd5 22. cxd5 Qe7 23. Bc5 Qd8 24. d6 fxe4 25. Bb5 Rf8 26. d7 {and now the knee-jerk reaction 26... Rxc5 27.Qxc5 is not viable as the d7-pawn remains on the board. Instead Black has} b6 $3 27. dxc8=Q Qxc8 $13) 19. c5 (19. cxb5 cxb5 20. Bxb5 Bb3 $1 {is the point. Once the bishop on e3 falls, the f4-pawn becomes vulnerable.} 21. Qf5 $5 Bc2 $1 (21... Bxd1 $6 22. Bxe8 Rxe8 23. Nxd1 $11) 22. Qxc2 Rxe3 $15) 19... Qc7 20. Rf3 (20. Ne4 Bd5 $13) 20... Ne7 $13 ({Again, Black has the option to stir things up with} 20... b4 21. d5 cxd5 22. Nb5 Qe7 23. f5 Ne5)) 18... Qc7 19. Bxg6 fxg6 20. Qxg6 Qf7 $1 $44 {Black has excellent compensation in the form of a better pawn structure, a bishop pair and more mobile pieces in general.}) 14. c4 Qd6 $5 (14... f5 $6 {does not really work here.} 15. Bxf5 Qd6 16. Nf4 g5 17. c5 Qf6 18. Bxc8 gxf4 19. Bxb7 fxe3 20. fxe3 Qe6 21. Bxa8 Qxe3+ 22. Qf2 Qxf2+ 23. Kxf2 Rxa8 {White's queenside majority provides lasting pressure.}) 15. Nf4 {According to Ashwin in his notes to the game Sjugirov - Bai, 2018, this move causes some problems for Black. On the other hand, the more recent aforementioned book by Rambaldi suggests that Black maintains the balance. I believe Ashwin's evaluation was closer to the truth.} (15. Bf4 {leads to a forcing continuation:} Rxe2 16. Bxd6 Rxc2 17. Ba3 $1 Be6 18. Bxc2 (18. d5 Bf5 $1 {gives Black a comfortable ending:} 19. Bxf5 Rxc4 20. d6 Bb6 21. d7 Rf4 $1 22. Bg4 f5 23. Bd6 Rxf2 $1 24. Rxf2 fxg4 25. Bxf8 g3 $1 26. Kf1 gxf2 27. Bc5 Bc7) 18... Bxc4 19. Rfe1 Ne6 $44 {Black is OK here, but as Rambaldi points out, it may not be easy to play for a win, due to the limited number of pieces that remain.}) 15... Be6 (15... g5 $4 16. c5) 16. Rfe1 (16. c5 Qe7 17. b4 Rad8 18. b5 Bb8 {followed by ...Qc7 gives Black sufficient counterplay.}) 16... Rad8 17. Kf1 $1 {This waiting move is not covered by Rambaldi, but it is given a mention by Ashwin. I believe it offers White some pressure, as it takes the sting out of the queen and bishop battery on the h2-b8 diagonal.} (17. c5 Qd7 18. a4 $5 {is a surprising idea presented by Rambaldi. If} Bb8 {White picks up an exchange with} ({In turn, the counter-intuitive} 18... Bxf4 $1 19. Bxf4 Ng6 20. Bd6 Ne7 {(Rambaldi) is reasonable for Black. Still, I think White may also be happy here, with some play on the queenside.}) 19. d5 $1 Bxd5 20. Nxd5 cxd5 21. Bb5 Qc7 22. Bxe8 Qh2+ 23. Kf1 Rxe8 24. f4) 17... Bc8 (17... a6 {is given by some engines, but it's a peculiar move. White can keep the tension with} 18. Qc3 (18. c5 Qd7 19. Nxe6 Nxe6 20. Bc4 Ba5 21. Re2 Nc7) 18... b5 19. b3 $14 {and the position obviously remains quite tense. It seems that White has a few more ideas than Black, such as preparing d5 or attacking on the queenside with a2-a4, so I am inclined to think White is practically better.}) (17... Bb8 {is a solid waiting move. The idea is that after White plays} 18. b3 {or any other waiting move, Black retreats the other bishop with} (18. d5 cxd5 19. Be4 $1 Rc8 $1 20. b3 Qe5 21. Bxd5 Bf5 22. Qd2 b6 $13) 18... Bc8 {so that in the analogous line to the game continuation} (18... Bd7 $5 19. Be4 $1 {and White will eventually get d5 in.} (19. d5 $6 cxd5 20. Bf5 Bc6 $1 $132 {is the difference.}) {Note that} 19... f5 $4 {doesn't work here because of} 20. Bxf5 Qf6 21. Bxd7 Bxf4 22. Bxe8) 19. d5 {Black can play} (19. Be4 {is not as strong here on account of} f5 $1 20. Bxf5 Qf6 21. Bxc8 Bxf4 $11) 19... cxd5 20. Nxd5 (20. Bf5 $1 {is more testing.} Bxf5 21. Qxf5 Qe5 (21... d4 22. Rxd4 Qe5 23. Qxe5 fxe5 24. Rxd8 Rxd8 25. Nd5 $14) 22. Qxe5 fxe5 23. Nxd5 $14) 20... Qh2 $1 $13) 18. Bf5 $6 ({White should seize the opportunity to execute the all-important pawn break} 18. d5 $1 c5 19. Re2 Bd7 20. Bf5 {and Black's position is a little bit difficult. E.g.} a6 21. b4 $1 b6 22. bxc5 bxc5 23. Rb1) 18... Bxf5 19. Qxf5 Qb4 ({Simplest is} 19... g6 20. Qc2 Ne6 {Hoping to penetrate with the queen to h2. In order to avoid that, White may play} 21. c5 (21. Nxe6 Rxe6 22. d5 cxd5 23. cxd5 Ree8) 21... Qd7 $13 {but then White retains no pressure in the centre.}) 20. b3 Qa5 (20... b5 $1 {was more in the spirit of the line.} 21. Rc1 Qa5 22. Re2 Bxf4 $1 23. Qxf4 Ne6 $1 {Black is prepared to sacrifice a pawn in order to activate his pieces.} 24. Qxh4 bxc4 25. Rxc4 (25. bxc4 Qa3 $44) 25... c5 26. Qh5 g6 27. Qf3 cxd4 28. Bxd4 Nxd4 29. Rxd4 Rxd4 30. Rxe8+ Kg7 $11) 21. Qxa5 Bxa5 22. Re2 $14 {/= This position is undoubtedly drawn in a game between engines, but in our case, we have a game between mere mortals where White can continue to pose questions.} Ne6 23. d5 $1 Nxf4 $2 {Black already makes a serious error.} (23... Bc7 $1 {was the only way to neutralise White's initiative.} 24. Nxe6 (24. Nh5 $5 Bb8 25. Red2 cxd5 26. cxd5 Ng5 $11) 24... fxe6 25. Bxa7 exd5 26. Rxe8+ Rxe8 27. cxd5 Ra8 28. Be3 Rxa2 29. dxc6 bxc6 30. Rc1 Rb2 $11) 24. Bxf4 Rxe2 25. Kxe2 cxd5 26. Rxd5 Rxd5 27. cxd5 $18 {Same-coloured bishop endings in this variation are dangerous for Black as their kingside is not easily defended.} Kf8 28. Bd6+ Ke8 29. Bc5 b6 (29... a6 30. Kf3 {and the king penetrates on the kingside.}) 30. Ba3 (30. Bd4 $1 {or 30.Be3 would have kept the f2-pawn defended, liberating the white king. Nonetheless, I do think the game continuation is still winning.}) 30... Bc3 31. Kd3 Be1 32. Ke2 Bc3 33. Kd3 Be1 {White cannot avoid the weakening move} 34. f3 Kd7 (34... b5 35. Ke4 {should also be winning for White. I don't think Black gets a fortress because the queenside pawns are now quite loose.}) 35. Bf8 g6 36. a4 $2 {This ending is way too subtle, but I have tried to illustrate the winning plan for White.} (36. Bh6 {allows} b5 $1 37. a4 a6 38. Ke4 {It is tremendously difficult to comprehend the nuances here. In the above note, I contended that White is winning in a similar position. Here, Black is holding somehow. There are some key differences in that the Black king is on d7 and not e8 Black's pawn is already on g6, meaning White's idea of f4-f5 can be prevented by means of a timely ...f5+, etc. In general, it suffices to show that Black has a more active version than the position after 34...b5, but the endgame experts might want to dig deeper.} Bc3 39. Bf8 f5+ 40. Kd3 Be5) (36. Bg7 $1 Ke7 (36... f5 {is the weakening that White hopes for, as will be clear in the main line.}) 37. Kc4 $1 {Preventing ...b5.} a6 38. Bh6 $1 (38. a4 $2 Bd2 {and White's bishop is stuck on a blocked diagonal.}) 38... Bf2 {Black couldn't play ...b5+ as the king would have penetrated through to c5.} 39. a4 Kd6 40. Bf4+ Kd7 41. Bc1 {It wasn't necessary to give the check straight away, but it always looks logical to drive the enemy king backwards before executing the plan.} Bg1 42. Bb2 Ke7 43. Bc3 $1 {Threatening Be1.} Bf2 {If it were Black to move in this position, then neither the bishop nor the king would be able to move and Black would be forced to make a pawn move...} 44. Bb4+ Kd7 45. Bd2 $1 Ke7 (45... Bg1 46. Be1 $1 g5 47. Bc3 Ke7 48. b4 $18) 46. Bc3 $22 {White passes the move to Black.} f5 47. b4 Kd7 {Black still could not allow Be1, so the king move was necessary.} 48. Bf6 $1 Kd6 49. b5 a5 {Definite progres at last!} 50. Bg5 Ke5 {Most stubborn. Keeping an eye on the d5-pawn so that the enemy king cannot move.} 51. Bd8 Kd6 52. Bf6 $22 {Another zugzwang. The king is forced to retreat, which gives White the opportunity to reroute his king.} Kd7 (52... Bg3 53. Bd4 Kc7 54. Be3 Bd6 55. Bf2 Be7 56. d6+ $1 {is a key point.} Bxd6 57. Bxh4 $18) 53. Kd3 Kd6 54. Ke2 Bc5 (54... Bg3 55. Bd4 Kc7 56. Kd3 Bd6 57. Bf2 Be7 58. d6+ $1 Bxd6 59. Bxh4 $18) 55. Bxh4 Kxd5 56. Kd3 Ke5 57. Bd8 $1 Bf2 (57... f4 58. Bc7+ Kf5 59. Kc4 $18) (57... Kf4 58. Bc7+ Kg5 59. Kc4 $18) (57... Kd5 58. g4) 58. Kc4 {Black cannot simultaneously defend his queenside and his opponent's plan of creating a passed h-pawn.} Kd6 59. Bg5 Ke5 60. g3 $1 Ke6 61. Bf4 Bc5 62. h4 Bf2 63. Kd3 Kd5 64. Ke2 Bc5 65. g4 fxg4 66. fxg4 Ke4 67. Bc7 $18) 36... a6 37. Kc4 Bf2 (37... Bd2 $1 {Prevents White from accessing the c1-h6 diagonal and the b4-square.} 38. Ba3 (38. Bg7 Ke7) 38... f5 39. Kd4 Bh6 $1 {and White cannot make progress.} 40. Bb4 {White gets the bishop to f4, but now Black has a safe defence with ...Bf6/e7.} Bg7+ 41. Kc4 Bf6 42. Be1 Be7) 38. Bb4 $1 f5 39. Bd2 {Black would love to have his bishop on f6 now, but in this variation, the bishop is poorly placed.} Kd6 (39... Kc7 40. b4 Kd6 41. Bg5 Kc7 42. b5 a5 43. Bf6 Kd6) 40. Bf4+ Kd7 41. Be5 Bg3 42. Bxg3 $4 ({The winning plan was already illustrated above.} 42. Bd4 Bc7 43. Bf6 Bg3 44. b4 Bf2 45. b5 a5 46. Kd3 $1 Kd6 47. Ke2) 42... hxg3 43. a5 bxa5 44. h4 f4 $4 (44... Kd6 45. Kd4 f6 46. Kc4 Kd7 $1 47. Kc5 Kc7 48. d6+ Kd7 49. Kd5 f4 $1 {is an amazing way to draw as Black.} 50. Kc5 (50. Ke4 $4 Kxd6 51. Kxf4 Kc5 {Black has gained a tempo on the game, as he didn't have to waste time capturing the d5-pawn.} 52. Kxg3 Kb4 53. f4 Kxb3 $19) 50... g5 $1 51. hxg5 (51. h5 $4 g4) 51... fxg5 52. Kd5 g4 53. Ke4 gxf3 54. Kxf3 Kxd6 55. Kxf4 Kc5 56. Kxg3 Kb4 57. Kf3 Kxb3 $11) 45. Kd4 Kd6 46. Ke4 f6 47. Kd4 (47. Kxf4 Kxd5 48. Kxg3 Kc5 49. f4 f5 50. Kf3 Kb4 51. g4 fxg4+ 52. Kg3 $1 (52. Kxg4 $4 Kxb3 53. h5 gxh5+ 54. Kxh5 a4 $11)) 47... a4 ({Black should have tried} 47... Ke7 {and on} 48. Kc5 $4 g5 {Black has the same resourceful draw as above.} 49. h5 g4 50. Kc6 gxf3 51. d6+ Kf7 52. d7 fxg2 $11) 48. bxa4 a5 49. Ke4 Kc5 50. Kxf4 Kxd5 51. Kxg3 Kc4 52. Kf4 Kb4 53. g4 g5+ 54. hxg5 fxg5+ 55. Kxg5 Kxa4 56. f4 $4 ({The white king should have ran towards the square with} 56. Kf4 $1 Kb4 (56... Kb3 57. g5 {is an important point. The g-pawn queens with check.}) 57. Ke3) 56... Kb3 57. f5 a4 58. f6 a3 59. f7 a2 60. f8=Q a1=Q {Amazingly, we have reached a well-known theoretical ending, in which the position is drawn but extremely tough to defend for Black. The basic point is that the Black king should stay near the corner that is diametrically opposed to the pawn's promotion square (Dvoretsky). This defence is not possible against central and bishop pawns. It seems that Ghasi was unfamiliar with the drawing zone, although the real mistake was more trivial.} 61. Qf7+ Kb4 62. Kg6 Qa6+ 63. Kg7 Qa1+ 64. Qf6 Qa7+ 65. Kg6 Qd7 66. Qf8+ Ka4 67. Qa8+ Kb4 68. Qe4+ Kc3 69. g5 Qd6+ 70. Kf5 Qd7+ 71. Qe6 Qh7+ $4 {Very provocative and simply incorrect. The queen will be short of checks on the side of the board. For both the defender and attacker, the general rule is that the queen belongs in the centre of the board.} (71... Qd3+ 72. Qe4 Qf1+ 73. Kg6 Kb2 $11) 72. g6 Qh3+ 73. Kf6 Qh4+ 74. Kf7 Kd3 75. g7 Qf4+ 76. Ke8 Qb8+ 77. Ke7 Qb4+ 78. Qd6+ 1-0


