{BATTLE OF BRITAIN IN BOURNEMOUTH I haven’t had a packed schedule recently, and when I sat down to play my first round game in the British Championship it was three months and 15 days since my last outing. Probably my longest break from competitive play since I was at school! I wouldn’t really recommend this approach – arranging some training games instead of watching cricket pre-tournament would have been a good idea, but it seemed to work out alright in the end. I reached a respectable 5/6 at the end of the first week, although three of my games were none too convincing. I began the second with a tough pairing – Black against second seed David Howell, which, for a Berlin, was quite an eventful game.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. Nbd2 O-O 7. Qe2 {The revolutionary way to treat the Berlin, White’s plan of castling on the opposite side to his opponent certainly changes the nature of the game.} Re8 8. Nc4 Nd7 9. Bd2 Nb6 $146 {Diagram [#] A new move in response. Due to some tactical points it’s not necessary to lose time defending the pawn on e5, but of course b6 is hardly an ideal spot for Black’s knight which normally heads to e6 via f8.} (9... Bd6 $145 {- 129/115 Perez Candelario,Manuel 2527 - Sargissian,Gabriel 2677, Villafranca de los Barros 2010 - 109/(187)}) 10. Ne3 (10. Ncxe5 $6 f6 11. Nc4 Nxc4 12. dxc4 Bf5 $17 {obviously doesn’t work.}) (10. Nfxe5 Bd4 11. Bc3 Bxc3+ 12. bxc3 {is much more interesting but Black has a lot of options here:} f6 13. Nxb6 axb6 $44 {is one reasonable idea.}) (10. Na5 $5 {can be considered but David’s move is more compatible with White’s most ambitious plan to castle queenside.}) 10... a5 (10... Bf8 $5 {is another idea.}) ({I was trying to avoid playing} 10... f6 {as this gives White a target on the kingside, but during the game I realised it’s not easy to do without this move, so perhaps it was better to play it now.}) 11. h4 {Diagram [#]} ({After} 11. O-O-O {either} Be6 $13 {or} (11... a4 $5 {starts queenside action quickly. David’s move is craftier, he begins his own play and introduces the handy option to play Ng5.})) 11... Bd4 (11... Be6 12. Ng5 $1 $36 {is annoying.}) ({I was still trying to avoid playing ...f7-f6 but again the immediate} 11... f6 12. O-O-O Be6 13. Kb1 Qd7 $13 {looks sensible.}) ({If} 11... Bf8 12. g4 $13 {and White’s attack starts to look worryingly advanced.}) 12. O-O-O Be6 13. Kb1 f6 {Diagram  Diagram [#]} (13... Na4 14. c3 {doesn’t really go anywhere.}) 14. g4 ({Very aggressive and certainly not bad, but there were two decent alternatives:} 14. Rdg1 $5 Na4 15. Nxd4 (15. Bc1 $6 Qe7 $15) (15. Nd1 $5 {leaves little to latch on to on the queenside.}) 15... exd4 16. Nd1 c5 17. g4 $13 {leads to very sharp play}) (14. Nf5 $5 {is also complex, but I think White is a little better here.}) 14... Bxe3 {I felt I had to grab the pawn although obviously it is not without dangers.} 15. Qxe3 Bxg4 16. Rdg1 {Diagram [#]} Bxf3 ({I calculated the unimportant line} 16... f5 $6 17. exf5 Nd5 18. Qe4 Nf6 19. Qc4+ Qd5 20. Rxg4 e4 21. Rxe4 $18 {winning for White,}) ({but missed the relevant} 16... Nc4 $5 17. dxc4 Bxf3 18. Qxf3 Qxd2 19. Qxf6 Qe1+ $1 {(This was the detail I overlooked.)} 20. Rxe1 gxf6 $11 {and a few moves have drained an intriguing middlegame of all interest.}) 17. Qxf3 Kh8 18. Qg3 ({The other option is to try to treble on the open line, rook first:} 18. h5 Qd6 19. Qg2 Re7 20. Rh3 (20. f4 $5) 20... Na4 21. Rg3 Rg8 $13 {which also looks to provide reasonable compensation.}) 18... Re7 19. f4 {Opening more dark squares is logical but it allows my knight to get nearer to the kingside.} Nc4 {Diagram [#]} 20. Bc1 ({After} 20. Bc3 exf4 21. Qxf4 {the handy intermezzo} Qd6 $1 {is an important detail, then} 22. Qf2 Ne5 23. h5 c5 $11 {and the impression is similar - White has play but my position remains solid.}) 20... exf4 21. Bxf4 Ne5 22. Bxe5 ({I was expecting} 22. h5 Qd6 $11 {but David was already low on time and his move is equally good, as White will gain complete control of the only open file.}) 22... fxe5 23. Rf1 Qd6 24. Rf5 a4 25. a3 b5 26. Rhf1 Rg8 27. Kc1 ({The more direct} 27. Rf8 {seems better and after} h6 28. h5 Rxf8 29. Rxf8+ Kh7 30. Qf2 Qe6 $11 {a draw is on the cards.}) 27... c5 28. h5 {Diagram [#] David offered a draw here but as the momentum of the game was positive, and my clock and board position are somewhat better, I was happy to continue.} b4 {Practically, now things are not simple for White as his king will always feel a little uncomfortable.} 29. Qe3 h6 30. Rg1 {Diagram [#]} (30. Rf8 {is met by} Rd7 $15) 30... Re6 ({As the only way to progress is to return the pawn and try to exploit White’s isolated pawns and airy king position, the immediate} 30... bxa3 31. bxa3 c4 32. dxc4 Rd8 $13 {made sense.}) 31. Rf7 bxa3 32. bxa3 c4 33. dxc4 Rf6 34. c5 {Diagram [#]} Qd8 ({Originally I intended} 34... Qa6 $1 35. Rxf6 ({as} 35. Rxc7 Rf1+ 36. Rxf1 Qxf1+ 37. Kb2 Rb8+ 38. Kc3 Qa1+ $19 {wins}) 35... Qxf6 $15 {and this caused a bit of panic. which looks more active than the game.}) 35. Rf1 $5 {Diagram [#]} (35. Rxf6 Qxf6 $15) 35... Rxf7 $2 (35... Rxf1+ $1 36. Rxf1 Qh4 $15 {was obviously correct as White’s rook is less impressively placed.}) 36. Rxf7 c6 {Diagram [#]} 37. Kb2 $2 (37. Ra7 $1 Qh4 38. Ra6 $13 {was better, as the rook can block checks on the b-file if required.}) 37... Qd1 $1 {David may have overlooked that this square was made available by White’s last move.} 38. Rb7 Qxh5 39. Qg3 {Although I have two connected passed pawns on the kingside, my passively placed pieces mean they won’t be moving forward very quickly.} Qe8 {Diagram [#]} 40. Kc3 ({A creative final move before the time control. Upon} 40. Rb4 {, keeping the rook active, I wanted to play} Qe7 ({The fearless machine suggests} 40... g5 $5 {and it is true the black rook is handily placed behind the g-pawn.}) 41. Rxa4 Qxc5 $17) 40... Qe6 41. Kb4 {Diagram [#]} Qa2 ({I didn’t consider the best move} 41... g5 $1 {at all. Importantly, this leaves White without a particularly useful move:} 42. Ka5 (42. Kxa4 $2 Qc4+ {wins immediately}) 42... g4 43. Kb6 Rg7 $19 {neutralises the active rook.}) 42. Ka5 Qxc2 43. Qxe5 Qd3 {Diagram  Diagram [#]} 44. Kb6 $2 ({The counter-intuitive} 44. Rb8 $1 {, swapping my passive rook, holds the draw:} Rxb8 45. Qxb8+ Kh7 {and either} 46. e5 ({or} 46. Qb4 Qd8+ (46... h5 47. e5 Qd5 48. Kb6) 47. Kxa4 h5 48. e5 Qd5 $11 {look likely to lead to a draw.}) 46... Qc3+ (46... Qxa3 47. Qb1+ Kg8 48. Qb8+ $11) 47. Kb6 Qxa3 48. Kxc6 Qf3+ 49. Kd7 Qd5+ 50. Qd6 Qb7+ 51. Qc7 $11) 44... Qxa3 45. Kxc6 Qd3 {Diagram [#]} 46. Rb8 ({The best try but one that is less effective here.} 46. Ra7 a3 47. Qd5 Qh3 $19 {leaves White’s king too exposed}) (46. Qd5 {is another logical line:} Qa6+ 47. Rb6 Qa8+ 48. Kb5 a3 49. Qe5 Kh7 50. Qf5+ g6 $19 {is winning but is not a line that inspired confidence in me at the board.}) 46... Rxb8 ({I rejected} 46... Qa6+ 47. Rb6 {However after} Qc4 $1 {White’s king is still too exposed to set up the mating threat as} (47... Qc8+ $2 {due to} 48. Kb5 {with the threat of Rh6 mate!}) 48. Kb7 {is met by} Qf7+ $19) 47. Qxb8+ Kh7 48. Qe5 {Diagram [#]} ({Again the best try as} 48. e5 a3 49. e6 a2 50. Qa7 Qe4+ $19 {wins easily.}) 48... Qa6+ ({The strongest move, the geometrical} 48... Qf1 $1 {, wasn’t easy to spot:} 49. Kd7 a3 50. Qd5 Qf2 51. c6 a2 $19 {winning.}) 49. Kd5 (49. Kd7 Qb7+ $1 (49... a3 $2 50. c6 a2 51. Qf5+ $11) 50. Kd8 a3 $19 {again winning.}) 49... a3 50. Qf5+ Kg8 51. c6 {Diagram  Diagram [#]} Qb5+ $1 (51... a2 $2 52. Qe6+ Kh8 53. c7 $11) 52. Kd6 Qxf5 53. exf5 a2 54. c7 a1=Q 55. c8=Q+ {Diagram [#]} Kh7 {Two new queens are on the board, but things are still not completely clear. If White can give up his pawn but get his king to the right corner square of the board, without my pawns advancing too far, the position is a theoretical draw. However with little time remaining there is virtually no chance to carry out this tricky operation.} 56. Kd5 (56. Qe6 $1 {is best and might save the day with correct play:} Qf6 $1 (56... Qd4+ $6 57. Ke7 Qh4+ 58. Kf7 Qh5+ $4 59. Kf8 $18 {, when White mates, is certainly not a good option!}) 57. Kd5 (57. Qxf6 gxf6 58. Kd5 Kg7 59. Ke4 Kf7 60. Kf4 Ke7 61. Kg4 Kd6 62. Kh5 Ke5 $19 {wins}) 57... Qg5 $1 (57... h5 $2 58. Qxf6 gxf6 59. Ke4 $11 {with a draw, was a line given by Alexander Baburin in Chess Today}) 58. Ke4 $1 {Diagram [#]} Qg2+ (58... h5 59. Kf3 Qg4+ 60. Kf2 h4 61. Qd5 Qg3+ 62. Kf1 Qg5 63. Kf2 Kh6 (63... h3 64. Qf3 $1 h2 65. Qd1 $1 $11) 64. Qe6+ Qf6 65. Kg2 Kg5 66. Qe3+ Kxf5 $11) 59. Ke3 h5 60. Qf7 Qg3+ 61. Ke2 Qg4+ 62. Kf1 h4 63. f6 Qf3+ 64. Kg1 Qxf6 $19 {is a tablebase draw but of course defending this position, especially with little time on the clock, is no picnic.}) 56... Qa2+ {Diagram [#]} ({This does drive White’s king where it wants to go, so} 56... h5 57. Qe6 (57. Qe8 $6 Qa5+ $1) 57... Qg1 {was simpler.}) 57. Ke5 (57. Ke4 {also makes sense but doesn’t seem to work:} Qg2+ 58. Ke3 h5 59. Qe8 (59. f6 $5 Qg5+ 60. Kf2 Qxf6+ 61. Kg2 {Diagram [#] Now it appears White has achieved his aim but the threat of a queen exchange means his king will get displaced again.} Qg5+ 62. Kf1 Qf4+ 63. Kg2 (63. Ke1 h4 $19) 63... Qg4+ 64. Qxg4 hxg4 65. Kg3 Kh6 66. Kxg4 Kg6 $19) 59... Qg5+ 60. Kf2 Qxf5+ 61. Kg2 (61. Ke2 h4 $19) 61... Qg6+ $19) 57... h5 {Diagram [#]} 58. Qc6 (58. Kf4 Qf2+ 59. Kg5 h4 60. Qc6 Qg3+ 61. Kh5 h3 $19 {and White is helpless.}) 58... Qe2+ 59. Kf4 Qg4+ 60. Ke5 (60. Ke3 Qxf5 $19) 60... h4 61. Qc2 Qg5 62. Ke4 Qg4+ 63. Ke5 h3 64. Qf2 (64. f6+ Qg6 $19 {decides.}) 64... Qh5 65. Qh2 {Diagram [#]} Qh4 (65... g6 $5 66. Kf4 gxf5 $1 $19 {still wins} (66... Qxf5+ $2 67. Kg3 $11 {is what White is hoping for.})) 66. Qc2 Qg5 {Diagram [#]} 67. Qf2 ({After} 67. Qh2 {I was intending} Qe3+ 68. Kd5 Qd3+ 69. Ke5 Qf3 {which seems to work:} 70. Qc2 Qg2 71. Qd1 Qg3+ 72. Ke6 Qe3+ 73. Kf7 h2 $19) 67... g6 68. Kd4 Qxf5 {Diagram [#] With White’s pawn annexed and his king cut off, the rest is not too difficult.} 69. Qh4+ Kg7 70. Qg3 g5 71. Qc7+ Kg6 72. Qb7 Kh5 73. Ke3 h2 74. Qh1 Qf4+ 75. Ke2 g4 76. Qd5+ Kh4 77. Qd8+ Kg3 0-1


