1. Nf3 {Roiz,M} d5 2. g3 c6 3. Bg2 Bg4 4. O-O Nd7 5. h3 Bh5 6. d3 Ngf6 7. Qe1 e5 8. e4 Bd6 {This way of handling the position has recently gained some popularity.} 9. exd5 {David is opening the e-file in order to put pressure on Black's central pawns.} ({Another standard approach is} 9. Nh4 O-O 10. Nf5 {, but Black usually manages to deal with an active f5:} Bc7 11. Nc3 (11. b3 Re8 12. Nd2 Nc5 13. Ba3 Ne6 $15 {Parvanyan,A - Kollars,D Hamburg GER 2016}) 11... Nb6 12. a4 a5 13. f4 dxe4 14. dxe4 exf4 15. gxf4 Bg6 16. Ng3 Re8 17. e5 Nbd5 $132 {Nakamura,H - Jakovenko,D Palma de Mallorca ESP 2017}) 9... Bxf3 {This exchange enables Nikita to release the pressure on the e5, though it looks like a definite concession.} (9... Nxd5 $5 {Another move which deserves serious attention is} 10. Nxe5 (10. Nh4 O-O 11. Nc3 Nxc3 12. bxc3 f5 $132) 10... Nxe5 11. d4 O-O 12. dxe5 Re8 13. f4 f6 14. Nc3 fxe5 15. f5 Nxc3 16. Qxc3 e4 17. Bf4 e3 $132 {Berkes,F - Swapnil,S Moscow RUS 2017}) 10. Bxf3 Nxd5 11. Nc3 ({Black would hardly face serious problems also after} 11. Nd2 $5 O-O 12. Nc4 Bc7 13. b4 Re8 $132 {, but it might be a better option for White.}) 11... Nxc3 12. bxc3 O-O {The position is about equal: the bishop pair compensates for the structural drawbacks, but not more.} 13. a4 $146 {This innovation doesn't change the assessment: Black has comfortable play.} (13. Rb1 {was previously twice employed by GM Movsesian:} Qc7 14. Bd2 (14. Bg2 Rae8 15. a4 Kh8 16. a5 f5 17. c4 f4 18. Be4 Nc5 $15 {Movsesian,S - Grischuk,A Moscow 2008}) 14... f5 15. Qe2 Rae8 16. Bg2 Kh8 17. Qh5 Bc5 18. Bg5 Bb6 $132 {Movsesian,S - Zontakh,A Loo RUS 2013}) 13... a5 {Nikita prefers to fix the favourable pawn structure, but it wouldn't be easy to attack the a4.} ({The more aggressive} 13... f5 $5 14. a5 Qc7 15. Bg2 Rae8 {might offer Black a preferable position.}) 14. Bg2 Qc7 15. Qe4 $1 {GM Howell manages to activate his queen and connect the rooks.} f5 16. Qc4+ Kh8 17. Ba3 {It is White who has to be careful - Black's attacking potential shouldn't be underestimated.} Bxa3 18. Rxa3 f4 ({The standard pawn sac} 18... e4 {should be rejected:} 19. Rb3 $1 (19. dxe4 $6 f4 20. gxf4 Rxf4 $36) 19... f4 20. gxf4 Rxf4 21. Qd4 {and the counterplay along the b-file allows White to maintain the balance.}) 19. Raa1 Nb6 ({Worth attention is} 19... Rf6 $5 20. Rfe1 Raf8 21. Qe4 Qd6 {though it would be tough to make any further progress on the kingside.}) 20. Qe4 Nd5 21. c4 Nf6 22. Qe2 fxg3 {Nikita is inviting simplifications.} ({It was possible to maintain the tension:} 22... Rae8 23. Rae1 Nd7 24. Qd2 Ra8 {, but after} 25. Qc3 $1 $11 {White also gets some targets for an attack.}) 23. fxg3 e4 24. Bxe4 $6 {Now White is going to suffer from the vulnerablity of his king.} (24. Kh2 exd3 25. cxd3 Rae8 26. Qd2 $11) 24... Nxe4 25. Qxe4 Qxg3+ 26. Qg2 Qe3+ 27. Kh1 Rae8 $15 {Despite the limited material balance, White's position is rather unpleasant.} 28. Rab1 h6 29. Rg1 Re7 30. Rbf1 Rff7 31. Qg4 Rf2 (31... Qe5 $5 32. Qg6 Kg8 $15) 32. Rxf2 Qxf2 33. Rg2 Qe1+ $6 {After this move Black couldn't deviate from exchanging the queens.} ({White's defensive task would be much tougher after} 33... Qf6 34. Kh2 Re3 $15) 34. Kh2 Qe5+ 35. Qg3 g5 (35... Qc5 36. Rf2 Kh7 37. Qf4 $11) 36. Rf2 ({An easier way was} 36. Qxe5+ Rxe5 37. h4 Kg7 38. hxg5 hxg5 39. Kg3 Kf6 40. Rh2 $11) 36... Kg7 37. Kg2 $2 {A loss of time. David is inviting fresh troubles.} (37. h4 g4 38. Kg2 h5 39. Qxe5+ Rxe5 40. d4 Re4 41. c3 Re3 42. Rb2 $11) 37... Qxg3+ 38. Kxg3 Re3+ 39. Kg2 Kg6 {Now White is doomed to a passive defence.} 40. Rf1 $2 {The last move before crossing the time control could have led to a disaster.} ({He had to play} 40. Rd2 h5 (40... Kf5 41. Rf2+ Ke6 42. Rf8 Re2+ 43. Kf3 Rh2 44. Kg4 Rxc2 45. Rh8 $11) 41. c5 $17) 40... Kh5 $2 {Returning the favour!} ({Instead} 40... Re2+ 41. Kf3 Rxc2 42. Rb1 Rh2 43. Kg3 Rd2 $19 {would have secured Nikita a winning position.}) 41. Rf6 $1 {Eventually David manages to activate his rooks again.} Re1 (41... Re2+ 42. Rf2 Rxf2+ 43. Kxf2 Kg6 (43... g4 44. d4 Kg5 45. hxg4 Kxg4 46. Ke3 Kf5 47. c5 h5 48. c4 h4 49. d5 $11) 44. c5 $1 Kf5 45. Ke3 h5 46. d4 g4 47. hxg4+ Kxg4 48. c4 Kf5 49. d5 $11) 42. Rf7 Kh4 43. Rxb7 Re2+ 44. Kf3 Rxc2 45. Rh7 h5 46. Ke4 $1 {The activity of the pieces enables White to achieve a draw now.} Rh2 47. c5 Rxh3 48. Rh6 Rh1 49. Rxc6 g4 50. d4 Re1+ 51. Kf5 Rd1 52. Ke5 Re1+ 53. Kf5 g3 54. Rg6 Kh3 55. d5 Rc1 56. c6 g2 57. Ke6 h4 58. Kd7 Kh2 59. d6 g1=Q 60. Rxg1 Kxg1 61. c7 h3 62. c8=Q Rxc8 63. Kxc8 h2 64. d7 h1=Q 65. d8=Q Qc6+ 66. Qc7 Qxa4 {Black has won a pawn, but his advantage is symbolic now.} 67. Qc5+ Kf1 68. Kc7 Qb4 69. Kc6 {The simplest.} Ke1 70. Qc1+ Ke2 71. Qc2+ Ke3 72. Qc1+ Kd3 73. Qd1+ Kc3 74. Qc1+ Kb3 75. Qb1+ 1/2-1/2


