1. Nf3 d5 2. e3 {Is surely not the most ambitious move. Apparently, David prefered to "play chess" instead of discussing the theory.} Nf6 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 exd5 6. d4 a6 ({If the knight is already developed to c3, then c4 seems to be the best option for Black:} 6... c4 $5 7. Be2 (7. Ne5 Nc6 (7... Bb4 $4 8. Qa4+) 8. b3 Bb4 9. Bd2 Bxc3 10. Bxc3 Ne4 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Qc1 Qf6 $15) 7... Bb4 8. O-O (8. Bd2 $5 a5 9. b3 Bxc3 10. Bxc3 b5 $13) 8... Bxc3 9. bxc3 O-O $13) {Diagram [#]} 7. g3 $1 {This move was new to me.} (7. Be2 {- 98/(308) Hoang,Thi Bao Tram 2303 - Sadorra,Julio Catalino 2548, Ho Chi Minh City 2015 - 125/122}) 7... Nc6 (7... c4 $5) 8. Bg2 {Diagram [#]} Be7 $6 {This is clearly a mistake.} ({Instead} 8... c4 $1 {was absolutely mandatory. After} 9. Ne5 Bb4 10. Bd2 O-O 11. O-O Re8 12. Nxc6 bxc6 $11 {the position was roughly equal in Carlsen, Magnus 2845 - Mamedyarov,Shakhriyar 2790, Shamkir 2019}) 9. O-O O-O 10. Ne5 $5 ({This game was played on the second board. Curiously, the very same position was reached on the second board (!) of the other match that was played in Hockenheim as well. Nico Georgiadis managed to save himself and clinch a draw from a very difficult position:} 10. dxc5 {is both simple and good.} Bxc5 11. b3 Re8 12. Bb2 Bg4 13. h3 Bf5 14. Ne2 Rc8 15. Nf4 Be4 16. Rc1 Ba7 {(Abasov, Nijat 2655 - Georgiadis,Nico 2529, Deutschland 2020)} 17. Bxf6 Qxf6 18. Nxd5 $16) 10... Be6 $146 (10... Qc7) 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. dxc5 Bxc5 13. b3 $14 {Diagram [#]} d4 $1 {Played after a long thought, as it took me a while to realise that Black would be clearly worse if I did not radically change the course of the game. White is going to fix and then to attack the hanging pawns, which would lead to a difficult and passive position for black. I need to be able to solve such problems quicker in the future!} 14. Na4 (14. exd4 $2 Bxd4 15. Bb2 c5 $1 $11 {Of course, White should avoid} 16. Bxa8 $2 Qxa8 $19 {as Black would be able to generate a devastating attack on the light squares.}) 14... Ba7 15. exd4 (15. Bxc6 $2 Rc8 16. Bf3 (16. Bg2 Bg4 $1 17. Qe1 Re8 $19) 16... Bh3 $1 17. Re1 d3 18. Nb2 Rxc1 $1 $19) (15. e4 d3 $1 16. Nb2 (16. Kh1 $2 Ng4 $19) 16... Bg4 $1 17. Qxd3 Qxd3 18. Nxd3 Be2 19. Nb4 Bxf1 20. Kxf1 $13) 15... Bxd4 16. Bb2 Bxb2 17. Nxb2 Bd5 {Diagram [#] Now we reach the position I aimed for with 13...d4. Due to the weak c6 pawn Black is still slightly worse, but the outpost on d5 and his fairly active pieces should offer decent compensation for the bad structure.} 18. Rc1 Ra7 $6 (18... Re8 $2 {would be a blunder due to} 19. Rxc6 $1 $16) ({Instead,} 18... Qa5 $1 {was called for. In actual fact, this was my initial idea when we reached the position on the board} 19. Na4 Rfe8 $11 {and Black should be very close to equality.}) 19. Nc4 Re7 20. Ne3 {Diagram [#]} Qa5 $6 {Now, it is too late for the queen move. I wanted to avoid the exchange of the queens entirely, but at that very moment there was no other option available.} (20... Bxg2 21. Qxd8 Rxd8 22. Kxg2 Rd2 23. Rc2 Rxc2 24. Nxc2 Re2 25. Rc1 Rd2 $1 $11 (25... Ne4 $4 26. Kf3 $18)) 21. Qc2 $6 ({The obvious} 21. Nxd5 cxd5 22. Rc2 Rfe8 23. Qd4 $16 {would have led to a clear advantage for White thanks to the better pawn structure and mighty bishop on g2.}) 21... Bxg2 22. Kxg2 Nd5 $2 (22... Re6 $11 {transposes to the game.}) 23. Nc4 $6 (23. Nf5 $6 Re5 $11) (23. Nxd5 $1 {Apparently, both of us underestimated White's chances after the exchange of the knights.} cxd5 (23... Qxd5+ 24. Kg1 Re6 25. Rfd1 $16) 24. Rfd1 $16 {would have given David a large long-term advantage thanks to the better pawn structure and superior major pieces.}) 23... Qd8 24. Rfd1 Rfe8 $11 {Diagram [#] Black seems to be doing really well now, since he should be able to defend the only weakness, namely the pawn on c6. At the same time all the black pieces are very well placed.} 25. Rd2 Re6 26. h4 $6 {Weakening the king's position without obvious reason.} Qf6 27. Qd3 h5 28. a3 Re4 29. Na5 $2 $138 {Diagram [#] A decisive mistake. My opponent was already in a very serious time trouble. Diagram [#]} Rxh4 $1 (29... Ne3+ $5 {was also promising, but I did not notice this move.} 30. fxe3 Rxe3 31. Qf1 Qe5 $1 {A powerful double attack!} 32. Qf4 Qxa5 33. Rd7 R8e7 34. Rcd1 Re2+ 35. Kh3 R2e4 36. Qf2 Qe5 $17) 30. Nxc6 {Diagram [#]} ({It was still possible to continue the fight after} 30. Rc4 $1 Rg4 31. Qf3 Qg5 $17 {however, it is almost impossible to find such a move in serious time trouble.}) 30... Nf4+ $1 31. gxf4 Qxf4 32. Rg1 {The best defence for White.} (32. Ne7+ Kh8 $1 $19 (32... Kf8 $2 33. Ng6+ fxg6 34. Qd6+ $1 $15)) 32... Rg4+ $1 (32... Re6 33. Ne7+ Rxe7 34. Qd8+ Kh7 35. Qxe7 Rh2+ 36. Kf1 Qxd2 37. Rxg7+ Kxg7 38. Qe5+ Kg6 39. Qxh2 Qd3+ 40. Kg2 Qxb3 41. Qd6+ Qe6 42. Qd3+ $17) 33. Kh1 Rxg1+ 34. Kxg1 Re1+ 35. Kg2 {Diagram [#]} Qg5+ $1 {The key move!} (35... Qg4+ $2 36. Qg3 Qe4+ 37. f3 $1 (37. Qf3 $4 Rg1+ $1 $19)) 36. Kh2 (36. Qg3 Qxd2 $19) 36... Qh4+ 37. Kg2 Qg5+ 38. Kh2 Qg1+ 39. Kh3 Qh1+ 40. Kg3 Qg1+ 41. Kh3 Qh1+ 42. Kg3 Rg1+ 43. Kf4 Qxc6 $19 {Now, Black is completely winning. The rest was rather easy to execute.} 44. Qd5 Qc1 45. Ke4 Qxa3 46. Qxh5 Qb4+ 47. Kd3 Qxb3+ 48. Ke2 {Diagram [#]} Qb5+ $1 49. Qxb5 axb5 50. Rd5 Rb1 51. Ke3 g6 52. Rd6 Re1+ 53. Kf4 Re6 54. Rd8+ Kg7 55. Rb8 Rf6+ 56. Ke3 Rf5 57. f4 Kf6 58. Re8 Rc5 59. Ke4 Rc4+ 60. Kf3 Rb4 61. Re5 Rb1 62. Kg4 b4 63. Rb5 b3 64. Rb6+ Kg7 65. Kf3 b2 66. Kg2 f5 67. Rb8 g5 0-1


