1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. a4 ({Three weeks later Howell preferred to debate} 6. h3 {with fellow h3 fan, Magus Carlsen. Play followed Svidler-Ivanisevic, Khanty-Mansiysk Olympiad 2010, right up until} e6 7. g4 Be7 8. Bg2 Nfd7 $1 {(this sensible, prophylactic choice continues to hold up well)} 9. Be3 Nc6 10. Qd2 O-O 11. O-O Nde5 12. b3 Nxd4 13. Bxd4 {when Carlsen went} Ng6 ({Ivanisevic had preferred} 13... b5 {, as saw back in October}) 14. Be3 ({after} 14. a4 Bd7 {it's not so easy to decide what to do with White's rooks and} 15. f4 $6 {doesn't work because of} Nxf4 $1 16. Qxf4 e5) 14... Qc7 15. Ne2 b5 16. c4 bxc4 17. Rac1 Bb7 18. Rxc4 Qd7 {with a pretty comfortable position for Black in Howell-Carlsen, London 2010.}) 6... Nc6 ({I've long been a fan of this move, but Black can actually remain true to the spirit of the Najdorf with} 6... e5 7. Nf3 Qc7 {. The critical test is} 8. Bg5 Nbd7 9. Nd2 {when it looks like White will obtain a bind, but with} h6 10. Bh4 g5 $1 11. Bg3 Nc5 12. Bc4 $5 ({ambitious instead} 12. a5 {was see in S.B. Hansen-Nakamura, Copenhagen 2005, which Tony covered at the time,}) ({but} 12. Qf3 {is more common}) 12... Be6 ({Tony recommended} 12... Ncxe4 $5 {, but Adams must have had something ready here perhaps it was} 13. Ncxe4 Nxe4 14. Bxf7+ $5 Kxf7 15. Nxe4 Bf5 {, as in Panchenko-Vitolinsh, Dnepropetrovsk 1980, and then} 16. Qf3 Kg6 17. h4 {when White's slightly safer king position perhaps just about outweighs Black's advantage of the two bishops}) 13. Qe2 Rc8 14. Bxe6 fxe6 $1 15. a5 Be7 16. h4 Kf7 17. Kf1 Rhg8 {Black was able to reach a satisfactory position and drew without much trouble in Adams-Bogner, German League 2010.}) 7. h3 ({Highly unusual. Instead} 7. Be2 {is White's standard choice when} e5 {gives him a choice, with} 8. Nb3 (8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. f4 {is the independent approach, but the queenless middlegame arising after} a5 10. fxe5 dxe5 11. Qxd8+ Kxd8 {is fine for Black}) 8... Be7 {taking play into the 6 Be2 variation.}) 7... e5 ({I also wondered about} 7... d5 {, but couldn't see what was wrong with trying to seize the initiative in the centre in true Najdorf fashion.}) 8. Nde2 $6 ({After} 8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. Bc4 Be6 {Black would have been pretty comfortable, but the text is rather ambitious and likely too ambitious.}) 8... Be6 9. f4 d5 10. f5 Bc8 $6 ({I wasn't convinced by} 10... Nxe4 $2 11. fxe6 Qh4+ ({Black also seems to come up short after} 11... Bb4 $5 12. exf7+ Kxf7 13. Qd3) 12. g3 Nxg3 13. exf7+ Kxf7 14. Qxd5+ {,}) ({but there was no need to retreat to c8, decent though the position it leads to is. Instead} 10... d4 $1 11. fxe6 fxe6 12. Bg5 (12. Nb1 $6 {preserves the piece, but after} Nxe4 13. Qd3 Nc5 14. Qf3 d3 {Black has a huge initiative}) 12... h6 13. Bxf6 Qxf6 {would have seen Black either regaining his piece with the upper hand or rejecting a repetition to attack with} 14. Na2 Qh4+ 15. Kd2 Qg5+ 16. Ke1 Bc5 $5 {.}) 11. exd5 Nb4 12. Ng3 Nfxd5 $6 ({If I wanted to recapture the pawn then} 12... Nbxd5 {was correct,}) ({but} 12... Bc5 $5 {(Nezis)} 13. Bg5 Bd4 {looks like a decent alternative, although White probably is OK here after} 14. Nh5 Kf8 15. g4 Nbxd5 16. Qd2 {with something of a mess.}) 13. Nxd5 $6 ({Allowing Black to escape into a roughly-level middlegame, but} 13. Bc4 $1 {would have been awkward, since} Nf4 14. Bxf7+ Ke7 15. Bb3 Qxd1+ 16. Kxd1 Nxg2 17. Bg5+ {leaves White with slightly the safer king and slightly the brighter prospects.}) 13... Qxd5 14. c3 Qxd1+ 15. Kxd1 Nc6 16. Be3 h5 $5 ({I'm still not sure if this was a good idea. The rook will become tied down to defending the h-pawn, but White too must weaken his kingside structure. The alternative was to regroup without delay with} 16... Ne7 17. Bd3 Nd5 18. Bg5 Bd7 {.}) 17. h4 Ne7 18. Bd3 Nd5 19. Bg5 Bd7 20. Be4 Bc6 {Thus both light-squared bishops reach the key diagonal at the same time and around here the chances still appear roughly balanced.} 21. Ke2 f6 22. Bd2 O-O-O 23. Rhd1 Bc5 24. b4 $5 {An ambitious if tempting advance.} Bb6 25. Kf3 $2 ({One can understand why Howell didn't want to allow} 25. c4 Ne7 26. Bxc6 Nxc6 27. c5 Nd4+ {when Black's knight reaches a decent square, but perhaps he should have gone in for this}) ({or calmly retreated his bishop to a safe square with} 25. Bf3 {.}) 25... Ne7 ({Far from terrible, but} 25... Nxb4 $1 {would have been a little embarrassing for White:} 26. cxb4 ({or} 26. Be3 Bxe3 27. Rxd8+ Rxd8 28. Kxe3 Nd5+ 29. Bxd5 Bxd5 30. Nxh5 Rh8 31. Nxg7 Rxh4 {with advantage to Black}) 26... Rd3+ 27. Ke2 Rxg3 {and Black nets a clear pawn, since} 28. Bf3 {doesn't trap his rook on account of} e4 {.}) 26. Bxc6 bxc6 $2 ({Whereas I completely missed the tactic on the last turn, I did consider} 26... Rd3+ $1 {, but wasn't so sure about} 27. Ke2 Rxg3 28. Be4 (28. Bd7+ Kb8 29. Kf1 {may be a better try, followed by pushing the queenside pawns}) 28... Rg4 {. However, White can't trap the rook here either and} 29. Bf3 Rxh4 {would just have left me a pawn to the good.}) 27. Be1 g6 $5 28. fxg6 Rdg8 ({I used up a fair amount of my remaining five minutes at this point, trying to find a way to seize the initiative. Black doesn't have to play so provocatively, but after} 28... Nxg6 29. Rxd8+ Bxd8 30. Nf5 Ne7 31. Nd6+ Kc7 32. Rd1 Nd5 {White is likely slightly for choice in the resulting unbalanced ending.}) 29. Rd6 Rxg6 $6 ({Somewhat more consistent with my last two moves would have been} 29... f5 $1 {when anything might have happened in the resulting scramble.}) 30. Rad1 Bc7 31. Re6 Rd8 $2 ({And here too} 31... f5 {was a better try. Howell really is a master in the art of luring his opponents into trying to find ways to be better, which just burns up their time advantage and often, as here, also leads to their own position collapsing.}) 32. Rxd8+ Kxd8 33. Nxh5 f5 34. Rxg6 Nxg6 35. Ng7 e4+ {White should be winning, but with both of us well down below two minutes by this stage I realised that I could still cause some difficulties with my e-pawn.} 36. Ke2 Nf4+ 37. Kf1 e3 38. g3 e2+ 39. Kf2 Nd3+ 40. Kxe2 Nxe1 41. Kxe1 $2 ({Missing} 41. Ne6+ {, which would have induced immediate resignation.}) 41... Bxg3+ 42. Ke2 Bxh4 43. Nxf5 Bf6 {Now Black is able to fight on and even has good chances to hold.} 44. Kd3 Kc7 45. Kc4 Be5 46. Nd4 Bd6 47. Ne6+ Kb7 48. a5 $1 {A big decision, but if White is going to make progress then he needs to restrict Black's king, use his knight to fend off the bishop and run with his own king around to d7.} Kb8 $2 ({I can't see a defence after this, but} 48... Be5 {would have offered decent chances to hold:} 49. Nc5+ Ka7 50. Kd3 Bg7 51. Ne4 Be5 52. Kc4 Kb8 {and it's not at all easy to find a way for White to get his king in.}) 49. Kd4 Kb7 50. Ke4 Kb8 51. Kf5 {Invading and winning, although I continued to blitz for a little longer.} Kb7 52. Nc5+ Ka7 53. Ke6 Bf4 54. Kd7 Bd2 55. Ne4 Be1 56. Kxc6 Bh4 57. Kc5 Be1 58. c4 Bh4 59. Nc3 Bf2+ 60. Kc6 Bd4 61. Nd5 Bf2 62. c5 Bh4 63. Kd7 Bg3 64. c6 1-0


