1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 e6 3. e4 d5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. e5 Ne4 6. Nf3 Nc6 {The most popular choice overall, but the alternative} (6... Bf5 {has been in vogue for the last few years. Indeed Howell had played this move with Black a few days earlier (see below). White has now tried:} 7. Be2 (7. d4 Bb4 {and now:} 8. Qa4+ (8. Bd2 {with a further split:} Nxd2 (8... Bxc3 9. Bxc3 O-O 10. Be2 Nd7 (10... c5 11. dxc5 Nxc3 12. bxc3 Be4 13. O-O Nd7 14. Nd4 Nxc5 15. f3 Bg6 16. Nb5 {worked out well for White in Giri-Wojtaszek, which can be found in the Archives}) 11. O-O c5 12. dxc5 Nxc3 13. bxc3 Nxc5 14. Rc1 Rc8 15. Nd4 Bd7 16. c4 dxc4 17. Bxc4 {with balanced chances, So,W (2770)-Nakamura,H (2787) Leuven (blitz) 2016 1-0 (71)}) 9. Qxd2 O-O 10. Bd3 Bxd3 11. Qxd3 c6 12. O-O Na6 13. Ne2 Be7 14. h3 Qd7 15. Nf4 Nc7 16. Rfe1 Ne6 17. Qf5 Rad8 18. Qg4 Nxf4 19. Qxf4 b6 {with a level game, Timofeev,A (2586)-Riazantsev,A (2646) Kolomna 2016 ½-½  (34)}) 8... Nc6 9. Bb5 O-O 10. Bxc6 Bxc3+ 11. bxc3 bxc6 12. Qxc6 {grabbing the pawn on offer} Rb8 13. c4 Be6 14. cxd5 Bxd5 15. Qc2 c5 16. O-O cxd4 17. Qd3 Nc5 (17... Rc8 18. Qxd4 Nc3 19. Qe3 Qb6 {gives Black enough counterplay for the pawn}) 18. Qxd4 Ne6 19. Qd3 Ba8 20. Qxd8 Rfxd8 21. Be3 Rb2 22. a3 a5 {and Black eventually held this slightly worse endgame, Jones,G (2650)-Howell,D  (2663) Bournemouth 2016 ½-½ (70)}) 7... c5 8. d4 Nc6 9. O-O {is covered in Aronian-Lysyj, in the Archives}) 7. Bb5 Be7 8. Qa4 {The course of this game seems to confirm that White should look elsewhere in search of an advantage:} (8. O-O O-O 9. Re1 Bf5 10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. Nd4 Bd7 $5 12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. Rxe4 c5 14. Nf3 Bc6 15. Re3 Qd5 16. b3 {and White was a bit better in Ding Liren-Wang Yue, see this game in the Archives}) (8. Nd4 Nxc3 (8... Bd7 $1 {is how Black should play this}) 9. dxc3 Bd7 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Bd3 O-O 12. Qc2 g6 13. Bh6 Re8 14. O-O {with a pleasant edge for White, Murey,J (2380)-Kholmov,R (2550) Sukhumi 1972 ½-½ (47)}) (8. Bxc6+ bxc6 9. Qa4 {trying to win a pawn, can be answered by} Bd7 10. Nxe4 c5 11. Qc2 dxe4 12. Qxe4 Bb5 {and Black has good compensation with White's king stuck in the centre.}) 8... Bd7 9. Nxe4 a6 $1 {A critical intermezzo.} 10. Bxc6 {Instead} (10. Be2 Nxe5 11. Qc2 Nxf3+ 12. Bxf3 dxe4 13. Bxe4 c6 {is equal}) 10... Bxc6 11. Nf6+ gxf6 12. Qf4 (12. Qd4 Qd7 13. exf6 Qe6+ 14. Qe5 {would transpose to the game}) 12... Qd7 {Not bad, but Black can do even better with} (12... Rg8 13. O-O d4 $1 14. exf6 Qd6 $1 15. d3 Qxf6 16. Qxf6 Bxf6 17. Re1+ Kd7 {and Black's two bishops have plenty of scope and give him the edge here, see Kortschnoj-Nielsen, in the Archives}) (12... d4 $1 {as suggested by John Watson, is similar to the previous line and also strong.}) 13. exf6 Qe6+ 14. Qe5 Qxe5+ 15. Nxe5 Bxf6 16. Nxc6 bxc6 17. Rb1 Kd7 {Black is slightly better in this endgame. Nevertheless, David Howell gradually outplays his opponent throughout the rest of the game, first equalizing, then increasing his advantage as Black slips up.} 18. b3 Rhe8+ {There is no particular virtue in chasing White's king here, as it is better placed in the centre than castled on the kingside.} (18... a5 $1 {opens the a-file as quickly as possible.}) 19. Kd1 a5 20. Bb2 Bxb2 21. Rxb2 c5 $6 {This is probably where Black loses any advantage. Instead after} (21... a4 {or}) (21... Re6 {and Black is still the one pressing.}) 22. Re1 Rxe1+ 23. Kxe1 Kd6 24. Rc2 {White is definitely fine now, and starts swinging his rook over to attack Black's split kingside pawns.} a4 25. Rc3 axb3 26. axb3 f5 $6 {A pseudo-active move that make the f5-pawn a target. Black is still OK after} (26... Rg8 27. Kf1 f6 {or}) (26... Ra1+ 27. Ke2 Rg1 28. Rg3 h5 {etc.}) 27. Rh3 Re8+ 28. Kd1 Re7 29. f4 {Now White has the more active rook and weak pawns to work on.} Rf7 {Passive.} (29... c4 {was a better try, activating the king via the c5-square.}) 30. Rh6+ Kd7 31. Ke2 c6 32. Kf3 Kc7 33. h3 Kb6 34. g4 fxg4+ $6 {Giving White a strong passed f-pawn} (34... c4 35. bxc4 dxc4 36. Rd6 Kc5 {activating the king with some chances for counterplay}) 35. hxg4 c4 36. bxc4 dxc4 37. Rd6 Kc5 38. Rd8 Ra7 $6 {It takes too much time to move the rook around, here} (38... Kb4 {was the best chance}) 39. f5 {The endgame is objectively winning now, and Howell doesn't go wrong in realizing his advantage.} Ra1 40. Kf2 Ra7 41. Ke3 Ra1 42. f6 Re1+ 43. Kf4 Rd1 44. Kg5 c3 45. f7 Rf1 46. f8=Q+ Rxf8 47. Rxf8 c2 48. Rf1 Kd4 49. Kh6 Kd3 50. Kxh7 Kxd2 51. g5 c1=Q 52. Rxc1 Kxc1 53. g6 c5 54. g7 c4 55. g8=Q c3 56. Qg1+ Kb2 57. Qd4 1-0


