1. c4 e5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. Nf3 {5 Nc3 is White's most common move, but the line employed by Howell. with 5 Nf3, 6 0-0 and 7 d4 has also been well tested.} Nc6 6. O-O (6. Nc3 Bc5 {transposes to a line we have looked at a lot in the last year and a half, see Nakamura-Aronian and earlier games in the Archives. Howell's move-order avoid this idea for the reason given in the next note.}) 6... Be7 {Black usually chooses between this and 6...Nb6, but has tried other moves:} (6... Bc5 $6 {isn't a good idea in this version, for example} 7. Nxe5 $1 Nxe5 8. d4 Nb4 9. dxc5 Qxd1 10. Rxd1 Nc2 11. Bf4 f6 12. Nc3 Nxa1 13. Nd5 O-O 14. Nxc7 Rb8 15. Rxa1 {and after a fairly forced series of moves, White has two pawns for the exchange, and is better due to his active two bishops and greater activity, Perez Fungueiro,M (2250)-Beltran Ortiz,E  (2005) Padron 2002 1-0 (50)}) (6... f5 $5 {is an unusual try analyzed in Movsesian-Ponkratov in the Archives.}) (6... Nb6 {can be answered by 7 d3 leading to the mainline Reverse Dragon, or the quite popular alternative} 7. b3 {- see Adams-Vachier-Lagrave in the Archives}) 7. d4 e4 8. Ne5 f5 9. Nxc6 bxc6 {The key position for this variation. White aims for pressure on the c-file and play against Black's weak c-pawns. On the other hand, Black has gained space on the kingside and blocked in White's "Dragon" bishop. Overall, White has scored around 60% from here in some 150 games in my database, and a higher percentage with Howell's 10 Qc2. Nevertheless, as Burg shows, if Black plays actively and with a sense of urgency, he has fair chances.} 10. Qc2 {White's most testing move. On ChessPublishing, we have looked at a number of earlier games with other moves (all game references can be found in the PGN Archives):} (10. Nd2 {is the main alternative, when:} c5 $6 (10... O-O 11. Nb3 a5 (11... Qd6 12. Qc2 Qg6 13. Bd2 f4 $2 (13... Ba6 {is OK for Black}) 14. Rfc1 Rf6 15. Na5 {favoured White in Wang Hao-Rublevsky}) 12. Bd2 a4 13. Na5 Bd7 $5 (13... c5 {is an adequate alternative}) 14. Qxa4 Qe8 {when Black probably doesn't have enough for the pawn, but he won anyway in Paunovic-Topalov}) 11. dxc5 Bxc5 {was played in Janssen-Van den Doel when White could have immediately got a winning position with} 12. Nxe4 $1) (10. Qa4 {is less critical. Now} Qd7 11. Rd1 c5 12. Qxd7+ Bxd7 13. dxc5 Be6 {was equal in Topalov-Timman}) (10. f3 exf3 11. Bxf3 O-O 12. Nc3 Be6 13. Qa4 Nb6 14. Qxc6 Bd7 {with a draw by repetition in Gulko-Harikrishna}) 10... Qd6 {Black has also played the other possible queen move, which seems roughly equivalent, for example:} (10... Qd7 11. Nc3 O-O {and now:} 12. f3 (12. Re1 {Marin calls this a "rather mysterious move"} Nb4 (12... Rb8 {should gives balanced chances}) 13. Qa4 Kh8 14. Bf4 c5 $6 15. Qxd7 Bxd7 16. dxc5 Nc2 17. Red1 Nxa1 18. Rxd7 Bxc5 19. Be5 Rg8 20. Rxc7 {and White was much better in Aronian,L (2792)-Fressinet,L (2687) Paris (Rapid) 2016 1-0 (49)}) (12. Nxd5 cxd5 13. Bf4 c6 14. Rfc1 Bb7 15. e3 a5 16. h4 Rfc8 17. Qd1 Ba6 {with a level game, Topalov,V (2749)-Karjakin,S (2781) Paris  (Blitz) 2017 1/2-1/2 (35)}) 12... exf3 13. Bxf3 {is an untested alternative. White opens the centre and has chances for a slight edge.}) 11. Nd2 {I believe the alternative is more critical:} (11. Nc3 Be6 12. Nxd5 Bxd5 13. Bf4 {White gains a tempo compared to Topalov-Karjakin in the previous note, taking advantage of Black's queen positioning on the d6-square.} Qd7 14. f3 exf3 {was played in Miroshnichenko,E (2651)-Eljanov,P (2712) Kiev 2011 1/2-1/2 (22), and now} 15. exf3 O-O 16. Be5 {would give White the upper hand, thanks to the powerfully placed e5-bishop.}) 11... O-O 12. Nc4 Qe6 {Black has also played:} (12... Qf6 13. Rd1 Rd8 14. Bf4 Nxf4 15. gxf4 Rxd4 16. Rxd4 Qxd4 17. Ne5 Qc5 18. Qxc5 Bxc5 19. e3 Bd6 20. Nxc6 a5 {with a roughly equal endgame, Gofshtein,L  (2504)-Baron,T (2504) Israel 2011 1-0 (29)}) 13. Na5 Nb4 14. Qc3 c5 $1 {Giving up the front c-pawn this way causes White to block the c-file. Instead:} (14... Nxa2 15. Qxc6 Bd7 16. Qxe6+ Bxe6 17. Bd2 {would leave White for choice, since he still has the open c-file to play with}) 15. dxc5 Nxa2 16. Qa3 Nxc1 17. Rfxc1 Bf6 18. e3 Ba6 {Black's two bishops and open lines give him sufficient counterplay} 19. Rab1 {White hopes to get his b-pawn moving.} Rfd8 20. b4 Bd3 {The bishop occupies an imposing outpost, but this is neutralized after White's next. Instead:} (20... Bb5 21. Bf1 a6 {would create a blockade of the queenside pawns, giving Black equal chances.}) 21. Bf1 Bxf1 {Of course not:} (21... Bxb1 22. Bc4 {with a powerful pin}) 22. Rxf1 Rd3 23. Qa4 Rad8 24. Nc6 R8d7 25. b5 {It looks as if White has outplayed his opponent, with positional pressure on the queenside, but Black now shows he still has resources.} f4 $1 {Targeting White's loosened kingside structure.} 26. exf4 e3 27. fxe3 {Instead:} (27. b6 {trading the queenside pawns will give White at best a 3 vs 2 kingside scenario with a rather exposed king. Now for example} cxb6 28. cxb6 exf2+ 29. Rxf2 axb6 30. Rxb6 Rd1+ 31. Kg2 Qd5+ 32. Kh3 Qh5+ 33. Kg2 Qd5+ {would lead to a draw}) 27... Qxe3+ 28. Kh1 Qxc5 29. Qa2+ Kh8 30. Rbe1 Re3 {It was safer to prevent back-rank issues, for example:} (30... g6 {and play remains dynamically roughly balanced}) 31. Qxa7 Qd5+ 32. Kg1 Rxe1 33. Rxe1 h6 34. Qe3 Kh7 35. Qe4+ {In the rook and minor piece endgame, Black gets enough counterplay. After:} (35. Ne5 {White is a pawn up, although a draw is still the favourite in light of White's open king's position.}) 35... Qxe4 36. Rxe4 Rd1+ {Here:} (36... Rd5 37. Rb4 g5 {is even simpler, tying White's rook to the defence of the b5-pawn.}) 37. Kg2 Rd2+ 38. Kh3 h5 39. Rc4 Rd5 40. Na7 Bd4 41. Rxc7 Bxa7 42. Rxa7 Rxb5 43. Kh4 {White scores a moral victory, but this 3vs2 rook endgame should end in a draw, and Burg makes no mistake.} Kh6 44. h3 Rb4 45. Ra6+ g6 46. Rf6 Ra4 47. g4 Rxf4 48. Rxf4 g5+ 49. Kg3 gxf4+ 50. Kxf4 hxg4 51. hxg4 Kg6 52. g5 Kf7 53. Kf5 Kg7 54. g6 Kg8 55. Kf6 Kf8 56. g7+ Kg8 57. Ke6 Kxg7 1/2-1/2


