1. c4 {Sadorra,J} c6 2. Nc3 d5 3. d4 Nf6 4. cxd5 cxd5 5. Bf4 {Over the past few years, the Exchange Variation has become a serious weapon among GM against the Slav.} Nc6 6. e3 Bg4 ({This and} 6... Bf5 {can lead to the same tabiya position after} 7. Qb3 Na5 8. Qa4+ Bd7) 7. Qb3 Na5 8. Qa4+ Bd7 9. Qc2 Rc8 10. Bd3 e6 11. Nf3 b5 12. a3 Be7 {This line has been played many times over.} 13. Qe2 $5 $146 {Howell's novelty is his move order which gives slightly more options, and surely gives his opponent something to think about!} ({The standard move order goes} 13. O-O O-O 14. Ne5 ({Here, Howell's idea of delaying fc1 doesn't work due to a concrete counter-idea from Black} 14. Qe2 Nh5 $1 15. Bxb5 Bxb5 16. Nxb5 (16. Qxb5 {now this capture doesn't come with check; move order matters a lot!} Nxf4 17. exf4 Nc4 $15 {[%csl Rb5]}) 16... Qb6 17. Nc3 Nb3 18. Rad1 Nxf4 19. exf4 Bf6 $15 {Black's active pieces and White's weaknesses make Black's position much easier to play. It is actually White who has to play very accurately to hold the balance.}) 14... h6 15. h3 Nc4 16. Rfc1 $14 {and recent games show that White has an edge here.}) 13... a6 (13... Nh5 14. Bxb5 Nxf4 (14... Bxb5 15. Qxb5+) 15. exf4 O-O 16. Bd3 $14) (13... Nc4 14. Ne5 O-O 15. O-O a6 (15... Be8 16. Rfc1 $1 (16. a4 $6 {here is premature as there's no target on a6 to attack when the knight on c4 later moves.} b4 17. Nb1 (17. Nb5 a6 18. Na7 Rc7 19. Nxc4 dxc4 20. Bxc7 Qxc7 21. Bxc4 Qxa7 22. Bxa6 Bc6 $13) 17... Nxe5 18. Bxe5 Ne4 19. Nd2 Nxd2 20. Qxd2 f6 21. Bg3 Bg6 $11) 16... a6 17. a4 $1 $36) 16. a4 $5 {Sadorra,J: '!' Here we see the option made possible by Howell's move order. Sadorra,J: 'transposes to lines under the 13th move - knight a5 to c4.'} (16. Rfc1 {is also good for an edge; transposing to some previous games; but it turns out it's really not necessary to play it yet.}) 16... Be8 (16... Qb6 $2 17. Nxd7 Nxd7 18. axb5 axb5 19. b3 $16) (16... b4 17. Nb1 Nxe5 18. dxe5 $6 Ne4 19. Bxa6 Ra8 20. Bb5 (20. Bd3 Nc5 $15) 20... Bxb5 21. Qxb5 g5 $1 (21... Ra5 22. Qe2 Nc5 (22... g5 $1 23. Bg3 Qc7 $17) 23. Qd1 b3 24. Nc3 Qa8 25. Qd4 Rb8 {½-½ (25) Drozdovskij,Y (2561)-Laznicka,V (2596) playchess.com INT 2006}) 22. Bg3 Qc7 $1 $17 {[%csl Rb1,Rb5,Re5,Rg3]}) 17. Rfc1 {Sadorra,J: '!' White prepares to trade on b5 followed by b2-b3.This transposes to several games where White has better chances. The most annoying defence for Black now seems to be} Na5 18. axb5 axb5 (18... Nb3 19. bxa6 Nxc1 20. Rxc1 Qb6 21. Ra1 Ra8 22. Bg5 $1 $16) 19. Nxb5 Nb3 20. Rxc8 Qxc8 21. Re1 Ne4 22. Bxe4 dxe4 23. Nc3 f6 24. Nc4 $16 {[%cal Gc4d2,Gc4d6] And Black has to work very hard to prove he has enough compensation for the pawn.}) 14. Ne5 O-O 15. O-O Qb6 (15... Nc4 16. a4 $1 {transposes to lines under the 13th move - knight a5 to c4.}) 16. a4 {White carries on with the standard plan.} ({Another good way to continue is to go for the Pillsbury set up with:} 16. Bg5 $5 Be8 17. f4 {[%cal Gf1f3,Gf3h3]} Nc4 (17... Qd8 18. f5 $1 $40 (18. Rf3 $6 {also works but allows a nice defensive resource where White has to be more precise.} Ne4 19. Bxe7 Qxe7 20. Nxe4 dxe4 21. Bxe4 f5 22. Bd3 (22. Bc2 $1 {is the precise move that maintains the advantage.} Bh5 23. g4 Bxg4 (23... fxg4 24. Rg3 Kh8 25. Rf1) 24. Nxg4 fxg4 25. Rg3 Rc7 26. Rxg4 Rfc8 27. Be4 $14) 22... Nb3 $1 23. Raf1 Bh5 24. g4 Bxg4 25. Nxg4 fxg4 26. Rg3 Nc1 27. Qd2 Nxd3 28. Qxd3 Qh4 $11) 18... Nc4 19. Bxf6 Bxf6 20. Ng4 Be7 21. f6 gxf6 22. Nxf6+ Bxf6 23. Qh5 $18) 18. Rf3 $1 $40 {[%cal Rd3h7,Rf3h3,Rg5f6,Re2h5] White is on an attacking version of cruise control e.g.} h6 $2 19. Bxf6 Bxf6 20. Ng4 $16) 16... b4 17. Nb1 Ra8 {A natural and solid move, but it also reveals that Black didn't sense the dangers in his position. Unfortunately for Black, there is only one way to equalise and it requires a very concrete approach.} ({I'm very sure Melkumyan considered} 17... Nb3 {but the question is always what resources he saw and how he evaluated the resulting positions.} 18. Bxh7+ {It is easy to see this tactical idea and dismiss it as good for White as it wins a pawn, but let's check and go deeper:} Nxh7 (18... Kxh7 19. Qd3+ Kg8 20. Qxb3 $16 {and Black is simply a pawn down for nothing.}) 19. Nxd7 Qa5 ({After seeing the line with 19...a5, it makes sense to check a retreat where the queen controls more squares:} 19... Qb7 $1 20. Nxf8 Bxf8 21. Nd2 Nxa1 22. Rxa1 Rc2 23. b3 (23. Qd1 b3 $1 24. Rb1 Qb4 $17 (24... Nf6 $5 25. f3 Qb4)) 23... Nf6 24. f3 Qc6 $36 {[%cal Gc6c3] with a strong initiative for a pawn loss that's not even noticeable.}) 20. Nxf8 Bxf8 21. Nd2 (21. Ra2 $4 Nc1 $19) 21... Nxa1 22. Rxa1 Rc2 {When I was taking a stab at analysing this on the board, it looked like Black would gain compensation but checking the line deeper shows that White can refute this idea} 23. Qd1 $1 (23. b3 Qb6 $44 {[%cal Gb6c6,Gc6c3]}) 23... Rxb2 24. Qc1 $18) 18. Bg5 $1 Be8 19. Nd2 {White's next plan is to either go the Pillsbury way with f2-f4 or the Colle way with an early queen switch via f3-h3.} h6 20. Bh4 Rc8 21. b3 $1 {At first, I thought this move was very questionable. While it restricts all Black's minor pieces, it also gives up an important outpost for the rook on c3 which allows counterplay in the future along the 3rd rank. Then again, after seeing that Black doesn't have any concrete follow-up to penetrate (and that White has to be accurate in conducting the attack after 21. f4), I think it's a very good practical decision because it takes less risk than the other option.} ({The Pillsbury method looks simple and even best according to the engine, but things usually aren't easy when facing counterplay over the board.} 21. f4 b3 $1 {[%cal Gc8c2,Gb6b4]} 22. Rf3 $6 {A natural follow-up but Black has defensive resources to meet it.} ({The best way to conduct the attack according to the engine is} 22. Ng4 $1 Qd8 23. f5 $1 $40) (22. Rfb1 {The engine also suggests this, but really? Placing rooks in the corner is not the point of the Pillsbury setup / Stonewall structure!}) 22... Kh8 $1 {[%cal Gf6g8]} 23. Rh3 Ng8 24. Bxe7 Nxe7 {and things aren't so easy} 25. g4 $2 (25. Ng4 Nf5) 25... f6 26. Nef3 Rc2 $1 $132) (21. Bxa6 $2 Rc2 {is the last thing on White's mind.}) 21... Rc3 22. Rab1 Qc7 23. f3 $5 {Careful and solid, thinking that the a6-pawn will not go anywhere.} (23. f4 {is also playable, but only if one sees the tactic in the line after} Nd7 $5 {which probably concerned Howell} 24. Bxe7 (24. Bh7+ $1 Kxh7 25. Bxe7 Nxe5 26. Bxf8 Nd3 {Compared to the line earlier, White has an extra tempo to start a kingside attack:} 27. e4 $3 Kg8 28. Bxg7 $1 Kxg7 29. f5 $40 {And it's almost impossible to defend this over the board.}) 24... Nxe5 25. Bxf8 Nxd3 $13) 23... Bd6 24. f4 Be7 25. Rfd1 $1 {More prophylaxis from Howell.} Ne4 $2 {Melkumyan finally cracks under the tension and passivity of his position, which not many can handle well.} 26. Bxe7 Qxe7 27. Bxe4 dxe4 28. Nxe4 Rxb3 29. Rxb3 Nxb3 30. Rb1 $5 ({The more forcing line is much better as White can gain a pawn for nothing in the ending.} 30. Qxa6 Qc7 (30... f6 31. Nd3 Bg6 32. Nef2 $16 {[%csl Rb3][%cal Gd3c5]}) 31. Rb1 Qc2 32. Qd3 Qxd3 33. Nxd3 Bxa4 34. Nxb4 $16) 30... f6 31. Nc4 {The following moves were played under the pressure of time trouble so the inaccuracies were inevitable and understandable.} ({A more accurate move is} 31. Nd3 $1 Bxa4 32. Qa2 Bc6 33. Ng3 Bd5 34. e4 Bc4 35. Nc5 $16 {looks good for White to me after} Nxc5 36. Qxc4 Nd7 37. Rxb4 $16 {The position has stabilised and White gets to keep his positional advantages.} (37. Nf5 $5) (37. f5 $5)) 31... Bg6 32. Nxf6+ gxf6 33. Rxb3 Rc8 34. e4 $5 {[%cal Gb3g3,Gb3h3,Gf4f5] Another double-edged decision taken by Howell as he creates weaknesses in the centre, but also creates better chances for a kingside attack!} Qd7 $1 {Correctly and bravely taking up the challenge.} 35. d5 exd5 36. exd5 Qxd5 37. Qg4 {In this wickedly tense and sharp position, Melkumyan had 1 min 40 secs to Howell's 30 secs. Now he used almost most of his time and played the "tricky"} Rc7 $4 ({With more time and a calm mind, I'm certain Black would have played the simple} 37... Qc5+ $1 38. Kh1 (38. Ne3 Kh7 39. Qd7+ Kh8 {and it's White who's the only one in trouble here e.g.} 40. h3 $2 (40. f5 Bh5 41. h3 Re8 $40) 40... Bc2 $19) 38... Qf5 $1) 38. Qxg6+ Rg7 39. Qe8+ Kh7 {Before playing his 37th move Black stopped his analysis here thinking that it's good for him as he has a strong double attack, but he unfortunately missed White's next move} 40. Qe2 $18 {A double defence! Black tried to regain some material but both players have received extra time and it was just a matter of good calculation and technical work for the British player.} Rxg2+ 41. Qxg2 Qd1+ 42. Kf2 Qxb3 43. Qe4+ $1 {Centralising the queen with check is almost always good!} Kg7 44. Nd6 ({Other moves also win here} 44. Qe7+ Kg8 45. Ne3 Qxa4 46. Ng4 $18 {with mate coming soon.}) 44... Qc3 45. Qe7+ Kg8 46. Ne8 Qd4+ 47. Kg2 Qd5+ 48. Kg3 Qf7 49. Nxf6+ Kg7 50. Ne8+ Kg8 51. Nf6+ Kg7 52. Qxf7+ Kxf7 53. Nd5 b3 54. f5 b2 55. Nc3 h5 56. h4 Ke7 57. Kf4 Kd6 1-0


