{[%evp 0,24,27,-37,14,14,17,9,12,17,17,20,-2,-4,-5,-17,-8,-2,-2,-15,-15,-18,-12,-20,-20,-21,13] In the previous game, White's limitations were caused by the fact that he did not manage to block the d5-pawn with the best-suited piece, meaning the knight. In the next example, he will achieve that due to Black's neutral play, but even that does not seem to ensure an advantage.} 1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3 e6 4. e3 Nc6 5. d4 d5 6. cxd5 exd5 7. Bb5 Bd6 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. O-O O-O 10. b3 a6 11. Bxc6 bxc6 12. Bb2 Bg4 13. Ne2 Bd6 14. Ne5 Bxe5 15. Bxe5 Qe7 16. Bxf6 Qxf6 17. f3 Bd7 18. Qd4 Qe7 19. Rac1 Rfe8 20. Kf2 a5 21. Rc5 h5 {This is a good move, but at this stage, Black had more urgent things to do.} (21... a4 $5 22. b4 (22. bxa4 $2 Rxa4 $19 23. Qxa4 Qxe3+ 24. Kg3 Qxc5) 22... a3 {White's blockade is marred by the potential weaknesses on b4 and a2.}) (21... Reb8 $5 22. Rfc1 a4 $11) 22. Rfc1 h4 23. R1c3 {White has managed to regroup properly and is close to installing the knight on d4.} Reb8 24. a3 {Unfortunately, this is necessary in order to deprive Black of counterplay.} (24. h3 Rb4 (24... a4 $5 25. b4 a3 $11) 25. Qd2 a4 $11 {WHite's queenside weakness (on a2 or b3) will compensate for his trumps.}) 24... Ra6 {The plan of keeping the rooks isolated on the queenside could have led to problems.} (24... a4 25. b4 $16 {absolves White from an important weakness, helping him to consolidate his blockade.}) (24... Qd6 $5 25. h3 Qe7 (25... Rb6 $2 26. Qxh4 Rxb3 27. Rxa5 $1 Rxa5 28. Rxb3 $16)) (24... Re8 $5 {would have kept e3 under pressure, restricting White's possibilities.}) 25. Qd3 Rbb6 $6 {Consequent, but dubious.} (25... Raa8 $1 {It would have been best to admit the previous mistake.} 26. Nd4 Qd6 27. Kg1 (27. h3 Qh2 $132) 27... Re8 28. Qc2 (28. Nxc6 Bxc6 29. Rxc6 Qxa3 $11) (28. h3 Bxh3 $5 $11) (28. a4 Rac8 29. Rxa5 c5 30. Nc2 h3 $132) 28... Re7 $11 {possibly followed by ...Rae8.}) 26. Nd4 Qf6 {For a long time, Black will refrain from ...h4-h3, while White would not spot the merits of h2-h3.} ({True, for Black, the issue is anything but one-sided.} 26... h3 27. g3 {secures White's kingside, allowing the king's transfer to the queenside.} Ra8 28. Ke2 $5 Rbb8 29. Kd2 Re8 30. Kc1 Rac8 31. Kb2 g6 32. a4 $14 {The pawn on b3 is safely defended, while that on a5 is a permanent weakness. White may also think of a way of starting a pawn attack on the kingside, even though that would be not easy to achieve. In any case, the play would have been one-sided.}) 27. Qd2 (27. h3 $1 {would have turned the pawn on h4 into a weakness. White could also p[lay h2-h3 a bit later, but we analyze this idea only once.} Qd6 (27... Qg5 28. f4 Qg3+ {fails to offer counterplay.} 29. Kf1 Qh2 30. Nf3 Qh1+ 31. Kf2 Qa1 32. a4 $16 {The pawn on h4 is doomed.}) 28. f4 Qf6 29. Qd2 Ra8 30. Kg1 Qd6 31. Qe1 {We first investigate the idea of attacking h4, which will prove ineffective.} Qe7 $1 {The queen needs to keep the rook on c5 under pressure.} (31... Qf6 32. Nf3 $16) 32. Kh1 $5 ({The idea behind Black's last move is that} 32. Nf3 $2 {runs into} Rxb3 $1 $11) 32... Ra7 33. Qd2 {Well, the first plan did not work. Time to try something different. I could have examined the plans in different variations, but I wanted to follow a possible thinking process during a game. It cannot harm to confuse the opponent by starting to create fake threats in order to switch to the real ones later.} Ra8 34. Qc2 Qd6 35. Nf3 Re8 36. Ng5 $1 {Black needs to weaken his kingside.} g6 37. Qf2 f6 38. Nf3 $16 {Now we see why the king stands better on h1 than on h2.}) 27... Rb8 {The start of a long phase of "just moving the pieces around".} 28. Qd3 Rbb6 29. Qd2 Rb8 30. Rc1 Qd8 31. Qd3 Rbb6 32. Qd2 Rb8 33. Qd3 Rbb6 34. Qc3 Rb8 35. Rd1 Qb6 36. Rc1 Qd8 37. Rb1 Qb6 38. Rg1 Qd8 39. Qd3 Rbb6 40. Qc3 Rb8 41. Re1 Qf6 42. Kg1 Qd6 43. Rc1 Qe7 44. Qd3 Rbb6 45. e4 $5 (45. h3 $1 $16) 45... dxe4 (45... Ra8 $1 {[%cal Ga8e8] followed by ...Re8 was better. This was Black's type of reaction in the previous game.}) 46. fxe4 (46. Qxe4 Qxe4 (46... Qf6 47. Rh5 $18) 47. fxe4 $14 {[%cal Gg1e3,Gh2h3]}) 46... Ra8 (46... h3 $1) 47. e5 (47. h3 $1 Re8 48. e5 $16) 47... h3 $1 {Finally. Suddenly, the play is not one-sided at all.} 48. Qg3 Re8 49. gxh3 f6 50. e6 Bxe6 51. Nxc6 $2 Qd7 52. Nxa5 Bxh3 53. Rc7 Qd4+ 54. Qf2 Qg4+ {The same symptom as in the previous example. Black plays for a draw in a won position.} (54... Re3 $1 $19) 55. Qg3 Qd4+ 56. Qf2 Qg4+ {These twin games prove that such a minor weakness as that on e3 is likely to prevent White from achieving more than an optical or practical advantage. They also show that the bishop could become a dangerous attacking piece if White pushes too hard. We should also notice the big rating difference in White's favor. Despite that, he failed to achieve an advantage and got into trouble in both games.} 1/2-1/2


