1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 e6 3. e4 d5 4. cxd5 {It seems inevitable that this line will become more and more popular now that the mainline} (4. e5 d4 {seems OK for Black - see my previous updates.}) 4... exd5 5. e5 Ne4 6. d4 {This is also becoming more popular, White retains the option of putting his king's knight on e2.} (6. Nf3 {is the mainline, see Ding-Wang and others in the Archive.}) 6... Bb4 7. Qa4+ Nc6 8. Bb5 Bd7 (8... O-O {will transpose to the next note after} 9. Nge2 Bd7 10. O-O) 9. Nge2 {"This is the main point of waiting to develop the knight. Here it protects c3 and d4 and leaves the f-pawn free to annoy the knight on e4." - Alex Fier.} Nxc3 {Something of a speciality of the German player who is the only one to play this recently.} (9... O-O {is normal,} 10. O-O Bxc3 11. bxc3 {but White is better here,} a6 12. Bxc6 Bxc6 13. Qc2 Bb5 (13... f6 {was analysed by Alex in Ding, L-Wei, Y, see the PGN Archive.}) 14. Re1 $5 (14. a4 {is the most common,} Bc4 15. f3 Ng5 16. Rf2 {planning Ng3 and f4 with straightforward attacking play, Stridde, P-Laube, R DDR 1984, 1-0  (31), and others.}) 14... c5 15. f3 {new,} (15. Nf4 $6 cxd4 16. cxd4 Rc8 {loses White's advantage, Janicki, P-Kiviaho, R corr 1980, 0-1 (32).}) 15... cxd4 (15... Ng5 16. dxc5) 16. Nxd4 Nc5 17. Ba3 b6 18. Qd2 Re8 19. Bxc5 $1 bxc5 20. Nf5 Re6 {Svidler, P (2739)-Hou, Y (2673) Caleta 2015, 1/2-1/2 (53),} 21. f4 {with some advantage, the knight can go to d6 followed by pawn f5.}) (9... a6 10. Bxc6 Bxc3+ 11. bxc3 Bxc6 12. Qc2 {is similar,} Bb5 13. f3 (13. O-O O-O {transposes above.}) 13... Bxe2 (13... Ng5 14. O-O O-O 15. a4 Bc4 {transposes directly to 14 a4 above.}) 14. Kxe2 Ng5 15. Be3 c5 {Nock, J-Walkenhorst, A Germany 1991, 1-0 (33),} 16. Rhb1 b5 17. a4 {and Black is in trouble and will lose a pawn.}) 10. bxc3 Be7 {This way Black retains his dark-squared bishop rather than his knight on e4.} 11. Nf4 (11. O-O a6 12. Bxc6 Bxc6 13. Qc2 Bb5 14. a4 (14. Re1 Bxe2 15. Qxe2 O-O 16. a4 Qd7 17. a5 {Pacovsky, J (2335)-Kucera, P (2375) Czechia 2001, 1/2-1/2 (36).}) 14... Bc4 {Mann, W-Trautmann, K DDR 1981, 1-0 (65),} 15. f4 {-f5.}) 11... O-O (11... a6 {is the alternative, but} 12. Nxd5 (12. Be2 Nxe5 13. Qb3 Ng6 14. Qxb7 c6 15. Nxg6 hxg6 16. Bf4 O-O 17. O-O {White has more space and control of the b-file, Markus, R (2619)-Kraemer, M (2520) Austria 2012, 1/2-1/2 (42).}) 12... O-O (12... axb5 $2 13. Qxa8) 13. Be2 (13. Nxe7+ $6 Qxe7 14. Bxc6 Bxc6 15. Qa3 {1/2-1/2 Hort, V (2600)-Unzicker, W Siegen 1970.}) 13... Nxe5 {transposes to the main game.}) (11... Bg5 $5 {Lehtinen, H (2368)-Nyback, T (2587) Mantta 2008, 0-1 (39), should be met by} 12. O-O Bxf4 13. Bxf4 O-O 14. Rfe1 {with two bishops and a plus.}) 12. Nxd5 (12. O-O a6 13. Be2 Nxe5 14. Qb3 Nc4 (14... Ng6 15. Qxb7 c6 16. Nxg6 hxg6 17. Bf4 {transposes to the Markus game, above.}) 15. Nxd5 b5 16. Nxe7+ Qxe7 {Manea, A (2389) -Kraemer, M (2544) Legnica 2013, 1/2-1/2 (24),} 17. Bd3 {intending Qc2 with the pair of bishops and a small plus.}) 12... a6 13. Be2 $1 Nxe5 {This tactic regains the pawn.} 14. Qc2 Ng6 15. Nxe7+ Qxe7 16. O-O {The upshot of the previous play is that White has the bishop pair and and extra central pawn, but Black is very solid.} Bc6 {Black could also try to exploit the loose e2-bishop by either} (16... Ba4) ({or} 16... Bf5 {but White would simply move his queen in both cases, e.g.} 17. Qd2 Rfe8 18. Re1) 17. c4 Be4 18. Qd2 Rfe8 19. f3 Bf5 20. Re1 c6 21. a4 Rad8 22. Bb2 Qd6 ({Maybe Black should choose the endgame,} 22... Qe3+ 23. Qxe3 Rxe3 24. Bf1 Rb3 {although White will always be a bit better,} 25. Bc1 Nf8 26. a5 $1 {as the d-pawn is poisoned:} Rxd4 $2 27. Re8 {and Ba3.}) 23. Bf1 f6 {Black can only sit and wait, as he has no pawn breaks (...c5 is met by d5), and no obvious way of improving his pieces.} 24. Bc3 c5 $6 25. d5 Nf8 26. Qb2 Qc7 27. a5 {Now it's obvious that White has a clear advantage, b7 and c5 are weak and need defending.} Nd7 28. Qf2 {I imagine David was probably getting very short of time by now, as he often does.} (28. Rxe8+ Rxe8 29. Ra3 $1 Rb8 30. Rb3 {leaves Black very passive.}) 28... Ne5 29. Re3 Nf7 30. Rae1 Kf8 31. Qb2 (31. g4 {would be positionally correct, squeezing the remaining black bishop.}) 31... Rxe3 32. Rxe3 Re8 33. Bd2 Rxe3 34. Bxe3 Ne5 35. Qb3 h5 36. Bf2 $2 (36. Qa3 {defends the a-pawn.}) 36... Kf7 $2 {Black misses his chance.} (36... Qxa5 $1 37. Qxb7 Qa1 38. Bxc5+ Kg8 {threatens ...Bd3, so} 39. Kf2 Bd3 ({or} 39... Qa2+ 40. Kg1 Qa1) 40. Bxd3 Nxd3+ 41. Ke2 Nf4+ 42. Kd2 Qa2+ 43. Kc3 Ne2+ 44. Kd3 Nf4+ 45. Kc3 {and White would draw assuming he could find all these moves.}) 37. Be2 $6 (37. Qa3) 37... Kg6 $2 (37... Qxa5 38. Qxb7+ Kg6 {is still the best chance.}) 38. Qa3 $1 {Finally!} Nd7 39. Bg3 Ne5 40. Bf2 {White repeats to gain time.} Nd7 41. g4 $1 hxg4 42. fxg4 Be4 43. Bg3 Ne5 44. Qe3 Bb1 45. Qb3 Be4 46. Qe3 Bb1 47. Bxe5 $1 {The simplest.} (47. Qd2 {menaces to push the d-pawn,} Qd6 48. Qb2 Be4 49. Qxb7 {and wins.}) 47... fxe5 (47... Qxe5 48. Qxe5 fxe5 49. h4 {wins easily, the king comes to e3 and then White advances his kingside majority, e.g.} Kf6 50. Kf2 Bh7 51. Ke3 Ke7 52. g5 Bf5 53. h5 Bh7 54. g6 Bg8 55. Ke4 Kf6 56. Bd1) 48. Qb3 (48. Bd3+) 48... Be4 49. Bf3 (49. Bd3 Bxd3 50. Qxd3+ {appears to be simpler,} Kf7 51. Qf5+ Kg8 52. Qe6+ Kh7 53. d6) 49... Bxf3 50. Qxf3 Kh7 51. Qd3+ Kg8 52. d6 Qxa5 53. d7 {The pawn is too strong.} Qd8 54. Qf5 Qa5 55. Qxe5 1-0


