1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4 Bg7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Bd3 Na6 7. O-O c5 8. d5 Bg4 9. Kh1 Rb8 10. Bd2 $5 {Not an especially bad move, but one hardly likely to give Pirc players sleepless nights. White unpreteniously develops.} (10. Be3 $6 {This looks slightly awkward. I can only imagine that the strong Ukrainian player Anna Muzychuk was not particularly familiar with this opening.} Nd7 $5 {Cherapinov first plays to restrain, and only later to destroy.} 11. a3 Nc7 12. a4 a6 13. a5 b5 14. axb6 Rxb6 15. Na4 Rb7 16. c4 e6 $1 {The white center has an unwieldy look, while by contrast the black position is very compact and contained.} 17. h3 Bxf3 18. Qxf3 exd5 19. cxd5 Rb3 $1 20. Bc2 Rb8 21. Rad1 Nb5 $1 22. e5 dxe5 23. Nxc5 ({The normal "sweeper sealer" idea of} 23. f5 {does not make much sense here (for one thing white does not have a knight on e4.)} Nd4 $17) 23... Nd4 $1 24. Bxd4 exd4 25. Nxa6 Rxb2 {Black's game plays itself. He has complete control of the dark-squares, while the knight on a6 is in danger of being stranded.} 26. Ba4 Nb6 27. Bc6 Nc4 28. Nc5 Ne3 29. Rb1 Rxg2 30. Rfe1 Qa5 31. Rxe3 dxe3 32. Qxg2 Qxc5 33. Qe4 Qc3 34. Qf3 Qd2 35. Qd1 Bc3 {0-1 Muzychuk,A (2528)-Cheparinov,I (2664) Aix-les-Bains 2011}) 10... Qc8 $1 {Aronian shows that Black does not always have to make slow preparations to make progress on the queenside. Black now has a direct threat of ...c4, followed by ...b5 etc.} 11. e5 $5 {Both players had a different opinion of this advance in the press conference after the game. Aronian felt it was dubious, while Howell felt it was better for White. Probably it is somewhere in between.} dxe5 12. fxe5 Nd7 13. Bg5 Bxf3 14. gxf3 c4 15. Be2 f6 (15... Bxe5 16. Bxe7 Re8 17. d6 Qc6 {is also fairly unclear.}) 16. exf6 Nxf6 17. Bf4 Ra8 18. Be5 Rd8 19. Qd4 Nb4 20. Qxc4 Nfxd5 {The game is close to equal now and after a few adventures ended in a draw.} 21. Rad1 Qc6 22. Nxd5 Nxd5 23. Qe4 Nb6 24. Qxc6 bxc6 25. f4 Rxd1 26. Rxd1 Bxe5 27. fxe5 Rf8 28. Rd4 c5 29. Re4 Kg7 30. Kg1 g5 31. h4 h6 32. hxg5 hxg5 33. Kg2 Rd8 34. Bd3 c4 35. Bxc4 Rd2+ 36. Kf3 Rxc2 37. Bb3 Rxb2 38. Rd4 Kg6 39. Rd8 Kf5 40. Re8 Nd7 41. Rxe7 Nxe5+ 42. Kg3 Rd2 43. Rxa7 Rd3+ 44. Kg2 Rc3 45. Ra5 g4 46. Bd1 Kf4 47. Ra4+ Kf5 48. Ra5 Rc4 49. Kg3 Rc3+ 50. Kg2 Re3 51. Kf2 Rh3 52. Bxg4+ Kxg4 53. Rxe5 Rh2+ 54. Ke3 Rxa2 1/2-1/2


