1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Bf4 c6 4. e3 Qb6 $5 ({Posing an immediate question and hoping to dissuade White from going long. Previously, we've only really considered} 4... Bf5 {when} 5. f3 e6 6. g4 Bg6 7. h4 h5 8. g5 Ng8 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 {reaching a tabiya of sorts where White should have an edge - see Juegel-Harff, Belgian League 2016, in the Archive.}) 5. Rb1 ({Wadsworth was no doubt satisfied with Black's solid structure after} 5. Qd2 $5 Qxb2 6. Rb1 Qa3 7. Bd3 {, but I dare say that, speculative or not, Jobava might still have sacrificed the pawn here.}) 5... Bf5 6. f3 ({Three rounds later Mark Hebden deviated with} 6. Bd3 Bxd3 7. cxd3 {, which makes good sense, just as in our main game. Hebden-Wadsworth continued} e6 8. Nf3 Nbd7 9. O-O Be7 10. h3 O-O 11. b4 Rfc8 12. Qb3 (12. Na4 {looks more to the point}) ({or even} 12. e4 $5) 12... a5 $1 13. a3 axb4 14. axb4 Qa6 15. b5 Qa3 {, with sufficient counterplay for Black.}) 6... e6 7. g4 {Thematic Jobava-Prie expansion.} Bg6 8. h4 h6 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. cxd3 $5 ({Once again, a tempting recapture, bolstering White's central presence, not least in the event of any ...c5 dxc5 exchange. That said,} 10. Qxd3 {can hardly be terrible and after} Qa6 {(Sharikov-Rodchenkov, Moscow 2020)} 11. Nge2 Qxd3 12. cxd3 {followed by Kd2, and maybe even Rbg1, White is surely slightly for choice.}) 10... Nbd7 ({Black would have done better to go} 10... c5 $1 {without delay and following} 11. dxc5 Bxc5 12. d4 Be7 13. Nge2 Nc6 {there would have been everything to play for in this Exchange Slav-type situation.}) 11. Nge2 c5 $6 ({The thematic break, but Black would probably have done better to have sat tight with} 11... a5 {and ...Be7.}) 12. dxc5 Bxc5 13. d4 Bd6 14. Kf2 $1 {A safe spot for the king and a move which sums up why White is better. His king is quite safe, whereas its counterpart doesn't really want to commit to either flank and so come under a direct attack. Note how the knight on d7 contributes little to Black's position.} g6 (14... Rc8 15. Qd3 O-O $5 {is preferred by the engines, but} 16. Bxd6 Qxd6 17. Ng3 {would scare many a human here.}) 15. Qd3 Rd8 16. Na4 $1 {Howell continues to take control of the position.} Qc7 17. Rbc1 Qb8 18. Nc5 ({A good case might also be made for a preliminary} 18. b4 $5 {ahead of invading on c5.}) 18... Nxc5 19. Rxc5 (19. dxc5 $5 Bxf4 20. exf4 $5 {would pretty much force} d4 {, but even here} 21. b4 {looks fairly good for White, with such fine pawns and control of both flanks.}) 19... Nd7 20. Rc2 h5 $1 {Thus far Wadsworth has been rather outplayed, but this was still a good move, asking a big question of White over the kingside.} 21. g5 $6 ({This may not be too terrible, but why seal up the kingside and allow Black to safely castle? I dare say that Howell was soon wondering why he hadn't preferred} 21. gxh5 $1 Rxh5 22. Bg5 {, keeping the kingside open and continuing to leave Black under pressure with Nf4 on its way.}) 21... O-O 22. Rhc1 $6 ({Now Black is definitely OK, whereas} 22. Bxd6 Qxd6 23. Qc3 {might yet have retained an edge.}) 22... e5 $1 {Breaking out.} 23. dxe5 Nxe5 24. Qd4 $5 ({Risky. Black should not be worse after} 24. Bxe5 Bxe5 25. Kg2 Bg7 {, but this would have been a much safer path for White.}) 24... Nc6 25. Qf6 $2 (25. Bxd6 Qxd6 26. Qf4 $1 {was required to maintain the balance.}) 25... d4 $1 {This fine pawn sacrifice must have come as a cold shower to Howell. Suddenly White is in serious trouble.} 26. exd4 Bxf4 ({Hardly terrible, but} 26... Nb4 $1 {would just have been very strong, and if} 27. Rc3 Nd5 28. Bxd6 Rxd6 {when White is losing the exchange and will see his queen and king continue to be targeted.}) 27. Qxf4 Qxf4 28. Nxf4 Rxd4 29. Rc4 (29. Ng2 $5 Nb4 30. Rc7 {, and if} Nd3+ 31. Ke3 {, might have been a better defensive try.}) 29... Rd2+ 30. Kg3 Rxb2 {Bagging a clear pawn.} 31. Nd5 $1 {Improving the knight and going for counterplay against the black king is White's best hope of rescuing the game.} Rd8 32. Nf6+ Kg7 33. Re4 $2 ({Ambitious and surely too ambitious, especially when converting Black's extra pawn after} 33. R1c2 {wouldn't have been such an easy task, with} Rxc2 34. Rxc2 Rd1 35. Re2 Ra1 $4 36. Re8 {a graphic example of what to avoid.}) 33... Rxa2 34. Rb1 Nd4 $1 ({Wadsworth continues to rise to the challenge.} 34... b6 $2 35. Rc1 Na5 36. Rc7 {would have given White enough counterplay.}) 35. Rxb7 $5 {Easy to criticise, but probably not such a bad practical try.} Nf5+ 36. Kf4 Nd6 {Forking the white rooks.} 37. Rc7 Nxe4 38. fxe4 Rf2+ ({The calm} 38... Ra3 $5 {is preferred by the engines, hoping for} 39. e5 $2 Rd4+ {.}) 39. Kg3 Rxf6 $6 ({A pretty human choice, but it transpires that the rook ending isn't so easy to win. As such,} 39... Ra2 40. Kf4 {was objectively stronger followed by transposing back into our previous note or going} a5 41. Nd7 Ra1 {.}) 40. gxf6+ Kxf6 41. Rxa7 Rd3+ (41... Rd1 {would arguably have been slightly more accurate, but it quickly becomes clear that Wadsworth has missed a trick.}) 42. Kf4 Rh3 $2 ({By now} 42... Rd4 $1 {was required and would have maintained good winning chances for Black.}) 43. e5+ Ke6 44. Ra6+ Ke7 45. Ra7+ Kf8 46. e6 $1 {Ouch. This powerful pawn sacrifice gives White enough counterplay to dash Black's aspirations of the full point.} fxe6 (46... Rxh4+ 47. Ke5 fxe6 48. Kf6 $1 {is similar, White being set to save the game with relative ease after} Rf4+ 49. Kxg6 h4 50. Kg5 {.}) 47. Kg5 e5 48. Kxg6 Rxh4 49. Kf6 {As so often in rook endgames, the difference in activity between the two kings makes all the difference.} Rf4+ 50. Kxe5 Rf7 51. Rxf7+ Kxf7 52. Kf5 1/2-1/2


