1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 5. Ngf3 c5 6. c3 Nc6 7. Bd3 Be7 8. O-O g5 9. dxc5 g4 ({Nakamura has experimented with} 9... Nxc5 $5 {which also seems perfectly sound as well.} 10. Bb5 Nd7 $1 ({or} 10... h6 11. Qe2 Qc7 12. c4 Bd7 13. cxd5 exd5 14. Nb3 Ne6 15. Rd1 a6 16. Bxc6 bxc6 {Howell,D (2597)-Nakamura,H (2715) London 2009, with a balanced position.}) 11. Re1 Qc7 12. Nb3 h6 13. Qe2 a6 14. Bxc6 bxc6 15. c4 a5 $1 16. cxd5 cxd5 17. a4 Ba6 $1 18. Qd1 Bc4 {Karjakin,S (2760)-Nakamura,H (2741) Moscow 2010, and Black was better.}) 10. Nd4 Ncxe5 11. Bb5 (11. Bc2 {is certainly also playable. White should play for f4 of course.} Nxc5 12. f4 gxf3 13. N2xf3 Ng6 14. Qe2 f5 15. Bh6 $6 {Bruzon Batista,L (2696)-Holt,C (2556) Arlington 2014} ({However} 15. c4 $1 $36 {seems more to the point here. White should open the centre and put pressure on Black's shaky pawns.})) 11... a6 12. Bxd7+ ({When I was faced with this position myself, I came up with the tentative} 12. Ba4 $6 {here. My opponent was whipping out his moves at a furious rate and looking ultra-confident, and it unsettled me. The problem was also that I couldn't really recall the theory here, and I went into a brain freeze.} Bxc5 13. f4 Nc4 $1 14. Qxg4 (14. Nxc4 dxc4 15. Qxg4 (15. b4 Ba7 16. f5 e5 17. Qxg4 b5 18. Bc2 Nf6 19. Qe2 Bxd4+ 20. cxd4 Qxd4+ 21. Be3 Qg4) (15. Be3 b5 16. Bc2 Nf6 17. Qe2 Bb7 {I think I saw this position and I didn't like it. It looks like a good Semi-Slav for Black, he intends to castle long and counter-attack White on the other wing. Still it was better than what happened in the game.} (17... Qc7) 18. f5 $2 (18. Rad1 Qc7) 18... e5 19. Bf4 Bxd4+ 20. cxd4 Qxd4+ 21. Kh1 O-O-O 22. Bxe5 Rhe8 $1) 15... b5 16. f5 e5) 14... b5 15. Bb3 $2 Ne3 16. Qg7 Rf8 17. Re1 Nf5 $1 18. Qxh7 Qf6 $17 {Gormally,D (2497)-Fodor,T (2495) Birmingham 2015, with a horrible position for White and I didn't last much longer. Basically it was one disaster of a game, but it demonstrates very well the counter-attacking potential of Black in this line - you need to play very vigorously as White otherwise you can get run over.}) 12... Bxd7 13. b4 $1 h5 14. Qe2 Qc7 15. f4 Nc6 (15... gxf3 16. N2xf3 Nc4 (16... Ng4 17. h3 e5 18. hxg4 exd4 19. Nxd4 Bxg4 20. Qf2 {is also unpleasant for Black}) 17. Ng5 $1 $40) 16. a4 Bf6 (16... Nxd4 $1 17. cxd4 f5 $1 18. Nb3 Kf7 19. Bb2 h4 {and Black is absolutely fine. It's also important to note that} 20. b5 $6 {doesn't really work here because of} axb5 21. axb5 Rxa1 22. Rxa1 Qxf4) 17. N2b3 O-O 18. Kh1 Ne7 19. Be3 Rfe8 20. Qd2 Bg7 21. Qf2 Ng6 22. Nc1 f5 23. Nd3 Rf8 24. Ne2 {White has manoeuvred pretty well and is now threatening to impose a bind with d4, so Black goes for a freeing advance in the centre, but this hardly improves his prospects either.} e5 25. Nxe5 Nxe5 26. fxe5 Bxe5 27. Bf4 $16 Rae8 28. Qh4 Rf7 29. Qxh5 Rh7 30. Qg5+ Rg7 31. Qh4 g3 32. h3 Qc6 33. Bxe5 Rxe5 34. Nxg3 d4 35. Rf3 dxc3 36. Qc4+ Qe6 37. Qxe6+ Bxe6 38. Nh5 Bd5 39. Nf6+ Kf7 40. Nxd5 Rxd5 41. Rxc3 Rd2 42. Rg1 Rb2 43. c6 bxc6 44. Rxc6 Rg6 45. Rc5 f4 46. Rc4 Rf2 47. Rc7+ Kf6 48. Rc6+ Kg5 49. Rxg6+ Kxg6 50. Rb1 1-0


