1. e4 {Martin,A Martin,A} c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Nc3 {An old move-order trick which may confuse the Najdorf or Dragon specialist.} Nf6 ({Some moves are simply bad now:} 3... g6 $2 4. d4 cxd4 5. Qxd4 $1 Nf6 6. e5 Nc6 7. Bb5 dxe5 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Bxc6 bxc6 10. Nxe5 $16) (3... a6 $6 4. g3 $1) 4. d4 ({Keres liked} 4. e5 dxe5 5. Nxe5) 4... cxd4 5. Nxd4 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 Nc6 8. Qd2 O-O {The parting of the ways, where White can choose from 9.0-0-0, 9.c4 or 9.g4, all of which require Black to respond accurately.} 9. O-O-O d5 10. exd5 Nxd5 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Bd4 Nxc3 $5 {From the games below one would think that this is a drawing weapon. Is the Dragon really reduced to such methods?} 13. Qxc3 Bh6+ (13... Bxd4 14. Rxd4 Qb6 {is another way, but in all these lines, one gets the impression that Black has slightly the worse of things without any winning chances whatseoever.} 15. Bc4 c5 16. Rd2 Be6 17. Re1 Bxc4 18. Qxc4 Rab8 19. c3 Qc7 20. f4 Rfd8 21. Red1 Rxd2 22. Rxd2 e5 23. g3 Re8 24. Re2 Kg7 25. Qd5 f6 26. fxe5 Rxe5 27. Rxe5 fxe5 28. Qe6 c4 29. Kc2 Qc5 30. Qd7+ Kh6 31. Qd2+ Kh5 32. Qe2+ Kg5 33. b3 cxb3+ 34. axb3 a5 35. Qf3 Kh6 36. h4 Kg7 37. Qb7+ Kf6 38. Qf3+ Ke6 39. Qg4+ Ke7 40. b4 Qf2+ 41. Kb3 Qf7+ 42. c4 axb4 43. Kxb4 Qf5 44. Qd1 Qe4 45. Qg1 Ke6 46. Qf2 h5 47. Kc3 Qc6 48. Qf8 Qd7 49. Qg8+ Kf5 50. Qd5 Qa7 51. Qf3+ Ke6 52. Qd5+ Kf6 53. Qf3+ Ke7 54. Kb3 Qb6+ 55. Kc2 Qd4 56. Qb7+ Kf6 57. Qf3+ Kg7 58. Qd3 Qf2+ 59. Kc3 Qe1+ 60. Kc2 Qf2+ 61. Kc3 Qa7 62. Qd6 Qa1+ 63. Kc2 Qa2+ 64. Kc3 Qa1+ 65. Kc2 Qa2+ 66. Kc3 {½-½ Mencinger,V (2399)-Shengelia,D (2511)/Pula 2011}) 14. Be3 Bxe3+ 15. Qxe3 Qb6 16. Qxe7 $1 {The only really critical move and now Black must justify the pawn sacrifice.} Be6 17. Qa3 $1 (17. Bd3 Bc4 18. b4 Bd5 19. Rd2 {½-½ Saric,I (2637)-Cvitan,O (2498)/Stari Mikanovci 2011}) (17. Qf6 Rfd8 18. Bd3 Bxa2 19. Rhe1 Bd5 20. h4 c5 21. Qc3 Qb4 22. Qxb4 cxb4 23. Ba6 Be6 24. b3 Kf8 25. Kb2 Rxd1 26. Rxd1 Ke7 27. Rd4 Rb8 28. Bd3 Rb6 {½-½ Antipov,M (2379)-Kargin,A (2400)/Budapest 2011/CB15_2011}) 17... Rad8 18. Bd3 Rd5 {Black has activity and a slight lead in development to compensate him for the pawn.} 19. Rhe1 (19. b3 {shuts off the white queen unnecessarily:} Rfd8 20. Rde1 Rd4 21. Re5 R8d5 22. Rxd5 Rxd5 23. Re1 Qf2 $1 $132 {A queen sortie which often crops up in this line.} 24. Re2 Qg1+ 25. Kd2 Qd4 26. g3 Rc5 27. b4 Rb5 28. Re4 Qf2+ 29. Re2 Qd4 30. Re4 Qf2+ 31. Re2 {½-½ Alekseev,E (2688)-Lintchevski,D (2539)/Olginka 2011}) 19... Rfd8 $6 {Although played by Sedlak in the game below, I think this is a mistaken and over-optimistic move. Black must regain the pawn and hope that his disadvantage isn't too great:} (19... Ra5 $1 20. Qc3 Rxa2 21. b3 Ra5 {Is this position so bad for Black?}) 20. Qc3 c5 (20... Rd4 21. Re5 R4d5 22. h4 (22. Rxd5 Rxd5 23. b3 $16) 22... Rxe5 23. Qxe5 Rd5 24. Qf4 Rd4 25. Qf6 $16 Rd5 26. Qf4 ({I really do not understand the repetition as} 26. g4 Qe3+ 27. Kb1 c5 28. b3 {is clearly better for White.}) 26... Rd4 27. Qf6 Rd5 28. Qf4 {½-½ Friedel,J (2531)-Sedlak,N (2580)/Amsterdam 2011. Maybe a result which was mutually convenient for both players, but it certainly gives a misleading view of the position.}) 21. Re5 (21. Be2 $1) 21... Rxe5 (21... c4 22. Rxd5 Bxd5 23. Bxc4 Bxc4 24. Rxd8+ Qxd8 25. Qxc4 Qg5+ 26. Kd1 Qxg2 27. Qf4 $16) 22. Qxe5 Bxa2 23. b3 {Forcing a sacrifice} Bxb3 24. cxb3 Qxb3 25. Bc2 Qa3+ 26. Kb1 Qb4+ 27. Qb2 Rxd1+ 28. Bxd1 Qe1 {Can Black hold this position? It seems unlikely.  Although it will take White quite some time to organise his game and protect his king from checks, an eventual mop-up of the black queenside is inevitable.} 29. Kc2 Qf2+ 30. Kc1 Qe3+ 31. Qd2 Qe5 (31... Qa3+ 32. Kb1 $18) 32. f4 Qa1+ 33. Kc2 Qa4+ 34. Kb2 Qe4 35. Bf3 Qf5 36. Qd8+ Kg7 37. Qd6 {Centralization increases the advantage.} Qc8 ({Let's check the winning method after the exchange of queens:} 37... Qf6+ 38. Qxf6+ Kxf6 39. Kc3 Kf5 40. g3 h5 41. Kc4 h4 42. Kxc5 hxg3 43. hxg3 g5 44. fxg5 Kxg5 45. Kb5 f5 46. Ka6 f4 47. g4 Kh4 48. Kxa7 Kg3 49. Bd1 $18) 38. Kc3 h6 39. Bd5 Qg4 40. Qc7 Qf5 41. Qe5+ Qf6 42. h4 g5 43. Qxf6+ Kxf6 44. fxg5+ hxg5 45. hxg5+ Kxg5 46. Kc4 f5 47. Kxc5 {Nice technique from David Howell towards the end.} 1-0


