1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. g3 Bb4 5. Nd5 Bc5 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O d6 8. d3 h6 ({The other main move for Black is to immediately go for exchanges with} 8... Nxd5 9. cxd5 Nd4 10. Nxd4 exd4 11. Bd2 a5 12. e4 dxe3 13. fxe3 Qg5 14. Rf4 Bd7 15. a4 Rae8 16. d4 Bb6 17. Qb3 {Carlsen,M (2865)-Adams,M (2738) Baden-Baden 2015, with a slight advantage for White due to the long-term potential of the central pawns.}) 9. e3 Bb6 {Black voluntarily gives up the bishop pair; in return he gets an open file and retains a fairly solid position.} ({Holding on to the bishop pair with} 9... a6 {is generally considered more popular. It's certainly more combative.} 10. b3 (10. a3 Ba7 11. b4 Nxd5 12. cxd5 Ne7 13. Nd2 (13. e4 f5 $1 ({or just} 13... c6 {like in the game;} 14. d4 $6 cxd5 15. dxe5 dxe4 16. exd6 Nf5 $1) 14. Nd2 c6 $15) 13... c6 $1 14. dxc6 Nxc6 15. Rb1 Be6 {Inarkiev,E (2691)-Leko,P (2730) Loo 2014, and Black was more than fine. He can follow up with ...d7 with visions of playing ...h3, or simply play ...d5.}) 10... Ba7 {Black retreats the bishop, in anticipation of his plan of taking on d5 and playing ...e7.} ({the immediate} 10... Nxd5 11. cxd5 Ne7 {can now be met by} 12. d4 $1 {crucially gaining a tempo on the bishop, and after} exd4 13. Nxd4 Bd7 14. Bb2 c6 15. dxc6 bxc6 16. Qc2 {White has a nagging edge}) 11. Bb2 Nxd5 12. cxd5 Ne7 13. Nd2 f5 $1 14. Rc1 f4 15. exf4 exf4 16. Rc4 {Anand,V (2786)-Gelfand,B (2755) Moscow 2013, with double-edged play.} fxg3 17. hxg3 Rf5 $1 {would be one neat way to follow up Black's previous play.}) 10. Nxb6 (10. Nd2 {is another reasonable alternative.} Nxd5 11. cxd5 Ne7 12. Nc4 c6 13. dxc6 Nxc6 14. Nxb6 Qxb6 15. b3 Bf5 16. Bb2 Rac8 17. Qd2 Nb4 $1 18. Bc3 $1 a5 19. e4 Bd7 20. Rfd1 {Eljanov,P (2702)-Sutovsky,E (2660) Poikovsky 2013, with a balanced position.}) 10... axb6 11. b3 Bd7 (11... Be6 {looks more natural to me, although in the game Yilmaz still intends to carry out the plan which is so natural for Black in these situations, trying to exchange light-squared bishops with an eventual ...h3..} 12. Bb2 Qd7 13. d4 (13. Re1 {might well have been preferred by David, who tends to like to keep the tension in positions for as long as possible} Bh3 14. Bh1 $13) (13. Nd2 $5 {making way for the f-pawn} Bh3 14. f4 Bxg2 15. Kxg2 {is another interesting try for White. Black has to be careful of a quick fxe5 followed by sacrificing an exchange on f6.} {But now the radical} d5 $1 {seems to solve all Black's problems;} 16. fxe5 Ng4 17. Qf3 $1 Ncxe5 18. Bxe5 Nxe5 19. Qxd5 Qxd5+ 20. cxd5 Nxd3 {with an unclear ending.}) 13... exd4 $1 (13... e4 $5 14. d5 $1 ({but not} 14. Nd2 {because of} d5 $1 15. cxd5 Bxd5 {when Black should be fine}) 14... exf3 15. dxe6 Qxe6 16. Bxf3 $14) 14. Nxd4 (14. exd4 d5 {is more than ok for Black, as the potential of the bishop on b2 has become limited}) 14... Bh3 15. Nxc6 Bxg2 $1 16. Ne5 (16. Kxg2 Qxc6+ 17. Qf3 $11) 16... dxe5 17. Qxd7 Nxd7 18. Kxg2 f6 $15) 12. Bb2 Re8 $6 {Slightly sloppy.} ({There was no reason not to just get on with the normal plan with} 12... Qc8 $1 13. d4 $1 exd4 ({holding firm with} 13... Re8 $1 {might be best;} 14. d5 (14. dxe5 dxe5 {also looks fine for Black, who now has an alternative plan of ...f5 and ...d8}) 14... Ne7 15. Re1 Bh3 16. Nd2 (16. Bh1 $1 {retaining those two bishops! But this is not so clear as the bishop on h3 is difficult to expel for White; if it remains there its presence creates a constant back rank problem for the white king}) 16... Bxg2 17. Kxg2 {when White has a plan of e4, followed by slow expansion with f4, however Black should be fine here; one possible way to play is} Nd7 18. e4 Nc5 {when counterplay with ..f5! is firmly on the menu.}) 14. Nxd4 Bh3 15. Nxc6 $1 {and now} Bxg2 $4 {no longer works because of} (15... bxc6 16. Bxf6 $14) 16. Ne7+) 13. h3 $1 {Now Black is not able to carry out this plan of ...c8, followed by ...h3, so White will retain his two bishops.} Ne7 14. a4 c5 15. Ne1 Qc8 (15... Bc6 16. e4 $1 Ng6) 16. Kh2 Nh7 $1 17. Nc2 Ng5 18. f4 $5 {The consequences of this pawn sacrifice are not exactly clear, but David is not the sort of player to shy away from complications.} (18. h4 Nh7 19. e4 f5 $1 {gives Black useful counterplay. The knight on h7 will go back to ...f6 where it targets g4.}) 18... Nxh3 {Now the Black knight is stranded so Black has to act dynamically. For the tiime being Yilmaz is up to the challenge.} 19. e4 Bg4 20. Qd2 f6 21. Rae1 h5 22. Ne3 Qd7 23. Bf3 {The most combative.} ({Alternatively White could have immediately forced matters with} 23. Nxg4 hxg4 24. Bxh3 gxh3 25. f5 $1 Nc6 26. Kxh3 {but now Black should be able to maintain the balance with} Kf7 $1 {intending to transfer the king to the queenside ...e7, ...d8, ...c7 etc.}) 23... Bxf3 24. Rxf3 h4 25. Ng2 Ng6 (25... Qg4 {does not solve all of Black's problems either;} 26. Ref1 $1 {now it's hard to see how Black will meet the threat of gxh4.} (26. Nxh4 $2 g5 27. fxg5 Nxg5 $1 (27... fxg5 28. Qd1 $1) 28. Rxf6 Qh3+)) 26. f5 Ng5 27. Rfe3 hxg3+ 28. Rxg3 Ne7 29. Qe2 Kf7 {It seems now as if Black is over the worst, but David is not willing to give up the initiative so easily.} 30. Rxg5 $1 {An excellent sacrifice. Even if Black is able to defend after this, it's very hard to find all the right moves over the board.} fxg5 31. Qh5+ Kf8 32. Bc1 Ng8 33. Bxg5 Qf7 $2 {After this Black is hardly able to defend, as his king is stuck on the kingside where it is just going to come under a heavy attack.} ({Better chances of resistance were offered by} 33... Nf6 $1 {where Black can hope to still flee with his king to the queenside.} 34. Bxf6 gxf6 35. Ne3 $1 Qf7 (35... Ke7 $2 36. Nd5+ Kd8 37. Nxf6 {is just a winning ending for White}) 36. Qh4 {and now the simplest route for Black is} Ke7 37. Nd5+ Qxd5 $1 38. cxd5 Rh8 {when he should be holding the ending.}) 34. Qh8 $1 Reb8 35. Ne3 b5 {Desperation, but Black was completely devoid of counterplay in any case.} (35... Ke8 36. Rg1 $1 Kd7 {[%mdl 64] doesn't help either ; White has the killing} 37. Bd8 $3 {perhaps not the only winning move, but certainly a nice one!} (37. Qh7 $2 Ne7 38. Bxe7 Rh8) ({although} 37. Bh4 Nh6 38. Qxg7 {also looks very good for White, it is probably not immediately decisive}) 37... Rxd8 (37... g5 38. Rxg5 {changes little}) 38. Rxg7 Ne7 39. Qxd8+ $18) 36. cxb5 $18 Qxb3 37. Nd5 (37. Rg1 {was also strong.} Qxd3 (37... Qf7 38. f6 $1 g6 39. Ng4) 38. Be7+ {with a mating attack.}) 37... Kf7 38. Qh5+ Kf8 39. Qh8 Kf7 40. Qh5+ Kf8 41. f6 $1 Qc2+ 42. Re2 g6 43. Qg4 Qd1 44. f7 Nf6 (44... Kxf7 45. Qd7+ Kf8 46. Rf2+) 45. Bxf6 Qf1 46. Rg2 1-0


