1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. g3 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Bg2 Nb6 7. O-O Be7 8. a3 O-O 9. b4 Be6 10. d3 (10. Rb1 {defending b3, see the PGN Archive for many examples of this.}) 10... a5 (10... f6 {is solid, but allows White to play} 11. Bb2 {and then the more active Rc1 - see the Archive.}) (10... Nd4 $5 {is also played immediately (see Socko-Mamedyarov for example), but maybe White can risk} 11. Nxe5 $5 {here, too} Bf6 12. f4 Nb3 13. Be3 {as in the main game,} Nxa1 14. Qxa1 {with some compensation, Mogilny, E-Espindola, C ICCF corr 1994, 0-1 (29), and others.}) 11. b5 Nd4 12. Nxe5 (12. Nd2 {is the most common, controlling b3 and preparing to drive away the knight with e3, see Nimzo-Fritz in the Archive.}) 12... Bf6 (12... Nb3 $6 {is inaccurate:} 13. Rb1 Nxc1 (13... Qd4 14. Rxb3 Qxe5 (14... Bxb3 15. Qxb3 Qxe5 16. Bxb7 a4 17. Qc2 {Kozak, P (1800)-Mashinskaya, I (2300) Karvina 2002, 1/2-1/2 (21).}) 15. Bxb7 {with two pawns already,} Rab8 16. Be4 a4 17. d4 Bxb3 18. dxe5 Bxd1 19. Rxd1 {White is a bit better.}) 14. Qxc1 Qd6 15. Nc4 Nxc4 16. dxc4 Bxc4 17. Bxb7 Rad8 18. a4 {with an extra pawn, Seeger, N-Oswald, T ICCF email 2007, 1/2-1/2 (60).}) (12... Bb3 $6 13. Qd2 Bf6 14. f4 Bxe5 15. fxe5 Re8 {Anton Gomez, B-Bailen Canales, F UECC email 1998, 0-1 (30),} 16. e3 Nc2 17. Rb1 a4 18. Bxb7 (18. d4) 18... Rb8 19. Be4 Rxe5 20. d4) 13. f4 (13. Nc4 $6 Nxc4 14. dxc4 Bxc4 15. Rb1 Qe8 $1 16. Be3 (16. Qa4 Nxe2+ 17. Nxe2 Bxe2 18. Bxb7 Bxf1 19. Kxf1 Rd8 20. Be3 Qe7 $17) 16... Rd8 17. Bxd4 Rxd4 18. Qc2 b6 $15) 13... Nb3 (13... Bxe5 14. fxe5 Nb3 15. Be3 {Tony Kosten: 'transposes below.'} Nxa1 16. Qxa1 Nd5 $13) 14. Be3 (14. Bb2 $6 Nxa1 15. Qxa1 {Tony Kosten: 'is also playable,'} Bxe5 16. fxe5 Nd5 $15 (16... Rb8 17. Ne4 {with compensation, Savchenko, B (2580) -Nakhapetiane, P (2504) Sochi 2012, 1/2-1/2 (35), but the dark squared bishop is less effective here with a white pawn on e5.})) 14... Nxa1 (14... Bxe5 15. fxe5 Nxa1 16. Qxa1 Nd5 17. Bc5 (17. Bf2 Qd7 18. a4 Rac8 (18... Rab8 19. Qb2 $13) 19. Qb2 $11) 17... Re8 18. a4 Qd7 $11 19. Bf2 {the position is unclear, White can push his centre or manoeuvre his knight to e4, but Black is solid and has an extra exchange, Steinbrueck, W  (2397)-Blauhut, H (2497) ICCF email 2007, 1/2-1/2 (43).}) 15. Qxa1 Nd5 (15... Bxe5 16. fxe5 Nd5 17. Bf2 Qd7 (17... a4 18. Ne4 b6 19. Qb2) 18. a4 $13) 16. Bd4 (16. Bc5 {Tony Kosten: 'had been preferred,'} Re8 $13 (16... Bxe5 17. fxe5 Re8 18. a4 Qd7 $13) 17. Ne4 Bxe5 18. fxe5 b6 {Hierreich, G  (1971)-Zelcic, R (2555) Malinska 2013, 0-1 (29).}) 16... Bxe5 $146 (16... Rc8 17. Ne4 $44 {Tony Kosten: 'forces'} Bxe5 {Garriga Nualart, J (2398)-Auzins, M (2424) ICCF email 2009, 1-0 (43), and again} 18. Bxe5 {looks good.} f6 19. Bd4 b6 20. Nf2 $5 {and e4.}) (16... a4 17. Ne4 Bxe5 18. Bxe5 (18. fxe5 b6 {Garriga Nualart, J (2398) -Dobrica, D (2340) ICCF email 2009, 1-0 (36).}) 18... f6 19. Bd4 Re8 20. f5 $1 (20. Nc5 Bf7 21. Nxb7 Qc8 22. Nc5 {is met by} Rxe2 {Prado, J (2221)-Corujedo Hernandez, R (2279) ICCF email 2008, 1/2-1/2 (31).}) 20... Bf7 21. g4 Ra5 22. g5 $1 Rxb5 23. gxf6 {and I wouldn't fancy having to defend this position as Black OTB, Schuster, P (2459) -Jaworski, M (2445) ICCF email 2008, 1/2-1/2 (39).}) (16... Re8 17. Ne4 Bxe5 {Garriga Nualart, J (2398)-Penkin, V (2113) ICCF email 2009, 1/2-1/2 (54), and now} 18. Bxe5 {seems best.}) (16... Nxc3 17. Qxc3 Bd5 18. e4 Be6 19. Bc5 (19. f5 Bc8 20. Bc5 Re8 21. d4 {is also promising, Sadler, C  (1916)-Stark, K (1685) IECC email 2009, 1-0 (31).}) 19... Re8 20. a4 {White will play d4-5, so} Bxe5 21. fxe5 Qd7 22. d4 Bh3 23. d5 Bxg2 24. Kxg2 {with adequate compensation, Cristancho, F (2079)-Germanes, R (1980) FICGS email 2010, 0-1 (73).}) 17. Bxe5 f6 (17... Nb6 $6 18. f5 $1 (18. Ne4 f6 19. Bd4 Bd5 $11) 18... f6 19. fxe6 fxe5 20. Rxf8+ Qxf8 21. Bxb7 Qc5+ 22. Kg2 Re8 23. Qa2 a4 24. Bc6 $14) 18. Nxd5 (18. Bd4 Qd7 $11) 18... Bxd5 19. Bxc7 Qxc7 (19... Qd7 20. Qd4 {forces} Qxc7 21. Bxd5+ {similar to the game.}) 20. Bxd5+ Kh8 21. Kg2 Qd7 22. Qa2 (22. Bf3 $5 Rac8 $11 (22... Rfc8 $11)) (22. Bc4 {is simpler, but} f5 {hinders e4.}) 22... Qxb5 23. Rb1 Qc5 24. a4 $5 (24. Rxb7 Rab8 25. Rxb8 Rxb8 26. Be4 a4 27. Qe6 Qe3 $11) 24... Rab8 (24... Qe3 25. Rxb7 Rab8 26. Rb5 Rfd8 $11) 25. Rxb7 {Tony Kosten: 'would transpose to the game.'} (25. Rb5 {Tony Kosten: 'would have kept a pair of rooks on the board,'} Qc3 26. Qc4 (26. Be4 {with fair compensation.}) 26... Qe1 (26... Qxc4 27. dxc4 b6 $11) 27. Qc2 Rfe8 28. Bf3 Rbc8 29. Qb2 Rc1 30. Kh3 Qf1+ 31. Kg4 Rc7 $11) 25... Qd4 (25... Rxb7 26. Bxb7 Re8 27. e4 Re7 $11) 26. Rxb8 Rxb8 27. Bc6 (27. Bf3 Qd7 $11) 27... Qe3 28. Bf3 Qd4 (28... Qe8 $5 29. Be4 Rb4 $11) 29. Bc6 Qe3 30. Bf3 {Tony Kosten: 'White still has two pawns for the exchange, but they aren't going anywhere and Black is active. Still, White has a simple plan of attacking on the kingside and Black fails to defend against this.'} Qd4 31. h4 {Tony Kosten: '!'} Qb4 (31... h6 32. Qc2 Qd7 33. Qc4 Rd8 $11) 32. Qc2 Qb3 $6 33. Qc7 Qb6 34. Qf7 Qd4 {Tony Kosten: '?' Tony Kosten: 'The queen is not able to defend the light squares here. This error might be down to time trouble, certainly David was probably very short of time by now, as is his custom!'} (34... Rd8 $142 35. h5 h6 $1 36. Qe7 (36. Qg6 Qe6 37. Be4 Kg8 38. Kf3 (38. Qh7+ Kf8 {is nothing - the black queen guards g8.}) 38... Kf8 $11) 36... Rc8 ({but} 36... Kg8 37. Bd5+ Kh7 (37... Rxd5 $2 38. Qe8+ Kh7 39. Qe4+) 38. Be4+ Kg8 {and it's not clear how White makes progress.}) 37. Kh3 $14) 35. h5 $1 $18 {[ h6] Tony Kosten: 'Now the threat of h6 is unpleasant.'} Qd6 (35... h6 36. Qg6 Qe3 {Tony Kosten: '(to stop Be4)'} (36... Qb2 37. Kh3 Rf8 38. Qf5 $1 Qc2 39. Qxa5 $18) 37. Qf5 $1 {Tony Kosten: 'and the a5-pawn is lost.'} Qd2 38. Kf2 Qb4 39. Be4 Kg8 40. Qh7+ Kf7 41. Bg6+ Ke6 42. Qxg7 Qb6+ 43. d4 $1 Qxd4+ 44. Kg2 Rb2 45. Kh3 Rxe2 46. Bf5+ $1 Kxf5 47. Qg4+ Ke4 48. Qxe2+ $18) (35... Qd8 36. h6 gxh6 37. Be4 Qg8 38. Qxf6+ Qg7 39. Qf5 Rf8 40. Qxa5 Rxf4 41. Qc5 Rf7 42. a5 $18) 36. h6 $1 Qf8 {Tony Kosten: 'Forced.'} (36... gxh6 {Tony Kosten: '??'} 37. Be4 $18) 37. Qa7 {Tony Kosten: '!'} gxh6 38. Qxa5 {Tony Kosten: 'Now it will be very difficult to both stop the a-pawn and defend the black kingside.'} Qg7 (38... Qd6 39. Qa7 Rg8 40. Be4 Rg7 41. Qa8+ Rg8 42. Qb7 Rg7 43. Qc8+ Rg8 44. Qf5 Rg7 45. a5 Ra7 46. Bb7 $1 $18) 39. Qf5 (39. Qc5 $142 $1 $18 {Tony Kosten: '!'}) 39... Rg8 (39... Qg6 40. Qc5 Rg8 41. Qf2 Qf5 42. Qd4 Qg6 43. g4 $1 $18) 40. g4 $1 h5 {Tony Kosten: 'Desperation.'} 41. Qxh5 Qd7 42. a5 f5 43. a6 fxg4 {Tony Kosten: '?'} (43... Rg6 44. a7 $1 Qxa7 45. Qxf5 $18) 44. Qe5+ Rg7 (44... Qg7 45. Bd5) 45. Bd5 {Tony Kosten: 'The immediate threat is Qb8+ and mate.'} 1-0


