{[%evp 0,87,14,-51,-14,-14,48,26,32,46,11,41,41,41,73,-9,-12,-18,9,5,-3,-8,14,16,52,49,72,52,93,60,60,73,104,95,100,88,127,98,116,119,111,103,127,151,133,129,110,132,119,108,156,156,170,166,202,202,199,200,199,200,195,197,197,197,197,195,200,200,200,206,204,207,208,205,208,201,207,223,237,212,212,194,230,241,264,273,310,320,29999,-30000]} 1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 g6 3. e4 e5 4. Nf3 Nc6 {We have transposed to our main line by a different move order, as if Black had played 4...g6.} 5. d4 $1 {In this position too this is the most principled move, but the game tends to transpose to King's Indian positions.} exd4 6. Nxd4 Bg7 7. Nc2 $5 {A quiet, but practical approach.} (7. Be3 {is also possible}) (7. Nxc6 {seems the most principled continuation} dxc6 (7... bxc6 $6 8. e5 Qe7 9. Qe2 Ng8 10. Bf4 $14 {is easier to play for White}) 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Bf4 {in the words of Adhiban, this is "the fabled Berlin Endgame with minor modifications but the presence of the white pawn on c4 makes it quite comfortable for Black". In fact, in two high level games White was not able to prove an advantage, despite his lead in development} Be6 10. Be5 $5 (10. O-O-O+ $6 {is imprecise, after} Nd7 $1 {½-½ Nepomniachtchi,I (2751)-Adhiban,B (2677) FIDE World Cup 2017 (2.2) Black had no problems getting a nice position -}) 10... Re8 11. f4 (11. Be2 $5 {should be more precise, but} Bh8 $1 {[%cal Yf6d7] seems ok for Black}) 11... Bd7 {I think Black has an interesting idea in mind} 12. Bxf6+ $6 {not a good decision} (12. O-O-O Rxe5 $1 {this is the point of Black's play} 13. fxe5 Ng4 {[%cal Yg4f2,Yg4e5] with interesting compensation by the exchange}) (12. Be2 $142 Rxe5 $5 13. fxe5 Ne8 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Yg7e5] even in this position the sacrifice seems interesting, as the bishop will be very nicely placed on e5}) 12... Bxf6 13. e5 Bg7 14. O-O-O Bh6 15. g3 Rxe5 $17 {½-½ Anton Guijarro,D (2667)-Sevian,S (2666) Capablanca Memorial Elite 54th 2019 (2) and White was already struggling for the draw in}) 7... O-O 8. Be2 Re8 9. f3 d6 10. O-O {Now, we've a position played in hundreds of games in the King's Indian.} Ne5 {This allows White to get a comfortable advantage.} (10... Nh5 $5 {is very concrete line} 11. g4 (11. Be3 Be5 12. Nd5 $5 {1-0 Bacrot,E (2722)-Guseinov,G (2621) Gashimov Memorial-B 1st 2014 (3) transposes to another sharp line of the King's Indian -}) (11. f4 Bxc3 $1 12. bxc3 Nf6 {[%csl Ye4] looks fine for Black despite the dark-squares}) {now, Black has} 11... Be5 $1 {and many games have finished in quick draws after} 12. gxh5 Bxh2+ $1 13. Kxh2 Qh4+ 14. Kg1 Qg3+ 15. Kh1 Re5 16. f4 Qh3+ $11) 11. Be3 ({White also got a good position after} 11. Ne3 c6 12. Kh1 {[%cal Gf3f4]} h5 13. Bd2 Qe7 14. Be1 {[%cal Ye1h4]} Nh7 15. f4 Nd7 16. Bxh5 $1 gxh5 17. Nf5 $36 {[%cal Gf5d6];1-0 Vitiugov,N (2482)-Krutko,A (2358) RUS-ch U18 Nojabrsk 2005 (2)}) 11... c6 12. Qe1 $1 Qe7 (12... d5 $2 13. Rd1 $18 {[%csl Rd5]}) 13. Rd1 a6 {[%cal Yb7b5] Black aims to contest White's space advantage with b7-b5, but this is not enough to solve his problems.} 14. Qd2 Be6 15. b3 b5 $5 (15... Rad8 $2 {would be a big mistake} 16. f4 Neg4 17. Bb6 $1 Rd7 18. h3 Nh6 19. Bf3 $18 {Black's position is so terrible that even with equal material the engine evaluates as +2 for White!}) 16. cxb5 axb5 (16... cxb5 $5 17. Nb4 $1 $16 {[%csl Yd5,Gd6]} ({the trap is if} 17. Qxd6 $2 Qxd6 18. Rxd6 Rec8 19. Bd2 Bf8 {[%csl Rd6] there is no good square for this rook})) 17. Qxd6 {White is a good pawn up.} Qxd6 18. Rxd6 Bf8 19. Rd2 b4 20. Na4 Nc4 $5 {What else? d4 was the threat.} 21. Bxc4 Bxc4 22. Rc1 Bb5 23. Nd4 $1 Bxa4 24. bxa4 Nxe4 $2 {Desperation.} (24... Rxa4 25. Nxc6 Rea8 26. Rcc2 $16 {was the best objective try for Black}) 25. fxe4 Rxe4 26. Kf2 $18 {This is already winning for White.} Rxa4 (26... c5 27. Nf3 c4 28. Ng5 $18) 27. Rxc6 Rxe3 28. Kxe3 Bh6+ 29. Kd3 Bxd2 30. Kxd2 Rxa2+ 31. Rc2 Rxc2+ 32. Nxc2 b3 33. Nd4 b2 34. Kc2 Kg7 35. Kxb2 Kf6 36. Kc3 Ke5 37. Kd3 f5 38. Nf3+ Kf4 39. Ke2 g5 40. Kf2 Kg4 41. Ke3 Kh5 42. Ne5 Kh4 43. Kf3 h5 44. Ng6# 1-0


