1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. O-O Qd6 6. Na3 b5 7. d4 $6 {The ensuing endgames are pleasant for Black.} exd4 8. Nxd4 (8. e5 $2 Qd5 $15) (8. Qxd4 Qxd4 {Black can of course enter the endgame with no fear; Smejkal who was a wizard of the d6 Exchange with Black scored a nice victory in it.} (8... Ne7 {Black can just develop as well.} 9. c3 Ng6 10. Nc2 Bb7 11. Qxd6 cxd6 {This queenless position is harmless for Black because of the two bishop he has.} 12. Nfd4 O-O-O 13. Nf5 d5 14. exd5 Rxd5 15. Nce3 Rd8 16. Rd1 {White plays quite well and obtains equality.} Rxd1+ 17. Nxd1 Ne5 18. Bf4 Nd3 19. Bd6 g6 20. Bxf8 Rxf8 21. Nd6+ Kc7 22. Nxb7 {Skorchenko-Pokazanjev, 61st ch-RUS HL 2008. White has managed to put his problems behind him and has equalised.}) 9. Nxd4 c5 10. Ne2 Bb7 11. f3 c4 12. c3 (12. Rd1 Bc5+ 13. Kf1 Ne7 14. Bf4 f5 $1 $132) 12... O-O-O 13. Be3 Ne7 14. Rad1 Rxd1 15. Rxd1 f5 16. exf5 (16. e5 Nc6 17. Bd4 Bxa3 18. bxa3 g5 $11) 16... Nxf5 17. Bf2 Bd6 18. Nd4 (18. Ng3 Rf8 $11 (18... Rd8 19. Kf1 (19. Nxf5 Bxh2+ 20. Kxh2 Rxd1 $17))) 18... Nxd4 19. Bxd4 Re8 $15 {White went on to lose fairly soon in the Pribyl-Smejkal, Havirov 1970 game, but he still should be able to hold.}) 8... c5 $1 9. Nf5 (9. Ne2 Qxd1 {The game to which I turn your attention is somewhat risky.} (9... Bb7 {Let me give you a more conventional way to play as well:} 10. f3 O-O-O 11. Qe1 Nh6 12. Qf2 Be7 13. c3 $6 (13. Bf4 Qe6 14. Ng3 b4 15. Nb1 g5 16. Be3 f5 $13) 13... f5 14. Bf4 Qc6 (14... Qg6 $5) 15. Ng3 (15. exf5 Nxf5 16. Ng3 $11) 15... g5 $1 {Now Black cleverly takes over.} 16. Be5 f4 17. Bxh8 fxg3 18. Qxg3 Rxh8 {Lewandowski-Liwak, Koszalin 1997. Black is clearly better.}) 10. Rxd1 c4 11. Bf4 {The bishop leaves the c1-square; Black may have a spectacular tactical move.} Bb7 12. Bxc7 c3 $3 {I like this surprising tactical shot.} (12... Bxe4 13. Rd4 Nf6 14. Re1 Bxa3 15. bxa3 O-O $11) 13. Bd6 (13. b4 Bxb4 14. Bd6 Bxd6 15. Rxd6 Ne7 16. Nxc3 Rc8 $44) 13... cxb2 14. Rab1 Ne7 15. c4 O-O-O $4 {This is a blunder in a playable position.} (15... Rd8 16. Rxb2 Nc8 17. e5 Nxd6 18. Rbd2 b4 19. Nc2 Be4 20. exd6 Bxc2 21. Rxc2 Bxd6 $11) 16. cxb5 Rxd6 17. Rxd6 Ng6 18. bxa6 $2 {White returns the favour.} (18. Rd3 $1 Bxe4 19. Rc3+ {wins.}) 18... Bxe4 $14 {Kountz-Galdunts, Walldorf 2006.}) 9... Qxd1 10. Rxd1 Bxf5 {Black doesn't even have the half a pawn disadvantage as White also has doubled pawns. Actually White's f5-pawn is a bit vulnerable.} 11. exf5 Bd6 12. c4 O-O-O 13. Kf1 b4 (13... c6 $5 {I would prefer to keep the tension on the queenside.} 14. Nc2 Nf6) 14. Nc2 Ne7 15. Ne3 Be5 (15... h5 $5) 16. Rxd8+ Rxd8 17. Ke2 h5 $6 {This is an unfortunate insertion; on the other hand it is really hard to see what its disadvantage is.} (17... Nc6 $5 18. Nc2 (18. Rb1 b3 $36) 18... Nd4+ 19. Nxd4 Rxd4 20. Be3 Rxc4 21. Kd3 Rh4 $17) 18. h3 Nc6 19. Nc2 Na5 (19... Nd4+ 20. Nxd4 Rxd4 21. Be3 Rxc4 22. Kd3 Bxb2 23. Kxc4 Bxa1 24. Bxc5) 20. Ne3 Bd4 (20... b3 $5) 21. Rb1 {The young English player defends his position well and in the end he gets his reward, the half point.} Bxe3 22. Bxe3 Nxc4 23. Bxc5 Rd2+ 24. Kf3 a5 25. Bf8 g6 26. fxg6 fxg6 27. Bg7 Kd7 28. b3 Nd6 29. Rb2 Rxb2 30. Bxb2 c5 31. Kf4 Ke6 32. g4 c4 33. bxc4 Nxc4 34. Ba1 hxg4 35. hxg4 a4 36. Kg5 Kf7 37. f4 Ne3 38. f5 gxf5 39. gxf5 Nd5 40. Kg4 Nc3 41. a3 1/2-1/2


