{It was a pleasure to be one of the commentators at the recent British chess championships in Torquay. I was working alongside Adam Hunt, who was very professional and able to handle the technical side of the broadcast. As in some ways I am a classic chess player who is unable to tie my shoelaces, this was a great relief.  I stayed in a guest house in Babbacombe, which was just outside of the town center, up this rather steep hill. As it was probably just too far to walk I would generally get the bus. Unfortunately I managed to upset the owners a little bit because there was a note on the door which said "please remember to shut the door after you at night" so foolishly not being able to work out how to shut it for sure, I put the latch on. Which meant that the owners were woken up by other residents unable to get in to the hotel at two in the morning. The owner's wife immediately figured out who must be responsible.  Other participants in the British championships had even more painful experiences. One poor soul was hounded out of his accomodation by the air bnb owner from hell, who pounded on his wall in the middle of the night when he dared to go to the toilet.   Anyway that's enough preamble from me. The best game prize was awarded to David Howell, for his game against Lorin D'Costa.} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 b6 3. Nc3 e6 4. e4 Bb7 5. Qe2 {An ambitious line, which has been favoured by chess greats like Leonid Stein and Yi Wei, amongst others.} c5 {one of Black's main responses. Black gains control over the center, at the cost of losing time in development, as his knight is driven back.} (5... Bb4 {is a solid alternative.} 6. e5 Ng8 7. a3 $1 (7. g3 {is the older line, but} Nc6 $1 {seems like a good response.} 8. Bg2 Nd4 {and Black is forcing exchanges}) 7... Bxc3 8. dxc3 Ne7 9. Bg5 O-O 10. O-O-O Qe8 11. Qd2 Bc6 (11... h6 12. Be3 Nf5 {seems much more solid}) 12. h4 a5 $6 {this is terribly slow} 13. h5 $1 f5 $2 14. exf6 gxf6 15. Bxf6 $1 Rxf6 16. Qg5+ Rg6 17. hxg6 Nxg6 18. Bd3 Na6 19. Rxh7 {1-0 (19) Belikov,V (2508)-Smirnov,I (2438) Alushta 2001}) 6. e5 Ng8 (6... Ng4 {looks more agressive, although is more likely to hand White a fierce initiative.} 7. d4 cxd4 (7... Nc6 $5 8. d5 Nd4 {is an interesting alternative.}) 8. Nxd4 Nh6 $2 9. Bxh6 gxh6 10. h4 {And White had complete control and went on to win in Wei,Y (2728)-Abdusattorov,N (2546) Makati 2018}) 7. d4 cxd4 (7... Bxf3 8. Qxf3 Nc6 9. d5 Nxe5 10. Qg3 {and with a development advantage and the two bishops, White had obvious compensation for the pawn in Czebe,A (2480)-Petrik,T (2362) Slovakia 2003}) 8. Nxd4 Nc6 9. Nxc6 Bxc6 {[#]  In some ways this position reminds me of the Petrosian variation of the queens indian with a3. Although by comparison to that line Black is slightly lagging in development, White also has some issues with the queen on e2 blocking his kingside.} 10. h4 $5 {Far-sighted. Given that Black eventually wants to play Ne7-f5, then this move makes sense, as by pushing the pawn to f5 White deprives the knight of any support with a later ...h5. it's also the prelude to a pawn storm, as we shall see later.} Ne7 {The first new move of the game, and not a bad one by any means.} (10... f6 11. Rh3 $5 {a prophylatic move, designed against Black's plan of playing ..Bb4 and taking on c3.} (11. Bf4 {is preferred by the engine, although after} Bb4 12. O-O-O Bxc3 13. bxc3 Qe7 {the position seems very unclear.}) 11... fxe5 12. Qh5+ g6 13. Qxe5 Qf6 14. Qe2 Qf5 $6 15. g4 $1 Qf7 16. Bd2 Bg7 {and now} 17. Ne4 $1 {would have crowned White's excellent opening play} (17. Nd5 $6 {was the game continuation in Hakobyan,A (2497)-Oparin,G (2622) Batumi 2018})) 11. h5 Nf5 12. Bf4 Be7 {[#]} 13. Rh3 $1 {This is exactly the kind of deep-thinking that seems to separate players like David from lesser mortals like myself. It shows as well that he's really studied the line.} ({In the commentary room myself and my co-commentator Adam, were analysing a much more flat continuation like} 13. O-O-O Bg5 14. Qg4 {and we overlooked the idea of storming your pawns forward on the kingside completely.}) 13... Bg5 14. Bh2 $1 {continuing with this ambitious plan. White wants to play g4 and f4 and push Black's minor pieces back, after which he will completely dominate the board.} O-O 15. h6 {imaginative, but the machine feels this is unnecessary.} (15. g4 Nh6 16. f4 Bh4+ 17. Kd2 {and White is very much for preference. Once the king sits on c2, then it is totally safe.}) ({another good alternative in the same spirit was} 15. f4 Bh4+ 16. g3 Nd4 17. Qd3 Nf3+ 18. Kf2 Be7 19. Bg2 Nxh2 20. Rxh2 {where once again I would prefer White, as White will play Rd1, when it is not clear how Black solves the problem of the backward d-pawn.} Bxg2 21. h6 $1) 15... Nxh6 16. f4 Bh4+ 17. g3 Be7 18. O-O-O f5 $1 19. exf6 {[#]} Rxf6 $2 (19... Bxf6 20. g4 {and now the slightly counter-intuitive capture} Bxc3 $1 21. Rxc3 Qe8 $13 {would have lead to an unclear position- in fact the engine even slightly favours Black.} (21... Qh4 {which I suggested in the commentary room, is in fact a mistake because of} 22. g5 $1 Ng4 23. Rh3 Qf2 24. Qxg4 $18)) 20. g4 Rf7 21. Qc2 Qf8 22. Bd3 {[#]} Rxf4 $2 {this is premature.} (22... g6 $1 23. Qe2 {otherwise Black was threatening to take on g4} Rxf4 {was a much improved version of the same sacrifice.} 24. Bxf4 Qxf4+ 25. Kb1 Rf8 { and now unlike in the game, Black in many variations can take on g4, where he doesn't have to worry about his h7 pawn hanging.}) 23. Bxf4 Qxf4+ 24. Kb1 Qxg4 25. Re3 $2 (25. Bxh7+ Kh8 26. Qd3 {would have maintained some element of control.}) 25... Kh8 $2 (25... g6 $1 {was again better, pointed out by the machine of course, although to a human player this is not such an easy move to make as your natural reaction is to fear a later capture on g6.}) 26. Be4 $1 Rf8 27. Bxc6 dxc6 28. Re4 Qg6 29. Rde1 Rf6 30. Qa4 {[#]} Nf5 (30... Ng4 $1 31. Qxa7 Bc5 {was the most active way to play, but I think Lorin was already in desperate time trouble.}) 31. Qxa7 h5 32. a3 Bc5 33. Ka2 Bf2 34. Rd1 Kh7 35. Qa8 c5 36. Rd8 Qf7 37. Re2 Ng3 38. Ne4 $1 $40 Nxe4 (38... Nxe2 39. Ng5+) 39. Rh8+ Kg6 40. Qxe4+ Kg5 41. Qg2+ 1-0


