1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Qf3 {Interest in this particular Dangerous Weapon appears to be waning compared to a year or two ago, despite that brutal fairly recent encounter, Short-Grandelius.} e6 ({Black's main move inasmuch as there is one after 6 Qf3. That aforementioned victory by the English no.1 saw instead} 6... Nbd7 {and with} 7. Be2 g6 8. Be3 Bg7 9. h3 $1 Ne5 10. Qg3 b5 11. f4 {White had already sounded the charge - see the Archive for full notes.}) ({If Black wishes to fianchetto, he should probably prefer to do so without delay and, indeed, Howell had faced} 6... g6 {just a few weeks before our main game:} 7. h3 Bg7 8. Be3 Bd7 9. O-O-O Nc6 10. g4 ({the related} 10. Nxc6 $5 Bxc6 11. Nd5 Bxd5 12. exd5 O-O 13. Kb1 {with chances for an edge was suggested in 'Dangerous Weapons',}) ({while we considered the more direct} 10. Qe2 Rc8 11. f4 O-O 12. g4 {in Sowray-Simacek, European Championship, Dresden 2007}) 10... Rc8 $5 {(Black continues to try and do without castling)} 11. Nxc6 {(this exchange, sidestepping any ...Ne5-c4 hits, makes all the more sense now that Black cannot recapture with the b-pawn)} Rxc6 12. Nd5 $2 ({but I'm at a loss to explain this one} 12. g5 Nh5 13. Nd5 {was surely indicated?}) 12... Qa5 13. Bd4 Nxd5 $2 ({returning the favour, rather than grab a key pawn with} 13... Qxa2 {the point being that} 14. Nxf6+ (14. Kd2 {might be preferred, but the tactics again favour Black after} Nxd5 15. Bxg7 Qa5+ 16. c3 Rg8 {:} 17. exd5 Rxg7 18. dxc6 Bxc6 {wins back the rook down the long diagonal}) 14... exf6 15. Bxf6 Bh6+ $1 16. g5 Bxg5+ 17. Bxg5 Qa1+ 18. Kd2 Qa5+ {regains the piece with some advantage}) 14. exd5 Bxd4 15. Rxd4 Rc7 16. Kb1 {and now in D.Howell-Yilmaz, Puerto Madryn 2009, Black might have obtained a decent counterplay after} e5 $1 {.}) 7. Be2 ({White keeps his options open. The openly more aggressive} 7. Be3 {is a very important alternative, though, when I suspect I would have followed in Kasparov's footsteps with} Nbd7 (7... Be7 8. g4 Nc6 9. g5 Nd7 10. h4 {resembled a Keres Attack and was quite dangerous for Black in G.Jones-Eggleston, British Championship, Torquay 2009, as we've seen before}) 8. Be2 h5 $5 9. Bg5 Qa5 10. Bd2 Qb6 11. Nb3 Qc7 12. a4 b6 13. Bg5 Bb7 {, which gave Black an acceptable-enough set-up in Adams-Kasparov, Linares 2002.}) 7... Nbd7 $5 ({New in this particular position. Black preferred a common-enough Scheveningen ploy with} 7... Qb6 8. Nb3 Qc7 {in Loder-Sharma, Bad Wiessee 2009, and after} 9. O-O Nbd7 10. a4 b6 11. e5 $6 ({premature I suspect that future games may instead debate something like} 11. Qg3 $5 Bb7 12. f3 h5 $1) 11... Bb7 12. exd6 Bxd6 13. Qh3 O-O 14. Be3 Ne5 {Black was already a tad more than comfortable.}) 8. g4 $5 ({Whether such aggression fits in with White's 7th is perhaps debatable. Indeed, I wouldn't be too surprised if} 8. O-O {were to be tested should this position ever arise again, not that there is anything whatsoever wrong with David's choice.}) 8... Qb6 9. Nb3 Ne5 ({I wasn't too keen on} 9... h5 10. g5 Ng4 11. Qg2 {,}) ({but perhaps} 9... h6 $5 10. Be3 Qc7 11. O-O-O b5 {wouldn't have been so bad.}) 10. Qg3 $6 ({Better is} 10. Qg2 $1 {when} Qc7 (10... h6 $5) 11. g5 Nfd7 12. f4 Nc4 13. Bxc4 Qxc4 14. Be3 {leaves White quite well advanced on the kingside and probably slightly for choice.}) 10... Qc6 $1 {A non-standard but strong idea.} 11. Nd4 Qb6 12. Nb3 Qc6 13. Be3 $5 {Very brave. David played this after some thought and later admitted that White should probably accept the repetition. However, at this point the two of us were tied with Mark Hebden on 7.5/9 and one further round after this one remaining.} Nxe4 14. Nxe4 Qxe4 15. O-O-O {White has a lead in development, but his pieces aren't all that well coordinated, and I certainly had confidence in my Sicilian structure.} Qa4 16. f4 Nc6 17. f5 $1 e5 ({Definitely safest. I wasn't too keen on} 17... Qxa2 18. Rxd6 Be7 19. Rxc6 bxc6 20. Qc7 {with some initiative for the exchange, as shown by} Bd7 21. Rd1 Rd8 22. g5 $1 {when the threats are mounting.}) 18. Kb1 (18. a3 $5 {was probably a better way to curtail Black's activity on the queenside.}) 18... Bd7 19. c3 $6 h5 $1 {With the king safe enough in the centre, it makes sense to open the kingside and so get the king's rook straight into play down the h-file.} 20. Rhf1 $6 ({He should first have pinned:} 20. Qh3 {and only then gone} O-O-O 21. Rhf1 {.}) 20... hxg4 21. Bxg4 Rxh2 $1 {David must have underestimated this one Black obtains a strong initiative for the exchange.} 22. Qxh2 Qxg4 23. Qf2 a5 $1 {It was also possible to solidly castle, but I couldn't see a good reason not to pursue the initiative!} 24. Bb6 a4 25. Nc1 a3 26. b3 Rc8 27. Nd3 ({Black's pieces also coordinate pretty well in the event of} 27. f6 gxf6 28. Qxf6 Be6 {and ...Ne7-d5.}) 27... Ne7 $1 {The dark-squared bishop is fine where it stands.} 28. f6 gxf6 $6 ({By this point I had just under four minutes left and David something like two (with no increment), and unsurprisingly time trouble begins to influence the game. Here} 28... Nd5 {would have been strong when} 29. fxg7 ({or} 29. Ba5 Nxf6) 29... Nxc3+ 30. Ka1 Qxg7 31. Rde1 Qg6 {leaves White in some trouble.}) 29. c4 Bf5 30. Ka1 $1 {Relatively the safest square and now White can hope to cause some problems down the d-file.} Rc6 $2 ({I can't really explain this one! Correct was} 30... Bg6 {followed by regrouping with ...Qe6, etc.}) 31. Nb4 Rxb6 $5 ({Not particularly liking} 31... Rc8 32. Rxd6 {I decided to give up a second exchange.}) 32. Qxb6 Qe2 ({Now the queens come off, but Black is by no means out of the game yet. Possibly a superior alternative was} 32... Qh3 $5 33. Rc1 Bh6 {when I only saw} 34. Qxb7 {, but this isn't, of course, fatal and after} Bxc1 35. Rxc1 Qh2 36. Qa8+ Kd7 37. Qxa3 Qd2 {anything again might have happened!}) 33. Qf2 Qxf2 34. Rxf2 Be6 35. Nd5 ({No doubt David saw} 35. Rxf6 Nf5 {, but missed} 36. Rf1 {in reply when Black probably doesn't have enough for the two exchanges.}) 35... Bxd5 36. cxd5 f5 {The game did begin as a Sveshnikov, didn't it?} 37. Kb1 Bg7 38. Kc2 e4 39. b4 {At this point we were both down to about a minute. This Sveshnikov-like position is hardly clear, although White shouldn't lose if he gives back an exchange for f5. Now I was about to play ...Be5, but first decided to gain a tempo...} Bd4 $4 40. Rxd4 {Oops!} 1-0


