1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 b6 3. g3 Bb7 4. d4 g6 $5 {This system with the double fianchetto is a very modern way to play. Black players have also tried the double fianchetto when the pawn would be on e6. Here the pawn is on e7 so this cannot be bad.} 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. d5 {David immediately tries to blunt in the b7 bishop.} (6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O Ne4 {is the main idea behind this system. The exchange of the f6 and c3 knights is in Black's favour.}) 6... Na6 {This is the way chess openings are played these days. All minors developed and central pawns remain untouched!} 7. e4 {Highly ambitious approach by David.} ({In my game against Grandelius Nils where I reached the same position, the game continued:} 7. Bg2 Nc5 8. Nd4 e5 {and now instead of Nc2} 9. Nb3 $14 {gives White a pleasant edge.}) 7... Nc5 (7... d6 8. Bg2 Nc5 9. Nd4 {Let}) 8. e5 Ng4 9. Bh3 $6 (9. Bf4 $6 d6 {White's centre starts to crumble.} 10. exd6 cxd6 $11 {Black has a perfectly fine position.}) ({White's best option could have been} 9. b4 $5 Na6 10. Bf4 $1 Nxb4 $6 11. h3 $1 Nh6 12. Qd2 Nf5 13. g4 $18 {and the knight is trapped.}) 9... Nxe5 10. Nxe5 Bxe5 11. Bh6 {David has sacrificed a pawn and prevented Black from castling. He has no direct point to attack but the general activity and space advantage should be decent compensation.} d6 (11... Bxc3+ $6 12. bxc3 $44 {secures the c5 square for the knight but the two bishops + queen will create dangerous threats on the kingside.}) 12. O-O Bc8 13. Bg2 {Of course, it makes sense not to exchange pieces when you have sacrificed material and have a space advantage.} Bf5 14. Re1 (14. g4 $5 {In for a penny, in for a pound!} Bd3 15. Re1 Bxc4 16. Rc1 $1 {It's very difficult for humans to assess this position as clearly better for White. Even winning. White is two pawns down but has two extra rooks in play. This could be one way to be sure about your compensation!} Rg8 {is relatively the best.} (16... Nd3 $2 17. Qa4+ $18) (16... a5 {trying to prevent b4.} 17. Ne4 Nxe4 18. Rxe4 Ba6 19. Rxe5 $1 dxe5 20. d6 exd6 21. Bc6+ Ke7 22. Qf3 $18 {is simply a crushing attack.}) 17. f4 Bh8 18. b3 Ba6 19. Re3 $16 {now that d3 is controlled, b4 will come strongly.}) 14... Qd7 (14... Nd3 {asks White what exactly is his compensation.} 15. Re3 Nxb2 16. Qf1 $1 $44 {The knight on b2 cannot really go anywhere.} (16. Qe2 $2 Na4 $1 $17)) 15. Re3 Bh3 16. b4 Bxg2 17. Kxg2 Na6 18. Rb1 c5 19. dxc6 Qxc6+ 20. Kg1 $2 {Black gets the time to consolidate.} (20. Nd5 $1 {it was so important to keep up the tempo of the attack and not care about the material.} Nc7 (20... e6 21. b5 Qxc4 22. bxa6 Qxd5+ 23. Qxd5 exd5 24. f4 $18) 21. f4 $1 Bf6 {it seems as if Black has defended all his weaknesses but White has the killer shot with} 22. Bg7 $3 Bxg7 23. Rxe7+ Kf8 24. Rxc7 $18) 20... Nc7 (20... Qxc4 21. Qa4+ Kd8 22. Rc1 $18) 21. Qd3 Ne6 22. Nd5 Rc8 23. Rc1 g5 24. Ree1 $2 (24. Qf5 Rg8 25. Rf3 {was much better and would have given White a strong attack.}) 24... Rg8 $1 {Threatening Rg6 to trap the bishop.} 25. Qxh7 $4 {A huge oversight by David. Maybe he did not like that Black was able to create threats of his own and panicked.} ({The computer still feels White can fight with} 25. c5 $5 bxc5 26. bxc5 Nxc5 27. Qxh7 Rh8 28. Qxh8+ Bxh8 29. Nxe7 $13) 25... Rh8 $1 {A piece is lost and the rest is very simple.} 26. Qe4 Rxh6 27. Qg4 Qd7 28. Rcd1 Rh8 29. Rxe5 dxe5 30. Nxb6 f5 (30... Qxd1+ 31. Qxd1 axb6 $19) 31. Qf3 Qc6 32. Qxf5 axb6 33. Qg6+ Kf8 34. Qf5+ Kg8 35. Qg6+ Kf8 36. Qf5+ Kg7 37. Qxe5+ Kg8 38. c5 Rh6 39. a4 Qxa4 40. Ra1 Qxb4 {A very interesting game and Howell's pawn sacrifice in the opening was surely a good practical attempt as it gave him a winning position on many ocassions but he just couldn't finish Pert off who defended quite stubbornly.} 0-1


