{Krasenkow,Michal: 'Vigorito, D: 'Here two young Grunfeld experts face off...in a King's Indian!''} 1. Nf3 {Krasenkow,M Krasenkow,Michal Krasenkow,Michal Krasenkow,Michal Krasenkow,Michal: 'Vigorito, D: 'Already a surprise! Howell almost always plays 1.e4. Perhaps Howell hoped to catch Vachier in some Anti-Grunfeld line.''} Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. d4 O-O 6. h3 {Krasenkow,Michal: 'Vigorito, D: 'The Makagonov System. This line was one of three recommended my Jan Markos in his 2008 book. He refers to it as the Krasenkov variation, but I prefer not to rename lines that are already established. White plays in a flexible manner, leaving Black to guess White's plans.''} e5 ({This is the most accurate move if Black wants to play in a classical manner. Instead} 6... Na6 {(Krasenkow,Michal) is frequently seen, but after} 7. g3 $1 {Black will essentially be forced to enter a Fianchetto line that he may not have intended to play, for example:} e5 8. Bg2 exd4 9. Nxd4 Re8 10. O-O Nc5 11. Re1) ({An alternative is} 6... c5 {Krasenkow,Michal} 7. d5 e6 8. Bd3 exd5 {when 9.cxd5 is the Modern Classical line of the Benoni, but White can also play} 9. exd5 Re8+ 10. Be3 {which we looked at recently in Kramnik, V (2790)-Guseinov, G (2609)/Baku 2010.}) 7. d5 Nbd7 {Krasenkow,Michal: 'Vigorito, D: 'This is playable of course but it is not very flexible.''} (7... Nh5 {(Krasenkow,Michal) is an independent line, while more common are}) (7... Na6 {(Krasenkow,Michal) and my personal preference}) (7... a5 {Krasenkow,Michal} 8. Bg5 Na6 {refraining from ...h6. Some of these lines may transpose.}) 8. Bg5 h6 ({After} 8... Nc5 $2 {(Krasenkow,Michal) White has} 9. b4 {but Black could play 8...a5.}) 9. Be3 Nc5 10. Nd2 a5 11. g4 ({I prefer Krasenkow,Michal: 'I prefer Vigorito, D: 'Krasenkow: 'I prefer'''} 11. Be2 {Krasenkow,Michal: 'Vigorito, D: 'is the most common.'' here - see theoretical database in CBM 134. Krasenkow,Michal: 'here - see theoretical database in CBM 134. Vigorito, D: 'Krasenkow: 'here - see theoretical database in CBM 134.'''}) ({The immediate} 11. a3 $5 {(Krasenkow,Michal) may be the most challenging because Black cannot really prevent the b4 advance.} Ne8 ({Black acquiesces to being pushed back because White is not well developed instead} 11... a4 12. Bxc5 dxc5 13. Nxa4 {is probably not good enough for Black}) 12. b4 axb4 13. axb4 Rxa1 14. Qxa1 Nd7 ({or} 14... Na6 15. Qa3 f5 16. Nb3) 15. c5 f5 16. Nc4 f4 17. Bc1 dxc5 18. bxc5 Nxc5 19. Ba3 b6 20. Bxc5 bxc5 21. Qa5 f3 {with great complications in Krasenkow, M (2655)-Radjabov, T (2530)/GMA, Dos Hermanas 2001.}) 11... c6 (11... Bd7) (11... Ne8) (11... Nh7) 12. a3 ({Krasenkow,Michal: 'Vigorito, D: 'A rare move which seems to mix plans.''} 12. Be2 $1 {Krasenkow,Michal: 'Vigorito, D: 'would transpose to the main continuations.' Vigorito, D: 'would transpose to the main continuations. Krasenkow: '!''' leads to the 11.Be2 line. Krasenkow,Michal: 'leads to the 11.Be2 line. Vigorito, D: 'Krasenkow: 'leads to the 11.Be2 line.'''}) 12... a4 $1 {Krasenkow,Michal: 'Vigorito, D: '!?' '!?' Vigorito, D: 'Krasenkow: '!''' That's it! To accept this pawn sacrifice, White must trade his important dark-squared bishop, after which the weakness of the dark squares, created with the g2-g4 advance, will become visible. And if White doesn't take the pawn, his queenside will be paralysed. Krasenkow,Michal: 'That's it! To accept this pawn sacrifice, White must trade his important dark-squared bishop, after which the weakness of the dark squares, created with the g2-g4 advance, will become visible. And if White doesn't take the pawn, his queenside will be paralysed. Vigorito, D: 'Krasenkow: 'That's it! To accept this pawn sacrifice, White must trade his important dark-squared bishop, after which the weakness of the dark squares, created with the g2-g4 advance, will become visible. And if White doesn't take the pawn, his queenside will be paralysed.'''} ({Krasenkow,Michal: 'Vigorito, D: 'The only previous game from this position saw White emerge on top after''} 12... Bd7 $143 {Krasenkow,Michal: 'Vigorito, D: 'Krasenkow: ''''} 13. b4 axb4 (13... Na6 14. Qb3 axb4 15. axb4 c5 16. bxc5 Nxc5 {0-1 Liedl,W (2183)-Freitag,M (2387)/Vienna AUT 2010/The Week in Chess 820 (51)} 17. Rxa8 Qxa8 18. Bxc5 dxc5 19. Bg2 $14) 14. axb4 Rxa1 15. Qxa1 Na6 16. Qa3 Nc7 17. Be2 Qc8 18. Qb3 cxd5 19. cxd5 b5 20. f3 Kh7 21. O-O {Krasenkow,Michal: 'Vigorito, D: '!' '!' Vigorito, D: 'with some advantage in Cramling, P (2470)-Fernandez Aguado, J (2400)/Barcelona 1990.'' Krasenkow,Michal: 'Vigorito, D: '!' Vigorito, D: 'with some advantage in Cramling, P (2470)-Fernandez Aguado, J (2400)/Barcelona 1990.''} Nfe8 22. Rc1 Qd8 23. Nd1 $14 {1-0 Cramling,P (2470)-Fernandez Aguado,J (2400)/Barcelona 1990/EXT 1997 (55)}) 13. Be2 ({Krasenkow,Michal: 'Vigorito, D: 'Here giving up the dark-squared bishop with''} 13. Bxc5 dxc5 14. Nxa4 {Krasenkow,Michal: 'Vigorito, D: 'is possible, but with White having weakened his kingside Black will always have some compensation.''} b6 $5 {etc. was the principled course but the text move (with the idea h3-h4, g4-g5) is not so harmless either.}) 13... Bd7 14. h4 $1 {Krasenkow,Michal: 'Vigorito, D: 'Krasenkow: '!'''} (14. Bxc5 dxc5 15. Nxa4 cxd5 16. Nxc5 dxe4 17. Ndxe4 Nxe4 18. Nxe4 Bc6 $44) (14. Kf1 Nh7 15. Rg1 Kh8 16. Rg3 {1-0 Odendahl,R (2434)-Hendriks,W (2425)/Dieren 2008/CBM 125 Extra (44)} b6 $11) 14... cxd5 (14... Qa5 $6 {1/2 Kern,G (2352)-Kuempers,U (2108)/Dortmund 2007/EXT 2008 (54)} 15. Bxc5 $5 dxc5 16. g5 Ne8 17. Bg4 $36) 15. cxd5 Rc8 {This gives White attacking chances. Krasenkow,Michal: 'This gives White attacking chances. Vigorito, D: 'Krasenkow: 'This gives White attacking chances.'''} (15... Ne8 $142 {to prevent the opening of the files.}) 16. g5 hxg5 17. hxg5 {[%cal Yh1h8]} Nh7 18. Rg1 {Krasenkow,Michal: 'Vigorito, D: 'This is a typical double-edged position. White has a lot of space, but with it comes a lot of 'responsibility'. With so many pawn moves, White could easily end up overextended.''} f5 $6 {Krasenkow,Michal: 'Vigorito, D: 'Krasenkow: '?!''' A wrong decision, after which White will make use of the g-file, too. However, it was not so easy to find a plan of counterplay: Krasenkow,Michal: 'A wrong decision, after which White will make use of the g-file, too. However, it was not so easy to find a plan of counterplay: Vigorito, D: 'Krasenkow: 'A wrong decision, after which White will make use of the g-file, too. However, it was not so easy to find a plan of counterplay:'''} ({Krasenkow,Michal: 'Vigorito, D: 'If Black does nothing then White will just play Qc2 and castle long. Another way to fight for the initiative is with''} 18... b5 $6 {Krasenkow,Michal: 'Vigorito, D: '!?' '!?' Vigorito, D: 'Krasenkow: '?!'''} 19. Bxb5 (19. Nxb5 {Krasenkow,Michal} Qb6) 19... Bxb5 20. Nxb5 Nd3+ 21. Kf1 $14 {Krasenkow,Michal: 'Vigorito, D: 'Krasenkow: ''''} (21. Ke2 {Krasenkow,Michal} Qa5 $1 {with the idea ...Qa6}) 21... Qd7 $5 {(Krasenkow,Michal) (attacking the knight and h3)} (21... f5 $5 {Krasenkow,Michal}) 22. Na7 ({or} 22. Qxa4 Rb8 23. Nc3 Qh3+ 24. Ke2 Nf4+ {with good play}) 22... Rc7 23. Nc6 Qh3+ 24. Ke2 Nf4+ 25. Bxf4 exf4 26. Qxa4 {is probably better for White, although his position is not completely safe.}) (18... Re8 $5 {[%cal Yg7f8,Yf8e7]} 19. Bf1 $1 Qa5 (19... Bf8 20. Qf3 Be7 21. Qg3 $16 {[%csl Gg5]}) 20. Qf3 b5 {looks the most logical; however, after} 21. Rh1 {[%cal Yf1h3] the initiative belongs to White.}) 19. gxf6 (19. exf5 gxf5 $13) 19... Qxf6 20. Qc2 ({This allows a little trick, although it was probably not unexpected. Instead after} 20. Rg2 {(Krasenkow,Michal) Black probably would have gone for} b5 $5) 20... Bh6 {Krasenkow,Michal: 'Vigorito, D: 'Black uses this tactic to exchange his passive bishop.''} (20... b5 $5 21. O-O-O Rb8 22. Rg2 b4 23. axb4 Rxb4 24. Rdg1 $36) 21. O-O-O (21. Bxh6 $4 {Krasenkow,Michal} Qxf2+) 21... Bxe3 22. fxe3 Kg7 (22... b5 23. Rg2 Rb8 24. Rdg1 Kg7 25. Na2 $1 Rfc8 26. Kb1 $16) 23. Kb1 {Krasenkow,Michal: 'Vigorito, D: 'White's position is easier to play. he can double rooks on the g-file, and Black must also be wary of pressure on his a4- and d6-pawns.''} Be8 24. Bb5 $5 {Krasenkow,Michal: 'Vigorito, D: 'Exchanging off his own bad bishop while weakening the a4-pawn.' Vigorito, D: 'Exchanging off his own bad bishop while weakening the a4-pawn. Krasenkow: '!?'''} Bxb5 25. Nxb5 Ng5 ({Leading nowhere is} 25... Nb3 {Krasenkow,Michal} 26. Nc3) 26. Nc3 $6 {Krasenkow,Michal: 'Vigorito, D: '?' '?' Vigorito, D: 'Krasenkow: '?!''' Too passive. Krasenkow,Michal: 'Too passive. Vigorito, D: 'Krasenkow: 'Too passive.'''} (26. Rdf1 $142 {Krasenkow,Michal: 'Vigorito, D: 'also looks promising however. After' Vigorito, D: 'also looks promising however. After Krasenkow: ''''} Qe7 27. Qd1 $1 (27. Rxf8 Rxf8 (27... Kxf8 {Krasenkow,Michal} 28. Qd1 $1 {decisively threatens Qg4}) 28. Nxd6 {Krasenkow,Michal: 'Vigorito, D: '!' '!' Vigorito, D: 'works rather simply.'' Krasenkow,Michal: 'Vigorito, D: '!' Vigorito, D: 'works rather simply.''} Qxd6 29. Rxg5 Rf2 $132) 27... Rxf1 (27... Ncxe4 $2 28. Nxe4 Nxe4 29. Rxf8 Rxf8 (29... Qxf8 30. Qg4 Nd2+ 31. Ka1 $18) 30. Qc2 Ng5 (30... Qh4 31. Nxd6 $1 $18) 31. Qg2 Kh6 32. Qh2+ Kg7 33. Qh4 Rf5 34. e4 $18) (27... Nh3 28. Rg2 (28. Rg3 Qh4) 28... Qd7 29. Nc3 $16) 28. Qxf1 Rh8 29. Nxd6 Qxd6 30. Rxg5 Qf6 31. Rg1 $14) ({Howell had a big time advantage but he gave it all back here and makes a rather big mistake. White plays simply but allows Black to fight for the initiative. Instead} 26. Nxd6 {Krasenkow,Michal} Qxd6 27. Rxg5 {was interesting, as} Ne6 28. Nc4 $1 Rxc4 29. dxe6 Rxc2 30. Rxd6 Rff2 31. Rb6 {favours White. It was probably not so esy to assess this from a distance.}) 26... Nf3 $1 $132 {Krasenkow,Michal: 'Vigorito, D: '!' '!' Vigorito, D: 'Krasenkow: '!'''} 27. Rg2 Nxd2+ 28. Qxd2 Qf3 29. Rdg1 Rf6 30. Rg4 Rh8 {Krasenkow,Michal: 'Vigorito, D: '!' '!' Vigorito, D: 'Black has good counterplay. White comes quickly undone.'' Krasenkow,Michal: 'Vigorito, D: '!' Vigorito, D: 'Black has good counterplay. White comes quickly undone.''} 31. Ka2 $2 {Krasenkow,Michal: 'Vigorito, D: 'Krasenkow: '?'''} ({Krasenkow,Michal: 'Vigorito, D: 'Perhaps low on time White misses the best chance to fight:''} 31. Nxa4 $1 {Krasenkow,Michal: 'Vigorito, D: 'eliminating the black a-pawn is a great relief to the white king.'' was the only way for White to keep the balance: Krasenkow,Michal: 'was the only way for White to keep the balance: Vigorito, D: 'Krasenkow: 'was the only way for White to keep the balance:'''} Nxa4 32. Qa5 Rh1 (32... Nc5 33. Qc7+ Kf8 (33... Rf7 {Krasenkow,Michal} 34. Rxg6+) 34. Qd8+ Kf7 35. Qxh8 {Krasenkow,Michal: 'Vigorito, D: 'and now Black must find the draw with''} Qe2 $11 {[%cal Rf6f2,Rf6f1] Krasenkow,Michal: 'Vigorito, D: '!' '!' Vigorito, D: 'threatening a light-squared perpetual check with ...Rf1+' Vigorito, D: 'threatening a light-squared perpetual check with ...Rf1+ Krasenkow: '=''' Krasenkow,Michal: 'Vigorito, D: '!' Vigorito, D: 'threatening a light-squared perpetual check with ...Rf1+''}) 33. Qxa4 Rxg1+ 34. Rxg1 Qxe3 $11) 31... Rh1 $19 {Krasenkow,Michal: 'Vigorito, D: '!' '!' Vigorito, D: 'This relieves the pressure against g6. White is in trouble as the e-pawns are weak and his king is uncomfortable. The rest of the moves were made in mutual time pressure.' Vigorito, D: 'This relieves the pressure against g6. White is in trouble as the e-pawns are weak and his king is uncomfortable. The rest of the moves were made in mutual time pressure. Krasenkow: '-+''' Krasenkow,Michal: 'Vigorito, D: '!' Vigorito, D: 'This relieves the pressure against g6. White is in trouble as the e-pawns are weak and his king is uncomfortable. The rest of the moves were made in mutual time pressure.''} 32. Qc2 (32. Rxh1 Qxh1 {[%cal Rf6f1]} 33. Qg2 Qxg2 34. Rxg2 Rf3 $19) (32. Qe1 Qxg4 33. Rxh1 Nxe4 $19) 32... Rxg1 33. Rxg1 Qxe3 34. Qh2 Qf2 $1 {Krasenkow,Michal: 'Vigorito, D: 'Krasenkow: '!'''} 35. Qh1 b5 $5 {Krasenkow,Michal: 'Vig