1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. Bd3 Nc6 {Miezis' invariable solid approach. Of course, there are several more active ways for Black to play at this juncture, with two recent developments being:} ({a)} 5... Nf6 6. O-O e5 $5 {is a move a lot of ink has been split over of late. The critical test is} 7. Bg5 {,} ({but in typical fashion Kamsky ducked a theoretical debate, preferring a manoeuvring game after} 7. Nb3 {. I can't believe that this should really trouble Romanishin's idea, but after} Nc6 ({heading for a Najdorf-like set-up with} 7... d6 $5 {makes a lot of sense White's extra tempo shouldn't be too important here and in Tuncer-Pantsulaia, Turkish Team Championship 2010,} 8. Nc3 Be7 9. a4 O-O 10. Kh1 Nc6 11. f4 Nb4 $1 12. a5 Bd7 13. Na4 Bc6 {gave Black decent, thematic counterplay}) 8. Nc3 d6 9. Nd5 $5 ({an improvement over} 9. Bg5 Be7 10. Qd2 O-O 11. Rfd1 Be6 12. Be2 a5 $1 {when grabbing the pawn didn't work for White in Gharamian-Jobava, European Championship, Aix-les-Bains 2011, as we've noted before}) 9... Be7 ({White's development lead looks a little scary after} 9... Nxd5 10. exd5 Nb8 {, but whether he can do anything so brilliant with it isn't clear}) 10. c4 Be6 11. Be3 Nd7 12. Qd2 O-O ({trying to insist on the exchange of dark-squared bishops with} 12... h6 $5 {very much came into the equation too}) 13. Rad1 Nc5 14. Bb1 Rc8 15. Nc1 $1 {White was slightly for choice in a Kalashnikov-like position, Kamsky-Ramirez, US Championship, Saint Louis 2012.})) ({b) After} 5... g6 {quite a critical test is} 6. O-O Bg7 7. Nb3 $1 Ne7 8. c4 O-O 9. Nc3 {, as was seen in Li Chao-Grandelius, Malmo 2012, where} Nbc6 (9... d5 $2 {backfires horribly after} 10. cxd5 exd5 11. Bg5 $1 {- see Karjakin-Davies, Mainz (rapid) 2010, in the Archive}) 10. Be2 ({keeping control, but} 10. Bg5 $5 {also looks quite dangerous, as we've analysed before}) 10... f5 $1 ({an idea I've suggested on these pages instead} 10... d6 11. Bf4 $1 e5 12. Be3 Be6 13. Qd2 f5 14. f3 {gave White a pleasant advantage in So-Nouri, Tarakan 2008,}) ({and Black also suffered in Anand-Bologan, Kolkata 1992, after} 10... b6 11. Bg5 h6 12. Be3 f5 13. Qd2 Kh7 14. f3) 11. c5 (11. Bg5 fxe4 12. Nxe4 Bxb2 13. Rb1 Bg7 {'doesn't look like more than a reasonable pawn sacrifice, with Black preparing to untangle with ...Qc7, ...Nf5 and ...b6' was my earlier view - maybe this will soon receive a test?}) ({the stem game for 10...f5 was actually Sadikhov-Rasulov, Tabriz 2012, where} 11. f3 f4 12. Bd2 g5 $5 13. Be1 $1 b6 14. Bf2 h5 15. a4 {led to pretty double-edged play in which White caused an upset}) 11... fxe4 (11... b6 {was my idea the rising Swedish star prefers to play it a move later}) 12. Nxe4 b6 $1 13. Nd6 $5 {(again White feels the need to sacrifice a pawn)} bxc5 14. Be3 ({admittedly} 14. Nxc5 {regains the pawn, but fails to trouble Black after, say,} Nf5) 14... Bxb2 15. Rb1 Be5 16. Bxc5 Qc7 17. g3 Nd5 $1 {and while the position remained rather complex, I'm not convinced that White had quite enough compensation.}) 6. Nxc6 dxc6 7. O-O ({It's also possible to begin with} 7. Nd2 $5 {and after} e5 8. Nc4 Nf6 9. O-O Qc7 10. Bd2 $5 {Black struggled in Leko-Khalifman, Budapest 2000, as covered by the Fed.}) 7... e5 8. Nd2 {The knight prepares to eye Black's weakened dark squares from c4. White already enjoys a pleasant edge from what I can see.} b5 $2 ({Keeping the knight out of c4, but this only makes things worse. After} 8... Be6 9. Nf3 Bd6 10. Ng5 Qe7 11. Nxe6 Qxe6 12. Bc4 Qe7 13. Qg4 {White forcefully seized the bishop-pair and the upper hand in Caruana-Hillarp Persson, Reykjavik 2008, as we've noted before,}) ({but} 8... Nf6 $5 9. Nf3 {was agreed drawn in A.Sokolov-Miezis, Biel 2011.} ({Here I dare say Howell was intending} 9. Nc4 {when} Bd6 (9... Qc7 10. Be3 Be6 11. Bb6 Qb8 12. Qf3 {doesn't help Black}) 10. Nxd6+ Qxd6 11. Be3 {gives White a pleasant pull with the bishop-pair, but at least Black is still quite solid.})) 9. a4 $1 {The young English Grandmaster is quick to pinpoint the drawback to Black's play.} Be6 10. Nf3 $1 ({Howell elects to keep it simple.} 10. f4 exf4 11. Nf3 Bc5+ 12. Kh1 {wouldn't have been so clear in D.Popovic-Drazic, Vrnjacka Banja 2005, had Black decided to complete his development with} Nf6 13. Bxf4 O-O {.}) 10... f6 ({This weakens the kingside and is quite slow, but} 10... Bd6 $2 {contained a tactical drawback:} 11. axb5 axb5 12. Rxa8 Qxa8 13. Bxb5 $1 {, netting a clear pawn.}) 11. Qe2 ({Rather than potentially complicate the struggle with} 11. Nh4 $5 {, Howell sticks to his policy of queenside pressure, safe in the knowledge that Black is about to come under heavy pressure there.}) 11... Ne7 ({After} 11... Bd6 12. Rd1 {it's by no means easy for Black to escape the tactic, with, for instance,} Rb8 13. axb5 axb5 14. c4 {one line where White's initiative is already rampant.}) 12. Be3 Ng6 13. axb5 axb5 14. c4 $1 {It's time to lever open the position with Black still two moves away from completing his development.} b4 ({Black's cause would have been pretty grim after} 14... bxc4 15. Bxc4 Bxc4 16. Qxc4 Qc8 17. Rxa8 Qxa8 18. Rd1 Be7 {, but neither is the text exactly palatable. Miezis is going to have to rethink what to do on move 8, or even move 5 dare I say?}) 15. c5 $1 {Isolating the b-pawn and reintroducing the idea of Bc4.} Rb8 ({Things are already so bad for Black that I can't help wondering about the tactic} 15... Rxa1 16. Rxa1 Bxc5 $5 17. Bxc5 Nf4 {. Yes, the rook in the corner will drop, but after} 18. Qe3 Qxd3 19. Qxd3 Nxd3 20. Ra8+ Kf7 21. Rxh8 Nxc5 {perhaps Black might be able to save the endgame on a good day.}) 16. Ra7 Be7 17. Bc4 {The pressure mounts through simple means.} Bxc4 ({Black will never manage to castle after this, but he had to avoid} 17... Qc8 18. Rd1 O-O $2 19. Rdd7 {.}) 18. Qxc4 Ra8 19. Rxa8 Qxa8 20. Nd2 {It's time to bring the knight and remaining rook into play. Meanwhile Black can do pretty much nothing, although Miezis does resist as well as he can.} Nf8 $1 21. h3 $1 Qc8 22. Ra1 $1 {Naturally the b-pawn can wait much better to keep Black from castling.} Ne6 23. Ra7 Nc7 ({Now that White has created some luft for his king, he is able to meet} 23... Qb8 24. Qa6 Kf7 {with} 25. Nc4 Rd8 26. Rb7 Qa8 27. Qxc6 {.}) 24. Nb3 ({Hardly bad, but even stronger would have been} 24. Qa2 $1 {followed by Nc4, invading with decisive effect.}) 24... Qb8 25. Ra5 Qb7 26. f4 $1 {Thwarted for now on the queenside, Howell realises he must create the famed second front.} Rf8 ({A weakness will appear on e5 after this, but} 26... exf4 27. Bxf4 Nb5 28. Qe6 Rf8 29. Bd6 Rf7 {was hardly what Black wanted to do either.}) 27. Nd2 Rf7 28. fxe5 fxe5 29. Qb3 $1 Kf8 30. Nc4 {Finally the knight reaches the promised land and the end is nigh.} Rf6 31. Nxe5 Re6 32. Bf4 g5 33. Bg3 Kg7 34. Qf3 ({Slight time trouble I guess.} 34. Ng4 $1 {, and if} Rxe4 35. Qd3 Re6 36. Qf5 {, would have given White a decisive attack.}) 34... Rf6 35. Qg4 Ne6 36. Nf3 Kg8 ({It appears both players were low on time. Here} 36... Rg6 {would still have made White have to work for the full point.}) 37. Kh1 ({And now} 37. e5 $1 Rg6 38. Qc4 {was the way to keep up the pressure.}) 37... Qd7 $2 (37... Bxc5 38. h4 {was no doubt Howell's idea, but Black had to try this and then perhaps} Qe7 {. The text loses in straightforward fashion.}) 38. Ra8+ Rf8 ({Now Black is overloaded, but his cause was hopeless too in the event of} 38... Bd8 39. Nxg5 Rg6 40. h4 {, and if} h6 41. Qf5 {.}) 39. Ne5 $1 {Minor blemishes aside, a masterclass in manoeuvring and how to maintain the initiative by Howell.} 1-0


