1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 d4 3. b4 g5 $5 {A sharp and interesting alternative to the mainline 3...f6, and other moves such as 3...Bg4, 3...c5 and 3...g6, which are all covered in the Archives. It is a good weapon for the well-prepared blitz player, since as we will see, some unusual tactics can occur.} 4. Qb3 {This move is new to this site, although it is Demuth's recommendation in his Reti repertoire tome. Other lines that can be found in the PGN Archives are:} (4. Bb2 Bg7 5. Nxg5 e5 6. Ne4 f5 {which is the subject of Duda-Bartel}) (4. Nxg5 e5 5. d3 Bxb4+ 6. Bd2 Qxg5 7. Bxb4 {is analyzed in Bocharov-Morozevich}) 4... Bg7 {The first point to note is that:} (4... g4 $2 {allows} 5. Nxd4 $1 {because of} Qxd4 6. Bb2 {etc.}) 5. Nxg5 e5 6. d3 {This is already a novelty in this little explored position. Alternatively:} (6. Qg3 $5 {is critical. Since Demuth's book was published, this has been played in a couple of games.} Qe7 (6... Ne7 {and White can choose:} 7. Ne4 (7. d3 Nbc6 (7... O-O $1 {(not fearing ghosts) looks good for Black, for example} 8. Qh4 h6 9. Nf3 Qd6 {and Black's lead in development is worth more than a pawn}) 8. a3 Bf5 $2 (8... O-O {is still best}) 9. Ne6 Bxe6 10. Qxg7 {and at this point White is well on top having removed the strong g7-bishop, Dardha,D (2449)-Maurizzi,M (2433) Europe Echecs INT 2020 0-1 (53)}) 7... Ng6 8. h4 f5 {leading to a very unclear position, is Demuth's mainline}) 7. b5 Nh6 8. Ne4 f5 {is another sharp line, for example} 9. Ba3 Qf7 10. Ng5 Qf6 11. e4 dxe3 12. fxe3 f4 13. Qh4 Nf7 14. Nf3 Qxh4+ 15. Nxh4 {with roughly balanced chances, Gual Pascual,A (2362)-Trepat Herranz,J (2363) Barcelona 2019 0-1 (39)}) (6. Ne4 $6 {loses time. After} f5 7. Ng3 Nf6 8. d3 O-O {Black has great play for the pawn, Di Benedetto,D (2137)-Kollars,D (2505) Rome 2016 0-1 (40)}) 6... Bh6 $1 {Spotting an unusual tactical point - since the c1-bishop is unprotected, the g5-knight is pinned.} 7. f4 {The only move, but likely not what White was hoping for from the opening.} (7. h4 $2 f6 {wins material.}) 7... exf4 8. h4 $6 {White could maintain an approximate balance with the retreat:} (8. Nf3 {for example} a5 9. b5 Bg4 10. Nbd2 Nd7 11. Qb2 Bg7 {with a weird looking position!}) 8... Nc6 9. b5 Nce7 10. c5 Be6 $6 {Returning the favour. Instead:} (10... Nd5 {leaves White in trouble since} 11. Bxf4 (11. Nf3 Ne3 {is equally painful}) 11... f6 {again exploits the pin on the h6-c1 diagonal}) 11. Nxe6 fxe6 12. Qxe6 Qd5 13. Qxd5 Nxd5 14. Na3 {White has emerged with a fine position. The rest of the game sees many ups and downs. As this was a blitz game, I will give only light notes and not point everything that the computer sees.} O-O-O (14... Ngf6 {can be answered by} 15. g3 {now exploiting the pin in the other direction!}) 15. Nc2 Ne3 16. Nxe3 fxe3 17. g4 {Black's central pawns look imposing, but White can work around them, and is meanwhile a clean pawn up with the two bishops.} Bf4 18. Bb2 Bg3+ 19. Kd1 Nf6 20. g5 Nh5 21. Rc1 Rhf8 22. Rc4 {More convincing was:} (22. Bh3+ Kb8 23. Bg4 Nf4 24. Rc4 {and White starts to dismantle Black's central pawns.}) 22... Be5 23. Bh3+ Kb8 24. Rf1 $2 (24. Bg4 {maintains a large advantage.}) 24... Nf4 {Suddenly White's position collapses.} 25. Rh1 {Or:} (25. Bg4 Nxd3 26. Rxf8 Nxb2+ 27. Kc2 Rxf8 28. Kxb2 d3+ {and the d-pawn can only be stopped at the cost of a rook.}) 25... Nxh3 (25... Nxe2 {was equally effective.}) 26. Rxh3 Rf1+ 27. Kc2 Re1 {After the e2-pawn falls, White is faced with a hopeless task and Navara wins convincingly from here.} 28. Rf3 Rxe2+ 29. Kb3 Rd2 30. Bxd4 Rxd3+ 31. Bc3 e2 32. Rxd3 Rxd3 33. Re4 Rxc3+ 34. Kb4 a5+ {Avoiding any back-rank disasters.} 35. bxa6 Rc1 36. Rxe2 Bd4 37. Re8+ Ka7 38. axb7 Kxb7 39. Kb3 Rc3+ 0-1


