{Due to the tournament situation, this was a very important game for me. I knew that a win would leave me with a reasonable chance of winning the tournament (although as it turns out, it wouldn't have sufficed). That explains my decision to take some risks and play the Dragon Sicilian. However, since I had already played that against Nigel Short in the second round, it can't have come as a complete surprise for David. In this game I got into difficulties, although given our desperate time trouble there were still winning chances for both sides near the time control.} 1. e4 {McShane McShane} c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 O-O 8. Qd2 Nc6 {*} 9. O-O-O (9. Bc4 {leads to the very sharpest lines of the Yugoslav Attack., but 9.0-0-0 is a major alternative.}) 9... d5 10. exd5 Nxd5 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Bd4 Bxd4 13. Qxd4 {[%csl Ra7,Rc6][%cal Ya8b8,Yb8b1,Yh2h4,Yh4h5] White has a long-term structural advantage in this position, so Black has to be careful in his handling of it. Due to the weak Black queenside pawns, a queen exchange is normally in White's favour, and the advance h2-h4-h5 is another important theme. However, Black has his trumps as well. If White advances his pawns too fast on the kingside, a queen exchange may lead to a balanced endgame with mutual weaknesses. Another important source of counterplay lies on the queenside, where White's king is more vulnerable than it looks (and c1 is not always an ideal square).} Qb6 {This might seem to contradict my point about exchanging queens, but capturing on b6 right now would improve Black's structure.} (13... Qc7 {is a common alternative.}) 14. Na4 {Now White would be happy to see a queen exchange on d4.} (14. Nxd5 cxd5 15. Qxd5 {is a risky pawn grab - Black enjoys good compensation for the pawn after} Be6) 14... Qa5 (14... Qc7 {can also be played immediately. However, there are some advantages for Black in drawing the pawn to b3 first. The main one is that the dark squares around White's king become more vulnerable so a check on a3 or even a1 becomes possible sometimes.}) 15. b3 {This is essentially forced - the loose knight on a4 meant that e7-e5 was a serious threat.} Qc7 16. h4 {A direct move.} (16. Bc4 {is also natural.} Rd8 17. Rhe1 {This was Jan Smeets' choice and so we can presume the critical test.} ({Instead a yet more recent game continued:} 17. Qc5 Be6 (17... Qe5 $1 {seems to be an immediate refutation of White's move as a winning attempt as} 18. Kb1 $6 Nc3+ $1 19. Ka1 Rd5 $1 20. Bxd5 Nxd1+ 21. Kb1 cxd5 22. Rxd1 Be6 {is very comfortable.}) 18. Kb1 Qd6 19. Qxd6 Rxd6 20. Rde1 Nf4 21. Bxe6 Nxe6 22. Nc3 Rd2 {and Black had already at least equalised. Vaibhav, S  (2418)-Joshi, G (2292) New Delhi 2010.}) (17. g4 Be6 18. Nc5 Nf4 19. Nxe6 Nxe6 20. Qe3 Nf4 21. Rxd8+ Rxd8 22. Re1 e6 23. Qe5 Qxe5 24. Rxe5 Nd5 {left Black with absolutely no problems in Pavlovic, M (2583)-Konguvel, P (2416) Pamplona 2010. The d5 knight adequately compensates for the queenside weaknesses while White's g4 isn't ideal from a positional point of view.}) 17... Bf5 ({I haven't seen a direct kill after} 17... Qxh2 {but it looks very risky.}) 18. Qe5 Qxe5 19. Rxe5 Bxc2 $5 {A typical idea in this line} 20. Rd2 (20. Kxc2 Nb4+ 21. Kc1 Nxa2+ 22. Kc2 Nb4+ {would just be a draw.}) 20... Bf5 21. Nc5 h5 22. Bxd5 cxd5 23. Rxe7 d4 {and Black held the draw without too many problems. Smeets, J (2669)-Negi, P (2596) Solingen 2010}) ({Leko has tried} 16. Re1 $5 {against Radjabov in 2009, where White prepares to offer an exchange of queens on e5.}) (16. Rd2 Rb8 17. Bc4 e5 $6 {I think this move is generally dubious here as it cedes control of the d6 square and blocks the queen which was putting pressure on White's kingside.} 18. Qc5 Nb6 19. Nxb6 (19. Nb2 $1 {is somewhat unpleasant to deal with.}) 19... axb6 20. Qd6 Qa7 21. b4 Qa3+ (21... Ba6 $1 {now favours Black}) 22. Kb1 Ba6 $4 {but you can't throw in the check first!} 23. Rd3 Qa4 24. Bb3 {1-0 Getz, N  (2276) -Ocantos, M (2176) Budapest 2010 and Black had to resign as the queen was getting trapped.}) 16... Bf5 $5 {David said that he expected this, but} (16... h5 {was played in most of the games which reached this position, as it is somewhat risky to allow White's pawn to h5.} 17. Bc4 Nb6 18. Nb2 (18. g4 $5 {was played against me in the 4ncl Rapidplay. An interesting idea allowing me to capture on a4 but then once White sticks the bishop on b3 I couldn't see a way through. Therefore I tried} Nxc4 19. Qxc4 Be6 20. Qc5 Qf4+ 21. Kb1 Qxf3 22. gxh5 Qxh5 23. Qxe7 Rfe8 24. Qf6 Bf5 {and I was fairly happy with my position. We'll go forward a few moves to highlight a feature we should look out for:} 25. Rd2 Re6 26. Rd8+ Rxd8 27. Qxd8+ Kh7 28. Qc7 Kg7 29. Qxa7 Bxc2+ $1 30. Kxc2 Re2+ 31. Kc3 Qe5+ 32. Kb4 Qe4+ 33. Ka3 Qxh1 {and Black was of course totally winning although in the confusion of rapid chess I first let the win slip through my fingers and then even lost it! Piper, M (2343)-Jones, G (2576) Newport Pagnell 2010.}) 18... Bf5 19. Rhe1 Rfd8 20. Qe5 Rxd1+ 21. Kxd1 Qxe5 {Exchanging queens condemns Black to a tough defence.} (21... Qd8+ $1 22. Kc1 e6 {sees the h4 pawn under scrutiny and} 23. g3 Nd5 {looks fine for Black provided he doesn't allow his bishop to get trapped.}) 22. Rxe5 Nxc4 23. Nxc4 Be6 24. Rc5 Bxc4 25. Rxc4 Rc8 26. Kd2 {and White converted his much better endgame. Volokitin, A (2661)-Jianu, V (2528) Baile Herculane 2010.}) 17. g4 {During the game I felt comfortable about allowing this advance. My reasoning was that g4 probably adds little to the attack, while if Black can now exchange queens then there will always be some counterplay against f3.} Be6 $146 {This didn't turn out well, but I was intending to play 19...a5 which I later discovered was bad.} (17... e5 18. Qc5 {Jones, Gawain: '!'} (18. Qd2 $5 {also makes sense} Be6 19. h5 Rad8 20. hxg6 fxg6 21. Nc5 Nf4 22. Nxe6 Nxe6 23. Bd3 Nd4 {Blehm, P (2511)-Charbonneau, P (2501) ICC 2006 and here} (23... Rxf3 24. Qe2 Rf4 25. Bc4 {looks ropey for Black but was probably necessary.}) 24. Bc4+ $1 Kh8 25. Qg5 Nxf3 26. Rxd8 Qxd8 27. Qxg6 {would have given White an overwhelming position.}) 18... Be6 19. Bc4 (19. h5 g5 {would have similarities to the game and White must have a clear advantage following} 20. Bd3 f6 21. Be4) 19... Rad8 {looks better for White, but Black seems better organised than in the game.}) 18. Nc5 Rad8 19. Bc4 (19. Nxe6 fxe6 {[%csl Ra3,Rc3,Gd8,Gf8][%cal Yd8d1,Yf8f3] gives Black excellent counterplay in spite of the shattered pawn structure.} 20. h5 Rf4 21. Qd3 Qd6 $1 22. hxg6 Qa3+ 23. Kd2 (23. Kb1 Nc3+ $1) 23... Qa5+ 24. Kc1 Qa3+ {would be an interesting draw.}) 19... Bc8 {Not a very happy choice.} (19... Qa5 {is the move which I wanted to play. After some thought I decided that it was probably bad, although perhaps for the wrong reasons.} 20. Nb7 {this doesn't win an exchange, but it does force the queens off.} Qa3+ 21. Qb2 Qxb2+ 22. Kxb2 Rb8 23. Na5 {This is what I was worried about.} (23. Nc5 Ne3 $1 {is decent for Black}) (23. Ba6 $1 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Yb7c5] never occurred to me but might be the best move.}) 23... Ne3 {Black has to try this tactic. During the game it seemed White had a couple of ways to be better, but there are some surprising twists:} (23... Rfc8 24. Nxc6 $1 {took me some time to spot, but gives White a clear extra pawn}) 24. Bxe6 $5 (24. Rd4 {looked like a safe edge to both players during the game, but the computer points out that} c5 $1 {gives Black decent play, e.g.} 25. Re4 Nxc4+ 26. Nxc4 Bd5 27. Rf4 f6 $132) 24... Nxd1+ 25. Rxd1 fxe6 26. Nxc6 Rb6 $1 {the best try, which I hadn't seen.} (26... Rb7 27. Ne5 {must give White a nice edge}) 27. Ne5 (27. Nxe7+ {seems to lead to a repetition:} Kf7 28. Rd7 Ke8 29. Rxa7 Rd6 {[%csl Re7][%cal Yd6d7]} 30. Nc8 Rc6 31. Ra8 Kf7 32. Ra7+ Ke8 $11) 27... Rd6 {and by challenging for the d-file, Black may be alright.}) (19... Qf4+ 20. Qxf4 Nxf4 21. Bxe6 Nxe6 22. Rxd8 Rxd8 23. Nxe6 fxe6 24. Re1 {would leave Black in a pretty miserable ending.}) (19... Nf4 {however, is probably not terrible:} 20. Nxe6 Nxe6 21. Qe4 Qf4+ 22. Kb2 Qxe4 23. fxe4 Nc5 24. e5 {still leaves Black suffering to hold the half point.}) 20. h5 e5 (20... Qf4+ {Jones, Gawain: 'looks possible but in the post mortem Luke remarked that'} 21. Qxf4 Nxf4 22. h6 $1 {[%csl Gc4] Jones, Gawain: '"And this pawn is a real pain" - McShane.' is important. The h6-pawn combines with the bishop on c4 to severely cramp Black's king.}) ({Black's best is probably} 20... Nb6 21. Qe3 $1 {This looks the most dangerous.} (21. Qe4 Nxc4 22. Qxc4 Qe5 {leaves White's knight dominating the bishop but at least Black's queen has become active.}) 21... Nxc4 22. bxc4 Rd6 23. Rd3 {and White's attack looks the much more foreboding.}) 21. Qf2 ({Jones, Gawain: 'However'} 21. Qd2 {[%cal Yd2h6] Jones, Gawain: '!' Jones, Gawain: 'looks very strong with one potential line running:' was more direct, and the move which David was trying to make work. However, the stumbling block was} Qe7 (21... Nf4 {is probably necessary but} 22. Qe3 Qe7 23. hxg6 hxg6 24. Nd3 Nxd3+ 25. Rxd3 Rxd3 26. Qh6 Rd1+ 27. Rxd1 {looks very good for White.}) 22. hxg6 (22. Qh6 g5 {A typical idea in the Chinese Dragon but here} 23. Ne4 f6 24. Nxg5 $1 {blows open Black's position.} fxg5 25. Qxc6 Bb7 26. Rxd5 $1 Bxc6 27. Rd7+ Qf7 28. Bxf7+ {is a tough line to see but leaves White with a decisive advantage.}) 22... Qxc5 $5 {and White can't do better than a draw here, e.g.} 23. Qh6 (23. gxf7+ Kh8 {seems to be alright as well}) 23... Qa3+ 24. Kd2 Qb4+ 25. Kc1 Qa3+ $11) 21... Qe7 22. Ne4 $1 {This is the move which frightened me, not fearing the check on a3.} g5 $13 (22... Qa3+ 23. Kb1 Nb4 {looks tempting at first, but then} 24. Nc3 $1 {just parries the threats and leaves Black's queen and knight offside.}) (22... f5 {Jones, Gawain: '!?' Jones, Gawain: 'is suggested on ChessVibes although' was playable, and we both looked at this.} 23. gxf5 Bxf5 {is better for White but messy. However, I decided 'on principle' that it wasn't a good idea to weaken my kingside in this fashion.} (23... gxf5 $5 24. Nc3 Be6 25. Bxd5 $5 cxd5 26. f4 $1 {is rather miserable.})) 23. h6 $1 {Jones, Gawain: 'Not allowing Black enough time to play ...h6 so his g5 pawn will always prove vulnerable.' Another important move - if Black could play h7-h6 the kingside structure would start to look quite steady.} Kh8 24. Qc5 {Jones, Gawain: '!' White is doing well, but perhaps} (24. Rhe1 $5 {was a more flexible way to progress - White keeps the option of exchanging queens on c5 later.}) 24... Qxc5 25. Nxc5 f5 {Jones, Gawain: 'Luke desperately tries for play.' I considered it essential to get some counterplay} (25... f6 26. Rd3 {just allows White further time to build up.}) 26. gxf5 Rxf5 {[%csl Re5,Rf3,Gf5,Rg5,Gh6,Rh8][%cal Yf5f3] Black is objectively worse, but the position is becoming very sharp and it was harder for David to handle in his time trouble.} 27. Rhe1 (27. Rhg1 $1 Rg8 28. Rg3 Rf6 29. Bxd5 cxd5 30. Rxd5 Rxh6 31. Rxe5 {would leave White a pawn up with excellent winning chances. The game continuation is also very good for White however.}) 27... Rxf3 28. Rxe5 g4 {Pushing a pawn is an easy plan!} 29. Ne4 {Jones, Gawain: 'The h6 pawn is extremely annoying to deal with. I'm fairly sure David would be able to convert the full point against most opponents but Luke is an extremely tricky character and David was in his typical time trouble.' We both had to play on our instincts here, and David brings his knight back to help control the g-pawn and create mating threats via g5.} (29. Bxd5 cxd5 30. Rdxd5 (30. Rexd5 Rg8 $13) 30... Rg8 {is very double edged. For example} 31. Rg5 Rff8 $1 {[%csl Gg4][%cal Yg4g1]}) 29... Rdf8 ({I would seriously consider} 29... Rf5 {White could win a pawn with} 30. Re7 $1 {but following} Rdf8 31. Rxa7 Rh5 32. a4 Rxh6 33. Bxd5 cxd5 34. Rxd5 {Black at least has counterplay in the shape of his kingside pawns.}) 30. Bxd5 cxd5 31. Ng5 {Jones, Gawain: 'Keeping the initiative.'} ({However} 31. Rdxd5 Bf5 32. Ng5 Rf1+ 33. Kb2 Bg6 34. Re2 {just looks like a clear pawn up.}) 31... R3f6 (31... Rf2 $1 {was stronger according to my computer, but I didn't think about this much. When the bishop comes to f5, it protects h7 and counterattacks c2.} 32. Re7 Bf5 33. Rd2 g3 34. Re3 {was another line discussed at the post mortem when the g3 pawn drops as} g2 35. Nf7+ $1 Kg8 36. Rg3+ Kxf7 37. Rxf2 {wins.}) 32. Re7 Rg6 $2 {Jones, Gawain: 'This should lose.' Objectively a serious error, but neither of us found White's winning possibility.} (32... Rxh6 33. Nf7+ Rxf7 34. Rxf7 Be6 {was suggested in the commentary room after the game. I was disappointed that I hadn't investigated this further during the game, as the h+g pawns looked rather potent. But it looks like White is winning the race after all.} 35. Rxa7 Rg6 36. b4 g3 37. b5 g2 38. Rg1 {[%csl Gb5][%cal Yb5b8] and the reinforcements on the h-file seem too slow.}) ({Jones, Gawain: 'Luke's best was'} 32... Bf5 $1 {Jones, Gawain: 'when the position isn't actually so clear.' was essential, with a very unclear position.} 33. Rf1 (33. Rxd5 g3 34. Rd2 Bg6 35. Rxa7 Rf5 36. Ne6 Rg8 37. Kb2 Rh5 {and the g3 pawn is a major asset.}) 33... a6 34. Re5 Kg8 35. Rxd5 Bg6 36. Rxf6 Rxf6 37. Rd8+ Rf8 38. Rxf8+ Kxf8 39. Kd2 Ke7 40. Ke3 Bxc2 41. Ne4 {is better for White but Black has reasonable drawing chances.}) 33. Rxd5 (33. Rxh7+ Kg8 34. Rg7+ Rxg7 35. hxg7 Rf5 $19 {[%csl Rg5] is one line showing the dangers here.}) 33... g3 {This position is a good example of the skewed perspective that a computer can give. With the right idea, White is absolutely winning, but it's not easy to see. If you don't see the idea, then Black has the upper hand in practice!} (33... Kg8 34. Nxh7 $1 {wins.}) 34. Rf7 $2 {Jones, Gawain: 'David errs in his terrible time trouble.'} ({Jones, Gawain: 'With more time I'm sure he would have found'} 34. Rxh7+ Kg8 35. Rf7 $3 {[%csl Gg5,Rg8,Gh6][%cal Yd5d8] Jones, Gawain: '!' Jones, Gawain: 'A pretty move which wins material.' eluded both players.} Re8 {even here, the win isn't trivial in desperate time trouble.} (35... Rxf7 36. Rd8+ {Jones, Gawain: 'is hopeless'} Rf8 37. h7+ Kg7 38. Rxf8 $18) (35... Rxh6 36. Rxf8+ Kxf8 37. Rd8+ Ke7 38. Rxc8 g2 39. Nf3 Rf6 40. Rg8 {and White has a trivial win.}) 36. Re5 $1 Rd8 37. h7+ Kh8 38. Rf1 $18 {[%csl Rg3][%cal Yf1g1] and White is in time to win the pawn.}) 34... Re8 $2 {Jones, Gawain: 'The last move actually gave Black the better position but Luke was in time trouble too.'} ({Jones, Gawain: 'Had he found'} 34... Kg8 $1 {Jones, Gawain: 'Then suddenly David would have to scramble to try and hold the half point.' would have actually turned the tables in my favour.} 35. Rf3 $1 {might hold the game though.} (35. Rxf8+ Kxf8 36. Nxh7+ Ke7 (36... Kf7 $2 37. Ng5+ $18) 37. Rg5 (37. Re5+ Be6 38. Ng5 g2 39. Nf3 Rxh6 40. Rg5 Rf6 41. Rxg2 Rxf3 {leaves Black with the winning chances although I feel it must be a draw due to the lack of material.}) 37... Kf7 $1 {seems to be winning.} 38. Ra5 (38. Rxg6 Kxg6 39. Ng5 Bg4 $3 $19) 38... g2 39. Ng5+ Kf6 40. Nf3 Bb7 41. Ng1 Rxh6 $19 {[%csl Gg2][%cal Yh6h1]}) 35... Bb7 36. Rxf8+ Kxf8 37. Nxh7+ Ke7 38. Rg5 Rxh6 (38... Kf7 39. Rxg6 Kxg6 40. Ng5 $1 Kxg5 41. h7 g2 42. h8=Q g1=Q+ 43. Kb2 $11) 39. Rxg3 Rxh7 $11 {this must be drawn.}) 35. Re5 {Jones, Gawain: '!?'} (35. Rxh7+ Kg8 36. Re7 $1 {was a chance to implement the same idea as before.} Rf8 37. h7+ Kh8 38. Rf7 Re8 39. Re5 {would have reached the same position but with an extra pawn which would be winning comfortably.}) 35... Rd8 36. Rd5 Re8 37. Re5 {Jones, Gawain: '?!'} Rd8 38. Rd5 {Jones, Gawain: '?!' Jones, Gawain: 'Apparently David had just 8 seconds left here to make the last couple of moves and so couldn't think about a way to win. An interesting game but I don't think 16...Bf5 is likely to be repeated.' McShane: '½-½ (38) Howell,D (2611)-McShane,L (2645) London 2010 CBM 140 [McShane]' David had less than 20 seconds left here. I was down to around 45 seconds before I claimed the draw by repetition. It's a good thing for me that I did, as with more time I'm sure David (and I!) would have discovered that the position is still winning for White.} (38. Rf3 $1 g2 39. Rg3 {wins due to a neat tactic:} Bh3 40. Nf7+ Kg8 41. Nxd8 Rxg3 42. Re8# $1) 1/2-1/2


