1. e4 {Roiz,M This move is David's main weapon, but I also had to get prepared for 1.c4 or 1.f3.} e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 {The most aggressive choice. My opponent mostly used to play 3.b5, but he also had definite experience in Scotch.} exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Nb3 Bb6 6. Nc3 Nf6 7. Qe2 {This original idea was successfully employed by World Champion Magnus Carlsen. Since his game vs Etienne Bacrot in 2010, White's aggressive setup has gained a lot of popularity.} O-O 8. Be3 ({Another common continuation was:} 8. Bg5 {To be honest, my home preparation was mainly based on my previous encounter in this line.}) 8... d5 {That was played rather quickly, since I was familiar with a game of my friend Boris Avrukh, where he went for an attractive queen sac.} ({In my opinion, the intermediate} 8... Re8 9. f3 {only helps White to meet} d5 ({Black's position was solid, but somewhat passive after} 9... d6 10. O-O-O Be6 11. Kb1 Nd7 12. Qf2 Bxe3 13. Qxe3 $14 {1/2 Panarin,M (2538)-Khalifman,A (2651)/Tyumen 2012/CBM 149 (41)}) {with} 10. O-O-O Be6 11. Qf2 Ne5 12. h3 Ng6 13. Bxb6 axb6 14. f4 Bd7 15. f5 Ne5 16. exd5 $14 {1/2 Caruana,F (2775)-Naiditsch,A (2700)/Dortmund 2012/CBM 150/[Marin,M] (60)}) 9. O-O-O d4 10. Bg5 {At this moment I was already out of preparation, though this move was played by Vishy Anand 2 years ago. For some reason, I didn't pay much attention to this idea and never analysed the subsequent sharp position.} ({The above-mentioned game of my friend saw:} 10. Nb5 $6 dxe3 11. Rxd8 Rxd8 12. f3 Be6 {Li,R (2426)-Avrukh,B (2609)/Chicago USA 2015, and Back got promising compensation.}) ({The somewhat slow} 10. f3 {isn't in the spirit of position, so Black should be fine after} Be6 11. Bg5 (11. Bf2 $6 Ng4 $1 12. fxg4 Qg5+ 13. Qd2 Qxd2+ 14. Rxd2 dxc3 15. bxc3 Bxf2 16. Rxf2 Bxg4 $15 {1/2 Nezar,M (2396)-Szabo,K (2545)/Haguenau 2013/CBM 154 Extra (34)}) 11... Re8 12. Kb1 Qe7 $1 (12... Nb4 13. Qe1 c5 14. Na4 $14 {1-0 Darini,P (2479)-Khomeriki,N (2228)/Nakhchivan AZE 2015 (24)}) 13. Na4 d3 $1 14. Qxd3 Rad8 15. Qe2 Bc4 16. Qe1 Bf2 $1 17. Rxd8 Bxe1 18. Rxe8+ Qxe8 19. Bxc4 Na5 $1 $132) 10... h6 {The most natural move.} ({As an alternative, I was mainly considering} 10... Qd6 {, but after} 11. Kb1 Re8 12. f3 Be6 13. Bxf6 gxf6 14. Qe1 $36 {Black doesn't get any compensation for an exposed pawn structure.}) 11. Bh4 Qd6 ({In the following high-level game Black did face definite problems after:} 11... Re8 12. f3 ({Another move which deserves serious attention is} 12. Nd5 $5 g5 13. Nxf6+ Qxf6 14. Bg3 {and the vulnerablity of Black's king may tell.}) 12... Be6 13. Kb1 Qe7 $6 14. Na4 Nb4 15. Qe1 $14 {1-0 Anand,V (2783)-Fressinet,L (2706)/Paris/St Petersburg 2013/CBM 154/[Szabo,Kr] (49)}) ({It was possible to simplify matters by means of} 11... g5 12. Bg3 Qe7 13. Nd5 Nxd5 14. exd5 Qxe2 15. Bxe2 Nb4 16. Nxd4 Nxd5 {, but after} 17. Bf3 $14 {Black's position looks rather unpleasant.}) ({Black's position looks dangerous also in the event of} 11... Be6 12. e5 g5 13. Bg3 Nd7 14. Nb5 $36) 12. Kb1 Qe6 $146 {A logical novelty - it definitely makes sense to avoid the pin as soon as possible.} ({In one preceding game Black lost the important d4 for free after:} 12... Re8 13. f3 a5 $6 14. Nb5 Qe5 15. Bg3 Qe7 16. N3xd4 $16 {0-1 Brunello,M (2235)-Markantonaki,H (2150)/Achaia 2013}) 13. Bxf6 Qxf6 14. Nd5 Qd6 {At this moment I was quite optimstic about my position. However, David's next move completely changed my good feeling...} 15. f4 $1 {A very strong move! White's plan is based on 16.f3 and d3 or c4, followed by g2-g4 advance. At the same time, the presence of the d5 makes Black's q-side counterplay problematic.} Be6 {The most natural move.} ({I was also considering} 15... Rd8 {to prevent White from pushing c2-c4, but this move looked awkward, so finally I rejected it. Indeed, after} 16. Qf3 Be6 17. Bc4 {White's position should be better, though} (17. g4 $5) 17... Nb4 $1 18. Nxd4 Bxd4 19. Rxd4 Qc5 20. Qc3 c6 21. Bb3 Qxc3 22. bxc3 Nxd5 23. exd5 Bxd5 24. Rhd1 Re8 {would offer great drawish chances in the resulting rook ending.}) 16. c4 $1 {Unfortunately, White is just in time to support the strong d5, since 16...dxc3 17.f6+ drops the queen.} (16. Qf3 Bxd5 17. exd5 Ne7 18. Nxd4 Qxd5 $11) 16... Nb4 ({The most tempting reaction on White's last move would be:} 16... f5 $5 17. e5 Qd7 {trying to get a rid of d5 at any cost. Most probably, this idea wouldn't solve all Black's problems, but it is still playable:} 18. g3 a5 (18... Bxd5 19. cxd5 Qxd5 20. Bg2 Qe6 21. Rc1 $36) 19. Bg2 a4 20. Nxb6 cxb6 21. Bxc6 Qxc6 22. Nxd4 Bxc4 23. Qd2 $14) 17. Qf3 {The most consistent.} ({For some reason, I didn't pay much attention to} 17. Nxd4 Bxd5 18. cxd5 Qxf4 {, though after} 19. g3 Qe5 20. Nf3 Qh5 21. Bg2 $14 {White is better due to superiority in the centre.}) 17... Rfe8 $2 {Being under serious time pressure, I was trying to activate my pieces at the cost of a pawn, but it is simply wrong.} ({For some reason, I overestimated the strengh of White's central pawns in the following line:} 17... Rad8 $1 18. a3 Nxd5 19. cxd5 Bd7 20. Bc4 $1 {It looks like only this strong move offers White some advantage} ({The move} 20. Nxd4 {is weaker:} Qg6 {the threat of 21...g4 practically forces} 21. f5 Qf6 {, so Black gets full positional compensation for a pawn.}) 20... Qg6 21. h3 Rfe8 22. Bd3 c6 23. e5 Bf5 24. dxc6 bxc6 25. g4 Bxd3+ 26. Rxd3 {The resulting position is double-edged, but White should be somewhat better.}) 18. Nxd4 $1 {My opponent correctly accepts the challenge.} ({My idea would be fully justified only after} 18. a3 $2 Nxd5 19. cxd5 Bxd5 $1 20. exd5 Re3 $19 {[%csl Rb3]}) ({Another way of winning the pawn offers Black much more activity:} 18. Nxb6 axb6 19. Rxd4 Qe7 20. a3 Nc6 21. Rd2 Rad8 $14) 18... Bxd4 19. Rxd4 Qc5 ({It would hardly be better choosing:} 19... Nxd5 20. cxd5 c6 21. Bd3 (21. Bc4 {is less convincing:} cxd5 22. Bxd5 Bxd5 23. Rxd5 Qe6 $14) 21... cxd5 22. f5 Bd7 23. Rxd5 Qc7 24. f6 $16) 20. Qc3 $1 a5 {Unfortunately, Black cannot exploit some delay with development of White's k-side pieces.} ({After} 20... Rad8 21. a3 Nxd5 22. cxd5 Qxc3 23. bxc3 Bd7 24. e5 $16 {White has a sound extra pawn.}) 21. a3 Na6 22. Be2 c6 23. Ne3 Rad8 {Any exchanges favour White here, but I had no choice.} (23... Qb6 24. Rhd1 Nc5 25. f5 Bc8 26. Bf3 $18) 24. Rhd1 Rxd4 25. Rxd4 $1 {David is on top again.} ({It would be more difficult to make progress after} 25. Qxd4 Qxd4 26. Rxd4 Nc5 27. Bf3 Bc8 28. g3 g5 $16) 25... Qb6 26. Bd1 Nc5 27. Bc2 a4 $6 $138 ({The most stubborn was:} 27... Bc8 28. g3 f6 {- White's position is still winning from the technical point of view, but his plan doesn't look obvious.}) 28. e5 $1 {Now Black's position is completely hopeless - there are no active ideas.} Bc8 29. g3 Nb3 30. Rd6 Nc5 31. Nd5 $1 {The most effective way - the knight is coming into the attack.} Qa7 32. Ne7+ Kf8 33. Nxc8 {White doesn't mind exchanging the ''passive'' bishop, since it is the main defender of Black's king.} Rxc8 34. Qe3 Qa5 35. f5 {The remaining few moves were just an agony.} Re8 36. Rxh6 $1 Kg8 (36... gxh6 37. Qxh6+ Ke7 38. Qd6#) 37. f6 Nb3 38. fxg7 {A prosaic choice.} ({The most effective way was:} 38. Bh7+ Kf8 39. Bg6 fxg6 40. Rh8+ Kf7 41. fxg7) 1-0


