1. e4 c5 2. c3 e6 3. d4 d5 {I've always thought that this was a rather good line against the c3-Sicilian. The reason it is not more popular is purely a function of preparation - Black needs to be comfortable in the French, both in the Advance Variation (as arises directly after 4.e5) and in the line played in the game, which is very closely related to the French Tarrasch variation 3. Nd2 c5 4.exd5 exd5. Obviously Nigel is a French specialist so such issues don't concern him.} 4. exd5 exd5 ({It's not too late for Black to play} 4... Qxd5 {, but this is much more easily reached via a 2...d5 move order, which doesn't allow an Advance French.}) 5. Nf3 Nc6 6. Bb5 (6. Be3 {is the main alternative, as covered in the Archives in V.Baklan - R.Polzin, Austrian Team Championship 2007 (1/2 - 1/2 in 38).}) 6... Bd6 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. O-O Nge7 9. Nbd2 O-O 10. Nb3 {This position should be compared to 1.e4 e6 2.d4 d5 3.Nd2 c5 4.exd5 exd5 5.Nf3 Nc6 6.Bb5 Bd6 7.dxc5 Bxc5 8.0-0 Nge7 9.Nb3. There the bishop normally retreats to d6 since 9...Bb6 can be met by 10.Re1 intending 11.Be3. Here White has already committed to the semi-useful c3 move, so Short reckons he can deploy his bishop more actively.} Bb6 11. Re1 Bg4 12. Be3 Re8 ({Afek has deviated from this normal developing move, with disastrous results.} 12... Bc7 13. Bc5 Re8 14. h3 a6 15. Bxc6 Bxf3 16. Qxf3 bxc6 17. Nd4 Qd7 18. Qg4 $1 $16 {C.Van Oosterom (2426) - Y.Afek (2283), Groningen 2010 (1-0 in 30)}) (12... Bxe3 13. Rxe3 Nf5 14. Rd3 Nce7 (14... Qb6 15. Rxd5 Nce7 16. Rc5 Rad8 17. Qe2 {didn't give Black enough compensation in A.Kartsev (2145) - Y. Afek (2310), Dieren 2010 (1-0 in 35)}) 15. h3 Bh5 16. Bc4 Nh4 17. Bxd5 Nxd5 18. g4 Qf6 19. Nxh4 Nf4 20. Rf3 {was J.Haarr (2211) - Y.Afek (2299), Oslo 2011 (1-0 in 58), and now} Rad8 {would have equalised.}) 13. h3 Bh5 14. Bxb6 (14. a4 $1 {is more ambitious. After} Bc7 15. Bc5 a6 16. Bxc6 Nxc6 17. Rxe8+ Qxe8 18. Qxd5 Bxf3 19. Qxf3 {White had a clear extra pawn in S.Smagin (2545) - O.Cvitan (2510), Biel 1995 (1-0 in 25).}) 14... Qxb6 15. Bxc6 ({White has more often retreated his bishop with} 15. Be2 {, but Black looks sufficiently active to hold the balance.}) 15... Bxf3 (15... bxc6 16. g4 Bg6 17. Qd4 Bc2 18. Qxb6 axb6 19. Nbd4 Be4 {was nothing special for White in G.Malbran (2306) - D.Valerga (2472), Buenos Aires 2006 (0-1 in 46).}) 16. Qxf3 bxc6 17. Re2 Ng6 18. Rae1 Rxe2 19. Rxe2 Rd8 20. Nd4 ({Trading queens with} 20. Qe3 {doesn't look like anything special either:} Qxe3 21. Rxe3 Rb8 {followed by ...f6 and ...Kf7.}) 20... c5 21. Nf5 d4 22. Qe4 h6 23. cxd4 cxd4 {Black has full counterplay.} 24. Rd2 Qa5 25. Rxd4 Rxd4 26. Nxd4 Qxa2 27. b3 Nf8 28. g3 g6 29. Kg2 a5 30. Qc6 Qd2 31. Qa4 Qd3 32. Nf3 Qd5 33. b4 axb4 34. Qxb4 Ne6 35. Qd2 Qxd2 36. Nxd2 Kg7 {It is interesting that Howell put his money on 6.Bb5. These positions have been known since the Karpov - Korchnoi matches to be very close to equality. A slight passivity in Black's game, coupled with the necessity of accurately handling positions outside the Sicilian domain (including the Advance French), are the only discouragements to anyone looking for a very sound defence to the c3-Sicilian.} 1/2-1/2


