1. e4 {Martin,A Martin,A} c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. Nc3 b5 {One of the sharper Taimanov lines, which White has to play carefully against to have any hope of advantage. Systems with g3, e2 and e3 are not very good now, so to start with White should play d3.} 6. Bd3 Bb7 7. O-O Nc6 8. Nxc6 Bxc6 9. Re1 (9. Qe2 Ne7 10. Bd2 Ng6 11. a4 b4 12. Nd5 a5 13. c3 b3 14. g3 Bd6 15. Ne3 O-O 16. Nc4 Bc5 17. Be3 Qe7 18. Nd2 Ne5 19. Bxc5 Qxc5 20. Nxb3 Qd6 21. Bb5 f5 22. f4 Ng4 23. e5 Qd5 {Ponomariov,R (2727)-Vallejo Pons,F (2629)/Linares 2002} 24. Bxc6 Qxc6 25. Nd4 $18) 9... Bc5 10. e5 $1 (10. Be3 {should also leave White with some advantage, as the exchange of dark-squared bishops is surely in his favour:} Bxe3 (10... Qb6 11. Qh5 Bxe3 12. Rxe3 Nf6 13. Qg5 $36) 11. Rxe3 Ne7 12. Qg4 Ng6 13. e5 Qh4 14. Qxh4 Nxh4 15. Rg3 Ng6 16. Re1 $14) 10... Qb6 $5 $146 {Black doesn't have an easy time of it however he plays:} (10... f5 11. Qh5+ g6 12. Qh3 Kf7 13. Be3 Qb6 14. Qh4 b4 15. Nd1 h6 16. a3 a5 17. Bxc5 Qxc5 18. axb4 axb4 19. Rxa8 Bxa8 20. Ne3 g5 21. Qh5+ Kg7 22. h4 Ne7 23. hxg5 Rh7 24. Ng4 hxg5 25. Qxg5+ {Caspi,I (2460)-Paljusaj,E (2316)/Rijeka 2010 1-0 (31)}) (10... Qh4 11. Be3 (11. Ne4 Bxe4 12. Rxe4 Qxf2+ 13. Kh1 Ba7 14. a4 bxa4 15. Rexa4 Bb8 16. Rf4 Qc5 17. Rc4 Qd5 18. Rc8+ Ke7 19. Bg5+ f6 20. Qh5 Qxe5 21. Qe8+ Kd6 22. Bd2 Qxb2 23. Rd1 Ne7 24. Bf4+ {1-0 Caspi,I (2427)-Kantsler,B (2468)/Israel 2010}) 11... Bxe3 12. Rxe3 f5 13. g3 Qd4 14. Bf1 Qxd1 {½-½ Haimovich,T (2425)-Kantsler,B (2487)/Herzliya 2008}) 11. Qe2 f5 12. a4 b4 13. a5 $1 {A very significant move, which makes the a6-pawn vulnerable for the rest of the game. Initially, it provokes a forced sequence.} Bxf2+ (13... Qb7 {is just no good.} 14. Na4 Bxa4 (14... Bd4 15. Qh5+ $1 g6 16. Qh4 $16) 15. Rxa4 $16) 14. Qxf2 Qxf2+ 15. Kxf2 bxc3 16. bxc3 (16. Rb1 cxb2 17. Rxb2 Ne7 18. Bd2 O-O 19. Rb6 Be4 $1 20. Rxa6 Rxa6 21. Bxa6 Nc6 {lets Black off the hook, to an extent.}) 16... Ne7 17. c4 Kf7 18. g3 (18. Rb1 $1 {looks pretty good too:} h6 19. Bd2 g5 20. Rb6 $16 Nc8 21. Rb3 Ne7 22. g3) 18... h6 19. h4 (19. Rb1 {again.}) 19... g5 $1 {A spirited attempt to get counterplay and probably the only good move} 20. hxg5 (20. h5 Rhb8 21. Bd2 Rb2 22. Reb1 Rab8 23. Rxb2 Rxb2 24. c5 Nd5 $13) 20... hxg5 21. Bxg5 Rh2+ (21... Ng6 22. Bf4 Nxf4 23. gxf4 Rh3 $132) 22. Ke3 Rg8 23. Bf4 Ng6 24. Kd4 {Howell's play with the king from now on is extraordinary.} Nxf4 25. gxf4 Rh4 26. Rf1 Rb8 27. Kc5 Ke7 28. Rf2 Kd8 29. Kd6 $1 {With both players getting short of time this is a very courageous decision.} Rc8 $2 $138 (29... Bf3 $1 30. Rg1 Bg4 31. Kc5 Kc7 {was the way to keep the game going.}) 30. Rb1 {He finally gets around to playing b1 and it is almost immediately decisive.} Rh1 (30... Ba8 31. Rb6 Rc6+ 32. Rxc6 Bxc6 33. c5 $18 Bb7 34. Rf1 Rg4 35. c6 $1 Bxc6 36. Bxa6 $18) 31. Rb6 $1 Be4 32. c5 Rb1 (32... Rd1 33. Rh2 $18) 33. Rxa6 Bxd3 34. Rh2 {The killer blow.} Bxa6 35. Rh8# 1-0


