1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. Nc3 b5 6. Bd3 Bb7 $5 {As subscribers should be aware, I've long been quite a fan of this solid choice for Black.} 7. O-O Nc6 8. Nxc6 Bxc6 9. Re1 {This line, Tiviakov's choice, continues to grow in popularity, but there have also been developments after the alternatives:} ({a)} 9. Qe2 Bc5 10. a4 ({the critical} 10. e5 $5 Bd4 {was covered in Felgaer-Kamsky, Khanty-Mansiysk Olympiad 2010,}) ({while} 10. Be3 Bxe3 11. Qxe3 Ne7 12. a4 {is perhaps just a little too simplistic and} b4 13. Ne2 O-O 14. Rfd1 Qa5 {seemed OK for Black at this stage in Tseshkovsky-Pritchett, Arco 2010, who might have met} 15. Nd4 {with} Qe5 $5 {, preparing to pin in the event of} 16. f4 Qc5) 10... b4 11. Nd5 Ne7 12. Nxe7 Qxe7 ({John thought that Ionescu's} 12... Bxe7 $5 {was perhaps safer he gave} 13. Bxa6 Qb6 14. Bd3 Rxa4 15. Rxa4 Bxa4 {as equal and after} 16. Be3 Qc7 17. Bd4 O-O 18. Ra1 Bc6 19. Qg4 g6 {Black is certainly extremely solidly placed}) 13. Bxa6 Bxe4 14. Qxe4 Rxa6 15. Qb7 $1 Ra5 {was covered by John Emms in Golubev-Nisipeanu, Predeal 2006, which only lasted another five moves. At this point White tried} 16. c3 $5 {in Lobzhanidze-De Jong, Groningen 2010, acquiring some mobile queenside passers and the upper hand after} O-O 17. cxb4 Bxb4 18. Rd1 Raa8 $6 ({this attempt to coordinate Black's pieces runs into a shot instead after} 18... Bd6 $1 {the position would have remained quite unclear: for instance,} 19. Qe4 Rb8 20. Bd2 Rh5 21. Bf4 $1 Bxf4 22. Qxf4 Rxb2 23. Qc1 Rb8 24. Qc7 Qd8 25. Rxd7 Qxc7 26. Rxc7 Ra5 {and the double-rook ending should be drawn}) 19. Bg5 $1 Qxg5 20. Qxb4 Rfb8 21. Qa3 d5 22. b4 Qe7 (22... Qf4 23. Rdb1 Rc8 24. b5 Rc2 25. Qe3 {keeps everything covered}) 23. Rdb1 d4 24. b5 {.}) ({b)} 9. Bf4 {was examined in Adhiban-Vachier Lagrave, World Junior Ch. , Puerto Madryn 2009, and White hasn't been too keen on this approach of late, largely it seems because of} b4 10. Ne2 Bc5 {.}) ({c)} 9. Be3 {develops a piece and rules out ...Bc5, but after} b4 10. Ne2 Nf6 {Black develops with tempo and} 11. f3 Qc7 12. Bf4 {gives him a few options, including the French-like} Qb6+ $5 13. Kh1 d5 14. e5 Nd7 {of Kiroski-Damljanovic, Struga 2011.}) 9... Bc5 ({Again Black often chooses to deploy his bishop to this active square here. I think it is best, although} 9... Ne7 {is an important alternative:} 10. Bd2 $5 ({a useful, semi-waiting move quite critical too is Ponomariov's} 10. Qh5 $5 Ng6 11. Bd2 {,}) ({but after} 10. Bg5 Qb8 11. a4 b4 12. Ne2 Ng6 13. Nd4 Qe5 $1 {White found his pieces under attack in Felgaer-Bachmann, Asuncion 2011, and could do no better than} 14. Nf3 Qxb2 15. Rb1 Qc3 16. Bd2 Qf6 17. Bg5 {, repeating moves}) 10... b4 ({this helps White to open the queenside, but} 10... Ng6 {was hardly optimal either, in view of} 11. a4 $1 b4 12. Nd5 {when White seizes the initiative}) 11. Ne2 Ng6 12. Nd4 Bb7 13. c3 $1 {and with the queenside opening, White was slightly for choice in Svetushkin-Meijers, Werther 2011.}) 10. e5 $5 {Bold. Again there are alternatives, including:} ({a)} 10. Be3 Bxe3 11. Rxe3 Ne7 $1 {seemed OK for Black in Tiviakov-Balogh, Croatian Team Championship 2009, as we've seen before.}) ({b)} 10. Qh5 {is quite an aggressive-looking move and has been played twice of late against one of the leading exponents of 6...Bb7, the Dutch IM Jan-Willem De Jong:} d6 11. e5 (11. Bg5 Nf6 12. Qh4 h6 ({maybe} 12... Bd4 $5 {, as it seems that Black can get away with} 13. a4 b4 14. Nd5 $5 Bxb2 15. Rab1 Be5 16. f4 Bd4+) 13. a4 bxa4 14. Nxa4 Bd4 15. c3 Be5 {and now in Baklan-De Jong, Groningen 2010,} (15... Ba7 {would have been safer}) 16. f4 $1 {would have been strong: for instance,} Rg8 17. fxe5 hxg5 18. Qxg5 dxe5 19. Nc5 {followed by b2-b4}) 11... Qb6 $2 ({now Black lands up a little weak on the dark squares as we've examined before, I'd prefer} 11... g6 {and if} 12. Qe2 {then} dxe5 13. Qxe5 Bd4 {keeps everything together}) 12. Be3 Bxe3 13. Rxe3 g6 14. Qg5 Qd8 15. Qf4 dxe5 16. Qxe5 Qf6 {and now White had a number of tempting continuations in Rietveld-De Jong, Groningen 2011, including the game's} 17. Qc7 {.}) 10... Qb6 ({New, but although this comes with tempo, again I'm not totally convinced and would prefer to keep the queen in touch with the kingside. After} 10... f5 11. Qh5+ g6 12. Qh3 Kf7 13. Ne2 h5 $1 14. Be3 Qb6 {(only now - to keep control of d4)} 15. Nf4 {(risky)} g5 $1 16. Nxe6 $1 (16. Nxh5 Ne7 {leaves White horrendously pinned}) 16... dxe6 17. Bxf5 Rh6 18. Bxe6+ Rxe6 19. Qf5+ Ke7 (19... Nf6 $5 20. exf6 Bxe3 21. Qh7+ Kxf6 22. Qh6+ Ke7 23. Rxe3 Rxe3 24. Qxg5+ Kd6 25. fxe3 {gives White three pawns for the piece, but perhaps Black can unravel and consolidate after} Re8) 20. Qh7+ Kf8 21. Qf5+ Ke7 22. Qh7+ {White gave perpetual in Pavlovic-Ivanisevic, Valjevo 2011.}) ({I also wondered about} 10... Qh4 $6 {, keeping White's queen out of g4 and h5, but} 11. Ne4 $1 Bxe4 12. Rxe4 Qxf2+ 13. Kh1 Ba7 14. a4 {was quite a dangerous gambit in Caspi-Kantsler, Israeli Team Championship 2010.}) 11. Qe2 ({This turns out well, although even after the simple} 11. Be3 {White has chances for a pull:} Bxe3 12. Rxe3 Ne7 13. Qh5 b4 (13... Nd5 14. Nxd5 Bxd5 15. Qh4 {leaves Black struggling to house his king}) 14. Ne4 Nf5 15. Ree1 {and while Black is very solid, White will remove the knight from f5 with a timely Ng3 or Qg5 and Nd6+.}) 11... f5 ({A standard idea in such positions. Instead after} 11... Ne7 12. Ne4 {White acquires the two bishops with a pleasant edge.}) 12. a4 b4 13. a5 $1 {Seizing space, fixing a6 and hoping to lure Black into the game continuation.} Bxf2+ $6 ({Inflicting structural damage, but Black will be rather vulnerable on the dark squares after this. Moreover, I'm not too sure why Ansell rejected the straightforward} 13... Qb7 14. Na4 Bxa4 15. Rxa4 Ne7 {. The weakness on a6 is a bit annoying and White may well have an edge, but he is yet to coordinate his forces and the black knight will take up a decent post on d5.}) 14. Qxf2 Qxf2+ 15. Kxf2 bxc3 16. bxc3 Ne7 17. c4 {Restricting Black's knight. This looks quite unpleasant for the second player, but Ansell fights back well.} Kf7 18. g3 h6 19. h4 g5 $1 {This doesn't equalise, but was the only way for Black to obtain any counterplay.} 20. hxg5 hxg5 21. Bxg5 Rh2+ 22. Ke3 Rg8 23. Bf4 Ng6 {After quite a logical passage of play Howell now finds an impressive way to keep on activating his pieces:} 24. Kd4 $1 {The king decides to remind Black of his dark-squared weaknesses and just watch the rest of its journey.} Nxf4 25. gxf4 Rh4 26. Rf1 Rb8 ({Good defence, whereas after} 26... Rgg4 $2 27. Kc5 Rxf4 28. Rxf4 Rxf4 29. Kb6 Rg4 30. Kxa6 {the a-pawn would have proved decisive.}) 27. Kc5 $5 Ke7 28. Rf2 Kd8 $2 ({Letting the king in. With both sides running low on time, I dare say Ansell was hoping to mate the errant white leader, but Howell has everything under control. Necessary was} 28... Rb2 {when it's not so clear how White improves his position - Kd4-c3 and Rg1 possibly.}) 29. Kd6 $1 Rc8 30. Rb1 Rh1 31. Rb6 $1 {An excellent post for the rook, eyeing the a-pawn while also helping to defend its monarch. Ansell now tries one last trick:} Be4 32. c5 Rb1 $5 33. Rxa6 $1 Bxd3 34. Rh2 $1 ({Sidestepping} 34. cxd3 $2 Rb4 {and now it's White who gets to sacrifice in style to force mate.}) 34... Bxa6 35. Rh8# 1-0


