1. e4 {Postny,Evgeny Postny,Evgeny Postny,Evgeny Postny,Evgeny: 'Postny'} c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 {Obviously, this scheme is not the way to fight for an opening advantage.} Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 (5... Qc7 6. Ne2 Bg4 7. f3 Bh5 8. Nf4 Nf6 9. Nxh5 Nxh5 10. O-O e6 {is another reliable continuation for Black.}) 6. Bf4 {Covering the important diagonal.} Bg4 {Black should take out the bishop before continuing the development with e7-e6.} 7. Qb3 Qc8 8. Nd2 e6 9. Ngf3 Be7 10. Kf1 $2 $146 {Really? Well, if I were following the game transmitted live on playchess.com server, I would have thought that White in fact played 10.0-0, while 10.f1 is just a mouse slip by someone relaying the game. However, before continuing to be harsh and putting a glaring question mark to the move in the text, let's think what could be White's ideas behind 10.f1? White assumes that the king is safe enough on f1, while the rook on h1 will support the advance of White's h- and maybe also g-pawn. This is how he is going to attack Black's king's residence. Sounds too good to be true? Yes, it is, and the continuation of the game proved it. A standard play would include, obviously, castling followed by f3-e5 at some point. Here is one recent example:} (10. Ne5 Bh5 11. Qc2 Nd7 12. O-O Ndxe5 13. Bxe5 Nxe5 14. dxe5 Bg6 15. Qa4+ Kf8 16. Bxg6 hxg6 17. Nf3 a6 18. Qf4 Qc7 19. Rac1 Rc8 20. b3 b5 21. a4 Kg8 22. axb5 axb5 23. Qe3 Kh7 $11 {0-1 Benjamin,J (2583)-Kamsky,G (2720)/Saint Louis 2009/CBM 130 (50)}) (10. O-O O-O 11. Rfe1 Bh5 12. Ne5 Nxe5 13. Bxe5 Bg6 14. Bxg6 hxg6 {is equal and has appeared in quite a number of games as well.}) 10... Bh5 {The bishop is going to g6. Naturally, the exchange of light-squared bishops favours Black.} 11. Re1 a6 {Preparing the standard plan of a pawn minority attack on the queenside.} 12. Qc2 (12. a4 {would stop Black from playing b7-b5, but not for very long. After the exchange of light-squared bishops Black would prepare b7-b5 advance by a8-b8.}) 12... b5 13. b4 $5 {This is an interesting way to hold Black's play on the queenside. The c3 is hopelessly weak, but it won't be easy for Black to attack it.} (13. h3 Bg6 14. Bxg6 hxg6 15. Qd3 O-O $15 {followed by b5-b4 at the right moment.}) 13... Bg6 14. Bxg6 hxg6 {[%csl Rc2][%cal Gc6b4,Gc8c2]} 15. Qd3 a5 16. a3 (16. Qxb5 $2 axb4 17. Ne5 Qa6 {leads to a total collapse for White.}) 16... axb4 17. axb4 Qb7 18. Nb3 O-O 19. h4 ({If White tries to cover the e4-square by} 19. Nfd2 $6 {, then Black can break through the centre by} Nh5 $1 20. Be3 e5 21. dxe5 Nxe5 22. Qe2 Rfe8 $17 {White's uncastled king is the main factor in the position.}) 19... Ne4 20. Nfd2 Ra3 21. Rb1 (21. Nxe4 dxe4 (21... Rxb3 $6 22. Qc2 Ra3 23. Bc1 Ra1 24. Nc5 Bxc5 25. dxc5 Rfa8 26. h5 R8a2 27. Qd3 {is exactly what White is striving for.}) 22. Qc2 f5 23. Nc5 Bxc5 24. dxc5 Rfa8 $15) 21... Rfa8 22. Kg1 (22. Nxe4 $6 dxe4 23. Qxe4 $2 {[%tqu "En","Can you spot the right move?","","","a3b3","",10]} Rxb3 $1 24. Rxb3 {[%tqu "En","And now?","","","c6d4","",10]} Nxd4 $3 25. Qxd4 (25. Qxb7 Ra1+ {is mate. Very neat tactics!}) 25... Ra1+ 26. Ke2 Rxh1 27. g3 Bf6 28. Be5 Qa8 $1 $19 {[%cal Ga8a2]}) 22... Nd8 $1 {A good manouevre. The knight is doing nothing on c6.} 23. Rh3 $1 {White didn't succeed with his kingside assault, but, at least, managed to develop all his pieces.} Qc6 {[%cal Gd8b7,Gb7d6]} 24. Na5 {Principled, but makes Black's play easier.} (24. Nxe4 dxe4 25. Qe3 Qd5 26. Nd2 (26. Nc5 Bxc5 27. bxc5 Nc6 28. Rxb5 Ra1+ 29. Kh2 Rf1 $36 {[%csl Rf2,Rh2][%cal Ga8a1,Ga8a2]}) 26... f5 27. Qg3 Kf7 28. h5 gxh5 29. Rxh5 Nc6 30. Rh7 Bf6 31. Bg5 Rxc3 $1 32. Qxc3 Bxg5 $17) 24... R8xa5 $1 {Of course!} (24... Qxc3 $2 {would fall into} 25. Qf1 $1 {[%cal Gh3a3]}) 25. bxa5 Nxc3 26. Rb3 (26. Re1 b4 27. Nb1 Rxa5 28. Nxc3 Qxc3 29. Qxc3 bxc3 30. Rxc3 Bb4 $17) 26... Ra1+ 27. Nb1 b4 28. Bd2 Na2 29. Re3 $2 {The decisive mistake.} (29. Rb2 $1 {would still keep White pretty much in the game. For instance:} Qa4 30. a6 Nc6 31. Kh2 Bd6+ (31... Bf6 32. Rc2 $1 $13) 32. f4 Nb8 33. h5 Qxa6 34. hxg6 Qxd3 35. gxf7+ Kxf7 36. Rxd3 Nc6 $15) 29... Nc1 $1 30. Bxc1 Qxc1+ 31. Kh2 Nc6 32. g3 {In time-trouble definitely missing that a5 is hanging, but the position is lost anyhow.} Nxa5 {[%csl Rb3]} 0-1


