1. e4 {Rogozenco,D Rogozenko} c5 2. c3 Nf6 3. e5 Nd5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. d4 cxd4 6. cxd4 d6 7. Bc4 Nb6 8. Bb5 dxe5 9. Nxe5 Bd7 10. Nxd7 Qxd7 11. Nc3 e6 12. O-O Rd8 13. a4 Be7 14. a5 Nd5 15. a6 Ndb4 16. axb7 Qxb7 17. Qf3 $146 (17. Qb3 Rd7 18. Ra4 O-O 19. Bxc6 Nxc6 20. Qxb7 Rxb7 21. d5 Nb4 22. dxe6 fxe6 $11 {½-½ Nisipeanu,L (2690)-Fedorov,A (2617)/Fuegen 2006 (34)}) 17... O-O 18. Be3 a6 (18... Bf6 19. Rfd1 Rb8 20. Qe4 {(, Fedorov)}) 19. Ba4 Bf6 ({The correct way to force matters was} 19... Qb6 {at once. Now after} 20. d5 (20. Rfd1 $2 Nxd4 21. Qg4 Bc5 $17) 20... Nd4 21. Qe4 {Black has} (21. Bxd4 Qxd4 22. dxe6 fxe6 23. Qe2 Bc5 24. Qxe6+ Kh8 $44) 21... Bc5 {equalizing completely.}) 20. Rfd1 {White is marginally better thanks to his bishop pair, but with accurate play Black should slowly solve the problems.} Qb6 $2 {This provocative move is just bad for concrete reasons.} ({A possible way to attack pawn d4 and neutralize White's pressure on the long diagonal was} 20... Qa8 {[%csl Rd4] Then after} 21. Qg4 (21. Qe4 Ne7 22. Qg4 Nf5 $11) {Black can try the aggressive} 21... h5 (21... Ne7 22. Ne4 $36) 22. Qf4 (22. Qe4 Ne7 $11) (22. Qxh5 Nxd4 $14 {/=}) 22... Ne7 $5 23. Ne4 Nf5 24. Nxf6+ gxf6 $14 {[%cal Gg8h8,Yf8g8] /}) (20... Qc7 21. Qg4 $14) 21. d5 Nd4 22. Qe4 e5 23. f4 $1 $18 Nxd5 {Other moves lose material as well.} 24. Nxd5 Rxd5 25. Qxd5 Ne2+ 26. Kf2 Qxb2 27. Ra2 $1 Qxa2 28. Qxa2 Nc3 29. Qc4 exf4 30. Bxf4 Nxd1+ 31. Bxd1 1-0


