1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c3 Nf6 4. e5 Nd5 5. d4 cxd4 6. cxd4 d6 7. Bc4 Be7 8. O-O O-O {This is actually a tiny bit unusual. Usually Black plays ...Nc6 either on the seventh or eighth move (or even sometimes earlier). Most probably things will just transpose, although White has a couple of small options to mix things up after this move-order.} ({Relevant to the note below is the sideline} 8... Nc6 9. Nc3 $6 Nxc3 10. bxc3 dxe5 11. Nxe5 Nxe5 12. dxe5 Qxd1 13. Rxd1 Bd7 $1 {with a small edge for Black.}) 9. Re1 (9. Nc3 $5 {is interesting now because the endgame would surely favour White, and also because after} Nxc3 (9... dxe5 $1 10. Nxe5 Nc6 11. Nf3 $13) 10. bxc3 Qc7 11. Bd3 Qxc3 12. Rb1 $1 {White has outstanding compensation for the pawn.}) (9. Bxd5 exd5 10. Nc3 Be6 11. Qb3 {shows one difference of the knight still being on b8, but} Qd7 12. Bf4 Nc6 13. exd6 Bxd6 14. Bxd6 Qxd6 {is just equal anyway.}) 9... Nc6 10. a3 b6 ({[This is an important note - pay attention!] Kotronias recommends} 10... Bd7 {. These positions are theoretically sound for Black, which is why I guess he was happy with this recommendation. However, I tend to find White's position easier to play because of Black's cramped structure and particularly the somewhat awkward position of the queen's bishop. White, on the other hand, has the straightforward and common plan of pointing everything towards the kingside, starting with a battery along the b1-h7 diagonal. For example, continuing Kotronias' analysis:} 11. Qd3 (11. Bd2 Rc8 12. Nc3 dxe5 13. dxe5 Ncb4 $1 14. Nxd5 $1 $146 Nxd5 15. Bxd5 exd5 {Here Kotronias analyses both 16. Qb3 and 16.Nd4, and shows the route to equality for Black in both cases. I'd like to propose} 16. Bb4 $5 {mainly for its surprise value, and because Black has to be a little bit accurate to achieve a draw:} Bxb4 17. axb4 Qb6 18. Qxd5 Rc2 $3 19. Nd4 $1 Bc6 20. Qd6 Rxb2 21. b5 $1 Bxb5 22. Qxb6 axb6 23. Rab1 Rxb1 24. Rxb1 {and with a bit of care, Black should draw without too many problems.}) 11... Rc8 12. Bd2 {and here Kotronias suggests the following equalising sequence:} dxe5 $1 $146 13. dxe5 Be8 $1 14. Bb3 Nc7 $1 15. Qe4 Nb5 $1 16. Be3 Na5 17. Bc2 g6 18. Nbd2 Bc6 19. Qd3 Bxf3 20. Nxf3 Nc4 {and "=". While this is objectively correct and also a good piece of original analysis, I think White can still ask a few questions in the ensuing endgame. The key reason for this is that the b5 knight is really out of play and takes a little while to get back into gear. Let me show you my analysis.} 21. Qb3 $1 {is also interesting.} (21. Rad1 $5 Qxd3 22. Bxd3 Nxb2 $1 (22... Nxe3 23. fxe3 $1 {(Control of the central squares and keeping the rooks connected is worth the structural problems besides, Black is a long way off being able to seriously attack e5.)} Nc7 24. Be4 $1 $14) (22... Rfd8 23. Bxc4 Rxc4 24. Rxd8+ Bxd8 25. Rd1 Bb6 26. Bxb6 axb6 27. Kf1 $14) 23. Bxb5 Nxd1 24. Rxd1 a6 25. Be2 Bxa3 $132) (21. Bh6 $1 {is my proposal.} Qxd3 22. Bxd3 Rfd8 23. Bxc4 Rxc4 24. Rac1 Rxc1 25. Rxc1 Nc7 26. Kf1 Nd5 27. g3 $1 {is a strange-looking sort of endgame that regular 2.c3 players are likely to be familiar with. The knight on d5 is strong indeed, but it also blocks Black's rook, while White has solid control over the c-file. Meanwhile, Black's king can't yet enter the game, while an exchange of bishops would gift White the d6 and potentially f6 squares. So overall, the assessment should be a small (but manageable) advantage for White.}) 21... Nxe3 22. fxe3 $1 Qb6 23. Bd3 Nc7 24. Qxb6 axb6 25. Rac1 Nd5 26. Rxc8 Rxc8 27. Kf2 {with a slightly better (but most unusual!) endgame for White.}) 11. Qe2 (11. Bxd5 {is rare, but a little tricky to meet.} exd5 12. Nc3 dxe5 13. dxe5 d4 $1 14. Nb5 d3 $1 15. Bf4 $1 Bf5 16. Rc1 Rc8 17. Nd6 Bxd6 18. exd6 Qf6 {and this should be a draw.}) 11... dxe5 12. dxe5 Bb7 13. Bd2 (13. b4 $6 {doesn't feel right.} Rc8 14. Nbd2 $6 Nf4 15. Qe4 Nxg2 $1 16. Kxg2 Na5 $17 {0-1 (38) Zubarev, A (2588) -Moiseenko, A (2701) Lvov 2014}) 13... Bc5 $5 14. Nc3 ({Now that Black has vacated defence of the g5 square, I would be very tempted to set up a Greek Gift sacrifice on h7 with} 14. Bd3 $1 {In fact, this threat is so dangerous that Black needs to deal with it immediately:} f5 $1 (14... Rc8 $4 15. Bxh7+ Kxh7 16. Ng5+ Kg6 17. Qe4+ f5 18. exf6+ Kxf6 19. Qxe6#) 15. Nc3 Nxc3 16. Bxc3 Ne7 $1 17. b4 Nd5 18. Bd2 Be7 19. Bc4 {with a small edge to White.}) 14... Nxc3 15. Bxc3 Nd4 $1 {Forcing play, and logical given Black's thirteenth move.} 16. Nxd4 (16. Bxd4 Bxf3 17. Qxf3 Qxd4 $11) 16... Bxd4 17. Bxd4 Qxd4 18. Rad1 Qc5 $11 19. Ba6 Bxa6 20. Qxa6 g6 21. g3 Rfd8 22. Rxd8+ Rxd8 23. Qxa7 Rd2 24. Qa8+ Kg7 25. Qf3 Rxb2 26. h4 h5 27. Qf6+ Kg8 28. Qd8+ Qf8 29. Rd1 Qxd8 30. Rxd8+ Kg7 31. Rb8 1/2-1/2


