1. c4 {David Cummings} c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 6. g3 Qb6 7. Ndb5 Ne5 8. Bg2 a6 9. Na3 {David Cummings: '!?' David Cummings: 'Howell revives a gambit line which was played frequently by Gelfand and Agrest in the 2002-2004 period, but only seen sporadically since.'} (9. Qa4 {David Cummings} Rb8 10. Na3 Bxa3 11. Qxa3 Nxc4 12. Qb3 {is an alternative way of sacrificing the c-pawn which was explored in Matlakov-Rambaldi in the January 2016 Update}) 9... Bxa3 {David Cummings: 'Declining the pawn with'} (9... Be7 {David Cummings} 10. O-O d6 {gives White a comfortable position as Black needs to spend more unravelling in order to complete development.} 11. Qb3 Qc7 12. Bf4 O-O 13. Rfd1 Ng6 14. Be3 Nd7 15. Na4 Rb8 16. Ba7 Ra8 17. Qe3 {with a small edge for White, see Gelfand-Nisipeanu in the Archives}) 10. bxa3 Nxc4 11. O-O {David Cummings: 'After the immediate'} (11. Bg5 {David Cummings} Qd8 (11... d5 12. O-O O-O {transposes to the main game}) (11... h6 {was played in an earlier Gelfand game which continued} 12. Bxf6 gxf6 13. O-O Rb8 14. Rc1 Qd6 15. Qc2 b5 16. a4 Qe5 17. axb5 axb5 18. a4 {with some initiative for White, Gelfand, B (2704)-Van Wely, L (2681) Bled 2002 1/2-1/2  (47)}) 12. Rc1 d5 (12... O-O {is preferred by Gelfand}) 13. O-O Ne5 {was played in Gelfand, B (2709)-Macieja, B (2653) Bermuda 2004 1/2-1/2 (41), and now} 14. e4 $1 {would give White an advantage according to Gelfand}) 11... O-O {David Cummings: 'Black can also delay castling, for example'} (11... d5 {David Cummings} 12. Bg5 h6 (12... Bd7 13. e4 $5 (13. Rb1 {would be more normal, for example} Qc5 {or} (13... Qd8 14. Rc1 O-O 15. e4) 14. Rxb7 Rd8 15. Qc1 {and in both lines chances are roughly balanced}) (13. Bxf6 $6 gxf6 14. e4 d4 15. Rb1 Qc5 16. Rxb7 Rd8 {and White has gone astray, Thinius, M (2380)-Rapport, R (2444) Marianske Lazne 2010 0-1 (29)}) 13... Nxe4 14. Nxe4 dxe4 15. Rb1 Qc5 16. Rxb7 O-O 17. Qc1 Bb5 18. a4 Bxa4 19. Bxe4 Rac8 20. Be7 Qe5 21. Re1 Rfe8 22. Bxh7+ Kxh7 23. Rxe5 Nxe5 24. Rc7 {with an unusual endgame that was eventually drawn in Agrest-Ivanchuk, see the annotated game in the Archives}) 13. Bxf6 gxf6 14. e4 (14. Rc1 {keeping pressure on the c-file and c4-knight is a better approach}) 14... d4 15. Rb1 Qa7 {and Black was fine in Fier, A (2566)-L'Ami, E (2611) Dieren 2011 1/2-1/2  (82)}) 12. Bg5 d5 {David Cummings: 'transposes to the main game'} (12... Qd8 $6 {(David Cummings) walking into a pin, is worse, and after} 13. Ne4 d5 14. Nxf6+ gxf6 15. Bh6 Re8 16. e4 e5 17. Rc1 b5 18. exd5 f5 19. Qh5 Qd6 20. Rfd1 {White was on top in Adhiban, B (2555)-Prathamesh, S (2389) Dubai 2013 1-0 (61)}) 13. Rc1 Nxa3 $146 {David Cummings: 'The first new move. Black has also tried'} (13... Rd8 {- 86/(20)} 14. Bxf6 {David Cummings} (14. e4 $5 {(David Cummings) is a possible improvement for White here, for example} dxe4 15. Qb3 Qxb3 16. axb3 Na5 17. Nxe4 Nxb3 18. Rc2 {when the pin on f6 gives White annoying pressure, despite his temporary material deficit}) 14... gxf6 15. e4 d4 16. Na4 Qb5 17. Rxc4 Qxc4 18. Nb6 Qc5 19. Nxa8 Bd7 {this position has been reached in three games:} 20. e5 (20. Qg4+ Kf8 (20... Kh8 21. Qf4 Rxa8 22. Qxf6+ Kg8 23. e5 Bc6 {was balanced in Yevseev, D (2527)-Vakhlamov, I (2315) Voronezh 2011 1/2-1/2 (75)}) 21. Qf4 Rxa8 22. Qxf6 Rc8 23. e5 Bb5 {and the players agreed a draw in Agrest, E (2584)-Wedberg, T (2540) Skara 2002 1/2-1/2 (23)}) 20... Rxa8 $2 (20... fxe5 21. Qg4+ Kf8 22. Bxb7 Rb8 {is unclear}) 21. exf6 Kh8 22. Bxb7 Rg8 23. Qd2 Bb5 24. Re1 d3 25. Be4 Qg5 26. Qxg5 Rxg5 27. a4 {reaching a winning endgame for White, Reinderman, D (2587)-Flumbort, A (2540) Haarlem 2010 1-0 (35)}) (13... Bd7 $5 {(David Cummings) is an untried alternative}) 14. e4 {Diagram [#] Diagram } d4 $6 {David Cummings: 'After this White gets a strong initiative, instead'} (14... Nb5 $1 {David Cummings: 'getting the knight back into play, makes more sense. White has excellent compensation for the pawns after for example'} 15. Bxf6 gxf6 16. exd5 (16. Qh5 Nxc3 17. Rxc3 d4 (17... dxe4 $6 18. Bxe4 f5 19. Qg5+ Kh8 20. Qf6+ Kg8 21. g4 $1 Qd8 22. Qh6 f6 (22... fxe4 23. Rh3 Re8 24. Qxh7+ Kf8 25. Qh6+ Ke7 26. Qg5+ Kd6 27. Rd1+ $18) 23. gxf5 Rf7 24. Rd3 Qf8 25. Qd2 Bd7 26. Bxb7 (26. Rxd7 $2 Qg7+ $17) 26... Rb8 27. Bxa6 $16) 18. e5 (18. Rf3 Qb5 $1 (18... e5 $2 19. Qh6 $40 { g4}) 19. Qh6 Qg5 $17) 18... fxe5 19. Qg5+ Kh8 20. Qf6+ Kg8 21. Qg5+ Kh8 $11) (16. Qg4+ {David Cummings} Kh8 17. Qh4) 16... Nxc3 17. Rxc3 exd5 18. Qxd5 Be6 19. Qh5 $44) 15. e5 $1 Nd7 (15... dxc3 16. exf6 e5 {David Cummings: 'is more tenacious, but White still has great play after'} 17. fxg7 Re8 18. Rxc3 Nb5 19. Rc4 $36 (19. Re3 {(David Cummings) with the two bishops and ruined Black kingside pawns})) 16. Ne4 (16. Be7 {(David Cummings) is another strong move}) 16... Nxe5 $2 {Diagram [#] Diagram  David Cummings: 'Allowing a brilliant combination. Black had to try'} (16... Nb5 17. Be7 (17. a4 Nc3 18. Nxc3 dxc3 19. Be7 $16) 17... Re8 (17... Nxe5 18. Bxf8 Kxf8 19. a4 Na7 (19... Nc7 20. a5 $18) 20. Qh5 $18) 18. Nd6 Nxd6 19. Bxd6 $16) (16... Qb4 {(David Cummings) or}) 17. Nf6+ $1 $18 {David Cummings: '!!' David Cummings: 'Howell seizes his chance and plays the rest of the game perfectly'} gxf6 (17... Kh8 18. Qh5 h6 19. Bxh6 {David Cummings: 'with a quick checkmate in sight'} gxf6 20. Bxf8+ Kg8 21. Qh6 $18) 18. Bxf6 Ng6 {David Cummings: 'Other moves don't help either:'} (18... Qb5 19. Qh5 Qd3 20. Qxe5 $18 Qf5 {David Cummings} 21. Rc5 {in both cases with a winning attack}) (18... Nac4 {David Cummings} 19. Qh5 {or}) 19. Qh5 e5 {David Cummings: 'Black was relying on this move to attack the f6-bishop, but Howell has a deadly interference move available. Without this, White's attack would fail.'} 20. Rc6 $1 (20. Bc6 $1 $18 {David Cummings: 'is the only other move to win, a more abstract version of the same idea'}) 20... Qd8 (20... bxc6 21. Qh6 $18) 21. Qh6 {David Cummings: 'No mercy! White keeps the attack going at full force rather than capturing Black's queen.'} (21. Bxd8 Rxd8 22. Rcc1 $18) 21... Qxf6 22. Rxf6 Bg4 23. Bd5 {David Cummings: 'Another piece enters the attack, and now its over'} Be2 24. Rxg6+ hxg6 25. Qxg6+ Kh8 26. Qh6+ Kg8 27. Be4 {David Cummings: 'It is mate in four moves, for example'} f5 {David Cummings} 28. Bd5+ Rf7 29. Qg6+ Kh8 30. Bxf7 Bxf1 31. Qh6# {As David Howell demonstrated in this game, defending against White's initiative is a difficult task, particularly in a rapid game. I expect we will see more examples of this line going forward. 1-0 (31) Howell,D (2685)-Jumabayev,R (2607) Tallinn (rapid) 127/20 2016 CI1-130 [Tadic,Branko]} 1-0


