{After a rather slow start (2/3) I was back on board 1 (with 4/5) facing David Howell, leading the tournament with maximum points.} 1. d4 {Edouard,R Edouard,R} Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 {Ok, g3 has been played... I decide to try a Benoni!} c5 4. d5 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nc3 g6 7. Bg2 Bg7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. O-O Nbd7 (9... Re8 {is the main -and probably most clever- move order.}) 10. a4 b6 11. h3 Qe7 (11... Re8 {might be better: I thought} 12. Bf4 {was annoying, but after} (12. Nd2 $5) 12... Ne4 $1 (12... Ba6 $5) 13. Nxe4 Rxe4 14. Bxd6 Ba6 15. Re1 Bxb2 16. Ra2 Nf6 {it looks like Black is alright.}) 12. Re1 Ne4 $1 {It is important to exchange one pair of knights before White can go e4. Otherwise my position will be stifled.} 13. Nxe4 Qxe4 14. Bf4 Qe7 (14... Bxb2 $6 15. Bxd6 (15. Rb1 $5 Bc3 16. Bxd6 Re8 17. Nd2 Qd4 18. Bf4 Ba6 19. e4 $36) 15... Bxa1 16. Qxa1 Re8 17. Bf4 {seemed very dangerous for Black to me.}) 15. e4 Ne5 ({After} 15... Bxb2 16. Rb1 {I didn't like any of the following lines:} (16. e5 $2 Nxe5 17. Nxe5 dxe5 18. d6 Qf6 19. Bh6 Be6 $19) 16... Bg7 (16... Bc3 17. Re3 Be5 18. Nxe5 Nxe5 19. Bh6 Re8 {[%cal Yf7f6]} 20. f4 Nc4 21. Re1 $44) (16... Be5 17. Nxe5 dxe5 18. Bh6 Rd8 19. Bf1 $44) 17. e5 Nxe5 18. Nxe5 dxe5 19. d6 Qd8 20. Bxe5 Bxe5 21. Rxe5 $14 {However, this might just hold.}) 16. Nxe5 Bxe5 17. Qd2 Re8 (17... Bxf4 $5 18. Qxf4 f6 19. Qd2 Re8 {is given = by the computer. Indeed, Black is very solid. It's not easy to see how White will breakthrough.}) 18. Ra3 $6 {The start of a too optimistic and dubious plan.} (18. Bxe5 {was necessary, and I was aiming to play} dxe5 19. Bf1 Bd7 {and in my opinon, White has no advantage here, even though the computer disagrees due to the d5-passed pawn. I was thinking I would put my queen on d6 and then sooner or later play either ...a6-...b5 or ...f5. Maybe White is slightly better, but I believe it is rather easy to play for Black.}) 18... Bd7 19. b4 $6 {Once again too optimistic!} Bxf4 20. gxf4 Qf6 $1 21. Rb1 {An attack in the center would be kind of inneficient, so David tries to find counterplay on the other part of the board...} (21. bxc5 bxc5 22. Rf3 (22. Qe3 Rab8 23. e5 Qf5 24. Be4 Qh5 $17) 22... Rab8 23. e5 Qf5 $17) 21... cxb4 22. Rxb4 Rac8 23. a5 b5 24. a6 Rc4 $2 {A tempting move, especially when my opponent starts to lack time. However, this leaves White escape with some kind of draw!} (24... Rc5 $15 {/}) 25. Rxc4 {(=)} bxc4 26. Kh2 $2 {A bad square, as the f4-pawn will be hanging with check.} (26. Qb4 $1 {would equalize. A hard move to find in time trouble in my opinion!} Qxf4 (26... Rc8 $2 27. Qb7 Rc5 28. e5 $1 $18) 27. Rc3 $1 {and White escapes.} (27. Qxc4 $2 Rc8 $19)) 26... Bb5 $1 27. Ra5 $2 (27. Kg3 $1 {was the only way to justify 26.Kh2, and after} Rc8 28. Qc3 {White is not losing at once.}) 27... c3 28. Qe3 c2 $1 29. Rxb5 $2 (29. e5 Bd3 (29... Bd7 $5) 30. Ra3 dxe5 31. Rxd3 Rc8 32. fxe5 Qf5 $19) 29... Qa1 {And my c-pawn queens. A very important victory for me!} 0-1


