{England's newest 2700 has expanded his repertoire a lot since his younger GM days, in which the 2.c3 Sicilian was a more common guest in his games. Here he plays one of his old favourite variations that generally isn't supposed to be very dangerous, although both David and Tiviakov have used it with good effect in the past.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3 Nf6 4. e5 Nd5 5. d4 cxd4 6. cxd4 d6 7. Bc4 Nb6 8. Bb5 dxe5 9. Nxe5 Bd7 10. Nxd7 Qxd7 11. Nc3 e6 12. O-O Be7 ({I'm not sure why more people don't play} 12... Rd8 {here. I find it the most annoying move. Howell tried} 13. a4 ({I took a couple of quick draws with White in my match with Dominguez in the 2009 World Cup, e.g.} 13. Bg5 Be7 14. Bxe7 Qxe7 15. Qf3 O-O 16. Bxc6 bxc6 17. Qxc6 Rxd4 {1/2-1/2 (34) Smerdon, D (2525)-Dominguez Perez, L (2719) Khanty-Mansiysk 2009}) 13... Be7 (13... Nd5 $1 14. Qg4 Nf6 15. Qf3 $6 Be7 $15 {0-1 (35) Rabiega, R (2504)-Olszewski, M (2555) Germany 2015}) 14. a5 Nd5 15. a6 {and now 15...0-0 is probably just a draw. Instead,} Ndb4 16. axb7 Qxb7 17. Qf3 O-O 18. Be3 {was a very tiny bit better for White in Howell, D (2519)-Mikhalevski, V (2598) Ottawa 2007 (1-0, 31).}) 13. Qg4 O-O 14. Bxc6 bxc6 (14... Qxc6 {is okay, though usually Black is too scared to play it!} 15. Bh6 Bf6 16. Rfd1 Qd7 17. Ne4 Qe7 18. Rd3 Rfc8 $1 $11) 15. Bh6 Bf6 16. Rfd1 Kh8 {The most popular move.} (16... Rfd8 17. Ne4 Qe7 18. Rac1 Rac8 19. Rd3 $5 Rd5 20. Be3 {is a tiny bit better for White, and} Ra5 21. a3 Rb5 22. b4 a5 23. Bd2 a4 $6 24. Be3 Rd5 25. Qf3 $16 {was much better for White in a recent GM clash. 1-0 (53) Naroditsky, D (2587)-Oparin, G (2546) Riga 2014}) 17. Ne4 Rg8 (17... Qd8 $1 {feels pretty equal to me.} 18. Bg5 (18. Nxf6 $5 Qxf6 19. Bf4 {keeps a bit more life in the position.}) 18... Bxg5 19. Nxg5 h6 20. Nf3 Qd5 $11 {1/2-1/2 (24) Godena, M (2516)-Alterman, B (2584) Israel 2013}) 18. Bg5 Nd5 (18... Bxg5 19. Nxg5 h6 20. Rac1 $14) 19. Rd3 Bxg5 20. Nxg5 Nf6 $2 {Up until now, Simon has played well. But this is a gross error.} (20... h6 21. Qe4 Nf6 22. Qe2 $5 Rgd8 $1 $11 (22... hxg5 $4 23. Rh3+ Nh7 24. Rxh7+ Kxh7 25. Qh5#)) 21. Rh3 $2 ({The ending after} 21. Qh4 $1 h6 22. Rf3 $1 Qe7 23. Ne4 Nd5 24. Qxe7 Nxe7 25. Rxf7 Nf5 26. Nc5 Nxd4 27. Rd7 Rgd8 28. Rd1 $16 {is very pleasant for White.}) 21... h6 (21... Qe7 22. Qf4 Rgb8 $1 $13) 22. Qf4 Rgf8 $4 {A second, and this time fatal, mistake.} (22... Qe7 $1 23. Ne4 $1 Rgd8 (23... Nxe4 $4 24. Rxh6+ gxh6 25. Qxh6#) 24. Nxf6 Qxf6 25. Qxf6 gxf6 26. Rxh6+ Kg7 27. Rh4 a5 $1 {with very good drawing chances.}) 23. Rxh6+ $3 {Ripping open the black kingside.} gxh6 24. Qxf6+ Kg8 25. Re1 $3 Qd5 (25... hxg5 26. Qxg5+ Kh8 27. Qf6+ Kg8 28. Re3 $18) 26. Qxh6 Qf5 27. Ne4 {A very nice attacking game by David, although I'm still not convinced that Black's task to achieve equality is all that difficult.} 1-0


