{I find this game to be really instructive. The Hippopotamus setup is one which has never been refuted, but I've always thought it looks particularly dubious where White has not committed a pawn to c4. Here David Howell gives a model demonstration of play against this structure, obtaining a strategically winning King's Indian position before Black completes his development.} 1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nf3 d6 4. Bc4 a6 5. O-O e6 6. a4 {A new move for this site. The position after Black's 6th move has already been covered in games annotated by Paul Motwani and Neil McDonald (both games were won by Black, indicating the practical advantages of Black's apparently passive setup). 6. a4 is thematic. The move isn't so much aimed against ...b5 (which is a standard method of gaining counterplay in the Pirc, but in combination with ... e6 and Black's delayed development would leave Black with serious positional questions to answer after a standard a4-break), but rather seizes more space and has a huge positional threat in a5, after which Black can't properly settle his queenside pawns - he will have a weakness on b7 (and a passive light squared bishop) if he does nothing, while he will have a weak pawn  (after ...b5 axb6) or a weak square (after ...c5) on b6 if he touches his queenside pawns.} b6 {The standard response - now a5 can be met by ...b5. White has then already used one of his queenside breaks, but as Howell shows, there is another one...} 7. d5 $1 {A counter-intuitive move, closing the position while Black is chronically underdeveloped. In fact this is a classic transformation of an advantage - Howell trades a lead in development for a better structure. Black had previously scored pretty well here, but Howell's move (and plan) is an important theoretical contribution.} (7. Re1 h6 8. Nbd2 Nd7 9. c3 Ne7 10. Nf1 Bb7 11. Bb3 c5 12. dxc5 Nxc5 13. Bc2 Rc8 {was A.Vargas - O.Almeida Quintana, Ocana 2015 (0-1 in 23). This is one of Black's dream scenarios in these structures - White has suddenly been tricked into an unconvincing setup against the Sicilian.}) (7. Bg5 Ne7 8. Nc3 h6 9. Be3 Nd7 10. Qe2 Bb7 11. Rad1 O-O 12. Rfe1 Qe8 {with a normal, balanced Hippo in N.Meskovs -T.Petersen, Aarhus 2015 (0-1 in 62), a game Black won despite a 100 rating point disadvantage.}) (7. b3 Bb7 8. Re1 Nf6 9. Nbd2 O-O 10. Bb2 d5 11. Bd3 dxe4 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Bxe4 Bxe4 14. Rxe4 c5 15. Qe2 Nd7 16. Rd1 Qc7 {and Black had equalised in A.Mokshanov - A.Tukhaev, Samara 2012 (0-1 in 41).}) (7. Nc3 Ne7 8. Re1 Bb7 9. Ba2 Nd7 10. Bf4 h6 11. h4 Nf6 12. Qe2 O-O {led to standard Hippo play in K.Rathnakaran - Z.Rahman, New Delhi 2009 (1-0 in 67). White's position looks impressive but Black is solid and flexible.}) 7... e5 {Effectively forced, since Black can't allow the position to open while he is underdeveloped with his king stuck in the centre.} 8. a5 b5 {Again forced, unless Black is willing to concede a weakness on the queenside.} 9. Bd3 Nf6 {Black would prefer to achieve ...f5 before this move, but it's not really feasible.} ({The immediate} 9... f5 $2 {runs into the standard} 10. exf5 gxf5 11. Ng5 $16 {with mayhem on the light squares.}) ({Hence} 9... h6 {would be a standard move, preparing ...f5 without allowing the white knight into g5 and e6. However, White can continue as in the game with} 10. c4 bxc4 11. Bxc4 Ne7 ({The immediate} 11... f5 12. exf5 gxf5 {is hard to believe with so little development, though I haven't found a clear refutation.}) 12. Nc3 O-O 13. b4 {when his queenside play looks more convincing than Black's kingside play. If Black is going for a King's Indian type position, however, perhaps he should have preferred this version.}) 10. c4 $1 {Breaking open the queenside. Something seems to have gone wrong with Black's position already.} bxc4 ({Playing in Breyer style with} 10... c6 {leaves White with strong pressure after} 11. Bg5 O-O 12. Nc3 $14 {. Black will be left with weaknesses after any reasonable resolution of the tension in the centre and on the queenside.}) 11. Qa4+ Bd7 $2 {Initiating an unfavourable exchange - Black needs his light-squared bishop to support his kingside aspirations.} ({As Gormally points out in his entertaining notes on www.gingergm.com, he should have changed the structure with} 11... c6 $1 12. Bxc4 (12. dxc6 $4 cxd3 13. c7+ Qd7 14. cxb8=Q Rxb8 $17 {doesn't work at all}) 12... Bd7 13. Qb4 cxd5 14. exd5 Bf5 $14 {White still has a pull here, but Black's position is preferable to the game.}) 12. Qxc4 Bb5 13. Qc2 Bxd3 14. Qxd3 O-O 15. Bg5 $1 {A move which greatly impressed Gormally. White doesn't need his dark-squared bishop and offers a trade to get his queenside attack rolling.} Nbd7 16. b4 h6 17. Bxf6 $1 Nxf6 18. Nbd2 {As in the King's Indian, Black is strategically lost on the queenside and needs to look to the kingside for counterplay. However, this isn't so easy to do, since the position is quite simplified and Black hasn't even started rolling with ...f5, while his queenside structure is in ruins.} Nh5 19. g3 f5 20. Rfc1 Qd7 21. Rc6 fxe4 $2 {Releasing the tension while looking for tactics which turn out not to work.} ({Howell's suggestion} 21... Qf7 $1 {is a tougher defence, though my computer doesn't believe in Black's attack after} 22. Nh4 Bf6 23. Ng2 $16) 22. Nxe4 Qg4 23. Nfd2 $18 {Black can't land any shots.} Nf4 24. Qc4 Rf7 25. f3 Nh3+ 26. Kg2 Rxf3 {I'm unsure whether the game ended here (as suggested by my version) or continued for a couple of moves. In any event, impressive stuff from Howell, and quite a dangerous plan against the provocative Hippo.} ({The game score given by Gormally continues} 26... Rxf3 27. Nxf3 ({There was nothing wrong with collecting the queen with} 27. Nf6+) 27... Nf4+ 28. Kf2 Rf8 {and Black resigned}) 1-0


