1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 c5 3. d5 ({The critical choice, but} 3. e3 {also remains a popular enough choice. One recent game which caught my eye saw} cxd4 (3... Qb6 4. Nc3 Qxb2 5. Nb5 Nd5 6. Rb1 Qxa2 7. Ra1 Qb2 8. Rb1 {has been a common drawing method, which surely everyone is now aware of}) 4. exd4 d5 5. Nf3 Nc6 6. Nbd2 g6 7. Bb5 $1 {(revealing the downside to Black's slightly slow approach)} Bg7 8. Ne5 Bd7 9. Nxd7 Qxd7 10. c3 {, which was surely a small edge for White with the two bishops in Tristan-Golubev, Internet (blitz) 2021. It quickly grew:} a6 11. Bd3 O-O 12. O-O Nh5 $5 13. Bg5 e5 14. dxe5 Nxe5 15. Be2 {and now the knight had to retreat, since} Qf5 $4 16. f4 {forced resignation, with g2-g4 also a threat.}) 3... b5 $5 {A Benko-like and fairly critical option, especially if Black is in a creative mood.} ({We've seen a fair bit of the solid} 3... d6 4. Nc3 e5 {,}) ({while Howell has also faced the Schmid Benoni,} 3... g6 4. Nc3 Bg7 5. e4 d6 {, of late, as did even Sergey Karjakin on a rare London outing for him:} 6. a4 ({David preferred} 6. h3 O-O 7. Nf3 {, but this is a little slow and} b5 $1 8. Nxb5 $2 Nxe4 9. c3 {already left White in some trouble in Howell-Weetik, Internet (blitz) 2021, when} Qb6 {would have been quite awkward to meet,}) ({so White should either play a la Karjakin or go} 6. Nf3 O-O 7. a4 $1) ({or even} 6. Bd3 $5 O-O 7. Nf3 {, as we considered back in Grischuk-Gelfand, Tal Memorial Blitz, Sochi 2014 - see the Archive}) 6... O-O 7. Be2 (7. Nf3 Qb6 $5 8. Ra3 $1 {works because} Nxe4 $2 9. Nxe4 Qb4+ {is rebuffed by} 10. Nfd2) 7... Qb6 $1 {(a new idea and not such an easy one for White to meet)} 8. Ra3 $2 (8. Rb1 $2 {also runs into} Nxe4 $1) ({and} 8. Qc1 Nxe4 $1 9. Nxe4 Bxb2 10. a5 $1 Bxc1 11. axb6 Bxf4 12. Rxa7 Bf5 13. Rxa8 Bxe4 {should give Black enough for the exchange, but White should either opt for this forcing line}) ({or} 8. Bb5 $5 {followed by a4-a5}) 8... Nxe4 $1 9. Nxe4 Qb4+ {(a tactic familiar to Trompowsky players, but clearly not the former world championship challenger)} 10. Qd2 Qxe4 11. Nf3 Bf5 12. Nh4 Qxc2 13. Nxf5 Qxf5 {simply left White two pawns down in Karjakin-So, New in Chess Classic (rapid) 2021.}) 4. f3 $5 {Preparing to advance in the centre with e2-e4. White can also react on the queenside, as we've considered before.} Bb7 ({Going for Blumenfeld-like play, but I would prefer} 4... g6 5. e4 Bg7) ({or even} 4... Nh5 $5 {, coverage of which can again be found in the Archive.}) 5. e4 e6 $6 ({This just doesn't seem to work and as} 5... b4 6. Nd2 {would merely give White a fine square on c4,}) (5... c4 $5 {must be the critical line:} 6. Nc3 $1 (6. a4 e6 7. dxe6 fxe6 8. axb5 d5 {certainly offers some compensation}) 6... e6 $5 7. Nxb5 Qa5+ 8. Nc3 exd5 9. Bd2 $1 {when White is better, but at least the position is quite messy.}) 6. dxe6 fxe6 7. Bxb5 $1 {And why not? There just isn't any ...Qa5+ Nc3 Nxe4 tactic to worry about with e4 so secure.} Nc6 8. Ne2 (8. Nc3 $5 {with the idea of} d5 $6 9. exd5 exd5 10. Qe2+ {and 0-0-0 was also tempting, but it's hard to find fault with David's sensible decision to whisk his king to safety on the kingside.}) 8... d5 9. exd5 exd5 10. O-O {Black does have the centre, but d5 can be targeted and there surely isn't anything like enough for a pawn here.} Bd6 (10... Be7 $5 11. Nbc3 O-O {was likely a better try, and if} 12. Bg5 $6 d4 {.}) 11. Bg5 $6 (11. Nbc3 $1 {would just have been pretty strong, and if} d4 12. Bxd6 Qxd6 13. Ng3 $1 {.}) 11... O-O 12. Nbc3 (12. Bxf6 $5 Qxf6 13. Qxd5+ Kh8 14. Nbc3 {is preferred by the fearless engines, but feels rather risky to the human eye.}) 12... d4 $2 ({This only serves to create weaknesses, whereas Black would actually have enjoyed fairly decent compensation after} 12... Ne7 $1 {when the bishop on b5 is a little loose and ...Qb8 very much an idea, as well as ...d4.}) 13. Ne4 Ne5 (13... Be7 14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. Nf4 {also quickly begins to look quite unpleasant for Black.}) 14. Bxf6 {Simple chess, harvesting positional trumps.} gxf6 15. Nxd6 Qxd6 16. Ng3 Kh8 17. Qd2 Qb6 {The American FM finds the only real plan, namely to try and roll the central pawns.} 18. Be2 (18. Bd3 $1 c4 19. Bf5 {would have retained a clear plus, and if} d3+ 20. Qf2 {.}) 18... Rad8 $2 ({Now White clamps down.} 18... c4 $1 19. Kh1 d3 20. cxd3 cxd3 21. Bd1 {is still somewhat better for White, but at least Black has one big trump and is very much on the board after} Bd5 22. Rc1 Rad8 {.}) 19. b3 $1 d3 $1 {This doesn't really help matters, but what else to try, not least at blitz and with White otherwise set to begin to take over after f3-f4?} 20. cxd3 c4+ (20... Nxd3 21. Bxd3 c4+ 22. Qf2 cxd3 23. Rad1 {would also leave White in full control of the position.}) 21. d4 $1 {Unfortunately for Solon, David finds the refutation of Black's play.} Rxd4 22. Qe3 {Very calm and very strong. White now threatens Nf5, as well as just bxc4.} Re8 23. Kh1 cxb3 24. axb3 {Black is only one pawn down, but his shattered kingside is likely to be targeted sooner or later now that White's own king is quite safe. Solon collapses quickly.} Bc6 $6 25. Ra6 $1 Qc5 $2 ({Even after} 25... Qd8 26. Qh6 {followed by Nh5 Black surely wouldn't have survived, and if} Nf7 27. Qc1 Bb7 28. Rxa7 {. Do observe how all the time White's position is quite secure, thanks to that mighty knight and fine pawn on f3.}) 26. Rxc6 $1 {Black is losing a piece or a rook.} 1-0


