1. c4 {Moradiabadi,E} c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 6. Bf4 d5 7. e3 Bc5 8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. Be2 O-O 10. O-O Bd6 11. Bxd6 Qxd6 12. Qa4 a5 13. Rac1 Ba6 14. Rc2 Rfb8 15. b3 {This game is an example of a GM's draw offer. The Black player, a much lower-rated IM, faces a strong British GM but thanks to his deep calculation and solid play he gets the upper hand after:} Rb4 $1 16. Qxa5 (16. Qa3 dxc4 17. bxc4 Qe5 18. Rd1 h5 19. h3 {is slightly better than Howell's choice.}) 16... Bb7 17. c5 Qxh2+ $1 {Howell, may have missed this.} 18. Kxh2 Rxa5 {Now Black has a greatly superior pawn structure and White's pawn on c5 is a great target.} 19. Na4 Ba6 $1 {Another strategically sensible move. Black gets rid of his bad bishop.} 20. Bxa6 Rxa6 21. Kg1 Kf8 22. f3 Ke7 23. Kf2 Nd7 24. Ke2 Ra5 25. Kd2 $1 {The exclamation mark is for Howell's draw offer. It was going to be a long session of suffering for White as Black could comfortably play h5-g6-e5-f5 and keep improving his position while all White could do was to stall. Howell, offered a draw before things got nastier. A wise decision on his part and not a very good one from his opponent's side, who showed more respect to his opponent than to his position.} (25. Kd2 h5 26. Rh1 g6 27. Kc3 Rb7 28. Kd2 e5 29. g3 Ke6 30. Rhc1 f5 {and a very bad position for White.}) 1/2-1/2


