1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Nc6 4. O-O Bd7 5. Re1 Nf6 6. c3 a6 7. Bc4 $5 {A fresh and dynamic approach, advocated and analysed by GMs Smerdon and Van Kampen.} Bg4 8. d4 cxd4 ({David's compatriot Gawain Jones faced} 8... e6 {en route to a memorable 1st place in the Dubai Open 2016. See G. Jones - B. Savchenko, Dubai Open 2016 (1-0 in 37) in the Archives.}) 9. cxd4 Rc8 (9... e5 {was played in D.Smerdon - J.Hall, Daventry 2014 (1-0 in 54), analysed by Dave in the Archives.}) ({Unsurprisingly, White's bishop pair and central control after} 9... Bxf3 10. gxf3 e6 11. d5 $1 {outweigh any academic considerations about his kingside structure.} Ne5 ({The} 11... Na5 {of L.Lasic - I.Kinez, Velika Gorica 2007 (0-1 in 63) is comfortably met by} 12. Bf1 $16) 12. Bb3 exd5 $6 13. f4 $16 {and Black was struggling to get out of the opening in R.Mamedov - V.Belous, Minsk 2015 (1-0 in 44).}) (9... e6 10. Nc3 Be7 {was tried in M. Podoba - A.Nikolova, Split 2012 (0-1 in 43). Here I think White should go for a pleasant position facing no counterplay after} 11. d5 Ne5 12. Be2 Nxf3+ 13. Bxf3 Bxf3 14. Qxf3 $14) 10. Be3 (10. Be2 {is also possible, but after} d5 (10... Nxe4 $4 11. d5 $1 $18 {and Black has too many hanging minor pieces}) 11. exd5 Nxd5 {Black has good chances to reach a decent IQP position.}) 10... e6 (10... Nxe4 {is obviously dangerous, but not easy to refute.} 11. Qb3 {regains the pawn immediately, when the following forcing sequence seems logical:} e6 12. Qxb7 Na5 ({Perhaps} 12... Be7 $5 {is best, when Black gets interesting compensation after} 13. Bxa6 Rc7 14. Qb3 O-O $44) 13. Qxe4 Bxf3 14. Qxf3 Nxc4 15. Nd2 {Black's a6-pawn is weak and he needs to complete development, but after something like} Nxe3 16. Qxe3 Be7 17. d5 e5 18. Rac1 O-O {he seems to have equalised.}) 11. d5 (11. Nc3 {allows the typical shot} Nxe4 12. Nxe4 d5 {, with equality.}) 11... exd5 ({Keeping the e-file closed with} 11... Ne5 {looks like a safer continuation, with good chances to equalise after} 12. Be2 Bxf3 13. Bxf3 Be7) 12. Bxd5 (12. exd5 {is riskier. After} Bxf3 13. gxf3 Ne5 14. Bf1 Be7 15. f4 Ned7 16. Nc3 O-O {the position is hard to judge. White has more space and the bishop pair but a weakened kingside, while Black has no weaknesses but is quite passive. This seems to be dynamically balanced.}) 12... Nxd5 (12... Be7 13. Nc3 $14 {looks very comfortable for White.}) 13. exd5 Ne5 14. Bd4 Bxf3 {Going for a very creative solution, but this doesn't appear to fully equalise.} (14... Be7 $1 {seems to equalise. Taking the pawn with} 15. Bxe5 dxe5 16. Rxe5 {is ill-advised in view of} Bxf3 17. gxf3 O-O {followed by . ..Bd6 with outstanding compensation.}) 15. Qxf3 Rc1 $5 {A great shot!} ({Again} 15... Be7 {is sounder, although} 16. Qb3 O-O 17. Nd2 {leaves Black facing some pressure.}) 16. Qe3 Rxe1+ 17. Qxe1 Qg5 ({Perhaps Black should consider the sacrifice} 17... Be7 $5 18. Bxe5 dxe5 19. Qxe5 O-O {This isn't easy to win for White.}) 18. Nc3 {Tempting, but perhaps not the best.} (18. Bxe5 dxe5 (18... Qxe5 19. Qb4 $16) 19. Qc3 Bd6 20. Qc8+ Qd8 21. Qxb7 Qc7 {Black has drawing chances but White plays for two results with an extra pawn.}) 18... Be7 19. Qe2 Qf4 (19... O-O 20. Re1 $14 {also leaves Black with some problems to solve.}) 20. Rd1 h5 21. a4 (21. h3 {prevents ...Qg4 and retains an edge.}) 21... Qg4 $1 22. f3 Qf4 {The minor disruption caused by f3 has helped Black.} 23. Qf2 O-O 24. Ne2 {Of course the position can be played on, but it's about equal now and maybe David was regretting not making more of such a promising position. Nonetheless, I think the notes indicate some interesting attempts to equalise.} 1/2-1/2


