{Thanks to IM Richard Pert for submitting these annotations to this recent British Championship encounter. As usual with a guest annotation any comments of my own will be prefixed by 'CHRIS:'.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 Nc6 8. Qd2 O-O 9. O-O-O d5 10. exd5 Nxd5 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Bd4 Nxc3 $5 {Chris and Gawain have mentioned this line a few times on the site so I thought that I would try it out against David as he would almost certainly have prepared hard for me.} ({CHRIS: Gawain's annotations are (as always) brilliant this month but it is interesting that he seems to ignore the following (from the same event):} 12... Bxd4 13. Qxd4 Qb6 14. Na4 Qa5 15. b3 Be6 16. Bc4 Rfd8 17. Qc5 Qc7 18. Kb1 Nf4 19. g3 Bxc4 20. Qxc4 Nd5 21. Rhe1 Nb6 22. Qe4 Nxa4 23. Qxa4 e6 24. Qe4 Rd5 25. c4 Rd7 26. Rxd7 Qxd7 27. Kc2 Rd8 28. Qe2 e5 29. Rd1 Qxd1+ 30. Qxd1 Rxd1 31. Kxd1 c5 32. a3 a5 33. b4 cxb4 34. axb4 axb4 35. c5 Kf8 36. Kc2 Ke7 37. Kb3 Kd7 38. Kxb4 Kc6 39. Kc4 h6 40. f4 e4 41. Kd4 f5 42. Kc4 e3 {1/2-1/2 Adams, M (2715)-Jones, G (2606) Sheffield ENG 2011. Credit to Gawain for this as it is a convincing draw against the eventual winner but I guess the point is that any followers of our site will note that nothing is especially new. Well 17 Qc5 instead of 17 Qe5 but Gawain isn't troubled by this and the conclusion is that his previous work on this site put him in good stead even against one of the World's top players.}) 13. Qxc3 Bh6+ 14. Be3 Bxe3+ 15. Qxe3 Qb6 16. Qxe7 Be6 17. Qa3 Rad8 18. Bd3 Rd5 19. Rhe1 $5 (19. b3 {This must be considered the main line here but white is struggling to prove any advantage here recently. Chris and Gawain have annotated various games in this variation.}) 19... Rfd8 $6 {This is a new move which previously on the site Gawain had mentioned may be an interesting new attempt (although he also stressed that he knew of nothing wrong with the main line). Blacks goal is to make a position where neither side can progress and hence achieve a draw, however it didn't go to plan in this game although perhaps I could have played differently.} (19... Ra5 {After this game we have learnt this move is not only the main line but also Blacks best.} 20. Qc3 Rxa2 21. b3 Ra5 {Chris and Gawain have annotated various games in this line and I recommend Black sticks to it in order to keep this variation alive. CHRIS: Richard is right that 19...Ra5 is the main line (I can't even see where Gawain mentions 19...Rfd8) but the sad truth is that that nearly always leads to a draw. Typically Dragon players like to win!}) 20. Qc3 c5 $1 {Must be the right way to follow up} (20... Rd4 $6 {Looks a bit wet} 21. Re5 R4d5 22. h4 Rxe5 23. Qxe5 Rd5 24. Qf4 Rd4 25. Qf6 Rd5 26. Qf4 {What is white doing taking a draw here? 26. g4, b3 or even h5 offer white an edge here.} Rd4 27. Qf6 Rd5 28. Qf4 {1/2-1/2 Friedel, J (2531)-Sedlak, N (2580)/Amsterdam NED 2011/The Week in Chess 871}) 21. Re5 $1 {A lot of calculation must have gone into this move as Black has several responses.} (21. Bf1 Rd4 {Gawain points out here that he is not sure how either side can progress.} 22. Rxd4 cxd4 23. Qa3 Qc7 24. g3 Bf5 25. Bd3 (25. Qa4 d3 26. Re8+ Rxe8 27. Qxe8+ Kg7 28. c3 Qc5 {also gives Black easily enough play for the pawn deficit.}) 25... Bxd3 26. Qxd3 Qa5 27. Re4 Qxa2 28. Rxd4 Qa1+ 29. Kd2 Rf8 30. b3 Qg1 31. Kc3 Qa1+ 32. Kd2 Qg1 33. Kc3 {1/2-1/2 Megaranto, S (2527)-Li Chao2 (2613)/Olongapo City PHI 2010}) 21... Rxe5 (21... c4 $5 {The other critical move and perhaps blacks Best} 22. Rxd5 (22. Be2 $2 Rxd1+ 23. Bxd1 Qg1 24. Qe1 Qxg2 25. Rxe6 {Leads to perpetual check}) 22... Rxd5 23. Qxc4 (23. Bxc4 $2 Rxd1+ 24. Kxd1 Qg1+ 25. Kd2 Qxg2+ $15) 23... Qe3+ (23... Ra5 24. Qc3 Qe3+ 25. Qd2 $14 (25. Kb1 Bxa2+ 26. Ka1 Ra4 27. Bb5 $14) 25... Qe5 $1 26. Qb4 (26. a3 $2 Rxa3 27. bxa3 $4 Qa1#) 26... Qe3+ 27. Kb1 Bxa2+ 28. Ka1 Qg5 29. f4 Qd8 30. g3 $14) 24. Kb1 Rg5 (24... Ra5 25. Qc7 (25. Qc3 Bxa2+ 26. Ka1 Ra4 27. Bb5 $14) 25... Bxa2+ 26. Ka1 Qg5 27. f4 Qh5 28. Re1 Bc4+ 29. Kb1 {And white is a pawn up for not a huge amount of compensation.}) 25. Qe4 Qxe4 26. Bxe4 Rxg2 27. h4 $14 {Whites c-pawn looks dangerous.}) 22. Qxe5 Bxa2 (22... Rd5 23. Qe3 $14 (23. Qc3 c4 {transposes to our previous note})) 23. b3 {I believe both players played accurately for the next few moves.} Bxb3 24. cxb3 Qxb3 25. Bc2 Qa3+ 26. Kb1 Qb4+ 27. Qb2 Rxd1+ 28. Bxd1 Qe1 29. Kc2 Qf2+ 30. Kc1 Qe3+ 31. Qd2 Qe5 32. f4 Qa1+ 33. Kc2 Qa4+ $2 {Losing the thread - I completely missed Kb2 here and was expecting Kd3 after which Black has good drawing chances} (33... Qa2+ 34. Kd3 c4+ 35. Ke2 Qa1 $14 {And white still has work to do to get the point.}) 34. Kb2 $1 {Its nearly all over now.} (34. Kd3 Qd4+ 35. Ke2 Qg1 36. Qd5 Qxh2 37. Kf3 $14) 34... Qe4 (34... Qc6 {Is a better try but its looking bad.}) 35. Bf3 Qf5 36. Qd8+ Kg7 37. Qd6 Qc8 38. Kc3 h6 39. Bd5 Qg4 40. Qc7 Qf5 41. Qe5+ Qf6 42. h4 g5 43. Qxf6+ Kxf6 44. fxg5+ hxg5 45. hxg5+ Kxg5 46. Kc4 f5 47. Kxc5 {In conclusion it looks as if black should stick to 19... Ra5 although it has to be said David played very accurately this game and I think White has to play this well to win these kinds of positions. If anyone is brave enough to try this variation again then I suggest they give 21...c4!? a whirl.} 1-0


