{The British championships was a strange tournament this year, because it lacked drama. Why? you may ask, well because David Howell dominated from start to finish and nobody else really got a look in. Which was kind of the story of my game against him as well...} 1. c4 $1 {David showed in this tournament that he's not just a one-trick pony, throwing in some quieter openings with White as opposed to just wheeling out his normal e4 repertoire.} Nf6 (1... e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. g3 g6 5. d4 exd4 6. Nxd4 Bg7 7. Nxc6 dxc6 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. e4 Bg4 10. Be2 Bxe2 11. Kxe2 Re8 12. f3 Nd7 13. Bg5+ Kc8 14. Rac1 a5 15. Rhd1 a4 {Black had a firm foothold in this ending that has many similarities with the Berlin Defence. Kramnik went on to record a fine victory in the game Gulko, B  (2595)-Kramnik, V (2715) Novgorod 1995 In fact this encounter, which is included in Kramnik's collection of best games, may have been at least part of the reason why he started playing the Berlin in the first place. Why though am I showing this game? Well the real truth will only be revealed later!}) 2. Nc3 g6 3. e4 {David of course, being a Grunfeld player himself, has had to face these kind of Anti-Grunfeld move orders many times. However it does give Black an additional option, which I chose in the game.} e5 $5 (3... d6 {Would transpose into the Kings-Indian. Mark Hebden, a Kings Indian Aficionado, asked me afterwards why I didn't do this. I explained that David had some experience in the Samisch and I couldn't remember any theory in that line. But given that I was a point behind at this stage, and really needed a win, the dynamism of that opening would surely have been a good choice. I'm increasingly coming around to the viewpoint that if you want to reach a higher level you need to have good knowledge of ALL openings.}) 4. Nf3 Nc6 {The drawback of putting the knight here, is that it is quite inflexible on c6.} ({I had recently prepared the line} 4... Bg7 {for another game, and don't know why I didn't just do this, as at least I might have had some idea of what I was doing. Admittedly this line doesn't have a great theoretical reputation, but I think this might be undeserved.} 5. Nxe5 Nxe4 (5... Qe7 $6 {Is considered inferior, and for good reason. After} 6. d4 d6 7. Nf3 Nxe4 8. Nd5 Qd8 9. Bd3 $1 {White already has a nice edge.} O-O 10. Bxe4 $6 ({The simple} 10. O-O $1 Re8 11. Re1 {was a very good alternative} Nf6 12. Rxe8+ Nxe8 13. Bg5 {Is awkward for Black}) 10... Re8 11. Nc3 {Black regained the piece with ..f5 but later lost in the game Gelfand, B (2713)-De la Villa Garcia, J (2473) Pamplona 1999}) 6. Nxe4 Bxe5 7. d4 $1 (7. g3 $5 {Was an interesting alternative used by Epishin to score a quick win.} Qe7 ({The computer likes} 7... d5 $1 {here and slightly prefers Black after} 8. cxd5 Qxd5 9. Bg2 Qd4 $15) 8. d4 Bg7 9. Bg2 f5 10. Bg5 Qe6 11. O-O fxe4 12. Bxe4 c6 13. d5 Qe5 14. Bxg6+ hxg6 15. Re1 {1-0 Epishin, V (2590)-David, A (2525)/ Montpellier 199800}) 7... Bg7 8. Bg5 f6 9. Be3 O-O 10. Nc3 Nc6 {Was the choice of Lev Aronian, but this may be slightly inaccurate due to the fact that White can put the bishop on a more active square, d3, immediately} (10... d6 $5 11. Be2 (11. Bd3 f5 $1 {Is the reason why Black should wait until White commits the bishop}) 11... Nc6 12. d5 Ne7 13. O-O Nf5 14. Bf4 Re8 {I think is a slightly improved version of the Timman-Aronian game as the bishop is slightly more passive on e2.}) 11. d5 $1 Ne7 12. Bd3 $1 d6 13. O-O Nf5 14. Bf4 Nh6 (14... Re8 $5) 15. Rc1 f5 16. Qd2 Nf7 17. Be3 Bd7 18. f4 Re8 19. Bf2 {This kind of passive position is not much fun for Black and probably part of the reason why most players have given up on this line. White later won in Timman, J  (2650)-Aronian, L (2518) Las Vegas 1999}) 5. d4 exd4 6. Nxd4 Bg7 7. Nc2 ({Let me explain why I included that Kramnik game earlier. I simply confused my theory and believed that we had the same position as the Gulko game, forgetting that White had played g3 there, not e4. Shows how bad my memory is these days. I also played the line against Miles when the pawn really was on g3 (that was in the days when my memory was quite decent) So I thought, ok, he can take on c6 here} 7. Nxc6 {but then I can take back with the d-pawn and get this Kramnik ending! In fact this is probably playable for Black too after} dxc6 (7... bxc6 8. e5 Qe7 9. Qe2 {I didn't fancy much, as the knight has to crawl back to g8}) 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Bf4 Re8 10. f3 Be6 11. Be2 Nd7 12. Rc1 Bd4 $6 {Ended in a win for White in the game Christiansen, L (2560)-Rahls, P (2230) Germany 1994} (12... Ne5 $1 13. b3 f5 {is probably better when Black is doing fine. Actually David plays the Berlin himself so he probably realised this ending wasn't too bad for Black. By playing Nc2 White is going for a Maroczy bind- a very dangerous situation for me, as I have scant experience in such positions. In fact the other game I lost with Black in this same tournament, the game went in a very similar fashion- I was unable to break out of the bind there either.})) 7... O-O 8. Be2 Re8 $6 {After the game I believed this to be a mistake- it probably is, as I force f3, a move that White wants to play in any case. But the serious mistakes came later. Nevertheless when you are playing 2650s, every little mistake is magnified- you have to really fight for the initiative right from the start, as you know if they start to get on top it's going to be a long afternoon.} ({..Re8 is certainly inferior if I want to play another plan I thought of in the game-} 8... d6 $1 9. O-O Nd7 10. Be3 Nc5 11. f3 {White has to waste a move on this anyway, as Black was threatening to win the pawn on e4 starting with ..Bxc3} f5 $1 12. exf5 Bxf5 13. Qd2 {And now both} Bxc2 ({Or the simple} 13... Re8) 14. Qxc2 Bd4 {give Black a fine game.}) 9. f3 d6 10. O-O Ne5 {Played with the intention of playing ..c6 and ..d5, the typical way of breaking out of the Maroczy bind, but in this particular situation it doesn't really work, as on e5 the knight will always run into an annoying f4 move at some stage. If the knight was still on b8, I could play .. c6 here straight away. This is why having committed the knight to c6 I really should have spent more time trying to work out other ways of breaking out of the bind. If I just shuffle around with the pieces it's very bad of course- White will just build up slowly and break through eventually. So I need to do something radical- either sac a pawn or a piece- just do something. There comes a time in a chess game where you have crossed the Rubicon and there's no going back-perhaps I had already reached it?} ({It only now started to dawn on me, that my original plan of trying to liberate my position with ..f5, was a lot worse due to the inclusion of the moves ..Re8 and f3} 10... Nd7 11. Be3 Nc5 12. Qd2 f5 {And now White has an extra move so he play the annoying} 13. Bg5 $5 {for example. Ho-hum.} (13. b4 $1 {is perhaps even stronger-} Ne6 14. exf5 {and I have to take back with the pawn- in any case all this shows is how lazy this ..Re8 move was.})) ({However I only very briefly considered the idea of} 10... Nh5 {which was suggested in the bulletin. I stopped after} 11. g4 {Thinking the knight would have to retreat, not even seeing} ({Of course the draw is hardly forced and} 11. Nd5 {Is eminently playable, for example}) 11... Be5 $1 12. gxh5 Bxh2+ $1 {With a perpetual after} 13. Kxh2 Qh4+ 14. Kg1 Qg3+ 15. Kh1 Qh3+ $11 {Again, this is why it helps to be experienced or to study all sorts of different openings- if I had more knowledge of the Kings Indian, I would probably have found this idea.}) 11. Be3 c6 12. Qe1 $1 {A very strong prophylactic move, found after much thought.} Qe7 $6 (12... Qc7 {was probably better}) (12... d5 13. cxd5 cxd5 14. Rd1 {Was the idea behind White's last move- the pin on the d-file is very strong.}) 13. Rd1 a6 14. Qd2 Be6 15. b3 b5 $2 ({Things were getting so desperate that I even considered saccing an exchange for nothing here with} 15... Rad8 16. Bb6 d5 {I recalled some old games of Kasparov, against Karpov and Gelfand and in particular, where he sacced an exchange to grab the dark squares. However I lacked the balls to do it. I wish I had, as at least I would have gone down in flames rather than been ground down, like what happened in the game. But in truth after} 17. f4 $1 Neg4 18. e5 Nd7 19. Bxd8 Rxd8 20. cxd5 cxd5 21. h3 Qc5+ 22. Nd4 Nh6 23. g4 {Black is just busted.}) ({Passive defence with} 15... Bf8 {was probably the only way to stay on the board, but I really didn't like my chances after} 16. Bg5 $1) 16. cxb5 axb5 {Losing a pawn, but the other re-capture was no bed of roses either.} (16... cxb5 17. Nb4 $1 {Looked horrible.} (17. Qxd6 $2 Qxd6 18. Rxd6 Rec8 19. Bd2 Bf8 20. Rd4 Bc5 {drops the exchange}) 17... Rec8 18. Nbd5 Nxd5 19. Nxd5 Bxd5 20. Qxd5 {Just looks a dream position for White.}) 17. Qxd6 Qxd6 18. Rxd6 Bf8 19. Rd2 $1 b4 20. Na4 Nc4 (20... Rxa4 21. bxa4 Bxa2 22. Nxb4 $1) 21. Bxc4 Bxc4 22. Rc1 Bb5 23. Nd4 Bxa4 24. bxa4 Nxe4 {Desperation.} (24... Rxa4 25. Rxc6 {a pawn down in the endgame with a bad position, really didn't appeal.}) 25. fxe4 Rxe4 26. Kf2 $1 {The most accurate, as any sac on e3 just leads to a technically winning ending with Rook and knight against rook, which is what happened in the game.} Rxa4 ({After the game he suggested I should have played} 26... c5 {and he's probably right. But after} 27. Nf3 $1 c4 28. Ng5 {it looks curtains in any case.}) 27. Rxc6 Rxe3 28. Kxe3 Bh6+ 29. Kd3 Bxd2 30. Kxd2 Rxa2+ 31. Rc2 Rxc2+ ({I could have kept the rook on here with something like} 31... Ra4 {but it would have changed nothing- White will eventually round up the b-pawn, and then breakthrough on the kingside.}) 32. Nxc2 b3 33. Nd4 b2 34. Kc2 Kg7 35. Kxb2 Kf6 36. Kc3 Ke5 37. Kd3 f5 38. Nf3+ Kf4 39. Ke2 g5 40. Kf2 Kg4 41. Ke3 Kh5 42. Ne5 Kh4 43. Kf3 h5 {A little joke in a hopeless situation. Besides by this point I was tired of getting outplayed, and wanted to go down the pub.} 44. Ng6# 1-0


