1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Bg4 3. Bg2 Nd7 4. h3 Bh5 {Retaining the bishop is the most common choice here, although the capture has also been seen.} (4... Bxf3 5. Bxf3 Ngf6 6. d3 c6 7. Nd2 g6 $5 (7... e5 {is the main move}) 8. e4 {is analyzed in Morozevich-Kasimdzhanov in the Archives}) 5. O-O c6 6. d3 Ngf6 7. Qe1 e5 8. e4 {An important tabiya in Capablanca's system against the Reti.} Bd6 {Black maintains a flexible pawn centre. This is a slightly provocative choice that leads to more double-edge positions than the mainline:} (8... dxe4 9. dxe4 Bc5 {which usually leads to a manoeuvring game with a fixed pawn structure - see Kramnik-Vachier Lagrave in the Archives.}) 9. exd5 {We have also looked at:} (9. Nh4 O-O 10. g4 Bg6 11. g5 Nh5 12. exd5 cxd5 13. Nxg6 hxg6 14. Bxd5 Nf4 {which is a sharp line covered in Maghsoodloo-Sjugirov in the Archives}) 9... Nxd5 {An earlier game of Howell's saw:} (9... Bxf3 {looks like a slight concession, now} 10. Bxf3 Nxd5 11. Nc3 Nxc3 {Howell,D (2682)-Vitiugov,N (2732) Caleta 2018 1/2-1/2 (75), and now} 12. Qxc3 O-O {gives White the two bishops, with no pawn weaknesses in a fairly open position, which should slightly favour him.}) 10. Nxe5 $5 {White goes for the principled continuation. Otherwise:} (10. Nc3 O-O {is solid for Black}) 10... Nxe5 11. d4 O-O 12. dxe5 Re8 13. f4 f6 {Black will get his pawn back. but the resulting position is unbalanced and hard to assess.} 14. Nd2 {The first new move. An earlier game featured:} (14. Nc3 fxe5 15. f5 Nxc3 16. Qxc3 e4 {with chances for both sides, Berkes,F (2648)-Swapnil,S (2534) Moscow 2017 1-0 (30)}) 14... fxe5 15. f5 {As in the Berkes game above, White gets a kingside majority that is countered by Black's passed e-pawn.} e4 $5 {Black avoids the blockade on the e4-square and opens the position further.} 16. Nxe4 {White has to calculate the consequences of the self-pin, since:} (16. g4 Bc5+ 17. Kh1 e3 {favours Black}) 16... Nf6 17. Bg5 Qb6+ 18. Be3 {The only move, leading to an interesting material imbalance. Here:} (18. Kh2 $2 Nxe4 19. Bxe4 Qd4 {and Black wins material}) 18... Rxe4 19. Bxe4 Bc5 20. Bxc5 Qxc5+ 21. Qf2 {Again forced, since:} (21. Kg2 Re8 {gives Black a more favourable version.} 22. Qf2 Qxf2+ 23. Rxf2 Nxe4 24. Rf4 Bf7 {and Black activates his bishop via the d5-square}) 21... Qxf2+ 22. Rxf2 Nxe4 {Black has two minor pieces for rook and pawn. Given the extra pair of rooks on the board, the chances are approximately balanced.} 23. Rf4 {An important nuance, as Black isn't able to stabilize his pieces as in the previous note.} Ng5 {Or:} (23... Re8 24. g4 Bf7 (24... Ng5 {transposes to the game}) 25. Re1 {forces the trade of rooks}) (23... Nxg3 {is an attempt to achieve greater clarity. Now} 24. Kf2 Ne2 25. Rh4 g6 26. Rxh5 gxh5 27. Kxe2 {and Black should hold this rook endgame.}) 24. Kh2 Re8 25. g4 Re2+ 26. Kg3 Be8 27. h4 Nf7 28. Rd1 {Going for activity rather defending than the c2-pawn.} h6 {Black goes for a solid setup. Alternatively:} (28... Rxc2 {can be met by} 29. Rb4 b6 30. Re4 Kf8 31. g5 {with some pressure}) 29. Rf2 Re7 $6 {Black starts to go too passive. Here:} (29... Re4 {keeps White occupied by eyeing the kingside pawns.}) 30. Rd4 (30. Rff1 $1 {leads to a position similar to the game. White will follow up with Rf1-e1 when Black cannot avoid the rook trade.}) 30... c5 31. Rdd2 Bc6 $2 {Allowing a trade of rooks swings the evaluation dramatically in White's favour. Here:} (31... Bb5 $1 {keeping an active rook on the board, maintains the balance.}) 32. Rfe2 Kf8 {Now:} (32... Rc7 {doesn't help because White gets his kingside pawns rolling after} 33. Kf4 Kf8 34. g5 {and White is well on top}) 33. Kf4 Rxe2 34. Rxe2 Nd6 {The minor pieces really benefited from an accompanying rook. Now Black is faced with an unpleasant defensive task.} 35. c3 (35. g5 {looks more natural}) 35... Kf7 36. g5 hxg5+ 37. hxg5 Bd7 $2 {Allowing a tactical finish. Instead:} (37... Kf8 38. Rh2 {is clearly better for White, who can press for a long time.}) 38. g6+ Kf6 39. Rd2 Ke7 40. f6+ $1 {This is the point. The breakthrough wins material.} gxf6 41. g7 Be6 42. Re2 {White wins the bishop and retains his g7-pawn after} (42. Re2 Kf7 43. Rxe6 Nb5 44. Re7+ {etc.}) 1-0


