1. Nf3 c5 2. c4 Nf6 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. g3 e5 {In this game, Smith goes for a rare setup that we haven't seen on ChessPublishing before. Black secures space in the centre (at the cost of leaving a hole on the d5-square) and then develops his dark-squared bishop on the e7-square. In the Symmetrical English, Black more often fianchettos with 4...g6 or plays on the light squares with 4...d5 or 4...e6.} 5. Bg2 d6 {Black has also played:} (5... g6 6. O-O Bg7 {although in this Botvinnik-style setup, the g8-knight is more naturally placed on the e7-square. One example continued} 7. d3 O-O 8. a3 d6 9. Rb1 a5 10. Ne1 Be6 11. Bg5 Qd7 12. Nc2 Rab8 13. b4 b6 14. bxc5 bxc5 15. Ne3 {with a small edge for White due to his grip on the light squares, Cvek,R (2518)-Brodowski,P (2436) Czechia 2011 1-0 (29)}) 6. d3 {White continues in typical "English" fashion, playing for control of the light squares coupled with queenside expansion. Black's setup is solid but a little passive. As there is no established theory here, and no really forcing variations, I've included a number of game extracts to illustrate the typical ideas. Here White can also castle immediately:} (6. O-O Be7 {and now:} 7. e3 {is a different approach, occupying the centre right away, for example} (7. d3 {with two high-level examples:} O-O (7... h6 8. Ne1 O-O 9. Nc2 Be6 10. Ne3 Qd7 11. Ned5 Bh3 12. f4 $5 (12. a3 {is more typical}) 12... Bxg2 13. Kxg2 exf4 14. Bxf4 Nxd5 15. cxd5 Nd4 16. a4 Bg5 {and Black has decent counterplay, Fridman,D (2653)-Efimenko,Z (2695) Plovdiv 2012 1/2-1/2 (41)}) 8. a3 h6 9. Ne1 Rb8 10. b4 cxb4 11. axb4 Nxb4 12. Rxa7 d5 13. cxd5 Bc5 14. Ra1 Bd4 15. Ra3 Nbxd5 16. Nxd5 Nxd5 17. e3 Bc5 {with balanced chances, Giri,A (2722)-Polgar,J (2701) Hoogeveen 2011 1-0 (47)}) (7. a3 O-O 8. Rb1 h6 9. b4 e4 10. Ne1 Bf5 (10... d5 $5) 11. d3 exd3 12. Nxd3 Rb8 13. Bf4 g5 14. Be3 Ne5 15. bxc5 Nxd3 16. exd3 dxc5 17. Nd5 Nxd5 18. Bxd5 {and White's powerfully placed d5-bishop gives him the edge, Socko,B (2588) -Bartel,M (2360) Poland 2018 1-0 (30)}) 7... O-O 8. d4 cxd4 9. exd4 Bg4 10. Ne2 e4 11. Nd2 $2 (11. Ng5 {is called for}) 11... Nxd4 12. f3 exf3 13. Nxf3 Nxf3+ 14. Bxf3 Bxf3 15. Rxf3 Rc8 {and Black is a clean pawn up, Ruck,R (2561)-Saric, I (2652) Tallinn 2016 0-1 (33)}) 6... Be7 {Black eschews the move ...h7-h6 that see in several of the notes. Instead:} (6... h6 7. a3 {and now:} Be6 (7... Be7 8. Nd2 O-O 9. Nf1 Nh7 $5 (9... Be6 10. Ne3 Qd7 {is more solid}) 10. Ne3 Bg5 11. Ned5 Bxc1 12. Rxc1 Nf6 13. Nxf6+ Qxf6 14. O-O Qd8 15. e3 {with good play for White on the light squares, Delchev,A (2625)-Pantev,V (2396) Bankia 2011 1-0 (40)}) 8. b4 $1 cxb4 9. axb4 Nxb4 {was played in Donchenko,A (2575) -Maisuradze,N (2302) Nancy 2016 1/2-1/2 (19), and now} 10. Qb3 a5 11. O-O Be7 12. Ba3 {gives White an edge with ideal Benko-style queenside play.}) 7. Bg5 {White takes the chance to go for this thematic move.} Ng8 {Black pushes the bishop back at the cost of a tempo. Practice has also seen:} (7... O-O 8. O-O Be6 9. a3 h6 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. Ne1 {In this case, this typical re-routing appears to be a little slow.} (11. Nd2 Qd7 12. Nd5 {looks pleasant for White}) 11... g6 12. Nc2 Bg7 13. Rb1 f5 14. b4 Qd7 15. Ne3 e4 16. Ned5 exd3 17. Qxd3 cxb4 18. Nb5 {was the course of Kramnik,V (2710)-Chandler,M (2565) Germany 1994 1-0 (32), and now} Ne5 {for example, would give Black sufficient counterplay.}) (7... Ng4 8. Bxe7 Nxe7 9. a3 O-O 10. O-O Nc6 11. b4 (11. Rb1 a5 12. h3 Nf6 13. e3 {looks a bit better for White}) 11... cxb4 12. Nd5 bxa3 13. Qb3 Nf6 14. Rxa3 {and here White's compensation is more questionable, Gross,S  (2349)-Sax,G (2511) Balatonlelle 2003 0-1 (38)}) 8. Bd2 Nf6 9. Bg5 Ng8 10. Bd2 Nf6 11. O-O O-O 12. a3 h6 {So Black plays this after all, but compared to Delchev-Pantev (see note to Black's 6th move), he is a tempo down, since White has inserted the extra move Bc1-d2. Here:} (12... a5 13. Rb1 h6 14. Ne1 Be6 15. Nd5 a4 $5 16. Nc3 d5 17. cxd5 Nxd5 18. Nxa4 {was seen in Shchekachev,A (2531) -Bogdanovich,S (2590) Berlin (blitz) 2015 0-1 (107). Black has perhaps some compensation for the pawn.}) 13. Ne1 Be6 14. Nd5 Qd7 15. b4 Bd8 {This move looks a little clumsy. Black wants to trade light-squared bishops with ... Be6-h3 but this likely isn't the best plan in any case. Instead:} (15... Rac8 {keeping things tight at the back, leaves White with a tougher nut to crack.}) 16. Bc3 Bh3 $6 {There is some logic in trading White's powerful g2-bishop, but after this exchange, White has permission to close the long diagonal with e2-e4 and play for the kingside pawn storm that we see in the game. Instead:} (16... cxb4 17. axb4 Bxd5 18. cxd5 Nd4 {is one line that makes more sense of Black's setup. White may be slightly better, but nothing too serious.}) 17. Nxf6+ {White can also start with:} (17. b5 Nd4 (17... Ne7 $6 {is now weak because of} 18. Nxf6+ {ruining Black's pawn structure.}) 18. Nxf6+ Bxf6 19. e3 Bxg2 20. Nxg2 Ne6 21. f4 {with a nice initiative for White.}) 17... Bxf6 18. b5 Ne7 19. e4 Bxg2 {This speeds up White's kingside play.} (19... a6 20. a4 axb5 21. axb5 Ng6 {maintaining the tension, is a better way to go.}) 20. Nxg2 a6 21. a4 axb5 22. axb5 Rxa1 23. Qxa1 Ng6 24. f4 {If you picture White's position as a kind of reversed King's Indian, it is an ideal version, since his kingside pawn roller is on its way, and Black so far has no counterplay.} Re8 25. f5 Ne7 26. h4 Nc8 27. Qd1 {Giving Black a momentary chance to make a bid for freedom.} Kh7 $6 (27... d5 $1 {is a big improvement, for example} 28. cxd5 (28. exd5 Qd8 29. Qa1 Nd6 30. Ne3 e4 {and Black is fighting.}) 28... Qxb5 {and Black is a crucial tempo up on the game continuation. Now it is not so easy for White to push through g3-g4-g5 quickly.}) 28. Bd2 {White could also play:} (28. g4 Rh8 29. Qf3 {maintaining the clamp.}) 28... d5 {The right idea, but a move too late. Still this is Black's best chance, since without it he was just going to get rolled over.} 29. cxd5 {This is better than:} (29. exd5 $6 Nd6 30. g4 e4 {and Black has counterplay}) 29... Qxb5 30. Qf3 Qb2 (30... c4 {can be met by} 31. g4 c3 32. Bc1 Be7 33. g5 {and White is on top.}) 31. Be3 {Howell puts on a powerful display over the next 10 moves to bring home the full point.} Qc3 32. g4 $1 {White can afford to give up the d3-pawn since his attack comes quickly.} Qxd3 33. g5 Nd6 {Giving up a piece, but:} (33... Bd8 {is met by} 34. g6+ Kg8 35. gxf7+ Kxf7 36. Qh5+ Kf8 37. f6 {and Black's position collapses}) 34. gxf6 Qxe4 35. Qh5 Rg8 36. Rf2 Nc4 37. Bc1 Qxd5 38. fxg7 Rxg7 39. Bxh6 e4 40. Bxg7+ Kg8 41. Qh8# 1-0


