1. c4 e6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 Nf6 4. b3 Be7 (4... c5 5. Bb2 Nc6 6. cxd5 exd5 7. Bb5 Bd6 8. O-O O-O 9. d4 cxd4 10. Nxd4 {I hadn't covered this position before, so I should mention the way for Black to equalise:} Qb6 $1 11. Be2 ({A worthy submission for the brilliancy prize is the line} 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Bd3 Ng4 13. h3 Nxe3 14. Bxh7+ Kxh7 15. Qh5+ Kg8 16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. Qg5+ $11 {and perpetual check.}) 11... Be5 12. Bf3 Re8 13. Na3 $6 {Too creative.} (13. Qd2 $142 $11) 13... Nxd4 (13... Bf5 $5 {and ...Be4 might even give Black an edge.}) 14. Bxd4 Bxd4 15. Qxd4 Qxd4 16. exd4 Bd7 $11 17. Nc2 Ne4 18. Rfe1 a5 19. Ne3 Bc6 20. Rac1 Kf8 21. Rc2 Rad8 22. Rec1 Ng5 23. Be2 Ne6 24. Rd1 g6 25. g3 f5 26. Kf1 Kg7 27. Ng2 g5 28. Ne1 g4 29. Ng2 h5 30. f3 Rd7 31. Nh4 Rf7 32. f4 Kf6 33. Kf2 Rfe7 34. Rcd2 Nxd4 35. Bf1 Ne6 36. Bd3 Ng7 37. Bf1 Ne6 38. Bd3 Nd4 39. Bf1 Nb5 40. Nxf5 Kxf5 41. Bxb5 Kf6 42. Bf1 Re3 43. Rd3 R3e7 44. R3d2 Re3 45. Rd3 {1/2-1/2  (45) So,W (2770)-Giri,A (2782) Leuven 2016}) 5. Bb2 O-O 6. Nc3 c5 7. cxd5 exd5 8. d4 Nc6 9. Be2 Bg4 (9... cxd4 10. Nxd4 {Now the machine wants to play ...Bc5 here which isn't a great sign for Black's position.} Bc5 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. O-O Bd6 13. Rc1 Bf5 14. Na4 Rc8 15. Nc5 {Equal, but easier to play White, e.g.} Qe7 16. Bd4 Ne4 17. Bd3 {and White is ready to play b4 to fix the Black queenside pawns.}) (9... Ne4 $5 10. O-O Be6 11. dxc5 Bxc5 12. Rc1 Nxc3 13. Bxc3 $14 {White has some pressure in this position, later he can play for b4-b5 or more simply exchange some more minor pieces with Nd4.} (13. Rxc3 $14)) 10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. O-O $14 {I haven't found a way for Black to equalise.} Rc8 (11... a6 12. h3 $1 Bh5 (12... Be6 $142 13. Bd3 h6 14. Ne2 $14) 13. Nh4 $5 {This is a useful theme to know, that we trade off their light-squared bishop in this manner. That's also why Black would rather have developed with ...Be6, to keep the pieces on the board.} (13. Rc1 Bd6 14. Nd4 $14) 13... Bg6 (13... d4 14. Bxh5 dxc3 15. Bxc3 $14) 14. Nxg6 hxg6 15. Bf3 $16 Ne7 16. Rc1 Rc8 17. Na4 Ba7 18. Rxc8 Qxc8 19. Qd3 Rd8 20. Rc1 Qb8 21. b4 d4 22. exd4 Qf4 23. Rd1 Nf5 24. Nc5 Bb8 25. g3 Nxg3 26. fxg3 Qxg3+ 27. Bg2 Qh2+ 28. Kf1 Nh5 29. Qf3 Nf4 30. Nd3 Rd5 31. Nxf4 Rf5 32. Ke2 Rxf4 33. Qd5 Qg3 34. Rf1 Rxf1 35. Bxf1 Bd6 36. a3 Kh7 37. Qxf7 Qh2+ 38. Qf2 Qh1 39. Qg2 {1-0 (39) Khairullin,I (2652)-Ponkratov,P (2604) Berlin 2015}) 12. h3 (12. Rc1 Bd6 13. h3 Bh5 14. Nb5 Bxf3 15. gxf3 $1 $14 {[%cal Yg1g2,Yf3f4] is not the world's most natural line, but it also seems sufficient for an edge. f4/Bf3 will take away important squares from Black's pieces, and the half open g-file can also give White some initiative.}) 12... Be6 (12... Bh5 13. Rc1 Be7 14. Nd4 $14) 13. Bd3 $1 Qe7 14. Ne2 $1 {This is an improvement, making ...Ba3 less effective and also enabling Nf4 to exert pressure on the IQP (not to mention Nd4-f5).} ({Another game this year saw the less accurate} 14. Rc1 Rfd8 15. Ne2 Ba3 16. Bxa3 Qxa3 17. Bb1 a6 $11 {and Black defended this marginally worse position in 1/2-1/2 (63) Batsiashvili,N  (2485)-Ju,W (2558) Teheran 2016}) (14. a3 {is interesting to stop ...Ba3 altogether, but Howell's move is better.}) 14... Ba3 (14... Rfd8 15. Nf4 Bd6 16. Rc1 $14) 15. Qb1 $5 {This works quite well as Black starts to try too hard to release the tension and attack White's pieces everywhere, but if Black didn't trade on b2, the rook on a1 may not be so happy.} (15. Bxa3 Qxa3 16. Qc1 {I prefer this approach as the endgame is actually very pleasant for White.} Qd6 17. Qb2 $14 {and a further Rac1/Rfd1 will make White's position pretty harmonious.}) 15... Bxb2 $6 ({Black should keep the tension with} 15... h6) (15... Rfe8 $5 {poses the question of how White's rook on a1 will enter the play.}) 16. Qxb2 Nb4 17. Rad1 (17. Bb1 Rfd8 18. a3 Nc6 19. Rd1 Ne4 20. Bd3 $14) 17... Nxd3 18. Rxd3 $14 {The white knight is better than the bishop in this structure.} Bf5 $6 {Too forcing.} (18... h6 $14 {If Black sits on the position, it is still not that easy for White to make progress. Maybe they would start with} 19. Nfd4 {and f3 like in Aronian-Morozevich.}) 19. Rc3 Rxc3 20. Nxc3 Be4 $6 {This only helps White play as he wants.} (20... h6) 21. Nd4 Qe5 (21... h6 22. Rc1) 22. Rc1 $16 h5 (22... Rc8 $2 23. Nxe4) (22... Rd8) 23. Qa3 $1 Ra8 (23... a6 24. Nce2 h4 25. Qc5 $16) 24. Qc5 {White penetrates the Black position to great effect.} Nd7 $2 (24... a6 25. Qb6 (25. Nxe4 Nxe4 26. Qc7 $16) 25... Rb8 26. Nce2) 25. Qb5 Nb6 26. Nxe4 Qxe4 27. a4 $1 $18 {Black is unable to defend the multiple weaknesses.} Qe7 (27... Qe8 28. Qxe8+ Rxe8 29. Rc7 Rb8 30. a5 Na8 31. Rd7 $18) 28. a5 Rc8 29. Rd1 Rc5 30. Nf5 Qf8 31. Qb4 Nc8 32. Qxb7 g6 33. b4 Rc4 34. Qxd5 Rxb4 35. Nd4 Ne7 36. Qd7 a6 37. Rc1 Rb8 38. Rc7 Nd5 39. Qxd5 Rb1+ 40. Kh2 Qb8 41. Qxf7+ 1-0


[Event "2015 British Chess Championship"]
[Site "University of Warwick, Covent"]
[Date "2015.07.31"]
[Round "5.1"]
[White "Howell, David W L"]
[Black "Pert, Richard G"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "A29"]
[WhiteElo "2698"]
[BlackElo "2440"]
[Annotator "Richard Pert"]
[PlyCount "81"]
[EventDate "2015.07.27"]
[EventRounds "11"]
[EventCountry "ENG"]

1. c4 {I hoped to able able to annotate a theoretically relevant game for Tony in the Flank Openings and fortunately in Round 5 of this years British Championships David played 1.c4 against me giving me the chance. When the pairings came out I thought the English was a possibility so had a look at this 1...e5 with Bc5 variation before the game. The result shouldn't be looked at too closely as Black was winning as few as 5 moves before the end but a personal meltdown in the time scramble gave White a slightly undeserved victory.} e5 2. g3 (2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. g3 Bc5 {a more common route to this position}) 2... Nf6 3. Bg2 Nc6 4. Nc3 Bc5 5. Nf3 {Actually I was expecting to reach this position via the 2.Nc3 move order (David's usual response).} d6 (5... O-O {is probably the same thing although it gives White Nxe5 options} 6. Nxe5 $5 Bxf2+ 7. Kxf2 Nxe5 8. b3 d5 $1 9. cxd5 c6 $44) 6. e3 O-O 7. O-O (7. d4 {White can try playing d4 immediately although Black has several acceptable responses} Bb4 $5 (7... exd4 8. exd4 Re8+ 9. Be3 Bb6 10. O-O a6 11. h3 h6) (7... Bb6 8. O-O h6 {with similar play to the game}) 8. O-O Bxc3 9. bxc3 e4 10. Nd2 Re8 11. Rb1 b6 12. f3 exf3 13. Qxf3 Bb7 14. Ba3 Na5 {0-1 (64) McNab, C (2427)-Rowson, J (2558) Hamilton 2004}) 7... a6 8. h3 (8. d4 {Mickey recently tried playing without h3} Ba7 9. dxe5 dxe5 10. b3 {actually I looked at this before the game and planned to use the same idea as I ended up using in the game} Qe7 $1 $146 {covering Ba3} (10... Bf5 11. Ba3 $14 {1-0 (47) Adams, M (2745)-Bates, C (2185) London 2014}) 11. Nd5 Nxd5 12. cxd5 Rd8 13. Nd2 (13. e4 Bg4 {gives Black the d4 square for his knight}) 13... Nb4 14. Ba3 a5 15. Rc1 f5 $1 $36) 8... Ba7 9. d4 h6 {Ok so this is essentially the starting position of this variation. h6 is a useful move preventing possible Bg5's after exchanges on d4 and generally improving Black's position whilst waiting to see how White wants to set up.} 10. dxe5 {this move is actually a novelty although of course transpositions are still possible} (10. b3 {is the normal way to go and has been analysed by Danny Gormally in 2013} Re8 (10... Bf5 $5) (10... exd4 $5) 11. dxe5 Nxe5 (11... dxe5 {preferred more recently by Toma} 12. Ba3 e4 13. Nd2 Bf5 14. Qc2 Qd7 15. Rad1 Qe6 16. g4 Bh7 17. Ne2 Ne5 $13 {0-1 (60) Spraggett, K (2544)-Tomashevsky, E (2715) Caleta 2014}) 12. Nxe5 dxe5 13. Ba3 c6 14. Qxd8 Rxd8 $14 {1/2-1/2 (35) Jones, G (2643)-Gormally, D (2496) Helensburgh 2013}) 10... dxe5 11. Qe2 {Howell's plan is to play Rd1 and Nd5 quickly} (11. Nd5 $6 {Nd5 without Rd1 is ineffective as Black is not forced to capture} Be6 $15) 11... Qe7 $1 {I spent some time at the board to calculate the variations. If White can not play Nd5 immediately then Black is at least equal} 12. Nd5 (12. Rd1 e4 13. Nd4 Ne5 {this seems to lead to some sort of forced draw} (13... Nxd4 14. exd4 Bf5 $13) 14. Nxe4 Nxe4 15. Bxe4 Bxh3 16. Bxb7 c5 17. Bxa8 Rxa8 18. Qh5 cxd4 19. Qxh3 Nf3+ 20. Kh1 Qe4 21. exd4 Ne1+) 12... Nxd5 13. cxd5 Nb4 $1 14. Rd1 (14. e4 {The point of Blacks play is that e4 can be met well with Bd7} Bd7 $1 15. a3 Bb5 16. Qd1 Bxf1 17. Bxf1 f5 $1 $15 {critically Black has this move and f3 and f2 look vulnerable}) 14... e4 15. Ne1 Rd8 16. Qc4 Be6 $1 {another accurate move picking up the d5 pawn} 17. Qxe4 Nxd5 $15 {The opening has been a clear success for Black who stands slightly better.} 18. Bd2 c6 19. Nd3 Qf6 20. Qa4 Nb6 21. Qc2 Bf5 22. e4 Bh7 23. Bc3 Qe7 24. Bb4 Qc7 25. Ba5 Rd4 26. Nc5 Rxd1+ 27. Rxd1 Qe7 28. Bb4 Nd5 29. Ba3 Nf6 30. Qc4 Qc7 31. b4 Re8 32. Re1 a5 33. Bb2 axb4 34. Qxb4 Qd6 35. Ba3 b6 $4 {trying to keep the position complicated in David's time trouble when the simple route leaves Black with no losing chances and a probable winning endgame} (35... Bxc5 36. Qxc5 Qxc5 37. Bxc5 Bxe4 38. Bf1 Bd5 39. Rxe8+ Nxe8 $17 {is a risk free winning attempt and would have been the prudent approach against a higher rated opponent}) 36. Na6 c5 37. Qa4 Re7 $4 {when it rains it pours!} (37... Qd2 $13) 38. Rd1 Qe6 39. Rd8+ Re8 40. Nc7 b5 41. Qxa7 {In conclusion this appears an interesting Black attempt against the g3 English. Perhaps White has to continue to search in the 10.b3 area although Tomashevsky seems to have that worked out too.} 1-0


