1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Bd7 4. Bxd7+ Qxd7 5. O-O Nc6 6. Qe2 g6 7. c3 Bg7 8. Rd1 e5 9. Na3 Nge7 {completing the Botvinnik setup, which can be used against a variety of Anti-Sicilians (most notably the Closed Sicilian) and, with White, in the English opening. Black targets any d4-break by White while being prepared to launch forward with ...f5 or ...d5 according to circumstances. It might be noted that this particular variation has scored abysmally for Black. However, it's not clear to me why this is - Black's setup seems logical and quite playable to me.} 10. Nc2 (10. d4 {is sharper and basically forces Black to capture on d4. This is also Gawain's recommendation.} cxd4 11. cxd4 exd4 12. Nb5 O-O 13. Nbxd4 {is a position which has been tested in a number of games, but Black seems to have a reliable route to equality:} Nxd4 14. Nxd4 d5 $1 15. Bf4 (15. e5 Nc6 16. f4 {is Gawain's recommendation, "forcing Black to play accurately to get his bishop out of jail", but this isn't such a difficult task: after} Nxd4 17. Rxd4 Qe6 $1 {...f6 is unpreventable, for instance} 18. Qf3 f6 19. Qxd5 Qxd5 20. Rxd5 fxe5 21. fxe5 Rf5 22. Be3 (22. Rd7 Bxe5 {and the threats on the back rank prevent White from capturing on b7}) 22... Rxe5 23. Rxe5 Bxe5 {is dead equal.}) 15... a6 16. Nb3 Rfe8 17. Qd2 Qa4 18. exd5 Nxd5 19. Qxd5 Qxf4 {and a draw was agreed in L.Fressinet (2654) - I.Smirin (2670), Plovdiv 2003.}) 10... O-O (10... d5 $5 {is a more ambitious option, aiming to exploit White's move order.} 11. d4 (11. exd5 Qxd5 {looks fine for Black. White needs to land a punch against the e5 and c5 structure before Black fully develops in order to have anything, but I don't see how this can be done.}) 11... exd4 12. exd5 Qxd5 13. cxd4 {was played in V.Baklan (2590) - D.Baramidze (2542), Austria 2006 (1/2 in 53), and now} cxd4 14. Ncxd4 Nxd4 15. Nxd4 Rd8 16. Be3 O-O {equalises.}) 11. d4 (11. b4 $5 {led to success in P.Kotsur (2570) - S. Arun Prasad (2384), New Delhi 2006 (1-0 in 56), but} cxb4 12. cxb4 (12. Nxb4 Nxb4 13. cxb4 {is also fine for Black}) 12... d5 {at least equalises.}) 11... Qc7 ({Black can transpose to the note to White's 10th with} 11... exd4 12. cxd4 cxd4 13. Ncxd4 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 {. This was the actual move order in Fressinet - Smirin. Since White's 12th move alternative looks like an edge, perhaps a transposition is prudent.}) 12. Bg5 (12. dxc5 dxc5 13. Bg5 {keeps the g7-bishop under wraps which, combined with the weakness of the d5-square, leaves White with the more comfortable game.}) 12... exd4 13. cxd4 Rae8 {Black's setup is very harmonious and I think he is fully equal here.} 14. Rac1 Qa5 (14... Nf5 {was tempting, increasing the pressure in the centre, but in view of the x-ray on the c-file Black is forced to retreat:} 15. d5 Nb8 16. Qd3 Ne7 {looks better for White than the game.}) 15. d5 (15. dxc5 dxc5 {might be playable but with such a bishop on g7 Black cannot be worse.}) 15... Ne5 16. Nxe5 Bxe5 {The position has acquired Benoni characteristics, but one where Black's queenside counterplay is far advanced and he has managed to trade his problem light-squared bishop. Meanwhile, White is a long way from executing the standard f4 and e5 advance. White needs to play with purpose here after a couple of sub-optimal moves the position quickly turns in Black's favour.} 17. Na3 (17. Ne3 {seems a more logical execution of the same idea, since} Qxa2 $6 18. Nc4 {leaves White threatening both Nxe5 and f4 with Nxd6.}) ({Trading Black's dark-squared bishop with} 17. Bh6 Bg7 18. Bxg7 Kxg7 {seems logical. Here White has an interesting shot with} 19. b4 $5 cxb4 20. Ne3 {with pressure, for instance} Nc8 21. Qb2+ f6 22. Rd4 Nb6 23. Rxb4 Rc8 {with an unclear game.}) 17... Bg7 18. Bf4 (18. Nc4 Qb5 19. Qg4 Nc8 {covers everything.}) 18... Nc8 19. Re1 f5 20. Qc2 $2 ({The resolute} 20. e5 $1 {was necessary:} Qb4 (20... dxe5 21. Bd2 Qd8 22. Rxc5 {with a level position - a blockading knight on d6 will be at hazard of exchange for the passive piece on a3. Note that} b6 23. Rc4 Qxd5 $6 24. Bb4 Rf7 25. Qc2 {leaves White with good compensation through his play on the c- and d-files.}) (20... Bxe5 {leads to complicated play but I haven't found anything especially compelling for Black.} 21. Nc4 Qxa2 22. Bxe5 dxe5 23. d6 Nb6 24. Nxe5 Re6 25. Ra1 Qb3 26. Qd2 Qb4 27. Qxb4 cxb4 28. Rxa7 Nc4 29. f4 Nxd6 30. Ra4 Rc8 31. g3 {and White should hold.} (31. Rxb4 Rc4 $1)) 21. Rc4 Qa5 22. Rcc1 Qb4 {leads to a draw.}) 20... fxe4 21. Rxe4 Bxb2 $2 {Not the most incisive continuation.} (21... b5 $1 {leaves Black with a dream Benoni position.} 22. Bd2 b4 23. Rce1 Rxe4 24. Qxe4 Kh8 $17) (21... Rxe4 22. Qxe4 Bxb2 {also leaves White on the ropes, for instance} 23. Nc4 Qa4 24. Qe6+ Kg7 25. Bxd6 Nxd6 26. Nxb2 Qd4 27. Nd3 c4 28. Qxd6 cxd3 {.}) 22. Nc4 Qc3 23. Rxe8 Rxe8 24. Qxc3 Bxc3 25. Nxd6 $2 (25. Kf1 {levelled the chances.}) 25... Nxd6 26. Bxd6 Bd2 {There are several points of interest in this endgame, but for our purposes we can stop here. White is clearly worse and soon goes under.} 27. Rf1 c4 28. Ba3 b5 29. Bc1 c3 30. Rd1 c2 31. Rf1 Re2 32. Bb2 b4 33. g3 a5 34. Kg2 a4 35. Kf3 Re1 36. Rxe1 Bxe1 37. d6 Kf7 38. Ke2 a3 39. d7 Ke7 40. Bc1 Kxd7 $1 0-1


