1. Nf3 c5 2. c4 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 6. Bf4 {This rare option has popped up in several games involving top players over the last couple of years. Of course we have looked at the alternatives 6 g3, 6 a3, 6 Bg5 and 6 Nbd5 in many games on this site.} d5 7. e3 Bb4 8. Be2 {In a later game in the Gibraltar tournament, Gelfand varied with:} (8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. Qa4 {but did not achieve an advantage after} Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 O-O 11. Be2 Ne4 12. Rc1 Qe7 13. cxd5 cxd5 14. Qb4 Qf6 15. Qd4 Re8 16. Qxf6 Nxf6 17. c4 e5 {and Black held in Gelfand,B (2721)-Vachier-Lagrave,M (2796) Caleta ENG 2017 1/2-1/2 (30)}) 8... dxc4 {An improvement over yet another MVL game which saw:} (8... O-O 9. O-O Bxc3 10. bxc3 Re8 11. Bg5 h6 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. cxd5 exd5 14. Qb3 Rd8 15. Bf3 Na5 16. Qb5 Qb6 17. Qxb6 axb6 18. Rfb1 {and White was slightly better in So-Vachier Lagrave (Baku 2015), which is analyzed in the Archives.}) 9. Nxc6 Qxd1+ 10. Rxd1 bxc6 11. Bxc4 Nd5 12. Bg3 $5 {A novelty involving a positional pawn sacrifice, with which Howell improves over an earlier game of Wei Yi's:} (12. O-O Bxc3 13. bxc3 Nxf4 14. exf4 Ke7 15. Rfe1 Rb8 {with an equal position, Wei,Y (2700)-Zhou,W (2635) Xinghua 2016 1/2-1/2 (31)}) 12... Nxc3 {Black could also consider declining the offer, for example with:} (12... h5 $5) 13. bxc3 Bxc3+ 14. Ke2 a5 {Black could consider keeping his king near the centre with:} (14... f6 {for example} 15. Rd3 Ba5 16. Bd6 Kf7 {but White keeps a slight pull after} 17. f4 {etc.}) 15. Rd3 Bf6 16. Rb1 e5 17. e4 O-O 18. Rd6 Be7 19. Rd3 {A step in the wrong direction. Regaining the pawn with} (19. Rxc6 {would leave White slightly better.}) 19... Re8 $1 {A cunning move with a concrete idea in mind.} 20. Bxe5 {Taking the pawn but allowing simplification. White could also try:} (20. Rb6 Bc5 21. Rxc6 Bd4 22. Rc7 Be6 23. Bxe6 Rxe6 24. Rb3 {which would keep some squeezing chances alive.}) 20... Bf6 21. Bxf6 Rxe4+ {Now both of White's bishops are en prise.} 22. Re3 {Or:} (22. Kf3 {and now Black continues with tactical means:} Bf5 23. Bd4 {and now:} g5 $3 {is an engine suggestion which also works, for example} (23... Rxd4 24. Bxf7+ (24. Rxd4 Bxb1 25. Rd7 Bg6 {is equal}) 24... Kxf7 25. Rb7+ Rd7 26. Rbxd7+ Bxd7 27. Rxd7+ {with a rook endgame where White is a little better but Black should hold}) 24. Rbd1 Rae8 $1 25. h3 c5 {and Black equalizes}) 22... Bg4+ 23. Kd3 Rxe3+ 24. Kxe3 gxf6 {Despite his scattered pawns, Black is still a pawn ahead, and so holds a draw without too much trouble.} 25. Rb6 Re8+ 26. Kd2 Bd7 27. g3 Re5 28. Ra6 Rc5 29. Kd3 Be6 {Trading White's active bishop makes the draw even more likely.} 30. Bxe6 fxe6 31. Ra7 h5 32. h4 f5 33. a4 e5 34. Ke3 Rd5 35. Ra6 Rc5 36. Ra7 Rd5 37. Ra6 1/2-1/2


