[BlackTeamCountry "GER"]

1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 e6 6. g3 Bc5 {The second most popular move for Black in this position.} (6... Qb6 {is the big main line, which we have covered many times on this site.}) 7. Nb3 Be7 (7... Bb4 {is also possible, but Meier is aiming for a hedgehog-style setup}) 8. Bg2 O-O 9. O-O b6 {Another popular move-order is} (9... d6 10. Bf4 {and now:} a6 (10... Nh5 11. e3 Nxf4 12. exf4 Bd7 13. Qd2 Qb8 14. Rfe1 {and White was slightly better in the famous game Karpov-Topalov, Linares 1994 which is analyzed in the Archives}) 11. Rc1 Qc7 (11... Ng4 12. Na4 Rb8 13. h3 b5 $6 14. cxb5 axb5 15. Rxc6 bxa4 16. Rxd6 Bxd6 17. Qxd6 {and White was better in Vladimirov-Kunte, also in the Archives}) 12. Nd5 $1 {A thematic idea in this structure, which we will revisit in the main game} exd5 13. cxd5 Bd7 14. dxc6 bxc6 15. Nd4 {and White is much better due to Black's weak pawns, Adhiban, B (2674)-Bacrot, E (2697) Berlin (blitz) 2015 1-0 (56)}) 10. Bf4 {Alternatively:} (10. e4 {was played by Howell in another recent game} Ba6 11. Nb5 Ne5 12. Qd4 d6 13. f4 Nc6 14. Qf2 d5 15. e5 Ne4 16. Qe2 Nc5 17. Be3 Ne4 $6 {Howell, D (2687)-Adair, J (2436) England 2015 1-0 (118), and here} 18. Rfd1 {gives White a large advantage due to the pin on the d-file}) (10. Nd5 $5 {This knight jump again, played one move earlier than in our main game} Ba6 {Leko ignores the "offer"} 11. Nxe7+ Qxe7 12. Nd2 d5 13. Qa4 Bb7 14. b3 Rfd8 15. Ba3 Qd7 16. cxd5 Nxd5 17. Rfc1 {when Black is solid but White has the slightly more pleasant position due to his two bishops, Morozevich, A (2758)-Leko, P (2744) Zug 2013 1/2-1/2 (45)}) 10... Bb7 (10... Ba6 {is more double-edged, after} 11. Nb5 d5 12. Nc7 Bxc4 13. Nxa8 (13. Nd2 Rc8 14. Nxc4 g5 15. Bxg5 Qxc7 16. Nd2 Qe5 17. Bxf6 Bxf6 18. Rb1 Rfd8 {1/2-1/2 was a quick draw in Van Wely-Hracek, covered in the PGN Archives}) 13... Qxa8 14. Rc1 e5 15. Bg5 Rd8 16. Re1 h6 17. Bxf6 Bxf6 {1-0 (71) Kortschnoj, V (2635)-Ftacnik, L (2595) Ceska Trebova 1997, and now} 18. e4 $1 {breaks up Black's centre, and after} dxe4 19. Qg4 {followed by Bg2xe4 gives White an edge}) 11. Nd5 $5 {A pseudo-sacrifice to try and unbalance the position. Other White tries at this point have been:} (11. Bd6 {is analyzed in two games in the Archives, with} Na5 {in Aronian-Carlsen and} (11... Ne8 {in Nielsen-Akopian})) (11. e4 {a natural move, just setting up the Maroczy bind structure} d6 12. Qe2 Qc7 13. Nb5 Qb8 14. Rad1 Rd8 (14... Ne5 {is recommended by Marin}) 15. c5 {with some initiative for White, Aronian, L  (2744)-Leko, P (2749) Morelia/Linares 2007 1/2-1/2 (41)}) 11... exd5 12. cxd5 Re8 {Black can't keep the extra piece so just returns the material immediately. Here Black has also tried:} (12... Nh5 13. dxc6 dxc6 14. Be5 Bf6 15. Bxf6 Nxf6 16. Nd4 Nd5 17. Rc1 Qf6 18. Nxc6 Bxc6 19. Rxc6 Qxc6 20. Bxd5 Qf6 21. Bxa8 Rxa8 22. Qc2 {and White has secured an extra pawn, Bratanov, Z (2448)-Spassov, L  (2389) Plovdiv 2007 1/2-1/2 (37)}) (12... Nb4 13. d6 Bxg2 14. dxe7 Qxe7 15. Kxg2 Nbd5 16. Bg5 Qe5 17. Bxf6 Nxf6 18. Qd2 {and here White has the better pawn structure but Black is active enough to hold the balance, Portisch, L  (2610)-Velimirovic, D (2575) Sarajevo 1986 1/2-1/2 (33)}) 13. e4 $5 {The first new move, trying to spice things up. An earlier game continued} (13. dxc6 dxc6 14. Rc1 Nd5 15. Bxd5 $6 {surrendering the two bishops left Black slightly better after} cxd5 16. Be3 Qd7 17. Bd4 Bd6 {in Sopur, L (2389)-Bulski, K (2396) Ustron 2007 1/2-1/2 (63)}) 13... Bf8 {Black refuses to be drawn into complications, though he could try} (13... Nb4 14. a3 Na6 15. e5 d6 16. exf6 Bxf6 17. Nd4 Nc5 {with chances for both sides}) 14. dxc6 dxc6 15. e5 {After this move, White's structure loses some flexibility, and Black's knight is well placed on d5. Instead} (15. Qc2 c5 16. Rad1 Qe7 17. f3 {keeps more tension in the position, although Black looks OK here.}) 15... Nd5 16. Qg4 Qc8 17. Qxc8 Raxc8 18. Rad1 h6 (18... g6 {followed by ...Bg7 targeting the e5-pawn looks promising. The opening has gone well for Black and if anyone, he is the one pressing here.}) 19. Rfe1 Nxf4 {Black decides to grab the two bishops and damages White's pawn structure} (19... g5 20. Bc1 Bg7 21. f4 {allows White to regroup and get his majority moving}) 20. gxf4 Rcd8 21. Rc1 (21. Nd4 {activating the knight would be roughly level}) 21... g5 22. fxg5 hxg5 23. Bxc6 Bxc6 24. Rxc6 Bd6 $1 {Regaining the pawn. Black is slightly better in this bishop vs knight scenario with rooks on the board.} 25. e6 Rxe6 26. Rxe6 fxe6 27. Kg2 Kf7 28. Nd4 g4 29. h3 gxh3+ 30. Kxh3 Rd7 31. Nf3 Kf6 32. Rc4 Be5 {Black could continue to press with a continuation such as} (32... Rg7 {and although White should hold, he has some work to do}) 33. b3 Kf5 {Inviting a draw by repetition which White accepts} 34. Nh4+ Kf6 35. Nf3 Kf5 36. Nh4+ Kf6 1/2-1/2


