1. d4 {Krasenkow,M Stohl, Igor Stohl,Igor Stohl,Igor Vuckovic,Bojan Stohl,Igor: 'Glenn Flear: 'Krasenkow,M'' Stohl,Igor: 'Vuckovic,Bojan Glenn Flear: 'Krasenkow,M''} Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Be3 ({Kramnik recently experimented with} 7. Qa4+ $5 {Stohl,Igor} Qd7 8. Qb3 O-O 9. Be3 c5 ({After the more usual} 9... b6 {White possibly intended to play} 10. Bb5 $5 {, which ocurred in a later game:} c6 11. Be2 c5 12. d5 e6 13. Nf3 exd5 14. exd5 Ba6 15. Bxa6 Nxa6 16. Rd1 Nc7 17. c4 Ne8 18. O-O Nd6 19. Bf4 Rfe8 20. Bxd6 Qxd6 21. Rfe1 Qd7 22. g3 Rxe1+ 23. Rxe1 $14 {Grachev,B (2680)-Edouard,R (2587)/Biel/2011/}) 10. d5 $1 e6 11. Bc4 exd5 12. Bxd5 Qc7 13. Ne2 Nd7 14. Bf4 Ne5 15. O-O c4 16. Qb4 Re8 17. Bg3 Rb8 18. Qxc4 Qxc4 19. Bxc4 Bd7 20. Rfd1 Nxc4 21. Bxb8 Ba4 22. Bxa7 Bxd1 23. Rxd1 $14 {Kramnik,V (2784)-Giri,A (2686)/Wijk aan Zee/2011/ - see notes to this game by Krasenkow in CBM 141.}) 7... c5 8. Rc1 (8. Qd2 {Stohl,Igor} Qa5) 8... Qa5 (8... O-O {Stohl,Igor} 9. Nf3 {gives Black a choice, the main move is} (9. Qd2 {allows} e5 $5 {- see Babula-Anand}) (9. d5 Qa5 10. Qd2 e6 11. Nf3 {also isn't ideal, here Black doesn't need the d8 move to put pressure on d4 anymore. More active is} exd5 12. exd5 Re8 13. Be2 (13. c4 $142 Qa3 $13) 13... Bf5 14. O-O Nd7 15. h3 Nb6 $6 (15... b5 $1 $36) 16. g4 Bd7 17. c4 Qxd2 18. Nxd2 Na4 19. Bf3 Nc3 $132 {Karpov,A (2730)-Kasparov,G (2800)/Lyon/New York/1990/}) 9... Qa5 (9... Bg4 $5 {- see Kramnik-Vacher-Lagrave and Caruana-Rodshtein})) 9. Qd2 {Stohl,Igor: '-8.c1'} (9. Qb3 {Stohl,Igor} a6 (9... cxd4 10. Qb5+ Qxb5 11. Bxb5+ Bd7 12. Bxd7+ Kxd7 13. cxd4 Nc6 14. Nf3 Rhc8 $11) 10. Bc4 O-O 11. dxc5 Nd7 12. Qb4 Qc7 13. Nf3 Nf6 14. O-O a5 15. Qb1 Ng4 16. Bd2 Qxc5 17. Be2 Qc7 18. h3 Ne5 19. Nxe5 Bxe5 20. Be3 Bd7 $132 {Likavsky,T (2480)-Hagara,E (2422)/SVK-chT/2004/}) 9... O-O ({In the opening one often castles without a second thought, but here Black also has the alternative} 9... cxd4 {Stohl,Igor} 10. cxd4 Qxd2+ {- see Kramnik-Giri.}) {Stohl,Igor: 'However, after'} 10. Nf3 {Stohl,Igor: 'he already can't transpose into Kramnik-Giri anymore,'} Rd8 {Stohl,Igor: '!?' '!?' Stohl, Igor: '!?' Stohl,Igor: 'Nowadays the most fashionable continuation. Other moves transpose into lines we have already seen in previously mentioned games:' Stohl,Igor: 'leads to the game position.'} (10... Bg4 {Stohl,Igor} 11. d5 {- see Caruana-Rodshtein.} (11. Be2 e6 $5 {-see Volkov-Sutovsky.})) (10... cxd4 {Stohl,Igor} 11. cxd4 Qxd2+ 12. Nxd2 {Stohl,Igor: '- see Karpov-Huebner.'} Nc6 13. Nb3 $14 {- see Karpov-Huebner.}) 11. d5 {Stohl,Igor: 'The most natural way to meet the pressure against the .'} (11. Be2 {Stohl,Igor} Nc6 12. d5 Bg4 13. O-O e6 14. Rfd1 exd5 15. exd5 Bxf3 16. Bxf3 Ne5 17. c4 Nxf3+ 18. gxf3 Qc7 19. Bf4 Qd7 20. Rb1 Re8 21. Re1 Bd4 22. Kg2 f6 23. Be3 Be5 24. Bf4 Bd4 $11 {Valgmae,T (2190)-Hoffmann,M (2506)/Caleta/2011/}) 11... e6 {Stohl,Igor: 'An equally logical reaction.'} ({After} 11... Bg4 {Stohl,Igor Black must reckon with} 12. Ng5 $5) ({However, a possible alternative is} 11... Nc6 $5 {Stohl,Igor , striving to transpose to the line from the previous note.} {An extra option for White is} 12. h4 $5 e6 13. h5 exd5 14. hxg6 (14. exd5 Be6 15. c4 {Sargissian,G (2673)-Gupta,A (2587)/Kavala/2010/} Nb4 16. a3 Qxa3 17. Bxc5 a5 $13 (17... Nc2+ 18. Qxc2 Qa5+ $1 19. Nd2 Bf5 20. Bd3 Bxd3 21. Qxd3 Qxc5 $11)) {An interesting and sharp line is} 14... hxg6 (14... fxg6 15. exd5 Be6 16. c4 Bf5 17. Qxa5 Nxa5 18. Nh4 Bd7 19. Bxc5 Rac8 20. Bxa7 (20. Be3 Ba4 $44) 20... Bb5 {Giri,A (2642)-Svidler,P (2735)/FRA-chT Guingamp/2010/} 21. Be2 $11) (14... dxe4 $2 15. gxh7+ Kh8 16. Bh6 $1 Bf6 17. Bg5 $18) 15. Bh6 $1 (15. exd5 $6 Bg4 $36 16. Ng5 $2 Rxd5 $1 17. Qxd5 Bxc3+ 18. Rxc3 Qxc3+ 19. Qd2 Rd8 $19 {Zakhartsov,V (2608)-Kurnosov,I (2662)/Irkutsk/2010/}) 15... Re8 (15... dxe4 $2 16. Bxg7 $40 {} Rxd2 17. Bf6 $18) 16. Bxg7 Rxe4+ 17. Be2 Kxg7 18. Ng5 (18. Qh6+ Kf6 19. Qg5+ Kg7 $11) 18... Re5 19. Nh7 (19. Rh7+ Kg8 20. Qf4 Bf5 2