{Van Delft & Ris: 'THE MIGHTY KRAMNIK We've reported before about the new Kramnik and again he was considering a piece sacrifice on move 13. He managed to control himself this time and won anyway with some fine tactics.'} 1. Nf3 d5 2. d4 Nf6 3. c4 dxc4 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. Nc3 ({More common alternatives are} 7. dxc5 {(CVO 52, 120, 129) and}) (7. Bb3 {(CVO 89, 139).}) 7... Nc6 ({Another option is} 7... b5 8. Bb3 Bb7 9. e4 $5 {which we covered in CVO 49 and 57.}) 8. a3 (8. a4 {is a rather harmless line, as after} Be7 9. Qe2 cxd4 10. Rd1 e5 11. exd4 exd4 12. Nxd4 Nxd4 13. Qe5 Qd6 {many games quickly ended in a draw.}) 8... b5 9. Ba2 Bb7 10. Qe2 Qc7 (10... cxd4 11. Rd1 {followed by 12.exd4 gives White nice play.}) (10... Be7 11. dxc5 (11. Rd1 $5) 11... Bxc5 12. b4 Bd6 13. Bb2 O-O 14. Rfd1 Qe7 15. Rac1 Rfd8 {with equality in Nikolaidis-Ivanchuk, Eretria 2011.}) 11. Rd1 ({The most consistent plan is to push d4-d5. Right now} 11. d5 {is a bit premature, since after} exd5 12. Nxd5 Nxd5 13. Bxd5 Be7 14. a4 Qb6 15. e4 O-O 16. Bg5 Nd4 $1 {Black was doing fine in Sandipan-Fridman, Pardubice 2002.}) (11. h3 {was played in Piket-Korchnoi, Tilburg 1998 and now the logical continuation would have been} Rd8 $1 {with approximately equal chances.}) 11... Rd8 12. d5 exd5 {Van Delft & Ris: 'Diagram [#]'} 13. Nxd5 ({Van Delft & Ris: 'Kramnik would have preferred installing a N permanently on d5 and hence mainly focused on'} 13. Bxd5 {Van Delft & Ris: 'but failed to make it work after' had been played before. Kramnik considered it but felt he couldn't make it work.} b4 $1 (13... Be7 14. e4 {as played in Schandorff-Unzicker,F Copenhagen 2010, was considered somewhat favorable for White by Kramnik.}) 14. axb4 cxb4 15. Rxa6 (15. Ng5 Rd7 $1 (15... bxc3 $2 {loses to} 16. Bxf7+ Ke7 17. bxc3 Rxd1+ 18. Qxd1 Qd7 19. Qb3 $1 $18) 16. Rxa6 bxc3 17. Bxc6 Bxc6 18. Rxd7 Qxd7 {and White can't bring his Q to the battlefield due to back rank problems.}) 15... bxc3 (15... Bxa6 16. Qxa6 {is pretty dangerous for Black.}) 16. Bxc6+ Bxc6 17. Rxd8+ Kxd8 18. Qd3+ Kc8 (18... Bd6 $2 {is beautifully met by} 19. Ne5 $1 Bd5 20. Rxd6+ Qxd6 21. Nxf7+ {and wins.}) 19. Nd4 Bb7 20. Ra4 Kb8 {and White's compensation is insufficient.}) ({Moreover} 13. e4 $2 {doesn't lead anywhere after} dxe4 14. Bg5 Be7 $1 {and Black is on top.}) 13... Nxd5 14. Bxd5 Be7 ({After} 14... Bd6 15. e4 {the B will be developed to g5.}) 15. e4 O-O 16. g3 Na5 17. Bf4 Qc8 ({Van Delft & Ris: 'Perhaps a better try would have been' Perhaps} 17... Qb6 {Van Delft & Ris: '!?' Van Delft & Ris: 'when White has to prove whether he has an edge at all.' , defending the knight and the b-pawn, is a little safer.}) 18. a4 $1 {[diag] Vlad was quite happy with his game here, once he had found this move, which undermines Black's queenside. Commentator Daniel King thought the queenside configuration had something in common with some positions in the Ruy Lopez where a similar strategy is appropriate.} ({Another idea is} 18. Bd2 {but then} Nc4 $1 19. Bxc4 bxc4 20. Bc3 (20. Qxc4 $6 Qg4 21. Ne5 Qh5 $1 {is quite unpleasant for White.}) 20... Qg4 {should be OK for Black.}) 18... b4 ({After} 18... Nc4 {Van Delft & Ris: '?' Van Delft & Ris: 'has lost its effect, since after'} 19. Bxc4 bxc4 20. Qxc4 {, Vlad thought Black had some play but not enough for the pawn.} Qg4 21. Rxd8 Rxd8 22. Ne5 {Black is forced to exchange Qs with} Qe6 {after which White is a full pawn up.}) 19. Rac1 ({Now Vlad didn't like Black's position.} 19. Ne5 Bxd5 20. Rxd5 Nb3 21. Rad1 Nd4 22. Qc4 Qe6 23. Be3 {was one of the lines Vlad looked out but it is not so clear.}) 19... Bc6 $2 ({Van Delft & Ris: 'A serious mistake, after which the damage is irreparable. Howell should have tried' This might have been a mistake, Vlad thought. He tried to make 19...Qb7 work but wasn't convinced. The computer suggestion} 19... Rfe8 {Van Delft & Ris: '!' Van Delft & Ris: 'preventing White from trading the dark-squared Bs.' doesn't look bad.}) 20. Bg5 $1 {Clever. White deflects the dark-squared bishop, thus removing a defender from the c5 pawn.} Bxg5 21. Rxc5 $1 {A cunning intermezzo move, exploiting the looseness of all Black's residual minor pieces. "Now it's basically over," said Vlad.} Bf6 ({Hikaru tried to make} 21... Bb5 $5 {Van Delft & Ris: 'can easily be parried with' work, but} 22. Qc2 {Van Delft & Ris: '!' Van Delft & Ris: 'and a loss of material is inevitable.' is a good move and the threats to the black minor pieces remain.}) 22. Rxa5 {By now Hikaru had lost faith in the position too. White is already one pawn up and on the brink of winning another. Black has no viable counterplay even though the a5 rook is slightly offside.} Bxd5 23. Raxd5 Rxd5 24. Rxd5 {Van Delft & Ris: '!'} (24. exd5 {might also have been played, though it's not easy for White to mobilize his passed pawn. Kramnik rightly evaluated that he can give up his b-pawn.}) 24... Qc1+ 25. Kg2 Bxb2 (25... Qxb2 26. Qxa6 {Van Delft & Ris: 'almost comes down to the same thing.'} Bc3 27. a5 {is similar to the game.}) 26. Qxa6 Qc2 27. Rd2 Qb3 ({Against} 27... b3 {Van Delft & Ris: 'can be met by' , White has} 28. Qe2 ({obviously not} 28. Rxc2 $2 bxc2 $19) 28... Rc8 {and now} 29. Ne1 {Van Delft & Ris: '!' Van Delft & Ris: 'and White wins.' resolves the position on c2.}) 28. a5 Bc3 29. Rd5 Qc2 30. Qb7 $1 b3 ({Van Delft & Ris: 'In case of'} 30... Qxe4 {allows White to win the pawn race with} 31. a6 {Van Delft & Ris: 'Black is unable to exploit the pins on the a8-h1 diagonal.' and there is no way of exploiting Black's pin on the long diagonal.}) 31. a6 b2 32. Rb5 Qa4 33. a7 h6 34. e5 ({An uneasy stand-off has been reached. Not} 34. Qb8 $2 {Van Delft & Ris: 'would have spoiled all the effort, due to' when Black can reply} Qxe4 {Van Delft & Ris: '!' and White's advantage has dissipated.}) 34... Kh7 (34... Qa1 35. Qe7 b1=Q 36. Rxb1 Qxb1 37. Qxf8+ Kxf8 38. a8=Q+ {Van Delft & Ris: 'should be technically winning for White.' should win.}) 35. Rb3 Qa2 36. h4 {Van Delft & Ris: '!' Van Delft & Ris: 'Diagram [#] Excellent technique. White isn't in a hurry and simply improves his position, boxing in the black K.' Commentator Lawrence Trent was justly proud of predicting this squeezing plan.} Kg8 37. h5 {Vlad called this 'making a box' for the black king. More of a coffin, actually.} Qa5 38. Qb8 Qa2 39. Rxc3 $1 b1=Q 40. Rc8 $1 {[diag]} (40. Rc8 {Van Delft & Ris: '!' Van Delft & Ris: 'and Black resigned, in view of'} Rxc8 (40... Qf1+ $1 {is clever but after} 41. Kxf1 Qa6+ 42. Kg2 Rxc8 43. Nd4 {Van Delft & Ris: '+-' seems to win anyway.}) 41. Qxc8+ Kh7 42. a8=Q {Van Delft & Ris: 'and White is just a piece up.' and White's pair of queens proves more potent than Black's.}) 1-0


