{THE LEGEND OF DRAWNIK. Chess of course, is huge on the internet these days. And, with the internet, you get your fair share of "trolls ". An internet troll, for those unfamiliar with such terms, is someone who deliberately makes insulting comments, to try to provoke some kind of negative emotional reaction. And with so many top tournaments now being broadcast live online, it was inevitable that the trolls would get their teeth in and that the top players would be unfairly saddled with some rather insulting nicknames at some point. Magnus Carlsen, whenever he draws a game, automatically becomes Magnus Drawsen. (Magnus Carlsberg, probably the best chess player in the world, is another nickname he goes by.) Hikaru Nakamura is often called something like Kaspamura (in recognition of his short-lived work with Garry Kasparov) or, more often, as just plain "Naka". Vladimir Kramnik, the recent winner of the strongest tournament ever to be held on these shores, the London Chess Classic, often has a reputation as a dry, arid player, who favours endgames and not terribly exciting openings like the Berlin Defence, and is occasionally summarily dismissed as "Drawnik". However, this nickname and reputation is somewhat inaccurate, in my view. Or at least outdated. While he went through a period of several years when at least with Black he tended to avoid any great risks, lately we've seen his style go back to something like his youth. He is much more flamboyant and aggressive, perhaps realising that, with the likes of Carlsen and Aronian around now, it would be difficult for him to win top tournaments without putting his head on the parapet at some stage. I mean, let's face it, it is rather hard to believe that Kramnik became world champion and got to 2800 on the rating list by simply having a good feel for the Berlin and Petroff defences. At some point you have to be able to win games. I recall that in a French league a few years ago, a couple of strong Russian grandmasters were telling me how Kramnik had a reputation for being the best tactician of his generation when he was younger, but gradually his style became more positional. Clearly though, he can still "turn it on" when he has to. In fact, in the London Chess Classic, Kramnik gave an extraordinary demonstration of his chess imagination, during the press conference of his game against the young British player David Howell. These press conferences are live streamed at the time and are saved as videos on the London Chess Classic site. They really should not be missed by anyone hoping to improve, as they give an invaluable insight into the chess minds of the very best players in the world. In fact, such was the breathless mental masterclass given by Kramnik, I was both inspired and depressed at the same time immediately after watching it. Inspired, because it gave some idea of what is possible in chess, and depressed because I got the distinct impression that, however hard I try to improve, I could never get near the level of such a player. I've tried to put at least the first part of this amazing video into its proper context, and any comments in quotation marks are Kramnik's unless indicated otherwise.} 1. Nf3 d5 2. d4 Nf6 3. c4 dxc4 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. Nc3 Nc6 8. a3 b5 9. Ba2 Bb7 10. Qe2 Qc7 11. Rd1 Rd8 12. d5 {"I have to do d5 if I want to get something"} exd5 13. Nxd5 ({The first important moment in the game. Kramnik started throwing some pretty wild variations around at this point. The main alternative was} 13. Bxd5 {which Kramnik analysed in great detail. Both players now agreed that} b4 $1 {was critical.} (13... Be7 14. e4 {followed by Bg5 and Kramnik liked White.}) 14. axb4 cxb4 {[diagram] "And now there are two moves."} 15. Ng5 ({The other move is} 15. Rxa6 {. Kramnik couldn't quite make this work either, although not without want of trying:} bxc3 (15... Bxa6 16. Qxa6 {and Kramnik felt this was good for White although, after} Nb8 17. Qa4+ Nbd7 {, the position is very unclear.}) 16. Bxc6+ Bxc6 17. Rxd8+ Kxd8 18. Qd3+ Kc8 {Now Kramnik suggested that he couldn't see anything for White after} ({Kramnik saw a beautiful variation after} 18... Bd6 $2 19. Ne5 Bd5 20. Rxd6+ $1 Qxd6 21. Nxf7+ {("Is that all you saw?" was a typically witty response from Lawrence Trent)}) 19. Nd4 Bb7 (19... Be4 {also looks good for Black}) 20. Ra4 Kb8 {and he couldn't see a way through here. However, what was astonishing was how deeply he had analysed.}) 15... Rd7 $1 {Now Kramnik suggested the flamboyant} (15... bxc3 16. Bxf7+ Ke7 17. bxc3 {(with a huge threat of Ba3)} Rxd1+ 18. Qxd1 Qd7 {. Howell had also seen up to this point. Kramnik now suggested the further moves} 19. Qb3 $1 Kd8 20. Ne6+ Kc8 21. Nxf8 Rxf8 22. Be6 {"This is what I calculated." At which point one of the commentators at the event, GM Danny King, interjected with the comment that "the other day you said you're too old to calculate. Listen - this is incredible depth" to which Vladimir replied, "Yeah, but I'm sure that there are some blunders"}) 16. Rxa6 $5 {but this seems to fall short after} bxc3 17. Bxc6 Bxc6 18. Rxd7 Qxd7 {where White would like to continue his attack here with} 19. Qc4 {but unfortunately for him this fails to} Qd1+ {. Now all these variations, with pieces sacced all over the place, could be dismissed as flights of fancy, and not a serious attempt. But in fact Kramnik was seriously considering all this, because if it works then as he said, he would have played Bxd5. Contrast this with many players who sleepwalk through the opening, plod along on auto-pilot, using general considerations and only really put their calculating hat on later in the game. What this showed was that Kramnik was already engaging his tactical imagination at an early stage, where everything looked very boring and solid. He was already trying to find a way through, to blast his way through the black defences using his incredible imagination, but this proved beyond him for the simple reason that Black has not made any serious errors yet. The scary thing is that he was already looking for a way to win at this stage of the game. The mere fact that he was even attempting to do so was something new to me, and I think it is an important lesson to take on board.}) (13. e4 $6 dxe4 14. Bg5 Be7 {and, as Howell pointed out,} 15. Bxf6 {does not work because of} exf3 $1) 13... Nxd5 14. Bxd5 Be7 15. e4 O-O 16. g3 $1 {[diagram] Kramnik liked this move and it's an important chain in White's plan, to maintain pressure on the centre before Black can fully consolidate. "My bishop is very powerful on d5."} Na5 $2 {Howell goes astray. Moving the knight away like this looks unnatural and indeed proves to be so. Of course, though, one can only imagine that there was an idea behind this as a player as strong as Howell will very rarely play with no plan in mind. I would speculate that here he felt that the bishop on d5 was so strong that it needed to be challenged as soon as possible. However, it turns out that the cure is worse than the disease. It's funny how when you face players of the calibre of Kramnik you can fear ghosts and not play your normal game. I'm sure that if Howell were playing me here he would have not hesistated to play} (16... Rfe8 $1 17. Bf4 Qb6 {with fairly unclear prospects. It is clear that the plan of a4 as played in the game would not be then so powerful. Black retains counterplay in the centre. For example, if White is impatient with} 18. e5 $2 {Then it is met immediately by} Rxd5 $1 (18... Nd4 $1 {is equally good}) 19. Rxd5 Nd4 {with advantage for Black.}) 17. Bf4 Qc8 18. a4 $1 ({Kramnik also considered the forcing move} 18. Bd2 {here:} Nc4 19. Bxc4 bxc4 20. Bc3 {and he spent a lot of time on this position as White has a serious positional threat of playing Ne5-c4. The problem, though, is that, after} Qg4 $1 {Black has serious counterchances. Besides, once you see 18 a4!, all other variations are really not important.}) 18... b4 ({"After} 18... Nc4 19. axb5 (19. Bxc4 bxc4 20. Qxc4 {is also possible}) 19... axb5 {"first of all I can get} 20. Ra7 {and then I can play for the initiative."}) 19. Rac1 ({"First of all I wanted to play} 19. Ne5 {here. I was calculating some line just for fun." After 19 Ne5 White's minor pieces completely dominate the middle of the board; another drawback of the earlier excursion Black made with 16...Na5?!. Kramnik now demonstrated the beautiful variation} Bf6 (19... Bxd5 $1 {"But of course you can do better, (to Howell) you can take, and now I was not sure if I should take with the pawn or with the rook. Maybe the rook. I finally thought."} 20. Rxd5 Rxd5 21. exd5 Nb3 {It's significant that here the black knight takes two steps to reach d4, whereas if he had kept it on c6 it could go there at once.} 22. Rd1 Nd4 23. Qc4 {"and I want Be3"}) 20. Ng4 Bd4 21. Rxd4 cxd4 22. Rc1 Qa8 (22... Qd7 23. Rc7 {wins}) 23. Nh6+ $1 gxh6 (23... Kh8 24. Nxf7+ Rxf7 25. Bxf7 Bxe4 26. Be5) 24. Be5 {[diagram] "And I don't see how to defend after this." Neither, unsurprisingly, do I.}) 19... Bc6 $2 {This meets with an immediate tactical refutation.} 20. Bg5 $1 Bxg5 (20... Bxd5 21. Bxe7 ({There was an amusing interlude in the post mortem, where both players showed they had considered the variation} 21. exd5 Bxg5 22. Nxg5 Qf5 23. Rxc5 Nb3 {[diagram] and now Howell shot Kramnik a questioning look, as if he had blundered. But even here he had seen one move further:} 24. Qc2 $1 {Although this variation isn't really necessary, as 21 Bxe7 is so clearly strong, it is another good example of how far Kramnik sees in even minor lines.}) 21... Bc4 22. Rxd8 (22. Qe3 Rxd1+ 23. Rxd1 Re8 24. Bxc5 {is also not bad}) 22... Qxd8 23. Qxc4 Qxe7 24. Qxc5 Qxe4 25. Ng5 {wins.}) 21. Rxc5 Bf6 ({After} 21... Bb5 {Kramnik demonstrated the following variation, which remarkably enough, is also the first line of the computer:} 22. Nxg5 (22. Qc2 $1 {is also strong as everything is hanging}) 22... Qxc5 23. axb5 Qe7 24. Qh5 h6 25. Nxf7 Rxd5 26. Nxh6+ {followed by taking on d5 and a6, and there are too many pawns.}) 22. Rxa5 Bxd5 23. Raxd5 Rxd5 24. Rxd5 Qc1+ 25. Kg2 Bxb2 26. Qxa6 {[diagram] Now the game should be effectively over as the white queen and rook easily contain the black b-pawn while the white a-pawn is not so easily dealt with. However, there is one more important twist as we shall see.} Qc2 27. Rd2 Qb3 28. a5 Bc3 29. Rd5 Qc2 30. Qb7 b3 31. a6 b2 32. Rb5 Qa4 33. a7 h6 34. e5 Kh7 35. Rb3 Qa2 36. h4 Kg8 37. h5 Qa5 38. Qb8 Qa2 39. Rxc3 b1=Q 40. Rc8 {Black resigned but they both missed at the time that 40...Qf1! followed by 41...Qa6 prolongs resistance. According to computers, which gives plus three pawns here, White should be winning in any case, but clearly there is plenty of work to be done. While it is clear that the idea of these press conferences are a great help to the watching audience, both at the venue and online itself, I can't help but think that the recent practice of having press conferences at the strongest tournaments in the world are a lost opportunity, at least for some of the players. Why? Because it is clear that they have replaced post mortems. As far as I'm aware these not particularly long press conferences are the only real interaction that the players get after the game, apart from some short discussions at the board. If I were David Howell, or any of the English guys taking on the big guns, I'd relish the chance to have a proper post mortem with someone like Kramnik. You can often learn far more from a post mortem with such a player than you can from the game itself, where everything is so much more hidden. The problem with that press conference was that, while it was hugely impressive to see Kramnik being so open with what he saw during the game (in refreshing contrast to say, Carlsen, who tends to be much more reticent during interviews, often just mumbling answers almost), you also got the impression that David could barely get a word in edgeways. That's what these top players tend to do if you're not careful; they will try to dominate you on and off the board, so that in a sense you are subverted to their will. The top players will look to dominate. That is part of the reason why they are so successful. So I don't think that these press conferences are really helping the young English players as much as a post mortem would, although I understand that it's only a minor gripe.} 1-0


