1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Qa4+ Bd7 5. Qb3 dxc4 6. Qxc4 Nc6 7. e4 Bg7 8. e5 Be6 9. exf6 Bxc4 10. fxg7 Rg8 11. Bxc4 {Belongs to a previous discussion, but I like White.} Rxg7 12. O-O g5 13. Bd5 Qd6 14. d4 g4 15. Bxc6+ Qxc6 16. Nh4 $5 {[%cal Gg2g3,Gh4g2,Gg2e3,Gg2f4] A nice positional moment. Bogdan knows that e3/f4 will both be good squares with this structure - and it might be useful to blockade the h-pawn too. How many players would just automatically choose 16 Ne5?} Qd7 17. d5 f6 18. Bf4 Kf7 19. Rad1 Rg5 20. g3 Rh5 21. Rd2 Rd8 22. Re1 Qc8 23. Rde2 Rd7 24. Re6 Qd8 25. Ng2 Rhxd5 $1 {A good defensive decision - otherwise Black can never free himself.} 26. Nxd5 Rxd5 27. Rxe7+ {Probably right. At first I wondered if Bogdan might have gone for more with} (27. Ne3 $5 {but in fact after} Kxe6 28. Nxd5+ Kf7 $1 29. Nxe7 Qd7 $1 {[%csl Re7] White might be in danger of getting a lesson in the importance of coordination over material.}) 27... Qxe7 28. Rxe7+ Kxe7 29. Ne3 {[%csl Ge3] One of the excellent destinations for this piece which Bogdan envisaged on move 16. White's 5th rank coverage feels like an important factor in his success.} Rc5 30. Kf1 $1 ({Of course} 30. Nxg4 $2 Rc2 $132 {would constitute a criminal rushing of affairs. Counterplay on the queenside is always to be avoided as we have seen.}) 30... Ke6 31. Ke2 c6 32. Kd2 h5 33. a3 {[%csl Gc1,Gc2,Gc3,Gc4,Gd5,Ge5,Gf5,Gg5] An instructive achievement in square coverage and restriction of counterchances. The unhappiness of the rook on c5 becomes increasingly clear.} Rb5 34. b4 a5 35. Nc2 Rd5+ 36. Ke2 axb4 37. axb4 Rd8 38. Bd2 $1 {[%csl Rh5][%cal Yd2b4,Gc2e3,Ge3g2,Gg2f4] Division of labour. It has to be the knight which will take the leading role in probing Black's weaknesses, so the bishop needs to undertake the apparently modest task of defending b4.} Ra8 39. Ne3 Ra1 40. Ng2 Kf5 41. Nf4 Rh1 (41... h4 42. gxh4 Rh1 43. Nh5 $5 Rxh2 44. Ng3+ Ke6 45. h5) 42. Nxh5 Rxh2 43. Ng7+ $1 {[%mdl 4096] Key moment according to Bogdan.} (43. Nf4 Ke4 $11 {leaves Black's king well centralised and relatively stable, and the White knight on a much less threatening circuit. After the more aggressive text the minor pieces support eaxh other admirably and again tie down Black's rook. Note that the bishop now needs f4 again!}) 43... Kg6 44. Ne8 $1 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Ge8d6]} Rh7 45. Nd6 Rd7 46. Bf4 $1 {Another great picture of more advanced cooperation. Impressive square coverage again - this time the Black king is a major victim of this. White's methodical play meanwhile has left him now prepared to bring the king up.} Kg7 47. Ke3 Kf8 48. Ke4 Ke7 49. Nf5+ Ke6 50. Nd4+ Ke7 51. Be3 $1 {[%csl Rg4][%cal Ge4g4] So simple. The weakness of g4 will now force Black's rook to go passive.} Rd5 52. Kf4 Rg5 53. Nb3 $1 {and White opens a second and decisive front. Once the rook is forced to retreat to g7 White's king invades a key square f5 and its effectively over.} Kd6 ({No chance of activity any more.} 53... Rb5 {is met with} 54. Bc5+ Kd7 55. Nd4 {when Fritz adds the nice, but not strictly necessary touch} b6 56. Nxb5 bxc5 57. Nc7 $1 cxb4 58. Na6 $18) 54. Nc5 Rg7 $8 (54... Kc7 55. Ne6+) 55. Kf5 Kd5 56. Ne4 Kc4 57. Bc5 b6 58. Bxb6 Kxb4 59. Kxf6 Rg8 60. Kf5 Rg7 61. Bd4 Rg8 62. Be3 Rg7 63. Nf6 c5 64. Nxg4 c4 65. Nf6 c3 66. Nd5+ Kc4 67. Nxc3 Kxc3 68. g4 Kc4 69. g5 Kd5 70. g6 Rc7 71. Bh6 Rc2 72. g7 Rc8 73. Kf6 Rc6+ 74. Kf7 Rc7+ 75. Kg6 Rc6+ 76. Kh7 Rc7 77. Kh8 {Consummate technic from Bogdan Lalic which I am sure will admirably repay careful study.} 1-0


