1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. g3 Bb4 4. Nf3 {John Bartholomew: 'This move order is a little unusual but might be the most accurate. White forces Black to tend to his e-pawn, thereby denying the second player some flexibility. Mihail Marin attributes this finesse to Portisch.'} (4. Bg2 {is the automatic move. Nakamura may have wanted to avoid the line} O-O 5. Nf3 Re8 6. O-O {, in which Black scores well with} e4 ({or} 6... c6 {, refusing to commit his knight to c6.}) ({Black could also play} 6... Nc6 {, reaching a tabiya of the Four Knights.}) ({or} 6... Bxc3 7. bxc3 Nc6 {transposing to the game.})) 4... Bxc3 {John Bartholomew: 'Howell responds in kind. Certainly there is nothing wrong with this standard trade, but if Black intends to commit his knight to c6 as he does in the game (instead of the critical 5...e4 - see below), then there isn't a pressing need to trade on c3 so early.'} (4... Nc6 5. Bg2 ({or} 5. Nd5) 5... O-O 6. O-O {reaches the big main line. See Carsten Hansen's guide "Four Knights 4 g3 - 4...Bb4 The Main Line" for an excellent roadmap.}) (4... e4 5. Nd4 O-O ({or} 5... Nc6 6. Nc2 Bxc3 7. dxc3) 6. Bg2 Re8 7. O-O Nc6 8. Nc2 Bxc3 9. dxc3 {transposes to a line that was popular in the 70's and 80's. White retains slightly better changes see Anastasian, A  (2568)-Sadvakasov, D (2635)/Moscow 2005/[John Watson] for a recent example.}) 5. bxc3 ({For} 5. dxc3 {, see Taimanov, M (2454)-Rublevsky, S (2657)/St Petersburg 2001/[TonyK].}) 5... Nc6 {John Bartholomew: 'Now the game merges with a more well-trodden path.'} ({Critical is} 5... e4 6. Nd4 O-O 7. Bg2 d5 {. I refer you to Kamsky, G (2714)-Gelfand, B (2736)/Moscow 2007/[Carsten Hansen], as well as to Marin's outstanding notes to the same game in ChessBase.} (7... c5 $5 {is another important move that both commentators examine in-depth.})) 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O Re8 {John Bartholomew: 'transposing to the game.'} (7... d6 {is a solid alternative.}) 8. d3 e4 9. Nd4 {John Bartholomew: 'Best.'} ({White has not done particularly well with} 9. Ng5 exd3 10. exd3 {. Now} h6 {is the most direct, e.g.} 11. Ne4 (11. Nf3 b6 12. Nd4 Bb7 13. Qa4 Na5 14. Bf4 Bxg2 15. Kxg2 Nb7 16. Rfe1 Nc5 17. Qc2 d6 18. Re2 Qd7 19. Rae1 Rxe2 20. Rxe2 Re8 21. Nb3 $6 Ne6 $1 22. Bc1 d5 $1 $36 {was model play for Black in Schiffler, G-Unzicker, W (2450)/Bad Liebenzell 1995.}) (11. Nh3 {can be met by} d5 12. cxd5 Nxd5 $132) 11... d6 {Alternatives are also decent:} (11... b6 12. Bf4 Bb7 13. Re1 Na5 14. f3 d5 15. Nxf6+ Qxf6 16. Qd2 c5 $132 {Taimanov, M (2580) -Bronstein, D (2590)/ Tallinn 1975.}) (11... Nxe4 12. Bxe4 d6 13. Rb1 Ne5 $1 {John Bartholomew: 'is 11... Nxe4 above.'} 14. Bf4 {Cordara, M (2185)-Naumkin, I (2500)/Celle Ligure 1995. Here} Bh3 {provides excellent counterplay, e.g.} 15. Re1 $6 (15. Bxe5 Bxf1 16. Bxg7 Bxd3 17. Qxd3 Kxg7 $13) 15... Bg4 $1 {and 16...Nf3+.}) 12. Re1 (12. Rb1 Nxe4 13. Bxe4 Ne5 $1 {is 11... Nxe4 above.}) 12... Bg4 $5 13. f3 $2 (13. Qc2 Ne5 $132) 13... Nxe4 14. dxe4 Be6 $17 {Hanauer, M-Reshevsky, S/New York 1938. Black was already much better due to his White's obvious pawn weaknesses.}) 9... exd3 {John Bartholomew: 'Here and over the next few moves Black sometimes plays ...h6. It's not clear to me that preventing Bc1-g5 is necessary, since White's bishop often goes elsewhere anyways.'} 10. exd3 Nxd4 11. cxd4 d5 {John Bartholomew: 'Howell plays directly through the center, fixing White's doubled d-pawns.'} ({An example of the} 11... h6 {strategy:} 12. d5 $5 d6 13. Bb2 {. Despite Black's efforts, White found a better diagonal for the bishop. Seirawan, Y (2653)-Gulko, B (2618)/Salt Lake City 1999/[TonyK].}) 12. Be3 {John Bartholomew: 'Nakamura mentioned in the post-game comments that he was on his own at this point. White has tried several moves here.'} ({First, what happens if White makes good on his 'threat' with} 12. Bg5 {? Now in fact} h6 $1 {is a smart reply.} 13. Bxf6 (13. Bf4 {is possible, but admits to a loss of time.}) 13... Qxf6 14. cxd5 (14. Bxd5 c6 15. Bg2 Qxd4 16. Qb3 Rd8 {was totally fine for Black in Shaikh, N (2071)-Troff, K (2216)/Porto Carras GRE 2010.}) 14... Qxd4 15. Rc1 {San Segundo Carrillo, P (2511)-Perez Felipe, M (2305)/El Sauzal ESP 2010.} (15. Qc2 {Kallio, H (2493)-Fressinet, L (2654)/ Plovdiv 2003. Now} Bf5 $1 $146 {is strong because} 16. Qxc7 Bxd3 17. Rad1 {(if the other rook moves, then 17... Re2 comes, attacking f2).} Qc4 $1 18. Qxc4 Bxc4 19. Rfe1 Rxe1+ 20. Rxe1 {and Black can even play for the win with his queenside majority, i.e.} b5 $5 (20... Bxa2 21. Ra1 Bc4 22. d6 Rd8 23. Bxb7 Rxd6 24. Rxa7 {is an immediate draw.})) {Now I propose} 15... Bg4 $5 {, e.g.} 16. Qb3 (16. Qd2 $5) 16... Be2 17. Rfe1 Bxd3 18. Qxb7 Rab8 19. Rxe8+ (19. Qxc7 Rxe1+ 20. Rxe1 Rb2 21. Qf4 Qxf4 22. gxf4 Rxa2 $11) 19... Rxe8 20. Bf1 (20. Qxc7 Re2 21. Qf4 {is the same as 19.Qxc7.}) 20... Be4 ({or} 20... Bxf1 21. Kxf1 Re5 $11) 21. Bg2 $11) (12. Bf4 {A logical square for the bishop.} c6 ({Black could try to dispense with ...c7-c6 by} 12... Bf5) 13. Re1 ({This allows Black to simplify, so} 13. Be5 $5 {was worth considering.}) 13... Rxe1+ 14. Qxe1 Bf5 15. Qc3 h6 16. h3 dxc4 17. dxc4 Be4 18. Re1 Bxg2 19. Kxg2 Qd7 20. Be5 Nh7 21. h4 Re8 22. Bf4 Rxe1 {1/2-1/2 Mamedyarov, S (2646)-Kobalia, M (2614)/Abu Dhabi 2005.}) ({Aronian played} 12. Rb1 {against Gelfand in 2008. Although he lost  (a rarity with White!), this useful move looks good enough for a slight plus.} h6 (12... Bg4 13. Qc2 dxc4 14. dxc4 Qxd4 15. Be3 Qe5 16. Rxb7 Bf5 {Friedel, J  (2527)-Gupta, A (2587)/Chalkis GRE 2010.} 17. Qb2 Qxb2 18. Rxb2 Be4 19. Rd1 $14 {The endgame is more comfortable for White.}) 13. Bf4 b6 14. Be5 $14 {Aronian, L (2757)-Gelfand, B (2719)/Dresden GER 2008. This last move is a standard idea that Nakamura also implemented in the game White exerts some slight pressure with the bishop pair. Strangely, the play reminds me of some main-lines of the Petroff.}) 12... h6 {John Bartholomew: 'A novelty. Again, I'm not convinced this move is necessary.'} (12... Be6 {was seen in an old Botvinnik game. The Patriarch played} 13. Rc1 (13. c5 {Botvinnik soon played this move anyways, so maybe he could have saved the Ra1-c1 tempo.}) (13. Qb3 {is also logical.}) 13... h6 14. h3 c6 15. Qd2 {, but didn't get much of anything after} Qd7 $11 {Botvinnik, M-Basman, M/Hastings 1966.}) ({Another clash of young super-talents saw} 12... Bf5 {This is the most desirable move provided Black doesn't run into problems with b7 or d5. Following} 13. Qb3 Qd7 ({or} 13... c6 {since White isn't planning on taking on b7 when d3 is hanging with tempo.}) 14. Rfe1 ({White has an extra pawn after} 14. cxd5 Bh3 15. Qxb7 Bxg2 16. Kxg2 Rab8 17. Qc6 Qxd5+ 18. Qxd5 Nxd5 {, but it's difficult to believe he'll win.}) 14... c6 15. Bg5 Rxe1+ $1 {Forcing the tempo.} ({A normal-looking alternative is} 15... dxc4 16. dxc4 Ne4 (16... Qxd4 17. Bxf6 Qxf6 18. Qxb7 $14) 17. Be3 Rad8 (17... Nf6 $5) 18. Rad1 {with a customary small advantage for White, though Black's position is reliable.}) 16. Rxe1 Re8 17. Rxe8+ Qxe8 18. h3 Qe1+ 19. Kh2 {Giri, A (2672)-So, W (2674)/Biel SUI 2010. Now} dxc4 20. dxc4 Bxh3 $1 {leads to total equality, though it's impossible to make this assessment without a strong engine:) For example,} 21. Bxf6 (21. Bxh3 Qxf2+ 22. Bg2 Ng4+ 23. Kh3 h5 $1 $132) (21. Kxh3 Qe6+ 22. Kh2 Ng4+ 23. Kh3 Nxf2+ 24. Kh2 Ng4+ 25. Kh3 {when Black can even try to play on with} h6) 21... Bxg2 22. Kxg2 gxf6 23. Qxb7 Qe4+ $11 {. So played the immediate 19...Bxh3, which turned out to be slightly inaccurate. It's possible he had analyzed this temporary bishop sacrifice before and simply forgot to insert the capture on c4.}) 13. h3 (13. Re1 $14 {might be a bit better. If Black chooses the plan with ...Be6 and ...Qd7 below, then White must lose time to defend h3.}) 13... b6 {John Bartholomew: 'Nakamura questioned this plan.'} ({Instead, he gave the sample line} 13... Be6 14. Qb3 b6 15. Rac1 c6 16. a4 Qd7 17. Kh2 {, in which Black is very solid.}) 14. Rc1 Qd7 15. Bf4 {John Bartholomew: '!' John Bartholomew: 'Heading for e5 to harass the knight on f6. Black also experiences problems with the c-pawn.'} Bb7 16. Be5 Nh7 17. c5 {John Bartholomew: 'Hikaru burned a ton of time before playing this move.'} ({The players examined the cute variation} 17. cxd5 Rac8 18. Qg4 Qxg4 (18... f5 $5) 19. hxg4 Nf6 20. Bxf6 gxf6 21. d6 Bxg2 22. d7 Bxf1 23. Rxc7 Rcd8 24. dxe8=Q+ Rxe8 25. Kxf1 Rd8 26. Rxa7 Rxd4 {, concluding that Black draws.}) ({They also examined} 17. Qg4 $5 {which may in fact be most promising.}) 17... Rac8 {John Bartholomew: 'Not bad, but Howell admitted that he underestimated White's next few moves.'} ({Instead} 17... c6 $5 {is interesting.}) 18. h4 Nf8 19. Kh2 bxc5 20. Bh3 Ne6 21. Rxc5 f6 22. Bf4 Qd8 (22... Qf7 $5) 23. Ra5 ({Attacking a7, but maybe the restrained} 23. Rc1 {was preferable.}) 23... c5 {John Bartholomew: '!?' John Bartholomew: 'Bold! Howell was drifting into bad time trouble around here.'} (23... a6 24. Re1 $16) 24. Rxa7 Qb6 25. Ra4 Nxd4 26. Qh5 ({Black has excellent compensation for the exchange after} 26. Bxc8 Bxc8 {. Knowing Nakamura's style and (taking into account Howell's time pressure), you could be almost certain that White would counterattack rather than bank material.}) 26... Qc6 $2 {John Bartholomew: '??' John Bartholomew: 'A blunder with his flag about to fall.'} (26... f5 {John Bartholomew: '!' John Bartholomew: 'is necessary. White has full compensation after'} 27. Be3 (27. Rxd4 cxd4 28. Bxf5 Ra8 {, but Black has all his bases covered.}) 27... g6 $11) 27. Rb1 {John Bartholomew: '?!'} (27. Rxd4 {was immediately winning, e.g.} cxd4 28. Bf5 Re7 29. Qg6 Kf8 30. Qh7 {. Black can barely move and will soon be crushed:} Ra8 31. Bg6 Qe6 32. Bd6 $18 ({or} 32. Re1 $18)) 27... Ra8 $2 (27... Ba6 28. Bxc8 Bxc8) (27... f5 {was again necessary.} 28. Ra7 Re7 29. a4 $16) 28. Rxa8 $18 Rxa8 29. Bg2 {John Bartholomew: ''} (29. Re1 {John Bartholomew: '+-'} Kf8 30. Bxh6 $1) 29... Ne6 $2 {John Bartholomew: 'The final mistake.'} (29... f5 30. Be5 Rf8) 30. Rxb7 $1 $18 {John Bartholomew: '!'} Qxb7 31. Bxd5 Qc8 32. Bxh6 {John Bartholomew: '!' John Bartholomew: 'Removing any doubts about the result.'} Ra6 (32... gxh6 33. Qg6+ Kf8 (33... Kh8 34. Qxh6+ Kg8 35. Qg6+ Kh8 36. Qxf6+ Ng7 37. Qh6#) 34. Qxf6+ Ke8 35. Bxe6 Qc6 36. Qe5 $18) 33. Be3 Rd6 34. Bxc5 $5 Rxd5 35. Qxd5 Kf7 36. Be3 Qa6 37. Qc4 Qa8 38. d4 1-0


