1. e4 ({The London line mentioned in one of the notes is} 1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 cxd4 6. exd4 Bf5 7. Bb5 e6 8. Ne5 Qb6 9. c4 dxc4 10. Bxc6+ bxc6 11. Ndxc4) 1... c6 2. d4 ({There is of course a lot of overlap with} 2. Nf3 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Ne5 {but this line seems more easily disarmed by} Nc6 5. d4 a6 $1 {, among other things.}) 2... d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Nf3 {With very few exceptions, this line has largely passed under the radar as far as ChessPublishing is concerned. My feeling is that with the publication of Gawain's Coffeehouse repertoire, it will increase in popularity and it will be necessary to cover!} Nf6 ({My recommendation for Black is checked in the other game from this month.} 4... Nc6 5. Bb5 (5. c3 $5 Bg4 $1 $11 {Smirnov,A-Kobalia, M INT 2020}) 5... Bg4 $5 {With an accurate sequence of moves after this Black will equalise too.} (5... Nf6 {It might not be so easy to equalise after this.} 6. O-O $1 ({Not} 6. Ne5 Bd7 7. Nxd7 Qxd7 8. c3 a6 $1 $11 {and since Black hasn't played ...e6 yet, there is still potential to go .. .e5 in one.}) 6... e6 7. Ne5 $1 Bd7 8. Nxd7 Qxd7 9. c3 {This position was discussed in Shankland-Ding, INT 2019.}) (5... a6 $6 6. Bxc6+ bxc6 7. c4 $1 $14 {Black suffers from poor development.}) ({After} 5... Bd7 $6 6. c4 $1 e6 7. Nc3 Nf6 8. O-O $14 {Black's best will be to go for a passive IQP type position.}) (5... e6 6. Ne5 Bd7 (6... Qc7 7. Bf4 Bd6 8. Qg4 $1 $14 {is unpleasant.}) 7. Nxd7 Qxd7 8. c3 Bd6 9. O-O Nge7 (9... Nf6 10. Nd2 {again transposes to 4...Nf6 and to Shankland,S-Ding,L INT 2019.}) 10. Nd2 O-O 11. Re1 $14 {White has achieved a pleasant bishop-pair position anyway. Groszpeter,A-Lyell,M Hungary 2018}) (5... Qa5+ $1 {is examined in Haria-Derakhshani.}) (5... g6 $6 6. Ne5 $14 {and Black must do something or other that creates an odd impression when combined with .. .g6.}) 6. c4 $1 e6 $1 {The more accurate move-order, reserving judgment on ... dxc4 issues.} (6... dxc4 $6 7. d5 a6 8. Ba4 b5 9. dxc6 $16 {is dire for Black}) (6... Nf6 7. Nc3 $1 e6 (7... g6 $6 8. h3 Bxf3 9. Qxf3 $16 {Carlsen,M-Savchenko, B Moscow 2019}) 8. h3 $1 Bxf3 9. Qxf3 {Yoo, C-Villegas,P INT 2019 Gawain finds an advantage here for White and I don't see a reason to disagree.}) 7. Nc3 dxc4 $5 (7... Nf6 8. h3 Bxf3 9. Qxf3 {is again Yoo-Villegas above.}) 8. h3 $146 {Likely the best try.} (8. O-O {Hovhannisyan,R-Marcus,H INT 2018} Bd6 $1 9. Bxc4 Nge7 $11) 8... Bh5 (8... Bxf3 9. Qxf3 Rc8 10. O-O Nf6 11. Bg5 $14) 9. O-O Nf6 $13 {Here the most White can hope for is to keep the enemy king in the centre. However this involves pushing the g-pawn far enough that White's own king safety can't be considered completely assured.}) (4... e6 5. Bd3 $5 $14 {is very little played but gives a pleasant Londonlike position.} ({After the maximalist} 5. Ne5 {Black can equalise.} Nd7 $1 6. Bd3 Bd6 7. f4 Nh6 $1 $146 {As far as I am aware this move has not been considered by anybody, but the idea of preparing . ..f6 is a totally normal one.} 8. O-O O-O 9. Qe2 Kh8 $11) (5. Bf4 $5 {is similar to Bd3. Murzin,V-Iordachescu,V Krasnaya Polyana 2021})) (4... Bf5 5. Ne5 Nc6 (5... Nd7 6. Nc3 $1 Ngf6 7. g4 $40) 6. Bb5 Rc8 7. Qe2 $1 Nf6 (7... e6 8. g4 $1 $16 {Jones}) 8. Bf4 Qb6 9. c3 a6 (9... e6 10. Nd2 {leads to even more unpleasant pressure in the long run.}) 10. Ba4 Nd7 (10... Qa5 11. Bxc6+ $1 bxc6 12. O-O $16) 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. O-O e6 13. a3 $14 {Reaching a similar bind to the one seen in Haria-Derakhshani.}) (4... a6 $5 {deserves much more attention.} 5. c4 $5 (5. Ne5 {here is not so good, e.g.} Nc6 6. c4 (6. c3 Bf5 $5 {or 6...Nxe5 and then ...Bf5 offers White little.}) 6... Nxe5 7. dxe5 e6 8. cxd5 (8. Be2 Ne7 9. O-O Bd7 $11 {Followed by . ..Bc6. White should probably stop thinking about being better here and focus on not overextending.}) 8... Qxd5 9. Qxd5 exd5 10. Nc3 Bb4 $11 {Murzin,V-Dreev,A Cheboksary 2021}) 5... Nf6 6. cxd5 $5 {White tries to find some version of the IQP positions where ...a6 is not a useful insertion.} (6. Nc3 Nc6 7. c5 Bg4 $1 (7... g6 8. h3 {leaves White a nice grip on the e5-square, e.g.} Bf5 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 Bg7 11. O-O $14) 8. Be2 g6 $1 9. Ne5 Bxe2 10. Nxe2 {Durarbayli, V-Blomqvist,E INT 2021} Bg7 $1 $11) 6... Nxd5 7. Bc4 e6 (7... Nc6 {leads to an easier edge after super-incisive play:} 8. Bxd5 $1 Qxd5 9. Nc3 Qc4 10. d5 Nb4 11. Ne5 Qd4 $1 12. O-O $1 $14) 8. O-O Be7 9. Nc3 Nc6 $1 {Now we are unfortunately just going to get a normal Panov again.} ({Not} 9... Nxc3 10. bxc3 O-O 11. Bd3 $14 {and Black's ...a6 is a bit out of place. Emms, J-Arkell, K Aberystwyth 2014}) (9... O-O 10. Bxd5 $5 $13 {The best try for an advantage, and incidentally also one that fits with the general aim of avoiding super-mainline theory.} ({Jones gives} 10. Re1 {here as well.})) 10. Bb3 O-O 11. Re1 {Black's most accurate answer is probably} Nf6 $5 {heading back into a theoretical c3-Sicilian/QGA position. Strong grandmasters have found little to write home about for White.}) (4... Bg4 5. h3 Bxf3 {The only consistent move, but White gets a pleasant bishop-pair edge now.} (5... Bh5 $6 6. g4 $1 Bg6 7. Ne5 $40) 6. Qxf3 Nc6 7. c3 Nf6 8. Bd3 $14) (4... g6 5. Be2 $5 Bg7 6. O-O $14 {White can simply handle this in normal London style and things should go well.}) 5. Ne5 g6 {Admitting to being slightly worse but just trying to play a long game.} ({The main equalising try is} 5... Nc6 {but it might not work out:} 6. c3 $1 {A relatively minor but very interesting move-order.} (6. Bb5 Bd7 $1 (6... Qb6 $6 7. c4 $1 $16 {leads to a worse version of the main line. Kuybokarov,T-Murzin,V INT 2020}) (6... Qa5+ 7. Nc3 {was Smirin,I-Svidler,P Netanya 2019, see Justin's notes in the Archives.}) 7. Nxd7 Qxd7 8. c3 a6 {Since Black hasn't been forced to play ...e6 yet, it is possible to go ...e5 in one move.}) 6... e6 (6... Bf5 {is very natural now that White has omitted to 'force' ...Bd7.} 7. Bb5 Qb6 $1 8. c4 $1 dxc4 (8... Nd7 9. Nxd7 Bxd7 10. O-O dxc4 11. Nc3 Qxd4 12. Qa4 $40) 9. Na3 e6 10. Bxc6+ bxc6 11. Naxc4 Qa6 12. Qe2 Bb4+ 13. Bd2 $14 {Curiously, we have transposed into Aronian, L-Inarkiev,E Moscow 2019 (which started as a London system.) Black's position is a little bit unpleasant.}) (6... a6 7. Bd3 g6 (7... Nxe5 $6 8. dxe5 Ng4 (8... Nd7 9. e6 $16) 9. f4 Qb6 10. Qe2 $16) (7... e6 8. Nd2 $5 Nxe5 9. dxe5 Nd7 10. Nf3 $14) 8. O-O Bg7 {Just} 9. Re1 $14 {as in Ponomariov, R-Keymer,V Dortmund 2021 should be enough.}) (6... g6 $6 7. Bb5 Qb6 {It at least makes sense to try and play this as soon as White has committed to c3 rather than c4, but firstly that is not irreversible (see previous note) and secondly White also has other options.} 8. Qb3 $1 $146 e6 (8... Bg7 9. Bxc6+ bxc6 10. Qxb6 axb6 11. Nxc6 $16) 9. O-O Bd6 10. Bh6 $40) 7. Nd2 {An interesting extra option.} ({There is also still} 7. Bb5 Bd7 8. Nxd7 Qxd7 {returning to Shankland-Ding.}) 7... Bd6 8. f4 g6 {Anand,V-Vallejo Pons, F Leon 2008} 9. Bd3 $40) (5... Bf5 {is met by} 6. Nc3 $1 $14 {followed by g4 with good tactical chances of a quick victory.}) 6. Be2 {Not a new move and also not a harmless one. The only square White's bishop should avoid is d3 (since .. .Bf5 'comes with tempo') and this one is almost as good as b5.} (6. Bb5+ $5 {is the normal theoretical recommendation.} Nbd7 (6... Bd7 7. Nxd7 Nbxd7 8. O-O Bg7 9. c3 (9. Re1 $5) 9... O-O 10. Nd2 Qb6 11. Qa4 Qc7 12. Nf3 $14 {Fitzsimons, D-O'Donnell,C Dublin 2021}) 7. O-O Bg7 (7... a6 $5 8. Be2 $146 {followed by Nd3 will leave Black's piece arrangement looking a bit strange.}) 8. Nf3 $5 (8. Re1 {is also possible first}) 8... O-O 9. Re1 Ne4 ({The machine also suggests the rather arcane} 9... Nb8 {but White can hardly not be better, e.g.} 10. c3 Nc6 11. h3 $14 {Kobalia,M-Tari,A INT 2021}) 10. Nbd2 Nd6 {Jones,G-Karjakin,S INT 2020} 11. Bf1 $1 $14 {Followed by a4, c3 and Nb3. In the game White played Be2 trying to keep the f1-square for the knight as well, but it looked less convincing.}) 6... Bg7 7. O-O O-O 8. Nd2 $11 {With a similar Londonlike position to the ones after Bb5+, but the advantages (not being hit by ...a6 with tempo) are less important than the disadvantages (Black can arrange their queenside how they like without needing to play ... Nd7-b8.)} Nc6 (8... Nfd7 $1 {has been tried before and is a more serious attempt to extract a usable concession.} 9. Ndf3 Nxe5 10. Nxe5 Nc6 (10... f6 $5 11. Nd3 e5 $132) 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. c3 {Cardoso Pimenta,C-Aranha Filho,A Montevideo 2015} e5 $1 $11) 9. c3 Bf5 ({Another attempt to remove the e5-knight without excessively clunky manoeuvres was} 9... Ne8 $1 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Nb3 Nd6 $11 {as in Brinovec, D-Zelcic,R Portoroz 2019}) 10. Nb3 Ne4 11. Bf4 f6 12. Nd3 $6 ({After} 12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. f3 Nd6 14. Nc5 e5 15. Be3 $14 {White can claim some kind of positional bind.}) 12... e5 13. Be3 b6 ({Black is at least not worse here and can even consider the maximalist} 13... Nd6 {with the idea of ...Nc4.}) 14. a3 a5 15. f3 {Driving Black's knight where it wanted to go.} (15. Nd2 {was possible but also doesn't solve all the problems. Black's central pawn duo continues to have immense practical power.}) 15... Nd6 16. Nd2 Be6 17. Bf2 Bf7 18. a4 Re8 19. Ne1 Ra7 $6 ({White's position has been getting steadily worse for a few moves now, and the concrete} 19... exd4 20. cxd4 Qe7 21. Bd3 Nb4 $19 {would already have posed him insuperable problems.}) 20. Nc2 {White embarks on a strong reorganising plan that will see him on the road to recovery.} Rae7 21. dxe5 $1 Nxe5 ({Noritsyn was of course using the fact that Black temporarily can't play} 21... fxe5 22. Bh4 $14 {, or at least would have to think very long and hard before offering the exchange quite so freely.}) 22. Re1 Bh6 23. Bf1 Qc7 24. Nd4 Qb7 25. Qc2 ({By contrast to the note from 5 moves ago, here it is White that could have used some of the holes in his opponent's position with} 25. Nb5 $14) 25... Kg7 26. Rad1 Rd8 ({With an IQP and this many pieces, Black has to play actively or risk running out of oxygen. A good option was} 26... Nec4 $11 {maintaining equality. As things were, it soon became Black's turn to 'slide'.}) 27. b3 Ree8 28. Nb1 Rc8 29. Qb2 Qb8 30. Na3 Nb7 31. Bb5 Re7 32. Bg3 $16 Rcc7 {Presenting White with a tactical opportunity that he does not miss. The execution from here was clinical.} (32... Nd8 {avoids immediate material losses but looks extremely miserable.}) 33. Nc6 Nxc6 34. Bxc6 Qd8 35. Bxc7 Rxc7 36. Bxb7 Rxb7 37. Nb5 Rd7 38. Qf2 Bf4 39. g3 Be5 40. Kg2 g5 41. Qd2 Bg6 42. Nd4 Qc8 43. Ne6+ Kg8 44. Nd4 Rc7 45. Re3 Bf7 46. Rde1 Kg7 47. Rxe5 fxe5 48. Qxg5+ Kf8 49. Qxe5 Rxc3 50. Qh8+ Bg8 51. Qf6+ Bf7 52. Ne6+ Ke8 53. Ng5+ Kd7 54. Re7+ 1-0


