1. e4 {Moradiabadi,E It is funny how both leaders played their best game of the two rounds in the sixth round.} e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 dxe4 $5 {An interesting choice by Howell.} 5. Nxe4 Be7 6. Nxf6+ {It seems that the Ukrainain GM, who is known for his aggressive style, was caught off guard. Thus, Onischuk goes for a less common line.} (6. Bxf6 gxf6 {is considered the mainline. However, Onischuk may have not been prepared against ...xf6.}) 6... Bxf6 7. Bxf6 Qxf6 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Qd2 c5 $1 {This is a mainline and equaliser. Could it be that Howell wanted more complications?} 10. O-O-O Rd8 11. Qc3 cxd4 {Another long pause for a well-known forced line.} 12. Rxd4 Rxd4 13. Qxd4 Qxd4 14. Nxd4 {This is a completely equal endgame. The way the British GM outplays his strong opponent reminds one of Capablanca's victories. Either it was bad day at the office for the Ukrainian or a Magnus-like performance from Howell. Either way this game is a great example and a worthy textbook lesson!} b6 15. Be2 Bb7 16. Nb5 Nd7 17. Rd1 Nf6 18. f3 {This is an ugly move and a bad sign. I would rather play g3 and keep my pawns on the squares that do not restrict my bishop.} Kf8 19. c4 Ke7 20. Kd2 g5 $1 {A great move by Howell. This is a typical move that every coach shows to their students. Black is trying to undermine White's pawn structure with ...g4. Another reason why f3 was not necessary.} 21. Ke3 Bc6 22. Nc3 a5 $1 {A great prohylactic move which costs White more moves to create a mobile majority. It is noteworthy to see that a3 will be faced with a4.} 23. b3 h6 24. a3 Ne8 $1 {Another excellent idea from Howell. The knight is going to d6 from where it can support Black's kingside majority.} 25. g4 {Tactically sound but still very ugly! Do not put your pawns on the same colour as your bishop in the endgame!} Nd6 26. f4 Rc8 27. Rc1 f5 $1 {Now the situation is critical and only accurate play can give White a draw.} 28. h3 Kf6 29. Rd1 $2 {A surprising losing blunder.} (29. fxg5+ hxg5 30. gxf5 exf5 31. Bf3 {was needed and White should sit tight and prepare to defend a probable rook and pawn endgame with a pawn down but where a draw is still very much a conceivable outcome.}) 29... gxf4+ 30. Kxf4 e5+ 31. Ke3 f4+ {Now Black's central pawns are unstoppable. The game is decided both practically and scientifically!} 32. Kf2 Ke6 33. Nd5 Ne4+ 34. Ke1 Bxd5 35. Rxd5 Nc3 36. Bd3 e4 37. Rd4 Ke5 38. Rd7 Ke6 39. Rd4 Ke5 40. Rd7 exd3 41. Rxd3 Nb1 42. a4 Ke4 43. Rd1 Nc3 44. Rd6 Ke3 {A lesson for all of us: Never play outside your element. Vladimir Onischuk is an ultra-sharp player with an aggressive style with both colours. That is what he is good at. By choosing a calm position against David Howell, he just got himself into the wrong psychological battle where he had to play against his own preference. More experienced and more universal, Howell on the other hand exploited every small mistake by Onischuk to score a crucial victory with Black.} 0-1


