1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Bc4 c5 8. Ne2 Nc6 9. Be3 O-O 10. O-O Na5 11. Bd3 b6 12. Qd2 e5 {Despite its great popularity, this particular game was the only example of this counter-thrust from the Olympiad. Marin,Mihail: 'Glenn Flear: 'Despite its great popularity, this particular game was the only example of this counter-thrust from the Olympiad.''} 13. Bh6 cxd4 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. cxd4 exd4 16. Rac1 {Here White players sometimes do without this move and play Marin,Mihail: 'Glenn Flear: 'Here White players sometimes do without this move and play''} (16. f4 {immediately. See Rodshtein-So (in the archives) for the most recent example where Black demonstrated a convincing defence.}) 16... Bb7 $5 {This natural developing move hasn't been employed that often, probably because the bishop can be useful on the c8-h3 diagonal. Marin,Mihail: 'Glenn Flear: '!?' Glenn Flear: 'This natural developing move hasn't been employed that often, probably because the bishop can be useful on the c8-h3 diagonal.''} ({Or Marin,Mihail: 'Glenn Flear: 'Or''} 16... Qd6 {as in the famous clash Topalov-Anand from their first match game earlier this year (see the archives). Marin,M: 'was played in Topalov,V (2805)-Anand,V (2787)/Sofia 2010/CBM 136/[Krasenkow] (1-0, 30)' Marin,Mihail: 'was played in Topalov,V (2805)-Anand,V (2787)/Sofia 2010/CBM 136/[Krasenkow] (1-0, 30) Glenn Flear: 'as in the famous clash Topalov-Anand from their first match game earlier this year (see the archives).''}) 17. f4 Rc8 ({The case for} 17... f6 $6 {is weakened by the placement of the bishop on a square which doesn't defend e6. Then} 18. f5 Qd6 19. Nf4 {already looks dangerous for Black.}) 18. f5 $5 {Marin,M: 'N' 'N' Marin,Mihail: 'N' 'N' Marin,Mihail: 'Glenn Flear: '!?''} ({Previous games have seen Marin,Mihail: 'Glenn Flear: 'Previous games have seen'' Marin,M: 'Black somehow managed to survive after'} 18. Rxc8 Qxc8 ({otherwise} 18... Bxc8 $5 19. f5 (19. Qb2 $1 Qd6 20. Nxd4 {is worth a small pull}) 19... Nc6 20. Nf4 (20. Bb5 Bb7 21. Bxc6 Bxc6 22. Rf3 Kh8 $1 23. fxg6 Bxe4 $1 $11) 20... Ne5 21. Nd5 {0.5-0.5 Peralta-Alonso, La Plata 2008} (21. f6+ Kh8 22. Nd5 Be6 23. Bb1 Bxd5 24. exd5 d3 25. Qb4 Qc8 $1 {and Black is fine}) 21... gxf5 $1 {and I prefer Black}) 19. f5 Nc6 20. Rf3 (20. f6+ Kh8 21. Qh6 Rg8 22. Rf3 Qf8 $11) (20. Bb5 $5 Qd8 $1) 20... Ne5 21. Rh3 Rh8 22. f6+ $1 {Marin,Mihail: 'Glenn Flear: '!''} Kg8 {Karjakin, S-Carlsen, M Foros 2008, with an edge to White. So if 18 Rxc8 does indeed yield something then this suggests that 16...Bb7 isn't such a great defence for Black. Marin,Mihail: 'Glenn Flear: 'Karjakin, S-Carlsen, M Foros 2008, with an edge to White. So if 18 Rxc8 does indeed yield something then this suggests that 16...Bb7 isn't such a great defence for Black.''} 23. Qh6 Qf8 {Karjakin,S (2732)-Carlsen,M (2765)/Foros 2008/CBM 125 (1/2, 30)}) 18... Nc6 $6 {A slack move. Marin,Mihail: 'Glenn Flear: '?!' Glenn Flear: 'A slack move.''} ({More precise is to exchange rooks first:} 18... Rxc1 $1 19. Qxc1 Nc6 {when White has less options. Then after} 20. f6+ Kh8 21. Qh6 Rg8 22. Rf4 (22. Rf3 Bc8 $1) 22... Qf8 {Black is better able to stave off the attack than in the game.}) 19. f6+ Kh8 20. Qg5 (20. Qh6) 20... Re8 21. Qh6 Rg8 {Marin,Mihail: 'transposes to the game.'} 22. Rf3 Qf8 {Without the rooks on c1 and c8 Black would have the additional option of ...Bc8. Marin,Mihail: 'Glenn Flear: 'Without the rooks on c1 and c8 Black would have the additional option of ...Bc8.''} 23. Qh4 h6 (23... h5 $5 {is possible, planning ...Kh7 and ...Qh6.}) 24. Rh3 Kh7 {This obviously looks dangerous for Black, but perhaps it is tenable with precise defence. Marin,Mihail: 'Glenn Flear: 'This obviously looks dangerous for Black, but perhaps it is tenable with precise defence.''} 25. Rxc6 $5 {A dynamic exchange sacrifice to eliminate the omnipresent threat of ...Ne5. Marin,Mihail: 'Glenn Flear: 'A dynamic exchange sacrifice to eliminate the omnipresent threat of ...Ne5.'' Marin,M: 'Here is where this rook was needed! The piece that was about to block the e-pawn is eliminated.'} ({White could instead keep the tension with} 25. Qg5 $5 {but Black is able to wriggle out with precise play:} Nb4 $1 ({after} 25... Re8 $6 26. Qf4 $1 {White is better due to the possibility of playing on both wings:} (26. Rxc6 $6 Bxc6 27. e5 {is what one's hand wants to play but after} Bd7 28. Rh4 Be6 29. Ng3 Rc8 ({or perhaps} 29... Rh8 30. Ne4 Kg8) 30. Ne4 Rh8 $1 {there is no obvious breakthrough}) 26... Rc8 (26... h5 27. Bb5) (26... Ne5 27. Bb5 Bc8 28. Bxe8 Bxh3 29. Qxe5) 27. e5 {with a strong initiative}) 26. Bc4 h5 $1 27. a3 $1 {After long deliberation I think this is White's best.} (27. e5 {is the natural move but after} Qh6 $1 28. Qxh6+ Kxh6 29. Bxf7 d3 {Black's position turns out to be superior e.g.} 30. Nc3 Rgf8 31. Bb3 (31. e6 Nxa2 $1) 31... Rce8 32. a3 Na6 {as White cannot maintain his pawn front}) 27... d3 28. axb4 ({worse is} 28. Bxd3 Nxd3 29. Rxc8 Bxc8 30. Rxd3 Ba6 {when Black is past his difficulties and can start playing for a win}) 28... dxe2 29. Bxe2 Qh6 30. Qxh6+ Kxh6 $11 {The endgame seems to be equal.}) 25... Rxc6 26. e5 Bc8 27. g4 {All White's eggs are in the kingside basket! Marin,Mihail: 'Glenn Flear: 'All White's eggs are in the kingside basket!'' Marin,M: 'Computers are happy with black, but I guess that most humans would feel incomfortable.'} Rc5 (27... Rh8 {is worth consideration, so as to play ...Kg8,} 28. Qg5 Kg8 29. Qf4 Qb4 $5) 28. Qg5 Rh8 $5 {This move threatens ...Kg8, so induces White's reply. Marin,Mihail: 'Glenn Flear: '!?' '(although Black can try one of the alternatives above)' Glenn Flear: 'This move threatens ...Kg8, so induces White's reply.''} ({An alternative idea is} 28... Ra5 {but White seems to be able to get away with} 29. Nxd4 $1 (29. Bc4 {can be met with} Ra3 30. Rh4 d3 $1 31. Nd4 d2 $1 32. Qxd2 g5 33. Bd3+ Kh8 {and White's attack runs out of steam}) 29... Ra4 30. Qf4 Rh8 (30... a5 31. Rh4 Rh8 {can even be met by} 32. Bxg6+ $1 {when the attack becomes life-threatening}) 31. Bc2 Rxa2 32. e6 $1 Bxe6 33. Nxe6 fxe6 34. Rc3 Ra1+ 35. Kg2 {and the attack is now too strong.}) (28... Bxg4 $5 {is another idea, returning material to stop White's initiative,} 29. Qxg4 Rxe5 30. Kf2 Qc5 {and the white king is exposed.}) (28... Bf5 $5 {is tricky,} 29. Bxf5 gxf5 30. Qxf5+ Kh8 31. Nxd4 Rg6 32. Qf4 {unclear.}) 29. Nf4 {Marin,Mihail: 'Glenn Flear: '=''} Rg8 {Back again! White has pressure, but no forced breakthrough whereas Black has an extra exchange but is tied down. The result is in the balance. Marin,Mihail: 'Glenn Flear: 'Back again! White has pressure, but no forced breakthrough whereas Black has an extra exchange but is tied down. The result is in the balance.''} 30. Rh5 $5 {Spectacular-looking but it shouldn't worry Black. White should instead repeat by dropping the knight back to e2. Marin,Mihail: 'Glenn Flear: '!?' Glenn Flear: 'Spectacular-looking but it shouldn't worry Black. White should instead repeat by dropping the knight back to e2.''} (30. Ne2 Rh8 {(although Black can try one of the alternatives above)} (30... Rd5 31. Bc4 $1) (30... Ra5 31. Nxd4 $1) 31. Nf4 $11) 30... Ba6 $5 {Marin,Mihail: 'Glenn Flear: '!?''} ({Black could play} 30... Rc1+ 31. Kf2 Rc3 {(to liquidate the bishop)} 32. Be4 Re3 33. Nh3 $1 Rxh3 34. Rxh3 Be6) ({or perhaps} 30... Bd7 31. Rh4 Be8 32. Be4 d3 (32... Rh8 33. Nd5) 33. Nxd3 Ra5 {when he shouldn't be worse.}) 31. Be4 $5 {Marin,Mihail: 'Glenn Flear: '!?''} (31. Bxa6 $2 {loses to the calm} gxh5) ({However White has a draw here if he desires:} 31. Ne6 $1 fxe6 32. f7 Bxd3 33. Rxh6+ Kg7 34. Qf6+ Kxh6 35. Qh4+ Kg7 36. Qf6+ $11) 31... Rc1+ {Risky. Marin,Mihail: 'Glenn Flear: 'Risky.''} (31... Bb7 32. Bd3 Ba6 (32... Rc1+) 33. Be4 {repeats.}) 32. Kf2 d3 $4 {Leaving the rook on a rather unfortunate square. Marin,M: '?' '?' Marin,Mihail: '?' '?' Marin,Mihail: 'Glenn Flear: '??' Glenn Flear: 'Leaving the rook on a rather unfortunate square.''} ({Correct seems to be} 32... Rf1+ 33. Kg2 (33. Kg3 Bc4 {(covering some key squares)} 34. Nh3 Rh8 35. Nf4 Kg8 $1 {and White's major pieces are en prise}) 33... Ra1 34. Kg3 $1 (34. Ne6 $2 {now fails:} Rxa2+ 35. Kg1 Ra1+ 36. Kg2 fxe6 37. f7 Bf1+ 38. Kg3 Ra3+ 39. Kf2 {and Black captures the f-pawn with check...} Qxf7+) 34... Rxa2 35. Nh3 Ra3+ 36. Kg2 {(threatening Qxh6+, mating!)} (36. Kf4 Rxh3 37. Rxh3 Bc4) 36... Rh8 (36... Rxh3 37. Rxh3 Bc4 {may be playable}) (36... Ra2+ {draws}) 37. Qxg6+ $1 {Delightful and forced!} fxg6 38. Ng5+ Kg8 39. Bd5+ Qf7 40. Bxf7+ Kf8 41. e6 Ra2+ 42. Kg3 Ra3+ 43. Kf2 Ra2+ 44. Kg3 $11 {and neither side dare avoid the draw.}) (32... Ra1 33. Nh3 Rxa2+ 34. Kg1 $11) 33. Ne6 {Marin,M: '!' '!' Marin,Mihail: '!' '!'} (33. Nh3 $1 Rh8 (33... d2 34. Qxh6+ Qxh6 35. Ng5+ Kh8 36. Rxh6#) 34. Bd5 $3 Qc5+ (34... d2 35. Qxg6+ fxg6 36. Ng5#) 35. Kg3 Rg1+ 36. Nxg1 Qxg1+ 37. Kh3 Qf1+ 38. Bg2 $18) 33... fxe6 34. Qxc1 d2 $2 {Panicking as things have clearly gone wrong, but Black can no longer do anything whereas White threatens Q-g5, K moves off the f-file and then f6-f7. Marin,Mihail: 'Glenn Flear: '?' Glenn Flear: 'Panicking as things have clearly gone wrong, but Black can no longer do anything whereas White threatens Q-g5, K moves off the f-file and then f6-f7.''} 35. Qxd2 Qc5+ 36. Kg2 1-0


