1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. Bf4 Bg4 7. Qb3 Qc8 8. Nd2 e6 9. Ngf3 Be7 10. O-O O-O 11. Ne5 Nxe5 (11... Bh5 {is more usual.}) 12. dxe5 Nd7 13. Qc2 g6 14. h3 Bf5 15. Bxf5 gxf5 16. Nf3 Kh8 17. Ng5 ({A slower build-up with} 17. Rad1 {may be stronger, as it allows less counterplay.}) 17... Qc4 18. Qd2 Nc5 19. Rad1 Rac8 20. b3 Qa6 21. c4 {Commencing a very interesting and dangerous-looking idea, although the computer is not convinced.} dxc4 22. Qe2 {The point. The white queen joins the attack on the kingside.} Bxg5 23. Bxg5 Ne4 24. Qh5 Rg8 25. Bh4 Rg6 26. f3 Qxa2 {Objectively, it seems that Blck is winning, but both players were short of time by now, and the position is still very complicated.} 27. g4 Nc3 28. Rf2 Qxb3 29. Rd7 Rf8 30. Be7 Qb5 31. Rfd2 fxg4 32. Bxf8 gxf3+ $2 ({This actually allows an amazing draw, but one can hardly expect the players to see the variations involved. Instead,} 32... Qb6+ 33. Kh2 Ne2 $1 {is winning, eg.} 34. Rxe2 gxf3 {etc.}) 33. Kh2 Qb6 34. R7d4 $2 ({here, the computer points out the incredible drawing line, starting} 34. Bg7+ $3 {Now both captures fail to win: The correct move, which Howell had intended, is} Kg8 {when White has the remarkable follow-up} (34... Kxg7 35. Rxf7+ Kxf7 36. Qxh7+ {is perpetual}) ({whilst} 34... Rxg7 $2 {actually loses after} 35. Rd8+ Rg8 36. Rxg8+ Kxg8 37. Qg5+) 35. Qxg6 $1 hxg6 36. Bf6 {threatening mate. Howell had even seen this, and thought he could escape the perpetual with} g5 {but it turns out that he cannot, since after} 37. Rd8+ Kh7 38. Rh8+ Kg6 39. Rg8+ Kf5 40. Rxg5+ Kf4 41. Rg4+ {he has to acquiesce in the draw, in view of} Ke3 $4 42. Bg5#) 34... Ne2 {Now Black is winning once again.} 35. Qxf3 Nxd4 36. Qe3 Nf3+ 0-1


