1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. h4 Bg7 6. h5 Nc6 7. g3 e5 8. h6 (8. Bg2 {seems to be more flexible.} Nxc3 (8... Be6 9. d3 $14 {[%cal Gf3g5]}) 9. dxc3 $6 (9. bxc3 e4 10. h6 Bf6 (10... Bxc3 11. dxc3 Qxd1+ 12. Kxd1 exf3 13. Bxf3 $14) 11. Nh2 O-O (11... Bf5 12. g4 Be6 13. Bxe4 {I don't think Black has enough play for the central pawn.}) 12. Bxe4 Re8 13. Bg2 Qd3 14. Kf1 Qa6 15. d4 $14) 9... Qxd1+ 10. Kxd1 Bg4 11. h6 Bf6 12. Ng5 Be7 13. Be3 f6 14. Ne4 Rd8+ 15. Ke1 Be6 16. b3 Kf7 $11 {½-½ (31) Van Wely,L (2640)-Wei,Y (2706) Wijk aan Zee 2016}) 8... Bf6 9. Bg2 O-O (9... Nxc3 10. dxc3 Qxd1+ 11. Kxd1 Be7 12. Be3 f6 13. Nd2 Bf5 $11 {½-½ (64) Khenkin,I (2656)-Safarli,E (2620) Istanbul 2012}) 10. O-O {The position is similar to one arising from the English opening. Just there is a surprising pawn on h6, which can either yield White attacking prospects, or become a target.} Re8 11. Ne4 (11. d3 {was preferable, not worrying about} Nxc3 $6 12. bxc3 e4 13. dxe4 Qxd1 14. Rxd1 Bxc3 15. Rb1 $14) 11... Be7 12. d3 Bg4 13. Re1 Bxf3 14. Bxf3 Nd4 15. Bg2 c6 16. Bd2 a5 {The position is balanced.} 17. Rc1 Qb6 18. Nc3 Nf6 19. Na4 Qa7 20. e3 Ne6 21. Qb3 Bf8 22. Qb6 Bxh6 23. Qxa7 Rxa7 24. Nb6 Bf8 25. Nc4 Nc5 26. Nxe5 Rxe5 27. d4 Rf5 28. dxc5 Bxc5 29. Red1 Bb4 30. e4 Bxd2 31. Rxd2 Re5 32. f4 Re7 33. e5 Ne8 34. Rcd1 f6 35. Rd7 Kf7 36. Bh3 f5 37. Bf1 b5 38. Rd8 Nc7 39. R1d6 Ne6 40. Rh8 Kg7 41. Rc8 Nc5 42. Bg2 Rac7 43. Rxc6 Rxc6 44. Bxc6 b4 45. b3 Ne6 46. Bd5 g5 47. Bxe6 Rxe6 48. Kf2 h5 49. Rc7+ Kg6 50. Ke3 h4 51. gxh4 gxh4 52. Kf3 Ra6 53. Rc4 Kh5 54. Rc8 a4 55. Rf8 Kg6 56. Kg2 a3 57. Kh3 Rc6 58. Kxh4 Rc2 59. Rf6+ Kg7 60. Kg5 Rxa2 61. Ra6 Rb2 62. Ra7+ Kg8 63. Kg6 Kf8 64. Kf6 Kg8 65. e6 Rxb3 66. e7 Re3 67. Ra4 Kh7 68. Rxb4 Kh6 69. Rb8 Kh5 70. e8=Q+ Rxe8 71. Rxe8 Kg4 72. Ke5 1-0


