1. d4 {Swiercz,D} Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Qa4+ Qd7 8. Bb5 {This is a quite tricky and recently popular line against the Grünfeld. I hadn't played it before and my opponent was visibly surprised as he was spending quite a lot of time in the opening.} c6 9. Be2 O-O 10. Qa3 {It's important to start with this move as} (10. Nf3 {allows} c5 {and now in the event of} 11. Qa3 (11. Bb5 {was in Ivanisevic-Giri, but Black seems to be fine there:} Qg4 12. O-O cxd4 13. Ba3 Nc6 14. cxd4 Qxe4 15. Rfe1 Qd5 16. Bc4 Qa5 17. Qxa5 Nxa5 18. Bd5 Nc6 19. Bxe7 Re8 20. Bc5 Be6 $11 {Ivanisevic-Giri 2012}) {Black is clearly OK after} 11... cxd4 $1 12. cxd4 Nc6 13. Be3 Nxd4 (13... Qg4 $5 {is even stronger and White needs to fight for equality. The point is that} 14. Ng5 $2 {does not work due to} (14. O-O Qxe4 {and White needs to look hard for compensation there.}) 14... Nxd4 $1 $19) 14. Bxd4 Bxd4 15. Rd1 e5 16. O-O Re8 17. Rd2 Qe7 18. Qxe7 Rxe7 19. Nxd4 exd4 20. Rxd4 Be6 {1/2 (20) Riazantsev,A (2671)-Grigoriants,S (2594) St Petersburg RUS 2015}) 10... b6 11. Nf3 c5 12. O-O Bb7 {I think that this move is slightly dangerous for Black.} ({Two days later I used the same line against GM Baron Tal and he played} 12... cxd4 13. cxd4 Bb7 14. Qe3 Nc6 15. Bb2 Rac8 16. Rab1 e6 17. Rfd1 Rfd8 18. h4 {with some pressure, but the position is far from being clear.}) 13. d5 $1 e6 14. Be3 exd5 15. Rad1 $1 {This is the point. Black faces some unpleasant tension in the centre.} Nc6 {This is a novelty and most probably better than the move which had been played so far.} (15... d4 {was played afew times previously, but Black's position is very shaky.} 16. cxd4 Bxe4 17. dxc5 Qb7 18. Rfe1 Nd7 19. Ba6 Qc7 20. Bb5 Nf6 21. Bd4 {with a clear advantage for White, as happened in 2 games of GM Maxim Matlakov.}) 16. exd5 Ne5 {Exchanging the knights is in White's favour as Black has a bad b7 and if the knights exchange, the b7 problem will get bigger for Black.} ({In my opinion it was better to try to keep the knights on the board with} 16... Ne7 17. c4 Nf5 {but still after} 18. Bf4 {I think White is slightly better due to his space advantage and the very strong pawn on d5, which restricts Black's possibilities. Of course Black can play this position but in the long run most probably it will be unpleasant.}) 17. c4 Rfe8 18. Rfe1 Nxf3+ (18... Ng4 19. Bc1 {trying to keep the knights on the board doesn't make much sense as g4 doesn't improve its position.}) 19. Bxf3 Be5 20. Re2 Bd6 $2 {I think that this is the first quite serious mistake as starting from this move Black follows a wrong plan.} (20... Qd6 21. g3 Re7 {with the idea ae8 was a better defence but still Black's position is unpleasant.}) 21. Rde1 Qf5 22. Bc1 $1 {A strong move, I take under control the e-file.} Rxe2 23. Rxe2 {Now it's clear why ...d6 was a mistake - White threatens c3-b2 and Black's king position is very vulnerable.} b5 {Black tries to get some kind of counterplay and activate the b7.} (23... Qb1 24. Qc3 Bf4 25. Re1 Bxc1 26. Rxc1 Qb4 27. Qe5 $16 {with a big advantage. Now even h4-h5 is coming.}) (23... Be5 24. h4 $16 {with serious problems as well.}) 24. g4 $1 {I like this move as it practically puts Black in a very uncomfortable situation, especially in time trouble (David had less than 10 minutes here).} Qb1 $2 {A big mistake, but it was very difficult to decide to play ...f6 with the threat of b2-c3, especially in time trouble!} (24... Qf6 {was better but White maintains good winning chances anyway:} 25. Bb2 Qf4 26. Qc3 f6 {the only move} 27. Qxf6 Qxf6 28. Bxf6 bxc4 29. Re6 Bf8 30. g5 $16) 25. cxb5 Qxb5 {This move loses on the spot, but anyway the position was very difficult.} (25... Rd8 {was more stubborn but after} 26. Qb2 Qxb2 27. Bxb2 {White is just a pawn up with a huge advantage.}) 26. Qc3 $1 $18 {White's queen comes to f6 and Black's position collapses.} Qb4 27. Qf6 Qd4 28. Qxd6 Qd1+ 29. Kg2 Qxc1 30. Re7 Qb2 31. Qc7 Ba6 32. Qc6 1-0


