1. d4 e6 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bg5 {It's nice to see yet another ChessPub columnist straying into our territory.} h6 4. Bh4 g5 ({We've seen the slightly more restrained} 4... d6 {on plenty of occasions, but Howell doesn't want to waste any time while hunting down the Torre bishop.}) 5. Bg3 Ne4 6. Nbd2 ({Challenging Black's knight and so forcing the exchange (in the ...d6 and only then ...g5 lines, Black will tend to route his knight to h5 when he may well not need to hurry with the trade on g3). The text is common and sensible. One can also make a case for} 6. Nc3 $5 {, but after} Nxg3 ({principled and best instead,} 6... Nxc3 7. bxc3 d6 8. e4 {looks quite pleasant for White, with a timely h2-h4 possible,}) ({and} 6... Bb4 7. Qd3 f5 8. h4 Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 Nxg3 10. fxg3 g4 11. Ne5 {would just be uncharted fun}) 7. hxg3 d6 8. e4 Bg7 9. Qd2 a6 10. Bd3 Nc6 (10... g4 11. Nh2 Qg5 $5 {is another possibility}) 11. Ne2 g4 12. Nh2 h5 13. c3 Bd7 {Black could hardly complain about how the opening had gone in Grachev-Ovetchkin, Vladivostok 2014.}) 6... Nxg3 7. hxg3 Bg7 8. c3 ({My recommendation in 'The Torre Attack: Move by Move', keeping White's options open with the e-pawn. Instead,} 8. e3 {was seen the last time ChessPub touched on this line and after} d6 9. c3 Nc6 10. Qc2 {"chances are finely balanced as White has a very solid structure and possible play on the h-file in return for the bishop pair" to quote Aaron in his notes to Karaulov-Mihalichenko, Kharkov 2003.}) 8... b6 $5 ({Howell, an occasional Hippo player, is happy to fianchetto both bishops and await events in the centre. More often Black has tried} 8... d6 9. e4 Nc6 {, but after} 10. Bb5 Bd7 11. Qe2 {White has a small but clear plus, partly due to the kingside holes and because he can attack no matter which side Black puts his king.}) 9. e3 ({Chris was rather butchered when he played aggressively against David in last year's British Championship and White can make use of the e4-square after the text, but I still can't really explain how he rejected} 9. e4 {. After} Bb7 10. Bd3 d6 11. Qe2 {White is ready to meet ...Nd7 with Ba6, and ...g4 would only drive White's knight around to a nice square on e3 (via h2 and f1).}) 9... Bb7 10. Bd3 d6 11. g4 $5 ({Clamping down on f5 and h5, but this is quite a double-edged choice. In the only previous test of this position, coincidentally played in the same country,} 11. Qe2 {had been seen and after} c5 (11... g4 $5 12. Nh4 h5 13. f4 {is a radical way to secure the kingside and one I suspect Chris didn't like will the knight ever get to move again?}) 12. g4 Nd7 13. Be4 $1 Bxe4 $6 14. Nxe4 Qc7 15. d5 $1 {White's light-square strategy had worked to perfection in I. Jones-Cleveland, Pontardulais 1997.}) 11... Nd7 12. Ne4 ({Once again, the consistent follow-up} 12. Be4 {came into the equation, since} Bxe4 (12... d5 13. Bd3 {can't be too bad for Black if he pushes his c-pawn, but} e5 $6 14. dxe5 Nxe5 15. Nxe5 Bxe5 16. Nf3 Bg7 17. Nd4 {would leave him more than slightly worse}) 13. Nxe4 f5 $2 14. gxf5 exf5 15. Ng3 Qf6 16. Qd3 {would just leave Black overextended on the kingside.}) 12... Qe7 {Howell has acquired the bishop-pair and achieved a typical Hippo-like development. The next stage will be to push White back with his pawns, if allowed.} 13. Qc2 $2 ({I wasn't a fan of White's last (Ng3 can always be met by ...Nf6), but this was a bad misjudgement.} 13. Qe2 {would have kept an eye on some key squares, meaning that after} h5 14. gxh5 g4 15. Nh4 {the g4-pawn is attacked.}) ({Moreover, if White wanted to do something of his own, then} 13. a4 $5 {very much came into the equation.}) 13... h5 $1 {Howell seizes his chance to escape the bind. There's little as satisfying as playing a pawn break your opponent thought they'd prevented.} 14. Rxh5 ({He might as well remove the rooks, so ...Bxg2 doesn't come with tempo. Indeed,} 14. gxh5 g4 15. Nfd2 f5 16. Ng3 Bxg2 17. Rg1 Bb7 18. e4 f4 19. Ne2 e5 {would have been even worse for White than the game Black's kingside play gives him the upper hand despite his restricted bishops.}) 14... Rxh5 15. gxh5 g4 16. Nfd2 f5 17. Ng3 Bxg2 18. Qa4 ({Howell is able to keep Ward out on the queenside after this. I have my doubts about White's position in any case, but at least} 18. Ba6 $5 {would have prevented Black's next and kept White in the game.}) 18... a6 $1 19. O-O-O b5 20. Qa5 $6 ({This merely puts the queen offside.} 20. Qc2 {would have been a tail-between-the-legs type retreat, but would have kept White very much on the board: for instance,} Kf8 21. Rg1 Bb7 22. e4 {, levering open the kingside to begin counterplay.}) 20... Nb6 21. e4 $2 {And this inopportune break merely serves to do much of Black's hard work (namely how to edge forward and which pawn break to play) for him.} f4 22. Ne2 Bh6 {Black's bishops rule the roost and suddenly Ward finds himself in a rather prospectless and grim position.} 23. Rg1 $6 f3 (23... Qh4 $1 {would have been immediately decisive, and if} 24. Rxg2 f3 {, but Howell's choice still retains a near-decisive advantage.}) 24. Ng3 Bf4 25. Kc2 Bxg3 26. fxg3 Qg5 {The queen replaces the bishop to dominate the dark squares and what of White's queen? Well, the less said about her unfortunate position, the better.} 27. Nc4 $2 ({This exchange of knights merely makes Black's task easier once again.} 27. e5 $1 dxe5 28. Re1 {was the last chance.}) 27... Nxc4 28. Bxc4 Kd8 $1 {Calmly covering c7 and now there's going to be no stopping the f-pawn.} 29. Bd3 Qe3 30. Rd1 f2 31. e5 d5 32. Qa3 Kd7 33. Bxb5+ axb5 34. Qxa8 Qe2+ 35. Rd2 Be4+ 36. Kb3 Qxd2 37. Qf8 Qc2+ 0-1


