1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ ({The Queen's Indian move order is} 3... b6 4. g3 Bb7 5. Bg2 Bb4+ ({while} 5... Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Re1 a5 $5 {is the position discussed after White's 9th move in the game.})) 4. Nbd2 b6 5. g3 Bb7 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O a5 {John Emms: '!?' John Emms: 'We've seen this move recently in a couple of games. Black plans to swap his bishop for the knight, and then adopt a typically solid set-up with ...d6 and ...Nbd7. The ...a5 advance can be a useful move in this set-up, and by playing it here Black is asking White to find a useful move before Black takes on d2.'} 8. Nb1 {John Emms: '!?' John Emms: 'And we've seen this move too! Typically Simon Williams plays the most creative option for White here.' is a rarely played move but has been played by strong players like Sergey Kasparov, Thejkumar, Perunovic and Ushenina.} ({John Emms: 'The most common choice here is'} 8. Qc2 {John Emms: 'which is covered in Bacrot, E-Naiditsch, A/ Baden Baden 2015.' is the normal move and White has pretty decent results.}) 8... Be7 {John Emms: 'Preventing the idea of c4-c5 and a2-a3 trapping the bishop.'} 9. Re1 {John Emms: '!?' John Emms: 'The first new move. It looks very sensible, and Re1 is a typical idea for White, but when I checked to see whether it had been played before, I found out that this position has actually been reached a number of times - but with White to move! See the variation above, where 7...a5 has been played quite a few times in the 7 Re1 variation.'} ({John Emms: 'Previously we've looked at'} 9. Nc3 {would have been the normal way to continue.} Ne4 10. Qc2 Nxc3 11. bxc3 $5 {- see the notes to Ushenina, A-Franciskovic, B/Rijeka 2010.}) ({Another option for White is to play the well-known gambit line} 9. d5 {with an extra ...a5 thrown in.}) 9... Qc8 {John Emms: 'Protecting the b7-bishop, in readiness for Nc3, ...Ne4.' The position is a normal one and majority of the players would choose moves like Nc3 or Bf4. But not Simon! He goes all out!} (9... d5 {is obviously an option here}) ({and so is} 9... d6 {It's worth noting that the extra ...a5 helps Black in the line} 10. Nc3 Ne4 11. Qc2 Nxc3 {In contrast to the 7 Re1 d6 line,} 12. Ng5 $2 {doesn't work here because after} ({Instead White should play} 12. bxc3 $1 {with play very similar to Ushenina, A-Franciskovic, B/Rijeka 2010.}) 12... Bxg5 13. Bxb7 {Black's rook has an escape square:} Ra7 $1) 10. d5 $5 {John Emms: 'With the b7-bishop protected, you would have thought White would be discouraged from this advance. However, Simon found a very nice idea.'} (10. Nc3 Ne4 $11 {is solid and equal.}) 10... exd5 11. cxd5 Bxd5 12. e4 $1 {John Emms: 'This is it - another pawn offer!' When you have said 'A' you must say 'B'.} ({If} 12. Nc3 Bb7 13. e4 {Black gets in} d6) 12... Bxe4 {Howell takes up the challenge and picks up the second pawn. But now he has a bishop on e7 that is hanging and White can create some dangerous threats.} ({John Emms: 'In contrast, if'} 12... Bb7 {John Emms: 'White gets in' was the safer choice.} 13. e5 $1 {Black's knight has to move from its ideal defensive post, and White is assured of attacking chances on the kingside.}) 13. Rxe4 $6 {John Emms: '!?'} ({John Emms: 'As Simon pointed out on his YouTube channel, White could play'} 13. Nc3 $1 {was the normal developing move.} d5 {John Emms: '(forced)'} 14. Nxe4 dxe4 15. Ng5 {John Emms: 'White will regain one of the two sac'ed pawns, and his positional advantages will compensate him for the other. Objectively this might be White's best option, although the text move is obviously very tempting.'} Na6 16. Nxe4 $14 {And here White has excellent compensation for the missing pawn. He has the two powerful bishops and the one on g2 is extremely strong.}) 13... Nxe4 14. Qd5 {That was White's point. A double attack on a8 and e4.} Nxg3 $1 {You can bank on Howell to find the best continuation in this complicated position.} 15. hxg3 (15. Qxa8 $2 Ne2+ 16. Kf1 Nxc1 $17) 15... c6 16. Qh5 d5 {Black has three pawns and a rook for White's two minor pieces. That's quite a bit of material. White's only hope is to put these minor pieces to good use in the middlegame and launch an attack.} 17. Bh3 Qb7 {John Emms: 'White is slightly down on material - with two pieces for a rook and three pawns - but has some attacking chances on the kingside.'} 18. Bf5 $6 {John Emms: '?' John Emms: 'A miscalculation, from which there's no way back for White.'} ({John Emms: 'After either'} 18. Nc3 {A normal developing move like Nc3 is not in the spirit of the position if you are Simon Williams.}) ({or} 18. Ng5 {the chances remain very much in the balance.}) 18... g6 19. Qh6 Re8 {John Emms: '!'} (19... gxf5 $2 {John Emms: 'gets Black mated after'} 20. Ng5 Bxg5 21. Qxg5+ Kh8 22. Qf6+ Kg8 23. Bh6 {with a forced mate.}) 20. Ng5 $2 {John Emms: 'Going all in. White could retreat the bishop from f5, when the loss of time swings the advantage firmly in Black's favour.'} (20. Bc2 {would have kept White in the game but Black is in the driver's seat after} Bf8 21. Qh4 Bg7 $17 {with a rock solid kingside.}) 20... Bxg5 $1 21. Bxg5 f6 $1 {John Emms: 'David Howell is particularly good at finding the most precise move in complicated positions.' A very strong defensive idea clearing the second rank for the black queen to join in the defence.} ({It's tempting to throw in} 21... Re1+ $2 {but this is a mistake:} 22. Kg2 f6 23. Nc3 $1 {intending} Rxa1 $2 24. Be6+ $1) 22. Bxg6 ({John Emms: 'After'} 22. Bxf6 {John Emms: 'the calm'} Qf7 $1 $19 {John Emms: '!' John Emms: 'is winning for Black:' was the neat point.} (22... gxf5 $2 23. Qg5+ Kf8 24. Qh6+ Kg8 $11) 23. Bc3 ({or} 23. Qg5 Rf8) 23... gxf5) 22... Re1+ $1 {John Emms: 'Now it's the right time for the check. Black is winning.'} 23. Kg2 fxg5 24. Nd2 $5 {In any case White is lost. Why not throw some more wood into the fire?} (24. Bf5 Qg7 25. Qh5 Na6 $19 {Black has co-ordinated himself and the game is over.}) 24... Rxa1 25. Bf5 Na6 26. Nf3 Qg7 27. Qxc6 Rf8 {An attempt at creating a brilliance which misfired.} 0-1


