1. e4 {Roiz,M} e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 5. d3 O-O 6. O-O d5 7. exd5 Nxd5 8. a4 {This advance is frequently seen in various lines of the Italian nowadays.} Nb6 {GM Howell chooses a considerably rare way of handling the position.} (8... Nf6 {doesn't offer Black full equality:} 9. Nbd2 Bf5 10. Qe2 Qe7 11. Ne4 Nxe4 12. dxe4 Be6 13. b4 Bd6 14. a5 $14 {Shankland,S (2656)-Nakamura,H (2814) Baku AZE 2015}) ({Quite popular is also} 8... a5 {, but exposing the b5-spot might cause Black some problems. For instance,} 9. Nbd2 Nb6 10. Bb5 Bd6 11. Re1 Bg4 12. Ne4 Na7 13. h3 Bh5 14. d4 Nxb5 15. axb5 exd4 16. Nxd6 Bxf3 17. Qxf3 Qxd6 18. Rd1 $14 {Giri,A (2782)-Aronian,L (2792) Leuven BEL 2016}) ({The flexible response} 8... a6 $5 {looks perfectly playable and leads to a complicated struggle:} 9. Nbd2 Kh8 10. Re1 f6 11. d4 Ba7 (11... exd4 12. Nb3 Ba7 13. Nbxd4 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 $14 {Giri,A (2755)-Tomashevsky,E (2731) Moscow RUS 2016}) 12. dxe5 Nxe5 13. Nxe5 fxe5 14. Nf3 c6 $6 (14... Bxf2+ $142 $1 15. Kxf2 Qh4+ 16. Kg1 Qxc4 17. Rxe5 Nf6 $11) 15. Bg5 Qb6 16. Bxd5 cxd5 17. Be3 Qxb2 18. Bxa7 Rxa7 19. Qxd5 $16 {1/2 (44) Kramnik,V (2808)-Karjakin,S (2781) Stavanger NOR 2017}) 9. Bb5 {The most challenging - the pressure on the e5 is one of Black's main worries.} ({The modest} 9. Bb3 a5 10. Bg5 Qd6 $11 {offers Black comfortable play.}) 9... Ne7 {This is a positional pawn sac - the exchange of the powerful b5 is Black's undisputable achievement.} 10. Nxe5 ({Another way of grabbing the pawn is} 10. a5 c6 11. axb6 cxb5 12. Rxa7 Rxa7 13. bxa7 Bxa7 14. Nxe5 Bf5 15. Na3 ({After} 15. Be3 Bb8 16. d4 f6 17. Nf3 Nd5 $44 {Alekseev,E (2636)-Eliseev,U (2606) St Petersburg RUS 2016, Black had decent compensation for a pawn à la Marshall.}) 15... Bb8 16. d4 f6 $2 ({The correct} 16... b4 $1 17. cxb4 Qd6 18. Nac4 Qxb4 19. b3 Qb5 {wouldn't yield White real winning chances.}) 17. Nd3 Qd7 18. Re1 $16 {Mamedov,R (2666)-Balogh,C (2614) Baku AZE 2016}) 10... c6 11. Bc4 Bd6 12. a5 $1 $146 {This innovation is a definite improvement} ({over} 12. Nf3 Nxc4 13. dxc4 Qc7 $44 {Sedina,E (2275)-Loiacono,A (2085) Trieste ITA 2016; Black was fine.}) 12... Bxe5 $6 {David manages to regain the pawn, but the lack of coordination enables White to seize the initiative.} ({A better choice would be} 12... Nxc4 13. Nxc4 Bc7 14. Bg5 f6 15. Bh4 Nf5 16. Bg3 Nxg3 17. hxg3 {though in the resulting position Black still has to claim sufficient compensation for a pawn.}) 13. axb6 Qxb6 14. Re1 Qc7 (14... Bd6 15. Nd2 Qc7 16. Qh5 {is just a transposition.}) 15. Qh5 $1 Bd6 16. Nd2 $14 {White's pieces are suddenly getting very active. Roiz,M: 'is just a transposition.'} Nd5 17. Ne4 Be6 18. d4 Rfe8 19. Nxd6 {Obtaining the bishop pair secures White a small, but long-lasting advantage.} ({It was also possible to keep the tension by means of} 19. Bd3 $5 g6 20. Qh4 Bf5 21. f3 $36) 19... Qxd6 20. Bd3 Nf6 {The most natural.} ({Of course, David isn't happy with exposing his king with} 20... g6) 21. Qg5 $6 {An unsuccessful decision - the queen is clearly misplaced there.} ({The correct way was} 21. Qf3 Bg4 22. Bf4 $1 Qd7 23. Qg3 $14) 21... h6 22. Qf4 $6 {Another inaccuracy, which drastically changes the course of the game.} ({It was necessary to connect the rooks:} 22. Bf4 hxg5 23. Bxd6 {even though in the subsequent position Black is able to set up a blockade and solve the problems:} Nd5 24. f3 a5 25. Kf2 b5 $11) 22... Bc4 $1 23. Rd1 Qe6 $1 ({Black's position would be better also in the event of} 23... Qxf4 24. Bxf4 Bxd3 25. Rxd3 b5 26. Kf1 a5 $15 {but the simplifications might make White's defensive task easier.}) 24. Bxc4 Qxc4 {Unfortunately, there is no good square for White's bishop at the moment.} 25. Qg3 $6 ({A better move was} 25. Qf5 Nd5 26. Bd2 a5 $15) 25... Re6 $1 {This strong move is connected with a pawn sacrifice.} 26. Rxa7 {Accepting the challenge.} ({In the event of} 26. Bf4 Nh5 27. Qf3 Nxf4 28. Qxf4 Re2 $17 {the penetration of Black's rook puts White in big danger.}) 26... Rxa7 27. Qb8+ Kh7 28. Qxa7 Ng4 $1 {The activity of Black's pieces is threatening.} 29. d5 $2 {Alas, Anton Guijarro doesn't withstand the pressure.} ({White's position was desperate, but had he played} 29. Bf4 Nxf2 30. Rf1 Nd3 31. Bg3 Re7 $17 {the result still would be unpredictable.}) 29... Qe2 30. Rf1 Rf6 31. Be3 ({The alternative -} 31. dxc6 bxc6 32. f3 {was equally bad:} Nxh2 33. Rf2 Nxf3+ $1 34. Rxf3 Qd1+ 35. Kh2 Rxf3 36. gxf3 Qxc1 $19) 31... Nxh2 $1 {The major loss of material is unavoidable now.} 32. Kxh2 Qxf1 33. Qxb7 Qc4 ({An even stronger move was} 33... c5 $1 34. d6 (34. Bxc5 Rf5 35. Be3 Qd3 $19) 34... Qd3 35. d7 Rd6 36. d8=Q Rxd8 37. Qxf7 Qe4 $19) 34. Bd4 ({After} 34. dxc6 Qh4+ 35. Kg1 Qe4 36. Qc7 Rxc6 37. Qb7 Qb1+ 38. Kh2 Qg6 {Black should be able to convert the material advantage into a full point, but the task is not trivial.}) 34... Rg6 $1 35. Qxf7 c5 $1 {GM Howell is playing precisely - now the vulnerablity of White's king starts to tell.} 36. Be5 Qh4+ 37. Kg1 Qh5 (37... Qe4 $1 38. Bg3 Rf6 39. Qa7 Rf5 {wins on the spot.}) 38. Bg3 Qd1+ 39. Kh2 Rg5 40. f3 Qxd5 41. Qxd5 Rxd5 {The resulting endgame is hopeless.} 42. b4 c4 43. Kg1 h5 44. Kf1 Rd2 {Now White is almost paralysed.} 45. Be5 g5 46. Bd4 Rb2 47. Kg1 Kg6 48. Kh2 Kf5 49. Be3 Rb3 50. Bd2 ({Or} 50. Bd4 Kf4 51. Kg1 g4 $19) 50... Rb1 51. Be3 Rd1 52. Bf2 Rd3 53. Be1 Re3 0-1


