1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 d5 5. c4 dxc4 6. Na3 c3 7. bxc3 O-O 8. O-O c5 9. Bb2 Nc6 10. e3 Bf5 11. Nd2 ({Khismatullin, D - Efimenko, Z Moscow 2008, continued with the more popular} 11. Qe2 {see the archives.}) 11... Qb6 {Diagram [#] Flear,Glenn: '!?' Flear,Glenn: 'A provocative move that has hardly occurred, but was once tried by Negi.'} (11... Rc8 12. Nb3 (12. e4 Bg4 13. f3 Bd7 14. d5 Ne5 15. c4 {(pushing all four central pawns in a row gains space but tends to leave some holes)} Nd3 16. Bc3 Nb4 17. Nc2 (17. e5 $5 {is plausible, when the engine suggests} Nfxd5 18. cxd5 Nxd5 19. Qc1 b5 20. Bb2 c4 $44 {when the two pawns plus the initiative compensate for the missing piece}) 17... Ba4 18. Nb3 b5 $5 $13 {Hakobyan, A - Salem, A St.Petersburg blitz 2018}) 12... Qb6 13. Qe2 cxd4 14. cxd4 Be4 $1 {(this recurrent theme is important to remember)} 15. Bh3 e6 16. Nc5 Bf3 $6 ({a natural enough move when one considers that} 16... Bd5 $1 17. Rfb1 {would (at first) seem to be promising for White. However, after} Rfd8 18. Bc1 Nb4 19. Nc2 {the complications are apparently playable e.g.} a5 20. a3 Rxc5 $1 21. dxc5 Qa6 22. Qxa6 Nxa6 $44 {as Black's pieces are going to be the more active.}) 17. Qxf3 Qxb2 18. Nc4 Qc3 19. Qe2 Nxd4 20. exd4 Qxd4 21. Nxe6 Qxc4 22. Qxc4 Rxc4 23. Nxf8 Bxf8 24. Rfc1 $16 {Cheparinov, I - Firat, B Batumi 2018.}) (11... cxd4 {- 101/(366)}) ({Banusz has faced} 11... Bg4 {but in this case it's not clear if one should avoid f2-f3 or not:} 12. Qb1 $5 ({the Hungarian GM settled on} 12. f3 {but wasn't able to claim an opening pull:} Be6 13. Nb3 cxd4 14. cxd4 Nd5 15. Qd2 {(the threat of N-c5 is a nuisance, but perhaps only a temporary one)} Ndb4 16. Nc5 Bc8 17. Rfd1 b6 {Banusz, T - Van Wely, L Spanish league 2017, and Black unravels with equality close to hand}) 12... Rc8 13. h3 Be6 14. Nb3 cxd4 15. cxd4 {(so with the long diagonal still open, the natural riposte is...)} Bd5 $1 {(...which obliges White to take risks if he wants to seek any advantage)} 16. e4 Bxb3 {Valderrama Quiceno, E - Soto, M Medellin 2020. A draw was agreed, but the position was just livening up. After} 17. axb3 Nxd4 18. e5 Nh5 19. Rd1 Ne2+ 20. Kf1 {Black would have to give up a piece, but this is far from clear as} Nexg3+ 21. fxg3 Qc7 $13 {leaves White with a draughty king.}) 12. Qb3 $146 (12. Nb3 Rfd8 {Flear,Glenn: '(delaying the inevitable for one more turn)'} 13. Qe2 cxd4 14. cxd4 Be4 $13 {Flear,Glenn: '=!' Flear,Glenn: 'is a typical ploy, as White will have to take some positional risks if he wants to avoid the exchange of light-squared bishops'} (14... e5 $6 15. d5 Nb4 16. Nc4 Qa6 17. e4 Rac8 18. exf5 Qxc4 $14 {Ibrayev, N - Negi, P New Delhi 2009, with a tense position where the bishop pair should keep White ahead.})) ({There are other ways to meet the threat to the bishop:} 12. Nac4 Qa6 13. d5 $6 (13. Re1 $5 $13 {removes the rook from a vulnerable square}) 13... b5 $1 14. Na3 {0.5-0.5 Nogueiras Santiago, J - Garcia Martinez, S Las Tunas 2001, and Black can seize the initiative following} b4 $1) 12... Be6 (12... Bd3 13. Rfc1 Na5 14. Qxb6 axb6 $13) 13. Qb5 Rfd8 14. Rfc1 {Flear,Glenn: 'Both sides jostle for position, but there is no residual advantage for White.'} Na5 ({Flear,Glenn: 'Simply'} 14... Qxb5 15. Nxb5 Rac8 (15... Rd7 {seems to be fine, as the 'obvious'} 16. Nb3 {is well met by} a6 17. Na3 Bxb3 18. axb3 Na5 $15) 16. Nb3 a6 17. Na3 b6 18. dxc5 Nd7 $1 19. cxb6 Nxb6 20. Nd4 Nxd4 21. cxd4 Na4 $44) 15. c4 {Flear,Glenn: 'The plan is to improve the dark-squared bishop's prospects.'} (15. e4 Qxb5 16. Nxb5 Ne8 17. d5 Bd7 18. Na3 e6 $36) 15... Ne8 $1 16. Bc3 $6 {Diagram [#] Flear,Glenn: '?' Flear,Glenn: 'An oversight.'} ({Flear,Glenn: 'Black is also comfortable following the superior'} 16. Nb3 {Flear,Glenn: 'e.g.'} Nxb3 (16... Nxc4 $2 17. Qxb6 Nxb6 18. Nxc5 $16) (16... Qxb5 17. Nxb5 Nxc4 18. Nxc5 Nxb2 19. Rab1 a6 $1 20. Na3 Nd3 21. Nxd3 Bf5 22. Rb3 Nd6 $11) 17. axb3 Nd6 18. Qxb6 axb6 $13 {Flear,Glenn: 'etc.'}) 16... Nxc4 $1 {Flear,Glenn: 'A tactic that rattles White's hold on the centre.'} 17. Qxb6 (17. Ndxc4 Qxb5 18. Nxb5 Bxc4 19. a4 (19. Na3 cxd4 20. Ba5 Bd3 $1 21. Bxd8 Rxd8 $17) 19... cxd4 20. Bxd4 Bxd4 21. Nxd4 Bd5 $15) 17... Nxb6 18. dxc5 $6 ({Flear,Glenn: 'Or'} 18. Bxb7 cxd4 (18... Rab8 19. Bc6 Nd5 $1 {and Black has the initiative.}) 19. Bxd4 Bxd4 20. exd4 Rab8 21. Bc6 Nd6 $17) 18... Bxc3 19. Rxc3 Rxd2 20. cxb6 axb6 (20... Nd6 $5 21. bxa7 Rxa7 22. e4 f6 $17) 21. Bxb7 Ra7 (21... Ra5 22. Bf3 Nd6 $17) 22. Bc6 Nd6 {Flear,Glenn: 'The smoke has cleared and it seems inevitable that White will drop his a-pawn, with nothing to show in return.'} 23. e4 Ra5 24. Kg2 Kg7 {Flear,Glenn: 'There's no rush, the opponent isn't going anywhere!'} 25. Nc2 Bxa2 (25... Rxa2 26. Rxa2 Bxa2 27. Kf3 Be6 $17) (25... Re5 26. Kf3 Bc4 27. Ne3 Be2+ 28. Kg2 Nxe4 $19) 26. e5 {Diagram [#] Flear,Glenn: '?!' Flear,Glenn: 'Already this smacks of desperation.'} (26. Kf3 Be6 27. Rxa5 bxa5 28. Ke3 Rd1 $17) 26... Nf5 (26... Nc4 27. Nb4 Nxe5 $19) (26... Rxe5 $1 27. Rxa2 Ree2 28. Kg1 Rxf2 $19) 27. Re1 Be6 28. Bf3 Ra2 $19 {Flear,Glenn: 'Obeying the rule that 'when in doubt, keep improving one's pieces'!'} 29. Be4 g5 (29... h5 $19) 30. h3 Rb2 31. g4 {Flear,Glenn: 'David was already anticipating this counter with his 29th move.'} Nh4+ 32. Kg3 b5 33. f4 b4 34. Rc7 Rb3+ {Flear,Glenn: 'Suddenly White's king finds himself surrounded by trouble.'} 35. Ne3 gxf4+ (35... Rd4 {Flear,Glenn: '!' Flear,Glenn: 'is immediately decisive.'} 36. Bb7 Rxe3+ $1 37. Rxe3 gxf4+ $19) 36. Kxf4 Rd4 37. Kg5 {Flear,Glenn: '?'} (37. Rc5 {would resist a little longer, when Black would have to find a way to increase the pressure. The following being a convincing way:} Ra3 38. Rb5 Bd7 39. Rc5 e6 {(White has run out of constructive moves)} 40. Rb1 Ba4 41. Rbc1 Bd1 42. Rxd1 Ng6+ 43. Kf3 Rxd1 $19) 37... Rxe4 0-1


