1. e4 {Berg,Emanuel Berg,Emanuel Berg,Emanuel Berg,Emanuel: 'Berg,E'} e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 {Having played the Spanish in almost all my games of late, it was time for a change not the least to surprise my opponent.} Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 5. b4 $5 {The Italian Wing Attack. Not really something particulary dangerous for Black but leading to interesting play and hopefully something my opponent hadn't checked.} Bb6 6. d3 d6 7. a4 {White hopes to get a space advantage on the queenside with some long term pressure.} a5 $1 (7... a6 {is the main alternative and the most popular move over the years. However I find it rather comfortable for White following} 8. Nbd2 {intending ideas like b3 and c4.}) 8. b5 Ne7 9. Bb3 {The bishop gives space for the knight on b1. It's better to wait with castling for White to avoid} (9. O-O Ng6 10. Ba2 O-O 11. Nbd2 Bg4 12. h3 Bh5 {½-½ (42) Jobava,B (2712)-Hammer,J (2601) Rogaska Slatina 2011; when Black has a nice initiative on the kingside.}) 9... Ng6 10. Na3 c6 {Black opens a route for his bishop to c7.} 11. Nc4 Bc7 {Now Black's plan is to proceed with ...d5.} 12. O-O O-O 13. Re1 Re8 {White can no longer stop Black from ...d5 so it's time to retreat with the knight from c4.} 14. Ne3 {A good square for the knight preventing ...g4.} d5 {Black has achieved his main aim and has a nice pawn centre. However this is where the real battle starts.} 15. exd5 cxd5 16. g3 $1 {A good move restricting Black's knight on g6 while also securing White's king against attacks along the b8-h2 diagonal. True it also has a drawback of weakening the light squares but that's nothing Black can take advantage of at first sight. I had been analysing this exact position at my hotel room before the game and come to the conclusion that White had interesting chances to fight for an edge although theoreticaly Black should be just fine.} b6 {A logical move preparing the a8-h1 diagonal for the light squared bishop.} 17. d4 {White's main idea in the position. Now after ...e4 he can play his knight back to d2 preparing the c4-break.} Bb7 {Black keeps the centre dynamic hoping for an opening of the long diagonal.} 18. Bb2 {So far I had evrything under control having played my moves quickly while my opponent had used a considerable amount of time.} Qd7 {A human move which I had not investigated during my preparation.} ({Instead the computer gave} 18... e4 19. Nd2 {which I was quite satisfied with. Having the pawn on e4 it's hard for Black to create anything really dangerous on the kingside. But White for his part can always open up with c4 at some point.}) 19. Re2 {Played after a long period of thought. The fact that Black's pawns were not static on d5 and e4 troubled me and I was slightly concerned about ...h3 ideas.} ({My first thought was to play} 19. Rc1 {which is also the computer's top suggestion. However I was not quite comfortable and thought that perhaps Black could get a quick attack on the kingside following} Qh3 $5 {Even with the computer by my side I'm far from convinced that the fearless} 20. c4 $1 {would lead to something good for White. To open the long diagonal towards White's king looks like a nightmare. When going down the lines a bit we end up in a critical position after} (20. Ng5 Qh6 21. dxe5) {The main continuation follows} 20... exd4 21. Bxd4 (21. Ng5 $5 {also deserves serious attention intending} Qh6 22. Nxf7 {with great complications.}) 21... Ng4 22. cxd5 Nh4 $1 23. Rc2 $1 $13 {An important defensive resource which is the only way of surviving for White. Although the computer engine keeps rather calm all the way down these lines even the smallest error could end up in disaster for White.}) 19... e4 {This plays into White's hands, especially as now I knew exactly which plan to follow.} ({Instead} 19... Qh3 {was what I expected when White has to be careful.} {I had planned to continue} 20. dxe5 Nxe5 21. Nxe5 Rxe5 22. Qf1 Qh5 23. Rae1 {when White has driven away Black's queen and has things pretty much under control.}) 20. Nd2 h5 $6 {This plan might look logical but in fact it only wastes time and in the end even helps White.} (20... Rad8 {looks better to keep control in the centre and be ready for the c4-break.}) 21. Qf1 {A practical move but there might well have been better options.} ({The immediate} 21. c4 $5 {is one interesting alternative.}) 21... h4 22. c4 dxc4 {This exchange gives White a very harmonious position. Perhaps Black should rather have allowed the advance c5 although that's not an easy decision to make.} 23. Ndxc4 Nd5 ({During the game I started to think about} 23... Nh7 {intending ...g5-f3. This would at least be slightly annoying for White but the central counterplay should prove stronger after} 24. d5 Ng5 25. Rd1 Nf3+ 26. Kh1 $14 {since Black lacks the power to continue his attack.}) 24. Rd1 $1 {Nicely preparing for e5 which is now a major concern for Black.} Qe7 25. Ne5 Rad8 $6 {Black was in a difficult situation but this does not solve the issue.} ({The straightforward} 25... Nxe3 {looks best when after} 26. fxe3 Bxe5 27. dxe5 Bc8 {followed by ...e6 Black is at least able to limit White's attacking chances. Still White has a solid plus following} 28. Rd6 Be6 29. Bxe6 fxe6 30. Qg2 $16) 26. Nxd5 $6 {Not at all bad but there was better to be found.} (26. Nxg6 $1 fxg6 {would simply leave Black in very bad shape having a king without a real shelter, e.g.} 27. Rc1 Kh7 28. Qh3 $18) (26. Nc6 $5 {was another good way to a clear advantage following} Bxc6 27. bxc6 $16 {with two potentially strong concted passed pawns as well as the pir of bishops.}) 26... Bxd5 27. Bxd5 Rxd5 28. Rxe4 hxg3 29. hxg3 Bxe5 30. dxe5 Nxe5 {A tricky move in time trouble. Black bravely enters the complications with the risk of losing a piece.} 31. Kg2 $6 (31. Re3 $1 {would have forced Black into giving up his knight after the forced line} Red8 32. Rde1 f6 33. f4 Qb4 34. Ba3 Qxa4 35. fxe5 Rxe5 36. Rxe5 fxe5 37. Bb2 $16 {with excellent winning chances for White.}) 31... Qb7 $6 (31... Qd8 $1 {was more precise when White keeps only a symbolic advantage.}) 32. f3 f6 33. Bxe5 $1 {Liquidating into a very comfortable endgame for White.} Rdxe5 34. Rxe5 fxe5 (34... Rxe5 $4 {cannot be played due to} 35. Rd8+ {when White's attack will become decisive.}) 35. Qc4+ Qf7 36. Rd5 Qe6 37. Qe4 {White has a nice grip holding Black passive defending his e5-pawn.} Kf8 38. g4 $1 {Launching the g-pawn is a good way to play for White. It gives more space and at some point the g-pawn might continue to g5 or even g6.} Kf7 39. Kg3 Kf8 40. Kg2 {A safety move to complete the time control.} Kg8 41. Kg3 Qe7 42. Rd1 $1 {It's time to regroup the pieces. Now h1 and c4+ can cause Black serious trouble.} Qf6 43. Rc1 Rf8 44. Rc4 {Importantly defending against the exchange of queens on f4.} Qf7 $2 (44... Rd8 {would have been better.}) 45. g5 $1 {Allowing this move should normally mean the end for Black. Now g6 is a crucial threat.} Qf5 46. Qxf5 $4 {I saw that this would give Black good drawing chances but} ({in the eternal time trouble I did not realise that} 46. g6 $1 {was just winning.} {There might follow} Qxe4 (46... Qe6 47. Rc6 $18) 47. fxe4 Rf6 48. Rc8+ Rf8 49. Rc6 (49. Rxf8+ Kxf8 50. Kg4 Ke7 $11 {is just a draw.}) 49... Rf6 50. Kg4 $1 Kf8 51. Rc8+ Ke7 52. Rc7+ Kf8 53. Kg5 Rf4 54. Rc6 Rxe4 (54... Ke7 {is the most stubborn but after} 55. Rxb6 Rxe4 56. Rb7+ Ke6 57. Rxg7 $18 {White's two passed pawns will decide.}) 55. Kf5 Rf4+ 56. Ke6 Rf6+ 57. Kd7 $18) 46... Rxf5 47. Kg4 g6 48. Rc6 Rf4+ 49. Kg3 Kf7 50. Rxb6 Rxa4 51. Rf6+ Kg7 52. Ra6 ({White could win a pawn by playing} 52. Re6 {but after} Kf7 53. Rxe5 Rb4 {Black will soon be able to force an exchange of his a-pawn against White's b-pawn which leads to a completely drawn endgame.}) 52... Kf7 53. Rf6+ Kg7 54. Ra6 Kf7 55. b6 Rb4 56. Rxa5 Ke6 57. Ra8 Rxb6 58. Rf8 1/2-1/2


