{[%evp 0,86,17,23,19,19,20,15,15,-37,-11,-11,1,1,1,3,0,0,12,23,26,40,55,54,12,30,39,35,35,5,-5,16,32,32,35,26,59,5,50,-38,-45,-185,-135,-347,-307,-524,-558,-579,-372,-353,-392,-539,-177,-222,-174,-311,-6,-8,-8,-3,100,113,119,-21,109,94,83,96,104,153,152,-20,-27,-66,-48,-78,-105,-105,-65,-169,-160,-237,-47,-386,-503,-539,-724,-1289,-1080]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. Ng5 d5 $1 5. exd5 Na5 6. Bb5+ c6 7. dxc6 bxc6 8. Qf3 $5 {This is an interesting sideline, as White develops the queen winning a tempo by both pinning and attacking c6.} Rb8 $1 {A nice and active answer. Black should not hesitate in such positions, but instead go for active play.} 9. Bxc6+ $6 {White will soon realise that being materialistic here is not a good choice .} (9. Bd3 $1 {is the right move.}) 9... Nxc6 10. Qxc6+ Nd7 $1 {[%csl Yc6,Yg5][%cal Gb8b6,Gc8b7] My suggestion is that Black should think not about one or two pawns in such positions, but in terms of development and (mainly) piece mobility (like AlphaZero!). White has won a second pawn, but in doing so he gave up the bishop pair and helped Black to solve a potential problem (the a5). On the other hand, by covering the check with the knight Black hits the g5, and the queen can be harassed with moves like ,,,b6 and ...b7. Black is two moves away from completing development, when he will be ready to look for active ideas like advancing the f-pawn. Although White is two pawns up, it looks like he acquired too many practical problems in return, and surviving the middlegame already seems a very difficult task.} 11. d3 ({Both retreats of the knight still give Black a pleasant initiative:} 11. Nf3 Rb6 12. Qe4 Bb7 13. Qe2 Rg6 $1 14. d4 $5 (14. O-O $2 {falls for the nice tactical idea} Rxg2+ $1 15. Kxg2 Qg5+ 16. Kh1 Qg4 $19) 14... Bd6 15. dxe5 Nxe5 16. Bf4 Qa5+ $1 17. Nbd2 Re6 $40) (11. Ne4 Rb6 12. Qc3 Bb4 13. Qg3 O-O $40 {[%cal Gf7f5,Yb6g6,Yc8b7]}) 11... Be7 12. Nf3 (12. Ne4 {was played in some games, but I still prefer Black's position.} Rb6 13. Qa4 O-O 14. Nbc3 f5 15. Nd2 Bb7 16. Nc4 Re6 $1 (16... Rg6 17. Nxe5 $1 Nxe5 $2 18. Qb3+ $16 {[%csl Gb7]}) 17. Rg1 $6 Nc5 18. Qa5 Qd7 $19 {[%csl Ra5][%cal Ge6a6]}) 12... Rb6 {A natural move and also one that you always want to play in such positions.} ({But} 12... O-O {was possibly more precise, as if} 13. Qe4 {Black can immediately launch a strong initiative in the centre:} f5 14. Qe2 e4 $1 15. dxe4 fxe4 16. Nfd2 (16. Qxe4 $2 Bb4+ 17. Kf1 Ne5 $1 $19) 16... e3 $3 17. Qxe3 (17. fxe3 Ne5 $40 {[%cal Yc8g4,Ye7h4]}) 17... Bc5 18. Qe6+ Kh8 19. O-O Rb6 $36 {[%cal Gb6g6,Gc8b7,Yd8h4] Although White is 3(!) pawns up, he has almost no pieces developed and faces big problems already; this line is a good example of how active play is far more important than material in such positions.}) 13. Qe4 Bb7 14. Qe2 Rg6 $1 {This rook is very annoying.} 15. Rg1 $2 {The problem is that after this move White can hardly find a good place for his king.} (15. O-O {looks risky:} O-O 16. Nbd2 f5 $1 17. Re1 Qc7 18. c3 Bf6 {Black has no reason to hurry, he can simply improve his position and wait for the right moment.} 19. Nf1 Ba6 $1 {[%cal Ye5e4]} 20. Qd1 f4 $1 {[%csl Gc1,Gf1] This advance restricts White's pieces very well, and if White loses patience, for example} 21. d4 $6 Bb7 $1 $40 {[%cal Ge5e4] just increases the pressure on White's camp}) ({The engine indicates} 15. Be3 $1 {trying to solve the problem of the king as soon as possible.} f5 $5 {Avoiding bd2.} (15... Rxg2 16. Nbd2 $13 {[%cal Ge1c1]}) 16. Nc3 Qa8 $1 17. O-O-O $1 Rxg2 {White's position seems very unpleasant, but he can complicate matters by playing actively:} 18. Nxe5 $1 Nxe5 19. Bc5 $1 Ng6 $8 20. Bxe7 Nxe7 21. Rhe1 Qd8 22. d4 Be4 $1 {The position remains complicated, and the computer ends with the typical computer draw :)} 23. Nxe4 fxe4 24. Qxe4 Rxf2 25. Qc6+ Qd7 26. Qa8+ Qd8 27. Qc6+ $11) 15... Qa8 $1 {[%cal Ga8h1,Yg6g1] The pressure on White's camp is very unpleasant now.} 16. Nbd2 O-O 17. c3 $6 {It is not easy to suggest how White should play, but this move normally creates new targets for Black.} (17. h4 $5 {looks like a desperate attempt already:} f5 18. h5 Rc6 19. Nc4 Bf6 $17 {[%cal Yf8e8,Ye5e4]}) 17... Nc5 $1 {[%csl Yd3] Howell immediately spots the new weakness.} (17... f5 {was also good.}) 18. Kd1 (18. Nxe5 $2 {would lead to a quick loss:} Re6 19. d4 f6 20. f4 fxe5 21. dxc5 Bxc5 $19 {[%cal Gb7a6]}) 18... e4 $1 19. Ne1 $2 (19. dxe4 Nxe4 20. Nxe4 Bxe4 21. Re1 Rd8+ 22. Nd4 f5 {White has some chances of resistance here but he needs to accept a bad position, since} 23. f3 $2 {loses to} Rxg2 $1 24. Qxg2 Bxf3+ $19) 19... Ba6 20. Nxe4 Nxd3 (20... Re6 $19 {was probably simpler.}) 21. Qe3 Rd8 {Black is already completely winning, and the only explanation for the game lasting so long from this point is the short time control which probably made Howell's task harder.} 22. Nd2 Bc5 23. Qf3 Nxf2+ 24. Kc2 Bb7 25. Qe2 Ne4 26. Rf1 Nxd2 27. Bxd2 Rxg2 $2 {Unnecessary.} (27... Be4+ 28. Kc1 Rgd6 {was a clear-cut continuation.} 29. Bf4 Re6 {It is even harder to suggest a move for White here.} 30. Qb5 (30. b4 $2 Bxg2 $1 31. Qxg2 Rxe1+ $19) 30... Qd5 31. Qb3 (31. Qe2 Bxg2 $19) 31... Qf5 {[%cal Yg7g5] and White is defenceless.} 32. g3 Qxf4+ 33. Rxf4 Be3#) 28. Nxg2 Bxg2 29. Rf4 Qd5 30. Re1 h6 {Things have even changed now and the advantage is with White.} 31. Bc1 (31. c4 $142) 31... Qc6 32. b4 $6 (32. Kb1 $142) 32... Bb6 33. Kb2 Bd5 34. c4 Be6 35. Kb1 $2 (35. Ka1 $142 {was safer.}) 35... Bc7 36. b5 Qc5 37. Rf3 Bxc4 $17 38. Qb2 Bd3+ 39. Rxd3 $2 (39. Ka1 {would still offer more resistance.}) 39... Rxd3 $19 40. Bxh6 Rd4 41. Be3 Qf5+ 42. Ka1 Re4 43. Rg1 Be5 0-1


