{[%evp 0,113,80,27,39,18,17,12,12,12,19,15,17,23,29,-6,5,-4,13,-20,-12,-14,6,-16,-7,3,1,1,11,4,3,9,18,10,21,3,19,-41,-26,-34,-3,-36,-8,-8,34,22,48,0,24,13,27,30,13,13,26,48,111,132,132,115,132,122,132,69,74,68,63,90,90,92,102,100,98,98,95,101,94,85,99,88,91,103,106,107,112,110,112,112,112,109,151,163,164,161,190,185,190,194,227,250,246,250,245,253,253,253,254,269,289,298,301,307,307,320,315,321]} 1. e4 {Tadic,Branko Giri, Anish Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish Giri,Anish: 'Giri, Anish''} e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 {Italian is a frequent guest in the practice of modern top players and Firouzja's is no exception there. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'Italian is a frequent guest in the practice of modern top players and Firouzja's is no exception there.''} Bc5 4. O-O Nf6 5. d3 h6 {Many players these days prevent Bg5 at the first possible opportunity. This also has downsides, but perhaps this is not a moment for one of my favourite lectures- the lecture on the Italian move order subtleties. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'Many players these days prevent Bg5 at the first possible opportunity. This also has downsides, but perhaps this is not a moment for one of my favourite lectures- the lecture on the Italian move order subtleties.''} 6. c3 d6 7. Re1 O-O 8. h3 {This is not neccessary here and there is also quite some point in the 8.bd2 move order, intending to save on the move h3, after, for example, 8.bd2 a5 9.f1. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'This is not neccessary here and there is also quite some point in the 8.bd2 move order, intending to save on the move h3, after, for example, 8.bd2 a5 9.f1.''} a5 {I believe it was Eljanov, who was one of the first players to introduce this system to high level practice. As space started to get more appreciated by the modern engines and therefore also modern players, the system with a5, limiting the queenside expansion with b4, has gained in popularity.  Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'I believe it was Eljanov, who was one of the first players to introduce this system to high level practice. As space started to get more appreciated by the modern engines and therefore also modern players, the system with a5, limiting the queenside expansion with b4, has gained in popularity. ''} 9. Nbd2 {One disadvantage of 8...a5 over 8...a6, is that White doesn't have to address the positional threat of a5 and can focus on development without wasting a tempo on a4 or b3. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'One disadvantage of 8...a5 over 8...a6, is that White doesn't have to address the positional threat of a5 and can focus on development without wasting a tempo on a4 or b3.''} Be6 10. Bb5 {Another disadvantage of 8...a5 system, is that it weakens the b5 square, where the bishop can relocate itself. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'Another disadvantage of 8...a5 system, is that it weakens the b5 square, where the bishop can relocate itself.''} Ba7 {A decent side-system, which is a sound alternative to the complex main-line 10...b8!?, where the queen gets into the game via the a7-square. That system has a good reputation, but is very complex and double edged. What David does instead, is simpler, intending to tranfser the c6 knight to g6 via e7 and expand on the queenside with c6-b5-a5.  Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'A decent side-system, which is a sound alternative to the complex main-line 10...b8!?, where the queen gets into the game via the a7-square. That system has a good reputation, but is very complex and double edged. What David does instead, is simpler, intending to tranfser the c6 knight to g6 via e7 and expand on the queenside with c6-b5-a5. ''} (10... Qb8 {(Tadic,Branko) - 142/115}) 11. Nf1 Ne7 12. Ng3 {It made sense to start with 12.d4 as well, but then White had to deal with 12...exd4 13.cxd4 d5 14.e5 e4 15.g3 c5 sequence, typical for this line, that happened in Tabatabaei-Sevian 2020. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'It made sense to start with 12.d4 as well, but then White had to deal with 12...exd4 13.cxd4 d5 14.e5 e4 15.g3 c5 sequence, typical for this line, that happened in Tabatabaei-Sevian 2020.''} c6 13. Ba4 b5 (13... Ng6 {(Tadic,Branko) - 127/116}) 14. Bc2 a4 {Grabbing space on the queenside. The point of this setup for Black, is that while he does give White the opportunity to stabilise a strong centre after 15.d4, the queenside expansion with b5-a4 had made sure that Black has some queenside space and if White is to challenge it with b3 and c4, a lot of trades will happen, leading to simplifications, that are favorable for Black, the side that has less space in the centre.  Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'Grabbing space on the queenside. The point of this setup for Black, is that while he does give White the opportunity to stabilise a strong centre after 15.d4, the queenside expansion with b5-a4 had made sure that Black has some queenside space and if White is to challenge it with b3 and c4, a lot of trades will happen, leading to simplifications, that are favorable for Black, the side that has less space in the centre. ''} 15. d4 Ng6 {Tadic,Branko: 'Diagram [#]'} 16. Be3 {Tadic,Branko: 'N'} (16. b3 {Tadic,Branko}) (16. Qd2 {Tadic,Branko}) 16... Re8 17. Bd3 Bb6 {The bishop is generally better placed on b6, anticipating the typical b3 push and the opening of the a-file with axb3 axb3. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'The bishop is generally better placed on b6, anticipating the typical b3 push and the opening of the a-file with axb3 axb3.''} 18. a3 $5 {Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: '!?'' An interesting concept that I hadn't come across before. Usually White would fight for the queenside space and squares with b4/b3, leading to a lot of trades. Alireza solves the issue of the hanging a2 pawn differently, weakens the light squares further, but does keep literally all the pieces on the board and thus more pressure on the opponent. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'An interesting concept that I hadn't come across before. Usually White would fight for the queenside space and squares with b4/b3, leading to a lot of trades. Alireza solves the issue of the hanging a2 pawn differently, weakens the light squares further, but does keep literally all the pieces on the board and thus more pressure on the opponent.''} Qc7 {Alternative and possibly a clearer plan would have been 17...c7, preparing d5, with mass simplifications in the centre to follow.  Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'Alternative and possibly a clearer plan would have been 17...c7, preparing d5, with mass simplifications in the centre to follow. ''} 19. Rc1 {Introducing the c3-c4 break idea. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'Introducing the c3-c4 break idea.''} Ba5 {Black starts being clever here. Very possible was not to be too deep about things and just bring the a8 rook towards the center- Rad8, hinting at the d5 break. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'Black starts being clever here. Very possible was not to be too deep about things and just bring the a8 rook towards the center- Rad8, hinting at the d5 break.''} 20. Re2 Qb7 {Moving out of the c-file and intending to meet 21.c4 with 21...bxc4 22.Bxc4 and 22...d5. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'Moving out of the c-file and intending to meet 21.c4 with 21...bxc4 22.Bxc4 and 22...d5.''} 21. c4 {It was hard to improve the position further and White decides that it is a good time to start some action. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'It was hard to improve the position further and White decides that it is a good time to start some action.''} bxc4 22. Bxc4 d5 $1 {Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: '!'' Creating tension in the center. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'Creating tension in the center.''} 23. Bd3 {Neither 23.exd5 cxd5 nor 23.dxe5 Nxe4 promise anything clear for White, so instead he maintains the tension. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'Neither 23.exd5 cxd5 nor 23.dxe5 Nxe4 promise anything clear for White, so instead he maintains the tension.''} exd4 $6 {Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: '?!'' So far Black has done quite okay, but the next phase of the game goes badly wrong for him. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'So far Black has done quite okay, but the next phase of the game goes badly wrong for him.''} (23... c5 $1 {This was a strong shot here, when the position would be very double edged and White would have to show quite some accuracy here too, in order not to get into some trouble. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'This was a strong shot here, when the position would be very double edged and White would have to show quite some accuracy here too, in order not to get into some trouble.''} 24. dxc5 (24. Rxc5 {Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish' Probably best, going for complications that will likely lead to lots of simplifications.} dxe4 25. Nxe4 Nxe4 26. Bxe4 Qxe4 27. Bd2 {White regains the piece, but is not fighting for any advantage here, as for example 27...b3!? leads to a comfortable endgame for Black, by force.}) 24... d4 $1 {Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: '!'' A positional pawn sacrifice- the point behind the 23...c5! break. The c5 pawn is in fact doomed and will eventually get surrounded and picked up. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'A positional pawn sacrifice- the point behind the 23...c5! break. The c5 pawn is in fact doomed and will eventually get surrounded and picked up.''} 25. c6 {Tadic,Branko} Qc7 26. Bd2 Bb3 27. Bxa5 Rxa5 28. Qd2 Nf4 29. Ree1 Ne6 $13) 24. Nxd4 {White's pieces are ready to activate themselves and Black had to realize that this is a point of no return. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'White's pieces are ready to activate themselves and Black had to realize that this is a point of no return.''} Bd7 $2 {Tadic,Branko: '?!' Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: '?'' Too submissive. Now White gets the time he needs to regroup and go on the offensive. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'Too submissive. Now White gets the time he needs to regroup and go on the offensive.''} (24... Bc7 $1 {Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: '!'' Black had to create counterchances here and play more concrete. This move not only hits the g3 knight, but also guards the d6 square and now Ndf5 is no longer the same. Black is doing fine here, though the position is yet to clarify. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'Black had to create counterchances here and play more concrete. This move not only hits the g3 knight, but also guards the d6 square and now Ndf5 is no longer the same. Black is doing fine here, though the position is yet to clarify.''}) 25. Ndf5 $1 {Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: '!'' Now the direct threat is d6 and at the same time, White is ready to up the heat with d4 coming up next. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'Now the direct threat is d6 and at the same time, White is ready to up the heat with d4 coming up next.''} Bc7 26. exd5 cxd5 $2 {Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: '?'' Black doesn't have a good response to 27.d4, so he had to take with the knight instead. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'Black doesn't have a good response to 27.d4, so he had to take with the knight instead.''} (26... Nxd5 {Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish' Here Black at least gets to activate his f6 knight, which gives chances for counterplay.} 27. Bd4 Ndf4 {The knight on f4 is also doing stuff and it turns out that capturing the g7 pawn leads to a mess that is quite favourable for Black.} 28. Rxe8+ Rxe8 {now 29.xg7 c5! as well as 29.xg7 xf5 30.xf5 d8! 31.Rc3 c5! gives Black a lot of counterplay, hitting the g2 pawn, but the simple and strong 29.f1! maintains some advantage, thought after 29...e5 30. xe5 xe5 Black is still in the game.}) 27. Bd4 $1 {Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: '!''} Be5 {Tadic,Branko: 'Diagram [#]' This natural attempt to neutralize the d4 bishop has two tactical flaws. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'This natural attempt to neutralize the d4 bishop has two tactical flaws.''} 28. Nxh6+ {Tadic,Branko: '!' This shot works quite well, but the computer points out that the simple 28.xe5! was even more efficient. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'This shot works quite well, but the computer points out that the simple 28.xe5! was even more efficient.''} (28. Rxe5 $1 {This is actually even cleaner. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'This is actually even cleaner.''} Nxe5 (28... Rxe5 {Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish' This might have been Black's idea, but now the shot on g7 or h6 is even more powerful.} 29. Nxg7 Kxg7 30. Bxg6 {And Black's position crumbles.}) 29. Nd6 {White regains the exchange and ends up strategically winning, thanks to the powerful bishops. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'White regains the exchange and ends up strategically winning, thanks to the powerful bishops.''} Qb8 30. Nxe8 Qxe8 {Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish'} (30... Nxe8 {Tadic,Branko} 31. Bf5 $16) 31. Bb1 {White is quite simply winning, as the d4 bishop is unopposed and the attack is absolutely free, besides the large positional advantage.}) 28... gxh6 29. Bxg6 {The tactics work for White, as he basically ends up up a pawn. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'The tactics work for White, as he basically ends up up a pawn.''} Bxg3 30. Rxe8+ Rxe8 31. Qf3 $2 {Tadic,Branko: 'Diagram [#] Giri,Anish: '?'' Trying to be clever almost backfired, as Firouzja overlooks a cute tactic, that doesn't win for Black only thanks to a very fortunate save. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'Trying to be clever almost backfired, as Firouzja overlooks a cute tactic, that doesn't win for Black only thanks to a very fortunate save.''} (31. fxg3 {Was obviously the way to go, with a winning advantage, though work still had to be done after Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'Was obviously the way to go, with a winning advantage, though work still had to be done after''} fxg6 32. Bxf6 Qb3 {Tadic,Branko} 33. Qxb3 axb3 34. Rc7 Bf5 $16) 31... Qc6 $1 {Tadic,Branko: '!!' Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: '!'' A beautiful resource, based on the back rank theme (Rxc6 Re1+). Now if White moves the rook, Black would remain up a piece, but fortunately for White he still has a way to keep the largest portion of his advantage.  Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'A beautiful resource, based on the back rank theme (Rxc6 Re1+). Now if White moves the rook, Black would remain up a piece, but fortunately for White he still has a way to keep the largest portion of his advantage. ''} 32. Bc2 $1 {Tadic,Branko: '' Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: '!''} Bb8 $2 {Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: '?'' The alternatives were offering better chances to save the game. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'The alternatives were offering better chances to save the game.''} (32... Qxc2 {Now the variation is forced- Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'Now the variation is forced-''} 33. Qxg3+ Qg6 34. Qxg6+ fxg6 35. Bxf6 {Tadic,Branko: ''} Kf7 {Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish'} 36. Bd4 {This endgame is terribly unpleasant for Black, but there are some drawish tendencies, thanks to the opposite coloured bishops and the fact that White hasn't yet mobilised his king.}) (32... Be5 {Is also a decent attempt at fighting on. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'Is also a decent attempt at fighting on.''} 33. Bh7+ {Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish'} (33. Bxe5 {Tadic,Branko} Rxe5 34. Bh7+ Nxh7 35. Rxc6) 33... Nxh7 34. Rxc6 Bxc6 35. Bxe5 Rxe5 {Black has quite some material for the queen. Now White has a strong sequence.} 36. Qg4+ $1 Kh8 37. Qf4 $1 {a simple double attack on the f7 and h6 pawns.} f6 38. Qxh6 {and White is the one playing for a win here, but with some accurate play, Black is likely able to setup a succesful defense here.}) 33. Qxf6 {White ends up up a pawn in an endgame. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'White ends up up a pawn in an endgame.''} Qxf6 34. Bxf6 Rc8 35. Bc3 {White is just up a pawn and has almost stabilsed. There was still a way for Black to fight on here. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'White is just up a pawn and has almost stabilsed. There was still a way for Black to fight on here.''} d4 $2 {Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: '?'' The final mistake, closing the a1-h8 diagonal, making the b2 pawn breath a sigh of relief, as Be5 is no longer an idea. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'The final mistake, closing the a1-h8 diagonal, making the b2 pawn breath a sigh of relief, as Be5 is no longer an idea.''} (35... Bd6 $1 {Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: '!'' Would actually still keep the game going. There is a threat of d4 followed by Rb8, while if White goes 36.Bd3 now, there is a strong reply 36...Be5!. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'Would actually still keep the game going. There is a threat of d4 followed by Rb8, while if White goes 36.Bd3 now, there is a strong reply 36...Be5!.''} 36. Bd3 Be5 $1 {Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish' And as Black will trade the dark squared bishops, White will still have quite some trouble converting this  (perhaps it is even holdable, objectively), as the b2 pawn will need protection.}) 36. Bd2 $1 {Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: '!'' Now Black is done, as the h6 pawn needs protection and 37.d3 is queued up. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'Now Black is done, as the h6 pawn needs protection and 37.d3 is queued up.''} Kg7 37. Bd3 {Black had to be in time with Bd6-Rb8, but now the c8 rook is practically trapped for a trade and the bishop endgame is dead lost, slowly but surely. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'Black had to be in time with Bd6-Rb8, but now the c8 rook is practically trapped for a trade and the bishop endgame is dead lost, slowly but surely.''} Rxc1+ 38. Bxc1 {Tadic,Branko: '+-' Black is down a pawn and is completely helpess here. Firouzja converts smoothly. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'Black is down a pawn and is completely helpess here. Firouzja converts smoothly.''} h5 39. h4 Bc6 40. g3 Bd7 41. Kf1 {The king is slowly making its entree. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'The king is slowly making its entree.''} Be5 42. Ke2 Bg4+ 43. Kd2 Bd7 44. Kc2 Be6 45. Bb5 Bb3+ 46. Kd3 {All black pawns are weak and it is the d4 pawn that is falling first. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'All black pawns are weak and it is the d4 pawn that is falling first.''} Kg6 47. Bd7 Bd1 48. Bd2 f5 49. Bf4 Bg7 50. Bd6 Bf6 51. Be8+ Kh6 52. Bc5 f4 53. Bxd4 Bd8 54. Kd2 Bb3 55. Be5 fxg3 56. fxg3 Ba5+ 57. Kc1 {The h5 pawn drops as well. Tadic,Branko: 'Giri,Anish: 'The h5 pawn drops as well.''} 1-0


[Event "British Chess Championship"]
[Site "Warwick University"]
