1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 (3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 d5 6. Nf3 b6 7. O-O Bb7 8. a3 Bd6 {is the Tal Variation of the Nimzo-Indian (see below).}) 3... b6 4. e3 Bb7 5. Bd3 d5 6. O-O Nbd7 7. b3 Bd6 8. Bb2 O-O 9. Nc3 a6 {The set-up David Howell has chosen here is a solid way of meeting the 4 e3 Queen's Indian. There are clear similarities here with the Tal Variation of the Nimzo-Indian.} 10. Rc1 Qe7 11. Na4 ({The alternative is to release the tension in the centre with} 11. cxd5 exd5 {- see the notes to Mamedjarova, Z-Chiburdanidze, M/Calvia 2004.}) 11... Rad8 ({Earlier this year Glenn enjoyed a very quick win in this line:} 11... c5 12. cxd5 exd5 $2 ({Black has to play} 12... Nxd5) 13. Nxb6 $1 {(a nice shot)} Nxb6 14. dxc5 Bxc5 15. Bxf6 gxf6 16. Nh4 $1 {(White has a winning attack)} Rfc8 17. Nf5 Qe6 18. Qh5 $1 Ba3 19. Qh6 Qxf5 (19... Bf8 20. Ne7+ $1) 20. Bxf5 Rxc1 21. Bxh7+ {1-0 Flear, G-Brunner, N/Montpellier 2015.}) ({The most popular choice for Black has been} 11... dxc4 12. bxc4 {and only now} c5) 12. Qe2 {The first new move.} (12. Ne5 dxc4 13. Nxc4 b5 14. Nxd6 cxd6 15. Nc3 e5 16. Ba3 e4 17. Be2 Nb6 18. Bb4 Nbd5 19. Ba5 Rc8 20. Nxd5 {1/2-1/2 was Petrosian, A-Schlosser, P/Budapest 1991.}) (12. c5 $1 {seems to be critical. Indeed c4-c5 is the consistent follow-up to 11 Rc1 and probably explains why Black normally chooses to play ...dxc4 followed by ...c5 to avoid this.} bxc5 13. dxc5 Nxc5 (13... Bxc5 $2 14. Nxc5 Nxc5 15. Ba3 Nfd7 16. Rxc5 Nxc5 17. Qc2 {wins}) 14. Nxc5 Bxc5 15. Ng5 $1 (15. Bxf6 gxf6 16. Bxh7+ {is met by} Kg7 $1) 15... Bd6 ({or} 15... e5 16. Nxh7 Nxh7 17. Bxh7+ Kxh7 18. Qc2+ e4 19. Qxc5 {with a slight edge for White}) 16. Bxf6 Qxf6 (16... gxf6 $4 17. Qh5) 17. Qh5 $1 (17. Nxh7 $2 Qe5) 17... h6 18. Nh7 Qe7 19. Nxf8 Rxf8 {White has won the exchange, but Black has a pawn and the two bishops as some compensation.}) 12... dxc4 {Now this is pretty much forced, as otherwise Black has to worry about cxd5 and Bxa6.} 13. bxc4 Ne4 (13... c5 {is also possible.}) 14. Rfd1 f5 $1 15. c5 $6 {The c4-c5 advance is what White has been angling for, but it doesn't turn out well. The question is, though, what else does White do? Maybe Black is already at least equal after 14...f5.} bxc5 16. Bxa6 (16. Bc4 $5) 16... Bxa6 17. Qxa6 cxd4 18. exd4 $2 (18. Bxd4 $1 {keeps White's pieces more active and restricts Black's advantage.}) 18... Ra8 19. Qc6 Ndf6 20. a3 Qd7 (20... Rfb8 $1 $17) 21. Qxd7 Nxd7 22. Nc3 $2 {Losing a pawn.} (22. Ne5 $1 {is stronger.}) 22... Rfb8 $1 23. Ba1 Bxa3 24. Rc2 Nxc3 25. Bxc3 Nf6 {Black is a clear pawn ahead with a good position, and David Howell goes on to convert his advantage without any real problems.} 26. Ng5 Rb6 27. Re1 Nd5 28. Bd2 Re8 29. g3 h6 30. Nf3 Bd6 31. h4 Kf7 32. Kg2 Ra8 33. Rec1 Kf6 34. Rc4 Ra2 35. R1c2 Rbb2 36. Rxb2 Rxb2 37. Rc6 Ra2 38. Rc1 Ke7 39. Rb1 Ra8 40. Kf1 Kd7 41. Ke2 Ra2 42. Kd3 Nf6 43. Be3 Ng4 44. Nd2 g5 45. hxg5 hxg5 46. Rg1 Be7 47. Nc4 Nxf2+ 48. Bxf2 Rxf2 49. Ne5+ Kc8 50. g4 Bf6 51. Nf7 Kd7 52. gxf5 Rxf5 53. Rg4 Ke7 54. Nh6 Rf3+ 55. Ke4 Rh3 56. Ng8+ Kf7 57. Nxf6 Kxf6 58. Rg1 Rh4+ 59. Ke3 Rh3+ 60. Ke4 Rh4+ 61. Kd3 Rh7 62. Ke4 Rg7 63. Rg4 Rg8 0-1


