1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. exd5 exd5 5. Ngf3 Nc6 6. Bb5 cxd4 $5 {Yet another clever idea for Black. It was first played by Botvinnik in 1941, was taken up by Korchnoi, and is a modern-day favourite of Short, so it has fine French pedigree.} 7. Qe2+ $1 {I decided this check would be our move, then checked other sources and was relieved to find the following opinions: "Probably the best try for an advantage." - Caruana "The only way to pose problems." - Marin.} ({To understand the point of 6...cxd4 we need to consider what happens if White simply castles. After} 7. O-O {the natural continuation is} Bd6 8. Nb3 Nge7 9. Nbxd4 {with the final move being needed as there is a pawn on d4 to retrieve. This transposes to a main line position normally reached via 6...Bd6 7.dxc5 Bxc5 8.0-0 Nge7 9.Nb3 Bd6 10.Nbd4. However in that main line position, we have better moves than 10.Nbd4, as we will see in Games 25-27. So now we can understand that 6...cxd4 is a devious attempt to trick the unwary into a lesser version of the 6...Bd6 line. But since we are wary, all Black will achieve is an unpleasant endgame.}) ({I am less keen on} 7. Nxd4 {due to} Bd7 {when} 8. Qe2+ {can be met by} Be7 {and Black will safely castle before White manages to play Re1.}) {For the record, the real move order of this game was 7.Nxd4 when instead of the troubling 7...Bd7, Black chose 7... Qe7+ 8.Qe2 Qxe2+ 9.Kxe2} 7... Qe7 {Almost everyone agrees that this move is essential.} (7... Be7 {The one person who believes in this line is GM Anatoly Vaisser who has played it four times.} 8. O-O {Black's problem is that he is struggling to castle as Re1 is coming.} a6 $1 {Black wants to play ...Nf6 and . ..0-0, without dropping the e7-bishop, and ...a7-a6 contributes to that plan by allowing ...Ra7.} (8... Nf6 {was played by Vaisser in his most recent game, but I think he made the right choice in his two earlier games.} 9. Re1 Bd7 10. b3 $1 Kf8 {White can be happy with this achievement.} 11. Bb2 Bc5 12. Bxc6 bxc6 {White is spoiled for choice:} 13. Nxd4 $14 {was Shirov - Gelfand, Moscow  (blitz) 2007} (13. Bxd4 Bxd4 14. Nxd4 $14 {was Sebag - Vaisser, Nancy 2013}) ({and best of all is} 13. Qd3 $1 $146 {planning Bxd4 and then recapturing with the queen.})) 9. Bxc6+ bxc6 10. Re1 $1 $146 {"An interesting idea, and perhaps the only try for an advantage." - Caruana} (10. Nxd4 c5 {is fine for Black, as Vaisser showed by drawing both Kosashvili - Vaisser, Tel Aviv 1990, and Sulskis - Vaisser, New York 1998.}) 10... Ra7 {White has many promising options, but I suggest the following bind-building line:} 11. b4 $5 Nf6 12. Nxd4 Rc7 13. N2b3 O-O 14. Nc5 $14 {White has no need to fear opposite-coloured bishops as there would be many other pieces remaining, including a beautiful knight on d4.}) 8. Nxd4 {We will take an ending where White's better structure is the difference.} ({Do not be tempted by} 8. Ne5 $6 Bd7 9. Bxc6 bxc6 10. O-O {Since Re1 is threatened, and} f6 {fails to} ({But one move shows it's an illusion:} 10... Kd8 $1 {There will be no checks on h5, and ...f7-f6 is coming.} 11. Nb3 f6 {So far this is Svidler - Dolmatov, Haifa 1995, and according to Dolmatov, Anand suggested} 12. f4 {White will certainly get some compensation for the piece, but it is not convincing. Call me conservative, but I will recommend the simple endgame edge rather than the risky piece sac.}) 11. Qh5+ {this at first looks superb for White.}) 8... Qxe2+ 9. Kxe2 Bd7 10. N2f3 {This position has been tested in over 30 games, with White scoring 55%. This score would be higher were it not for two Korchnoi wins with Black from bad positions, including an infamous game against HÃ1/4bner which we shall see below.} Bd6 ({One of many ways Black can try to hold a slightly worse ending. I will show a few examples:} 10... Nxd4+ 11. Nxd4 Bc5 12. Be3 Bxb5+ (12... Bxd4 13. Bxd7+ Kxd7 14. Bxd4 f6 15. Rhd1 $14 {Ravi - Dolmatov, Kolkata 1996}) 13. Nxb5 Bxe3 14. Kxe3 Kd7 15. Rhd1 Nf6 16. f3 $14 {Smirin - Korchnoi, Biel 2002.}) (10... a6 11. Bd3 Bd6 ({A more recent example was:} 11... f6 12. Nxc6 $5 bxc6 13. c4 Bd6 14. cxd5 cxd5 15. Be3 $14 {In Oleksienko - Zvjaginsev, Legnica 2013, Black eventually drew a rook ending a pawn down.}) 12. Nf5 Bxf5 13. Bxf5 Nge7 {Instead I suggest:} 14. Bh3 $1 $14 {N The bishop may look odd on h3, but after a plan such as Rd1, Kf1, g2-g3 and Bg2, all will be normal again, with White's bishop pair pressing against the IQP.} ({In Averbakh - Botvinnik, Moscow 1943, after} 14. Bd3 Nb4 {Black was OK.})) (10... Nf6 11. Re1 Nxd4+ 12. Nxd4 $14 {is yet another endgame edge.}) 11. Re1 Nge7 12. Kf1 $14 {Our misplaced king was the only problem and that was easily fixed, leaving White with a normal anti-IQP endgame edge.} a6 13. Bd3 O-O 14. c3 Rfe8 15. Be3 {Finally varying from} ({and slightly improving on, the game Akopian - Lputian, Yerevan 1997, which continued:} 15. h3 Nxd4 16. Nxd4 Nc6 17. Rxe8+ Rxe8 18. Nxc6 Bxc6 19. Be3 Be5 20. Rd1 g6 21. Be2 Kg7 22. Bf3 Rd8 23. h4 $14 {White kept grinding away, and eventually won.}) 15... Nxd4 16. Nxd4 Nc6 17. Nf3 Ne5 18. Nxe5 {White's 13th, 17th and 18th moves show a simple but important idea: we are happy to exchange some minor pieces, but only if it does not improve Black's structure.} Bxe5 19. Rad1 Rac8 20. h3 Be6 21. Be2 b5 {When one sees the game continuation, it is tempting to criticize this move, but instead doing nothing is not appealing either.} 22. Rd2 Bc7 {The bishop looks better on e5, so a luft-making move such as 22...g6 would have been my choice.} 23. Red1 Rcd8 $6 {Now Black loses a pawn.} (23... Rb8 {discourages the plan that works so well in the game, and allows Black to meet} 24. Bf3 {with} ({But if White makes the a-pawn safe with} 24. a3 $1 {then the suffering continues.}) 24... d4 {hitting a2.}) 24. a4 $1 bxa4 25. Bxa6 Rb8 26. Ra1 f5 27. Rxa4 $16 {A perfect model game, if we stopped right here.} Bd7 28. Rad4 $2 {Falling for a well-hidden back rank trick.} (28. Ra3) ({or} 28. Ra1 {would leave White a pawn up with the better structure.}) 28... f4 $1 {Short is sharp.} 29. Bxf4 Bxf4 30. Rxf4 Ra8 31. Rxd5 {There is nothing better.} ({The piece is lost in an even worse version after:} 31. Be2 $2 Ra1+ 32. Rd1 Rxd1+ 33. Bxd1 Bb5+ 34. Kg1 Re1+ $19) 31... Rxa6 32. Kg1 $15 {White has three pawns for the bishop, but the pawns are unable to advance effectively, so only Black can try to win.} Be6 33. Re5 Rc8 34. Kh2 Rb6 35. Re2 h6 36. Rd4 Rc7 37. Kg3 Bf7 38. Red2 g6 39. Rd6 Rb3 40. Re2 Rcb7 41. Rdd2 {White is totally tied up, but there is no way to increase the pressure; the bishop can race around the board, but that feeble little pawn on b2 will always be beyond its reach.} Kg7 42. f3 R7b6 43. h4 Be6 44. Kf4 Kf6 45. Rf2 h5 46. Rfe2 Bc4 47. Rf2 Bf7 48. Rfe2 Be6 49. Rf2 Bc8 50. Rd8 Bf5 51. Rdd2 Ra6 52. Rfe2 Ra4+ 53. Kg3 Rb6 54. Rd8 Be6 55. Rdd2 Rc6 56. Rd8 Ra2 57. Rb8 Ra1 58. Rd2 Rh1 59. Rb4 Bf5 60. Rbd4 Rc7 61. Rd6+ Kg7 62. R6d4 Rb7 63. Re2 Rb1 1/2-1/2


