1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h6 5. g4 Bh7 6. e6 fxe6 7. Bd3 Bxd3 8. Qxd3 Nf6 9. Nf3 {Howell deviates from the recommendation in the course to play 9.Qg6+ covered here. What Howell played also gives White a significant advantage, but it is slightly less precise.} Qd6 10. Ne5 {Planning to go for a deadly check with Qg6 followed by a fork with Nf7} Ne4 11. f3 {Chasing away the knight. Black cannot move the knight is Qg6 is deadly.} Nd7 12. fxe4 Nxe5 13. dxe5 Qxe5 {Howell is a piece up. It is instructive to see how we convert this position. The priority is to get the king to safety by castling queenside.} 14. Nc3 {Developing and defending the d4-pawn.} O-O-O 15. Bd2 {Getting ready to castle and consolidate, but Black has other plans.} dxe4 16. Qxe4 {Howell wasn't worried about allowing ...Qg3+ as Black has not enough attackers to create serious problems.  16.Qe3 This would have been my choice. We prevent ...Qg3+ and get ready to castle safely. Later we can pick up the e4-pawn.} Qg3+ 17. Ke2 {This is better than 17.Kd1 , which wouldn't allow the a1-rook to join the game. The rest of the game is a matter of technique. It's interesting to see how Howell converts this winning position.} g5 18. hxg5 Bg7 19. Rag1 Qd6 20. Bf4 e5 21. Be3 hxg5 22. Rh5 {I like this choice from Howell. Surely you are familiar with the rule that you want to trade pieces once you are up. By trading pieces, you reduce your opponent's counter-chances. So why didn't Howell capture the rook on h8?  22.Rxh8 I think it is a good decision from Howell not to trade rooks. White would trade the strong rook on the h-file and give up control over the h-file. 22...Rxh8 White now has to worry about Black's rook entering the position on h2. Still, White would have a winning position here. However, trading the rooks made life slightly more difficult for us. It's beneficial to trade pieces once we are up in material . However, we shouldn't make trades that benefit our opponent more than us.} Kb8 23. Bxg5 Bf6 24. Be3 {Howell decides again not to trade the bishop and retreat. This is a decision I like.  24.Bxf6 Trading the bishop would improve Black's pawn structure. 24...exf6 Black got rid of the doubled pawns now and did benefit from the trade.} Rxh5 25. gxh5 Qe6 26. h6 Qh3 27. Rh1 {The rook is supporting the past pawn.} Qg3 28. Qf3 {At this point, Howell is willing to trade queens. The trade of queens would be a trade that comes without any downsides for White. That's why it would make it easier to covert the winning position into a victory as it takes away Black's counter-chances.} Qg6 {Black understandably refuses the trade of queens.} 29. Ne4 {Defending against ...Qxc2+} Bh8 30. Rg1 Qe6 31. b3 {Defending against ...Qc4+. Howell keeps the position under control and doesn't give Black any counter-chances.} Qd5 32. h7 Qb5+ 33. Kf2 Qa5 34. Rg8 Bf6 35. Nxf6 exf6 36. Qxf6 {Black resigned. Also, here Howell didn't trade rooks on the previous move with 36.Rxd8 Qxd8 . White's rook is stronger than Black's rook as it prevents Black from defending the last rank. Black cannot prevent us from promoting to a queen when our rook is on g8. Also Black wouldn't be able to capture the rook on g8 as we would recapture and promote to a queen. What is instructive about this game is that Howell showed that to convert a winning position to victory, we should avoid making trades that favor our opponent. When there is no downside in trading pieces, we benefit from this when we have a material advantage since it reduces our opponents' chances to fight back in the game.} *


