1. g3 {White started originally with 1.g3, but the players entered position from our Chapter later on.} e5 2. c4 d6 3. Nc3 g6 {This move mostly demonstrates, that Black doesn't mind entering KID paths with g3. Also, in the case of 4.Bg2 Bg7 Black might consider ...f7-f5 at some point.} 4. d4 {White takes an opportunity of seizing the centre. Now Black is at a crossroads.} Bg7 {Elisabeth accepts the possible liquidation into an endgame.  The most common alternative was 4...Nd7 , and then our repertoire is based on 5.Bg2 Bg7 6.dxe5  StartBracketInstead, 6.Nf3 transposes to Classical KID with g3.EndBracket 6...dxe5 7.b3} 5. dxe5 dxe5 6. Qxd8+ Kxd8 7. b3 {This move is a novelty. The second fianchetto is very effective now - the bishop might be placed both on b2 or a3.} Na6 {This feels artificial. Elisabeth covers the c7-pawn, so it is easier to move the king on d8.  7...c6 weakens d6, so after 8.Ba3! Nd7 9.O-O-O Nh6 10.Bh3↑ White seizes the initiative.  Hardly better is also 7...Nh6 8.Ba3 f6 9.O-O-O+ Nd7 10.Bh3↑} 8. Bg2 {The pressure of the bishop on g2* along the diagonal is supposed to force the somewhat committing ...c7-c6. The following line illustrates the issues of Black's setup: 8...c6 9.Ba3 f5 10.e4! Not only preventing the blocking ...e5-e4, but also intending to open the central files. 10...Nf6 11.O-O-O+ Ke8 12.Nf3 Despite the queen trade Black's king is in big danger.} Ke8 {Too awkward is 8...Nh6 9.Ba3 f6 10.b4↑ with a powerful play on the queenside.} 9. Ba3 {The most ambitious way - the Ba3 heavily restricts the mobility of Black's pieces.} f5 10. O-O-O Nh6 {Hardly better is 10...e4 11.Nb5! Nf6 12.f3 , the knight on a6 is stuck and the king on e8 is under fire.} 11. e4 {David is temporarily locking the Bg7 and creates a favorable pressure in the centre.} Ng4 12. Rf1 {It was more tempting to play 12.Nh3!? Possibly, it was rejected by GM Howell in view of 12...f4 13.gxf4 exf4 , although 14.e5! also puts Black's king in serious danger.} Bh6+ 13. Kb1 Bf8 {A decent idea - the exchange of bishops might partly solve Black's problems.} 14. Bxf8 {More promising was 14.Bb2! Bc5 15.Nd1 fxe4 16.Bxe4 Rf8 17.Nf3↑ White's pieces are better mobilized, and the e5-pawn is weak.} Rxf8 15. h3 Nf6 16. exf5 Bxf5+ {Black gains an important tempo and almost completes her development.} 17. Ka1 c6 {This timid move spoils Elisabeth's previous efforts.  The knight's activation was called for: 17...Nb4! 18.Bxb7 Rd8 19.g4 Bd3 20.Rd1 Nd7⇆ Black has a sufficient compensation for a pawn.} 18. Re1 Nb4 {After 18...Nd7 19.Nf3 Nb4 20.Re2± White wins a pawn either way.} 19. Rxe5+ Kf7 20. Nf3 {Black has no compensation for a pawn.} Rad8 21. Re2 {A decent prophylactic move. It is vital to cover the 2nd rank.} Kg8 22. Rd1 Rxd1+ 23. Nxd1 Be4 {More challenging for White would be 23...Ne4!? 24.a3 Nd3 , and then he should find the consolidating 25.Nd4! Nc1 26.Re3 Rd8 27.Kb2 Rxd4 28.Kxc1± , keeping everything under control.} 24. Ne1 {An accurate move.} Rd8 25. Nc3 Bxg2 26. Nxg2 {Black's activity is fully neutralized.} Kf7 27. Ne1 Kf8 {After 27...a5 28.Kb1 Na6 29.Nf3 White still should make progress soon.} 28. a3 Na6 29. Kb2 Nc5 30. Kc2 a5 31. Nf3 h6 32. Re3 {Now all of White's pieces are placed optimally.} g5 33. h4 g4 {This makes David's task easier as the g4-pawn is weak.  33...Ng4 34.Re2 Re8 35.Rd2±} 34. Ne5 Kg7 35. Re1 Rd6 36. Re3 h5 37. Nd3 {Inviting favorable simplifications.} Ne6 38. Ne2 Kf7 39. Ne5+ Kg7 40. Nd3 Kf7 41. Re5 b6 42. Ndf4 Ng7 43. Nc3 Rd4 44. Nfe2 Rd8 45. Ne4 {Stronger was 45.Nf4! Nd7 46.Rg5 Re8 47.a4+-} Nxe4 46. Rxe4 Ne6 47. Re5 Rh8 48. Nf4 Nxf4 49. gxf4 Rh6 {Luckily for GM Howell, Elisabeth returns the favor.  Had she played 49...Rd8! 50.Kc3 Rd1 draw would be a possible result.} 50. c5 b5 {Or 50...bxc5 51.Rxc5 Rf6 52.f5+-} 51. Kd3 Rh8 52. Ke4 {The activity of king+rook easily decides the game.} Rd8 {This is too late.} 53. Rxh5 Rd2 54. Rh7+ Kf6 55. Rh6+ Kf7 56. Kf5 Rd5+ 57. Kxg4 Rxc5 58. f5 Rc1 59. Kg5 Rg1+ 60. Kf4 c5 61. Rc6 Rc1 62. Rc7+ Kf6 63. Rc6+ Kf7 64. h5 c4 65. bxc4 bxc4 66. h6 c3 67. h7 Kg7 68. Rc7+ Kh8 69. f6 Rc2 70. f3 Rh2 71. Rc8+ *


