1. e4 {Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'RR RR: 'Marjanovic,Slavoljub Marjanovic,Slavoljub Marjanovic,Slavoljub''} e5 ({Here is the earliest example of the 'Greek Gift' (see the notes to White's 20th, below), from a 16th century manuscript by Polerio:} 1... e6 {Marjanovic,Slavoljub: '(RR) Marjanovic,Slavoljub'} 2. d4 Nf6 ({the latest example I know about was played by one of my Redhill Chess Club team mates, Cliff Chandler:} 2... d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Be7 5. e5 Nfd7 6. h4 O-O 7. Bd3 c5 8. Nh3 cxd4 $4 9. Bxe7 Qxe7 {and, familiar with the Greek Gift pattern, Cliff played} 10. Bxh7+ $1 {; his opponent knew it as well and so resigned rather than face} Kxh7 11. Qh5+ Kg8 12. Ng5) 3. Bd3 Bb4+ 4. c3 Ba5 5. Nf3 O-O 6. e5 Nd5 7. Bxh7+ $1 {. The Greek Gift sacrifice. It wins time for the white queen and knight to launch a decisive attack on the black king. After} Kxh7 8. Ng5+ {it is soon over, for example} Kg8 ({or} 8... Kh6 9. Nxe6+ {winning the queen,}) ({while after} 8... Kg6 9. h4 $1 {followed by 10 h5+ or 10 Qg4 the black king is defenceless}) 9. Qh5 Re8 ({he had to give up the queen with} 9... Qxg5) 10. Qxf7+ Kh8 11. Qh5+ Kg8 12. Qh7+ Kf8 13. Qh8+ Ke7 14. Qxg7# {.}) 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 ({Black spurns} 3... a6 {in favour of immediate development and a counterattack against e4. This was an approach advocated by World Champion Emanuel Lasker in his book 'Common Sense in Chess' way back in 1895. For most of the 20th Century 3...a6 held unchallenged sway. But will the 21st Century be a new age of the Berlin Defence? Marjanovic,Slavoljub: '(RR) (Marjanovic,Slavoljub) in favour of immediate development and a counterattack against e4. This was an approach advocated by World Champion Emanuel Lasker in his book 'Common Sense in Chess' way back in 1895. For most of the 20th Century 3...a6 held unchallenged sway. But will the 21st Century be a new age of the Berlin Defence?'}) 4. O-O Nxe4 {Neil McDonald: 'Question: S'RR: 'Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: 'Neil McDonald: 'Question: So what are the pros and cons for Black in taking the pawn on e4? Answer: The positive point of the capture is that, although White will get a pawn on e5, he won't be able to construct a 'perfect' centre with pawns on d4 and e4 any longer. Having reduced the white centre in size and flexibility, Black is in less danger of falling into a long term positional bind. His pieces have more centre squares available to them. On the minus side, capturing on e4 and getting the knight away takes three moves, so the white pieces are getting out more quickly than the black pieces. Black will have to make some concession to survive the increased energy he is giving the white pieces by opening lines in the centre. In the Berlin Endgame, for example, Black 'buys off' White's immediate pressure by forfeiting the right to castle. ''''' o what are the pros and cons for Black in taking the pawn on e4? Answer: The positive point of the capture is that, although White will get a pawn on e5, he won't be able to construct a 'perfect' centre with pawns on d4 and e4 any longer. Having reduced the white centre in size and flexibility, Black is in less danger of falling into a long term positional bind. His pieces have more centre squares available to them. On the minus side, capturing on e4 and getting the knight away takes three moves, so the white pieces are getting out more quickly than the black pieces. Black will have to make some concession to survive the increased energy he is giving the white pieces by opening lines in the centre. In the Berlin Endgame, for example, Black 'buys off' White's immediate pressure by forfeiting the right to castle. '} 5. d4 {Neil McDonald: '!' '!''RR: 'Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: 'Neil McDonald: '!'''''} ({More energetic than} 5. Re1 {. White wants to keep the initiative as well as regain his pawn. Marjanovic,Slavoljub: '(RR) (Marjanovic,Slavoljub) . White wants to keep the initiative as well as regain his pawn.'}) 5... Be7 {This alternative to the mo'RR: 'Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: 'This alternative to the more popular 5...Nd6 is a pet line of the Russian GM Malakhov and was advocated by many great players in the past including Steinitz, Anderssen, Zukertort, Lasker and others.'' Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: 'This alternative to the more popular 5...Nd6 is a pet line of the Russian GM Malakhov and was advocated by many great players in the past including Steinitz, Anderssen, Zukertort, Lasker and others.' Mikhalevski, V: 'This alternative to the more popular 5...Nd6 is a pet line of the Russian GM Malakhov and was advocated by many great players in the past including Steinitz, Anderssen, Zukertort, Lasker and others. Neil McDonald: 'The Rio de Janeiro Variation. Howell returns the pawn at once to speed up his development.''''' re popular 5...Nd6 is a pet line of the Russian GM Malakhov and was advocated by many great players in the past including Steinitz, Anderssen, Zukertort, Lasker and others. Neil McDonald: 'The Rio de Janeiro Variation. Howell returns the pawn at once to speed up his development.'} ({Similar to the game would be} 5... Nd6 {Marjanovic,Slavoljub: '(RR) Marjanovic,Slavoljub'} 6. Bxc6 bxc6 (6... dxc6 {is the Berlin Endgame discussed below}) 7. dxe5 Nb7 {, and now Hübner suggests} 8. Nd4 $5 {intending 9 Qf3 as clearly better for White. Black would certainly have problems unravelling his game.}) ({Question: But why not grab a pawn with 5...exd4 or 5...Nxd4? Answer: We can quickly dismiss} 5... Nxd4 $2 {as after Marjanovic,Slavoljub: '(RR) (Marjanovic,Slavoljub) as after '} 6. Nxd4 exd4 7. Re1 f5 8. f3 {White wins a piece.}) ({More tricky is} 5... exd4 {, though Marjanovic,Slavoljub: '(RR) (Marjanovic,Slavoljub) , though'} 6. Re1 f5 7. Nxd4 Nxd4 8. Qxd4 c6 9. f3 $1 {leads to a good endgame for White after} cxb5 10. fxe4 Qb6 {(Black gets the queens off to avoid the frontal attack on his king)} 11. exf5+ Kf7 {, and now rather than} 12. Be3 {, which turned out pretty well for White in O.Korneev-Z.Varga, Zalaegerszeg 2004,} ({the simple} 12. Qxb6 axb6 13. Nc3 {, leaving Black with mangled pawns, looks even stronger to me – if} Bc5+ 14. Be3 {.})) 6. Qe2 ({Question: Can you guess why this might be preferred to} 6. Re1 {? (Hint: think of the Berlin Variation with 5...Nd6 6 Bxc6 dxc6.) Answer: After Marjanovic,Slavoljub: '(RR) (Marjanovic,Slavoljub) ? (Hint: think of the Berlin Variation with 5...Nd6 6 Bxc6 dxc6.) Answer: After '} Nd6 7. Bxc6 dxc6 8. dxe5 Nf5 {, in contrast to the normal Berlin Endgame Black has his bishop on e7, so that} 9. Qxd8+ {doesn't displace his king – he can recapture} Bxd8 {. Therefore White plays 6 Qe2 instead of 6 Re1, so if Black headed for this line he could be hit at the end by 9 Rd1, embarrassing his queen. That is why he recaptures with 7...bxc6 rather than 7...dxc6 below.}) 6... Nd6 {Neil McDonald: 'Black saves'RR: 'Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: 'Neil McDonald: 'Black saves his knight with gain of time by hitting the white bishop.''''' his knight with gain of time by hitting the white bishop.'} ({Besides, he doesn't want to walk into a pin on c6 after} 6... d5 {Marjanovic,Slavoljub: '(RR) Marjanovic,Slavoljub'} 7. Nxe5 {.}) 7. Bxc6 bxc6 8. dxe5 Nb7 {Here White has a wide choi'RR: 'Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: 'Here White has a wide choice of options.'' Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: 'Here White has a wide choice of options.' Mikhalevski, V: 'Here White has a wide choice of options. Neil McDonald: 'Strategically speaking, a very double-edged situation has arisen. Black's development has suffered – the bishop on c8 is still shut in – and his knight is on a strange square, though given time it could go from c5 to e6, where it would sit nicely in the centre. Meanwhile White has a serious space advantage, but Black hopes to neutralize it with ...f7-f6, when his bishop pair might become the defining feature of the position.''''' ce of options. Neil McDonald: 'Strategically speaking, a very double-edged situation has arisen. Black's development has suffered – the bishop on c8 is still shut in – and his knight is on a strange square, though given time it could go from c5 to e6, where it would sit nicely in the centre. Meanwhile White has a serious space advantage, but Black hopes to neutralize it with ...f7-f6, when his bishop pair might become the defining feature of the position.'} ({Instead after} 8... Nf5 {the black horse can become a target for White's kingside expansion. For example, Marjanovic,Slavoljub: '(RR) (Marjanovic,Slavoljub) the black horse can become a target for White's kingside expansion. For example,'} 9. c4 O-O 10. Nc3 d5 11. Rd1 Be6 12. g4 $1 Nh4 13. Nxh4 Bxh4 14. f4 {when Black had no answer to the double threat of 15 f5, winning the d5-pawn, or 15 g5, shutting in the bishop on h4, in M.Vachier Lagrave-A.Kosten, Haute Le Port Marly 2009.}) 9. c4 {This rare continuation (les'RR: 'Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: 'This rare continuation (less than 10 games in the last 10 years) was introduced by Zukertort in 1868! The idea behind the move is to take better control over the centre before playing Nc3.'' Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: 'This rare continuation (less than 10 games in the last 10 years) was introduced by Zukertort in 1868! The idea behind the move is to take better control over the centre before playing Nc3.' Mikhalevski, V: 'This rare continuation (less than 10 games in the last 10 years) was introduced by Zukertort in 1868! The idea behind the move is to take better control over the centre before playing Nc3. Neil McDonald: 'Adams increases his pawn presence in the centre before developing his knight to c3. ''''' s than 10 games in the last 10 years) was introduced by Zukertort in 1868! The idea behind the move is to take better control over the centre before playing Nc3. Neil McDonald: 'Adams increases his pawn presence in the centre before developing his knight to c3. '} ({You can also find information on the more popular} 9. Nd4 {Grischuk, A (2717) -Malakhov, V (2679)/Elista RUS 2007/[TonyK]. Marjanovic,Slavoljub: '(RR) (Marjanovic,Slavoljub) Grischuk, A (2717) -Malakhov, V (2679)/Elista RUS 2007/[TonyK].'}) ({and} 9. Nc3 {Anand, V-Timman, J/Wijk aan Zee 1999/[Nigel Davies]. Marjanovic,Slavoljub: '(RR) (Marjanovic,Slavoljub) Anand, V-Timman, J/Wijk aan Zee 1999/[Nigel Davies].'}) ({and also the less common} 9. Re1 {Lau, R-Smagin, S/ Berlin 1990/[Nigel Davies], in our PGN Archive. Marjanovic,Slavoljub: '(RR) (Marjanovic,Slavoljub) Lau, R-Smagin, S/ Berlin 1990/[Nigel Davies], in our PGN Archive.'}) 9... O-O 10. Nc3 ({Zukertort's} 10. Be3 {found no followers. That game continued Marjanovic,Slavoljub: '(RR) (Marjanovic,Slavoljub) found no followers. That game continued'} f5 $5 11. exf6 Bxf6 12. c5 $6 d5 $1 13. Nd4 $2 {0-1 Zukertort, J-Anderssen, A/Berlin 1868 and now} Nxc5 14. Nxc6 Qd6 $17 {promised Black a clear advantage.}) 10... f6 {The main line. The exchange'RR: 'Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: 'The main line. The exchange of the e5-pawn is important for Black, though as the game shows, it has drawbacks, in particular it weakens the position of Black's king.'' Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: 'The main line. The exchange of the e5-pawn is important for Black, though as the game shows, it has drawbacks, in particular it weakens the position of Black's king.' Mikhalevski, V: 'The main line. The exchange of the e5-pawn is important for Black, though as the game shows, it has drawbacks, in particular it weakens the position of Black's king. Neil McDonald: 'The thematic challenge to the white centre. Even so, Black has to be careful not to try for too much activity when his queenside is still undeveloped.''''' of the e5-pawn is important for Black, though as the game shows, it has drawbacks, in particular it weakens the position of Black's king. Neil McDonald: 'The thematic challenge to the white centre. Even so, Black has to be careful not to try for too much activity when his queenside is still undeveloped.'} ({Smyslov preferred Neil McDonald: 'I have'Smyslov preferred Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Smyslov preferred Mikhalevski, V: 'Smyslov preferred Neil McDonald: 'I have seen a photograph of the game M.Tal-V.Smyslov, Moscow 1971, and Tal looked pretty satisfied with his position from the opening after '''' seen a photograph of the game M.Tal-V.Smyslov, Moscow 1971, and Tal looked pretty satisfied with his position from the opening after '} 10... Nc5 {, but came under some pressure after Marjanovic,Slavoljub: '(RR) (Marjanovic,Slavoljub) , but came under some pressure after'} 11. b3 (11. Be3 $5 Ne6 12. Rad1 $14) 11... f6 12. Bb2 fxe5 13. Nxe5 {Neil McDonald: 'etc.''Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: 'Neil McDonald: 'etc.''''} Qe8 $1 14. Rae1 Ne6 15. Nd3 Qg6 16. f4 $14 {Tal, M (2620)-Smyslov, V (2620)/Moscow 1971.}) 11. Re1 {This line is considered to 'RR: 'Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: 'This line is considered to be equal and was out of fashion for quite a while until Svidler beat the main expert of the line, Malakhov, in 2010.'''' be equal and was out of fashion for quite a while until Svidler beat the main expert of the line, Malakhov, in 2010.} ({Malakhov also faced Tal's} 11. Bd2 {Marjanovic,Slavoljub: '(RR) Marjanovic,Slavoljub'} fxe5 12. Nxe5 Bf6 13. Rae1 Qe8 14. Ng4 Qxe2 15. Nxf6+ Rxf6 16. Rxe2 d6 {and Black held the position, though White's chances in Naiditsch, A (2674)-Malakhov, V (2725)/Sibenik 2010, look higher.}) 11... fxe5 12. Qxe5 {Ehlvest's idea, which he in'RR: 'Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: 'Ehlvest's idea, which he introduced back in 1992, but Svidler was next to give it another test.'''' troduced back in 1992, but Svidler was next to give it another test.} ({Earlier White preferred} 12. Nxe5 {, but all of those games were drawn. Marjanovic,Slavoljub: '(RR) (Marjanovic,Slavoljub) , but all of those games were drawn.'}) 12... Bf6 13. Qg3 $1 {Adams is the first to devia'RR: 'Marja