ub'} (19... h6 20. Nf7 {RR: '!' '!' '!' '!'} Rxf7 {RR} 21. Re8+ {mit Gewinnstellung.}) 20. Rxf8+ Kxf8 21. Nxh7+ Kg8 22. Qd8+ Kxh7 23. Re4 $18) 19... Qxf8 20. Nce4 $1 {with two decisive threats 'RR: 'Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: '+-!' Mikhalevski, V: 'is also winning. See 18...Qd6.'' Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: '+-!' '+-!' Mikhalevski, V: 'is also winning. See 18...Qd6.'''' of 21.Nf6!! and 21.Nxh7!, which Black can't stop. For example,} Ba6 21. Nxh7 {Marjanovic,Slavoljub: '!''RR: '!' 'Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: '+-!' Mikhalevski, V: 'White wins a tempo attacking Black's queen, but the text is also enough for a win. By the way, this position also arises after 18...Qd6. See above.'' Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: '+-!' '+-!' Mikhalevski, V: 'White wins a tempo attacking Black's queen, but the text is also enough for a win. By the way, this position also arises after 18...Qd6. See above.''''} Qf5 22. Nhf6+ Kf7 23. Qxc7 $1 {Marjanovic,Slavoljub: '+-''RR: '+-' 'Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: '!'' Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: '!' '!''''} Nxc4 {Marjanovic,Slavoljub: '(RR) Marjanovic,Slavoljub'} 24. Nxd7 $1 Kg8 25. Qxc6 $18) 19. Nce4 $1 {Neil McDonald: 'Exercise: H'RR: 'Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: '!'' Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: '!' '!' Mikhalevski, V: 'Neil McDonald: 'Exercise: How should White continue after 19...Nxc4? Generally speaking, in order to carry out a successful attack on the enemy king, a large superiority in firepower is required. This is because the king himself and his defensive wall of pawns can be surprisingly resilient. Here, however, White's advantage is overwhelming. He has all his pieces – the queen, two rooks and a knight – engaged in the attack, whereas only the black queen and rook on f8 are available to the defence. ''''' ow should White continue after 19...Nxc4? Generally speaking, in order to carry out a successful attack on the enemy king, a large superiority in firepower is required. This is because the king himself and his defensive wall of pawns can be surprisingly resilient. Here, however, White's advantage is overwhelming. He has all his pieces – the queen, two rooks and a knight – engaged in the attack, whereas only the black queen and rook on f8 are available to the defence. '} (19. Rxf8+ $1 {RR: 'Marjanovic,Slavoljub'} Qxf8 20. Nce4 $1 $18 {is also winning. See 18...Qd6.}) 19... Ba6 {Protecting the last rank.'RR: 'Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: 'Protecting the last rank.''''} ({Neil McDonald: 'Answer'Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: 'Neil McDonald: 'Answer: After'''' : After'} 19... Nxc4 {Neil McDonald: ',''(RR) Marjanovic,Slavoljub Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: 'Neil McDonald: ',''''} 20. Rxf8+ Qxf8 21. Nf6+ $1 $18 {also leads to a disaster. Neil McDonald: '!' '!' Nei'also leads to a disaster. Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'also leads to a disaster. Mikhalevski, V: 'also leads to a disaster. Neil McDonald: '!' Neil McDonald: 'wins: upon'''' l McDonald: 'wins: upon'} Kh8 {Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Marjanovic,Slavoljub'} (21... gxf6 {Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Marjanovic,Slavoljub'} 22. Ne6+ {picks up the queen,}) ({as does} 21... Qxf6 {Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Marjanovic,Slavoljub'} 22. Re8+ Qf8 23. Rxf8+ Kxf8 {with the knight to follow as well after} 24. Qf4+) {the quickest of many wins is} 22. Qh4 h6 23. Qe4 $1 {with catastrophe on h7 for the black king.}) 20. Nxh7 $1 {Neil McDonald: 'Question: I'RR: 'Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: 'Neil McDonald: 'Question: I guess you need strong powers of calculation to carry out a kingside attack? Answer: Not particularly, the important thing is to be familiar with standard attacking patterns. For example you might have seen the 'Greek Gift' sacrifice. If you look at Adams' move 20 Nxh7!, you can see it borrows the theme of the Greek Gift – a piece is sacrificed on h7 to expose the black king and so win time for a decisive combination by the white queen and knight. It isn't quite as forcing as there is no check, but Black can't ignore the destruction of his kingside. So Howell decides to take the knight and in sporting style lets his opponent carry out a neat mate in the centre of the board. ''''' guess you need strong powers of calculation to carry out a kingside attack? Answer: Not particularly, the important thing is to be familiar with standard attacking patterns. For example you might have seen the 'Greek Gift' sacrifice. If you look at Adams' move 20 Nxh7!, you can see it borrows the theme of the Greek Gift – a piece is sacrificed on h7 to expose the black king and so win time for a decisive combination by the white queen and knight. It isn't quite as forcing as there is no check, but Black can't ignore the destruction of his kingside. So Howell decides to take the knight and in sporting style lets his opponent carry out a neat mate in the centre of the board. '} ({After} 20. Rxf8+ $1 Qxf8 21. Nxh7 $1 $18 {White wins a tempo attacking Black's queen, but the text is also enough for a win. By the way, this position also arises after 18...Qd6. See above.}) 20... Rxf3 ({Oder} 20... Kxh7 {RR} 21. Ng5+ Kg8 22. Rxf8+ Qxf8 23. Qh3 {mit baldigem Matt.}) 21. gxf3 $1 {Neil McDonald: 'The white q'RR: 'Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: '!'' Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: '!' '!' Mikhalevski, V: 'Neil McDonald: 'The white queen has to stay on g3 to support his next move. ''''' ueen has to stay on g3 to support his next move. '} Kxh7 {Otherwise 22.Qg6 with the s'RR: 'Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: 'Otherwise 22.Qg6 with the subsequent 23.Nef6.'''' ubsequent 23.Nef6.} 22. Ng5+ Kg8 23. Qh4 Bxc4 {This last attempt to protec'RR: 'Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: 'This last attempt to protect the king fails.'''' t the king fails.} 24. Qh7+ Kf8 25. Re5 $1 {A decisive move. Black is doomed. N'RR: '!' RR: 'Marjanovic,Slavoljub: 'Mikhalevski, V: '!' Mikhalevski, V: 'A decisive move. Black is doomed.'' Marjanovic,Slav