1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bb4+ 5. c3 Bc5 6. Nxc6 {This idea was introduced by Kasparov back in 1997 in his game vs Leko.} (6. Be3 {Nepomniachtchi, I (2729)-Najer, E (2638)/Olginka RUS 2011/[Mikhalevski, V].}) 6... bxc6 7. Bd3 d6 (7... Ne7 {is more popular, but it usually transposes to the text after} 8. O-O O-O ({or} 8... d6) 9. Nd2 d6) (7... Qh4 {is another interesting line.}) 8. O-O Ne7 9. Nd2 O-O 10. b4 $1 {The most logical. White is going to exchange the dark-squared bishop by means of Nc4.} ({White also tested other moves:} 10. Kh1 f5 11. f4 Bb6 12. Qf3 {Wiersma, E (2414) -Kasimdzhanov, R (2672)/Fuegen 2006, and now Black could have equalized by means of} fxe4 13. Nxe4 d5 14. Ng5 h6 15. Bh7+ Kh8 16. Bd3 Kg8 $11) (10. Nb3 Bb6 11. Nd4 Bd7 12. Bg5 {Kovchan, A (2554)-Lenic, L (2565)/Trieste 2009.} h6 13. Bh4 Qe8 $1 14. Nf5 Nxf5 15. exf5 Qe5 16. Re1 Qf4 17. Bg3 Qg5 {and Black is just slightly worse.}) 10... Bb6 11. a4 $5 {White provokes an advance of the a-pawn.} ({The immediate} 11. Nc4 $5 $14 {also makes sense.}) 11... a5 ({White also looks better after} 11... a6 12. a5 Ba7 13. Nf3 {and the a6-pawn is becoming a target.}) 12. Nc4 $1 {Attacking the loose bishop on b6.} axb4 {A novelty.} ({In the only preceding game Black played} 12... Be6 13. Nxb6 cxb6 14. Qc2 (14. b5 $5) 14... Qc7 15. Rd1 $14 {with a slight edge for White in Kotronias, V (2591)-Mastrovasilis, A (2556)/Vrahati GRE 2010.}) 13. Nxb6 cxb6 14. cxb4 $14 {White is slightly better thanks to the bishop pair, the dark-squared bishop is especially strong.} c5 15. Bb2 Be6 (15... Nc6 $5 {deserved attention, trying to provoke an exchange on c5.}) 16. Re1 ({I like} 16. Bb5 $5 {, which prevents ...Nc6 and prepares Qd3 with pressure on d6 and a possible transfer of the queen to g3. For example,} Qc7 17. Qd3 f6 18. Qg3 Kh8 19. Rfd1 Rfd8 20. Rac1 $14) 16... f6 {A useful move, which puts an obstacle on the way of White's dark-squared bishop.} ({Once again} 16... Nc6 $5 {was worth serious attention.}) 17. Qd2 $5 {White connects the rooks.} (17. bxc5 $1 {allowed him to retain an edge as Black would have to either create the passed a-pawn after 17...bxc5 or the passed e-pawn after 17...dxc5.} bxc5 ({or} 17... dxc5 18. Qc2 $14 {with the subsequent 19.e5.}) 18. Bc3 Nc6 19. Qd2 Na5 20. Rad1 Qc7 21. Bb5 $14) 17... Nc6 $1 {Finally.} 18. Bc3 $1 {Retaining favorable tension for White.} Qc7 19. b5 {This looks premature as it yields Black the a5-square.} (19. Rec1 $5 {would make Black's task more difficult.}) 19... Na5 20. Bc2 Rfd8 {Black protects the main potential weakness in advance.} 21. Rab1 $6 {White covers the b3-square, but misses an exchange of his bishop.} (21. Qd3 {bringing the queen to the best square on g3, where she attacks the d6-pawn and creates threats along the g-file, deserved serious attention.} c4 22. Qg3 Kh8 23. Rad1 $14) 21... Kh8 {Prophylaxis.} ({However} 21... Nc4 $1 22. Qe2 Na3 23. Ra1 Nxc2 24. Qxc2 d5 {allowed Black to at least equalize.}) 22. Qf4 Ba2 {Before retreating the bishop to g8 Black wants to misplace White's rook.} (22... Nc4 $5 23. Bb3 Qf7 $11 {is roughly equal thanks to the strong knight on c4.}) 23. Rb2 ({Probably Howell didn't want to leave the b-file by means of} 23. Rbd1 $5 {in view of} Bb3 {Then after a trade of the bishops it seems that the a-pawn is in trouble, though White suddenly creates counterplay on the kingside.} 24. Bxb3 Nxb3 25. Qh4 $1 Qf7 (25... Rxa4 {is strongly met by} 26. Bxf6 $1) 26. f4 $1 {with the idea} Rxa4 27. e5 {in both case with a slight edge for White.}) 23... Bg8 {Now Black wants to play 24...Nc4 with tempo.} 24. Rbb1 Qf7 $5 {Clearly showing his intentions.} ({Black could have tried to repeat the position by means of} 24... Ba2) 25. h3 {On one hand this is a useful move, on the other it takes away the h3-square from White's rook.} ({So, the immediate} 25. Re3 {bringing the rook to the kingside and protecting the c3-bishop, deserved serious attention.}) 25... h6 $5 {Black is going to create pressure on the e4-pawn by means of 26...Bh7.} 26. Re3 Bh7 27. Rd1 Qe7 {The position remains roughly equal, but suddenly White commits suicide.} 28. Bxa5 {This move isn't that bad yet, but the idea behind it is just a blunder.} ({The computer recommends setting a diabolical trap by means of} 28. Rd2 $5 {Indeed it's difficult to realize that} Nc4 $6 {can be met by} (28... Ra7 $1 $11 {is better.}) 29. e5 $3 Nxe3 (29... Nxe5 30. Bxh7 Kxh7 31. Qe4+ $1 Kg8 32. f4 $16 {is also a difficult line to find.}) (29... fxe5 30. Qxc4 Bxc2 31. Rxc2 d5 32. Qe2 $1 $16) 30. exf6 Qe6 31. fxg7+ Kg8 32. fxe3 Bxc2 33. Rxc2 $14) (28. Rde1 $11 {is more human.}) 28... Rxa5 29. Red3 $2 {This looks like a blackout. Probably White missed Black's 34th move.} ({After} 29. Bb3 $11 {the position remains equal.}) 29... Qxe4 $17 30. Rxd6 $4 {White is still unaware of the unpleasant surprise.} ({White should have played} 30. Qd2 $17 {retaining some practical chances to escape.}) 30... Qxf4 31. Rxd8+ Bg8 32. Bg6 {If not for Black's reply this idea of 33.Rxg8 with a subsequent 34.Rd8 would indeed be very strong, but} Qc4 $1 $19 {A cold shower. Now it's over.} 33. g3 Rxa4 34. Re1 {Despite having a decisive material advantage Black still has to be cautious.} f5 ({Black had a strong idea at his disposal.} 34... Qb3 $3 {Preparing 35...Rd4 with the subsequent ...Qd5.} 35. Ree8 Rd4 $1 36. Rc8 Qd5 $1 $19 {Threatening 37...Rd1.}) 35. Re7 ({The best practical chance would be} 35. Bxf5 {Then Black would have to find} Qc3 $1 ({In fact} 35... g6 36. Be6 Qc3 37. Rf1 Ra1 $19 {is also enough for a win.}) 36. Ree8 Qb3 37. Be6 Qb1+ $1 (37... Qf3 $1 $19 {also works.}) 38. Kg2 (38. Kh2 Ra1 $1 39. Rxg8+ Kh7 $19) 38... Qe4+ 39. Kh2 Ra1 40. g4 Qh1+ 41. Kg3 Ra3+ 42. Kf4 Qf3+ 43. Ke5 Qf6+ 44. Ke4 Ra4+ $19 {and Black wins.}) 35... f4 $5 36. gxf4 (36. Bf7 {doesn't help.} Ra1+ 37. Kg2 (37. Kh2 fxg3+ $1 $19) 37... Qf1+ 38. Kf3 Qh1+ $1 39. Kg4 h5+ $1 40. Kg5 Ra8 $1 41. Rxa8 Qxa8 42. Re8 Qa1 $1 $19) 36... Qxf4 $6 (36... Ra1+ {is more precise, but the text is good enough for a win.} 37. Kg2 Qf1+ 38. Kg3 Qg1+ 39. Kf3 Qxg6 $19) 37. Bf7 $2 {A blunder in a lost position.} ({White could have transposed into a rook endgame, though after} 37. Rxg8+ Kxg8 38. Re8+ Qf8 39. Bh7+ $1 Kf7 40. Bg6+ $1 Kxg6 41. Rxf8 Rb4 $19 {two connected pawns promise Black an easy win.}) 37... Qg5+ {White loses a rook and so he resigned. Despite his loss, the opening line promises White a slight edge.} 0-1


