1. e4 {Baburin (www.chesstoday.net)} e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 {Mikhalevski, V: 'No more Berling endgame.'} Bc5 5. c3 O-O 6. O-O Re8 {Mikhalevski, V: 'A relatively rare continuation, which was only introduced in the 21th century.'} (6... d6 {is the main line. Gashimov, V (2760)-Grischuk, A (2746)/Ningbo CHN 2011/[Mikhalevski, V].}) 7. Bg5 {Mikhalevski, V: 'The most aggressive.'} (7. Nbd2 {is the major alternative. Then a relatively recent top game featured an interesting novelty.} d6 $5 8. d4 exd4 9. cxd4 Nxd4 $1 {This exchange sacrifice is the point of 7...d6.} 10. Bxe8 Qxe8 11. Nxd4 Bxd4 {and it turns out that Black obtains good compensation for the exchange.} 12. h3 Bd7 13. Re1 Bc6 14. Nf3 Bb6 15. Be3 Ba5 16. Bd2 Bb6 $11 17. Be3 Ba5 18. Bd2 Bb6 19. Be3 {and a draw was agreed in Dominguez Perez, L (2713)-Aronian, L (2783)/ Leon (m) 2010.}) 7... h6 8. Bh4 Bf8 {Mikhalevski, V: 'Black introduces a new idea. Before playing ...d6 he removes his bishop from an attack by means of d4.'} ({In a few preceding games Black played} 8... a6 9. Ba4 Ba7 10. Re1 d6 11. Nbd2 Kh8 12. Nf1 Rg8 13. Ne3 g5 14. Bg3 $14 {and White was slightly better in Alekseev, E (2691)-Van der Werf, M (2432)/Plovdiv 2010, thanks to his control over the weak f5-square.}) 9. Nbd2 d6 10. d4 {Mikhalevski, V: '!' Mikhalevski, V: 'The only way to fight for the advantage.'} exd4 11. Nxd4 Bd7 12. Nxc6 bxc6 ({White retains a slight edge after} 12... Bxc6 13. Bxc6 bxc6 14. Qa4 g5 15. Bg3 Qd7 16. Rfe1 $14) 13. Bd3 {Mikhalevski, V: 'White is slightly better thanks to the central pawn on e4.'} Be7 ({Black could have started with} 13... Rb8 $5 {and after} 14. f4 Be7 ({but not} 14... Rxb2 $6 15. Nc4 Rb8 16. e5 d5 17. Na5 c5 $1 18. exf6 c4 19. Bc2 c6 $1 20. Nb3 cxb3 21. axb3 $14)) 14. f4 Qb8 {Mikhalevski, V: '!?' Mikhalevski, V: 'Black provokes the pawn sacrifice as White can't protect the b2-pawn.'} ({After} 14... Ng4 15. Bxe7 Qxe7 16. Qf3 Rab8 17. b3 {White retains slightly better chances.}) 15. Bxf6 {Mikhalevski, V: '!'} (15. Qc2 $2 {would be wrong in view of} Nd5 $1 16. exd5 (16. Bxe7 $2 Ne3 $1 17. Qc1 Nxf1 $17) 16... Bxh4 17. dxc6 Bxc6 $15) 15... Bxf6 16. e5 {Mikhalevski, V: '!' Mikhalevski, V: 'A strong positional pawn sacrifice, which is based on a long-term initiative.'} dxe5 17. Ne4 {Mikhalevski, V: '!'} Qxb2 {Mikhalevski, V: 'This principled continuation looks a little bit risky.'} (17... Be7 18. f5 $1 {also leads to a strong initiative.}) (17... Qd8 $1 {was a safer alternative.} 18. Qh5 g6 19. Nxf6+ (19. Qxh6 Bg7 $11) (19. Qf3 Qe7 $1 20. f5 Bxf5 21. Nxf6+ Qxf6 22. Bxf5 (22. g4 {is met by} Qg5) 22... gxf5 23. Qxf5 Qxf5 24. Rxf5 Rad8 {and Black is at least not worse.}) 19... Qxf6 20. Qxh6 e4 {Black closes the f-file and equalizes.} 21. Bc4 Bf5 $11) 18. f5 Red8 19. Bc4 {Mikhalevski, V: '!' Mikhalevski, V: 'Carlsen puts additional pressure on Black's position.'} Be8 {Mikhalevski, V: 'The correct practical decision.'} ({The computer's} 19... Be6 $5 {is very unclear.} 20. Nxf6+ Kf8 $1 21. Bd3 Bc4 22. Qg4 $1 Bxd3 23. Nh5 Bxf1 24. Qxg7+ Ke8 25. Rxf1 Qxc3 {and even though Black seems to survive the attack it would be very impractical to go for such wild complications without knowing their consequences.}) 20. Qh5 {Mikhalevski, V: '!?'} Rd6 {Mikhalevski, V: '?!' Mikhalevski, V: 'A good defensive resource, but it would be better to protect the bishop with the queen.'} ({After} 20... Qb6+ $1 21. Kh1 c5 22. Rae1 Rab8 {the position remains very tense.}) 21. Rab1 Qc2 22. Qg4 {Mikhalevski, V: 'White seems to create a hidden threat of 23.Rfc1 in order to meet 23... Qa4?? with 24. Nxf6 gxf6 25.Bxf7! a discovered attack on a4! However, Black can meet 23.Rfc1 with 23...h5! Nevertheless, Black's move is useful.'} (22. Rbe1 $5 {was an interesting alternative.} c5 $1 23. Bb3 Qd3 24. Rf3 Qa6 25. Qg4 {with attack.}) 22... Kf8 {Mikhalevski, V: '!'} 23. h3 {Mikhalevski, V: '!' Mikhalevski, V: 'Carlsen demonstrates fantastic composure, which is only typical of great players.'} Rad8 {Mikhalevski, V: '!' Mikhalevski, V: 'So far so good. Howell also shows good defensive skills.'} 24. Kh2 {Mikhalevski, V: '!' Mikhalevski, V: 'White puts his king into safety and prepares a rook lift.'} Qa4 {Mikhalevski, V: '!' Mikhalevski, V: 'All the other pieces are in their best defensive positions and so Black disturbs White's attack with the queen.'} 25. Rb4 Qa3 26. Rb7 R6d7 {Mikhalevski, V: '?!' Mikhalevski, V: 'An inaccuracy.'} ({After} 26... Qa4 $1 27. Qe2 Qa5 $11 {it would be difficult for White to make progress.}) 27. Qf3 {Mikhalevski, V: '!?' Mikhalevski, V: 'White pretends to attack the c6-pawn. Sometimes waiting tactics achieve more than immediate aggression.'} ({However} 27. Qh5 $1 {would set some immediate problems.} Qa4 (27... Qe7 28. Rxa7 $14) 28. Nxf6 gxf6 (28... Qxc4 29. Nxd7+ Rxd7 30. Qf3 $1 $14) 29. Qh4 $1 Rd6 30. Rxc7 $14) 27... Qa4 (27... a5 $5) 28. Qe2 {Mikhalevski, V: 'Black's task is far from being easy. Any inaccuracy may become fatal.'} Re7 $2 {Mikhalevski, V: 'Black doesn't stand the pressure and takes away an important square from his king. This turns out to be a decisive mistake.'} (28... Qa5 {Mikhalevski, V: '!?' Mikhalevski, V: 'with the idea of 29...Rd6 deserved attention.'} 29. Qh5 Rd6 $11) 29. Nxf6 $18 gxf6 30. Qe3 {Mikhalevski, V: '+-!' Mikhalevski, V: 'Suddenly Black is defenseless.'} Red7 (30... Qxc4 $2 {loses on the spot to} 31. Qxh6+ Kg8 32. Rb4 $1 $18) (30... Kg7 {is not better due to} 31. Rb4 Qa5 32. Rf3 $1 $18 {For example,} Red7 33. Rg3+ Kf8 34. Qxh6+ Ke7 35. Rg8 $1 $18) 31. Qc5+ {Mikhalevski, V: '!' Mikhalevski, V: 'The king is not allowed to e7.'} Rd6 (31... Kg7 {is strongly met by} 32. Rb4 $1 Qa3 33. Be6 $1 $18) 32. Rxc7 {Mikhalevski, V: '!'} Qc2 {[%tqu "En","","","","c7c8","",10]} 33. Rc8 $3 {Mikhalevski, V: '!'} R8d7 {Baburin (www.chesstoday.net): 'Diagram '} 34. Be6 $1 Ke7 35. Bxd7 Bxd7 36. Rh8 (36. Qxa7 {Baburin (www.chesstoday.net) Mikhalevski, V: '!'} Qe2 37. Qc7 $1 Rd2 38. Rg1 $1 $18 {would be even better and Black can't stop 39.Qd8 with the subsequent 40.Qxf6.}) 36... Qd3 37. Rf3 Qd5 38. Qxa7 e4 39. Qb8 $6 {Mikhalevski, V: '?' Mikhalevski, V: 'A mistake, probably in time trouble.'} (39. Rf1 {Baburin (www.chesstoday.net): '' Mikhalevski, V: '!' Mikhalevski, V: 'was much more precise.'} Qe5+ 40. Kh1 $18 Rd3 41. Qa8 $1 $18 {and White wins.}) 39... Qe5+ $16 40. Rg3 {Mikhalevski, V: '' Mikhalevski, V: 'and Black resigned in his best position in the last 10 moves.' Mikhalevski, V: 'For the sake of truth it has to be said that after'} Qxf5 41. a4 $1 Ke6 42. Rxh6 $16 {White is still clearly better. Another great positional achievement from the World number one player! Moreover, White managed to set some problems in the opening and so Black is still to find an improvement. The ball is now in Black's court.} 1-0


