{Van Delft & Ris: 'THE MIGHTY KRAMNIK We've reported before about the new Kramnik and again he was considering a piece sacrifice on move 13. He managed to control himself this time and won anyway with some fine tactics.' Gormally, Danny: 'THE LEGEND OF DRAWNIK. Chess of course, is huge on the internet these days. And, with the internet, you get your fair share of "trolls ". An internet troll, for those unfamiliar with such terms, is someone who deliberately makes insulting comments, to try to provoke some kind of negative emotional reaction. And with so many top tournaments now being broadcast live online, it was inevitable that the trolls would get their teeth in and that the top players would be unfairly saddled with some rather insulting nicknames at some point. Magnus Carlsen, whenever he draws a game, automatically becomes Magnus Drawsen. (Magnus Carlsberg, probably the best chess player in the world, is another nickname he goes by.) Hikaru Nakamura is often called something like Kaspamura (in recognition of his short-lived work with Garry Kasparov) or, more often, as just plain "Naka". Vladimir Kramnik, the recent winner of the strongest tournament ever to be held on these shores, the London Chess Classic, often has a reputation as a dry, arid player, who favours endgames and not terribly exciting openings like the Berlin Defence, and is occasionally summarily dismissed as "Drawnik". However, this nickname and reputation is somewhat inaccurate, in my view. Or at least outdated. While he went through a period of several years when at least with Black he tended to avoid any great risks, lately we've seen his style go back to something like his youth. He is much more flamboyant and aggressive, perhaps realising that, with the likes of Carlsen and Aronian around now, it would be difficult for him to win top tournaments without putting his head on the parapet at some stage. I mean, let's face it, it is rather hard to believe that Kramnik became world champion and got to 2800 on the rating list by simply having a good feel for the Berlin and Petroff defences. At some point you have to be able to win games. I recall that in a French league a few years ago, a couple of strong Russian grandmasters were telling me how Kramnik had a reputation for being the best tactician of his generation when he was younger, but gradually his style became more positional. Clearly though, he can still "turn it on" when he has to. In fact, in the London Chess Classic, Kramnik gave an extraordinary demonstration of his chess imagination, during the press conference of his game against the young British player David Howell. These press conferences are live streamed at the time and are saved as videos on the London Chess Classic site. They really should not be missed by anyone hoping to improve, as they give an invaluable insight into the chess minds of the very best players in the world. In fact, such was the breathless mental masterclass given by Kramnik, I was both inspired and depressed at the same time immediately after watching it. Inspired, because it gave some idea of what is possible in chess, and depressed because I got the distinct impression that, however hard I try to improve, I could never get near the level of such a player. I've tried to put at least the first part of this amazing video into its proper context, and any comments in quotation marks are Kramnik's unless indicated otherwise.'} 1. Nf3 {Gormally, Danny} d5 2. d4 Nf6 3. c4 dxc4 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. Nc3 ({More common alternatives are} 7. dxc5 {(CVO 52, 120, 129) and}) (7. Bb3 {(CVO 89, 139).}) 7... Nc6 ({Another option is} 7... b5 8. Bb3 Bb7 9. e4 $5 {which we covered in CVO 49 and 57.}) 8. a3 (8. a4 {is a rather harmless line, as after} Be7 9. Qe2 cxd4 10. Rd1 e5 11. exd4 exd4 12. Nxd4 Nxd4 13. Qe5 Qd6 {many games quickly ended in a draw.}) 8... b5 9. Ba2 Bb7 10. Qe2 Qc7 (10... cxd4 11. Rd1 {followed by 12.exd4 gives White nice play.}) (10... Be7 11. dxc5 (11. Rd1 $5) 11... Bxc5 12. b4 Bd6 13. Bb2 O-O 14. Rfd1 Qe7 15. Rac1 Rfd8 {with equality in Nikolaidis-Ivanchuk, Eretria 2011.}) 11. Rd1 ({The most consistent plan is to push d4-d5. Right now} 11. d5 {is a bit premature, since after} exd5 12. Nxd5 Nxd5 13. Bxd5 Be7 14. a4 Qb6 15. e4 O-O 16. Bg5 Nd4 $1 {Black was doing fine in Sandipan-Fridman, Pardubice 2002.}) (11. h3 {was played in Piket-Korchnoi, Tilburg 1998 and now the logical continuation would have been} Rd8 $1 {with approximately equal chances.}) 11... Rd8 12. d5 {Gormally, Danny: '"I have to do d5 if I want to get something"'} exd5 {Van Delft & Ris: 'Diagram [#]'} 13. Nxd5 ({Van Delft & Ris: 'Kramnik would have preferred installing a N permanently on d5 and hence mainly focused on' Gormally, Danny: 'The first important moment in the game. Kramnik started throwing some pretty wild variations around at this point. The main alternative was'} 13. Bxd5 {Van Delft & Ris: 'but failed to make it work after' Gormally, Danny: 'which Kramnik analysed in great detail. Both players now agreed that' had been played before. Kramnik considered it but felt he couldn't make it work.} b4 $1 {Gormally, Danny: 'was critical.'} (13... Be7 14. e4 {as played in Schandorff-Unzicker,F Copenhagen 2010, was considered somewhat favorable for White by Kramnik. Gormally, Danny: 'followed by Bg5 and Kramnik liked White.'}) 14. axb4 cxb4 {Gormally, Danny: '[diagram] "And now there are two moves."'} {Gormally, Danny: 'The other move is'} 15. Rxa6 {Gormally, Danny: '. Kramnik couldn't quite make this work either, although not without want of trying:'} (15. Ng5 Rd7 $1 {Gormally, Danny: 'Now Kramnik suggested the flamboyant'} (15... bxc3 $2 {loses to} 16. Bxf7+ Ke7 17. bxc3 {Gormally, Danny: '(with a huge threat of Ba3)'} Rxd1+ 18. Qxd1 Qd7 {Gormally, Danny: '. Howell had also seen up to this point. Kramnik now suggested the further moves'} 19. Qb3 $1 $18 {Gormally, Danny: '!'} Kd8 {Gormally, Danny} 20. Ne6+ Kc8 21. Nxf8 Rxf8 22. Be6 {"This is what I calculated." At which point one of the commentators at the event, GM Danny King, interjected with the comment that "the other day you said you're too old to calculate. Listen - this is incredible depth" to which Vladimir replied, "Yeah, but I'm sure that there are some blunders"}) 16. Rxa6 {Gormally, Danny: '!?' Gormally, Danny: 'but this seems to fall short after'} bxc3 17. Bxc6 Bxc6 18. Rxd7 Qxd7 {and White can't bring his Q to the battlefield due to back rank problems. Gormally, Danny: 'where White would like to continue his attack here with'} 19. Qc4 {(Gormally, Danny) but unfortunately for him this fails to} Qd1+ {. Now all these variations, with pieces sacced all over the place, could be dismissed as flights of fancy, and not a serious attempt. But in fact Kramnik was seriously considering all this, because if it works then as he said, he would have played Bxd5. Contrast this with many players who sleepwalk through the opening, plod along on auto-pilot, using general considerations and only really put their calculating hat on later in the game. What this showed was that Kramnik was already engaging his tactical imagination at an early stage, where everything looked very boring and solid. He was already trying to find a way through, to blast his way through the black defences using his incredible imagination, but this proved beyond him for the simple reason that Black has not made any serious errors yet. The scary thing is that he was already looking for a way to win at this stage of the game. The mere fact that he was even attempting to do so was something new to me, and I think it is an important lesson to take on board.}) 15... bxc3 (15... Bxa6 16. Qxa6 {is pretty dangerous for Black. Gormally, Danny: 'and Kramnik felt this was good for White although, after'} Nb8 {Gormally, Danny} 17. Qa4+ Nbd7 {, the position is very unclear.}) 16. Bxc6+ Bxc6 17. Rxd8+ Kxd8 18. Qd3+ Kc8 {Gormally, Danny: 'Now Kramnik suggested that he couldn't see anything for White after'} ({Gormally, Danny: 'Kramnik saw a beautiful variation after'} 18... Bd6 $2 {is beautifully met by} 19. Ne5 $1 Bd5 20. Rxd6+ {Gormally, Danny: '!'} Qxd6 21. Nxf7+ {and wins. Gormally, Danny: '("Is that all you saw?" was a typically witty response from Lawrence Trent)'}) 19. Nd4 Bb7 (19... Be4 {(Gormally, Danny) also looks good for Black}) 20. Ra4 Kb8 {and White's compensation is insufficient. Gormally, Danny: 'and he couldn't see a way through here. However, what was astonishing was how deeply he had analysed.'}) ({Moreover} 13. e4 $2 {doesn't lead anywhere after Gormally, Danny: '?!'} dxe4 14. Bg5 Be7 $1 {and Black is on top. Gormally, Danny: 'and, as Howell pointed out,'} 15. Bxf6 {(Gormally, Danny) does not work because of} exf3 $1) 13... Nxd5 14. Bxd5 Be7 ({After} 14... Bd6 15. e4 {the B will be developed to g5.}) 15. e4 O-O 16. g3 {Gormally, Danny: '!' Gormally, Danny: '[diagram] Kramnik liked this move and it's an important chain in White's plan, to maintain pressure on the centre before Black can fully consolidate. "My bishop is very powerful on d5."'} Na5 {Gormally, Danny: '?' Gormally, Danny: 'Howell goes astray. Moving the knight away like this looks unnatural and indeed proves to be so. Of course, though, one can only imagine that there was an idea behind this as a player as strong as Howell will very rarely play with no plan in mind. I would speculate that here he felt that the bishop on d5 was so strong that it needed to be challenged as soon as possible. However, it turns out that the cure is worse than the disease. It's funny how when you face players of the calibre of Kramnik you can fear ghosts and not play your normal game. I'm sure that if Howell were playing me here he would have not hesistated to play'} (16... Rfe8 $1 {Gormally, Danny} 17. Bf4 Qb6 {with fairly unclear prospects. It is clear that the plan of a4 as played in the game would not be then so powerful. Black retains counterplay in the centre. For example, if White is impatient with} 18. e5 $2 {Then it is met immediately by} Rxd5 $1 (18... Nd4 $1 {is equally good}) 19. Rxd5 Nd4 {with advantage for Black.}) 17. Bf4 Qc8 ({Van Delft & Ris: 'Perhaps a better try would have been' Perhaps} 17... Qb6 {Van Delft & Ris: '!?' Van Delft & Ris: 'when White has to prove whether he has an edge at all.' , defending the knight and the b-pawn, is a little safer.}) 18. a4 $1 {[diag] Vlad was quite happy with his game here, once he had found this move, which undermines Black's queenside. Commentator Daniel King thought the queenside configuration had something in common with some positions in the Ruy Lopez where a similar strategy is appropriate.} ({Another idea is Gormally, Danny: 'Kramnik also considered the forcing move'} 18. Bd2 {but then Gormally, Danny: 'here:'} Nc4 $1 19. Bxc4 bxc4 20. Bc3 {Gormally, Danny: 'and he spent a lot of time on this position as White has a serious positional threat of playing Ne5-c4. The problem, though, is that, after'} (20. Qxc4 $6 Qg4 21. Ne5 Qh5 $1 {is quite unpleasant for White.}) 20... Qg4 {should be OK for Black. Gormally, Danny: '!' Gormally, Danny: 'Black has serious counterchances. Besides, once you see 18 a4!, all other variations are really not important.'}) 18... b4 ({Gormally, Danny: '"After' After} 18... Nc4 {Van Delft & Ris: '?' Van Delft & Ris: 'has lost its effect, since after'} 19. Bxc4 (19. axb5 {Gormally, Danny} axb5 {"first of all I can get} 20. Ra7 {and then I can play for the initiative."}) 19... bxc4 20. Qxc4 {Gormally, Danny: 'is also possible' , Vlad thought Black had some play but not enough for the pawn.} Qg4 21. Rxd8 Rxd8 22. Ne5 {Black is forced to exchange Qs with} Qe6 {after which White is a full pawn up.}) 19. Rac1 ({Gormally, Danny: '"First of all I wanted to play' Now Vlad didn't like Black's position.} 19. Ne5 {Gormally, Danny: 'here. I was calculating some line just for fun." After 19 Ne5 White's minor pieces completely dominate the middle of the board; another drawback of the earlier excursion Black made with 16...Na5?!. Kramnik now demonstrated the beautiful variation'} Bxd5 {Gormally, Danny: '!' Gormally, Danny: '"But of course you can do better, (to Howell) you can take, and now I was not sure if I should take with the pawn or with the rook. Maybe the rook. I finally thought."'} (19... Bf6 {Gormally, Danny} 20. Ng4 Bd4 21. Rxd4 cxd4 22. Rc1 Qa8 (22... Qd7 23. Rc7 {wins}) 23. Nh6+ $1 gxh6 (23... Kh8 24. Nxf7+ Rxf7 25. Bxf7 Bxe4 26. Be5) 24. Be5 {[diagram] "And I don't see how to defend after this." Neither, unsurprisingly, do I.}) 20. Rxd5 Nb3 (20... Rxd5 {Gormally, Danny} 21. exd5 Nb3 {It's significant that here the black knight takes two steps to reach d4, whereas if he had kept it on c6 it could go there at once.} 22. Rd1 Nd4 23. Qc4 {"and I want Be3"}) 21. Rad1 Nd4 22. Qc4 Qe6 23. Be3 {was one of the lines Vlad looked out but it is not so clear.}) 19... Bc6 $2 {Gormally, Danny: 'This meets with an immediate tactical refutation.'} ({Van Delft & Ris: 'A serious mistake, after which the damage is irreparable. Howell should have tried' This might have been a mistake, Vlad thought. He tried to make 19...Qb7 work but wasn't convinced. The computer suggestion} 19... Rfe8 {Van Delft & Ris: '!' Van Delft & Ris: 'preventing White from trading the dark-squared Bs.' doesn't look bad.}) 20. Bg5 $1 {Clever. White deflects the dark-squared bishop, thus removing a defender from the c5 pawn.} Bxg5 (20... Bxd5 {Gormally, Danny} 21. Bxe7 ({There was an amusing interlude in the post mortem, where both players showed they had considered the variation} 21. exd5 Bxg5 22. Nxg5 Qf5 23. Rxc5 Nb3 {[diagram] and now Howell shot Kramnik a questioning look, as if he had blundered. But even here he had seen one move further:} 24. Qc2 $1 {Although this variation isn't really necessary, as 21 Bxe7 is so clearly strong, it is another good example of how far Kramnik sees in even minor lines.}) 21... Bc4 22. Rxd8 (22. Qe3 Rxd1+ 23. Rxd1 Re8 24. Bxc5 {is also not bad}) 22... Qxd8 23. Qxc4 Qxe7 24. Qxc5 Qxe4 25. Ng5 {wins.}) 21. Rxc5 $1 {A cunning intermezzo move, exploiting the looseness of all Black's residual minor pieces. "Now it's basically over," said Vlad.} Bf6 ({Gormally, Danny: 'After' Hikaru tried to make} 21... Bb5 $5 {Van Delft & Ris: 'can easily be parried with' Gormally, Danny: 'Kramnik demonstrated the following variation, which remarkably enough, is also the first line of the computer:' work, but} 22. Qc2 {Van Delft & Ris: '!' Van Delft & Ris: 'and a loss of material is inevitable.' Gormally, Danny: '!' Gormally, Danny: 'is also strong as everything is hanging' is a good move and the threats to the black minor pieces remain.} (22. Nxg5 {Gormally, Danny} Qxc5 23. axb5 Qe7 24. Qh5 h6 25. Nxf7 Rxd5 26. Nxh6+ {followed by taking on d5 and a6, and there are too many pawns.})) 22. Rxa5 {By now Hikaru had lost faith in the position too. White is already one pawn up and on the brink of winning another. Black has no viable counterplay even though the a5 rook is slightly offside.} Bxd5 23. Raxd5 Rxd5 24. Rxd5 {Van Delft & Ris: '!'} (24. exd5 {might also have been played, though it's not easy for White to mobilize his passed pawn. Kramnik rightly evaluated that he can give up his b-pawn.}) 24... Qc1+ 25. Kg2 Bxb2 (25... Qxb2 26. Qxa6 {Van Delft & Ris: 'almost comes down to the same thing.'} Bc3 27. a5 {is similar to the game.}) 26. Qxa6 {Gormally, Danny: '[diagram] Now the game should be effectively over as the white queen and rook easily contain the black b-pawn while the white a-pawn is not so easily dealt with. However, there is one more important twist as we shall see.'} Qc2 27. Rd2 Qb3 ({Against} 27... b3 {Van Delft & Ris: 'can be met by' , White has} 28. Qe2 ({obviously not} 28. Rxc2 $2 bxc2 $19) 28... Rc8 {and now} 29. Ne1 {Van Delft & Ris: '!' Van Delft & Ris: 'and White wins.' resolves the position on c2.}) 28. a5 Bc3 29. Rd5 Qc2 30. Qb7 $1 b3 ({Van Delft & Ris: 'In case of'} 30... Qxe4 {allows White to win the pawn race with} 31. a6 {Van Delft & Ris: 'Black is unable to exploit the pins on the a8-h1 diagonal.' and there is no way of exploiting Black's pin on the long diagonal.}) 31. a6 b2 32. Rb5 Qa4 33. a7 h6 34. e5 ({An uneasy stand-off has been reached. Not} 34. Qb8 $2 {Van Delft & Ris: 'would have spoiled all the effort, due to' when Black can reply} Qxe4 {Van Delft & Ris: '!' and White's advantage has dissipated.}) 34... Kh7 (34... Qa1 35. Qe7 b1=Q 36. Rxb1 Qxb1 37. Qxf8+ Kxf8 38. a8=Q+ {Van Delft & Ris: 'should be technically winning for White.' should win.}) 35. Rb3 Qa2 36. h4 {Van Delft & Ris: '!' Van Delft & Ris: 'Diagram [#] Excellent technique. White isn't in a hurry and simply improves his position, boxing in the black K.' Commentator Lawrence Trent was justly proud of predicting this squeezing plan.} Kg8 37. h5 {Vlad called this 'making a box' for the black king. More of a coffin, actually.} Qa5 38. Qb8 Qa2 39. Rxc3 $1 b1=Q 40. Rc8 $1 {Gormally, Danny: 'Black resigned but they both missed at the time that 40...Qf1! followed by 41...Qa6 prolongs resistance. According to computers, which gives plus three pawns here, White should be winning in any case, but clearly there is plenty of work to be done. While it is clear that the idea of these press conferences are a great help to the watching audience, both at the venue and online itself, I can't help but think that the recent practice of having press conferences at the strongest tournaments in the world are a lost opportunity, at least for some of the players. Why? Because it is clear that they have replaced post mortems. As far as I'm aware these not particularly long press conferences are the only real interaction that the players get after the game, apart from some short discussions at the board. If I were David Howell, or any of the English guys taking on the big guns, I'd relish the chance to have a proper post mortem with someone like Kramnik. You can often learn far more from a post mortem with such a player than you can from the game itself, where everything is so much more hidden. The problem with that press conference was that, while it was hugely impressive to see Kramnik being so open with what he saw during the game (in refreshing contrast to say, Carlsen, who tends to be much more reticent during interviews, often just mumbling answers almost), you also got the impression that David could barely get a word in edgeways. That's what these top players tend to do if you're not careful; they will try to dominate you on and off the board, so that in a sense you are subverted to their will. The top players will look to dominate. That is part of the reason why they are so successful. So I don't think that these press conferences are really helping the young English players as much as a post mortem would, although I understand that it's only a minor gripe.' [diag]} (40. Rc8 {Van Delft & Ris: '!' Van Delft & Ris: 'and Black resigned, in view of'} Rxc8 (40... Qf1+ $1 {is clever but after} 41. Kxf1 Qa6+ 42. Kg2 Rxc8 43. Nd4 {Van Delft & Ris: '+-' seems to win anyway.}) 41. Qxc8+ Kh7 42. a8=Q {Van Delft & Ris: 'and White is just a piece up.' and White's pair of queens proves more potent than Black's.}) 1-0


