1. Nf3 {Marin,M Marin,M} Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. b3 Bg7 4. Bb2 O-O 5. c4 d6 6. Bg2 e5 7. d3 {Marin,M: 'After my 8th round win against Berg, I could not resist the temptation to repeat the opening. The game was played in the morning so I assumed my opponent would not have the time to check all my openings and even less such a "sideline". My thoughts proved true since David played the opening phase very slowly.' After my 8th round win against Berg, I could not resist the temptation to repeat the opening. The game was played in the morning so I assumed my opponent would not have the time to check all my openings and even less such a "sideline". My thoughts proved true since David played the opening phase very slowly.} Re8 ({Marin,M: 'The aforementioned game went' The aforementioned game went} 7... Nc6 {Marin,M (2580)-Berg,E (2573) Reykjavik 2015 CBM 170 [Marin] (1-0, 60) Marin,M: 'Marin,M (2580)-Berg,E (2573) Reykjavik 2015 CBM 170 [Marin] (1-0, 60)'}) 8. O-O a5 9. a3 c6 10. Nbd2 Nbd7 {Marin,M: 'Black prepares ...d6-d5 at the cost of slightly delaying the queenside development.' Black prepares ...d6-d5 at the cost of slightly delaying the queenside development.} ({Marin,M: 'Another possible approach examined in my article is' Another possible approach examined in my article is} 10... Na6 11. Qc2 Bd7 12. Bc3 b5 {Taimanov,M (2510)-Ruderfer,M (2400) Moscow 1979 MCD [Marin] (½-½, 45) Marin,M: 'Taimanov,M (2510)-Ruderfer,M (2400) Moscow 1979 MCD [Marin] (½-½, 45)'}) 11. b4 $5 ({Marin,M: 'I remembered quite clearly that in my article I had focused on' I remembered quite clearly that in my article I had focused on} 11. Qc2 {Marin,M: '. preparing to occupy the c-file if Black displays ambitions in the centre, as in Horvath,J (2551)-Popovic,P (2532) Austria 2001 EXT 2002  [Marin] (1-0, 41). But over the board I was carried away by another thought: what if, after my entertaining Breyer game Svetushkin,D (2586)-Marin,M (2580) Reykjavik 2015 CBM 170 [Marin 170] (1/2-1/2, 41) I would use the same setup with reversed colours?!' . preparing to occupy the c-file if Black displays ambitions in the centre, as in Horvath,J (2551)-Popovic,P (2532) Austria 2001 EXT 2002 [Marin] (1-0, 41). But over the board I was carried away by another thought: what if, after my entertaining Breyer game Svetushkin,D (2586)-Marin,M (2580) Reykjavik 2015 CBM 170 [Marin 170] (½-½, 41) I would use the same setup with reversed colours?!}) 11... d5 12. e4 {Marin,M: 'The similarity of my position with the game against Svetushkin was so obvious that the Romanian captains later confessed me they had been making jokes during the game about me playing the Breyer with either colour!' The similarity of my position with the game against Svetushkin was so obvious that the Romanian captains later confessed me they had been making jokes during the game about me playing the Breyer with either colour!} dxe4 {Marin,M: 'David played this after a long period of thought.' David played this after a long period of thought.} ({Marin,M: 'The most ambitious move is' The most ambitious move is} 12... d4 {Marin,M: 'with a genuine reversed Breyer structure. The main difference is that the bishop is on g7 instead of c7.' with a genuine reversed Breyer structure. The main difference is that the bishop is on g7 instead of c7.} 13. c5 b6 {Marin,M: 'The critical move.' The critical move.} ({Marin,M: 'The Ruy Lopez approach' The Ruy Lopez approach} 13... Nf8 $2 {Marin,M: 'is pointless because the knight does not have the g6-square at its disposal and after' is pointless because the knight does not have the g6-square at its disposal and after} 14. Nc4 {Marin,M: 'the b6-square is vulnerable.' the b6-square is vulnerable.}) 14. cxb6 ({Marin,M: 'During the game I considered' During the game I considered} 14. Nc4 {Marin,M: 'as a candidate but after' as a candidate but after} Ba6 15. Nd6 Re7 {Marin,M: 'the knight risks being trapped.' the knight risks being trapped.}) 14... axb4 $6 ({Marin,M: 'The exchanges initiated with this move played in both previous games reaching this position help White activate his pieces on the queenside. A better move is' The exchanges initiated with this move played in both previous games reaching this position help White activate his pieces on the queenside. A better move is} 14... Nxb6 15. Qc2 Bf8 $13) 15. axb4 Rxa1 16. Qxa1 Qxb6 (16... Nxb6 17. Rc1 $14) 17. Nc4 Qxb4 {Marin,M: 'I had reached this point in my calculation and evaluated that White has overwhelming compensation for the pawn, without knowing that this had been played before.' I had reached this point in my calculation and evaluated that White has overwhelming compensation for the pawn, without knowing that this had been played before.} 18. Ba3 ({Marin,M: 'My other candidate was' My other candidate was} 18. Rb1) 18... Qa4 (18... Qb3 19. Nfd2 Qxd3 20. Rc1 Qe2 21. Qb1 $1 {[%csl Gd3][%cal Gg2f3]} Qg4 (21... Ng4 22. Rf1 Ba6 23. Bf3 Bxc4 24. Bxe2 Bxe2 25. Re1) 22. Nd6 $16 {[%cal Gc1c6]}) 19. Bd6 Qxa1 20. Rxa1 {Marin,M: 'I stopped my calculating in this position, with the same pleasant evaluation.' I stopped my calculating in this position, with the same pleasant evaluation.} Bf8 21. Ra8 (21. Bxf8 Kxf8 22. Ra7) 21... c5 22. Ra7 Re6 {Dobrovolsky,L (2390)-Konopka,M (2425) Ceske Budejovice 1993 (1-0, 29) Marin,M: 'Dobrovolsky,L (2390) -Konopka,M (2425) Ceske Budejovice 1993 (1-0, 29)'} 23. Bxf8 Nxf8 24. Rc7 (24. Nfxe5 Ra6 $5 $14) 24... Bd7 25. Nfxe5 Ra6 26. Bf1 Ra1 27. Kg2 $16) 13. dxe4 {[%cal Gc4c5,Gd2c4]} c5 {Marin,M: 'This was David's idea. After blocking the queenside, both sides will have to prepare an invasion of the central d4/d5 squares.' This was David's idea. After blocking the queenside, both sides will have to prepare an invasion of the central d4/d5 squares.} 14. b5 $146 {Marin,M: 'An involuntary novelty, as I had been on my own ever since 11.b4. The position is almost symmetrical but White's queenside space advantage and slightly better development make his position more pleasant.' An involuntary novelty, as I had been on my own ever since 11.b4. The position is almost symmetrical but White's queenside space advantage and slightly better development make his position more pleasant.} (14. Bc3 $6 axb4 15. axb4 Rxa1 16. Qxa1 cxb4 17. Bxb4 {[%csl Gc5]} Qc7 18. Qc1 b6 19. Ne1 Nc5 $17 {Gryncharov,G-Donchev,D (2440) Elenite 1987 (0-1, 41)}) 14... Qc7 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd7f8,Gf8e6]} 15. Ne1 {Marin,M: 'I played this without hesitation as I wanted to bring my knight as soon as possible to d5 and clear the path for my f-pawn along the way. But there were several other possibilities, some of them based on manoeuvring with the other knight, which actually needs fewer tempi to reach d5.' I played this without hesitation as I wanted to bring my knight as soon as possible to d5 and clear the path for my f-pawn along the way. But there were several other possibilities, some of them based on manoeuvring with the other knight, which actually needs fewer tempi to reach d5.} ({Marin,M: 'At a later stage of the game I regretted that I did not leave the knight on f3 for a bit longer, so as to force Black into over-protecting e5. And since I played a3-a4 and Ra3 anyway, I thought it might have been wiser to start with these moves.' At a later stage of the game I regretted that I did not leave the knight on f3 for a bit longer, so as to force Black into over-protecting e5. And since I played a3-a4 and a3 anyway, I thought it might have been wiser to start with these moves.} 15. a4 Nf8 16. Ra3 N6d7 17. Ne1 Ne6 18. Nc2 Nd4 19. Ne3 Nb6 20. Nd5) (15. Qc2 Nf8 16. Rad1 N6d7 17. Nb1 Ne6 18. Nc3 Nd4 19. Nd5 Qd8 20. Nxd4 exd4 21. Bc1 Nb6 22. a4 Nxd5 23. cxd5 b6 24. f4 f6 $11 {Marin,M: 'This is similar to the final stage of game.' This is similar to the final stage of game.}) (15. Re1 $5 {Marin,M: 'I find this to be the main candidate for my plan.' I find this to be the main candidate for my plan.} Nf8 16. a4 Bg4 (16... N6d7 17. Nf1 Ne6 18. Ne3 Nd4 19. Nd5 Qd8 20. Ba3 $14) 17. h3 Bxf3 18. Qxf3 Ne6 19. Nf1 Rad8 20. Qc3 Nd4 21. Ne3 b6 22. h4 {[%cal Gg2h3] Marin,M: 'The engines give this as completely equal but I believe that the bishop pair offers White some sort of long term (even though symbolic) advantage.' The engines give this as completely equal but I believe that the bishop pair offers White some sort of long term (even though symbolic) advantage.}) 15... Nf8 16. Nc2 Ne6 ({Marin,M: 'During the game I assumed that after' During the game I assumed that after} 16... Bh6 17. Ne3 Bxe3 18. fxe3 {Marin,M: 'I would inevitably get the upper hand by transferring the other knight to d5, while Black would be deprived of the same plan. This is correct, but I failed to notice that this actually implied a promising pawn sacrifice:' I would inevitably get the upper hand by transferring the other knight to d5, while Black would be deprived of the same plan. This is correct, but I failed to notice that this actually implied a promising pawn sacrifice:} Bg4 (18... N6d7 19. Nb1 Nb6 20. Nc3 Nxc4 21. Nd5 Qd8 22. Qc2 Nxb2 23. Qxb2 $36) 19. Qc2 N6d7 20. Nb1 Be6 21. Nc3 Bxc4 22. Nd5 Bxd5 23. exd5 Qd6 24. e4 Nb6 25. a4 Nfd7 26. Bh3 {Marin,M: 'Despite his extra pawn Black is quite passive, but it remains an open question whether White can really break his position.' Despite his extra pawn Black is quite passive, but it remains an open question whether White can really break his position.}) 17. Ne3 Nd4 18. a4 Qd8 19. Ra3 {Marin,M: 'I thought this would be the best way to activate the rook, hoping to transfer it to the kingside along the third rank. But in the game this did not happen...' I thought this would be the best way to activate the rook, hoping to transfer it to the kingside along the third rank. But in the game this did not happen...} h5 20. Nd5 Bh6 21. Nb3 {Marin,M: 'I later found out that at this moment my team mates shared my confidence that White has the initiative.' I later found out that at this moment my team mates shared my confidence that White has the initiative.} Nxd5 $1 {Marin,M: 'The most accurate answer, forcing me to display my intentions in the centre.' The most accurate answer, forcing me to display my intentions in the centre.} (21... b6 22. Nxd4 cxd4 (22... exd4 23. Nxf6+ Qxf6 24. e5) 23. f4 Nxd5 24. cxd5 f6 25. f5 $36) (21... Qd6 22. Nxf6+ Qxf6 23. Nxc5 Bf8 24. Bxd4 exd4 25. Rf3 Qg5 26. Nd3 Bg4 27. e5 $44 {[%csl Gd3] / Marin,M: '/'}) (21... Nxb3 22. Qxb3 Nxd5 23. cxd5 $14 {[%cal Gb3c4,Gf2f4,Ga3f3]}) 22. cxd5 (22. exd5 Bg4 23. f3 Bf5 $15) 22... b6 23. Nxd4 $6 ({Marin,M: 'I rightly discarded' I rightly discarded} 23. Nd2 {Marin,M: 'because of' because of} f5 24. f4 (24. Nc4 f4 25. Bc1 Ra7 26. gxf4 Bxf4 27. Bxf4 exf4 28. Kh1 g5 $13) (24. exf5 Bxf5 $132) 24... fxe4 (24... exf4 25. Bxd4 cxd4 26. e5 Rxe5 27. Nc4 $36 Rxd5 $2 28. Nxb6 $18) 25. Nxe4 Bg4 26. Qd2 Ra7 $13 {[%cal Ga7f7]}) (23. Bxd4 cxd4 24. f4 Bg4 25. Qd3 Rc8 $15) (23. Qd3 $1 h4 24. f4 $14) 23... exd4 (23... cxd4 $2 24. f4) 24. f4 f6 $1 {Marin,M: 'I completely underestimated this move, which slows down my central pawns.' I completely underestimated this move, which slows down my central pawns.} 25. Re1 ({Marin,M: 'I did not find anything encouraging after the thematic' I did not find anything encouraging after the thematic} 25. f5 gxf5 ({Marin,M: 'David also suggested' David also suggested} 25... Ra7 26. fxg6 Re5) 26. Qxh5 Bg7 27. Qg6 Ra7 {[%csl Gb2]}) 25... Qd6 26. Qc2 Ra7 27. Raa1 {Marin,M: 'By now I had resigned myself to the idea of a draw, even though my opponent's severe time trouble gave me some hope.' By now I had resigned myself to the idea of a draw, even though my opponent's severe time trouble gave me some hope.} Rae7 28. Bc1 Bf5 {Marin,M: 'In principle this is a blunder, but... a lucky one as Black has one saving trick in the critical line below.' In principle this is a blunder, but... a lucky one as Black has one saving trick in the critical line below.} 29. Bd2 Bd7 ({Marin,M: 'David had initially planned' David had initially planned} 29... Qxd5 {Marin,M: 'overlooking' overlooking} 30. exf5) 30. h4 ({Marin,M: 'It really hurt that' It really hurt that} 30. e5 {Marin,M: 'does not win:' does not win:} fxe5 31. fxe5 Rxe5 ({Marin,M: 'After his carelessness, David also considered' After his carelessness, David also considered} 31... d3 {Marin,M: 'but this seems insufficient:' but this seems insufficient:} 32. Qxd3 Rxe5 33. Rxe5 Qxe5 34. Qxg6+ $16) 32. Rxe5 Rxe5 33. Bxh6 g5 $1 $15 {[%csl Gc5,Gd4] Marin,M: 'Quite a nasty move, trapping the extra bishop. My last move actually renews the threat but such a strong opponent could not blunder for the second time in a row in the same way.' Quite a nasty move, trapping the extra bishop. My last move actually renews the threat but such a strong opponent could not blunder for the second time in a row in the same way.}) 30... Kh7 31. Qd3 Bg4 32. Rf1 Qd7 33. Kh2 Qc7 34. Rf2 Qd7 35. Raf1 Qd6 36. Bc1 Rg8 37. Bd2 Rge8 38. Re1 Qc7 39. Ref1 Qd6 {Marin,M: 'And one move before the official limit we agreed to a draw by repetition.' And one move before the official limit we agreed to a draw by repetition.} 1/2-1/2


