{This is a good example of how NOT to play the classical main line as White.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 5. d3 a6 6. O-O Ba7 7. Re1 d6 8. Bb3 O-O 9. h3 Ne7 10. Nh4 $6 {This aggressive move is seldom seen, and David Howell's play in this game gives us a good indication why that is the case.} ({In the book I focussed on the much more typical} 10. Nbd2 Ng6 11. Nf1 {- (see, for example, Felgaer-Hector).}) 10... Ng6 11. Bg5 {This is the point to White's previous move. The bishop cannot be pushed away by 11...h6? as this loses the exchange. However, it's all a bit crude and Black's reply is more than good enough.} ({If} 11. Nxg6 hxg6 12. Bg5 {Black can break the pin without fear of weakening his kingside:} Qe8 $5 13. Nd2 Be6 14. Nc4 Nh7 15. Be3 {with an equal position, P.Jaracz-A.Delchev, Arnhem 1990. Still, given the game continuation, that might be White's best line.}) 11... Kh8 $1 {An excellent reply. The key point is that Black will be happy to recapture on g6 with the f-pawn, with the activity he gains on the open f-file at the very least compensating for the weakening of his pawn structure. With this in mind there is now nothing White can reasonably do to prevent ...h6 coming.} (11... Nxh4 12. Bxh4 {justifies White's play, as now Black has the typical problem of not being able to break the pin unless he accepts a structural concession on the kingside.} h6 13. Nd2 Qe7 14. Nf1 Be6 15. Ne3 Rab8 {was N.Bojkovic-J.Belic, Cetinje 1990, and here} 16. Nf5 Bxf5 17. exf5 {intending d4 looks favourable for White.}) (11... h6 $2 12. Nxg6 {wins material.}) 12. Nf5 {Continuing ambitiously.} (12. Nxg6+ {is met by} fxg6 $1) (12. Nd2 h6 $1 13. Nxg6+ fxg6 14. Bh4 $2 (14. Be3 {must be played, and it's equal}) 14... g5 $1 15. Bg3 g4 $1 {is a frightening example of how Black's attack can gain momentum if the f-file opens. If} 16. h4 $2 {then} Nh5 $1 {is murderous.}) 12... h6 13. Be3 c5 $5 {This paradoxical self-blocking of the a7-bishop is actually a really clever idea. The block is only temporary, and Howell's move highlights the superficial nature of White's play. The bishop on e3 only gets in the way of White's central plans, while the seemingly active knight on f5 is in fact insecure, especially since ...d5 is coming. Even so, it actually takes a very neat tactical point to fully justify Black's decision.} ({There was nothing wrong with} 13... Bxf5 14. exf5 Nh4) 14. Qf3 (14. Ng3 d5 15. exd5 Nxd5 16. Bxd5 Qxd5 17. c4 Qc6 {is better for Black, with ...Rd8 and ...f5 two possibilities.}) ({Perhaps White should try} 14. c4 $5 {to prevent ...d5 - a nice echo of Black's 13th move!}) 14... d5 $1 15. exd5 $4 {Clearly missing Black's intended 17th move, and Erdogdu can be forgiven for doing so as it's not the sort of move which is immediately obvious at this point. See if you can find Howell's idea:} ({If} 15. g4 {then} c4 $1 {and White's centre crumbles after} 16. Bxa7 Rxa7 17. dxc4 dxe4) ({White has to go backwards with} 15. Ng3) ({or try} 15. Bxd5 $5 {although the complications here after} Bxf5 $5 16. Bxb7 (16. Qxf5 $4 Nh4 {is similar to the game}) 16... Nh4 17. Qg3 Nh5 18. Qxe5 Rb8 19. exf5 Rxb7 20. Qe4 Rxb2 {look to be in Black's favour.}) 15... Bxf5 16. Qxf5 {Obviously White was expecting 16...Nxd5, but...} Nh4 $1 {...and White resigned!} ({After} 16... Nh4 $1 17. Qxe5 Bb8 $1 {the bishop comes back into play with a vengeance, trapping the queen in mid-board. A nice miniature from Howell, an a good reason to avoid 10 Nh4 for White.}) 0-1


[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Sample Games on Master Level "]
[Black "Howell, David vs. Aronian"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B06"]
[PlyCount "110"]

1. e4 g6 {We have mentioned this game in the Mad Dog chapter (Nf3-Bc4 setups - chapter 10) . Let's take a look at it as a whole. Note that one of the best players of the last decade, Levon Aronian, is the one playing the Black pieces.} 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nf3 d6 4. Bc4 Nf6 5. Qe2 O-O 6. e5 dxe5 7. dxe5 Nd5 8. h3 Be6 {A move that changed the theory of this variation, which was recommended in the theoretical part of the course.} 9. O-O Nd7 {9...c6 !?} 10. Bd2 a5 {I think the advance of the c-pawn is more prudent, but Aronian plays more creatively, gaining some space on the queenside, which is probably also not that bad.} 11. Nc3 N7b6 {11...c6 !?} 12. Bxd5 Nxd5 13. Ne4 Nb4 {The point of a5 is revealed. Black doesn't have any direct problems here. He might only be slightly passive, but what can you do..} 14. Bxb4 {Now sure how much I like this decision  14.Rad1 Qc8 15.a3 Nc6 16.Bf4 Seems more logical, when White retains a slight edge} axb4 15. Rfd1 Qc8 16. Qb5 c6 17. Qxb4 Bd5 {White did win the pawn, but Black has enormous compensation in form of the two bishops and the fact e5 is a permanent target} 18. Ned2 Qc7 19. c4 c5 20. Qb5 Be6 21. Ne4 Ra5 22. Qb3 b5 {Very strong play by Aronian !} 23. Qe3 bxc4 {Black has regained the pawn and opened a file on the queenside. The pawn on e5 still restricts the dark-squared bishop and the position is probably balanced. Even so, there is a lot to play for.} 24. Nc3 h6 25. Rd2 Qb8 {25...Rb8 !?} 26. Rad1 Rc8 27. Qe4 Ra7 28. a3 Bf8 29. Nd5 Qb3 30. Nc3 Bf5 {This is probably overzealous as the bishop might come in the way of White's kingside pawns.} 31. Qe3 Raa8 {Mistakes come in pairs..  31...e6 Preventing f5 from afar, was apparently better 32.g4 Bd3} 32. Ne1 {Not yet spoiling things ,but missing a chance.  32.g4 ! Was very energetic. Be6  32...Bd3 33.e6 33.Nh4 Is pointed out by the engine, intending f4-f5. Black has to play g5 34.Nf5 And accept he is worse} h5 {Now Black manages to prevent g4... for the moment} 33. Kh2 {But this is too timid and lets Black back in the game.  33.Qg5 Renewing the threat was stronger, Black probably has to go Bg7 34.g4 f6 35.exf6 exf6 36.Qf4 hxg4 37.hxg4 Be6 When his position is highly suspicious, although the game is not yet over.} Bg7 {Now the worst is over for Aronian and the game continues.} 34. f3 Qb7 35. f4 Bh6 36. Kg1 Ra6 37. Nd5 Be6 38. Qf2 Kg7 39. Nc3 Rb6 40. Kh2 Rb3 {40...Rb8 !?} 41. Re2 Qb6 42. Kg1 Qa5 43. Qf3 Rd8 44. Rxd8 Qxd8 45. Rf2 h4 46. Kh2 {46.Qe3 !?} Qd7 {46...Bf5 !? 47.Kg1 Qd4 48.Kh2 Rxb2 49.Rxb2 Bxf4+} 47. Kh1 Rb8 {I have been left without words for quite some time simply because the players have been shuffling around and I didn't quite understand what has been going on.} 48. Ne4 {But this is a fatal mistake, allowing Black to finally exchange his bad light squared bishop and gain the upper hand.  48.Qe3 Would have continued the dance. Qd4 49.Nc2} Bd5 49. Qe3 Bxe4 50. Qxe4 Qd4 {Now it is all over suddenly. The pawn on f4 falls or White has to take on d4, allowing a monstrous pawn duo.} 51. Qc2 {Howell decides for the first option, but loses all the same.  51.Qxd4 Was no better cxd4 52.Kg1 d3 53.Kf1 Rd8 And Black will win} Bxf4 52. Re2 Bg3 53. Nf3 Qd3 54. Kg1 Rd8 55. Rd2 Qxc2 {A very strange, ragged and difficult game. But from the purely opening perspective, Black didn't have anything to complain about and there is no reason not to follow in Aronian's footsteps.} *


