ai IND 2010/The Week in Chess 796 (48)}) 14... exd5 {Stohl,Igor: 'After'} 15. exd5 {Stohl,Igor: 'play transposes into the 13...c6 line above.'} c4 16. Bxc4 Be6 17. Rd1 Ne7 18. dxe6 $1 {Stohl,Igor: '!' Stohl,Igor: '- see Pashikian-Cornette'} Rxd2 19. Rxd2 Qxc3 (19... Nf5 $5) 20. Bb3 Qc1+ 21. Rd1 Qc3+ 22. Ke2 $5 a5 23. Rd7 a4 24. Rc1 $44 {1/2 Potkin,V (2646)-Svidler,P (2722)/Moscow RUS 2010/The Week in Chess 841 (42)}) (13... Qa4 {Stohl,Igor} 14. c4 {is less effective, as now White is a tempo up on Sargissian-Svidler above:} Na6 15. Be2 exd5 16. exd5 b6 17. Bd1 Qa3 18. Rc3 Qa5 19. O-O Nb4 20. a3 Nc6 21. Qc1 Ne7 22. Re1 Nf5 23. Bd2 $14 {Kosic,D (2483)-Gupta,A (2627)/Kavala/2011/}) 14. exd5 Na6 $6 {Stohl,Igor: 'N' Not the best way to develop the knight. Stohl,Igor: 'Only this is a real novelty.'} (14... Nc6 15. Bd3 {- see above} ({With the  already exchanged on d5 White has the extra option} 15. Bc4 {Stohl,Igor , but this is well met with} b5 $5 (15... Be6 {} 16. Qb2 Bf7 $5 17. Qxb7 Qb6 $1 $132) 16. Be2 Ne7 (16... c4 {also deserves attention.}) 17. d6 Be6 18. Bxc5 Nf5 $44 {[%cal Rg7h6,Ya8c8] h6,ac8})) 15. Be2 {Stohl,Igor: 'Time has come to finish development.'} (15. h4 {Stohl,Igor} Bg4 $132 {is double-edged} (15... Be6 $5 16. c4 Nb4 17. a3 Qxa3 18. Bxc5 a5 $13 {with  in the spirit of Sargissian-Svidler above.})) 15... Be6 $6 {Stohl,Igor: 'Howell wants to stabilise the position, the text move seems to be the best:'} ({Stohl,Igor: 'The analogous position to Pashikian-Cornette'} 15... c4 16. Bxc4 Be6 17. Rd1 (17. Bxa6 {Stohl,Igor} Qxa6 18. c4 Rac8 $132) (17. Nd4 {Stohl,Igor} Bf7 18. Nb3 Qa4 19. Bxa6 Qxa6 20. c4 b5 $11) (17. Rb1 $5 {Stohl,Igor} Bxd5 18. Rb5 Qxb5 19. Bxb5 Bxf3 20. Bc4+ $14) 17... Nc7 (17... Bf7 {Stohl,Igor} 18. Bb3 f5 19. O-O $36 {[%cal Rf3g5] g5}) 18. dxe6 Rxd2 19. Rxd2 {- this version of the queen sacrifice is more favourable for White than it was in Potkin-Svidler. Stohl,Igor: 'leads to a position, in which the e6 threatens to advance immediate