1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. h3 e5 7. Nde2 h5 8. Bg5 Be7 9. Ng3 {The knight is heading towards the f5-square with the hope of shaking the solid black defence.} (9. g3 Be6 (9... b5 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. Nd5 h4 12. a4 bxa4 13. Rxa4 Nd7 14. Nec3 Bg5 15. b4 O-O 16. gxh4 Bxh4 17. Qh5 g6 18. Rg1 Kg7 19. Nd1 Rh8 20. Qf3 Nb6 $15 {½-½ Movsesian,S (2721)-Khismatullin,D (2649)/Moscow 2011}) 10. Bg2 Nbd7 11. O-O (11. a4 Rc8 12. O-O O-O 13. Qd2 Re8 14. Rfd1 $13) 11... Rc8 12. a4 O-O {This type of position is respected by the computers as fairly logical in the 7...h5 line. The machines have tested this very position more than 700 times; Black was not able to hold the normal score of 45%. Objectively the situation is about equal, but White has more chances to play for an advantage.} 13. b3 Nc5 14. Be3 b5 15. axb5 axb5 16. b4 Na4 17. Nxb5 Nb2 (17... Qd7 18. Rxa4 Qxb5 19. c3 Ra8 $11) 18. Qc1 Nc4 19. Na7 Rc7 20. b5 $14 {1-0 Antipov,M (2412)-Korobov,A (2671)/St Petersburg 2011 (80)}) (9. Qd2 Nbd7 (9... Be6 10. g3 (10. O-O-O Nbd7 11. f4 Qa5 12. a3 b5 13. f5 Bc4 14. Kb1 Rb8 15. Bxf6 Nxf6 16. Nd5 Qxd2 17. Nxf6+ Bxf6 18. Rxd2 d5 19. exd5 e4 20. Ng3 e3 21. Rd1 Kd7 22. Ne4 e2 23. Bxe2 Bxe2 24. Rd2 Bc4 25. Nxf6+ gxf6 26. b3 Rhe8 27. Ka2 Rbc8 28. bxc4 Rxc4 $11) 10... Nbd7 11. Bg2 O-O 12. O-O b5 13. Rfd1 Nb6 $11) 10. O-O-O (10. Ng3 g6 11. h4 b5 12. a4 b4 13. Nd5 Nxd5 14. Qxd5 Ra7 15. Bc4 O-O 16. Bh6 Nb6 17. Qd3 Nxc4 18. Bxf8 Kxf8 19. Qxc4 Rc7 20. Qxb4 Rxc2 $13) 10... b5 11. a3 Bb7 12. Ng3 g6 13. h4 Rc8 14. f3 Qc7 15. Be2 Nc5 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17. Qxd6 Qxd6 18. Rxd6 Be7 19. Rdd1 Ne6 20. Nd5 $11 {0-1 Sutovsky,E (2675)-Gelfand,B (2755)/Netanya 2009 (47)}) 9... h4 (9... g6 $5 {It is important to note, that the 9.g3 idea will not serve as a refutation of the black defensive set up. In the event that the 9...h4 should run into trouble Black can always return to the solid positional move 9...g6!? with fair chances for full equality.} 10. Bc4 (10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. Bc4 O-O 12. O-O b5 13. Bb3 Ra7 14. Nge2 Nc6 15. a4 b4 16. Nd5 Bg7 17. c3 bxc3 18. Nexc3 Rb7 19. Bc4 Rxb2 20. Qd3 Qg5 21. Rab1 $11 {½-½ Rabatin,J (2123)-Ivanov,M (2486)/Havirov 2010 (25)}) 10... Be6 (10... Nbd7 11. a4 h4 12. Nge2 Nc5 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. b4 Ne6 15. Nd5 Nf4 16. Nexf4 exf4 17. Nxf6+ Qxf6 18. Ra3 Be6 19. Bxe6 Qxe6 20. O-O Rc8 $11 {½-½ Rios,C (2388)-Ortiz Suarez,I (2553)/Silvania 2011 (49)}) 11. Bxf6 (11. Bb3 Nbd7 12. Qf3 (12. O-O Rc8 13. Qf3 Nc5 14. Rad1 Nxb3 15. axb3 h4 16. Nge2 Nh5 17. Bxe7 Qxe7 18. Qd3 Rc6 19. f4 exf4 20. Qd4 O-O 21. Nxf4 Nxf4 22. Rxf4 $11 {1-0 Vallejo Pons,F (2554)-Rytshagov,M (2529)/Istanbul 2000 (49)}) 12... Rc8 13. Nf1 Nb6 14. Ne3 Nh7 15. Bxe7 Qxe7 16. Ncd5 Nxd5 17. Bxd5 Nf6 18. Bb3 Kf8 19. O-O Kg7 20. Rfd1 Rhd8 21. Rd2 $11 {½-½ Kryvoruchko,Y (2679)-Ftacnik,L (2544)/Czechia 2012 (43)}) 11... Bxf6 12. Nd5 Bg5 13. c3 Nd7 14. Bb3 O-O 15. O-O Bh6 16. Re1 Nc5 17. Bc2 h4 18. Nf1 Bxd5 19. Qxd5 Qe7 20. Ne3 Bxe3 21. fxe3 $11 {½-½ Naroditsky,D (2483)-Andriasian,Z (2605)/Groningen 2012 (25)}) 10. Nf5 Bxf5 11. exf5 {At the first glance White is able to report considerable success. The exchange of Black's light-squared bishop offers promise for the domination, but the situation is more complex. Black has the initiative due to the natural idea c6-d4, attacking the vulnerable f5-pawn.} (11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. exf5) 11... Nc6 12. Bc4 (12. Qd2 Qa5 13. O-O-O O-O-O 14. Bxf6 Bxf6 15. Bc4 Rd7 16. Nd5 Qxd2+ 17. Kxd2 Bd8 $11) (12. Bxf6 Bxf6 13. Bc4 (13. Nd5 Ne7 14. Nxe7 Qxe7 15. Bc4 e4 16. O-O $11) 13... Rc8 14. O-O Nd4 (14... Qd7 15. Qg4 Nd4 16. Bd5 Nxf5 17. Ne4 Be7 $11 18. c3 g6 19. Rad1 $44) 15. Bd5 Qb6 (15... Qd7 16. Qg4 Nxf5 17. Ne4 Be7 $11) 16. Be4 Qxb2 17. Nd5 Qa3 18. Re1 Qc5 19. Rb1 b5 20. a4 bxa4 21. Rb7 $14 {1-0 Tarlev,K (2497)-Gabrielian,A (2541)/Kislovodsk 2010 (29)}) 12... Nd4 13. Bxf6 (13. O-O Nxf5 14. Bxf6 Bxf6 15. Qd5 Qe7 16. Rad1 g6 17. Qf3 Qd7 18. Rfe1 Rd8 19. Ne4 Be7 20. Bd5 $44) 13... Bxf6 14. Bd5 {White is voluntarily playing for compensation for the f5-pawn in control of the central light squares.} (14. O-O Qc8 15. Bd3 Nxf5 16. Bxf5 Qxf5 17. Qxd6 Rd8 18. Qb4 b5 19. Rad1 Rxd1 20. Rxd1 Be7 21. Qa5 O-O 22. Qxa6 Bc5 $11) 14... Nxf5 (14... Qd7 15. Be4 Nxf5 16. Bxf5 Qxf5 17. Qxd6 Rd8 18. Qb4 b5 19. O-O Be7 20. Qb3 O-O 21. a4 bxa4 22. Rxa4 Rb8 $11 {1-0 Fernandez Romero,E (2472)-Ortiz Suarez,I (2562)/Pamplona 2012 (52)}) 15. Ne4 (15. Bxb7 Rb8 16. Bc6+ Kf8 17. Be4 Nd4 18. Rb1 g6 $11) 15... Qc7 (15... O-O 16. c3 g6 17. O-O $44) 16. c3 Be7 17. Qf3 g6 18. O-O-O Kf8 $2 {Even the experienced grandmaster does not sense the danger! It was much better to choose the relative security of immediate castling.} (18... O-O 19. Kb1 Ng7 $11) 19. g4 $1 Nh6 (19... hxg3 20. fxg3 Rh7 21. Kb1 $16) 20. Qe3 Kg7 21. Rhg1 Raf8 22. f4 exf4 (22... f5 23. gxf5 Nxf5 24. Qf2 Rh6 25. Rg4 $16) 23. Qd4+ Kh7 24. Nf6+ Bxf6 25. Qxf6 $16 Re8 26. g5 Qe7 27. Qxe7 Rxe7 28. gxh6 Kxh6 29. Rde1 Rhe8 30. Kd2 f5 31. Bxb7 Re3 32. b4 g5 33. Bf3 Rxf3 34. Rxe8 Rxh3 35. Rh8+ Kg7 36. Rh5 Rg3 37. Rxg5+ Kf6 38. Rg8 Ke5 39. Re8+ Kd5 40. Rf1 h3 1-0


