1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 $5 {According to his post-game interview, David Howell wanted to take the game away from theoretically double-edged positions in which his opponent excels.} exd5 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bd3 {Once again, taking the game to simpler positions where the more experienced player will gain the upper hand.} (5. c4 {is more popular and ambitious leading to IQP middlegames.}) 5... Bd6 6. Qe2+ {This check variation has been gaining in popularity lately and has put Black under long-term pressure in the ending. Here's a few sample high-level games:} Be7 (6... Qe7 7. Qxe7+ Bxe7 8. O-O O-O 9. Re1 Re8 10. Bf4 c6 11. Nbd2 Nbd7 (11... Bg4 12. Ne5 Be6 13. Nb3 a5 14. Nc5 Bxc5 15. dxc5 Nbd7 16. Nxd7 Bxd7 17. f3 $16 {1-0 (33) Carlsen,M (2838)-Meier,G (2630) chess.com INT 2017}) 12. h3 Nb6 13. a4 $1 Be6 (13... a5 14. Bc7 Nbd7 15. c3 b6 (15... Nf8 16. Nb3 $16) 16. Re3 $14 {[%cal Gf3e5,Ga1e1,Gg2g4]}) 14. Ng5 Bd7 15. a5 Nc8 16. Ngf3 a6 (16... Nd6 $4 17. Rxe7 Rxe7 18. Bxd6 $18) 17. Nb3 Na7 18. Nc5 Bxc5 19. dxc5 $14 {½-½ (55) Hracek,Z (2612)-Andreikin,D (2723) Minsk BLR 2017. Black has a daunting defensive task ahead of him.}) 7. O-O O-O {This symmetrical structure can also arise from the Petroff and Berlin Defences (6.f1 instead of 6.xc6).} 8. Re1 Nc6 ({A more natural move and possibly better move order is} 8... Re8 9. Bg5 Bd7 (9... Be6 $5 10. Nbd2 Nbd7 11. c3 Bd6 12. Qf1 c6 $11 {and I don't see how White can cause Black any problems here.}) 10. Qd1 h6 11. Bh4 Nc6 12. c3 Nh5 $1 $11 {0-1 (55) Hovhannisyan,R (2611)-Anton Guijarro,D (2626) Martuni 2015}) 9. c3 Re8 10. Bg5 Bg4 11. h3 Bh5 12. Nbd2 a6 $6 {This type of play is "Too slow" according to Howell. In fact, the weakening it creates on the queenside will also be an influential factor in the evaluation of some possible lines later in the game. But overall, I think Black underestimated White's plan of improving his position as will be seen in the next few moves.} ({A better continuation is} 12... h6 13. Bxf6 (13. Bh4 {This simple retreat could be what Black was worried about, but the forcing lines, though risky-looking, favour Black in the end:} g5 $1 (13... Bf8 14. Qf1 $36) 14. Bg3 (14. g4 gxh4 15. gxh5 Ba3 $1 16. Ne5 Bxb2 $1 (16... Nxe5 $2 17. dxe5 Bxb2 18. Qe3 Bxa1 19. Kh1 $40) 17. Kh1 Bxa1 18. Rg1+ Kf8 19. Qe3 Re6 $1 (19... Bxc3 20. Qxh6+ Ke7 21. Nxc6+ bxc6 22. Re1+ $132) 20. Qxh6+ Ke7 {and White's compensation is questionable.} 21. Nxf7 Qf8 $1 22. Rg7 Re8 $17) 14... Ba3 $17) 13... Bxf6 14. Qf1 {The same approach to the game. Here, Black seems to have enough resources to defend and fully equalise with natural moves} (14. Qxe8+ Qxe8 15. Rxe8+ Rxe8 $11 16. g4 Bg6 17. Bxg6 fxg6 {doesn't gain White anything as he cannot exploit Black's doubled pawns.}) 14... Qd7 15. g4 (15. Bb5 Rad8 16. Ne5 Bxe5 17. dxe5 a6 18. Bxc6 Qxc6 19. f4 {Black has his fair share of chances in this complex middlegame.} Qb6+ (19... Bg6 $5) 20. Qf2 Qxb2 21. Rab1 Qxc3 22. Rec1 Qa3 23. Rxc7 Rc8 $11) 15... Bg6 16. Bxg6 fxg6 17. Qd3 (17. Qb5 Rf8 $1 {White is not making a real threat so it's best to start creating counterplay.} (17... b6 $6 {Weakening squares is unecessary.} 18. Re3 $1 {[%cal Ga1e1]} Rxe3 19. fxe3 a6 20. Qd3 g5 (20... Qf7 21. e4 $1) 21. e4 $1 $36) 18. Re3 (18. Qxb7 Rab8 19. Qa6 Rxb2) 18... a6 19. Qd3 Qf7 20. Rae1 Rae8 $11 {and Black is holding.}) 17... g5 (17... Qf7 18. Qb5 {could get annoying.}) 18. Re3 Rxe3 19. fxe3 Ne7 20. Kg2 (20. e4 $2 Ng6 $36 {[%csl Rf4]}) 20... c6 21. Rf1 Rf8 $11) 13. Qf1 $1 Bg6 14. Re3 Nh5 (14... Bxd3 15. Qxd3 Qd7 16. Rae1 h6 {Inviting some exchanges. What else can Black do?} 17. Bf4 $1 {Keeping more pieces to keep Black cramped.} (17. Bxf6 $5 Bxf6 18. Nb3 {Now due to a6 it's a bit difficult to cover c5.} Rxe3 19. Qxe3 b6 {Black is still worse but could most likely hold.}) 17... Bd6 18. Ne5 $14) 15. Rae1 Qd7 16. Bxe7 Rxe7 17. Rxe7 Nxe7 18. Ne5 $14 {Now White has increased his edge as his pieces are clearly superior to their counterparts.} Qd6 19. Ndf3 Nf4 20. Nxg6 $1 {White's bishop will prove more useful in the long run.} hxg6 21. Bc2 Qf6 22. h4 $1 {Creating an outpost or entry square for the knight on g5.} Nf5 {Preventing the knight jump to g5.} 23. g3 (23. Ng5 Nxh4) 23... Ne6 24. Qd3 Nd6 25. Ne5 (25. h5 {Looks pretty good and straightforward but things are not so easy after} Ne4 26. hxg6 N6g5 $1 27. Kg2 (27. gxf7+ $6 Qxf7 {[%csl Rf2,Rf3][%cal Ga8f8,Rf8f2]}) 27... Rf8 $132 {Black can get serious counterplay on the f-file.}) 25... Nf8 (25... Re8 26. h5 {Now this works because of} Ne4 27. f3 $1 Nxg3 28. hxg6 fxg6 29. Qxg6 $18) 26. Ng4 Qd8 {White has made another huge improvement in his position. Now that Black's pieces are warded off, White prepares a kingside breakthrough.} 27. Kg2 Qd7 28. Qf3 Re8 ({Black has no time for} 28... c6 29. h5 gxh5 30. Ne5 $40) 29. Ne5 (29. Rxe8 Nxe8 {Black covers d5 in time.}) 29... Qb5 (29... Qe6 30. Nd3 Qd7 31. Qxd5 {wins a pawn for nothing.}) 30. b3 {Simple and effective.} ({More energetic was} 30. b4 $1 {threatening to win the d5 pawn with a2-a4!} c6 {White to play**********************************************} (30... f6 31. a4 Qb6 32. Qxd5+ $18) (30... Re6 31. a4 Qe8 32. Qxd5 c6 (32... f6 33. Nxg6) 33. Qa2 $1 $18 {[%cal Gc2b3,Ga2g8]}) 31. Rh1 $1 {A nice, patient attacking move! Black is helpless against the threat of h4-h5.} (31. h5 gxh5 32. Qxh5 Re6 {and Black can still put up resistance e.g.} 33. Rh1 (33. Nxf7 $4 Rxe1 34. Nxd6 Qf1+ 35. Kh2 Qh1#) 33... Rh6 $13) 31... Re6 (31... f6 32. Nxg6) (31... f5 32. h5 gxh5 33. Qxh5) 32. h5 gxh5 33. Rxh5 {[%cal Gf3g4,Gg4h4]} g6 34. Rh1 {[%cal Gf3g4,Gg4h4] with the plan of transferring the queen to the h-file.} f5 35. g4 $1 $18 {[%csl Rh8][%cal Gf3h3,Rh3h8]}) 30... Qa5 (30... Re6 31. a4 Qa5 (31... Qe8 32. Qxd5 c6 33. Qc5 f6 34. Nd3 Ne4 35. Qb4 $16) 32. b4 Qb6 33. Qxd5) 31. a4 {Black's queen is now out of action.} c6 32. h5 (32. Rh1 $1 {is also strong here as seen in lines under 30. b4.}) 32... gxh5 33. Qxh5 f6 (33... Re6 {is a more stubborn defence.}) 34. Nc4 $5 {Very practical but may be a tad too simple, but nevertheless enough to win!} (34. Ng6 $1 {was a matter of clearly calculating forcing lines leading to a win for White.} Qd8 (34... Nxg6 35. Rxe8+ Nxe8 36. Bxg6 Nd6 37. Qh7+ Kf8 38. Qh8+ Ke7 39. Qxg7+ $18) (34... Rxe1 35. Qh8+ Kf7 36. Qxf8+ Ke6 37. Qe7#) 35. Qh8+ Kf7 36. Nxf8 Rxe1 (36... Rxf8 37. Qh5+ Kg8 38. Qh7+ Kf7 39. Bg6#) 37. Bg6+ Ke7 38. Qxg7+ Nf7 39. Qxf7+ $18 {Somewhere in one of the lines here, David was missing a strong move that's why he decided to go the safe and solid way to convert his advantage.}) 34... Qc7 ({Of course the engine is screaming several pluses but looking at this on the board, I think White still has to be very accurate after} 34... Qd8 $1 35. Nxd6 Rxe1 36. Qf7+ Kh8 37. Nf5 Ne6 38. Qg6 $1 {An important silent killer.} Qd7 (38... Qg8 39. Nh6 gxh6 40. Qxh6+) 39. Ne7 $1 Ng5 40. Qh5+ Nh7 41. Qxh7#) 35. Rxe8 Nxe8 36. Qxe8 dxc4 37. bxc4 $18 {The endgame is winning for White as Black has neither compensation nor a shred of counterplay.} Qd7 38. Qxd7 Nxd7 39. c5 b5 40. Bf5 Nb8 41. a5 {Black finally resigns.} 1-0


