1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. g3 Bg7 6. Bg2 Nxc3 7. bxc3 O-O 8. O-O c5 9. Qa4 {The queen move hopes to present a clever alternative to the method of fighting for the centre with pawns.} (9. d4 Nc6 10. e3 Bg4 11. h3 Bxf3 12. Bxf3 Qd7 13. Bg2 Rad8 14. Qe2 e6 15. Ba3 cxd4 16. cxd4 Rfe8 17. Rfc1 Rc8 18. Rab1 b6 19. Qb5 Nb8 20. Qxd7 Nxd7 21. Bc6 $18 {1-0 Nakamura,H (2715)-Flermoen,P (2100)/Oslo 2009 (34)}) 9... Bd7 10. Qa3 Na6 $1 {In nominal terms the location of the knight at the edge of the board should not be so good. In fact it seems stronger than the obvious 10...c7 as it develops the piece and preserves flexibility for the future.} (10... Qc7 11. d3 (11. Rb1 b6 12. d4 cxd4 13. cxd4 Bc6 14. Bf4 Qb7 15. Rbc1 Bd5 16. Rfe1 b5 17. Rc7 Qb6 18. Qxe7 Na6 19. Rd7 Be6 20. Rd6 Qa5 21. Rxe6 fxe6 22. Qxe6+ Kh8 23. Bd2 $18 {1-0 Milos,G (2620)-Olivencia,F (2229)/Sao Paulo 2005 (34)}) 11... c4 12. d4 Nc6 13. Bf4 Qa5 14. Qxa5 Nxa5 15. Bc7 b6 16. Ne5 Bxe5 17. Bxe5 Rad8 18. h3 Bc6 19. e4 Ba4 20. Rfc1 Nc6 21. Bf4 f6 (21... e5 $1 22. dxe5 (22. Be3 exd4 23. cxd4 Nxd4 24. Rxc4 Nc2 25. Rc1 Nxe3 26. Rxa4 Nxg2 27. Rxa7 Ra8 $11) 22... Rfe8 23. Bg5 Rd3 24. f4 Rxg3 25. Kf2 Rxg5 26. fxg5 Nxe5 $11) 22. Be3 e5 23. d5 $16 {½-½ Koshy,V (2405)-Safarzadeh,E (2275)/Madras 1995 (58)}) 11. Rb1 (11. d4 Bc6 12. Bf4 cxd4 13. cxd4 Nc7 14. Bxc7 Qxc7 15. Rac1 Rfd8 16. e3 Qd6 17. Qxd6 Rxd6 18. Ng5 Bxg2 19. Kxg2 Ra6 20. Rc2 Rd8 21. Rfc1 Bf8 22. Ne4 b6 23. g4 f6 {½-½ Arutinian,D (2507)-Jobava,B (2401)/Tbilisi 2006}) 11... Bc6 12. d3 Qc8 (12... Qd6 13. Be3 c4 14. Qxd6 exd6 15. Nd4 Bxg2 16. Kxg2 cxd3 17. exd3 Nc5 18. Rfd1 b6 19. c4 Bxd4 20. Bxd4 f5 {½-½ Podgaets,M-Razuvaev,Y/Odessa 1974}) 13. Bf4 {White seems to be struggling to obtain any advantage at all. Black toys with a sound plan of b6, allowing the improvement of the location of his pieces.} (13. Be3 b6 14. d4 (14. Qc1 Rd8 15. Nd2 Bxg2 16. Kxg2 Qc6+ 17. Kg1 Nc7 18. c4 Ne6 19. Qc2 h5 20. Nf3 Bf6 21. a4 h4 22. a5 h3 23. axb6 axb6 $17 {0-1 Mamedov,N (2614)-Melkumyan,H (2530)/Kavala 2009 (39)}) 14... Be4 15. Rbc1 Rd8 16. Rfe1 Qb7 17. Qb3 e6 18. Red1 Rac8 19. Qb2 Bf8 20. Bg5 Re8 21. Ne1 Bxg2 22. Nxg2 h6 23. Be3 $11 {½-½ Riumin,N-Botvinnik,M/Leningrad 1934 (46)}) 13... b6 14. Qb3 Nc7 15. Bxc7 $5 {The long term strategic idea that deserves some attention. Rodstein is making a long term bet on fighting the endgame with the knight against the black bishop.} (15. Ng5 Bxg2 16. Kxg2 h6 17. Nf3 Rd8 $11) 15... Qxc7 16. Nd2 Rfd8 17. Bxc6 Qxc6 18. a4 h5 19. Qc4 e6 20. Rb3 {Objectively the position is balanced, but Black must be careful to avoid an endgame with his pawn structure fixed on the dark squares.} Qd5 (20... Bh6 21. f4 (21. Nf3 Qd5 $11) 21... Bg7 22. Rfb1 Rd4 23. Qb5 Qxb5 24. axb5 Ra4 $11) 21. Qxd5 exd5 (21... Rxd5 22. Nc4 Bf6 23. a5 bxa5 24. Nxa5 a6 25. Kg2 $14) 22. c4 Re8 (22... d4 23. a5 Re8 24. Re1 Re6 $11) 23. e3 Rad8 24. Rfb1 Be5 {[%mdl 4096] The bishop on the c7-square should be good enough to defendi the vulnerable b6-spot.} (24... dxc4 25. Nxc4 Re6 26. a5 $14) 25. Kf1 Bc7 26. Ke2 d4 27. e4 Kf8 28. f4 Ke7 (28... h4 29. Kf3 hxg3 30. hxg3 f6 $11) 29. a5 {White is ignoring the chance to exploit the less precise move by Howell for the improvement of his structure.} (29. e5 $5 f6 30. exf6+ Kxf6+ 31. Ne4+ Kg7 32. a5 $14) 29... bxa5 30. Rb5 Bb6 31. Nb3 Kd6 32. Nxa5 Rb8 33. R5b2 Kc7 34. Nb3 a5 35. Ra2 Ra8 36. Rba1 Ra7 37. e5 $2 {Rodstein was probably dreaming about bringing his king or knight to e4. The pawn advance at this moment suffers from an obvious flaw.} (37. Ra4 f6 38. Kf3 Rea8 $11) 37... f6 $1 38. Nd2 $2 {Yet another second rate move turns the tables, Black will be the ambitious party with a spare pawn.} (38. Rf1 $1 Kc6 (38... fxe5 39. f5 Rf8 (39... e4 40. fxg6 exd3+ 41. Kxd3 Re3+ 42. Kd2 Kd6 43. Rb2 a4 44. Nxd4 cxd4 45. Rxb6+ Kc5 46. Rb8 Kxc4 47. Rc8+ Kb4 48. Rf4 $16) 40. fxg6 Rxf1 41. Kxf1 Ra8 42. Rf2 a4 43. Rf7+ Kd6 44. Rf6+ Kc7 45. Na1 e4 46. Ke2 exd3+ 47. Kxd3 a3 $14) 39. Nd2 Bd8 40. Rb2 fxe5 41. f5 gxf5 42. Rxf5 h4 43. gxh4 Bxh4 44. Nf3 Bd8 45. Rxe5 $15) 38... fxe5 39. fxe5 Rxe5+ 40. Ne4 Rf5 41. Rb1 Kc6 42. h3 Bc7 43. Rb5 Bb6 (43... Rb7 44. g4 Re5 45. Rxb7 Kxb7 46. Kd1 hxg4 47. hxg4 $15) 44. Ra1 (44. Rb1 $1 $11) 44... Rf8 (44... a4 45. Rb2 Rf8 46. Rba2 Rfa8 47. Rf1 Bd8 48. Kd1 $15) 45. Rb2 Raa8 46. Kd2 $2 {White is helping the opponent with gusto, since now the danger of losing will increase dramatically.} (46. Rb5 Ra6 47. Rb2 $15) 46... Rf3 $1 47. Kc2 Ra7 {Black was not mentally ready to switch gear and try winning the position. Despite the compromised bishop on b6 his chances were already very reasonable.} (47... Re8 $1 48. Rb5 (48. Kd2 Rxe4 49. Rxb6+ Kxb6 50. dxe4 Rxg3 $19) 48... Re5 49. h4 Bc7 50. Rab1 a4 51. Ra1 Rxe4 52. dxe4 Rc3+ 53. Kd2 a3 $17) 48. Rab1 Ra6 49. Ra2 Ra7 50. Rab2 Ra6 51. Ra2 Ra7 52. Rab2 1/2-1/2


