1. Nf3 Nf6 2. d4 g6 3. Bg5 Bg7 4. Nbd2 O-O 5. c3 d6 6. e3 Qe8 { e5} (6... Nbd7 7. Be2 e5 8. O-O Qe8 {- 6...e8}) 7. Be2 (7. a4 h6 {It is usually advisable to insert h6 h4, because then the  has no retreat on the c1-h6  after a possible e3-e4.} 8. Bh4 e5 9. dxe5 dxe5 10. a5 {White completely neglects the , as if it would be completely closed.} (10. e4 $5) 10... Nh5 { f5} ({The alternative plan by} 10... e4 $5 11. Nd4 c5 12. N4b3 Qc6 {gains a lot of space in the .}) 11. Bc4 Kh8 12. e4 f5 13. exf5 gxf5 {Black's strong central pawns cannot be attacked easily.} 14. O-O Nc6 15. Bb5 e4 $5 {immediately looks logical.} (15... Qg6 16. Nc4 e4 17. Bxc6 bxc6 18. Nfe5 {This is the difference!} Qe8 19. a6 {White is completely obsessed by the advance of this flank .} (19. f4 Ba6 20. Rf2 Nxf4 21. Rxf4 Bxe5 22. Nxe5 Qxe5 23. Bg3 $44 {but not more than.}) (19. Bd8 Bxe5 20. Nxe5 Ba6 21. Bxc7 Bxf1 22. Kxf1 $44) 19... Rb8 20. Qd8 $5 (20. f4 $2 Nxf4 $17 {Mikac-Sutovsky, Portoroz 1997}) 20... Bxa6 21. Qxe8 Rfxe8 22. Rxa6 Bxe5 23. Nxe5 Rxe5 24. Rxc6 $14) 16. Nd4 Qg6 17. Nxc6 bxc6 $13) (7. Bd3 {runs into} e5 {and soon or later the fork by e5-e4 is threatened.} 8. Qc2 (8. O-O Nbd7 9. Qc2 h6 10. Bh4 Nh5 11. g4 Nhf6 {White has won a tempo, but weakened his .} 12. h3 d5 13. e4 {White is better developed, so he has to open the position.} dxe4 (13... exd4 14. cxd4 dxe4 15. Nxe4 Nxe4 16. Bxe4 Nb6 (16... Nf6 17. Bxf6 Bxf6 18. Bd5 {with a double .}) 17. Rfe1 Qd7 18. Qb3) 14. Nxe4 Nxe4 15. Bxe4 f5 $1 {This is a bright idea to get out of passivity at any rate.} 16. gxf5 gxf5 17. Bxf5 Nc5 $1 {This is the point!} 18. Bxc8 Qxc8 19. Nxe5 Qxh3 20. Ng6 Ne6 $1 21. Ne7+ (21. Nxf8 Rxf8 $17 {and suddenly the white  is helpless against the threats.}) 21... Kh8 22. Ng6+ {White has to keep the checks.} Kg8 {½-½ Reuss-Aronian, Deizisau 2002}) 8... Nh5 9. e4 $1 (9. dxe5 {Timman} dxe5 10. e4 Nf4 $1 $15) 9... Nc6 (9... f5 $143 $6 {is premature because of} 10. dxe5 dxe5 11. exf5 gxf5 12. O-O-O $1 {and White will soon blow up Black's seemingly mighty .} e4 (12... h6 13. Be3 e4 14. Bc4+ Kh8 15. Nh4 $14) 13. Nxe4 $1 fxe4 14. Bxe4 {White gets some pawns and good attacking chances for the piece.} Nf6 15. Bxf6 Bxf6 16. Rhe1 Kh8 $1 {Timman} (16... Qh5 $2 {allows White to win more pawns for the piece.} 17. Qb3+ Kg7 18. Bxb7 Bxb7 19. Qxb7 Qc5 20. Rd5 $1 Qc6 21. Qxc6 Nxc6 22. Rc5 $18 {Timman-Van Wely, Groningen 1997 68/51 CBM 57}) 17. Bxb7 Qxe1 18. Rxe1 Bxb7 19. Qf5 $1 (19. Ne5 Nc6 $1 $13) 19... Bxf3 20. gxf3 $14 {with better chances in the , the black pieces lack any of harmony.}) (9... exd4 $5 {Stohl} 10. Nxd4 ({The "natural"} 10. cxd4 $143 {is countered by} f5 {ruining White's  anyway.} 11. e5 Nc6 $1 $36) 10... f5 (10... Nd7 $11) 11. f3 f4 $5 $13 { d7-e5} (11... fxe4 12. Bc4+ (12. Nxe4 $6 d5 13. Qb3 Qf7 $36) 12... Kh8 13. Qxe4 Nf6 $132 (13... c6 14. O-O d5 15. Qxe8 Rxe8 16. Rfe1 $1 $14))) 10. dxe5 Nxe5 $11 {Timman}) (7. Bc4 {is logical because after e5 the  is well-placed on the a2-g8 .} Nbd7 { e5 looks more flexible.} (7... e5 8. dxe5 dxe5 9. e4 $1 (9. Qb3 Nc6 { a5} 10. Qa3 Kh8 (10... e4 $5 11. Nd4 Ne5) 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. h4 {This aggressive idea is not in the spirit of this positional variation.} Be7 13. Qa4 Bd7 14. h5 g5 15. Qc2 f5 $13 {Hill-Agdestein, Canberra 1997}) 9... Nbd7 (9... h6 {is already met by} 10. Be3 $1) 10. h3 $5 {secures the retreat of the  to the ideal square e3.} (10. O-O h6 11. Bh4 (11. Be3 $6 {is already weaker due to} Ng4) 11... Nb6 (11... Nh5 $5) 12. Bb3 a5 13. a4 Bd7 (13... Nh5 $5) 14. Bxf6 Bxf6 15. Nc4 Nxc4 16. Bxc4 {½-½ Hug-Gallagher, Switzerland chT 1997})) (7... h6 $5)) 7... e5 (7... h6 $5 8. Bh4 e5 9. O-O {- 7...e5}) 8. O-O (8. dxe5 dxe5 9. e4 Nbd7 10. b4 (10. h3 Nh5 11. O-O Nf4) 10... h6 11. Bh4 b6 12. O-O Bb7 13. Bxf6 {White usually exchanges this , but he has not enough play on the light squares.} Nxf6 14. Qc2 Qe7 15. Rfe1 Rfd8 16. Bf1 a5 17. a3 Nd7 18. Nc4 axb4 19. axb4 Rxa1 20. Rxa1 Ra8 21. Rxa8+ Bxa8 22. Ncd2 Nf6 23. Bc4 Ne8 24. Qa2 $11 {Malaniuk-Nielsen, Lyngby op 1991}) 8... Nbd7 (8... h6 9. Bh4 Nbd7 (9... Bf5 10. a4 Nc6 11. a5 e4 12. Ne1 g5 13. Bg3 Ne7 14. a6 (14. f3 $6 Ned5) 14... b6 15. Nc2 Bg6 16. Nb4 c5 17. Nc2 Nf5 18. Na3 Rd8 $13 {Short-Kramnik, Moscow 1996}) (9... Nc6 10. a4 Nh7 (10... e4 11. Ne1) 11. Bc4 Kh8 (11... e4 12. Ne1 Kh8 13. f3) 12. dxe5 dxe5 (12... Nxe5 13. Nxe5 Qxe5) 13. e4 Nd8 { e6 improving the 's position.} 14. Re1 Ne6 15. Bb5 c6 16. Bf1 {weakening × d6} Nhg5 17. Nc4 Nxf3+ 18. Qxf3 f6 19. Rad1 $14 {V.Kovacevic-Cvitan, Solin/Split 2000}) 10. a4 {- 8...bd7}) (8... Nc6 9. dxe5 Nxe5 $5 (9... dxe5 10. e4 Qe7 11. Qc2 h6 12. Bh4 Bg4 13. Nc4 Bxf3 14. Bxf3 Qe6 15. Ne3 Ne7 16. Be2 $14 {Bogdanovski-Ungureanu, Pula 2003}) 10. Nxe5 Qxe5 (10... dxe5)) 9. a4 (9. dxe5 dxe5 (9... Nxe5 10. Nxe5 Qxe5 $11) 10. e4 Nc5 11. Qc2 Ne6 12. Bh4 Nf4 13. Bc4 N6h5 14. Rfe1 Bg4 15. Bf1 (15. h3 Bd7 {This manoeuvre has weakened g3, the retreating square of the .} 16. Rad1 h6) 15... h6 16. Re3 Bd7 17. Nc4 b5 18. Na5 g5 19. Bg3 {White has always problems with his dark-squared .} Qe7 20. b4 c5 21. a3 c4 22. a4 a6 23. Rd1 Be6 $11 {Lukasiewicz-Tkachiev, Geneva op 1997}) 9... h6 10. Bh4 Nh7 (10... e4 11. Ne1 Nh7 $1 12. Nc2 f5 $13 13. f3 Nhf6 (13... Ndf6 {Gligoric} 14. fxe4 Nxe4 15. Nxe4 Qxe4 $1) 14. Bxf6 (14. fxe4 Nxe4 15. Nxe4 Qxe4) 14... Nxf6 15. fxe4 fxe4 16. a5 c6 17. Qe1 d5 {Now Black has a clear space advantage.} 18. c4 Be6 19. Qg3 Kh7 20. cxd5 cxd5 $15 {Kovacevic-Gligoric, Yugoslavia 1979 28/122}) 11. e4 Bf6 (11... g5 12. Bg3 h5 13. h3 g4 14. hxg4 hxg4 15. Nh4 exd4 16. cxd4 Bxd4 17. Bxg4 Bxb2 {wins the  but loses the  after} 18. Rb1 $36) 12. Bg3 {The  is not impressive here, but exchanging it is worse.} (12. Bxf6 Nhxf6 13. Qc2 a5) 12... Qe7 (12... Ng5 $6 13. Nxg5 Bxg5 {allows the breakthrough} 14. f4 exf4 15. Bxf4 $16) (12... a5 {preventing the space-gaining a4-a5 deserves attention.} 13. Qc2 Qe7) 13. Re1 ({Why not first} 13. a5 a6 {and then} 14. Re1) 13... h5 (13... a5 {is again an option.}) (13... Ng5) 14. h4 (14. h3 Ng5 (14... a5) 15. Nxg5 Bxg5) 14... Re8 (14... a5 {This was the last opportunity to resist on the .}) 15. a5 a6 (15... Bg7 {allows the further advance weakening the light squares after} 16. a6 b6 17. Bb5) 16. Nc4 Nhf8 (16... Bg7 17. Qd2) 17. Qd2 (17. Ne3 { d5}) 17... Ne6 18. Rad1 (18. Ne3 {was still possible.}) 18... Bg7 19. Bf1 f6 {If Black has to play like that this is the bankrupcy of his opening strategy. He simply forgot about his , which happens sometimes in the King's Indian, where the  on c8 looks excellent!} (19... exd4 20. cxd4 Nf6 21. d5 Nc5 22. e5 $16) 20. b4 {White has a big space advantage, and Black has no real counterplay on the .} Kh7 21. Ne3 Bh6 22. Qc2 Ndf8 (22... c6 23. d5) 23. Nd5 Qg7 24. dxe5 dxe5 25. c4 {White continues the advance on the . The weakness of × d4 remains symbolic, as we will see in the game.} Nd8 26. Nd2 Nfe6 27. Nb3 Nc6 {Black's  manoeuvres are really exhausting...} 28. Qc3 Rd8 (28... Ncd4 29. Nxd4 Nxd4 30. Rxd4 $1 exd4 31. Qxd4 $18) 29. b5 Ncd4 30. Nxd4 Nxd4 {} 31. Rxd4 $1 {This typical positional exchange sacrifice puts an end on the career of the kinghts.} exd4 32. Qxd4 $18 {and Black's position is completely destroyed.} Kh8 (32... Be6 33. Nxf6+ Kh8 34. Qe5 $18) 33. Qb2 axb5 34. cxb5 Qf7 35. Ra1 {Safety first.} (35. Qxf6+ Qxf6 36. Nxf6 Rf8) 35... Rxd5 {Desperation, but it was hopeless.} (35... Bg7 36. Nxc7 f5 37. Qa2 $18) 36. exd5 Qxd5 37. Qxf6+ $1 Bg7 38. Qxg6 Bxa1 39. Bd3 Qd7 40. Qh6+ Kg8 41. Bc4+ 1-0


