1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 e6 6. Be3 {This move is supposed to force Black to exchange pawns on d4.} Be7 $5 {In most of the games Black automatically takes on d4, but Carlsen shows that the rare 6...e7 is a reasonable option as well. Especially since he declared later on "I was well prepared in this variation".} 7. dxc5 Qxd1+ 8. Kxd1 O-O 9. Nbd2 Ng4 {This position has occurred only three times in praxis.} 10. Nb3 $146 {Faced with a rare variation and a well prepared opponent, Howell understandably tries to play as safe as possible. However, thanks to the bishop pair (there will be an exchange on e3 sooner or later) now Black can fight for advantage in a quiet and pleasant position.} ({The most principled continuation is} 10. b4 {which was played in previous games and which is probably the only way to test the viability of 6...e7. Then after} a5 ({The exchange on e3 is premature:} 10... Nxe3+ 11. fxe3 a5 12. Nd4 Rd8 13. Kc2 axb4 14. cxb4 Bf6 (14... e5 15. N4b3 Bf5+ 16. e4) 15. Bb5 Bxd4 16. exd4 Rxd4 17. Nc4 e5 18. Kc3 $16 {1-0 Murariu,A (2430)-Doncea,V (2380)/Baile Tusnad 2005 (33)}) {White can continue} 11. Kc2 {In order to evaluate precisely this complicated position practical examples are needed. In most cases Black wins back the pawn, but in return White gains more space on the queenside. The following variations show that in spite of his exposed king, there are hopes for White to achieve some advantage:} (11. Nd4 Rd8 $5 (11... axb4 12. cxb4 Rd8 13. Kc2 Bf6 (13... e5 $44) 14. N2b3 e5 15. Nb5 Nc6 16. a3 Bf5+ 17. Kc3 e4+ 18. N3d4 Nxd4 (18... b6 $142 $44) 19. Nxd4 Rac8 20. Bb5 b6 21. c6 Bxd4+ 22. Bxd4 Bd7 23. Bxb6 Bxc6 24. Bc4 $16 {0-1 Seret,J (2455)-Adorjan,A (2565)/Luzern 1985 (77)}) 12. Kc2 $140 e5 $36 13. N4b3 Bf5+ {Now the advantage of postponing exchanges both on b4 and on e3 become clear. White doesn't have e3-e4 (as in case of an earlier exchange on e3), nor can he play} 14. Kb2 {in view of} a4 15. Na5 Nxe3 {winning a piece.}) (11. Bc4 axb4 12. cxb4 Nc6 $44 13. b5 Nb4 14. Ne4 Nxe3+ 15. fxe3 Ra3 16. Re1 Rd8+ 17. Kc1 f5 18. Ned2 Rc3+ 19. Kb2 Bf6 20. Nd4 Rxe3 21. Rxe3 Rxd4 22. Kb3 Rxd2 23. Rc1 Rb2+ 24. Ka4 Nxa2 $19 (24... Nc2 25. Bxe6+ Kf8 $2 26. Re2 Rxa2+ $4 27. Bxa2 {1-0 Van de Oudeweetering,A (2369)-Pavlovic,M (2545)/Amsterdam 2004 (36)})) (11. a3 $5) 11... axb4 12. cxb4 Bf6 (12... Nc6 13. Kb3 Nxe3 14. fxe3 b6 15. Bb5 Na7 16. Be2 bxc5 17. b5 Bb7 18. a4 $14) (12... Bd7 13. Bc4 Ba4+ 14. Bb3 Nc6 15. a3 Bf6 $13) 13. Rb1 ({also deserves attention} 13. Bd4 Bxd4 14. Nxd4 Nxf2 15. Rg1 e5 16. Nb5 Nc6 17. Kb3 $13) 13... Rxa2+ (13... e5 14. Ne4 Rxa2+ 15. Kb3 Be6+ 16. Bc4 Bxc4+ 17. Kxc4 Nxe3+ 18. fxe3 Rxg2 19. Rhg1 $44) 14. Kb3 Ra8 15. Ne4 Be7 16. Bb5 $13 {/}) 10... Nxe3+ 11. fxe3 Nd7 12. c6 {This way White at least breaks up his opponent's pawn structure.} bxc6 13. Na5 Bc5 $5 {An interesting approach from Carlsen: he doesn't even try to defend his c-pawn. Instead he activates the pieces.} (13... c5 {with an equal position is of course possible as well.}) 14. Nd4 Nf6 {It turns out that taking the pawn on c6 leads only to a temporary material advantage for White: thanks to the activity of his pieces Black will regain the pawn in all variations.} 15. Bc4 (15. Naxc6 Ng4 16. Ke2 (16. Kd2 e5 17. Nc2 Bb7 18. Na5 Rad8+ $17) 16... Bd7 $44 {/}) 15... Ng4 16. Ke2 e5 17. Nc2 (17. Ndxc6 Nxe3 $17) 17... Bf5 18. h3 Nf6 19. Nb4 Be4 20. Nbxc6 Rfe8 {Black's advantage is minimal, since regaining the pawn will lead to further simplifications.} 21. Rhg1 Bb6 22. b4 Rac8 23. b5 (23. Bb5 Nd5 $17 {[%csl Rc3,Re3]}) 23... Bxa5 24. Nxa5 Rc5 {White has succeeded in exchanging a knight for his opponent's bishop, but he is still on the defensive due to the lack of coordination between his pieces and multiple pawn weaknesses.} 25. a4 $1 Rec8 26. Bd3 ({There is no time to bring the rook to the d-file:} 26. Rgd1 Bxg2) ({or} 26. Rad1 Bc2) 26... Bxd3+ (26... Rxc3 27. Bxe4 Nxe4 28. Nc6 $132) 27. Kxd3 Rxc3+ 28. Ke2 Rc2+ (28... e4 29. Rgd1 Rc2+ 30. Rd2 {favours White again.}) 29. Kf3 e4+ 30. Kf4 R8c5 31. Nc6 {Finally bringing the knight back into the game. Black can't create decisive threats against the white king, which means that the position should be close to equal.} g5+ 32. Kg3 R5c3 33. Ne7+ (33. Nxa7 Rxe3+ 34. Kh2 g4 {threatening xh3 mate looks scary for White, but the computer shows that it is a draw after} 35. Kh1 gxh3 36. b6 Ng4 37. b7 Nf2+ 38. Kh2 Ng4+ 39. Kh1 $11) 33... Kf8 $1 (33... Kg7 34. Nf5+ Kg6 35. Ne7+ Kh5 {exposes unnecessarily the king. For instance:} 36. Rae1 ({not} 36. Raf1 Rxe3+ 37. Kh2 Rf3 $1) 36... Ra3 $140 37. Kh2 {[%cal Ge1f1]} Rxa4 38. Ref1 $132) 34. Nf5 Nd5 35. Rge1 $2 {A blunder in time trouble.} (35. Rad1 {would have allowed White to escape:} Rd3 36. Rc1 Nxe3 37. Nxe3 Rxe3+ 38. Kg4 Rf2 (38... Rxc1 39. Rxc1 $11) 39. Kxg5 ({but not} 39. Rc7 h6 $1 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gf4h4]} 40. Kh5 Kg7 41. h4 ({or} 41. g3 Rh2 42. Rxa7 Rf3 43. b6 Rxh3+ 44. Kg4 Rh2 $19) 41... Rg3 {and Black wins, since} 42. Rxa7 {runs into mate after} g4 {[%cal Gf2f5]}) 39... Ra3 (39... Rg3+ 40. Kh4 Rgxg2 41. Rxg2 Rxg2 42. Re1 f5 43. Rf1 $11) 40. Rc4 e3 (40... f5 $2 41. Kf6) 41. Rf4 {and White will achieve a draw, although accurate defence is still required.}) 35... Nf4 $19 36. Rg1 Ne2+ 37. Kg4 Nxg1 38. Rxg1 f6 {Of course this should be winning for Black, but things are not trivial due to White's excellent knight on f5 and his active king.} 39. h4 gxh4 40. Kxh4 Ra3 41. g4 Rxa4 42. Rd1 Raa2 43. Rd7 Rh2+ 44. Kg3 Rhg2+ 45. Kh3 Rgf2 46. Nd4 Kg8 $6 {Starting with this moment Carlsen loses the thread, missing even a forced win later on.} ({After} 46... Ra3 47. Kg3 (47. Nf5 Rf3+ 48. Kh4 Ra2 $19) 47... Rf1 48. Kg2 (48. Nf5 Rf3+ 49. Kh2 Ra2+ 50. Kg1 h5 $19) 48... Re1 49. Kf2 Rh1 50. Kg2 (50. Nf5 h5 51. Kg2 (51. gxh5 Rxh5 52. Nd6 Rh2+ 53. Kg3 Rd2 $19) 51... Rc1 52. gxh5 Rc5 53. Nd6 Rg5+ 54. Kh2 Rxe3 $19) 50... Raa1 {Black would have kept excellent winning chances, since} 51. Rxa7 Rxa7 52. Kxh1 Ra3 {is lost for White.}) 47. Re7 Kf8 48. Rc7 ({White correctly prefers to keep his opponent's king cut off rather than release it after} 48. Rxe4 Kf7 {when it is much easier for Black to play than in the game.}) 48... Ke8 49. Kg3 Rf1 50. Rxh7 Ra3 51. Kg2 $2 {Both players became visibly tired. Bringing back the king is a bad mistake, which, however, remained unpunished.} ({The active king after} 51. Nf5 Rf3+ 52. Kh4 {would have been enough for successful defence:} ({Again going back is hopeless:} 52. Kg2 $2 Ra2+ 53. Kg1 Rff2 54. Rxa7 Rg2+ 55. Kf1 Raf2+ 56. Ke1 Rb2 57. Kf1 Rgd2 $19) 52... Ra2 53. Nd6+ Kd8 (53... Kf8 54. Rf7+ Kg8 55. Kh5 Rd2 56. Rd7) 54. Nb7+ Kc8 55. Nd6+ Kb8 56. Rb7+ Ka8 57. Kh5 Rxe3 58. Re7 $11) 51... Rd1 52. Nf5 (52. Nc6 Rxe3 53. Kf2 Rf3+ 54. Ke2 Rd7 $19) (52. Rh3 Rd2+ $19) 52... Rd7 $2 (52... Ra2+ {wins by force, since after} 53. Kg3 Rg1+ 54. Kf4 Rf2+ 55. Kxe4 Rxg4+ 56. Kd5 Rxf5+ 57. Ke6 {Black simply gives a check on e5} Re5+ $19) 53. Rh8+ Kf7 54. Kg3 Rb3 55. Kf4 {The king is back into play and Black is not able to win anymore.} Rb1 (55... Rb4 56. Rh7+ Ke6 57. Rh6 $132 {[%cal Gg4g5]}) 56. Kxe4 Rf1 57. Rh7+ Ke6 58. Rh8 Rc7 59. Nd4+ Kd6 $11 60. Rd8+ Rd7 61. Rc8 Rg7 62. Rd8+ Rd7 63. Rc8 Re7+ 64. Kd3 Rc7 65. Rd8+ Rd7 66. Rg8 Rg1 67. Ke2 Kc5 68. Kf2 Rb1 69. Rf8 Rd6 70. Rf7 Rb2+ 71. Kf3 Ra2 72. Ke4 Kb6 73. Rf8 Rg2 74. Kf3 Rh2 75. Rb8+ Kc7 76. Ra8 Kb7 77. Rf8 Rh7 78. Kf4 Rh1 79. Kf3 1/2-1/2


