{This was my first encounter with David and I wasn't sure what to expect from him as he has quite a broad repertoire.} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 {This was not in my top 6 list which I thought he could opt for!} d5 3. Bg2 e6 4. O-O Be7 5. c4 (5. d3 {I thought maybe he was aiming for a King's Indian Attack.}) 5... O-O 6. d4 {So main Catalan it is. Probably he was fine with the Catalan but wanted to avoid Grünfeld/Kings Indian/QGA from my repertoire.} dxc4 {I have played few games with this solid main line and decided to stick with my preparation for this game.} 7. Qc2 a6 8. a4 Bd7 9. Qxc4 Bc6 10. Bg5 Bd5 (10... h6 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. Nc3 Bxf3 13. Bxf3 c6 14. e3 (14. Qb3 {will transpose to the game}) 14... a5 {Earlier I had this position twice against Akopian and Papaioannu} 15. b4 {Although both my games ended in a draw but there was some pressure I had to withstand which I wanted to avoid for this game.}) 11. Qc2 Be4 12. Qd1 h6 $5 {So the whole point is to get a similar position to 10...h6 but with the white queen on d1 and not on c4 in order to stop White from playing b4.} (12... c5 {is more popular here and has been seen a number of times at the top level.}) 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. Nc3 Bxf3 15. Bxf3 c6 {Now we have the exact same position with white queen on d1 instead of c4.} 16. Qb3 (16. e3 a5 {[%cal Gb8a6,Ga6b4] and White is not in time to break with b4.}) 16... Qc7 {We are back to one of the main lines of 10...h6 where White doesn't play b4.} 17. e3 (17. Rfd1 a5 18. Rac1 Ra6 19. d5 Qb6 $1 {Jumabayev,R (2558)-Harikrishna,P (2666) Mashhad 2011, and Black had a fine position.}) 17... a5 {David was taking s decent amount of time for each move after 12...h6 and I felt he perhaps wanted to get the b4 break in as in the case of 10....h6 and now that he hadn't got the said move he had to come up with some original plan over the board.} 18. Be2 $5 {And he comes up with one! This way White first of all stops all kind of a6-b6 ideas and switches the diagonal of his light squared bishop which will now look at kingside (from d3 or c4) and instead of creating pressure on the queenside now it will focus on a long term kingside attack!} Na6 {The knight belongs on b4. This way White won't be able to create any threats with queen and bishop on the b1-h7 diagonal.} 19. Ne4 Be7 20. Rac1 Nb4 21. Bc4 {And now it was my turn for a long think. So Black has got his minor pieces on the right squares for the moment. What next? Where to put the rooks was my main concern. By keeping his bishop on c4 David has created the potential attacking threat of f4-f5 which will happen sooner or later. Also since the bishop has moved from the h1-a8 diagonal it's clear that White will focus his play on the kingside now.} Rae8 $1 {This looks rather stupid at first sight but since White's main plan is f4-f5 (otherwise the bishop on c4 doesn't make much sense) it makes sense not to move the f8-rook in order to keep the f7-pawn protected and by bringing the other rook to e8 Black is now excellently prepared to meet f4-f5 ideas anytime.} 22. f4 (22. Rfd1 {is possible and of course White doesn't have any problems here but on the other hand now White also doesn't have any clear plans on the kingside and the bishop on c4 is not doing much.} Bd8 $5 {[%cal Gc7e7,Gb4d5,Ge7b4]} (22... Rd8 $5 {I was also considering this move as an alternative})) 22... Bd8 $1 {Now Black doesn't have to worry about f5 ideas anymore.} 23. Qd1 $1 {Now that White has already committed f4 it makes sense to switch the force completely to the kingside and launch an attack.} Qe7 24. Qf3 Nd5 {[%cal Ge7b4]} 25. Rc2 (25. Nc5 $1 {I felt this was needed in order to not allow any counterplay on the queenside.} Bb6 26. Nd3 Bc7 (26... Nb4 27. Ne5 $14) 27. Kg2 Rd8 {I was intending to stay solid and wait for White's break. The computer screams that every line is equal. White definitely has some play here and is probably slightly better although Black is extremely solid.}) 25... Qb4 26. Nc5 {[%cal Gc5d7]} Re7 (26... Bb6 $1 {I simply can't remember why I didn't play this move!} 27. Nd7 $140 Rd8 $1 28. Nxf8 Nxe3 $17 {I saw these tactics but then maybe I got tempted with the move that I played or simply forgot that I thought about b6 after he played c5 :)}) 27. e4 $6 {This move would have given White a steady advantage if Black didn't have the following tactics.} (27. b3 Bb6 {maintains equality.}) 27... Bb6 $1 (27... Nb6 28. Qb3 $1 $14 {was his idea.}) 28. exd5 $2 (28. Nb3 Nf6 $15) (28. Qf2 Bxc5 29. dxc5 Nf6 $15 {White has too many weakness to protect now}) (28. Nd3 Bxd4+ 29. Kh1 Qxa4 30. b3 Qa3 31. exd5 exd5 $15) (28. Kg2 $1 {was the only way not to get into a worse position} Bxc5 29. dxc5 Nf6 30. e5 Nd5 $13) 28... cxd5 29. Qb3 (29. Qa3 Qxa3 30. bxa3 dxc4 $15) (29. Bb3 Qxd4+ 30. Qf2 Qxf2+ (30... Qb4 {This was also very tempting}) 31. Rfxf2 Rc8 32. Nd3 Rxc2 33. Bxc2 Rc7 34. Bb3 Kf8 $17 {this was one of the options I was considering}) (29. Nd3 Bxd4+ 30. Kg2 Qxa4 31. b3 Qc6 $17) 29... Bxc5 30. dxc5 Qxc5+ 31. Rff2 dxc4 32. Qxc4 {Black is a healthy pawn up and White's king is also weak so it is very difficult to hold this endgame, especially if Black can keep the queens on the board.} Qa7 $1 {The safest way to keep the queens on the board.} (32... Qe3 33. Qc5 $1 {and White's drawing chances will increase significantly after exchange of queens.}) 33. Kg2 Rd7 34. Rfd2 b6 35. Qc6 (35. Rxd7 Qxd7 36. Qc6 Qd4 $17 {[%csl Rg2]}) 35... Rfd8 36. Rxd7 Rxd7 37. h4 $6 {This further weakens White's king position.} h5 $1 38. Kh2 Kh7 (38... Rd1 $4 {I was considering this move for some time then recovered from the shock and played ...h7 instead!} 39. Qc8+ Kh7 40. Rc7 $18) 39. Qe4+ g6 40. Qc6 Rd1 {And all Black has to do now is to get his queen out. This was the 40th move and I didn't realise that the win was still far away.} 41. b3 $1 (41. Qe8 Qb7 $19) (41. Qc7 Rd2+ {[%csl Rb2]} 42. Kh3 Qxc7 43. Rxc7 Kg7 44. b4 axb4 45. Rc6 Ra2 46. Rxb6 Rxa4 47. Rb8 Kf6 48. Rb7 Kf5 49. Rxf7+ Ke4 $19) 41... Rd3 $1 {Not to allow the exchange of queens.} 42. Qb5 Rd6 43. Rc8 $1 {Just when I thought the game was over David comes up with the most stubborn defence.} (43. Rc6 Rd2+ 44. Kh3 Qa8 $1 (44... Qd7 45. Rxb6 Qd4 46. Rb7 {and it's a draw!}) 45. Qxb6 Rd6 $1 $19 {was my intention.}) 43... Rd2+ $1 (43... Qb7 44. Rh8+ $1 {is a fine trick} Kxh8 45. Qe5+ Kg8 46. Qxd6 {and the win is very very far away for Black.}) 44. Kh3 Qb7 45. Qc6 Qa6 46. Rh8+ {Again the only way.} (46. Qc4 Qxc4 47. Rxc4 Rb2 48. Rc3 Kg7 {should be winning easily.}) 46... Kxh8 47. Qc3+ e5 $1 {Otherwise it's not so easy to come up with a concrete plan.} 48. Qxd2 exf4 (48... Qf1+ 49. Kh2 exf4 50. gxf4 Qf3 51. Qd4+ Kh7 52. Qxb6 Qxf4+ 53. Kg2 {White should be lost, but here White will create some counterplay with an outside passed pawn.}) 49. gxf4 (49. Qxf4 Qc8+ 50. Kh2 Qc2+ 51. Kg1 Qxb3 $19) 49... Qc8+ 50. Kh2 Qc5 {Not to allow b4.} 51. Qb2+ Kh7 52. Qd2 Qe7 53. Qf2 (53. Kg3 Qe6 $19) 53... Qf6 {And White is in zugzwang.} 54. Kh1 (54. Kg2 Qe6 $19) (54. Qg3 Qb2+ 55. Kh3 Qe2 $19) 54... Qe6 55. Qg3 Qg4 56. Qe3 Qxh4+ 57. Kg2 Qf6 58. Kh2 Qe6 59. Qd3 Qf5 60. Qe3 Qc2+ 61. Kg3 Qc5 62. Qe1 Qd4 63. Qe8 Qg1+ 64. Kf3 Qg4+ 65. Ke3 Qe6+ 0-1


