1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 {An interesting opening choice, used in 2014 by Howell against me among other things; in this tournament it was used not only in the present game, but also replicated by McShane later on, in the first blitz tiebreak.} 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Na5 {Thus, intentionally or otherwise, arriving at a schematically quite similar position to the one I had against Howell the previous day...} 10. Bc2 c5 11. d4 Qc7 12. Nbd2 Bd7 13. Nf1 $5 cxd4 14. cxd4 Rac8 15. Ne3 Nc6 16. d5 Nb4 17. Bb1 a5 $1 18. a3 Na6 19. b4 Ra8 {Luke McShane shows an impressive devotion to principle, not worrying too much about defending pawns. At this point, I would not be surprised if both players already considered a Black win to be likely.} (19... g6 20. Kh2 Nh5 21. Bd2 a4 22. g3 Ng7 23. g4 Kh8 24. Rg1 Qb6 $14 {McShane,L-Short,N London 2017} 25. Qe2 Nc7 26. Bd3 Qb7 27. Rg2 f5 28. gxf5 gxf5 29. Rag1) (19... axb4 20. axb4 Nxb4 21. Bd2) 20. Bd2 Rfc8 21. Bd3 Qb7 22. g4 (22. Qb1 {Black tends to simply get bad bishops here.} Nh5 {Now we follow another McShane game, this time from the other side of the board, but which was also played in front of the author of these lines.} 23. Bf1 axb4 24. axb4 Nc7 25. Rc1) 22... g6 23. Nf1 $2 (23. Kg2 $11 {is more likely to be an overextension. One thing I noted about the top players in this tournament over the past week was that they want to somehow occupy lots of space without committing that many pawns!} Bd8 {The most popular move, and the engine choice by a long chalk, but it does commit to a Kings' Indian type of position.} 24. Ng1 axb4 25. axb4 Nc7 26. Ne2 Rxa1 27. Qxa1 Ra8) 23... axb4 24. axb4 {White is now slightly worse. Probably Howell had visions of weathering the storm and then grinding a long endgame out with the better structure, but Black is too active for that to become reality.} Bd8 25. Ng3 Nc7 26. Qe2 $2 {The decisive mistake.} Rxa1 $1 27. Rxa1 Ra8 28. Qe1 Nfe8 29. Qc1 Ng7 $1 {Both this move and the next one are quiet, but absolutely lethal.} 30. Rxa8 Qxa8 $1 {Mate in 10, say the engines.} 31. Bh6 Nce8 32. Qb2 Qa4 33. Kg2 {was the only move according to the engines, but this would be nerve-wracking to play after} Bb6 {The point is that Black does not deliver mate after} 34. Bc2 Qa7 35. Bd3 Qa4 36. Ne2 $11 {and must content himself with ...f1 and perpetual check.} Nc7 $5 $15 (36... Qa7 37. Nc3) 37. Nxe5 $1 {reminds Black of his third weak pawn- the one on h5.} dxe5 38. Qxe5 Nce8 39. Bxg7 $11 {White needs some machinery to stay in the game, either on this move or soon, e.g.} Qd1 (39... Nxg7 40. Qb8+) 40. Bh6 Qxd3 $1 $11 41. Qe7 Ng7 42. Ng3 (42. Qxd7 {and now Black can't take the pawn in any of his 3 ways.} Qxe4+ 43. Kf1 $11 Qb1+ 44. Bc1 $18 Qxb4 {is also okay, but a little passive.} 45. d6 $14 {White probably has a little something here if he is just patient about it, but David Howell probably felt it was his lucky day and tried to win without tiebreaks.}) 42... Qc2 {was clearly the intention, even though it is not immediately clear where the mate will come from. For instance:} 43. Qf6 Nf5 44. Qxb6 Nh4+ $19 45. Kh2 Nf3+ 46. Kg2 {and now Black can choose between various moves including ...xb2, ...c5xd5, or ...h5 maintaining both options.} Nh4+ {is the most solid move to keep equality:} 47. Kh2 Nf3+ 48. Kg2 Nh4+ 49. Kh2 0-1


