1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 $5 {Played quickly, and the idea was probably to transpose to a Panov after 4.d4 cxd4 5.exd4 c6 6.c3.} 4. Nxd4 {Played after a great many minutes thought. I remember it amused me during the game that at many points I was actually behind David on the clock, and I then wondered how common this could possibly be. The following round, Luke McShane went even further behind David on the clock, proving my suspicions unfounded.} Bb4+ 5. c3 Be7 6. Nxc6 {The 'backup' idea that I had in mind when playing my 4th move.} bxc6 7. Bc4 d6 (7... Nf6 $146 {was the rather original idea I was thinking about.}) 8. Qb3 (8. Qh5 d5 $5 {This incredibly maximalist try was the main reason I rejected 5.b4! However, the engine thinks I can just take this and probably stand better.} 9. exd5 Nf6 10. Qe2 cxd5 11. Bb5+ Bd7 {should give White enough play, and in any case I rarely mind being material down for approximately adequate compensation.}) 8... Nf6 (8... d5 9. exd5 Nf6 $11 {is a position David would love as White, so it is unsurprising he didn't choose the Black side.} 10. dxc6 $5 {This was my second original idea in the game.} O-O $5 11. O-O Bd6 12. Nd2 Bg4 13. f3 Bf5 $1 $11 {Black has achieved solid equality, and as so often in such cases, his position seems easier to play.} 14. Rd1 Qe8 15. Nf1 Qxc6 $1 $15 {is surprisingly annoying.} 16. Qb5 $5 Qxb5 17. Bxb5) 9. Bxf7+ Kf8 10. e5 (10. Be6 Nxe4 $1 11. Bxc8 $3 {Black has a more pleasant position, even if it is still basically equal.} Qxc8 (11... Nc5) 12. O-O (12. Qc4 Nc5 13. O-O $11 {The position is level, but White will have ever so slightly more structural integrity at the end.} Qe6 14. Qxe6 Nxe6 $11 {is by no means stupid, but it is clear to me that in this position, the better player will emerge with a better position after about 4-5 further moves.} 15. Be3 {deserves attention, but I didn't like the structure after} Kf7) 12... d5 13. Nd2 $11 Nc5 (13... Nxd2 14. Bxd2 Qd7 15. Rae1 Kf7 16. Qc2 c5 17. Re3) 14. Qc2 g6 15. Re1 (15. b4 Ne6 $11 16. Bb2 $5 {occupied my attention for a while, trying to force me to take an IQP anyway.} Kg7 $1 17. c4+ d4 18. Qe4) 15... Bf6 $11 {is also sensible, if a bit counter-intuitive.} 16. b4 Ne6 17. Nf3) (10. Nd2 {as I thought a3 to be quite a useless addition.} d5 11. e5 Kxf7 12. exf6 Bxf6) 10... Ng4 $2 {A fairly significant error after half an hour of thought. Possibly, my opponent was convinced that on psychological grounds I would have to trade the queens, and simply wanted to do so in the best way he could.} (10... dxe5 $1 {It is not clear to me why I didn't choose this move, which is easily the most natural, and which might even give White an edge.} 11. Bc4 (11. O-O $1) 11... Bc5 {Now White gets all kinds of useful developing moves for free, like g3, e3 and e5.} 12. Nd2) (10... Nd7 11. exd6 $14 (11. e6 $1 {The best way to pose questions about the legitimacy of White's quality-over-quantity approach to development.} Nc5) (11. Bh5 Nxe5) 11... Nc5 12. Qc2 Kxf7 13. dxe7 Qxe7+ 14. Be3 $1 $14 {has the potential to go even worse for Black}) 11. Bh5 (11. e6 $11 {was almost certainly best, trying to play either e2 or f4.} Ne5 12. O-O Nxf7 13. exf7 d5) (11. exd6 $1 $132 Bxd6 $11 {was my first thought, but I somehow couldn't countenance leaving development for even one more move, the bishop pair notwithstanding.}) 11... Nxe5 12. O-O $2 {Returning the favour after half a minute of thought...} (12. Bf4 Nd3+ 13. Kd2 Ne5 (13... g6 14. Bh6+ (14. Kxd3 {could still be a bit interesting.} gxh5 (14... Bf5+ 15. Ke2 Rb8 $15 {was something I assessed as lost, but in reality it may not be.}) 15. Bh6+ Ke8) 14... Ke8 15. Bf3 Ne5 16. Bg7 Nxf3+ $19 17. gxf3) (13... d5 14. Kxd3 Rb8 $17 15. Qa4 Bf5+ 16. Ke2 Rxb2+ 17. Nd2 $15 {is a little unpleasant, but White is not a million miles away from setting up some kind of d3, e3 fortress.})) 12... d5 (12... Ba6 13. Re1 Rb8 14. Qd1) 13. Qa4 (13. Bf4 Nd3 14. Bg3 g6 15. Be2 Nc5 16. Qd1 Bf6 17. Nd2 {I assessed this position type as lost, though maybe it still forces Black to find an idea or two. The general idea is that Black plays ...g5-g4, then ...f3-h1 to tie the White king to e3, then ...h5, and finally ...g3. Matters become a little bit complicated if White takes on e5, but not too much. For instance:} Kg7 18. Nb3 Ne4) 13... Bd6 (13... Qd7) (13... Qd6 14. Bf4) 14. Re1 (14. f4 Bc5+ 15. Kh1 Qf6 16. Re1 Ng6 (16... Nf7)) (14. Na3 Qf6) 14... Bf5 (14... Qf6 15. Qxc6) 15. Na3 {Not bad as such, but in practical terms this severely limits my winning potential. Now Black can relax and play for a win in his own time, which he proceeds to do.} (15. Bf4 Qh4 {Now Howell doesn't miss his chance. There isn't any way to keep the pawn.} (15... Qf6 16. Bxe5 Bxe5 17. f4 Bd6 {Simply taking on g4 also wins.} (17... Qh4 18. Rxe5 Qxh5 19. Qxc6) 18. Qxc6) 16. Nd2 Be4 17. Nxe4 Qxf4 18. g3 Qf5 $1 19. Nxd6 cxd6 20. f4 Qxh5 21. fxe5 dxe5 22. Qxc6 $2) 15... Qf6 16. Bf4 g6 {There was also ...b6.} 17. Bxe5 (17. Be2 $2 Kg7) 17... Bxe5 $1 {Correctly noticing that he has to defend d8 with the rook and not just the bishop.} 18. Bg4 Bxg4 19. Qxg4 h5 (19... Kg7 20. Qd7+ Kh6 $6) 20. Qh3 Kg7 21. Nc2 Rae8 22. Nb4 Re7 23. Re3 Rhe8 24. Nd3 Bd6 {There follow some repetitions.} 25. Rae1 c5 26. Rxe7+ Rxe7 27. Rxe7+ Qxe7 28. Qe3 Qxe3 29. fxe3 c4 30. Nf4 c6 31. Kf2 Kf6 32. Kf3 Kf5 33. g3 a5 34. h3 $2 {Very close to losing by force.} a4 35. g4+ hxg4+ $1 {Now White goes on tilt, despite his position not yet being indefensible.} 36. hxg4+ Kf6 37. a3 $2 {In perfect chess, maybe the losing mistake.} g5 38. Ne2 Bc5 39. Ng3 Ke5 40. Nf5 0-1


