1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bf5 $5 {This system with the double fianchetto is a very modern way to play. Black players have also tried the double fianchetto when the pawn would be on e6. Here the pawn is on e7 so this cannot be bad.} 5. Ng3 Bg6 6. h4 {David immediately tries to blunt in the b7 bishop.} h6 {This is the way chess openings are played these days. All minors developed and central pawns remain untouched!} 7. Nf3 {Highly ambitious approach by David.} Nd7 8. h5 Bh7 9. Bd3 $6 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 Ngf6 11. Bf4 {David has sacrificed a pawn and prevented Black from castling. He has no direct point to attack but the general activity and space advantage should be decent compensation.} (11. Bd2) 11... e6 (11... Qa5+ 12. Bd2 Qc7) 12. O-O-O Nd5 13. Bd2 {Of course, it makes sense not to exchange pieces when you have sacrificed material and have a space advantage.} Nb4 (13... Be7 14. Ne4 Qc7 15. c4 N5f6 16. Kb1 O-O-O 17. g3 Nxe4 18. Qxe4 Nf6 19. Qe2 b6 20. Bf4 Bd6 21. Ne5) (13... Qc7 14. c4 Nb4 (14... Nf4 15. Qe4 Nxg2 16. Ne5 Nxe5 17. dxe5 O-O-O 18. Bc3) 15. Qb3 a5 16. a3 a4 17. Qe3 Na6 18. Kb1 Be7 19. d5 Nac5 20. dxe6 fxe6 21. Bb4) (13... Bd6 14. Ne4 Qc7 15. c4 N5f6 16. Nxd6+ Qxd6 17. g3 O-O-O 18. Bf4 Qb4 19. Qe2 Qa5 20. a3) 14. Bxb4 (14. Qb3 a5 (14... Qb6 15. c4 O-O-O (15... Be7 16. c5 (16. Kb1 Na6 (16... c5 17. d5) 17. Qa4) 16... Bxc5 17. dxc5 Nxc5 18. Qa3 Nbd3+ (18... Ncd3+ 19. Kb1) 19. Kb1 Nxf2 20. Be3 Nxd1 21. Bxc5 Qxb2+ 22. Qxb2 Nxb2 23. Kxb2) 16. Ne4 (16. c5 Bxc5 17. dxc5 Nxc5 18. Qa3 Ncd3+ 19. Kb1 Nxf2 20. Bxb4 Rxd1+ 21. Rxd1 Nxd1 22. Bc5 Qb5 23. Nd4 Qc4 24. Qxa7 Qd3+ 25. Kc1 Ne3)) 15. a3 a4 16. Qc4 Nd5 17. Ne4 Qc7 (17... Be7 18. Ne5 O-O 19. g4)) 14... Bxb4 15. Kb1 (15. Qb3 Qb6 16. Ne5 Be7 17. Nxd7 Qxb3 18. axb3 Kxd7 19. Ne4 Kc7 20. Rh3 Rhd8 21. Rg3 Bf8 22. Rf3 Rd7) (15. Ne4 Qe7 16. Ne5 O-O-O 17. Qe2 Nf6 18. f4 Rhe8 19. Rhf1 Kb8 20. Kb1 Ba5 21. g4 Bb6 22. g5 (22. c3) 22... Nxe4 23. Qxe4 f6 24. gxf6 gxf6 25. Nf3 Bc7) 15... Qe7 (15... Qb6 {Let} {In my game against Grandelius Nils where I reached the same position, the game continued:} 16. Ne5 (16. Ne4 Rd8 17. Nfd2 {is the main idea behind this system. The exchange of the f6 and c3 knights is in Black's favour.} O-O 18. Nc4 Qc7) (16. a3 Be7 (16... Bd6 17. Ne4) 17. Rhe1 O-O 18. Nf5 Bf6 19. Nd6 Rad8) 16... Nxe5 17. dxe5 O-O {and now instead of Nc2} 18. Ne4 $14 {gives White a pleasant edge.} Rad8) 16. a3 (16. c3 {White's centre starts to crumble.} Bd6 (16... Ba5 $6 17. Nf5 $1 Qf8 (17... exf5 $18 {and the knight is trapped.} 18. Rhe1) 18. Rhe1 O-O-O) 17. Nf5 $11 {Black has a perfectly fine position.} {White's best option could have been} Qf8 $5 (17... exf5 18. Rhe1 $1)) (16. c4 O-O-O) 16... Ba5 (16... Bd6 17. Nf5 Qf8 (17... exf5 $18 {is simply a crushing attack.} 18. Rhe1 $6 Ne5 $44 {secures the c5 square for the knight but the two bishops + queen will create dangerous threats on the kingside.} 19. Nxe5 $6) 18. Nxd6+ Qxd6) 17. Nf5 exf5 (17... Qf8 18. Ne5 Nf6 (18... exf5 19. Nxd7 Kxd7 20. Qxf5+ $1) 19. Ne3 Bc7 $16 {now that d3 is controlled, b4 will come strongly.} 20. f4 $2 O-O-O $18 21. g4 {trying to prevent b4.} Qe7) 18. Rhe1 Bxe1 19. Rxe1 Qxe1+ 20. Nxe1 $2 {Black gets the time to consolidate.} O-O 21. Qxf5 Nf6 22. Nf3 (22. Nd3 $1 {It's very difficult for humans to assess this position as clearly better for White. Even winning. White is two pawns down but has two extra rooks in play. This could be one way to be sure about your compensation!} Rfe8 {is relatively the best.}) 22... Rfe8 23. g4 (23. Ne5 $5 {In for a penny, in for a pound!} Re6 24. c3 Rae8) 23... Rad8 24. g5 $2 (24. c3 $2 Rd5 $1 $17) 24... Nxh5 $1 {Threatening Rg6 to trap the bishop.} (24... hxg5 25. h6 $18) (24... Rd5 25. Ne5 hxg5 26. h6) (24... Nd5 25. gxh6 gxh6 26. Ne5 $18 Re7 {asks White what exactly is his compensation.} 27. c4 Nb6 28. Qf6 $1 $44 {The knight on b2 cannot really go anywhere.}) 25. Ne5 $4 {A huge oversight by David. Maybe he did not like that Black was able to create threats of his own and panicked.} (25. gxh6 g6 26. Qa5 $13 Rd7 (26... a6 {it seems as if Black has defended all his weaknesses but White has the killer shot with} 27. Qc7 $3 Rb8 28. Ne5) 27. Ne5 Rde7 {was much better and would have given White a strong attack.} 28. Qxa7 Kh7 29. Nd3 Kxh6 $18 30. Nc5 $1 {it was so important to keep up the tempo of the attack and not care about the material.} Rc7 31. c4 $1) 25... f6 $1 {A piece is lost and the rest is very simple.} 26. gxh6 (26. gxf6 Nxf6 27. c3 h5) (26. Ng4 hxg5 (26... fxg5 27. Qg6 $19 {The computer still feels White can fight with} Kf8 $5 28. Qxh5 Re1+ 29. Ka2 Rxd4 30. Ne3) 27. Qg6 Nf4 28. Nxf6+ Kf8 29. Nh7+ (29. Qf5 Re1+ 30. Ka2 gxf6 31. Qxf6+ {A very interesting game and Howell's pawn sacrifice in the opening was surely a good practical attempt as it gave him a winning position on many ocassions but he just couldn't finish Pert off who defended quite stubbornly.} Ke8) 29... Kg8 30. Nf6+ (30. Qxg5 Re1+ 31. Ka2 Rxd4)) 26... fxe5 27. Qxh5 (27. Qxh5 exd4 28. hxg7 Kxg7 29. Qg5+) 0-1


