1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 O-O 5. O-O d6 6. d4 Nc6 7. Nc3 a6 $5 {More usual is the move Nc6 which leads to the main lines of the Mar Del Plata Variation.} 8. Bf4 Rb8 9. Rc1 {Played in the style of Tigran Petrosian. Now Nc5 can be pushed back with b4 as the e4 pawn would not be hanging.} Bg4 (9... b5 10. Nd5 {David hesitates a bit as he doesn't want to give Black activity down the h-file. The engine who fears nothing gives the following winning variation.} (10. cxb5 axb5 11. Nxb5 Rxb5 12. Rxc6 Rxb2) 10... bxc4 11. Nxf6+ exf6 12. Rxc4 Ne7 13. b3 Nd5) (9... Bd7 10. Qd2 b5 11. Nd5 bxc4 12. Nxf6+ Bxf6 13. Rxc4 {From this point onwards both players keep shuffling their pieces. Gormally defends with great tenacity and makes Howell's task as difficult as possible.} e5 14. dxe5 Nxe5 15. Nxe5 dxe5 16. Bh6 Be6 17. Rc2 Qxd2 18. Rxd2 Rfd8 19. b3 g5 20. Rxd8+ Rxd8 21. Rc1 Rd6 22. h4 gxh4 23. gxh4 Bxh4 24. Rxc7 Bg4 25. Be3 Bxe2 26. b4 Kg7 27. a4 Bd8 28. Rc6 Be7 29. Rc7 Bd8 30. Rb7 Kg6 31. b5 axb5 32. axb5 f5 33. b6 h5 34. Rb8 f4 {Finally White decides enough is enough and goes for it. But he hasn't chosen the most ideal moment.} 35. Be4+ Kg5 36. Bc5 Rd1+ 37. Kh2 Bxb6 $1 38. Be7+ Kh6 39. Rxb6+ Kg7 40. Bf6+ Kf7 41. Bxe5 f3 42. Bf5 Rf1 43. Rb7+ Ke8 44. Bd4 Rd1 45. Bf6 Kf8 46. Be6 Bb5 47. Rxb5) 10. b3 h6 11. d5 e5 $6 {The knight on a6 looks a little silly now and Black is left without any King's Indian type like play.} (11... Na5 12. Qd2 Kh7 13. c5) 12. dxc6 {I wonder what was Howell's intention with this move. Because f2-f4 is definitely not such a great idea.} exf4 13. gxf4 $6 (13. cxb7 fxg3 {Gormally realises that he must seek some activity and so, sacrifices a pawn. But it is not going to be sufficient.} 14. hxg3 Rxb7 15. Ne5) 13... Nh5 {Black is able to exchange pieces which will help him come out of his space crunch.} 14. Qd2 bxc6 15. Nd4 Qh4 (15... Bxd4 16. Qxd4 {Taking the open h-file.} c5 17. Qd2 Qh4 18. e3 {White's position is just so easy to play. Black is passive and has no counterplay. While White dances on the light squares.} Nf6) 16. Nxc6 $5 {A very interesting rook lift but the rook doesn't have any occupation on the kingside yet.} Rb6 17. e3 Bh3 18. Bxh3 Qxh3 19. Ne7+ Kh7 $6 {Now the light squared weaknesses will be terribly felt.} 20. f3 $1 (20. Ncd5 Qg4+ 21. Kh1 Qf3+) 20... Re8 21. Ncd5 $1 Rb7 {Black has to retain the bishop but allowing the white bishop to e6 cannot be a pleasant choice.} 22. c5 (22. Nc6 Qd7 23. Na5 Rbb8 24. c5) 22... dxc5 23. Nc6 $6 Qe6 (23... Qd7 24. Rxc5 $1 {The right exchange. Now the remaining minor pieces on the board are completely in White's favour.} Re6) 24. Rxc5 Qd6 (24... Nf6 25. Nxf6+ Qxf6) 25. Rc4 Rb5 26. Rd1 $14 Nf6 27. Nxf6+ Qxf6 28. Ne5 (28. e4 Rh5 29. e5 $6 {it was unnecessary to reroute the knight to b4. It was sitting pretty on d4.} Qf5 30. Qd7 Re6 31. Qd3 Qh3 32. Rd2) 28... Qe7 29. Ng4 {Black's only problem is that the knight on b4 can be removed by the g3 bishop but the e4 knight will always remain untouched.} Rb6 (29... f5 30. Qc1 c5 31. Ne5 Bxe5 32. fxe5 Qxe5 33. Rd3) 30. Re4 Re6 31. Nf2 Qh4 32. Qc2 Qh5 33. Kg2 f5 34. Rxe6 Rxe6 35. Qc5 (35. Qxc7 Rxe3) 35... g5 (35... Rf6) 36. Qxf5+ Rg6 (36... Qg6 37. Qxg6+ Kxg6 38. Ne4 $1 {With this cute little tactic, the knight comes into the game.} gxf4 39. exf4 $11 {Black is no longer worse.} Rc6 40. Kg3) 37. Ng4 $5 {Fixing more pawns on dark squares but to some extent weakening his own king.} (37. Ng4 Z0 38. Rd7 Z0 39. Nf6+) 1/2-1/2


