1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 a6 7. Qf3 (7. a3 b5 8. Nxc6 Qxc6 {1/2 (20) Riazantsev,A (2671)-Grigoriants,S (2594) St Petersburg RUS 2015} 9. Bd3 $5 {is even stronger and White needs to fight for equality. The point is that} Bb7 $2 {does not work due to} 10. O-O $1 $19 Nf6 11. Re1 {and White needs to look hard for compensation there.} Rc8 {was in Ivanisevic-Giri, but Black seems to be fine there:} 12. Qf3 Bd6 13. Bd4 Qc7 14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. Qh5 Be5 16. Nd1 Ke7 17. c3 Rcg8 18. Ne3 Rg5 19. Qh3 h5 20. Qh4 Rhg8 21. g3 $11 {Ivanisevic-Giri 2012} f5 22. exf5 Qc6 23. Nd5+ Qxd5 24. Be4 Qc4 25. b3 Qxc3 26. Bxb7 Bf6 27. Rac1 Qxb3 28. Qe4 Rg4 29. Qe2 h4 30. fxe6 fxe6 31. Rcd1 hxg3 32. fxg3 Rd4 33. Kg2 Rxd1 34. Rxd1 Qxa3 35. Qd2 Qb2 36. Qxb2 Bxb2) 7... d6 (7... Nf6) 8. O-O-O {This is a quite tricky and recently popular line against the Grünfeld. I hadn't played it before and my opponent was visibly surprised as he was spending quite a lot of time in the opening.} Bd7 9. Qg3 Nf6 10. f4 {It's important to start with this move as} b5 11. e5 (11. Bd3 Rc8 12. Kb1 g6 13. Nxc6 Bxc6 14. Bd4 Bg7) 11... dxe5 12. fxe5 Qxe5 {I think that this move is slightly dangerous for Black.} 13. Bf4 $1 Qh5 14. Nxc6 Bxc6 15. Be2 $1 {This is the point. Black faces some unpleasant tension in the centre.} Qc5 {This is a novelty and most probably better than the move which had been played so far.} (15... Qg6 16. Bf3 {with the idea ae8 was a better defence but still Black's position is unpleasant.} Rc8 17. Bxc6+ {trying to keep the knights on the board doesn't make much sense as g4 doesn't improve its position.} {In my opinion it was better to try to keep the knights on the board with} Rxc6 18. Qf3 Nd5 {but still after} 19. Rhe1 {I think White is slightly better due to his space advantage and the very strong pawn on d5, which restricts Black's possibilities. Of course Black can play this position but in the long run most probably it will be unpleasant.} Rxc3 {was played afew times previously, but Black's position is very shaky.} 20. bxc3 Ba3+ 21. Kb1 O-O 22. Be5 Bc5 23. Rxd5 exd5 24. Qxd5 Rc8 25. Qd7 {with a clear advantage for White, as happened in 2 games of GM Maxim Matlakov.} {Two days later I used the same line against GM Baron Tal and he played} Qc6 26. Rd1 f6 27. Qxc6 Rxc6 28. Rd8+ Kf7 29. Bf4 g5 30. Bc1 Bd6 31. g3 {with some pressure, but the position is far from being clear.} Be5 {allows} 32. Bb2 {and now in the event of} Kg6 {Black is clearly OK after} 33. Rd5 $1 Rc4 34. Kc1 h5 35. Rd8 h4) 16. Be3 (16. Bf3 $16 {with serious problems as well.} b4) 16... Qe7 {Exchanging the knights is in White's favour as Black has a bad b7 and if the knights exchange, the b7 problem will get bigger for Black.} 17. Bf3 Qb7 18. Rhf1 Rc8 19. Bd4 b4 20. Bxf6 gxf6 $2 {I think that this is the first quite serious mistake as starting from this move Black follows a wrong plan.} 21. Ne2 Bxf3 22. Rxf3 $1 {A strong move, I take under control the e-file.} f5 23. Nd4 {Now it's clear why ...d6 was a mistake - White threatens c3-b2 and Black's king position is very vulnerable.} Qc7 {Black tries to get some kind of counterplay and activate the b7.} 24. Qg5 $1 {I like this move as it practically puts Black in a very uncomfortable situation, especially in time trouble (David had less than 10 minutes here).} (24. Qf2 $16 {with a big advantage. Now even h4-h5 is coming.} Bc5) 24... h6 $2 {A big mistake, but it was very difficult to decide to play ...f6 with the threat of b2-c3, especially in time trouble!} 25. Qd2 Be7 {This move loses on the spot, but anyway the position was very difficult.} 26. Kb1 $1 $18 {White's queen comes to f6 and Black's position collapses.} (26. Nxf5 exf5 27. Rxf5 Bg5) 26... a5 27. c3 Qb7 28. Ka1 Bg5 29. Qe1 O-O 30. h4 Bf6 31. Qd2 bxc3 32. bxc3 Rb8 {was more stubborn but after} 33. Rff1 Rfd8 34. Rb1 {White is just a pawn up with a huge advantage.} Qd5 {was better but White maintains good winning chances anyway:} 35. Rxb8 Rxb8 36. Qe3 Kh7 {the only move} 37. g4 Bxd4 38. cxd4 Qb5 39. Qf2 Qc4 40. a3 $16 Qc3+ 41. Ka2 Qb3+ 1-0


