1. d4 {This move is David's main weapon, but I also had to get prepared for 1.c4 or 1.f3.} d5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bg5 {The most aggressive choice. My opponent mostly used to play 3.b5, but he also had definite experience in Scotch.} e6 4. e4 dxe4 5. Nxe4 Be7 6. Bxf6 Bxf6 7. Nf3 {This original idea was successfully employed by World Champion Magnus Carlsen. Since his game vs Etienne Bacrot in 2010, White's aggressive setup has gained a lot of popularity.} Nd7 8. Bd3 O-O {That was played rather quickly, since I was familiar with a game of my friend Boris Avrukh, where he went for an attractive queen sac.} 9. Qe2 c5 10. O-O-O {At this moment I was already out of preparation, though this move was played by Vishy Anand 2 years ago. For some reason, I didn't pay much attention to this idea and never analysed the subsequent sharp position.} (10. Nxf6+ Nxf6 $1 (10... Qxf6 $14 {1-0 Darini,P (2479)-Khomeriki,N (2228)/Nakhchivan AZE 2015 (24)} 11. Qe4 $6 g6 $1 12. c3) 11. dxc5 Qa5+ 12. c3 Qxc5 13. O-O b6 $1 $132 14. Rfe1 Bb7 15. Ne5) 10... cxd4 {The most natural move.} 11. g4 (11. Nxf6+ Qxf6 12. Qe4) 11... g6 12. h4 Bg7 $146 {A logical novelty - it definitely makes sense to avoid the pin as soon as possible.} 13. h5 Re8 ({, but after} 13... Nf6 $14 {Black's position looks rather unpleasant.} {Black's position looks dangerous also in the event of} 14. hxg6 hxg6 ({, but after} 14... fxg6 15. Neg5 Qb6 16. Bc4) 15. g5 Nh5 16. Rxh5 gxh5 $36 {As an alternative, I was mainly considering} 17. Rg1) (13... Ne5 14. Nxe5 Bxe5 $36 {Black doesn't get any compensation for an exposed pawn structure.} {The above-mentioned game of my friend saw:} 15. g5 $6 Bf4+ 16. Kb1 Bxg5 17. hxg6 fxg6 {Li,R (2426)-Avrukh,B (2609)/Chicago USA 2015, and Back got promising compensation.} {The somewhat slow} 18. Rdg1 {isn't in the spirit of position, so Black should be fine after} Bf4 19. Qh5 Rf7 20. Rxg6+ Kf8 $1 21. Rg2) (13... Qa5 $1 14. Kb1) 14. hxg6 hxg6 {At this moment I was quite optimstic about my position. However, David's next move completely changed my good feeling...} ({I was also considering} 14... fxg6 {to prevent White from pushing c2-c4, but this move looked awkward, so finally I rejected it. Indeed, after} 15. Neg5 (15. Rxh7 Kxh7 16. Neg5+ {and the vulnerablity of Black's king may tell.} {It was possible to simplify matters by means of} Kg8 17. Bxg6 Re7 18. Bh7+ Kh8 19. Rh1 Qb6 20. Bf5+ Kg8 21. Bxe6+ Kf8) 15... Nf8 16. Nxh7 {White's position should be better, though} Nxh7 $1 17. Bxg6 Ng5 18. Rh5 Nxf3 (18... Nf7 19. Bxf7+ $14 {1-0 Anand,V (2783)-Fressinet,L (2706)/Paris/St Petersburg 2013/CBM 154/[Szabo,Kr] (49)} {Another move which deserves serious attention is} Kxf7 $5 20. Ne5+) 19. Qxf3 Rf8 (19... Re7 20. Rdh1 Rc7 {would offer great drawish chances in the resulting rook ending.} 21. Qf4 $5 {In one preceding game Black lost the important d4 for free after:} d3 (21... e5 22. Bh7+ Kh8 $6 23. Rxe5) 22. Bh7+ Kh8 $6 23. Bxd3+ Kg8 24. Bh7+ Kh8 25. Bg6+ $16 {0-1 Brunello,M (2235)-Markantonaki,H (2150)/Achaia 2013} {In the following high-level game Black did face definite problems after:} Kg8 26. Qh2) 20. Bh7+ Kh8 21. Qh3 Rf4 22. Qh2) 15. g5 $1 {A very strong move! White's plan is based on 16.f3 and d3 or c4, followed by g2-g4 advance. At the same time, the presence of the d5 makes Black's q-side counterplay problematic.} e5 {The most natural move.} 16. Rh4 $1 {Unfortunately, White is just in time to support the strong d5, since 16...dxc3 17.f6+ drops the queen.} Nf8 17. Rdh1 {The most consistent.} Bf5 $2 {Being under serious time pressure, I was trying to activate my pieces at the cost of a pawn, but it is simply wrong.} 18. Qf1 $1 {My opponent correctly accepts the challenge.} Rc8 (18... Bxe4 19. Bxe4 Qd7 20. Qg2) (18... Ne6 19. Bb5 (19. Rh8+ Bxh8 20. Rxh8+ Kxh8 {The resulting position is double-edged, but White should be somewhat better.} {The move} 21. Qh1+ {is weaker:} Kg8 {the threat of 21...g4 practically forces} 22. Nf6+ Kf8 {, so Black gets full positional compensation for a pawn.} {For some reason, I didn't pay much attention to} 23. Bxf5 gxf5 24. Nxe5 Rc8 {, though after} 25. Qh8+ Ke7 26. Ng8+ Rxg8 27. Qf6+ $14 {White is better due to superiority in the centre.} {The most tempting reaction on White's last move would be:} Kd6 $5 28. Nxf7+ Kd7 {trying to get a rid of d5 at any cost. Most probably, this idea wouldn't solve all Black's problems, but it is still playable:} 29. Nxd8 Rcxd8) (19. Nf6+ Bxf6 20. gxf6 Qxf6 21. Rh8+ (21. Bxf5 Qxf5) 21... Qxh8 22. Rxh8+ Kxh8 23. Bxf5 $14 gxf5 24. Nxe5) (19. Qg2 Nf4 $36 20. Qh2 Kf8 21. Rh8+ Ke7 22. Rh7 Rh8 $11) 19... Qc7 $16 (19... Rf8 20. Qg2 (20. Rh8+ Bxh8 $1 {It looks like only this strong move offers White some advantage} 21. Rxh8+ Kxh8 22. Qh1+ Kg8 23. Nf6+ Qxf6 24. gxf6 Rac8) 20... Nf4 21. Qh2 $14 {For some reason, I overestimated the strengh of White's central pawns in the following line:} Nh5 $1 22. Ng3 Qc8 23. Ne1) 20. Bxe8 {is less convincing:} (20. Rh8+ Bxh8 $19 {[%csl Rb3]} {Another way of winning the pawn offers Black much more activity:} 21. Rxh8+ Kg7 22. Rh7+ Kf8) 20... Rxe8 21. Qd1 (21. Rh8+ Bxh8 $14 {My idea would be fully justified only after} 22. Rxh8+ $2 Kg7 23. Rxe8 Bxe4 $1) 21... Rc8) 19. Rh8+ Bxh8 20. Rxh8+ $1 Kxh8 {Unfortunately, Black cannot exploit some delay with development of White's k-side pieces.} 21. Qh1+ (21. Nf6 Bg4 22. Nxg4 (22. Qh1+ Bh5 23. Nxh5 gxh5 24. Qxh5+ $16 {White has a sound extra pawn.} {It would hardly be better choosing:} Kg8 25. g6 Qf6) 22... Nh7 {The most stubborn was:} 23. Qh3 Kg7 24. Qh6+ {- White's position is still winning from the technical point of view, but his plan doesn't look obvious.} {It would be more difficult to make progress after} Kg8 25. Bxg6 fxg6 26. Nf6+ Nxf6 27. Qxg6+ Kh8 28. gxf6 $16 Qc7 29. f7 Re6 30. Qf5 Qxc2+ 31. Qxc2 $18 {After} Rxc2+ 32. Kxc2 Kg7) 21... Nh7 (21... Kg8 22. Nf6+ Qxf6 {The remaining few moves were just an agony.} 23. gxf6 Rc6 $1 (23... Bxd3 24. Qh6 Rxc2+ 25. Kd1 Ne6 26. Ng5) 24. Bxf5 Rxf6 (24... gxf5 {A prosaic choice.} {The most effective way was:} 25. Qh6) 25. Be4) 22. Nf6 Kg7 (22... Qxf6 $1 {David is on top again.} 23. gxf6 Kg8 (23... Bxd3 $1 {The most effective way - the knight is coming into the attack.} 24. Qh6 Rxc2+ 25. Kd1 Rg8 {White doesn't mind exchanging the ''passive'' bishop, since it is the main defender of Black's king.} 26. Ng5) 24. Bxf5 Rc7 25. Qh6 $6 $138 Nxf6 $1 {Now Black's position is completely hopeless - there are no active ideas.} 26. Bxg6 fxg6 27. Qxg6+ Rg7 28. Qxf6) 23. Qh6+ (23. Qh6+ {Any exchanges favour White here, but I had no choice.} Kh8 24. Qxh7#) 1-0


