1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. f3 O-O 6. Be3 c5 7. Nge2 Nc6 8. d5 Ne5 9. Ng3 e6 10. Be2 exd5 11. cxd5 a6 12. a4 h5 13. O-O $1 Nh7 14. Qd2 h4 15. Nh1 f5 16. Nf2 Re8 17. Kh1 Bd7 (17... Rb8) (17... b6 18. exf5 Bxf5 19. Nfe4 Nf7 20. Bd3 Qc8 21. Rac1 Qb7 22. Rcd1 Rac8 23. Qf2 c4 24. Bb1 b5 25. axb5 axb5 26. Bd4) (17... Qf6 18. Rae1 Bd7 19. f4 Nf7 20. e5 dxe5 21. fxe5 Qxe5 22. Bxc5 Bh6 23. Qd1 Qc7 24. Nd3 Bf8 (24... Nf6 25. Bd4 Ne4 26. Nxe4 fxe4 27. Nc5) (24... Nhg5 25. Bd4 h3 26. Nc5 Nd6 27. a5 Nde4 28. N3xe4 Nxe4 29. Nxe4 Rxe4 30. Bf3 hxg2+ 31. Kxg2 Rh4 32. d6) 25. Bxf8 Nxf8) 18. exf5 (18. Rae1 Rb8 {I think I saw this position and I didn't like it. It looks like a good Semi-Slav for Black, he intends to castle long and counter-attack White on the other wing. Still it was better than what happened in the game.} (18... Rc8 19. exf5 Bxf5 20. Nfe4 Nf7 21. Bd3 Ne5 22. Be2 Nf7 23. Bd3 $1 Ne5 24. Be2) 19. exf5 $2 gxf5 20. f4 Nf7 21. Bh5 Qf6 22. Nh3 Qh6 23. Bxf7+ Kxf7 $1 24. Ng5+ Kg8 25. Qd3 Qf6 {is certainly also playable. White should play for f4 of course.} 26. Bc1 b5 27. axb5 Rxe1 28. Rxe1 axb5 29. Qh3 Nxg5 $6 {Bruzon Batista,L (2696)-Holt,C (2556) Arlington 2014} {However} 30. fxg5 $1 $36 {seems more to the point here. White should open the centre and put pressure on Black's shaky pawns.} {Nakamura has experimented with} Qd4 $5 {which also seems perfectly sound as well.} 31. Qf3 b4 $1) (18. Rab1) (18. a5 $1) (18. Rg1) (18. f4 {Karjakin,S (2760)-Nakamura,H (2741) Moscow 2010, and Black was better.} {or} Ng4 (18... Nf7 19. Bd3 Qf6 20. Rae1 {Howell,D (2597)-Nakamura,H (2715) London 2009, with a balanced position.} Rac8) 19. Nxg4 fxg4 20. Rae1 (20. f5 gxf5 21. exf5 Qe7) 20... g3) 18... gxf5 (18... Bxf5 19. Nfe4 $2 Rc8 (19... Nf6 20. Ng5) 20. Bh6 Bh8 21. g4 hxg3 $1 22. Nxg3 Qd7 $17 {Gormally,D (2497)-Fodor,T (2495) Birmingham 2015, with a horrible position for White and I didn't last much longer. Basically it was one disaster of a game, but it demonstrates very well the counter-attacking potential of Black in this line - you need to play very vigorously as White otherwise you can get run over.} (22... Bh3 23. Rg1 Qh4 24. Nce4 Nf7 25. Be3 Re7) 23. Nce4 Nf7 24. Bf4 Nf6 25. Bd3 Nxe4 26. fxe4 Bg4 27. Be2 Ne5 28. Ra3 Rf8 29. Bxg4 Qxg4 30. Nf5) 19. Nh3 (19. Rg1 Qf6 $1 20. g3 hxg3 21. Rxg3 Re7 {and Black is absolutely fine. It's also important to note that} 22. Rag1 $6 {doesn't really work here because of} Kh8 23. Rh3 f4 (23... Nf7 $1 24. Bd3) 24. Nce4 Qf8 (24... fxe3 $1 $40 25. Nxf6 Bxh3 26. Qc2 (26. Qxe3 Ng4) 26... Nxf6 27. Nxh3 Nxd5 28. Ng5 Bh6 {is also unpleasant for Black} {When I was faced with this position myself, I came up with the tentative} 29. Qf5 $6 {here. My opponent was whipping out his moves at a furious rate and looking ultra-confident, and it unsettled me. The problem was also that I couldn't really recall the theory here, and I went into a brain freeze.}) 25. Rxh7+ Kxh7 26. Bxf4) 19... Ng6 20. Rfe1 Qf6 21. f4 Re7 (21... b5 22. axb5 axb5 23. Rxa8 Rxa8 24. Bxb5 Bxb5 25. Nxb5 Qxb2 (25... Rb8 26. Nc3 Qf7 27. Bg1 Rb6 28. Re6 Ngf8 29. Bxc5 $1) 26. Qxb2 Bxb2 27. Nxd6 Nf6 28. Rd1 Bd4 29. Bxd4 cxd4 30. Nxf5 Nxd5 31. Nxd4 Ngxf4) 22. Bh5 Bh6 23. Bf2 Rae8 (23... Rg7 24. Re2 Re8 25. Rxe8+ Bxe8 26. Re1 Bd7 27. a5 Qd8 28. Bxg6 Rxg6 29. Qe2 Qxa5 30. Qe7 Nf8 31. Bxh4 Qb4) 24. Bxg6 {White has manoeuvred pretty well and is now threatening to impose a bind with d4, so Black goes for a freeing advance in the centre, but this hardly improves his prospects either.} Qxg6 25. Bxh4 Rxe1+ 26. Rxe1 b5 27. axb5 $16 axb5 1-0


