1. c4 e6 2. Nc3 d5 3. d4 c5 4. cxd5 exd5 $1 5. dxc5 d4 (5... Nf6 6. Be3 Nc6 (6... Na6 7. Bd4 Bxc5 8. e3) 7. Nf3 Bg4 (7... Qa5 8. a3 Ne4 9. Rc1 Be6 10. g3) 8. Nd4 Rc8 9. Nb3) 6. Na4 (6. Ne4) 6... b5 (6... Nc6) (6... Bxc5 7. Nxc5 Qa5+ 8. Bd2 Qxc5 9. Rc1 Qf5 10. Qa4+ Nc6 11. Nf3 Qd5 12. e3 dxe3 13. Bxe3) 7. cxb6 axb6 8. b3 $5 {This is an interesting sideline, as White develops the queen winning a tempo by both pinning and attacking c6.} (8. e4 $6 Bd7 (8... Bb4+ 9. Bd2 $19 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 Rxa4 11. Bb5+ Bd7 12. Bxa4 $40 {[%cal Gf7f5,Yb6g6,Yc8b7]} Bxa4 $1 {is the right move.} 13. Nf3) 9. b3 b5 $19 {[%csl Ra5][%cal Ge6a6]} 10. Nb2 Nf6 $1 11. Bd3 $2 (11. Qxd4 Nc6 12. Qe3 Bb4+ $1 13. Bd2 $5 Ng4 14. Qf4 g5 15. Qg3 Bxd2+ $1 16. Kxd2 Qa5+ $40) (11. e5 $2 {falls for the nice tactical idea} Ne4 $1 12. Nd3 Nc6) 11... Bb4+ $16 {[%csl Gb7]} {Both retreats of the knight still give Black a pleasant initiative:} 12. Bd2 Ba3) (8. e3 Bb4+ (8... Bd7 9. b3 Bb4+ 10. Bd2 dxe3 11. fxe3 Qh4+ 12. g3 Qe4 13. Bxb4 Qxb4+ 14. Qd2 Qxd2+ 15. Kxd2 Bc6 16. e4 Nd7) 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 Rxa4 11. Bb5+ Bd7 12. Bxa4 Bxa4 13. Qxd4) (8. Qb3 Be6 9. Qb5+ (9. Qc2 Bb4+) 9... Bd7) 8... Nf6 $1 {A nice and active answer. Black should not hesitate in such positions, but instead go for active play.} (8... b5 {Black can immediately launch a strong initiative in the centre:} 9. Nb2 Nf6 10. e3 $1 Nc6 11. Nf3 (11. Bxb5 $40 {[%cal Yc8g4,Ye7h4]} Qa5+ $2) 11... Bb4+ 12. Bd2 $3 Bxd2+ 13. Qxd2 Ne4 14. Qc1 Qa5+ 15. Nd2 $36 {[%cal Gb6g6,Gc8b7,Yd8h4] Although White is 3(!) pawns up, he has almost no pieces developed and faces big problems already; this line is a good example of how active play is far more important than material in such positions.} O-O) (8... Nc6 9. e4 (9. Nf3 b5 $1) 9... b5 $1 $19 10. Nb2 {was played in some games, but I still prefer Black's position.} Nf6 11. Bd2 Rb8 12. Bd3 Ba3 13. Rb1 O-O) 9. e3 $6 {White will soon realise that being materialistic here is not a good choice .} (9. Nf3 b5 10. Nb2 $11 Bb4+ 11. Bd2 $13 {[%cal Ge1c1]} {But} Ba3 {was possibly more precise, as if}) 9... Nc6 (9... Bd7 10. Qxd4 (10. Nf3 b5 11. Nb2 dxe3 12. Bxe3 $17 {[%cal Yf8e8,Ye5e4]} Bb4+ {looks risky:} 13. Bd2 Qe7+ (13... Bxd2+ $1 $40 {[%cal Ge5e4] just increases the pressure on White's camp} {The engine indicates} 14. Qxd2 $1 {trying to solve the problem of the king as soon as possible.} O-O $5 {Avoiding bd2.} 15. Be2 Ne4 $1 16. Qf4 $1 Qa5+ {White's position seems very unpleasant, but he can complicate matters by playing actively:}) 14. Be2 $1 Ne4 15. Bxb4 (15. O-O $1 {[%cal Ye5e4]} Bxd2 16. Nxd2 $1 {[%csl Gc1,Gf1] This advance restricts White's pieces very well, and if White loses patience, for example} Nc3 $6) 15... Qxb4+ 16. Kf1 {Black has no reason to hurry, he can simply improve his position and wait for the right moment.} O-O) (10. exd4 $1 Bb4+ 11. Bd2 $1 Qe7+ $8 12. Be2 (12. Qe2 Bxd2+ 13. Kxd2 Ne4+) 12... Ne4 13. Nf3 Bxa4 14. bxa4 Bxd2+ $1 {The position remains complicated, and the computer ends with the typical computer draw :)} 15. Nxd2 Nc3) 10... Nc6 11. Qb2 (11. Qxb6 Bb4+ 12. Bd2 Bxd2+ 13. Kxd2 Ne4+ $19 {[%cal Gb7a6]} 14. Ke1 {was also good.} Qf6 $5 {looks like a desperate attempt already:}) 11... Ne4 12. Bd3 (12. a3 {It is even harder to suggest a move for White here.} b5 13. Nc3 (13. Bd3 Qa5+ 14. b4 (14. Ke2 $19 f5 $19 {was probably simpler.} (14... Bf5 $2 {would lead to a quick loss:} 15. Qb1) 15. Bxe4 fxe4 16. Nc3 (16. Bd2 Qa6 $19) 16... b4 17. Nxe4 bxa3 18. Qd2 Bb4 {White has some chances of resistance here but he needs to accept a bad position, since} 19. Nd6+ $2 {loses to} Ke7 $1) 14... Qxa4 15. Bxe4 $19 Bxb4+ $2 16. Ke2 $1 O-O) 13... Nxc3 14. Qxc3 {[%cal Yg7g5] and White is defenceless.} b4) 12... Bb4+ (12... Bg4) 13. Ke2 Bf5 {would still offer more resistance.} 14. Bxe4 $142 {was safer.} Bxe4 $142 15. f3 $142 Bd3+ 16. Kf2 O-O {was a clear-cut continuation.}) 10. Bb5 (10. Nf3 b5 (10... Bb4+ 11. Bd2 dxe3 $17 12. Bxb4 Nxb4 13. Qxd8+ $2 Kxd8 $19) 11. Bxb5 $6 Qa5+ 12. Nc3 Qxc3+ 13. Bd2 Qc5 14. Nxd4 $2 Bd7 15. Rc1) 10... Qd5 $1 {My suggestion is that Black should think not about one or two pawns in such positions, but in terms of development and (mainly) piece mobility (like AlphaZero!). White has won a second pawn, but in doing so he gave up the bishop pair and helped Black to solve a potential problem (the a5). On the other hand, by covering the check with the knight Black hits the g5, and the queen can be harassed with moves like ,,,b6 and ...b7. Black is two moves away from completing development, when he will be ready to look for active ideas like advancing the f-pawn. Although White is two pawns up, it looks like he acquired too many practical problems in return, and surviving the middlegame already seems a very difficult task.} 11. Qe2 Ra5 12. exd4+ Kd8 {A natural move and also one that you always want to play in such positions.} 13. Bxc6 Qxc6 14. Bd2 Ba3 $1 {This rook is very annoying.} 15. Nf3 $2 {The problem is that after this move White can hardly find a good place for his king.} Re8 $1 {The pressure on White's camp is very unpleasant now.} 16. Ne5 Qxg2 17. Bxa5 $6 {It is not easy to suggest how White should play, but this move normally creates new targets for Black.} bxa5 $1 {Howell immediately spots the new weakness.} (17... Qxh1+ 18. Kd2 Qxa1 19. Bxb6+ Ke7 $2 {Unnecessary.} 20. Ng6+ Kd6 21. Bc5+ Bxc5 22. dxc5+ Kc7 {Things have even changed now and the advantage is with White.}) 18. Kd2 (18. Rf1 Bh3 19. Kd2 Ne4+ 20. Kc2) 18... Ne4+ $1 19. Ke3 $2 (19. Kc2 Bf5) 19... Nd6 20. Kd2 f6 21. f3 Bb4+ {Black is already completely winning, and the only explanation for the game lasting so long from this point is the short time control which probably made Howell's task harder.} 0-1


[Event "FIDE Grand Swiss"]
[Site "Riga"]
[Date "2021.11.06"]
[Round "10"]
[White "Firouzja, Alireza"]
[Black "Howell, David"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "E24"]
[WhiteElo "2770"]
[BlackElo "2658"]
[Annotator "Giri,Anish"]
