{[%evp 0,113,80,27,39,18,17,12,12,12,19,15,17,23,29,-6,5,-4,13,-20,-12,-14,6,-16,-7,3,1,1,11,4,3,9,18,10,21,3,19,-41,-26,-34,-3,-36,-8,-8,34,22,48,0,24,13,27,30,13,13,26,48,111,132,132,115,132,122,132,69,74,68,63,90,90,92,102,100,98,98,95,101,94,85,99,88,91,103,106,107,112,110,112,112,112,109,151,163,164,161,190,185,190,194,227,250,246,250,245,253,253,253,254,269,289,298,301,307,307,320,315,321]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 {Italian is a frequent guest in the practice of modern top players and Firouzja's is no exception there.} Bb4 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 c5 {Many players these days prevent Bg5 at the first possible opportunity. This also has downsides, but perhaps this is not a moment for one of my favourite lectures- the lecture on the Italian move order subtleties.} (5... d6 6. e4) 6. f3 (6. e3 b6) 6... Nc6 (6... d5) 7. e4 d6 8. Be3 {This is not neccessary here and there is also quite some point in the 8.bd2 move order, intending to save on the move h3, after, for example, 8.bd2 a5 9.f1.} b6 {I believe it was Eljanov, who was one of the first players to introduce this system to high level practice. As space started to get more appreciated by the modern engines and therefore also modern players, the system with a5, limiting the queenside expansion with b4, has gained in popularity.} (8... Qa5 9. Kf2) 9. Bd3 {One disadvantage of 8...a5 over 8...a6, is that White doesn't have to address the positional threat of a5 and can focus on development without wasting a tempo on a4 or b3.} e5 (9... Na5 10. Nh3 (10. Ne2 Qc7) 10... e5 11. Nf2 Ba6) 10. d5 {Another disadvantage of 8...a5 system, is that it weakens the b5 square, where the bishop can relocate itself.} (10. Ne2 Na5 11. Ng3) 10... Na5 {A decent side-system, which is a sound alternative to the complex main-line 10...b8!?, where the queen gets into the game via the a7-square. That system has a good reputation, but is very complex and double edged. What David does instead, is simpler, intending to tranfser the c6 knight to g6 via e7 and expand on the queenside with c6-b5-a5.} 11. Ne2 Kd7 12. O-O {It made sense to start with 12.d4 as well, but then White had to deal with 12...exd4 13.cxd4 d5 14.e5 e4 15.g3 c5 sequence, typical for this line, that happened in Tabatabaei-Sevian 2020.} (12. f4 Ng4) (12. g4 Kc7 13. h4) 12... Kc7 13. f4 (13. h3 Nd7) 13... Ng4 14. Bd2 exf4 {Grabbing space on the queenside. The point of this setup for Black, is that while he does give White the opportunity to stabilise a strong centre after 15.d4, the queenside expansion with b5-a4 had made sure that Black has some queenside space and if White is to challenge it with b3 and c4, a lot of trades will happen, leading to simplifications, that are favorable for Black, the side that has less space in the centre.} (14... f5) 15. Bxf4 f6 16. Nd4 Ne5 (16... cxd4 17. cxd4) 17. Nb5+ Kb7 {The bishop is generally better placed on b6, anticipating the typical b3 push and the opening of the a-file with axb3 axb3.} 18. Bxe5 $5 {An interesting concept that I hadn't come across before. Usually White would fight for the queenside space and squares with b4/b3, leading to a lot of trades. Alireza solves the issue of the hanging a2 pawn differently, weakens the light squares further, but does keep literally all the pieces on the board and thus more pressure on the opponent.} dxe5 {Alternative and possibly a clearer plan would have been 17...c7, preparing d5, with mass simplifications in the centre to follow.} 19. d6 {Introducing the c3-c4 break idea.} (19. a4 a6 20. Na3 Ka7 21. Nc2) 19... Rb8 {Black starts being clever here. Very possible was not to be too deep about things and just bring the a8 rook towards the center- Rad8, hinting at the d5 break.} (19... Be6 20. Nc7 Qxd6 21. Nxa8 Rxa8 22. Qf3) (19... a6 20. Nc7 Rb8 21. Be2 Qd7 22. Ra2 Rd8 23. Rd2 Ka7) 20. Be2 Be6 {Moving out of the c-file and intending to meet 21.c4 with 21...bxc4 22.Bxc4 and 22...d5.} 21. Nc7 {It was hard to improve the position further and White decides that it is a good time to start some action.} Bf7 (21... Qd7 22. Nxe6 (22. Rf3) 22... Qxe6 23. Bg4 Qxc4 24. Qc2) 22. Rb1 (22. Rf3 Nxc4 (22... Qd7 23. Rg3 Rhg8 24. Nd5 Qxd6 25. Rd3 Qf8 26. Ne7 Rh8 27. Rd7+ Ka8 28. Nd5 Rb7 29. Nc7+ Kb8 30. Na6+ Ka8 31. Ra2) 23. Rd3 Nb2 24. Rd2 Nxd1 25. Ba6+ Kc6 26. Bb5+ Kb7) 22... Qd7 $1 {Creating tension in the center.} (22... Nxc4 23. Bxc4 Bxc4 24. Qa4 (24. Rf2 Qd7 25. a4 Rhd8 26. Rd2 Qc6) 24... Qxd6 (24... Bxf1 25. Rxf1 Qxd6 26. Nb5) 25. Rfd1 Qc6 26. Qxc4 Qxc7 27. Qd5+ Qc6 28. Qf7+ Ka6 29. a4 (29. Rd7 Rb7 30. Rxb7 Qxb7 31. Qc4+ b5 32. Qe2 Ka5 33. c4 a6) 29... Qxe4 30. a5 bxa5 31. Ra1 Qe3+ 32. Kh1 Qxc3 33. Rdc1 Qb2 34. Qd5 Rhd8 35. Qxc5 Qd2) 23. Bg4 {Neither 23.exd5 cxd5 nor 23.dxe5 Nxe4 promise anything clear for White, so instead he maintains the tension.} (23. Nd5 Qxd6 (23... Rbd8) 24. Nxf6 Qxd1 25. Rbxd1 Bxc4 26. Bxc4 Nxc4 27. Rd7+ Ka6 28. Rxg7) (23. Rb5 Rhd8 (23... Nxc4 24. Qa4 Nxd6 25. Rxb6+ Kxc7 26. Qxa7+ Rb7 27. Rxb7+ Nxb7 28. Rb1 Qc6 29. a4 c4 30. Kf1) 24. Qa4 Qxd6 25. Nd5 Ka8) 23... Qc6 $6 {So far Black has done quite okay, but the next phase of the game goes badly wrong for him.} 24. Be6 {White's pieces are ready to activate themselves and Black had to realize that this is a point of no return.} Bxe6 $2 {Too submissive. Now White gets the time he needs to regroup and go on the offensive.} (24... Rhf8 {White regains the piece, but is not fighting for any advantage here, as for example 27...b3!? leads to a comfortable endgame for Black, by force.} 25. Qd3) 25. Nxe6 $1 {Now the direct threat is d6 and at the same time, White is ready to up the heat with d4 coming up next.} Nxc4 26. Qg4 Rhg8 $2 {Black doesn't have a good response to 27.d4, so he had to take with the knight instead.} 27. d7 $1 (27. Rfd1 Ne3 (27... Nxd6 28. Rd5) 28. Qh5 Qe8 {White is quite simply winning, as the d4 bishop is unopposed and the attack is absolutely free, besides the large positional advantage.} (28... Nxd1 29. Qf7+ $1 {A positional pawn sacrifice- the point behind the 23...c5! break. The c5 pawn is in fact doomed and will eventually get surrounded and picked up.} Ka6 {Probably best, going for complications that will likely lead to lots of simplifications.} 30. Rxd1 Qa4 31. Rd5) 29. Nxc5+ {This might have been Black's idea, but now the shot on g7 or h6 is even more powerful.} Ka8 30. Qxe8 Rgxe8 {And Black's position crumbles.} 31. d7 {Here Black at least gets to activate his f6 knight, which gives chances for counterplay.} Nxd1 32. dxe8=Q {The knight on f4 is also doing stuff and it turns out that capturing the g7 pawn leads to a mess that is quite favourable for Black.} Rxe8 33. Rxd1 {now 29.xg7 c5! as well as 29.xg7 xf5 30.xf5 d8! 31.Rc3 c5! gives Black a lot of counterplay, hitting the g2 pawn, but the simple and strong 29.f1! maintains some advantage, thought after 29...e5 30. xe5 xe5 Black is still in the game.} bxc5 $1 {Black had to create counterchances here and play more concrete. This move not only hits the g3 knight, but also guards the d6 square and now Ndf5 is no longer the same. Black is doing fine here, though the position is yet to clarify.} 34. Rd7 $1 {This was a strong shot here, when the position would be very double edged and White would have to show quite some accuracy here too, in order not to get into some trouble.}) 27... Ne3 {This natural attempt to neutralize the d4 bishop has two tactical flaws.} 28. Qh3 {This shot works quite well, but the computer points out that the simple 28.xe5! was even more efficient.} (28. d8=N+ {The h5 pawn drops as well.} Rbxd8 $1 {Would actually still keep the game going. There is a threat of d4 followed by Rb8, while if White goes 36.Bd3 now, there is a strong reply 36...Be5!.} 29. Nxd8+ (29. Qxg7+ Rxg7 30. Nxd8+ {Black has quite some material for the queen. Now White has a strong sequence.} Kc7 $1 31. Nxc6 Nxf1 $1 {a simple double attack on the f7 and h6 pawns.} 32. Nxa7 (32. Rxf1 Kxc6 $1 {This is actually even cleaner.} 33. Rxf6+ Kb5 {White regains the exchange and ends up strategically winning, thanks to the powerful bishops.}) 32... Nd2 {and White is the one playing for a win here, but with some accurate play, Black is likely able to setup a succesful defense here.} 33. Re1 {Was obviously the way to go, with a winning advantage, though work still had to be done after} Nf3+) 29... Rxd8 $1 {And as Black will trade the dark squared bishops, White will still have quite some trouble converting this  (perhaps it is even holdable, objectively), as the b2 pawn will need protection.} 30. Qxg7+ {Now the variation is forced-} Rd7 31. Qxf6 Nxf1 32. Qxf1 (32. Qxc6+ {Is also a decent attempt at fighting on.} Kxc6 33. Rxf1 Kb5) 32... Qxe4 33. Re1 Qf4 {This endgame is terribly unpleasant for Black, but there are some drawish tendencies, thanks to the opposite coloured bishops and the fact that White hasn't yet mobilised his king.}) 28... Nxf1 29. Rxf1 {The tactics work for White, as he basically ends up up a pawn.} Qxe4 (29... Rbd8 30. Rd1) 30. Qh5 (30. Rd1 Qe2 (30... Rbd8 31. Nxd8+ Rxd8 32. Qe6 Qc6 33. Rd6) 31. Qf3+ Qxf3 32. gxf3 Rbd8 33. Rd6) 30... Rgd8 31. Rd1 $2 {Trying to be clever almost backfired, as Firouzja overlooks a cute tactic, that doesn't win for Black only thanks to a very fortunate save.} g6 $1 {A beautiful resource, based on the back rank theme (Rxc6 Re1+). Now if White moves the rook, Black would remain up a piece, but fortunately for White he still has a way to keep the largest portion of his advantage.} (31... Qa4) 32. Qxh7 $1 Qe2 $2 {The alternatives were offering better chances to save the game.} 33. Rb1 {White ends up up a pawn in an endgame.} (33. Rf1 Qe3+ 34. Rf2 Qd3) 33... Qc2 34. Rf1 Qd3 35. Nxd8+ {White is just up a pawn and has almost stabilsed. There was still a way for Black to fight on here.} Rxd8 $2 {The final mistake, closing the a1-h8 diagonal, making the b2 pawn breath a sigh of relief, as Be5 is no longer an idea.} 36. Qe7 $1 {Now Black is done, as the h6 pawn needs protection and 37.d3 is queued up.} Rxd7 37. Qxf6 {Black had to be in time with Bd6-Rb8, but now the c8 rook is practically trapped for a trade and the bishop endgame is dead lost, slowly but surely.} Qxc3 38. Qxg6 {Black is down a pawn and is completely helpess here. Firouzja converts smoothly.} Qe3+ 39. Kh1 c4 40. Qe6 Qd3 41. Kg1 {The king is slowly making its entree.} c3 42. Qxe5 c2 43. Rc1 Qd1+ 44. Kf2 Qd2+ 45. Kg3 Rd3+ 46. Kh4 {All black pawns are weak and it is the d4 pawn that is falling first.} Qxg2 1-0


