1. c4 c5 (1... Nf6 2. Nc3 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 O-O 5. e4 d6 6. Nge2 c5 {1-0 Caspi,I (2427)-Kantsler,B (2468)/Israel 2010} 7. O-O {should also leave White with some advantage, as the exchange of dark-squared bishops is surely in his favour:} Nc6 8. d3 Rb8 9. h3 Ne8 10. Be3 Nd4 11. Rb1 Bd7 12. b4 b6 13. a4 $14 a5 14. Bxd4 cxd4 15. Nb5 e5 16. bxa5 $36 bxa5 17. Qd2 Bc6 18. f4 Nf6 19. f5 Nd7 20. Ra1 Nc5 21. Ra3 Bf6 22. fxg6 fxg6 23. h4 Rb7 24. Nc1 g5 25. Nb3 Nxb3 26. Rxb3 gxh4 27. gxh4 Rbf7 28. Qh6 Bxh4 29. Rxf7 Rxf7 30. Nxd6 Rf6 31. Qxh4 {Ponomariov,R (2727)-Vallejo Pons,F (2629)/Linares 2002} Qxd6 32. c5 Qf8 $18 33. Rb8 Qxb8 34. Qxf6 Qc7 35. Kh2 Bxa4 36. Bh3 Be8 37. c6 Bf7 38. Be6 Bxe6 39. Qxe6+ Kf8 40. Qf6+ Ke8 41. Qe6+ Kd8 42. Qf6+ Ke8 43. Qe6+) 2. g3 Nc6 3. Bg2 g6 4. Nc3 Bg7 5. Nf3 e5 {One of the sharper Taimanov lines, which White has to play carefully against to have any hope of advantage. Systems with g3, e2 and e3 are not very good now, so to start with White should play d3.} 6. d3 Nge7 7. Bg5 f6 (7... h6) 8. Bd2 d6 9. O-O Be6 10. a3 $1 Qd7 $5 $146 {Black doesn't have an easy time of it however he plays:} 11. Rb1 O-O (11... Rc8 12. b4 b6) 12. b4 cxb4 13. axb4 $1 {A very significant move, which makes the a6-pawn vulnerable for the rest of the game. Initially, it provokes a forced sequence.} d5 14. b5 Nd8 15. Na4 Bf7 (15... dxc4 16. Nc5 Qc8 17. Nxe6 (17. Bb4 Rf7 18. Ne4 Nd5 19. Nd6 Qc7 20. Nxf7 Nxf7 21. dxc4 Qxc4) 17... Nxe6 (17... Qxe6 18. dxc4 {Caspi,I (2460)-Paljusaj,E (2316)/Rijeka 2010 1-0 (31)} Qxc4 19. Bb4 Qe6 20. Nd2 f5 21. Qb3 Qxb3 22. Rxb3 Bf6 {½-½ Haimovich,T (2425)-Kantsler,B (2487)/Herzliya 2008} 23. Rd3 a5) 18. Bb4 Rf7 19. Rc1 Qe8 20. dxc4 a5) 16. Bb4 Re8 17. Nd2 b6 (17... f5 18. Nc5 Qc8 19. Qa4) (17... e4 18. Nc5 Qc7 19. dxe4 dxc4 20. Rc1 a5 21. Ba3) 18. Bxe7 Rxe7 19. Nc3 e4 $1 {A spirited attempt to get counterplay and probably the only good move} 20. Nxd5 Bxd5 21. cxd5 exd3 22. d6 dxe2 (22... Qxd6 $16 23. Nc4 Qd4 24. Bxa8 Qxc4 25. exd3) 23. Qb3+ Nf7 (23... Rf7 $16 24. Rfe1 Rc8 $1 25. Bd5) 24. dxe7 {Howell's play with the king from now on is extraordinary.} exf1=R+ 25. Nxf1 Re8 26. Bc6 Qxe7 27. Bxe8 Qxe8 28. Ra1 (28. Rc1) 28... Qd7 29. Rd1 $1 {With both players getting short of time this is a very courageous decision.} Qe8 $2 $138 30. Rc1 {He finally gets around to playing b1 and it is almost immediately decisive.} Qd7 31. Ne3 $1 f5 32. Nd5 Be5 33. Rc7 Qxc7 34. Nxc7 {The killer blow.} Bxc7 35. Qa2 Bd6 36. Qxa7 $18 Bc5 37. Qd7 Kg7 38. Qe6 Bd4 39. Kg2 $18 Bc5 40. f3 h5 41. h3 $1 Bd4 (41... Ng5 42. Qe5+ Kf7 (42... Kh6 {is just no good.} 43. Qf4) 43. Qc7+ (43. Qh8 Ne6 {lets Black off the hook, to an extent.}) 43... Kf6 (43... Ke6 44. Qg7 $1) (43... Ke8 44. Qg7) 44. Qd8+ Be7 45. Qxb6+) 42. Qc4 $18 Bc5 $1 43. Qc3+ Kh7 44. Qf6 Nd6 {was the way to keep the game going.} 45. Kf1 Ne8 46. Qf7+ Ng7 47. Ke2 $132 Bd4 48. Kd3 Bf2 49. g4 fxg4 50. fxg4 Bc5 51. Ke4 Bg1 52. Ke5 $13 Be3 {again.} 53. Qd7 $1 {looks pretty good too:} Kh6 54. Kf6 Bg5+ 55. Kf7 $16 hxg4 56. hxg4 1-0


