1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 {An old move-order trick which may confuse the Najdorf or Dragon specialist.} Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nxd4 Bb4 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. Bd3 d5 8. exd5 Qe7+ {The parting of the ways, where White can choose from 9.0-0-0, 9.c4 or 9.g4, all of which require Black to respond accurately.} 9. Qe2 Qxe2+ 10. Kxe2 cxd5 11. Nb5 Kd8 12. Rd1 c6 $5 {From the games below one would think that this is a drawing weapon. Is the Dragon really reduced to such methods?} 13. Nd4 Re8+ (13... Kc7 14. c4 (14. Bf4+ Kb7 15. f3 Bd7 16. Nf5 Nh5 17. Bc1 g6 18. Nd4 Rae8+ 19. Kf1 Bd6) 14... Bd6 15. h3 Bd7 16. Kf1 c5 (16... Rhe8 17. cxd5 Nxd5) 17. Nc2 d4 18. b4 cxb4 19. Bb2 Rhe8 20. Bxd4 a5 21. Re1) 14. Kf1 Kc7 (14... Bd7 15. Bg5 (15. c4 Ke7 16. Bg5 h6 17. Bh4 g5 {½-½ Antipov,M (2379)-Kargin,A (2400)/Budapest 2011/CB15_2011} 18. Bg3 dxc4 19. Bxc4 {is another way, but in all these lines, one gets the impression that Black has slightly the worse of things without any winning chances whatseoever.} Ne4 20. Bd3 Nxg3+ 21. hxg3 Bc5 22. Be4 Bxd4 23. Rxd4) 15... h6 16. Bxf6+ gxf6 17. Bf5 Re5 18. Bxd7 Kxd7 19. c3 Bd6 20. Nf3 Re4 21. Rd4) 15. c4 (15. Bf4+ Bd6 16. Bxd6+ Kxd6 {is clearly better for White.} 17. c4 Bd7 18. b4 $16 c5 $1 19. bxc5+ Kxc5 20. Be2 (20. Nb3+ Kd6 21. Rac1 Ba4 22. cxd5 {½-½ Saric,I (2637)-Cvitan,O (2498)/Stari Mikanovci 2011} Rac8 23. Rd2 Rxc1+ 24. Nxc1) 20... Ba4 {Is this position so bad for Black?} 21. Nb3+ {shuts off the white queen unnecessarily:} Kd6 22. Bf3 Re5 23. Rd4 Bc6 24. Na5 Rc8 25. Rad1 Ba8 $1 $132 {A queen sortie which often crops up in this line.} 26. cxd5 Ree8 27. Nc6 Bxc6 28. dxc6+ Kc7 29. Rd7+ Kb6 30. Rb7+ Ka6 31. Rd3 Re5 32. Ra3+ Ra5 33. Be2# {½-½ Alekseev,E (2688)-Lintchevski,D (2539)/Olginka 2011}) 15... Ba6 (15... g6 {Nice technique from David Howell towards the end.} {Let's check the winning method after the exchange of queens:} 16. Bg5 Ne4 17. Bf4+ Bd6 18. Bxd6+ Nxd6 19. cxd5 cxd5 20. Rac1+ Kd7 21. Bb5+ Nxb5 22. Nxb5 Re5 23. Nc7 Rb8 24. Nxd5 Ke6 25. Rc6+ Kd7 26. Rc3 Ba6+ 27. Kg1 Be2 $18 28. Rd2 Ke8 $18 29. f4) (15... Bg4 16. f3 Be6 17. Bf4+ Kb7 18. Rac1 Rac8 19. c5 Ba5 20. b4 Bc7 $16 21. Bxc7 $1 Kxc7 22. b5 Bd7 23. a4 Re7 24. Rb1 Rb8 25. Rb3 Nh5 26. Rdb1 $16 Nf4 27. Bf5 Ne6 28. Bxe6 fxe6 29. f4 {½-½ Friedel,J (2531)-Sedlak,N (2580)/Amsterdam 2011. Maybe a result which was mutually convenient for both players, but it certainly gives a misleading view of the position.} {I really do not understand the repetition as} g5) 16. Bf4+ $1 {The only really critical move and now Black must justify the pawn sacrifice.} Kb7 17. Rac1 $1 (17. cxd5 Bxd3+ 18. Rxd3 Nxd5 19. Bg3 Re4 20. Rc1 Rae8 {Centralization increases the advantage.} 21. Rdd1 Rc8 22. a3 Bf8 23. Rd3 g6 24. Nb3 Ra4 25. f3 Re8 26. Be1 Re6 27. Na5+ Kb6 28. Rb3+ Ka6 29. Rxc6+ Rxc6 30. Nxc6) 17... Rac8 18. c5 Re4 {Black has activity and a slight lead in development to compensate him for the pawn.} 19. Bxa6+ Kxa6 $6 {Although played by Sedlak in the game below, I think this is a mistaken and over-optimistic move. Black must regain the pawn and hope that his disadvantage isn't too great:} 20. Bd6 Ba5 21. f3 Ree8 22. Rd3 Bc7 23. Bxc7 {Forcing a sacrifice} Rxc7 24. Rb3 Rcc8 25. Rcc3 Rb8 26. Ra3+ Kb7 27. Rcb3+ Ka8 28. Nxc6 Rb7 {Can Black hold this position? It seems unlikely.  Although it will take White quite some time to organise his game and protect his king from checks, an eventual mop-up of the black queenside is inevitable.} 29. Nd4 Rc7 30. c6 Rce7 31. Rb5 Re1+ 32. Kf2 Rd1 33. Rb7 1-0


