1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Be7 5. Bf4 O-O 6. e3 Nbd7 7. Be2 dxc4 8. O-O c5 9. dxc5 Nxc5 10. Bxc4 $5 {Not an especially bad move, but one hardly likely to give Pirc players sleepless nights. White unpreteniously develops.} Qxd1 $1 {Aronian shows that Black does not always have to make slow preparations to make progress on the queenside. Black now has a direct threat of ...c4, followed by ...b5 etc.} 11. Rfxd1 $5 {Both players had a different opinion of this advance in the press conference after the game. Aronian felt it was dubious, while Howell felt it was better for White. Probably it is somewhere in between.} b6 12. Nd4 Bb7 13. f3 Rfc8 14. Rac1 a6 ({The normal "sweeper sealer" idea of} 14... Ncd7 {does not make much sense here (for one thing white does not have a knight on e4.)} 15. Ncb5 $17 e5 16. Nf5) 15. a3 Nh5 (15... Kf8 16. Ba2 (16. b4 Ncd7) (16. e4 Ncd7 $1 17. Nxe6+ fxe6 18. Bxe6 Rd8 {Black's game plays itself. He has complete control of the dark-squares, while the knight on a6 is in danger of being stranded.} 19. Bc7 Bc5+ 20. Kf1 Re8 21. Bxd7 Re7 22. Na4 Rxd7 23. Nxb6 Bxb6 24. Bxb6 Rxd1+ 25. Rxd1 Rc8) (16. Bf1 Nh5) 16... Ke8 17. e4 $1 b5 18. b4 Ncd7 19. Nb3 $1) (15... Ncd7 16. Ba2 e5 17. Nf5 {0-1 Muzychuk,A (2528)-Cheparinov,I (2664) Aix-les-Bains 2011}) 16. Be5 Nf6 17. Bg3 Kf8 18. e4 Ke8 19. Bf1 (19. Rc2 b5 20. Bf1 {is also fairly unclear.} (20. Ba2 $6 {This looks slightly awkward. I can only imagine that the strong Ukrainian player Anna Muzychuk was not particularly familiar with this opening.} Nfd7 $5 {Cherapinov first plays to restrain, and only later to destroy.} 21. b4 Na4 22. Nxa4 Rxc2 23. Nxc2 bxa4)) (19. e5 Nh5 20. Bf2 Nd7) (19. Ba2 Nh5 $1 {The white center has an unwieldy look, while by contrast the black position is very compact and contained.} 20. Bf2 Nf4) 19... g6 20. Bf2 (20. Rc2 b5 (20... Nh5 21. Bf2 e5 22. Nde2 Nf6 23. b4 Ncd7) 21. b4 Ncd7 (21... Na4 22. Nxa4 Rxc2 23. Nxc2 bxa4 24. Ne3 a5 25. bxa5 Bc5 26. Bf2 Rxa5 27. Nc4 Bxf2+ 28. Kxf2 Ra7 29. Nd6+ Kf8 30. Bb5) 22. Nb3 Bd8 23. Bf2) 20... e5 {The game is close to equal now and after a few adventures ended in a draw.} 21. Nc2 Nb3 22. Rb1 b5 23. Ne3 Rd8 24. a4 Nd2 25. axb5 Nxb1 26. Rxb1 Bc5 27. Nc4 Bxf2+ 28. Kxf2 axb5 29. Nxb5 Kf8 30. Nxe5 Bxe4 31. fxe4 Nxe4+ 32. Kg1 Nd2 33. Rc1 Ra2 34. Na3 Rxb2 35. Nac4 Nxc4 36. Nxc4 Rc8 37. Ra1 Rc2 38. Ne5 Rc1 39. Rxc1 Rxc1 1/2-1/2


