1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 dxc4 $5 {This is clearly the move I would prefer to play myself although it involves more risk than the alternative ...d7.} 5. e4 Bb4 6. Bg5 c5 7. Bxc4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 {A solid move but also a bit time-consuming.} Qa5 10. Bb5+ Bd7 11. Bxf6 gxf6 $6 12. Bxd7+ Nxd7 13. O-O a6 14. Rb1 Qc7 15. Qh5 Nc5 16. Rb4 Qe5 17. Qh6 ({The rook lift} 17. Qxe5 {intending ...e6 next is also interesting.} fxe5 18. Nb3 Nxb3 19. axb3 O-O-O 20. f4 exf4 21. Rc4+ Kb8 22. Rxf4 Rd7 (22... Rd1+ 23. Kf2 Rd2+ 24. Kf3 Rhd8) 23. Rd4 Rc7 24. Rd3 Rg8 25. Kf2 a5 26. c4 Ka7 27. Rh3 Rg7 28. Rh5 Ka6 29. Rfh4 a4 30. bxa4 Rxc4) (17. Qh4 Qg5 (17... Rd8 18. Nf3 Qxc3 19. e5 Rg8 (19... f5 20. Rc4 Qa5 21. Ng5 Ne4 22. Rxe4 fxe4 23. Qf4 Rf8 24. Nxh7 Rh8 25. Ng5 Rf8 26. Nxe4) 20. Qxh7 Ke7 21. Rf4 f5 22. Qh4+ Ke8 23. g3 Ne4 24. Rxe4 fxe4 25. Qxe4 Rd5 26. Qf4 Qc2 27. Ng5 Qf5 28. Qxf5 exf5 29. Nh7 Rg6 30. Nf6+ Rxf6 31. exf6 Rd6 32. Re1+ Kf8 33. Re5 Rxf6) 18. Qh3 Rg8 (18... Qe5 19. Qh4 Qg5 20. Qh3 Qe5 21. Re1 Rd8 22. Qe3 Rg8 23. Nf3 Qc7 24. Rd4 Nd7 25. Red1 Ke7 26. g3) (18... h5 19. Rc4 (19. f4 Qg4 20. Qe3 Rg8 21. Rb2 Rc8 22. Rd2 h4 23. Nf3 h3 24. g3 Kf8 25. Rd4 Kg7 26. Rfd1) 19... Rc8 20. Nb3 b6 21. Nxc5 Rxc5 22. Qd3 O-O 23. f4 Qg6 24. f5 Qg5 25. Rxc5 bxc5 26. Qxa6 (26. Kh1) 26... Qe3+ 27. Kh1 Qxe4 28. Qd6 Ra8) 19. g3 (19. Rc4 b5 20. Rxc5 Qxc5 21. Nxe6 fxe6 22. Qxe6+ Kf8 23. Qxf6+ Ke8 24. Qe6+) 19... h5 20. Rc4 Rc8 21. Nb3 b6 22. Nxc5 Rxc5 23. f4 Qg4 24. Qxg4 hxg4 25. Rxc5 bxc5 26. Rb1 Kf8 27. f5 Kg7 28. fxe6 fxe6 29. Rb6 e5 30. Rxa6 Rd8) (17. Qf3 Rd8 18. Nb3 Nxb3 19. axb3 b5 (19... Rd7) 20. Qe3 O-O 21. Rd4 a5 22. f4 Qh5 (22... Qc5) 23. Qd3 Rxd4 24. Qxd4 Qg6 25. Ra1 (25. Rf3 Kh8 26. Rg3 Qh6 27. e5) 25... Ra8 26. c4 bxc4 27. bxc4 Qh6 28. Qd2 a4 29. c5 a3) 17... Rc8 18. Nf3 (18. a4 Qxe4 19. Qxf6 Rg8 $1 20. Qf3 Rg4 21. Qh3 h5 22. Nb3 Qg6 23. Nxc5 Rxc5 24. Qf3 Rd5 25. g3 Rxb4 $15 {Although Black is symbolically better White now holds an easy draw due to the opposite coloured bishops.} 26. cxb4 Qc2 $15 {leaves White's king wide open.} 27. Qf4 {looks better develpoing another piece.} {However keeping the structure by playing} Qxa4 {also deserves attention.}) 18... Qxc3 19. Rd4 Ke7 20. e5 Nd7 21. Qh4 Rhg8 22. Kh1 b5 23. h3 Rc4 (23... Rgd8 $1 {Another nice blow!}) 24. Rxd7+ Kxd7 25. Qxf6 Qd3 (25... Ke8 26. Rd1 $6 {This passive move looks a bit too slow and clearly gives Black a dangerous initiative.} Rc8 $1 {White is already in great danger.} 27. Ng5 Qc7 (27... Rxg5 28. Qxg5 Qc2 {0-1 (19) Pedersen,D (2254)-Jaksland,T (2277) Denmark 2014} 29. Rd2 $1 {although Black is better following} Qg6 30. Qh4) 28. Ne4 {This invites a nice combination but it's already hard to make good suggestions for White.} (28. Nxh7 Qc2) 28... Kf8 $1 29. Ng5 $4 {This automatic reply loses on the spot. He had to play} Rxg5 (29... Ke8) 30. Qxg5 Qc2 $1) 26. Qxf7+ Kc6 27. Qxe6+ Kb7 28. Re1 Rg6 29. Qf7+ Rc7 30. Qf4 Rc4 31. Qf8 Rc8 32. Qe7+ Rc7 33. Qh4 Qc4 (33... Qd5) (33... Rcg7) 34. Nd4 Qxa2 (34... Qd5 35. Qe4 Qxe4 36. Rxe4) (34... Rd7 35. Nf5 ({The crazy-looking} 35. e6 $5 {is actually not out of the question either. Clearly when sacrificing no fewer than two pawns in five moves there's a lot at stake but Black also receives a lot of activity.} {There might follow} Qxd4 36. Qxd4 Rxd4 37. e7 Rg8 38. e8=Q {This opens up the f-file.} Rxe8 39. Rxe8 Rd2) 35... Qd5 36. Re4 Qxa2 {½-½ (17) Muzik,M (2270)-Civin,T (2270) Czechia 1999}) 35. Qe4+ Kb6 (35... Kb8 36. e6 Qxf2 37. Rd1) 36. Qe3 (36. e6 Qxf2) 36... Kb7 37. Qf3+ Kb6 38. Nb3 Rc2 (38... Qa3 39. e6) 39. Qe3+ Kb7 40. e6 Rxf2 41. Qe4+ Kb6 42. Qd4+ (42. Qd4+ Kb7 43. Qd5+ Kb6 44. e7 Rfxg2 45. Qd8+ Kb7 {Here I suggest the improvement} 46. Qc8+ $146 {when there might follow} Kxc8 47. e8=Q+ Kb7 48. Re7+ {intending ...c6 next. Black has full compensation for the sacrificed pawn due to his piece activity and central control.} {Another interesting option is} Kb6 $5 49. Qd8+ Kc6 50. Qd7+ Kb6 51. Qb7#) 1-0


