1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 O-O 8. c3 d5 9. exd5 e4 10. dxc6 exf3 11. g3 (11. d4) (11. Qxf3) 11... Re8 {This move was introduced by Kasparov in his blitz match vs. Karpov. The present game is its maiden test at the "serious" level.} 12. d4 (12. Qxf3 $1 Bc5 13. Rf1 $16 {[%csl Rd4]} Bg4 $5 14. Qg2 Qc8) 12... Bg4 13. Bg5 h6 (13... Qd6 14. Qd3 h6 15. Bxf6 Bxf6 16. Nd2 Qxc6 17. Qg6 Be6 $11 {0-1 Karpov,A (2619)-Kasparov,G (2812)/Valencia 2009/CBM 132 Extra (36)} 18. Qh5) 14. Bxf6 Bxf6 15. Nd2 Qd6 {Black has no better option. The resulting position is rather favorable for White due to the poor position of the black pieces, especially the b6 knight.} 16. h3 $1 $146 {[%csl Rb6][%mdl 8]} Bh5 (16... Rxe1+ $11 17. Qxe1 $143 {[%csl Ra2]} Bxh3 18. Qe4) 17. Qc2 Bg5 18. Ne4 Qxc6 (18... Qg6 19. Qd3) 19. Nxg5 hxg5 20. Qf5 Rxe1+ $14 {[%csl Rd4] A typical picture: White has transformed his temporary advantage into a permanent plus, however, far from a decisive one.} (20... Qg6 {, and Black should hold on due to his blockading d6 knight.} 21. Qxg6 {[%cal Rd2f3]} Bxg6 $1 22. Bd5) 21. Rxe1 Re8 {[%csl Gd6]} 22. Re5 $1 (22. Rxe8+ Qxe8 {is clearly better for White due to his strong bishop.} 23. Qe5 Qxe5 $1 24. dxe5) 22... Rxe5 23. dxe5 Bg6 (23... Qg6 24. Qxg6 {may give White some more winning chances.} Bxg6 25. Bd5) 24. Qxg5 Qe4 25. Qd8+ Kh7 {Materially Black is OK but his pawns are quite weak so White keeps up the pressure.} 26. Qh4+ $6 Qxh4 27. gxh4 f6 (27... Bh5) 28. exf6 gxf6 29. Bd5 {looks attractive but Black sets up an unassailable fortress.} a5 30. b4 axb4 31. cxb4 Bd3 32. Kh2 Bc4 33. Be4+ (33. Bxc4 {In conclusion: 11...b4 doesn't guarantee Black equal chances.}) (33. Bxf3 $5 Bxa2) 33... Kh6 34. a3 (34. a3 Be6 35. Bxf3 Kg6 36. Kg3 f5 37. Kf4 Bd7 38. h5+ Kf6 39. Be2 Bc6 40. Bd3 Bd7 41. h6) 1/2-1/2


