{Due to the tournament situation, this was a very important game for me. I knew that a win would leave me with a reasonable chance of winning the tournament (although as it turns out, it wouldn't have sufficed). That explains my decision to take some risks and play the Dragon Sicilian. However, since I had already played that against Nigel Short in the second round, it can't have come as a complete surprise for David. In this game I got into difficulties, although given our desperate time trouble there were still winning chances for both sides near the time control.} 1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Bb4 3. g3 (3. Nd5) 3... Bxc3 4. dxc3 (4. bxc3 d6 5. Bg2 $1 {[%csl Gc4] is important. The h6-pawn combines with the bishop on c4 to severely cramp Black's king.} Ne7 {is the move which I wanted to play. After some thought I decided that it was probably bad, although perhaps for the wrong reasons.} 6. d3 {this doesn't win an exchange, but it does force the queens off.} O-O) 4... Nc6 5. Bg2 Nge7 6. Nf3 d6 7. O-O (7. e4 Be6 $18 {[%csl Rg3][%cal Yf1g1] and White is in time to win the pawn.} 8. Qe2 f6 9. b3 Qc8 10. h3 O-O $18 11. Ba3 a6 $1 {wins.} 12. Nd2 b5 13. Rd1 Rd8 14. h4 Bg4 $19 {[%csl Rg5] is one line showing the dangers here.} 15. f3 Be6 16. O-O Bh3 17. Rf2 {was suggested in the commentary room after the game. I was disappointed that I hadn't investigated this further during the game, as the h+g pawns looked rather potent. But it looks like White is winning the race after all.} Bxg2 18. Kxg2 Qe6 19. Nf1 f5 20. exf5 Qxf5 {[%csl Gb5][%cal Yb5b8] and the reinforcements on the h-file seem too slow.} 21. Qe4 $1 {was essential, with a very unclear position.} Qxe4 $1 {was stronger according to my computer, but I didn't think about this much. When the bishop comes to f5, it protects h7 and counterattacks c2.} 22. fxe4 bxc4 23. bxc4 Na5 {is very double edged. For example} 24. Ne3 c5 $1 {[%csl Gg4][%cal Yg4g1]} 25. Rfd2 Nb7 $13 26. Rb1 $5 {was a more flexible way to progress - White keeps the option of exchanging queens on c5 later.} Rd7 27. Rdb2 Ra7 {looks tempting at first, but then} 28. Kf3 $1 {just parries the threats and leaves Black's queen and knight offside.} Kf7 {was playable, and we both looked at this.} 29. Ke2 Ke8 {is better for White but messy. However, I decided 'on principle' that it wasn't a good idea to weaken my kingside in this fashion.} 30. Kd3 $5 Nd8 {[%cal Yd2h6] was more direct, and the move which David was trying to make work. However, the stumbling block was} 31. Rf1 Rab7 32. Rbf2 $5 {and White can't do better than a draw here, e.g.} Ne6 33. Bc1 Nc8 34. h5 Rf7 35. Rf5 $11 h6 36. Nd5 {seems to be alright as well} Nd8) 7... Be6 (7... O-O $1 8. e4 f5) 8. b3 f6 9. e4 (9. Ne1 $3 {[%csl Gg5,Rg8,Gh6][%cal Yd5d8] eluded both players.} Qd7 {even here, the win isn't trivial in desperate time trouble.}) 9... Qd7 (9... O-O $18 10. Ne1 Qd7) 10. Be3 (10. Ne1 O-O 11. Nc2 $3 $19 Bh3 $2) 10... O-O-O 11. Nd2 (11. Qe2 h5 12. b4 h4 13. a4 hxg3 $19 {[%csl Gg2][%cal Yh6h1]} 14. fxg3) 11... h5 12. f4 Bh3 (12... h4 13. f5) 13. f5 {[%csl Ra7,Rc6][%cal Ya8b8,Yb8b1,Yh2h4,Yh4h5] White has a long-term structural advantage in this position, so Black has to be careful in his handling of it. Due to the weak Black queenside pawns, a queen exchange is normally in White's favour, and the advance h2-h4-h5 is another important theme. However, Black has his trumps as well. If White advances his pawns too fast on the kingside, a queen exchange may lead to a balanced endgame with mutual weaknesses. Another important source of counterplay lies on the queenside, where White's king is more vulnerable than it looks (and c1 is not always an ideal square).} Bxg2 {This might seem to contradict my point about exchanging queens, but capturing on b6 right now would improve Black's structure.} 14. Kxg2 {Now White would be happy to see a queen exchange on d4.} Rdg8 15. Kh1 {This is essentially forced - the loose knight on a4 meant that e7-e5 was a serious threat.} g6 16. fxg6 {A direct move.} Rxg6 $5 {David said that he expected this, but} 17. Qf3 {During the game I felt comfortable about allowing this advance. My reasoning was that g4 probably adds little to the attack, while if Black can now exchange queens then there will always be some counterplay against f3.} Qg4 {This didn't turn out well, but I was intending to play 19...a5 which I later discovered was bad.} (17... h4 $1 {seems to be winning.}) 18. Qxg4+ hxg4 19. Rf2 Kd7 {Not a very happy choice.} 20. Raf1 Ke6 21. Nb1 Rh5 22. Kg1 $1 {This is the move which frightened me, not fearing the check on a3.} f5 23. exf5+ $1 {Another important move - if Black could play h7-h6 the kingside structure would start to look quite steady.} Rxf5 24. Rxf5 {White is doing well, but perhaps} Nxf5 25. Bf2 b6 {I considered it essential to get some counterplay} 26. Na3 Rg7 {[%csl Re5,Rf3,Gf5,Rg5,Gh6,Rh8][%cal Yf5f3] Black is objectively worse, but the position is becoming very sharp and it was harder for David to handle in his time trouble.} 27. Nc2 Rf7 28. Re1 Kd7 {Pushing a pawn is an easy plan!} 29. Re4 {We both had to play on our instincts here, and David brings his knight back to help control the g-pawn and create mating threats via g5.} Rg7 30. Kg2 Nce7 31. Ne3 Nxe3+ 32. Bxe3 Ke6 $2 {Objectively a serious error, but neither of us found White's winning possibility.} 33. Bf2 Kf5 {This position is a good example of the skewed perspective that a computer can give. With the right idea, White is absolutely winning, but it's not easy to see. If you don't see the idea, then Black has the upper hand in practice!} 34. Re1 $2 Rh7 $2 35. a4 Nc6 36. b4 a5 37. c5 bxc5 38. bxc5 {David had less than 20 seconds left here. I was down to around 45 seconds before I claimed the draw by repetition. It's a good thing for me that I did, as with more time I'm sure David (and I!) would have discovered that the position is still winning for White.} d5 $1 39. Bg1 Ke6 {wins due to a neat tactic:} 40. Re2 Rh8 41. Rb2 Rf8 42. Re2 Rb8 $1 43. h3 gxh3+ 44. Kxh3 $1 {was a chance to implement the same idea as before.} Rb3 $1 {would have actually turned the tables in my favour.} 45. Rc2 $1 {might hold the game though.} Ra3 46. Kh4 Rxa4+ 47. Kh5 Rc4 48. g4 d4 49. g5 Rxc3 $11 {this must be drawn.} 50. Rh2 (50. Rg2) 50... Rc1 51. Rg2 d3 $1 52. Be3 Re1 53. Bd2 Re2 54. Rxe2 dxe2 $11 55. Kg4 a4 56. Kf3 Nd4+ 1/2-1/2


