1. d4 e6 2. Nf3 c5 3. c4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Bb4 6. g3 O-O 7. Bg2 Nc6 8. O-O Qe7 9. Na4 Rd8 (9... d5 10. a3 (10. cxd5 $1 $18 exd5) 10... Bd6 11. cxd5 exd5 12. Nc3 Be5 $18 13. Be3) 10. a3 Bd6 11. b4 (11. Nb5 $14 Be5 $2 12. f4 Bb8 13. c5 d5 14. cxd6 Bxd6) 11... Be5 12. Bb2 Bxd4 $1 {That's it! To accept this pawn sacrifice, White must trade his important dark-squared bishop, after which the weakness of the dark squares, created with the g2-g4 advance, will become visible. And if White doesn't take the pawn, his queenside will be paralysed.} 13. Bxd4 Nxd4 14. Qxd4 $1 d6 15. Nc3 (15. Rfd1 Bd7 16. b5 (16. Nc3 Bc6 17. e4) 16... Be8) 15... e5 {This gives White attacking chances.} 16. Qh4 (16. Nd5 Nxd5 17. Qxd5 Rb8) (16. Qd3 Be6 $11 {[%cal Rf6f2,Rf6f1]} 17. Rac1 $142 Rac8 18. Nd5 $1) 16... Be6 17. Ne4 {[%cal Yh1h8]} Rd7 18. c5 (18. Rfd1 Nxe4 $19 (18... Rc8 19. c5 Nxe4 20. Qxe7 Rxe7 $11 21. cxd6) 19. Qxe7 Rxe7 20. Bxe4 Bxc4 $19 21. Rxd6 $1 {was the only way for White to keep the balance:} Bxe2 22. Rc1) 18... Nxe4 $6 {A wrong decision, after which White will make use of the g-file, too. However, it was not so easy to find a plan of counterplay:} 19. Qxe7 (19. Qxe4 dxc5 {[%cal Rf6f1]} 20. Qxe5 c4) 19... Rxe7 20. Bxe4 dxc5 21. bxc5 f5 22. Bg2 Rc8 23. Rfb1 e4 24. Rc1 $5 Bd5 25. f3 Rc6 (25... Rec7 26. fxe4 fxe4 $19 27. Bh3 $5 $19 {[%cal Rf4h4]}) 26. fxe4 $6 {Too passive.} fxe4 $1 $132 27. Rab1 Kf7 28. Kf2 Rec7 (28... e3+ $1 29. Kg1) 29. Ke3 Rxc5 (29... Rh6 30. h3 Rg6 $8 31. g4 h5 32. Rf1+ $11) 30. Rxc5 Rxc5 31. Bxe4 $2 Bxe4 $19 32. Kxe4 b6 33. Kd4 Ke6 (33... Rc2 $2 34. Kd3 Ra2 35. Rb3 Ke6 36. h4 {[%csl Gg5] Black's g-pawn is now unstoppable.} Kf5 $1 {, and White's counterplay is quite enough for a draw.} 37. e4+ Ke5 $1 38. Rb5+ Ke6 39. Rb3) 34. a4 Rd5+ $1 35. Kc3 Rh5 $5 36. h4 Re5 $2 {Giving White another chance.} 37. Kd3 Rd5+ 0-1


