1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Qe2 Nxe4 6. Qxe4 Qa5 $5 {This clever move has become the main line at high level. Black's threat is 7...f5, and we can't play 7.d3 for pinning reasons. That's why Whte generally doesn't tolerate the queen here.} 7. b4 $5 {This accelerates the development of the dark-squared bishop on the long diagonal and chases the queen.} (7. Qf4 Qf5 {This transposes in the line 6...d5 7.f4 f5 that we considered in the previous game, but preferred another variation starting with 7.h4.}) (7. Bd3 {This also looks interesting in order to prevent ...f5, and intend a later b2-b3 for the development, but there is an annoying move} Na6 $1 8. Qe5 Qxe5+ 9. Nxe5 Nb4 10. Be4 f6 {It already seems clear that Black can't be in trouble here.} 11. c3 Nd5 12. Nf3 a5 13. d4 a4 $11 {½-½ (41) Adams,M (2703)-Howell,D (2696) London 2018}) 7... Qf5 (7... Qd5 {Compared to 6...d5, and even if there are pros and cons, I would rather prefer to have it included.} 8. Qe3 $1 Bf5 9. c4 Qe4 10. Bb2 e6 11. Bc3 Nd7 12. Be2 Be7 (12... a5 13. bxa5 $1 Nc5 14. Nd4 Qxe3 15. fxe3 Bg6 16. Nb3 $14) 13. d3 Qxe3 14. fxe3 {White is getting a massive pawn centre.} Bf6 $6 15. Kd2 Rd8 16. Bxf6 Nxf6 17. Kc3 $16 {½-½ (48) Wen,Y (2588)-Xiu,D (2538) Daqing 2019}) 8. Qe3 Qe6 {Again, it seems that Black should push to trade the queens, otherwise things will only get worse.} 9. Be2 Qxe3 {White was threatening to move his queen, so there is no time to wait.} 10. fxe3 f6 (10... Bf5 11. d3 e6 12. Bd2 Na6 13. a3 Nc7 {1-0 (56) Zelbel,P (2448)-Svane,R (2613) Magdeburg GER 2020} 14. c4 $1 $146 O-O-O 15. e4 Bg6 16. h4 h5 17. Ne5 $16 {There might be a hole on d4 at some point, but it doesn't compensate for the activity and the space advantage that White enjoys.}) 11. a3 (11. a4 $6 {This was tried by Jones in the same match, and but it's kind of too weakening for White's kingside, and he couldn't manage to handle it properly.} e5 12. Ba3 Bf5 13. d3 Nd7 14. O-O Bg6 15. e4 a5 16. b5 cxb5 17. axb5 Bxa3 18. Rxa3 b6 $15 {0-1 (43) Jones,G (2683)-Howell,D (2676) London ENG 2019}) (11. d4 e5) 11... e5 12. d4 $1 {Of course White fights for the centre.} exd4 13. exd4 Be6 14. Bf4 Nd7 15. O-O $6 (15. c4 $1 {Anticipating Black's next move was probably stronger.} Nb6 16. d5 $1 (16. Rc1 $6 g5 17. Bg3 g4 18. Nd2 Bh6 $132) 16... cxd5 17. c5 $1 {A strong pawn sacrifice, because now Black's pieces are lacking strong spots.} Nc4 {Now White has at least two very promising plans.} 18. O-O (18. Nd4 $5 Bd7 19. O-O-O $5 O-O-O 20. Bf3 Ba4 21. Ne6 $1 Bxd1 $6 22. Rxd1 Re8 23. Nc7 Rd8 $2 24. Bg4+ $18) 18... O-O-O 19. Nd4 Bd7 20. Rac1 $14 Nxa3 $4 21. c6 $18 {[%cal Rb7c6,Re2a6]}) 15... Nb6 $1 {Now pushing the c-pawn is going to be a tough task.} 16. Bd3 Bc4 17. Rae1+ Kf7 18. Bc1 Bxd3 19. Ne5+ Kg8 20. Nxd3 Nc4 $15 {He just needs to organise his pieces, but strategically, Black is much better. and the position seems quite easy to play.} 21. Re4 Bd6 22. c3 Kf7 23. Ne5+ $6 Nxe5 24. dxe5 Rhe8 25. Bf4 Re6 $1 26. Rd4 $2 (26. Re3 Bc7 27. Rh3 $1 Bxe5 28. Bxe5 Rxe5 29. Rxh7 Rd8 30. Rh3 $15 {Still hard, but holdable for White.}) 26... Bxe5 27. Bxe5 Rxe5 28. Rd7+ Re7 29. Rfd1 Rae8 30. Kf2 Rxd7 31. Rxd7+ Re7 32. Rd8 $17 {This sort of endgame is pretty close to being lost.} a6 33. a4 h5 34. Kf3 Kg6 35. Kf4 Kf7 $2 (35... Re2 $1 36. Kf3 Rc2 37. Rd3 b5 38. axb5 axb5 $19 {[%cal Rg6f5,Rg7g5] Now White is fixed and clearly lost.}) 36. h4 {Now it's really hard for Black to achieve any kind of progress.} Kg6 37. a5 Kf7 38. Rb8 Kg6 39. Rh8 $2 (39. c4 Rd7 40. g3 {This is the best setup. There is no problem about giving up the c4-pawn.} Rd4+ 41. Kf3 Rxc4 42. Rxb7 $11 {[%cal Rb7b6]}) 39... Re2 40. Rb8 Re7 (40... Rxg2 $1 41. Rxb7 Rg4+ 42. Ke3 Rxh4 43. Rb6 Rh3+ 44. Kd4 h4 45. Rxc6 Rh1 46. Rxa6 h3 47. Ra8 Rd1+ 48. Kc5 Kh7 $19 {[%cal Rh3h1]}) 41. Ra8 Kf7 42. g3 Kg6 43. c4 Kf7 44. Ra7 {It seems that White is the one playing for a win, probably because of the match situation.} Kf8 45. Kf5 Kf7 46. Ra8 Re5+ 47. Kf4 Re7 48. Rh8 Kg6 49. Rf8 Re1 50. Rb8 Re7 51. Rd8 Kf7 52. Rc8 Kg6 53. Rh8 Re1 54. Rb8 Rc1 55. Rxb7 Rxc4+ 56. Ke3 c5 57. b5 axb5 58. Rxb5 Kf5 59. Kd3 Rc1 60. Kd2 Ra1 61. Kc2 Kg4 62. Kb2 Ra4 63. Kb3 Ra1 64. Kb2 Ra4 65. Rxc5 Kxg3 66. Kb3 Ra1 67. Rxh5 g6 68. Rc5 f5 69. Kb2 Ra4 70. Kb3 Ra1 71. h5 gxh5 72. Kb2 Ra4 73. Kb3 Ra1 74. Rxf5 h4 75. Kb2 Ra4 76. Kb3 Ra1 77. Rg5+ Kf4 78. Rh5 Kg4 79. Rc5 h3 80. Rc4+ {After a strange endgame, where Black was trying to take as little risk as possible despite a much better and sometimes winning position, the game eventually concludes in an obvious draw.} 1/2-1/2


