1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nge7 (3... a6 {The original move order.} 4. Ba4 Nge7 5. O-O Ng6) 4. O-O Ng6 5. c3 a6 6. Ba4 d5 7. exd5 Qxd5 8. d4 {Opening up the center is one way to play the initiative. However, black has a strong reply.} (8. Bb3 {- see Zhigalko-Sadhwani game}) 8... Bg4 $1 {Pinning the knight solves all problems for black. He is preparing 0-0-0. Also, in the center, the tension is high.} 9. Nbd2 {Overprotect the f3 is the most reasonable.} (9. dxe5 O-O-O {The e5 pawn is falling anyway, so black is not rushing to take it back immediately but instead playing for development.} 10. Qxd5 Rxd5 11. Bxc6 bxc6 12. Nbd2 Nf4 $132 {Prepares d3 with a double edge position.}) (9. Bb3 Bxf3 $1 {A crucial intermediate move. After some trades, the position will be cleared up.} 10. Bxd5 Bxd1 11. Rxd1 O-O-O 12. Bxf7 exd4 13. cxd4 Nxd4 14. Nc3 Ne2+ $5 15. Kf1 Rxd1+ 16. Nxd1 Nxc1 17. Rxc1 Bd6 $11 {Wieczorek-Sadhwani, Spilimbergo 2021}) (9. c4 Qxd4 $1 {I like this move so much. It's easy to understand the sense, but still a very nice move. The knight is pinned on f3, so again the position will be just simplified.} (9... Qxc4 $6 {It would just fall into the trap.} 10. Bb3 $1 Qb4 11. Bxf7+ $1 Kxf7 12. Ng5+ Kg8 13. Qxg4 Nxd4 14. Be3 $36) 10. Nxd4 Bxd1 11. Rxd1 exd4 12. Bxc6+ $1 (12. Rxd4 Nge5 13. Bxc6+ (13. Rd1 Nxc4 14. Nc3 Bd6 15. Bxc6+ bxc6 16. b3 Nb6 17. Re1+ Kd7 $15 {Ter Sahakyan-Williams, Tornelo INT 2021}) 13... Nxc6 14. Re4+ Be7 15. Nc3 O-O-O $11) 12... bxc6 13. Rxd4 Bd6 14. Nc3 O-O-O 15. Be3 Rhe8 $11) 9... exd4 $1 10. h3 (10. Qe1+ {Unpins the f3.} Be7 11. Nxd4 Bd7 12. Bb3 Qh5 13. Bd1 Qd5 14. Bb3 $11) (10. Re1+ Be7 11. h3 Bxf3 (11... dxc3 12. hxg4 cxd2 13. Bxd2 O-O-O (13... O-O $13) 14. Rc1 $13) 12. Nxf3 O-O-O $1 13. Bxc6 Qxc6 14. Nxd4 Qd5 $11 {The arisen symmetrical position is pretty drawish.}) 10... Bxf3 $6 (10... dxc3 $1 {The best is this intermediate capture.} 11. hxg4 cxd2 12. Qe2+ (12. Bxd2 O-O-O $1 $15) 12... Be7 13. Bxd2 O-O-O $15 {White would be happy to put the bishop on c3, but they should always worry about f4 jumping, making blacks' position comfortable here.}) 11. Nxf3 O-O-O 12. cxd4 $2 (12. Bb3 $1 {Pressure on the a2-g8 diagonal would be much better.} Qf5 13. cxd4 $14) 12... Nxd4 {Wins the pawn.} 13. Nxd4 Qxd4 14. Qc2 Qd3 $6 {Trading the queens is a solid move, but the white bishop pair compensate the pawn down. It would be better to keep the queens at the board and attack the dark squares.} (14... Qe5 $1 $17 {Followed by d6 gives a tremendous advantage for black.}) 15. Bg5 $6 (15. Qxd3 $1 Rxd3 16. Bc2 Rd8 17. Be3 Bd6 $15) 15... Qxc2 16. Bxc2 f6 (16... Be7 $1 {Black probably was worried about going for an opposite-colored bishop ending.} 17. Bxg6 (17. Be3 Bf6 $17) 17... Bxg5 18. Bxf7 Bf6 19. Rab1 Rd2 20. b4 c6 21. Rfd1 Rhd8 22. Rxd2 Rxd2 $19 {[%cal Yf6d4] Black is pretty active, and the position is most probably won. The plan is d4, c7-b6-b5.}) 17. Bf5+ Kb8 18. Be3 Bd6 19. Rac1 (19. Rad1 Rhe8 $17) 19... Bf4 20. Rfe1 Bxe3 21. Rxe3 Rhe8 $17 22. Rec3 c6 23. Kf1 Nf8 24. Rb3 Kc7 25. Rd3 g6 26. Rxd8 Rxd8 27. Bc2 Ne6 28. Bb3 Nd4 29. Re1 Rd7 30. Re8 Nxb3 31. axb3 Kb6 32. Ke2 Kb5 33. Re6 f5 34. Re3 Kb4 35. f4 a5 36. g4 b5 37. gxf5 gxf5 38. Re6 Kxb3 39. Rxc6 Kxb2 40. Rc5 Rb7 41. Rxf5 a4 0-1


