1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Qf6 5. Nb3 Qg6 6. Qe2 (6. f3 {is a more popular continuation.}) 6... Nf6 7. f3 ({White doesn't hurry with} 7. Nc3 $6 {, because} Bb4 $15 {and the pin is unpleasant for him.}) 7... a5 8. Be3 $146 {The first new move in the game by Nakamura.} (8. a4 Bb4+ 9. c3 Be7 {(Quirhuayo-Dos Santos, Buenos Aires 2015)} 10. e5 Nd5 11. Qe4 Qxe4+ 12. fxe4 Nb6 13. Bf4 {and White's pawn structure is bad, however he has some activity.}) 8... d5 $1 {The best reply! Black immediately plays actively in the centre and he isn't afraid of the X-ray effect of the e2-queen.} 9. Nc3 ({In the event of} 9. exd5 Nxd5 $36 {looks dangerous for Black, but White doesn't have a good check with the bishop.}) (9. e5 Nd7 ({but not} 9... Nxe5 $2 10. Bd4 $16 {and Black loses a piece}) 10. f4 a4 11. Nd4 Nxd4 12. Bxd4 c6 $132 {with a complicated middlegame.}) 9... dxe4 10. O-O-O {An ambitious move, White continues the development and he is threatening with the b5.} ({Nevertheless} 10. Nb5 $1 {was more accurate,} Bd6 11. O-O-O O-O $13 {with a complicated position.}) 10... Be7 {Of course Black also continues the development.} 11. Nb5 O-O 12. Nxc7 Rb8 13. Qb5 {A tempting reaction. The queen stops ...b5, however this is not the best square for it.} (13. Kb1 {would be more solid, but} Bf5 $36 {is also unpleasant for White.}) 13... Bd7 $6 {A natural reply, but it wasn't the best.} (13... Rd8 $1 {was correct and suddenly White is in trouble, for example:} 14. Rxd8+ Bxd8 15. Nd5 Nxd5 16. Qxd5 exf3 17. gxf3 (17. Qxf3 Nb4 $19 {and Black is winning.}) 17... Qxc2+ $1 {A smart solution!} 18. Kxc2 Nb4+ $17 {and Black will be a healthy pawn up in the endgame.}) 14. Nc5 Nd4 15. Qb6 $6 {A dubious move, because White should protect the important c2-square.} ({White should have played} 15. Qc4 Nf5 ({or} 15... Bxc5 16. Qxc5 {transposing to the game.}) 16. Bf4 Bc6 $132 {with a double-edged fight.}) 15... Bxc5 $6 {Error in reply!} (15... Nxc2 $1 {was the tactical blow,} 16. Nxd7 ({or} 16. Kxc2 exf3+ 17. Bd3 Bf5 18. gxf3 Rfd8 $17 {and White is in trouble.}) 16... Nxe3 17. Qxe3 Nxd7 18. Qxe4 Qxe4 19. fxe4 Nc5 $15 {and Black looks nicely placed.}) 16. Qxc5 Ne6 17. Nxe6 Bxe6 18. Qg5 $1 {A good move, White simplifies the position. Now Black has to be careful, otherwise with the bishop pair White can play for the advantage.} exf3 19. gxf3 Rfc8 20. Qxg6 (20. Bd3 {was the alternative,} Qxg5 21. Bxg5 Bxa2 22. Rhg1 $44 {with compensation for the pawn.} ({But not} 22. b3 $2 {, because of} Bxb3 $17)) 20... hxg6 21. a3 b5 22. Bd4 b4 23. axb4 axb4 24. Bd3 Nd7 (24... Ra8 $5 {was the other logical option.}) 25. Rhe1 Rc6 $6 {Black would like to activate his , but probably this was not the best moment for it.} ({The engine suggests} 25... g5 {to gain some space and play move by move on the kingside.}) 26. Be4 Ra6 27. b3 Nf6 28. Be5 Re8 29. Bd3 Ra5 30. Kb2 Nd5 31. Bc4 Rea8 32. Bxd5 $6 {This is a surprise for me to give up the bishop pair with White and play an opposite-coloured bishop endgame.} ({I think after} 32. Ra1 $1 {White has a slight edge, for example:} Ra3 (32... Rxa1 33. Rxa1 Rxa1 34. Kxa1 $14) 33. Bd6 $1 $14 {and Black's position is not easy.}) 32... Bxd5 {And the draw was agreed!} 1/2-1/2


