1. c4 e6 2. Nc3 d5 3. d4 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 Ne4 8. Bxe7 Qxe7 9. Rc1 c6 10. g4 {This "sudden" kingside attack converts a quiet position of the Lasker System into a mess.} Nd7 11. h4 {[%mdl 4]} e5 ({Perhaps Black should consider more closely} 11... Nxc3 12. Rxc3 c5 {- Mamedyarov-Fridman in CBM 146. Although here, too, Varuzhan Akobian managed to pose problems to Black:} 13. cxd5 exd5 14. g5 h5 15. Bg2 b6 (15... c4 16. Nd2 Nb6 17. Qxh5 Bf5 18. Qf3 Bd3 19. Bf1 Na4 20. Bxd3 Nxc3 21. Bf5 $44 {1/2 (41) Chirila,I (2521)-Papp,G (2552) Baia Sprie 2012}) 16. dxc5 Nxc5 17. Nd4 Ne4 18. Bxe4 Qxe4 19. f3 Qe5 20. Kf2 $14 {1-0 (48) Akobian,V (2653)-Fridman,D (2639) Tromsoe 2014}) 12. cxd5 Nxc3 13. Rxc3 cxd5 {This line has been examined in detail in several CBM issues, most recently in CBM 144; annotations to Aronian-Harikrishna by GM I.Stohl, and CBM 160, annotation to Laznicka-Dvirnyy by GM L.Ftacnik.} 14. g5 {This pawn seriously restricts Black's pieces.} (14. dxe5 Nxe5 15. Nxe5 Qxe5 16. Be2 Be6 {1/2 (16) Stanciu,A (2288)-Georgescu,T (2391) Brasov 2011}) (14. Bb5 e4 15. Bxd7 Bxd7 16. Ne5 Be6 17. g5 hxg5 18. Qh5 g4 19. Nxg4 Bxg4 20. Qxg4 f5 $13 {1/2 (51) Dimic,P (2201)-Grigorchuk,S (2297) Zaragoza 2013}) 14... e4 (14... h5 15. Bb5 (15. dxe5 Nxe5 16. Be2 $14 Bg4 $6 17. Nxe5 Bxe2 18. Qd4 Rfe8 19. f4 $16 {1-0 (37) Rozum,I (2498)-Baglaev,E (2099) St Petersburg 2012}) 15... exd4 16. Qxd4 Nb6 (16... Rd8 17. g6 Nf8 18. gxf7+ Qxf7 19. Ng5 Qf6 20. Qxf6 gxf6 21. Nf3 $16 {1-0 (44) Ipatov,A (2614)-Chigladze,I (2365) Yerevan 2014}) (16... Qe4 17. Qxe4 dxe4 18. Nd2 Ne5 19. Nxe4 Be6 20. f4 $1 Bd5 21. fxe5 Bxe4 22. O-O $14 {Aronian,L (2805)-Harikrishna,P (2669) Ningbo 2011 CBM 144 [Stohl,I]}) 17. O-O Bf5 18. Qf4 Be4 (18... Qe4 19. Nd4 Qxf4 20. exf4 Bc8 21. Re1 a6 22. Bd3 $16 {1-0 (30) Dambacher,M (2490)-Sonntag,H (2364) Germany 2015}) 19. Rc7 Qb4 20. Nd4 Qxb2 21. Rxb7 $14) (14... hxg5 15. hxg5 e4 16. Ne5 g6 17. Ng4 Qxg5 18. f4 {1-0 (27) Colpe,M (2349)-Grabarczyk,M (2436) Lueneburg 2015} Qd8 19. Qd2 Kg7 20. Qh2 Rh8 21. Qxh8+ Qxh8 22. Rxh8 Kxh8 23. Rc7 $14) 15. Nd2 (15. Ne5 $6 Nxe5 16. dxe5 Qxe5 17. Rg1 Kh8 18. Qh5 f6 19. Qe2 Bd7 20. gxh6 gxh6 21. Qc2 Rac8 $17 {1/2 (47) Chirila,I (2521)-Dimitrov,A (2339) Golden Sands 2012}) 15... hxg5 (15... g6 16. Qb3 (16. gxh6 Nf6) (16. Rg1 h5 17. Be2 Nb6 18. Nf1 Be6 19. Bxh5 Qb4 20. Bg4 Qxb2 $15 {1-0 (75) Benjamin,J (2534)-Akobian,V (2616) Saint Louis 2013}) 16... Nb6 17. a4 $36) 16. Qh5 $1 (16. hxg5 $143 $2 Qxg5 17. Rh5 Qg1 $1 18. Rh3 (18. Rxd5 Nf6 19. Rd6 Be6 $17 {0-1 (35) Sadzikowski,D (2448)-Grabarczyk,M (2460) Wroclaw 2013}) 18... Nf6 19. Rg3 Qh1 20. Nb3 b6 21. Kd2 Bg4 $17 {1/2 (59) Wang,H (2718)-Kravtsiv,M (2571) Shenzhen 2011}) 16... g6 (16... g4 17. Qxd5 $1 (17. Qxg4 Nb6 $5 (17... Rd8 18. Rg1 Qf6 19. Qg3 Nf8 20. f3 exf3 21. Nxf3 Bf5 22. Bh3 Bxh3 23. Qxh3 Qh6 24. Ne5 $14 {1-0 (28) Laznicka,V (2681)-Dvirnyy,D (2575) Yerevan 2014 CBM 160 [Ftacnik,L]}) 18. Qg3 Bd7 19. Rg1 f6 20. Nb3 Rfc8 21. a3 Na4 22. Rc7 $11 {L.Ftacnik}) 17... Nf6 (17... Nb6 18. Qxe4 Qxe4 19. Nxe4 Be6 20. Nc5 Bd5 21. Rg1 $16 {1-0 (38) Kunin,V (2575)-Gstach,J (2237) Schwarzach 2014}) 18. Qg5 Qb4 19. Rb3 Qd6 20. h5 Nh7 21. Qc5 $14 {1-0 (33) Li,R (2419)-Rodgaard,J (2354) Istanbul 2012}) 17. Qxg5 Qxg5 18. hxg5 $14 {In the resulting endgame White controls the c- and h-files so Black is doomed to defence. That means that the whole line is not quite satisfactory for Black, and he should rather look for other replies to 10.g4.} Rd8 (18... Nb6 $5 19. b3 Bf5 20. Nb1 Rac8 21. Kd2 f6 22. Rxc8 Bxc8 23. gxf6 Rxf6 24. Rh2 Bd7 25. Nc3 Kg7 26. Be2 a6 27. Bd1 Rf8 28. Ne2 Rh8 29. Rxh8 Kxh8 30. Kc3 $14 {1-0 (33) Sadzikowski,D (2487)-Dubiel,J (2410) Germany 2014}) 19. f3 exf3 20. Nxf3 Nf8 21. Bd3 {, and White gradually converted his positional advantage:} Be6 {Black could probably have defended better, e.g.} (21... Bd7 $5 22. Kd2 Rac8 23. Rhc1 Ne6 {or}) (21... Bg4 22. Ne5 Be6 {[%cal Yf8h7]}) 22. Kd2 Rac8 23. Rhc1 Nh7 24. a4 Rxc3 25. bxc3 {[%mdl 4096]} Bg4 26. Ne5 Be6 27. Rg1 Kf8 28. e4 $1 b6 29. Ke3 dxe4 30. Bxe4 Bb3 31. Bc6 Bd5 ({It was better to refrain from the bishop exchange:} 31... Be6 {although after} 32. c4 {White should gradually crush Black.}) 32. c4 Bxc6 33. Nxc6 Re8+ 34. Kd3 a5 35. d5 {[%csl Gd5]} Kg7 36. Kd4 Re2 37. Ne5 Rd2+ 38. Kc3 Re2 39. Nd7 {[%csl Rb6]} Re3+ 40. Kd4 Rb3 41. d6 Rb2 42. Kd5 Rd2+ 43. Kc6 Rd4 44. Nxb6 Nf8 45. c5 Ne6 46. Re1 Kf8 47. Rxe6 fxe6 48. Kd7 1-0


