1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bb5 Bc5 5. O-O O-O 6. Nxe5 Nxe5 7. d4 Bd6 8. f4 Nc6 9. e5 Bb4 10. exf6 Qxf6 11. a3 $1 (11. Nd5 $6 Qxd4+ 12. Be3 Qxd1 13. Raxd1 Bd6 14. f5 f6 15. Bf4 Ne5 16. Bxe5 fxe5 17. f6 c6 $4 ({It was important to give the intermediate check:} 17... Bc5+ 18. Kh1 c6 19. Ne7+ Kh8 20. Nxc8 Rfxc8 21. fxg7+ Kg8 $1 {and White will be fighting for a draw.}) 18. Ne7+ {The d6 is hanging, so Black has to take the knight and White will get a powerful passed pawn.} Bxe7 19. fxe7 Re8 20. Bc4+ d5 21. Rxd5 $1 cxd5 22. Bxd5+ Be6 23. Bxe6+ Kh8 24. Rf7 $18 {1-0 (28) Kulaots,K (2585)-Roiz,M (2652) Plovdiv 2012}) (11. Be3 Bxc3 12. bxc3 d5 13. Qf3 Bf5 (13... Ne7 14. Bd3 Bf5 15. Bd2 Rad8 16. Rab1 Qc6 17. Rfe1 Bxd3 18. cxd3 Nf5 19. Qh3 Nd6 $11 {½-½ (27) Lavrentyev,Y (2328)-Dobrica,D (2321) ICCF email 2007}) 14. Qxd5 Rfe8 15. Rae1 Bxc2 16. Bd2 a6 17. Bxc6 bxc6 $11 {0-1 (37) Perunovic,M (2622)-Tkachiev,V (2637) Warsaw 2013}) 11... Ba5 ({After} 11... Bxc3 12. bxc3 {White enjoys a slight edge thanks to the bishop pair . Nevertheless, this is a lesser evil for Black.}) 12. Nd5 $1 Qxd4+ 13. Be3 Qxd1 14. Raxd1 {Compared to the above mentioned game Kulaots-Roiz, this is a much better version for White. Black's bishop can't retreat to d6 and stabilise Black's queenside.} d6 15. b4 Bb6 16. Bxb6 cxb6 17. Bxc6 bxc6 18. Ne7+ Kh8 19. Rxd6 {White has a big advantage in the endgame.} c5 20. bxc5 bxc5 21. Rb1 g6 22. Rb5 c4 23. Kf2 Be6 24. Nc6 Bf5 25. Nd4 Be4 26. g3 Rfd8 27. Rxd8+ Rxd8 28. Ke3 Bd5 29. Ra5 Rd7 30. Nb5 Re7+ 31. Kd2 Bf3 32. Nd4 Rd7 33. Kc3 Bd5 34. Nb5 Re7 35. Rxa7 Re2 36. Rd7 Be6 37. Rd2 Re1 38. a4 Ra1 39. Kb4 Rb1+ 40. Kc5 Ra1 41. Nc3 1-0


