1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Bc4 c5 8. Ne2 Nc6 9. Be3 O-O 10. O-O Na5 11. Bd3 b6 12. Qd2 e5 13. Bh6 cxd4 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. cxd4 exd4 16. Rac1 Bb7 (16... Qd6 {was played in Topalov,V (2805)-Anand,V (2787)/Sofia 2010/CBM 136/[Krasenkow] (1-0, 30)}) 17. f4 Rc8 18. f5 $146 ({Black somehow managed to survive after} 18. Rxc8 Qxc8 19. f5 Nc6 20. Rf3 Ne5 21. Rh3 Rh8 22. f6+ Kg8 23. Qh6 Qf8 {Karjakin,S (2732)-Carlsen,M (2765)/Foros 2008/CBM 125 (1/2, 30)}) 18... Nc6 19. f6+ Kh8 20. Qg5 (20. Qh6 Rg8 {transposes to the game.}) 20... Re8 21. Qh6 Rg8 22. Rf3 Qf8 23. Qh4 h6 24. Rh3 Kh7 25. Rxc6 $5 {Here is where this rook was needed! The piece that was about to block the e-pawn is eliminated.} Rxc6 26. e5 Bc8 27. g4 {Computers are happy with black, but I guess that most humans would feel incomfortable.} Rc5 28. Qg5 Rh8 29. Nf4 Rg8 30. Rh5 Ba6 31. Be4 Rc1+ 32. Kf2 d3 $2 (32... Ra1 33. Nh3 Rxa2+ 34. Kg3 (34. Kg1 $11) 34... Ra3+ 35. Kf4 Rxh3 36. Rxh3 Bc4) 33. Ne6 $1 (33. Nh3 $1 Rh8 (33... d2 34. Qxh6+ Qxh6 35. Ng5+ Kh8 36. Rxh6#) 34. Bd5 $3 Qc5+ (34... d2 35. Qxg6+ fxg6 36. Ng5#) 35. Kg3 Rg1+ 36. Nxg1 Qxg1+ 37. Kh3 Qf1+ 38. Bg2 $18) 33... fxe6 34. Qxc1 d2 35. Qxd2 Qc5+ 36. Kg2 1-0


