1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. d4 Be7 {This alternative to the more popular 5...Nd6 is a pet line of the Russian GM Malakhov and was advocated by many great players in the past including Steinitz, Anderssen, Zukertort, Lasker and others.} 6. Qe2 Nd6 7. Bxc6 bxc6 8. dxe5 Nb7 {Here White has a wide choice of options.} 9. c4 {This rare continuation (less than 10 games in the last 10 years) was introduced by Zukertort in 1868! The idea behind the move is to take better control over the centre before playing Nc3.} ({You can also find information on the more popular} 9. Nd4 {Grischuk, A (2717) -Malakhov, V (2679)/Elista RUS 2007/[TonyK].}) ({and} 9. Nc3 {Anand, V-Timman, J/Wijk aan Zee 1999/[Nigel Davies].}) ({and also the less common} 9. Re1 {Lau, R-Smagin, S/ Berlin 1990/[Nigel Davies], in our PGN Archive.}) 9... O-O 10. Nc3 ({Zukertort's} 10. Be3 {found no followers. That game continued} f5 $5 11. exf6 Bxf6 12. c5 $6 d5 $1 13. Nd4 $2 {0-1 Zukertort, J-Anderssen, A/Berlin 1868 and now} Nxc5 14. Nxc6 Qd6 $17 {promised Black a clear advantage.}) 10... f6 {The main line. The exchange of the e5-pawn is important for Black, though as the game shows, it has drawbacks, in particular it weakens the position of Black's king.} ({Smyslov preferred} 10... Nc5 {, but came under some pressure after} 11. b3 (11. Be3 $5 Ne6 12. Rad1 $14) 11... f6 12. Bb2 fxe5 13. Nxe5 Qe8 $1 14. Rae1 Ne6 15. Nd3 Qg6 16. f4 $14 {Tal, M (2620)-Smyslov, V (2620)/Moscow 1971.}) 11. Re1 {This line is considered to be equal and was out of fashion for quite a while until Svidler beat the main expert of the line, Malakhov, in 2010.} ({Malakhov also faced Tal's} 11. Bd2 fxe5 12. Nxe5 Bf6 13. Rae1 Qe8 14. Ng4 Qxe2 15. Nxf6+ Rxf6 16. Rxe2 d6 {and Black held the position, though White's chances in Naiditsch, A (2674)-Malakhov, V (2725)/Sibenik 2010, look higher.}) 11... fxe5 12. Qxe5 {Ehlvest's idea, which he introduced back in 1992, but Svidler was next to give it another test.} ({Earlier White preferred} 12. Nxe5 {, but all of those games were drawn.}) 12... Bf6 13. Qg3 $1 {Adams is the first to deviate from the two earlier games and introduces an interesting novelty.} ({After} 13. Qh5 g6 14. Qh6 Bg7 15. Qh3 d6 16. Qg3 {The queen eventually gets to g3. So Adams decided to retreat there immediately. Svidler, P (2722)-Malakhov, V (2712)/ Moscow RUS 2010. In an attempt to improve upon Malkahov's 16...Qd7 I suggest} Nc5 17. Bg5 Qd7 18. Re7 Qg4 19. Rxc7 Qxg3 20. fxg3 Bxc3 21. bxc3 Ne6 22. Rxc6 Rxf3 23. gxf3 Nxg5 {with mutual chances.}) 13... Nc5 $6 {The wrong route for the knight, which is ready to jump to d3, but White doesn't and shouldn't care!} ({There was a better route for the knight} 13... Nd6 $1 {going to f5. Now the position after} 14. c5 Nf5 15. Qf4 Rb8 {requires deep investigation.}) 14. Bg5 $1 {The initiative is more important than a pawn here.} Nd3 $2 {After this move Black finds himself on the edge of a precipice.} (14... d6 {was necessary.}) 15. Re3 $1 Nxb2 (15... Bxg5 16. Nxg5 Nf4 {would be a better practical chance, but Black's position after} 17. Rae1 $16 {isn't sugar.}) 16. Rae1 $1 {White's initiative is very dangerous.} Bxg5 ({The subsequent line confirms my words.} 16... Nxc4 17. Re7 $1 Bxe7 (17... Bxc3 18. Bh6 $1 $18) 18. Rxe7 $18 {and Black will have to sac on e7 to stay in the game. However, White is already clearly winning.}) (16... Ba6 $1 {would be a lesser of evils, but after} 17. Re7 $1 Bxc3 18. R1e3 $1 Rf5 $1 19. Rxc3 Qf8 20. Rxd7 $16 {White retains the better chances, although Black escaped the immediate danger.}) 17. Nxg5 {Now a threat of Re7 forces} Qf6 $1 {White has many more pieces in attack and the precise} 18. Rf3 $1 $18 {leaves no hope.} Qd8 ({or} 18... Qd6 19. Rxf8+ Qxf8 20. Nce4 $1 {with two decisive threats of 21.Nf6!! and 21.Nxh7!, which Black can't stop. For example,} Ba6 21. Nxh7 Qf5 22. Nhf6+ Kf7 23. Qxc7 $1 Nxc4 24. Nxd7 $1 Kg8 25. Qxc6 $18) 19. Nce4 $1 (19. Rxf8+ $1 Qxf8 20. Nce4 $1 $18 {is also winning. See 18...Qd6.}) 19... Ba6 {Protecting the last rank.} (19... Nxc4 20. Rxf8+ Qxf8 21. Nf6+ $1 $18 {also leads to a disaster.}) 20. Nxh7 $1 ({After} 20. Rxf8+ $1 Qxf8 21. Nxh7 $1 $18 {White wins a tempo attacking Black's queen, but the text is also enough for a win. By the way, this position also arises after 18...Qd6. See above.}) 20... Rxf3 21. gxf3 $1 Kxh7 {Otherwise 22.Qg6 with the subsequent 23.Nef6.} 22. Ng5+ Kg8 23. Qh4 Bxc4 {This last attempt to protect the king fails.} 24. Qh7+ Kf8 25. Re5 $1 {A decisive move. Black is doomed.} Be6 ({or} 25... Qf6 26. Qh8+ Bg8 27. Nh7+ $18) 26. Qh8+ Ke7 (26... Bg8 27. Rf5+ Ke7 (27... Qf6 28. Rxf6+ gxf6 29. Nh7+ $1 $18) 28. Qxg7+ $18 {is similar to the game.}) 27. Qxg7+ Kd6 28. Ne4# {An elegant checkmate in the middle of the board. A very well played game by Adams, who didn't leave his young opponent a single chance. 13...Nd6 seems to be the way to improve upon Black's play.} 1-0


