1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 6. g3 Qb6 7. Ndb5 Ne5 8. Bg2 a6 9. Na3 $5 {Howell revives a gambit line which was played frequently by Gelfand and Agrest in the 2002-2004 period, but only seen sporadically since.} (9. Qa4 Rb8 10. Na3 Bxa3 11. Qxa3 Nxc4 12. Qb3 {is an alternative way of sacrificing the c-pawn which was explored in Matlakov-Rambaldi in the January 2016 Update}) 9... Bxa3 {Declining the pawn with} (9... Be7 10. O-O d6 {gives White a comfortable position as Black needs to spend more unravelling in order to complete development.} 11. Qb3 Qc7 12. Bf4 O-O 13. Rfd1 Ng6 14. Be3 Nd7 15. Na4 Rb8 16. Ba7 Ra8 17. Qe3 {with a small edge for White, see Gelfand-Nisipeanu in the Archives}) 10. bxa3 Nxc4 11. O-O {After the immediate} (11. Bg5 Qd8 (11... d5 12. O-O O-O {transposes to the main game}) (11... h6 {was played in an earlier Gelfand game which continued} 12. Bxf6 gxf6 13. O-O Rb8 14. Rc1 Qd6 15. Qc2 b5 16. a4 Qe5 17. axb5 axb5 18. a4 {with some initiative for White, Gelfand, B (2704)-Van Wely, L (2681) Bled 2002 1/2-1/2  (47)}) 12. Rc1 d5 (12... O-O {is preferred by Gelfand}) 13. O-O Ne5 {was played in Gelfand, B (2709)-Macieja, B (2653) Bermuda 2004 1/2-1/2 (41), and now} 14. e4 $1 {would give White an advantage according to Gelfand}) 11... O-O {Black can also delay castling, for example} (11... d5 12. Bg5 h6 (12... Bd7 13. e4 $5 (13. Rb1 {would be more normal, for example} Qc5 {or} (13... Qd8 14. Rc1 O-O 15. e4) 14. Rxb7 Rd8 15. Qc1 {and in both lines chances are roughly balanced}) (13. Bxf6 $6 gxf6 14. e4 d4 15. Rb1 Qc5 16. Rxb7 Rd8 {and White has gone astray, Thinius, M (2380)-Rapport, R (2444) Marianske Lazne 2010 0-1 (29)}) 13... Nxe4 14. Nxe4 dxe4 15. Rb1 Qc5 16. Rxb7 O-O 17. Qc1 Bb5 18. a4 Bxa4 19. Bxe4 Rac8 20. Be7 Qe5 21. Re1 Rfe8 22. Bxh7+ Kxh7 23. Rxe5 Nxe5 24. Rc7 {with an unusual endgame that was eventually drawn in Agrest-Ivanchuk, see the annotated game in the Archives}) 13. Bxf6 gxf6 14. e4 (14. Rc1 {keeping pressure on the c-file and c4-knight is a better approach}) 14... d4 15. Rb1 Qa7 {and Black was fine in Fier, A (2566)-L'Ami, E (2611) Dieren 2011 1/2-1/2  (82)}) 12. Bg5 d5 (12... Qd8 $6 {walking into a pin, is worse, and after} 13. Ne4 d5 14. Nxf6+ gxf6 15. Bh6 Re8 16. e4 e5 17. Rc1 b5 18. exd5 f5 19. Qh5 Qd6 20. Rfd1 {White was on top in Adhiban, B (2555)-Prathamesh, S (2389) Dubai 2013 1-0 (61)}) 13. Rc1 Nxa3 {The first new move. Black has also tried} (13... Rd8 14. Bxf6 (14. e4 $5 {is a possible improvement for White here, for example} dxe4 15. Qb3 Qxb3 16. axb3 Na5 17. Nxe4 Nxb3 18. Rc2 {when the pin on f6 gives White annoying pressure, despite his temporary material deficit}) 14... gxf6 15. e4 d4 16. Na4 Qb5 17. Rxc4 Qxc4 18. Nb6 Qc5 19. Nxa8 Bd7 {this position has been reached in three games:} 20. e5 (20. Qg4+ Kf8 (20... Kh8 21. Qf4 Rxa8 22. Qxf6+ Kg8 23. e5 Bc6 {was balanced in Yevseev, D (2527)-Vakhlamov, I (2315) Voronezh 2011 1/2-1/2 (75)}) 21. Qf4 Rxa8 22. Qxf6 Rc8 23. e5 Bb5 {and the players agreed a draw in Agrest, E (2584)-Wedberg, T (2540) Skara 2002 1/2-1/2 (23)}) 20... Rxa8 $2 (20... fxe5 21. Qg4+ Kf8 22. Bxb7 Rb8 {is unclear}) 21. exf6 Kh8 22. Bxb7 Rg8 23. Qd2 Bb5 24. Re1 d3 25. Be4 Qg5 26. Qxg5 Rxg5 27. a4 {reaching a winning endgame for White, Reinderman, D (2587)-Flumbort, A (2540) Haarlem 2010 1-0 (35)}) (13... Bd7 $5 {is an untried alternative}) 14. e4 d4 $6 {After this White gets a strong initiative, instead} (14... Nb5 {getting the knight back into play, makes more sense. White has excellent compensation for the pawns after for example} 15. Bxf6 gxf6 16. Qg4+ Kh8 17. Qh4) 15. e5 Nd7 (15... dxc3 16. exf6 e5 {is more tenacious, but White still has great play after} 17. fxg7 Re8 18. Rxc3 Nb5 19. Re3 {with the two bishops and ruined Black kingside pawns}) 16. Ne4 (16. Be7 {is another strong move}) 16... Nxe5 $2 {Allowing a brilliant combination. Black had to try} (16... Qb4 {or}) (16... Nb5) 17. Nf6+ $3 {Howell seizes his chance and plays the rest of the game perfectly} gxf6 (17... Kh8 18. Qh5 h6 19. Bxh6 {with a quick checkmate in sight}) 18. Bxf6 Ng6 {Other moves don't help either:} (18... Nac4 19. Qh5 {or}) (18... Qb5 19. Qh5 Qd3 20. Qxe5 Qf5 21. Rc5 {in both cases with a winning attack}) 19. Qh5 e5 {Black was relying on this move to attack the f6-bishop, but Howell has a deadly interference move available. Without this, White's attack would fail.} 20. Rc6 $1 (20. Bc6 {is the only other move to win, a more abstract version of the same idea}) 20... Qd8 21. Qh6 {No mercy! White keeps the attack going at full force rather than capturing Black's queen.} Qxf6 22. Rxf6 Bg4 23. Bd5 {Another piece enters the attack, and now its over} Be2 24. Rxg6+ hxg6 25. Qxg6+ Kh8 26. Qh6+ Kg8 27. Be4 {It is mate in four moves, for example} (27. Be4 f5 28. Bd5+ Rf7 29. Qg6+ Kh8 30. Bxf7 Bxf1 31. Qh6# {As David Howell demonstrated in this game, defending against White's initiative is a difficult task, particularly in a rapid game. I expect we will see more examples of this line going forward.}) 1-0


