1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Bd7 4. Bxd7+ Nxd7 $5 {There is nothing wrong with this move, which, although being slightly passive, has less theory attached to it. Hikaru continues his tournament (lifestyle?) strategy of avoiding more well-trodden paths.} 5. O-O Ngf6 6. Re1 ({Definitely the most straightforward way to play White's position is to just pretend you're on the white side of a Grand Prix:} 6. d3 g6 7. Ng5 $5 {intending f4, Nc3, Qe1-h4 etc. Black can't really be worse, but White's position is certainly the easier to play.}) 6... e6 (6... Rc8 $5 7. d3 (7. c3) 7... e6 8. Nc3 Be7 $13 9. e5 $6 dxe5 10. Nxe5 Nxe5 11. Rxe5 {Kovchan, A (2585)-Ivanchuk, V (2726) Lvov 2014} c4 $1 $15) 7. c3 {This is the main line, but it doesn't seem very testing to me. Black gets a very playable game with little effort.} (7. d4 $5 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Be7 9. c4 O-O 10. Nc3 a6 11. b3 $14 {with a nice Maroczy structure. Karjakin, S (2786) -Indjic, A (2539) Tromso 2014}) (7. b3 $5 Be7 8. Bb2 O-O 9. c4 a6 10. d4 cxd4 11. Nxd4 Qc7 12. Nc3 {gives a similarly pleasant edge for White. Papin, V  (2565) -Diu, V (2475) Taganrog 2011}) 7... Be7 8. d4 O-O 9. Nbd2 (9. e5 Ne8 {is perfectly acceptable for Black Szmetan, J (2390)-Tal, M (2625) Rio Hondo 1987}) 9... cxd4 10. cxd4 Qb6 $11 {White has the dream centre, but his knights are a little stuck defending the pawns, which means the bishop on c1 is still a while away from entering the game. Black's development advantage gives him easy play to be honest, I'd rather be Black here!} 11. b3 d5 $1 12. e5 Ne8 13. Nf1 Nc7 {Now Black has a very nice French structure, as the light-squared bishops have been exchanged and White has made critical queenside weaknesses with b3.} 14. Ng3 Rac8 15. Re3 Nb5 16. Rd3 $6 {This idea is common to the similar structures arising after 3...Bd7, as we have discussed several times, but here it is all wrong. White's attack is far too slow, owing to the huge holes in his queenside.} Rc6 $15 17. Bg5 Bxg5 18. Nxg5 h6 19. Nh3 Rfc8 20. Nf4 Qd8 21. a4 Nc3 22. Qf3 Qg5 23. h3 Nf8 24. Kh2 Ng6 $1 {After this it is clear that White's attacking ambitions on the kingside are just fantasy.} 25. Nxg6 (25. Nfh5 Ne4 $1 $17) 25... Qxg6 26. Re3 b5 $1 27. axb5 Nxb5 28. Ne2 $1 {Black is clearly better, but from here on in, David defends like a tiger.} Rc2 29. Ra5 Rb8 30. Rd3 Rb2 31. Qe3 Rb6 32. Rd2 Qb1 33. Nc3 Nxc3 34. Qxc3 R6xb3 35. Rxb2 Qxb2 $2 (35... Rxb2 $1 36. Qe3 Qc2 37. Rxa7 Qxf2 38. Qxf2 Rxf2 $19) 36. Qxb2 Rxb2 37. Kg3 Rb4 38. h4 {I'm not sure if this endgame is objectively lost or not I would guess so, but it's hard to win against accurate defense.} g6 39. Kg4 Rxd4+ 40. f4 f6 41. exf6 Kf7 42. Rxa7+ Kxf6 43. Kf3 Rd3+ 44. Ke2 Rb3 45. Rh7 h5 46. Rd7 Rb1 47. Rd8 Rh1 48. g3 Kf5 49. Kf3 Rf1+ 50. Ke2 Ra1 51. Rf8+ Kg4 52. Rf6 Kxg3 53. Rxe6 Kxf4 54. Rxg6 Ra3 55. Rg5 (55. Kd2 $1 $11) 55... Re3+ 56. Kd2 Re5 57. Rg8 Ke4 58. Rh8 Kf3 59. Rg8 Re4 60. Rg5 Rd4+ 61. Kc2 Rxh4 62. Rxd5 Rh1 63. Kb2 $2 (63. Rd3+ $1 {is the only drawing move.}) 63... h4 64. Rd4 Ke3 $4 (64... Kg3 $1 {avoids the famous Vancura drawing position.} 65. Rd3+ Kf2 66. Rd4 h3 67. Rd3 h2 $19) 65. Rc4 $1 $11 h3 66. Rc3+ Kd4 67. Rg3 Rh2+ 68. Ka1 Rh1+ 1/2-1/2


