1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. g3 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Bg2 Nb6 7. O-O Be7 8. a3 O-O 9. b4 Be6 10. d3 {This is actually by far the most common move here, although I always thought that it was slightly less accurate than} (10. Rb1 {defending b3, see the PGN Archive for many examples of this.}) 10... a5 {The most common, and critical.} (10... f6 {is solid, but allows White to play} 11. Bb2 {and then the more active Rc1 - see the Archive.}) (10... Nd4 $5 {is also played immediately (see Socko-Mamedyarov for example), but maybe White can risk} 11. Nxe5 $5 {here, too} Bf6 12. f4 Nb3 13. Be3 {as in the main game,} Nxa1 14. Qxa1 {with some compensation, Mogilny, E-Espindola, C ICCF corr 1994, 0-1 (29), and others.}) 11. b5 Nd4 12. Nxe5 $5 {I had thought this was dubious, but if someone as strong as David plays it I guess it must have plenty of redeeming factors.} (12. Nd2 {is the most common, controlling b3 and preparing to drive away the knight with e3, see Nimzo-Fritz in the Archive.}) 12... Bf6 (12... Nb3 $6 {is inaccurate:} 13. Rb1 Nxc1 (13... Qd4 14. Rxb3 Qxe5 (14... Bxb3 15. Qxb3 Qxe5 16. Bxb7 a4 17. Qc2 {Kozak, P (1800)-Mashinskaya, I (2300) Karvina 2002, 1/2-1/2 (21).}) 15. Bxb7 {with two pawns already,} Rab8 16. Be4 a4 17. d4 Bxb3 18. dxe5 Bxd1 19. Rxd1 {White is a bit better.}) 14. Qxc1 Qd6 15. Nc4 Nxc4 16. dxc4 Bxc4 17. Bxb7 Rad8 18. a4 {with an extra pawn, Seeger, N-Oswald, T ICCF email 2007, 1/2-1/2 (60).}) (12... Bb3 $6 13. Qd2 Bf6 14. f4 Bxe5 15. fxe5 Re8 {Anton Gomez, B-Bailen Canales, F UECC email 1998, 0-1 (30),} 16. e3 Nc2 17. Rb1 a4 18. Bxb7 (18. d4) 18... Rb8 19. Be4 Rxe5 20. d4) 13. f4 Nb3 (13... Bxe5 14. fxe5 Nb3 15. Be3 {transposes below.}) 14. Be3 (14. Bb2 Nxa1 15. Qxa1 {is also playable,} Bxe5 16. fxe5 Rb8 17. Ne4 {with compensation, Savchenko, B (2580) -Nakhapetiane, P (2504) Sochi 2012, 1/2-1/2 (35), but the dark squared bishop is less effective here with a white pawn on e5.}) 14... Nxa1 15. Qxa1 {White has sacrificed an exchange, but in return has a pawn, the centre, and good squares for his minor pieces in a fairly closed position.} Nd5 (15... Bxe5 $1 {is sometimes preferred, conceding the f6-bishop, but blocking the a1-h8 diagonal, but as Black often has to capture on e5 later on anyway, this may well be the most accurate,} 16. fxe5 Nd5 17. Bc5 Re8 18. a4 Qd7 19. Bf2 {the position is unclear, White can push his centre or manoeuvre his knight to e4, but Black is solid and has an extra exchange, Steinbrueck, W  (2397)-Blauhut, H (2497) ICCF email 2007, 1/2-1/2 (43).}) 16. Bd4 {This natural move is actually a novelty in over-the-board chess, where the inferior} (16. Bc5 {had been preferred,} Re8 17. Ne4 Bxe5 18. fxe5 b6 {Hierreich, G  (1971)-Zelcic, R (2555) Malinska 2013, 0-1 (29).}) 16... Bxe5 {It seems funny to play this now when White can recapture with the bishop, but White was menacing Ne4 when Black would have to capture anyway. Previously Black had tried a number of moves in correspondence games:} (16... a4 17. Ne4 Bxe5 18. Bxe5 (18. fxe5 b6 {Garriga Nualart, J (2398) -Dobrica, D (2340) ICCF email 2009, 1-0 (36).}) 18... f6 19. Bd4 Re8 20. f5 $1 (20. Nc5 Bf7 21. Nxb7 Qc8 22. Nc5 {is met by} Rxe2 {Prado, J (2221)-Corujedo Hernandez, R (2279) ICCF email 2008, 1/2-1/2 (31).}) 20... Bf7 21. g4 Ra5 22. g5 $1 Rxb5 23. gxf6 {and I wouldn't fancy having to defend this position as Black OTB, Schuster, P (2459) -Jaworski, M (2445) ICCF email 2008, 1/2-1/2 (39).}) (16... Re8 17. Ne4 Bxe5 {Garriga Nualart, J (2398)-Penkin, V (2113) ICCF email 2009, 1/2-1/2 (54), and now} 18. Bxe5 {seems best.}) (16... Rc8 17. Ne4 {forces} Bxe5 {Garriga Nualart, J (2398)-Auzins, M (2424) ICCF email 2009, 1-0 (43), and again} 18. Bxe5 {looks good.} f6 19. Bd4 b6 20. Nf2 $5 {and e4.}) (16... Nxc3 17. Qxc3 Bd5 18. e4 Be6 19. Bc5 (19. f5 Bc8 20. Bc5 Re8 21. d4 {is also promising, Sadler, C  (1916)-Stark, K (1685) IECC email 2009, 1-0 (31).}) 19... Re8 20. a4 {White will play d4-5, so} Bxe5 21. fxe5 Qd7 22. d4 Bh3 23. d5 Bxg2 24. Kxg2 {with adequate compensation, Cristancho, F (2079)-Germanes, R (1980) FICGS email 2010, 0-1 (73).}) 17. Bxe5 f6 18. Nxd5 Bxd5 19. Bxc7 {Winning a second pawn.} Qxc7 (19... Qd7 20. Qd4 {forces} Qxc7 21. Bxd5+ {similar to the game.}) 20. Bxd5+ Kh8 21. Kg2 {White has two good central pawns for the exchange and his light-squared bishop is strong.} Qd7 22. Qa2 $5 (22. Bc4 {is simpler, but} f5 {hinders e4.}) 22... Qxb5 23. Rb1 Qc5 24. a4 $1 {The b-pawn is not running away.} (24. Rxb7 Rab8 25. a4 {would transpose to the game.}) 24... Rab8 25. Rxb7 (25. Rb5 {would have kept a pair of rooks on the board,} Qc3 26. Be4 {with fair compensation.}) 25... Qd4 26. Rxb8 Rxb8 27. Bc6 Qe3 28. Bf3 {White still has two pawns for the exchange, but they aren't going anywhere and Black is active. Still, White has a simple plan of attacking on the kingside and Black fails to defend against this.} Qd4 29. h4 $1 Qb4 30. Qc2 Qb3 31. Qc7 Qb6 32. Qf7 Qd4 $2 {The queen is not able to defend the light squares here. This error might be down to time trouble, certainly David was probably very short of time by now, as is his custom!} (32... Rd8 33. h5 h6 34. Qe7 {is unpleasant,} (34. Qg6 Qe6 35. Be4 Kg8 36. Qh7+ Kf8 {is nothing - the black queen guards g8.}) {but} 34... Kg8 35. Bd5+ Kh7 (35... Rxd5 $2 36. Qe8+ Kh7 37. Qe4+) 36. Be4+ Kg8 {and it's not clear how White makes progress.}) 33. h5 {Now the threat of h6 is unpleasant.} Qd6 (33... h6 34. Qg6 Qe3 {(to stop Be4)} 35. Qf5 {and the a5-pawn is lost.}) 34. h6 Qf8 {Forced.} (34... gxh6 $4 35. Be4) 35. Qa7 $1 gxh6 36. Qxa5 {Now it will be very difficult to both stop the a-pawn and defend the black kingside.} Qg7 37. Qf5 (37. Qc5 $1) 37... Rg8 (37... Qg6) 38. g4 h5 {Desperation.} 39. Qxh5 Qd7 40. a5 f5 41. a6 fxg4 $2 42. Qe5+ Rg7 (42... Qg7 43. Bd5) 43. Bd5 {The immediate threat is Qb8+ and mate.} 1-0


