1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ ({The Queen's Indian move order is} 3... b6 4. g3 Bb7 5. Bg2 Bb4+ ({while} 5... Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Re1 a5 $5 {is the position discussed after White's 9th move in the game.}) 6. Nbd2) 4. Nbd2 b6 5. g3 Bb7 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O a5 $5 {We've seen this move recently in a couple of games. Black plans to swap his bishop for the knight, and then adopt a typically solid set-up with ...d6 and ...Nbd7. The ...a5 advance can be a useful move in this set-up, and by playing it here Black is asking White to find a useful move before Black takes on d2.} 8. Nb1 $5 {And we've seen this move too! Typically Simon Williams plays the most creative option for White here.} ({The most common choice here is} 8. Qc2 {which is covered in Bacrot, E-Naiditsch, A/ Baden Baden 2015.}) 8... Be7 {Preventing the idea of c4-c5 and a2-a3 trapping the bishop.} 9. Re1 $5 {The first new move. It looks very sensible, and Re1 is a typical idea for White, but when I checked to see whether it had been played before, I found out that this position has actually been reached a number of times - but with White to move! See the variation above, where 7...a5 has been played quite a few times in the 7 Re1 variation.} ({Previously we've looked at} 9. Nc3 Ne4 10. Qc2 Nxc3 11. bxc3 $5 {- see the notes to Ushenina, A-Franciskovic, B/Rijeka 2010.}) ({Another option for White is to play the well-known gambit line} 9. d5 {with an extra ...a5 thrown in.}) 9... Qc8 {Protecting the b7-bishop, in readiness for Nc3, ...Ne4.} (9... d5 {is obviously an option here}) ({and so is} 9... d6 {It's worth noting that the extra ...a5 helps Black in the line} 10. Nc3 Ne4 11. Qc2 Nxc3 {In contrast to the 7 Re1 d6 line,} 12. Ng5 $2 {doesn't work here because after} ({Instead White should play} 12. bxc3 $1 {with play very similar to Ushenina, A-Franciskovic, B/Rijeka 2010.}) 12... Bxg5 13. Bxb7 {Black's rook has an escape square:} Ra7 $1) 10. d5 $5 {With the b7-bishop protected, you would have thought White would be discouraged from this advance. However, Simon found a very nice idea.} (10. Nc3 Ne4 $11 {is solid and equal.}) 10... exd5 11. cxd5 Bxd5 12. e4 $1 {This is it - another pawn offer!} ({If} 12. Nc3 Bb7 13. e4 {Black gets in} d6) 12... Bxe4 ({In contrast, if} 12... Bb7 {White gets in} 13. e5 $1 {Black's knight has to move from its ideal defensive post, and White is assured of attacking chances on the kingside.}) 13. Rxe4 $5 ({As Simon pointed out on his YouTube channel, White could play} 13. Nc3 d5 {(forced)} 14. Nxe4 dxe4 15. Ng5 {White will regain one of the two sac'ed pawns, and his positional advantages will compensate him for the other. Objectively this might be White's best option, although the text move is obviously very tempting.}) 13... Nxe4 14. Qd5 Nxg3 15. hxg3 c6 16. Qh5 d5 17. Bh3 Qb7 {White is slightly down on material - with two pieces for a rook and three pawns - but has some attacking chances on the kingside.} 18. Bf5 $2 {A miscalculation, from which there's no way back for White.} ({After either} 18. Nc3) ({or} 18. Ng5 {the chances remain very much in the balance.}) 18... g6 19. Qh6 Re8 $1 (19... gxf5 {gets Black mated after} 20. Ng5 Bxg5 21. Qxg5+ Kh8 22. Qf6+ Kg8 23. Bh6) 20. Ng5 {Going all in. White could retreat the bishop from f5, when the loss of time swings the advantage firmly in Black's favour.} Bxg5 21. Bxg5 f6 $1 {David Howell is particularly good at finding the most precise move in complicated positions.} ({It's tempting to throw in} 21... Re1+ $2 {but this is a mistake:} 22. Kg2 f6 23. Nc3 $1 {intending} Rxa1 $2 24. Be6+ $1) 22. Bxg6 ({After} 22. Bxf6 {the calm} Qf7 $1 {is winning for Black:} 23. Bc3 ({or} 23. Qg5 Rf8) 23... gxf5) 22... Re1+ $1 {Now it's the right time for the check. Black is winning.} 23. Kg2 fxg5 24. Nd2 Rxa1 25. Bf5 Na6 26. Nf3 Qg7 27. Qxc6 Rf8 0-1



